<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra9.gif" alt="Feature">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 



<H3><B> NATWEST MARKETS </B></H3>


<H2> <B>Messy divorce in Hong Kong</B> </H2> 

<H4> <B>When one of Hong Kong's
biggest conglomerates and NatWest Markets got together in 1994 they spoke of a
partnership for the long haul. But just a year after Wheelock NatWest wrote its
first trading ticket the joint venture has been dissolved amid vague excuses of
regulatory difficulties. Just another case of NatWest screwing up in Asia? Or was
Wheelock NatWest sacrificed as part of a new strategy in London? Steven Irvine
reports</B> </H4> 

<P> It probably won't be long before the name Wheelock NatWest
is forgotten. Many outside Hong Kong will not even know it existed. A brokerage,
with a corporate finance arm and a fund manager attached; capitalized at $125
million, with 250 staff, and seven offices across Asia; it did virtually nothing
in two and a half years.

<P> It has only one major point of interest. Former employees say it was as good
as destroyed by one of its own shareholders, NatWest. It provides a good example
of the pitfalls of joint ventures, especially in a difficult region like Asia.

<P> A joint statement in November by the two partners, NatWest Markets and
Wheelock, a Hong Kong property conglomerate, said that the joint venture was
wound up because of "a number of changes in the industry, and in the overall
regulatory environment".

<P> However, it is clear that regulatory barriers were not the real problem.

<P> "We entered the joint venture with a long-term view in mind," says John
Howland-Jackson, chairman of NatWest Markets Asia. "And Wheelock fulfilled all
their obligations and contributed whatever they could. But things changed in the
world of NatWest Markets."

<P> What changed?

<P> "NatWest Markets has changed and is a successful organization today," says
its chairman, Martin Owen. "People actually queue outside our door now. The very
best in the world want to work for us."

<P> In May 1994 when it signed up with Wheelock this was not the case. In Asia
the firm's reputation was terrible. County NatWest, the bank's previous
incarnation, had lost money in the early 1990s both in Japan and Hong Kong. Both
operations were shut down &#173; as was Singapore. In Hong Kong there were
recriminations at the sudden loss of 60 jobs. It didn't look as if anyone would
take NatWest seriously if it ever came back.

<P> But with Asian equity markets booming in 1993, NatWest Markets decided to
renew its presence in the world's highest growth region.

<P> In the early part of 1994 the Berwick Group, a consultancy firm, was given
the task of getting NatWest back into Asia.

<P> Nicholas Sibley, the recently appointed head of Wheelock's financial
division, Wheelock Capital, and an old Hong Kong hand, was sounded out over lunch
by an old friend at Berwick. The former head of Jardine Fleming and BZW Asia
wasn't instantly keen but struck up a good rapport with Simon Meredith-Hardy, his
opposite number at NatWest Markets. The joint venture was announced in May 1994.

<P> The choice of Wheelock wasn't as random as it at first might seem. Peter Woo
Kwong-ching, the head of the Wheelock conglomerate, and one of three remaining
candidates for the post of chief executive of Hong Kong after the handover to
China, likewise had a special connection with NatWest &#173; he was a founding
member of its international advisory board.

<P> The rationale was simple. Wheelock, the 149-year-old property-to-retail
conglomerate with an annual turnover of $13 billion, is one of the most important
Hong Kong Chinese companies. It would give the venture credibility, persuade
clients NatWest Markets was not about to repeat its disappearing act of the early
1990s and lend its name to the recruitment process.

<P> Sibley was to be Wheelock's day-to-day point man &#173; the experienced pair
of shoulders who could swing almost anything over a lunch and go the extra mile
over dinner. Howland-Jackson, Owen's deputy, was to liaise between London and
Hong Kong.

<P> <B>Premature congratulation</B>

<P> Those who were cynical about whether the agreement between them would come to
anything watched as the summer passed and a chief executive failed to be
appointed. A full five months later, David Miller came from US bank State Street
to take on the post. He and Nick Sibley knew each other from Jardine Fleming,
where Sibley had made him head of Tokyo.

<P> "We have positioned ourselves as a major house in the restructuring of
corporate China," Miller told <I>Euromoney</I>'s special Asian issue in February
1995.

<P> China was the theme. Meocre Li, Arthur Andersen's former managing partner in
China, became the firm's corporate finance head. His accountancy background gave
him good access to Chinese companies. It looked a clever hire.

<P> The staff count grew quickly. There were 90 employees in October 1995, and by
the time the joint venture was dissolved in October 1996, there were 250.

<P> Two to three months before the end, an inner circle of Hong Kong gossips
sensed it was coming. But the public face of Wheelock NatWest was buoyant to the
end. As recently as July, Miller commented: "My job is to build an innovative and
powerful force in Asian investment banking, and there is a three- to five-year
building phase." Wheelock chief executive, John Hung, said the company was in it
"for the long haul".

<P> And so, it seemed, was NatWest Markets. It had achieved its aim of getting
back into Asia. And even snatched a brief moment of glory, with the $135 million
IPO spin-off of Concord Land &#173; its first major lead managership. But
ironically the deal's launch came almost simulataneously with the announcement
that the joint venture was to end in divorce. The joint venture &#173; created in
nine weeks by Sibley and Meredith-Hardy &#173; fell apart almost as quickly.

<P> "It was moving very rapidly in a direction of not just research and broking
but becoming very capital-intensive and particularly risk-intensive," says Owen.
"Frankly we never do risk-intensive businesses outside of our own structure for
control issues &#173; irrespective of who our joint venture partner is."

<P> Wheelock had been led to believe otherwise. As far as it was concerned,
NatWest's $250 billion balance sheet had always been part of the Wheelock NatWest
equation. The $125 million of paid-up capital was regarded as a token amount to
be leveraged off the bigger prize in London. But it gradually emerged that the UK
partner's balance sheet would be selectively available.

<P> Early on the omens were bad. A team of traders was hired in July 1995 in
accordance with the business plan. Ross Reason, former head of equity derivatives
and trading at SG Warburg, brought two colleagues and expected to sit down and
start to make some money. Miller commented at the time: "Our senior management
takes every opportunity to employ the best people in the business." But what use
are the best people in the business if they can't work?

<P> NatWest Market's management's approved the appointments. But a turf war soon
erupted in London. The risk management people were concerned about loaning out
the NatWest balance sheet for Reason's derivatives activities. Reason and his
team were given a bureaucratic barrage of excuses and, to their horror, no
computer systems. This despite the joint venture agreement which specified that
the UK bank would provide all the systems and audits Wheelock NatWest would
require.

<P> With no systems Reason couldn't trade. Exasperated, the Wheelock NatWest
management intervened personally with Martin Owen.

<P> Owen recalls there were faults on both sides and does not deny that he was
forced to "review pockets of potential politics". Although there was undeniably a
period of six months in which the traders lacked computer systems, part of the
problem, he says, was that Reason's team were poor articulators of what they
wanted to do. They lacked familiarity with NatWest's internal processes for
obtaining trading limits, and also lacked a knowledge of the sort of robust
systems they required.

<P> Should it not have been NatWest's systems people who figured out such
technical details? "This takes time," says Owen. "And it took six months for them
to articulate what they wanted to do. They wanted to do reasonably exotic things
and these systems had to be tailored." Owen adds that the scale of the trading
Reason's team envisaged was beyond anything that was in the business plan.

<P> Wheelock NatWest completely missed out on a bull market in the warrants
business in the last quarter of 1995 and the opening quarter of 1996. Owen
authorized a couple of deals personally, but the warrants business cannot be
easily transacted through a chief executive in another time zone.

<P> In the end, specific individuals were given "limited" authority to trade. But
Reason left in early 1996.

<P> "The issue we have struggled with post-Barings," says Owen, "is how do you
demonstrate clearly in an autonomous arms-length business how risk is controlled
where its principal controls are through board meetings once a month." Wheelock
NatWest, he says, was not even an acceptable counterparty in the derivatives
market. All of its trades had to be done back-to-back with NatWest Financial
Products.

<P> It was clear from this early stage that the joint venture wasn't working out
quite as both parties envisaged. In NatWest's Markets' Broadgate headquarters,
other acquisitions focused the minds of Owen and his senior management. Among
these were M&amp;A boutique Gleacher in 1995, and US bond house Greenwich and UK
corporate advisory Hambro Magan in 1996.

<P> But NatWest's decision to buy fund manager Gartmore proved more than just a
diversion.

<P> Wheelock NatWest had its own fund management business. By the time of its
demise, Wheelock NatWest Investment Management had been managing $600 million,
the bulk of which came from the partners (including Wheelock's pension fund) and
$200 million from Japan.

<P> <B>A fund manager too far</B>

<P> The poaching of Nigel Wightman in June 1995 was controversial. The Asia
Pacific chief executive of Rothschild Asset Management brought eight fund
managers with him, leaving Rothschild in tatters. His brief was to build the
Asian business on behalf of Wheelock NatWest and NatWest Markets &#173; whose
Asian investment management team had just transferred across to the joint
venture.

<P> Wightman had been told that NatWest might acquire a domestic fund manager in
the UK, but this would only "add value" to the existing business. He was led to
think that NatWest Markets was committed to growing its on-the-ground Asian fund
management business.

<P> All but two of his ex-Rothschild team were already in the firm's NatWest
Tower office in Hong Kong's Causeway Bay. The final pair had less than a week
left on their gardening leave when news broke in February that NatWest was buying
Gartmore, the London-based global fund manager. It didn't take them long to
realize they had no job to go back to.

<P> NatWest executives in Asia were surprised by the Gartmore acquisition. Martin
Owen and Gartmore's chief executive, Paul Myners, handled the negotiations
personally. Owen says the deal was concluded in less than 10 days. Secrecy did
not permit word of the ongoing negotiations to be passed on to the joint venture
since both were public companies, and stock exchange negotiations forbade it.
However, Owen does say the Hong Kong joint venture was told 24 hours before the
announcement was made public.

<P> What immediately alarmed Wheelock was that NatWest had bought a fund manager
that had an extensive Asian business of its own. Gartmore had a Japan fund (with
&#163;73 million under management), a Pacific growth fund (&#163;127 million),
and a dedicated Hong Kong fund (&#163;23 million). With the exception of Japan,
all of Gartmore's funds are managed from London.

<P> Myners had worked with the joint venture's Wightman at Rothschild in the
early 1980s. So Wightman had no illusions about the future. Myners' style is
independent, as is Gartmore's. Gartmore is an organization that has a philosophy
of keeping all of its staff in London, and managing the funds in a distinct
Gartmore style. Myners had told his buyer that the business would be left alone.
(This was confirmed by Owen's November reorganization. It was announced that
Gartmore would have a separate operating committee and that Myners would report
directly to Owen.)

<P> Wheelock NatWest chief executive Miller and fund management head Wightman
went to London. They asked whether Gartmore's Asian funds would be farmed out to
the joint venture. Myners looked over to Owen. He said no.

<P> "Gartmore's philosophy is that all fund management remains in London," Owen
told <I>Euromoney</I>, "If you pack funds off to Wheelock NatWest that is a
different philosophy." These philosophies, he says, are conflicting.

<P> But there wasn't room for two NatWest-linked fund management businesses in
Asia: Gartmore and Wheelock NatWest. It would confuse clients, as Owen puts it,
to have "two centres of fund management excellence competing for business in the
region". One would have to go, and since NatWest had just paid &#163;472 million
for Gartmore it was quite obvious which.

<P> Wheelock was bemused. Did it have any say in the closing of its own business?
The joint venture agreement was inspected. It was a document of 30 or so pages,
strong on procedure &#173; how often board meetings will be held and the like
&#173; but vague on details regarding mutual commitments.

<P> Sibley, the deputy chairman of Wheelock NatWest, had been involved in drawing
up the agreement. But his view had been that if you had to resort to reading the
agreement, the joint venture was over anyway &#173; in spirit if nothing else.

<P> <B>What's yours isn't mine</B>

<P> The two shareholders had set out with the assumption that anything in Asia
was the joint venture's. On the specific subject of fund management this included
Asia-targeted funds generated from institutions in London.

<P> However, the joint venture agreement was flawed. One of NatWest's
London-based index-funds was Japan-targeted, and therefore NatWest couldn't sign
any agreement that guaranteed all Asia-linked funds out of London would go to the
new joint venture. Its index fund business was too profitable. Both sides,
however, had already agreed during internal meetings to give Wheelock NatWest
Investment Management a broad mandate that in practice comprised London. This all
smacked of formality and since neither partner wanted to stall the process, the
written agreement therefore mentioned <I>only </I>the joint venture's exclusive
right to manage funds collected in Asia itself.

<P> NatWest took legal advice on this point, and lawyers said it did not
contravene the letter of the joint venture agreement.

<P> Immediately following the Gartmore acquisition, Wheelock boss Peter Woo
pressed his case. He wrote a polite letter to NatWest chairman Lord Alexander
stating his concerns about the unsuitability of the Gartmore acquisition in
respect to their Asian fund management business. He received a reply from
Alexander stating he would look into it. Nothing happened, so a second letter was
sent.

<P> Woo eventually ordered a meeting. In April he arrived in London with Sibley
to meet Alexander and NatWest chief executive Derek Wanless. He explained the
position, and requested the fund management issue be resolved to his
satisfaction. Both Woo and Sibley departed for Hong Kong with the impression it
would be.

<P> It was not.

<P> Instead NatWest hired financial M&amp;A boutique Phoenix and tried to find a
buyer for Wheelock NatWest Investment Management. But after limited interest in
the US this came to nothing. The fund management business was quietly closed in
October, and the Rothschild team, so expensively hired, was paid off and fired.

<P> "I'm sad we've disrupted their lives," says Howland-Jackson. "It is not good
practice."

<P> "I became puzzled that Gartmore became so emotive an issue," says Owen. "But
I was sitting in a different place. My mind was in Europe." Such
misunderstandings appear to have permeated the joint venture throughout. By the
summer their pace accelerated.

<P> The five executive directors of Wheelock NatWest were still waiting for
NatWest Markets to sign off on the long-term incentive scheme, which was to
comprise a substantial part of their pay. Wheelock had agreed to this back in
December 1995.

<P> All five, which included John Williamson, NatWest's former head of custody,
talked of resigning, but concluded it would be a betrayal of the staff they had
hired.

<P> Matters ought to have improved with the relocation of Howland-Jackson, Owen's
deputy, to Asia. Howland-Jackson had been the venture's staunchest ally in
London.

<P> But his arrival in August coincided with news that NatWest Markets had hired
Steve Yamane from Morgan Stanley &#173; a trader whose epitaph could be "The man
who finally broke Wheelock NatWest". Yet again NatWest Markets had failed to
inform the joint venture of its new hire, who would head Asian equity trading and
derivatives.

<P> It was another <I>fait accompli</I>. NatWest Markets had unilaterally decided
to take Asian trading out of the joint venture's sphere of influence and put it
in NatWest Markets. The press release made no mention of Wheelock NatWest. It was
as if it didn't exist. Wheelock NatWest would not be viable if trading was pulled
out.

<P> What lay behind this change of strategy was the arrival in June of Tom
Whelan. A former Morgan Stanley head of equity derivatives, he was hired by Owen
to take charge of global equities. His hires in Tokyo reflected his intention to
generate revenues from proprietary trading in Japan.

<P> The joint venture agreement never prohibited NatWest Markets from trading in
Asia. But NatWest Markets could only trade with other marketmakers. The joint
venture agreement didn't allow NatWest Markets to go near client business.
Wheelock sources suggest NatWest wanted the client flows, to run its proprietary
trading more effectively.

<P> Yamane's Tokyo operation therefore violated the joint venture agreement.

<P> Owen came to Hong Kong and met with Peter Woo. It was not a pleasant meeting.
According to accounts circulating in Hong Kong, Woo was not prepared to watch
NatWest treat him in the same fashion as it had done over Gartmore. Apparently he
banged his fist on the table at one point. He also used what has since been
called the <BR> D-word in reference to NatWest's treatment of the joint venture.
The D-word is believed to be "despicable". Woo was clearly annoyed by this
diversion from his campaign to become the Hong Kong government's chief executive
in July 1997.

<P> He pointed out that the joint venture agreement had been violated and
threatened legal action. It was clearly the end of the relationship. All that was
left was to figure out how much it would cost to buy out Wheelock's 50% share.

<P> The figure will appear as an exceptional item in Wheelock's end-of-year
accounts, and it is hinted that it is substantially more than if the conglomerate
had just banked its capital. The public announcement of the break-up had to be
delayed till the payment could be voted at a full NatWest board meeting. A heated
discussion is said to have taken place over the figure.

<P> Ironically, the Hong Kong press reacted to the news on November 5 by savaging
Wheelock. Conglomerates analysts in Hong Kong accused the company of yet another
failed joint venture to add to the tie-up with Richard Branson's Virgin group,
which was signed in February 1994 but hasn't left the drawing board.

<P> They pointed to the hype. Wheelock had claimed the joint venture would help
finance projects all over China thanks to NatWest's financial expertise and
Wheelock's contacts. What projects? What contacts? Had any materialized? Analysts
noted that Wheelock had also said it would turn Wuhan into the "Chicago of
China". Four years later plans for a container terminal, a commuter rail system
and a power plant have come to nothing.

<P> Woo made himself available to host functions, or to take part in meetings at
the Chinese Central Bank. But his political ambitions prevented him travelling
round China with the corporate financiers &#173; which would have been difficult
even without the political ambitions. The Wheelock name, it is true, did not
bring too many deals, although it is rumoured in the market that its Philippines
connections have helped it (whatever <I>it</I> will be, when NatWest settles on a
name for the revamped Asian business) to win a lead role in the public offer for
Philippines Nickel.

<P> <B>Hope over experience</B>

<P> Sibley's attempt to build a Jardine Fleming of the 1990s before he finally
leaves Hong Kong's shores in February 1997 to retire, received censure, even from
friends. "You never step in the same river twice," one said. Unlike Jardine
Matheson, the conglomerate which tied up with Robert Fleming (two Scottish
houses), Wheelock was not engaged in much corporate business of its own. When
Jardine Fleming was formed it was immediately thrown into the fee-paying hostile
takeover of Dairy Farm by Hongkong Land (a Jardine company). Such transactions
provided the backbone for Jardine Fleming's expansion across Asia.

<P> Where does the failed joint venture leave NatWest Markets in Hong Kong? Owen
is bullish: "Asia is more relevant to us than it was five years ago. We
understand it better, we understand the risks of the region better and we have
much better people working for us."

<P> However, Owen has made clear that product centralization will be instituted
for the sake of greater efficiency. Reporting lines will go into London.
Integration will occur. Some already have. One rival syndicate head laughs that
he has been invited on a junk-boat trip to meet NatWest Market's London head of
syndicate.

<P> What has NatWest bought? The 250 staff are of varying quality. Among those
considered top-notch are the likes of Philip Mok, formerly BZW's top-rated head
of Hong Kong research, who brought a whole team with him, and is known to be good
at training new recruits. But with only about $95 million of capital consumed
(the venture had $30 million left of the $125 million it had drawn down) the
process of building has proved dramatically less costly than the $3
million-a-head price tag for Gleacher.

<P> What of NatWest's reputation? "This place is a village," says one Hong Kong
financier. "Overall NatWest probably did the right thing. But everyone who does
business with them now sends negative signals to Wheelock. I'd say this has set
them back five years in Hong Kong and China."

<P> The business focus, however, has changed. China is no longer the clarion
call. "Japan is our single biggest priority in the region," says Howland-Jackson.
"That is not to decry the importance to us of China, India or South East Asia."


<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

