<h2>
December 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra9.gif" alt="Feature">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 



<H3><B> THAILAND </B></H3>


<H2> <B>Why the Big Mango stayed on the tree</B> </H2> 

<H4> <B>1996 was not a
good year for Thailand. Economic problems piled up as thick as Bangkok's
legendary traffic and the pundits forecast a Mexico-style accident. But the Big
Mango, as Thailand's capital city is known, did not go splat</B> <B>&#173; thanks
to skilful technocrats who steered the country to safety. It's early days but the
worst could be over, reports Gill Baker</B> </H4> 

<P> Outside South America, the
country most haunted by the ghost of the Mexican crash is Thailand. All the signs
of success coming apart at the seams are there, including a large current account
deficit, a build up of short-term debt, an overvalued currency, a moribund stock
market, overextended banks, a property slump and inept government.

<P> As if this wasn't enough, journalists, analysts and academics have been busy
penning articles pointing out the dangers Thailand faces. Financial meetings in
London and New York have been abuzz with Thailand horror stories and many bankers
with Thailand risk have flown to Bangkok to assess the situation.

<P> If Thailand was indeed on the brink of collapse, such scaremongering should
have sent it over the edge. But the country has held firm and, while the problems
are by no means resolved, the country's technocrats are starting to breathe a
little easier.

<P> Thailand's civil service is noted for its cool steering of the economy during
periodic crises such as military coups, political upheavals and riots. Such
domestic difficulties are commonplace for an experienced Thai technocrat. But
there was less confidence about whether they could prevent substantial capital
flight out of liberalizing financial markets. This was the challenge that
defeated Mexico.

<P> So far Thailand has fared much better and analysts are now starting to
attribute the country's economic problems to structural adjustment &#173; the
malaise affecting all the Asian tigers &#173; rather than a new-style emerging
markets rout. One analyst has even accused Moody's &#173; which raised tension in
September by downgrading the country's short-term debt  &#173; of getting hold of
the wrong information.

<P> "There's no way [Thailand's short-term debt] is over 40 [billion US
dollars]," says Mark Greenwood, managing director of Asia Equity Thailand. "The
book-keeping has been wrong and that was not properly explained to Moody's
because they were talking to the wrong people at the BOT [Bank of Thailand]."

<P> This, says Greenwood, was because the central bank was preoccupied with the
troubled Bangkok Bank of Commerce (see <I>Euromoney</I> October 1996, page 62) at
the time of Moody's research, and the banking supervision and statistical
department were not communicating with each other properly.

<P> If this were true (Moody's says it stands by its decision), it reflects
rather poorly on BOT technocrats, whose reputation did indeed suffer during the
Bangkok Bank of Commerce (BBC) debacle, when the BOT's independence was
questioned and its former governor, Vijit Supinit, came in for criticism. A more
generous assessment of the Thai crisis is that BOT executives, notwithstanding
the BBC affair, have handled an unstable situation with customary aplomb.

<P> Through a series of small but emphatic measures, the BOT has been acting over
a long period to slow capital inflows (so cutting down the scale of any
subsequent outflows), to cool overheating and credit growth, and to push Thailand
very gradually towards a free-floating baht. (The contradiction between a fixed
exchange rate and the need to run an independent monetary policy is at the root
of Thailand's difficulties.) Such policies have provoked the disdain of the
financial community which sees them as a reversal of Thailand's liberalization
efforts. But given Thailand's success in avoiding a shock devaluation that might
have triggered a crash, this seems a small price to pay.

<P> <B>On the edge</B>

<P> At times things have looked very delicate and the economic situation remains
serious. After a run of spectacular economic growth over the past decade,
Thailand has become a victim of its own success. Inflation, at around 5.7% a
year, is barely under control; export growth has weakened; and in August the
current account deficit was around Bt30 billion ($1.18 billion). Despite the
insistence of senior Thai bureaucrats that the problem is merely a blip, others
are not so convinced.

<P> "The consensus is too optimistic in hoping everything will return to normal
after just one year. Many of the problems are structural and will take three to
five years of adjustment," says a report from Kleinwort Benson, which believes
the stock market has yet to hit bottom and is warning investors to steer clear or
be saddled with "dead money" for a year.

<P> The stock market has been falling for most of the year, hitting a low of 905
in October. Expectations that the poorly regarded government of Banharn
Silpa-arch would be replaced by a Democrat-led coalition following last month's
elections sent the index up to just over 1,000, only for it to fall back after
the New Aspiration Party came in ahead.

<P> "It's a real mess," says Robert McMillen, managing director of investment
banking at  General Finance &amp; Securities. "They will probably announce a
reasonably acceptable [government] finance team, then Banharn is going to stick
his nose in and I am not sure it will materialize."

<P> Throughout the crisis the currency has been the main focus of attention. The
baht is pegged to a basket of currencies whose composition is a closely guarded
secret; but Morgan Stanley calculates it to be 88% US dollars, 8% yen and 4%
Deutschmarks. The dollar/baht mid-rate is announced daily by the Bank of
Thailand, which pledges to buy or sell unlimited amounts within a band Bt0.02
either side of the mid rate.

<P> Sporadic rumours of a baht devaluation have kept foreign investors in a state
of nervousness since the Mexico crisis, but so far the Bank of Thailand has stood
firm in its intention to support the currency, pouring millions of dollars into
the repurchase and offshore swap markets in July and August.

<P> A potential trigger for a devaluation would be an outflow of funds. Merrill
Lynch estimates there is around $24 billion of "hot" money in portfolio inflows
and non-resident deposits which could be sold and would bring down the baht. But
the investment bank points out that Thailand had international reserves of just
under $40 billion, as at the end of July, which is a substantial buffer. In
addition, Thailand's reserves are sufficient to cover around 30 months of current
account deficits, against just six months' cover in pre-crash Mexico.

<P> But whether the reserves are sufficient in relation to Thailand's short-term
debt is a topic of debate. Moody's downgrading of Thailand's sovereign debt from
Prime-1 to Prime-2 was based on a short-term debt figure of $41 billion. A
Moody's report said: "The downgrade reflects the country's increased
vulnerability to a financial shock through the balance of payments as a result of
the very rapid and recent accumulation of short-term external debt." The rating
agency also points out that "the spill-over effects of any financial instability
may also have negative implications for Thailand's long-term foreign currency
debt ratings".

<P> Asia Equity's Greenwood believes the situation is not as serious as Moody's
claims. He argues that while nominally the figures show $41 billion of short-term
debt, the booking of part of the debt figure by BOT was inaccurate and is being
re-examined. Some $9 billion of the short-term debt figure, Greenwood says, comes
from Bangkok International Banking Facilities (BIBF) loans arranged by foreign
branches of Thai banks. (BIBFs are offshore banking operations which enable
institutions to borrow non-baht currencies overseas and lend either domestically
or offshore.) This is effectively long-term debt since it is being raised as
long-term money offshore but lent back into Thailand as short-term money.

<P> A further $9 billion, says Greenwood, comes from foreign bank lending, mainly
by Japanese BIBFs, which involves borrowing short-term and relending long-term to
Japanese companies in Thailand, replacing much of the equity which used to be
booked as foreign direct investment. Greenwood puts genuine short-term debt at
nearer $23 billion than $41 billion &#173; $30 billion at the outside.

<P> The BIBF is the centrepiece of Thailand's attempts to liberalize financial
markets, and management of the resulting flows has challenged the BOT. Some of
its measures to rein in the economy have not earned much praise. Most recent
among these have been restrictions on lending by BIBFs. The minimum loan size has
been increased from $2 million to $5 million, and total domestic BIBF lending by
local institutions has been capped at 7% of baht loans, with the aim of stemming
short-term foreign capital inflows. Foreign BIBFs are required to match
one-for-one their domestic and offshore loan extensions. The result of these
measures will be increased interest rates as demand for credit intensifies, thus
restoring confidence in the baht but tightening liquidity &#173; at least that is
the theory. But conventional wisdom has a way of being turned on its head in
Thailand.

<P> "It is hard to contemplate the future without more shocks," says the
Kleinwort Benson report. The build-up of short-term debt, predominantly through
BIBFs, has been a chief cause of concern, increasing exposure to changes in
international sentiment. Total foreign debt was around $83 billion at the end of
1995, of which $16.4 billion was public and $66.2 billion was private, including
$23.7 billion from BIBFs.

<P> Thailand's current problems have been worsened by financial liberalization at
a time of economic slowdown. Many of the domestic institutions are just not lean
enough, or lack the necessary expertise, to compete in a freer market. There is
also a fundamental change affecting Thailand and many of its Asian neighbours as
companies shift from cheap-labour manufacture of such goods as textiles and
footwear to businesses harnessing technology, management and skilled staff. Jan
Cherim, general manager at ING Barings in Bangkok, believes Thailand is facing an
extended period of readjustment. "The thing that astonished me is the way in
which expectations have been so bizarre about the Thai market," he says. "In the
first part of the year export growth dropped to single digits and everyone
panicked as if the sky was falling in. People forget what it means. It just means
exports are growing at a slightly slower rate. I'm not at all pessimistic about
growth. It is about time they shifted gears, and not at all unhealthy &#173; you
cannot defy gravity with these ridiculous figures for ever."

<P> "The current economic downturn apparently caught forecasters off guard," says
Tara Siam Business Information in its latest quarterly economic review. Managing
director Chesada Loha-unchit says: "All the major economic indicators clearly
point to a downturn in the Thai economy and there is a chance that unless
something is done quickly, it may be headed for a hard landing." The company
forecasts growth at 7.2% for this year and next, with 6.2% inflation for the full
1996 year. "It is quite clear that Thailand can no longer be complacent in taking
external factors such as international capital flows and major world currency
alignments for granted," says Chesada. "The experience of the last few years has
clearly shown that traditional economic policy tools, although not completely
ineffective, cannot be used in the same way in an economy which has become much
more open. The high interest rate policy in an environment of controlled foreign
exchange risk is the most glaring contradiction."

<P> <B>The derivatives question</B>

<P> One consolation is that shocks will not be magnified through derivatives.
Thai banks and companies are still not using derivatives to any large extent, and
the foreign banks are tending to lend offshore in US dollars, with proceeds
swapped into baht, with most borrowers tending to have dollar revenue, says
Goldman Sachs regional banking analyst Wanna Matanachai. However, some of the
dollar borrowing is not fully hedged. "If the BOT starts to widen the currency
band it could have some repercussions," says Wanna. A number of Singapore banks
are exposed to straight Thai lending, but Japanese banks account for a huge slice
of BIBF lending and are the most vulnerable.

<P> Thai convertible bonds were heavily traded by foreigners offshore in the week
before the election. A number have put options close to maturity that look
certain to be exercised. One Thai company which appears to have prepared for the
problem is listed Sino-Thai Engineering and Construction, which raised an $80
million loan recently to cover the early redemption later this year of its $80
million 10-year convertible, which was lead-managed by Jardine Fleming and Swiss
Bank Corporation in 1993. The loan was arranged by the Singapore branch of HSBC
Investment Bank.

<P> Companies that may not be so fortunate include troubled Somprasong Land and
Bangkok Land, which have another two or three years' breathing space on their
puts. Although property companies are likely to be hardest hit, those in volatile
sectors such as electronics could also be struggling. A notable exception is
Alphatec, which has already made provisions to fund redemption of its bond due
1999, which is puttable next June at 111.25%.

<P> "Maybe one or two have adopted the ostrich management style, and there will
be fireworks," says Cherim of ING Barings. On the other hand, most convertible
issuers are high-profile companies and if it seems they might have to default,
they will go running to their main local relationship banks for help. "They will
mortgage their first-born in exchange for being bailed out," says Cherim. It is
unlikely they will be able to refinance in the public markets, he says. "Price
targets are a million miles off. It would be a very brave investor who did not
exercise the put," he adds.

<P> The authorities have been tinkering with financial rules and regulations for
the last year and a half. Some policies have been announced and then rescinded or
modified while others have never got past the ideas stage. The latest is an
announcement by the central bank that as part of its new open market policy no
limits will be imposed on lending growth next year. Lending growth was restricted
to 21% this year, compared with 24.5% last year. Finance ministry permanent
secretary Chatumongol Sonakul was quoted as saying the move was the first step
towards a free-floating baht, but that would not happen until "sufficient
devices" were in place. The central bank is also looking to appoint primary
dealers through which to trade government securities in order to control
liquidity.

<P> Ironically, it was the Mexican peso crisis which contributed to the brevity
of the latest cycle in Thailand. The crisis increased emerging markets' capital
costs and focused attention on capital accounts. Since the beginning of 1995,
measures to stem capital inflows to Thailand have included an increase from 2% to
7% in the reserve requirement for non-resident short-term baht bank deposits, and
a similar reserve requirement for finance companies; exclusion of "non-priority"
foreign currency loans in calculations of banks' net foreign exchange positions;
and a rise in the minimum capital adequacy requirement from 8% to 8.5% for
commercial banks, and from 7% to 7.5% for finance companies.

<P> <B>In the clear</B>

<P> These policies seem to be working with BIBF out-in loans &#173; money
borrowed offshore and on-lent domestically &#173; dropping by about 1% to $30.7
billion. Average monthly net inflows into non-resident baht deposits fell from
$1.3 billion in the first quarter of the year to $150 million in the second
quarter.

<P> A research paper by Thai broker Phatra Thanakit calls for a relaxation in
exchange controls over the long term. "Given the irreversible trends of
globalization and financial liberalization, it is necessary for the local
financial system to withstand dramatic and frequent changes. The pressure is
likely to increase when inflows are short-term in nature because of the risk of
quick reversal," says the paper. "The current exchange rate regime in which the
value of the baht is pegged to the basket of currencies makes it increasingly
difficult for the Bank of Thailand to effectively control domestic liquidity and
money growth. In other words, it is not possible to simultaneously maintain the
exchange rate and interest rate stability, while foreign capital is fully mobile.
To cope with the highly volatile and mobile capital inflows, it is crucial for
the exchange rate system to shift from the peg system to a more flexible exchange
rate policy."

<P> Even if Thailand has avoided a Mexico-style crash it must still face up to
the poor condition of many of its banks and companies. The stock market has been
adversely affected by poor third-quarter results from major companies along with
continued worries about the health of the banking sector,  exemplified by the BBC
scandal which revealed huge bad and doubtful debts put at around Bt20 billion and
brought charges of embezzlement against senior bank executives.

<P> Most of Thailand's 15 commercial banks are believed to have serious bad debt
problems, exacerbated by the close-knit, often family-oriented, nature of their
operations. This leads to intra-group lending and judgments on creditworthiness
that are at best unsophisticated and at worst highly questionable. The drive to
report ever-increasing profits has meant provisioning has not always been as
stringent as it might be.

<P> The property market has been one of the key reasons for the woes of banks and
finance companies. The bottom has dropped out of a market which only two years
ago looked like a licence to print money. Residential demand has dried up, and
there is an oversupply of office space.

<P> "The financial system is strained by poor-quality loans made during the
upswing of the present cycle in 1994-95," says a Morgan Stanley report. "The
finance companies are in worse shape than the banks because of their larger
exposure to property." Morgan Stanley puts non-performing loans at 4.1% in the
second quarter for finance companies, compared with 3.9% for the whole of 1995.
The ratio for banks was 7.7% in 1995, but the investment bank was unable to come
up with a definitive figure for this year.

<P> The smaller banks, which lack the huge branch networks and capital base of
their bigger counterparts and are under more threat from liberalization, have
fared worst. But in a report entitled "Crisis? What Crisis?", Morgan Stanley
notes: "We believe the Bank of Thailand is capable of managing the problems in
the financial system and avoiding a system-wide crisis. The central bank does not
want banks to fail, and it has the instruments to prevent failures and the
experience to manage the work-out of troubled institutions."

<P> On all fronts, it seems, Thailand's technocrats are managing bad situations
well. But if Thailand is in the clear what is needed now are long-term measures
to take account of  new economic realities. The new finance minister Amnuay
Viravan is a former banker. Will he go down in history as the man who freed the
Thai baht?

<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

