<H3><B> ASIAN BANKS </B></H3>

<P>

<a href="em.96.12.6a.html"> Japanese top 50 </b></a>

<P>

<a href="em.96.12.6b.html"> Asian 100 </b></a>

<P>

<a href="em.96.12.6c.html"> Asean top 25 </b></a>

<P>

<a href="em.96.12.6d.html"> Australian top 25 </b></a>

<P>

<a href="em.96.12.6e.html"> Indian sub-continent top 25 </b></a>

<P>

<a href="em.96.12.6f.html"> North Asia top 25 </b></a>

<P>




<H3> <B>Korea and Taiwan dominate
<I>Euromoney's</I> latest ranking of Asian banks with 21 of the top 50 between
them. Australasia has been included in the list for the first time this year,
with four Australian banks in the top 10. Japan's banks still suffer from the
country's poor economic condition and their performance is improving only slowly,
writes Rebecca Dobson</B> </H3> 

<P> The Republic of Korea dominates
<I>Euromoney</I>'s 1996 table of the top Asian banks with 21 entrants, 11 of
which appear in the top 50. Only Housing &amp; Commercial Bank rises, however, up
28 places to 55, with equity almost doubled at $880 million from $469 million.
Government ownership was reduced to 46.8% following an initial public offering
(IPO) in January, when the bank changed its name from Korea Housing Bank to
reflect its new commercial status.

<P> Among the 20 Korean banks that lost ground, Korea Exchange Bank, at 16, is
the republic's largest commercial bank with shareholders' equity standing at $2.9
billion, ranking second behind Korea Development Bank. A breakdown by total
assets sets Korea Exchange Bank above its peers at $70 billion (up from $55
billion according to last year's figures). Also worth noting are Shinhan Bank,
whose equity is up to $2.3 billion from $1.9 billion after last year's rights
issue, and Kookmin Bank, which brought two share issues to the market in 1995,
reducing the government's stake to 23.94% and raising the bank's equity from $1
billion to $1.5 billion.

<P> Taiwan is also distinguished with 10 banks in the top 50. However,
deregulation and the creation of 16 new banks since 1990 have increased
competitive pressure and produced a drop in net income and a rise in funding
costs. The economy is slowing, especially in the domestic market with GDP growth
now around 6%, and all banks have fallen in the ranking except Taiwan Cooperative
Bank, which remains at 39. Significant changes include the Bank of Taiwan, which
drops to 13 from seven with a 7.64% fall in profits; Chang Hwa Commercial Bank,
down to 37 from 30 &#173; its fall in profits is 16.07%; Chung Shing Bank,
slipping 24 places to 88, reveals its shareholders' equity to be down by $12
million to $542 million.

<P> <I>Euromoney</I> has responded to readers' suggestions and extended this
year's Asian 100 to cover Australasia bringing seven banks from that region into
the chart. Four banks appear in the top 10 &#173; National Australia Bank,
Westpac Banking Corp, Australia &amp; New Zealand Bank and Commonwealth Bank of
Australia &#173; ousting Bangkok Bank, Oversea-Chinese Banking Corp and Bank of
Taiwan.

<P> Overall, there are 17 new entrants into this year's ranking. In all, only 13
banks move up the list, 64 fall, and six remain in last year's position. Three
Philippine banks make it into the ranking this year: at 47, Metropolitan Bank
&amp; Trust Co's recent aggressive strategy has paid off with shareholders'
equity up to $912 million from $601 million following its rights issue in August
1995 &#173; the fourth since 1993. Philippine National Bank drops to 73; its
equity fell from $816 million to $640 million due to the sharp decrease in asset
reclassification reserves. Philippine Commercial &amp; Industrial Bank enters the
top 100 at 76.

<P> Of the six Malaysian banks to feature in the ranking this year, only Bank
Bumiputra moves up &#173; just two places to 50. Malayan Banking and Public Bank
slipped by eight and nine places respectively to 25 and 45 after a quiet year in
the domestic equity market. Indonesian banks have dropped too: Bank Rakyat
Indonesia falls by 10, Bank Negara Indonesia by 18, Bank Dagang Negara by 18 and
Bank Ekspor Impor Indonesia by 19.

<P> Japan's top 50 banks are much the same as last year. The decline in the yen,
bankruptcies, weak credit growth and a struggling consumer sector are hindering
the economy and bank performance is sluggish. Newly-merged Bank of
Tokyo-Mitsubishi tops the rankings by shareholders' equity and by total assets
and boasts the second highest net profit at $414 million after Dai-Ichi Kangyo
Bank.

<P> Profits elsewhere are significantly lower as bad loans and falling property
prices persist. Some of the highest ranking banks show the steepest losses: Fuji
Bank (minus $3,021 million), Sakura Bank (minus $1,694 million) and Sanwa Bank
(minus $1,157 million). Sumitomo Bank, which recorded losses last year of $3.2
billion, has regained some lost ground and rises to third from fifth place with
net profits of $367 billion.

<p>
</td>
