<H3><B> EUROPEAN IPOs </B></H3>


<H2> <B>When it's time to leave home</B> </H2> 

<H4> <B>Family businesses often
fight shy of the exposure required by a stock exchange listing. Yet if family
firms need fresh capital for growth or to meet the competition, a public offering
needn't spell the end of family control. James Featherstone looks at the state of
European private-company flotation and the investment strategies of 13
family-controlled businesses. </B> </H4> 

<P> Only a tiny proportion of the
hundreds of thousands of family-owned companies in Europe are listed on
exchanges. But increasingly, second- and third-generation family members are
seeking to raise capital and realize some of their assets. An initial public
offering (IPO) is not a straightforward decision for management. A wider choice
of exchanges, a greater emphasis on equity investment in continental Europe and
generally buoyant capital markets have increased the profile of flotations as a
way of raising capital. But such considerations as loss of total control, the
greater disclosure required of a company when publicly quoted and the effects of
share-price volatility on corporate fortunes can make managers think twice about
an IPO.

<P> Although public listings are an increasingly attractive option, there is
evidence to suggest that family-owned businesses are more hesitant than other
private companies about undertaking them. A recent survey of the corporate
finance requirements of Dutch companies undertaken for the Amsterdam Stock
Exchange by market research company The Netherlands Institute of Public Opinion
and Market Research (Nipo) found that although 32% of companies polled said it
was "highly likely" they would go for a public listing within three years,
family-owned companies were consistently less enthusiastic. The more stringent
disclosure requirements involved was the main reason cited. Private companies
with a wider spread of share ownership are generally larger than family
businesses, so the extra financial openness involved in a public listing is more
acceptable and familiar to them. Many family companies do not have much or indeed
any experience of disclosing information to third parties.

<P> In addition, the price sensitivity of quoted stock and the larger number of
shareholders can cause owners to worry about loss of control. Italian packaging
company EMA, which listed on the Milan stock exchange last year, is a case in
point. EMA's share price initially doubled before falling back to the issue price
on the back of bad annual results and a strong lira, which hit the company's
export earnings. Italian companies that depend heavily on exports, such as the
fashion houses featured here, have more reason to be concerned about a domestic
listing than a suitable foreign one, since an appropriate foreign listing can
insulate them from currency fluctuations. Choosing the right exchange is one of
the most important decisions for a family company (see box).

<P> Domestic political events affect family companies' listing decisions. In
Italy, for example, the tax breaks that did so much to direct the attention of
Italian entrepreneurs to the stock exchange look unlikely to be renewed in the
1997 budget, which it is expected will conform to the deficit requirements for
European monetary union. Companies doing IPOs in Italy were given a 16% rebate on
corporation tax for the three years after a listing. A Milan-based Italian
companies analyst said: "Italian family entrepreneurs don't care that much about
listing. If this tax window closes, there will not be a great incentive for them
to go public." Alternative markets may still prove attractive, but local
conditions can affect companies' perceptions of the effectiveness of publicly
quoted equity.

<P> <B>Catching up slowly</B>

<P> An increased readiness on the part of investment managers Europe-wide to
increase the proportion of equities in their holdings is stimulating stock
markets and making listing a more attractive prospect for family companies. But
continental Europe is still far behind the UK and the US. In Belgium on average
businesses trade for 90 years before listing; in the UK it's 17 years. Of the
top-10 investment managers in Europe ranked by total pension fund assets under
management, nine are UK-based. These funds have holdings of $724 billlion, 81% of
which is invested in equities. French mutual funds, by contrast, which are second
only to the US in their total holdings, are only 15% invested in equities. The
German figures are even more striking &#173; only 9% of pension fund holdings are
in equities. Attitudes to equity in Germany are strongly affected by the banks'
approach to corporate finance which still tends to stress partnership and loans
rather than listed equity.

<P> Change is in the air. Dutch pension funds are set to increase their equity
weighting by anything up to 30%. Even the cautious Danish institutional funds,
which are prohibited from holding more than 20% of their portfolios in equities,
are giving them greater consideration. Governments and financial institutions
&#173; including French mutuals &#173; are beginning to realize that equities
might provide the added value bonds, cash and money market instruments cannot
muster. French fund management companies are having to cope with short-term
interest rates that have halved recently, hence the appeal of equities.

<P> This change in equity culture is running parallel with many family companies
going public as part of the natural development of their businesses. A number of
academic studies have shown that the third generation in a family concern is most
likely to sell part or all of its holdings, so companies founded in the first
half of this century are now poised to consider doing this.

<P> Family businesses then, more than non-family owned concerns, will have to
weigh the greater access to investment funds, the release of capital and the
higher company profile against the greater disclosure requirements and the
greater risk of equity capital markets.

<P> <B>Italy</B>

<P> Italy and Germany have the largest proportion of family-owned businesses in
Europe so there is great potential for IPOs. A number of Italian fashion houses
were tipped by analysts as likely candidates. The almost miraculous success of
the Gucci flotation on the New York Stock Exchange last year has drawn attention
to similar companies still in family hands. Before listing, Gucci had to contend
with a highly damaging family war and a series of bad business decisions that led
the Italian government to appoint a chairman to try to stabilize the company. But
the flotation was a great success. The issue was heavily oversubscribed and
within the first week of trading Gucci's share price increased by 20%. So other
Italian fashion houses are now well placed to take advantage of positive investor
sentiment.

<P> <B>Valentino</B> Rumours of an IPO for Milan-based fashion house Valentino
are growing. Giancarlo Giametti, its co-owner, has stated publicly that the
company is talking to US investment bank Goldman Sachs about a New York Stock
Exchange listing. As with the other Italian fashion houses featured here, a US
presence is important. The proposed listing makes sense &#173; Valentino opened a
new flagship store on New York's Madison Avenue in September. Goldman Sachs was
brought in by the company in 1995 to advise on a programme of restructuring and a
possible flotation. But there are obstacles. Giametti and chief designer
Valentino Garavani want to retain a stake after the listing and it is rumoured
that this halted talks with Goldman Sachs earlier this year. Although the company
does not reveal ownership details, it is well known that Garavani owns around 65%
and Giametti the rest. "The fact that Goldman Sachs has the mandate for
restructuring makes a listing a near certainty," says an Italian broker. "We're
expecting it any day now."

<P> <B>Ducati Motor</B> Italian motorcycle manufacturer Ducati Motor is a good
bet for an IPO in the longer term. The company is a recently formed joint venture
between TPG Partners, a $720 million private investment partnership owned by US
investment fund Texas Pacific Group, and Italian holding company Cagiva, which is
controlled by Claudio and Gianfranco Castiglioni. The deal went through in
September this year, TPG Partners acquiring a 51% stake in Ducati. The remainder
of Ducati Motors is owned by Cagiva, which bought Ducati in 1985. Large
injections of investment or venture capital are a strong indication of an
eventual listing. A spokesman for TPG Partners says a listing by Ducati Motors
was "a very real possibility", but that TPG Partners and Cagiva want to "build a
strong trading company first". Ducati has proved its trading strength by posting
an annual growth rate of 25% for the last five years &#173; sales in 1995 topped
$200 million. Ducati is a niche manufacturer that produces fast, powerful &#173;
often red &#173; bikes. Recent additions to the product line include the popular
Sport Naked, known as Il Mostro to devotees. Deutsche Morgan Grenfell advised TPG
Group and Cagiva on the purchase and a consortium of Deutsche Morgan Grenfell,
Banque Paribas, and Banca Commercial Italiana provided financing.

<P> <B>Prada</B> An analyst for a Milan-based brokerage company used a novel
method for assessing rumours of an IPO from fashion company Prada: "When I was in
New York recently, the crowd in the Prada shop there was very impressive," he
says. "That I find interesting. They should be listed somewhere." This is backed
up by harder evidence. The fashion business is a dynamic sector in Italy and
Prada is up with the leaders. In the last few years it has taken advantage of an
upturn in the luxury goods sector and has posted good growth and sales figures.
Prada recently staged a joint show with UK artist Damien Hirst at the Florence
Biennale featuring a live zoo. No investment bankers were present to sound out
the possibility of a public offering.

<P> <B>Salvatore Ferragamo </B>If Ferruccio Ferragamo, the Milan-based fashion
house's group chief executive officer, chooses not to go public, his five
children and other members of the Ferragamo family will inherit a rapidly
expanding business. Like the other fashion houses featured here, Ferragamo is
exploiting an upturn in the luxury goods market, posting a 34% increase in
turnover last year compared with 1994. In the last two years the company has
widened its geographical coverage by opening new shops in such places as Sydney,
Melbourne, the Australian Gold Coast, Dubai, Beijing and Monte Carlo. But
Ferragamo's own retailers account for only 25% of sales; the balance being
wholesale.

<P> Ferragamo has similarities with Gucci, the formerly troubled fashion company
that was floated so successfully in New York last autumn. Both companies are
family-owned, they produce goods for the same sector and Ferragamo has been
tipped for a flotation for a number of years, as was Gucci. Ferragamo, unlike the
pre-float Gucci, is in a very sound position and the company is not obliged to go
public in order to sort out family and financial problems.

<P> It can also take advantage of the tight control it has over its branded
products and franchises, two areas the Gucci management allowed to slip away in
the years leading up to its IPO. Ferragamo has held to a focus on shoes and other
luxury leather goods, its traditional specialities, avoiding uncontrollable
proliferation of products &#173; a problem Gucci had to address before listing.
If Ferragamo goes public, the choice of stock market may be simple: 45% of sales
are to the US and US investors now have a proven appetite for Italian fashion
houses.

<P> Such a sound business has inevitably attracted the interest of investment
banks. But the company is still entirely in family hands and a spokesman told
<I>Euromoney</I> it has no plans to list. Wanda Ferragamo, the wife of the
founder, is still in charge as president of the group she runs with her six
children, including Ferruccio Ferragamo.

<P> <B>Diesel </B>Renzo Rosso, founder and sole owner of Diesel, has never worn a
suit to work. Corporate finance officials looking for business from the northern
Italian clothing company may want to bear that in mind along with Rosso's
management ethos: "You can't run a business by the book ... I don't much care for
qualifications and titles, the important thing is the person fits into the group.
When you give someone the chance to fly, they very often do."

<P> The company has all the right credentials for going public: dynamic growth, a
high European profile with wholly owned subsidiaries in France, the UK and the
US, and the potential for further expansion. This makes Diesel an attractive
investment prospect. The Italian brokers and banks <I>Euromoney</I> spoke to have
been waiting for Diesel to list in Milan for some time. Marina Tosin, a company
official, said Diesel is preparing for an IPO and is looking to list some time in
1998, probably on the New York Stock Exchange. But Tosin insists that Diesel is
in the very early stages. "We are still studying the project," she says. "The
date is not fixed, it could be postponed." Diesel has yet to approach an
investment bank, either in Italy or the US, to advise on the issue although Tosin
says a US bank would be favourite for lead manager.

<P> <B>Air Europe</B> An Italian carrier based in Gallarate in central Italy, Air
Europe has an ambitious expansion programme. New aircraft and new routes outside
its main domestic market are partly to be financed by a listing on the Milan
stock exchange scheduled for a so-far undecided date next year. It is studying
the possibility of an IPO managed by Sopaf, an Italian investment bank that owns
18.4% of the airline. Management is looking to float 25% of the company, the
minimum requirement for a listing on the Milan stock exchange. However, the
company says it has not made a firm decision to list in Italy. "We are at the
beginning of the process and we don't know where we are going to float," says
Lupo Rattazzi, Air Europe's president and a member of the Rattazzi family which
owns an interest in the company. Decisions such as these will be taken by Sopaf
which, according to an agreement signed when it became a shareholder in Air
Europe, will be lead manager in any listing. According to Rattazzi, 1997 is the
most promising date for a listing because it is a favourable point in the airline
industry cycle. The company expects a slowdown in growth in 1998 and wants to
take advantage of a public offering before then.

<P> <B>Belgium</B>

<P> The Belgian equity market has been sluggish since the mid-1980s, the last
period when there was much activity in new listings, but a number are expected in
the short to medium term. High-profile textiles company Syoen Textiles listed on
the Brussels exchange on September 30 and has performed well so far. Brokerage
companies spoken to by <I>Euromoney</I> expressed confidence in prospects of a
rising stock market.

<P> <B>Interbrew </B>An IPO from Belgian brewing conglomerate Interbrew is high
on the wish list of brokers throughout Europe. But information is sparse.
Interbrew has a reputation for discretion and does not disclose information on
which families own the company, how much they own, what the company owns, or how
large it is. But some facts are known: Interbrew is effectively controlled by the
de Spoelberch and Van Damme families. It is generally assumed that between them
they control most of the stock. A large number of companies are owned and
controlled by Interbrew. Canadian brewer John Labatt, Dutch brewers Orangeboom
and Dommelsch, and Interbrew France are all 100% in Interbrew hands. It also has
controlling interests in two Italian breweries and a number of eastern European
breweries. This year Interbrew has moved into China with the partial acquisition
of the Zhu Jiang and Sichan Blue Sword breweries. In 1994 the company sold its
interests in a number of African breweries.

<P> A spokesman for Interbrew said there were no plans to list on any stock
exchange and never had been and that there was no reason to list. But the high
level of gearing taken on after John Labatt was acquired last year has prompted
speculation about an IPO. "Interbrew is such a big company it's incredible that
it is not public," says the head of research at a Belgian brokerage.

<P> <B>Germany</B>

<P> Germany has over a million family businesses, so the scope for IPOs is large.
But the Neuer Markt, Frankfurt's second exchange, will not open until March 1997.
And although the Frankfurt exchange has been pushing all-time highs recently it
has relatively few new issues and listing requirements are stricter than many
companies would like.

<P> <B>Georg Urban </B>Ulrik Urban is the fifth-generation owner and managing
director of Georg Urban, a conglomerate founded by the Urban family early in the
19th century. The company holds a wide range of subsidiaries with interests in
record production, food manufacturing, car importing and building.

<P> Georg Urban is growing strongly and the need for more capital is the main
reason for its seeking a listing early in 1997 on AIM (the Alternative Investment
Market), the UK's second market. Ulrik Urban ruled out a listing on the Frankfurt
stock exchange because he believes equity investment in Germany is
underdeveloped. Waiting for the Neuer Markt to open was not an option as the
disclosure requirements are more stringent than AIM's. Urban believes the main
methods of raising finance in Germany &#173; partnerships and bank loans &#173;
are too restrictive and rarely include a stock exchange flotation. "An exchange
like AIM is very much needed in Germany," he says. "It will be difficult for any
German company to go to the Neuer Markt but easy to go to AIM." The companies
Urban wants to float would be too small to list on the Frankfurt exchange but are
well suited to AIM, which presently lists 13 foreign companies. Ulrik Urban will
be listing the first German companies on AIM and hopes to open the way for many
more, increasing the profile of public equity as a way of raising capital in
Germany. "In Germany people put their money in a fund, get 5%, and are happy," he
says. "They are just not aware that they can invest in a stock market; even if in
Germany you are still restricted in the companies you can invest in."

<P> <B>Denmark</B>

<P> <B>Tinglev Element</B> <B>Fabrik</B> Expansion plans and a reluctance to
increase borrowing lie behind Tinglev Element Fabrik's decision to list on the
Copenhagen stock exchange in the spring of 1997, says finance director Jorn
M&oslash;ller. The company, based in Tinglev, produces prefabricated concrete
building structures for the German market. Almost 99% of Tinglev Element Fabrik's
business is done in Germany, mainly former West Germany. Managing director Jacob
Cnutsen owns 75% of the shares, the rest being in the hands of Danish investment
fund LD Invest. Cnutsen will not be selling any of his stock in the company.
M&oslash;ller says no decision has been taken on the lead manager for the float,
although Alfred Berg is in talks with the company.

<P> <B>InWear</B> Clothing company InWear has recently announced that it will
seek a listing on the Copenhagen stock exchange in the near future. Managing
director and majority shareholder Nils Martinsen has good reason to look forward
to going public. He owns 92.5% of the Dkr389 million ($66 million) shareholder
equity in the company he founded 27 years ago. Total shareholder equity is 53% of
total assets.

<P> There is no obvious reason why InWear should list now. It has had
considerable success as a Europe-wide clothing retailer and has financed
expansion internally so far. Martinsen says simply: "The time was right for a
listing". Additional financing for further expansion is not, says Martinsen, a
principal reason for floating. Plans could be financed from existing capital, he
said, without the boost a listing would bring.

<P> Expansion so far has been impressive. Apart from the manufacturing division
of the company, InWear has 12 sales companies it owns directly and outlets in 25
countries. It is a major exporter &#173; some 85% of its clothes are sold outside
Denmark. Profits are very healthy: up 90% in the year to June 1996. Den Danske
Bank and Alfred Berg have been appointed co-sponsors for the float.

<P> <B>The Netherlands</B>

<P> <B>SHV Holdings</B> "The market view is that it might happen one day and it
should happen one day, but there is no firm information at the moment," a leading
Dutch broker said recently about the prospects of an SHV Holdings flotation. SHV
was founded in 1896 from a merger of Dutch coal-trading companies. Today it has
two main businesses controlled by an intermediate holding company: SHV Energy,
which produces and trades energy and raw materials, and SHV Makro, which is a
Europe-wide retail company. Both main businesses have subsidiaries worldwide and
total sales are fls26 billion ($4 billion) and income fls829 million.

<P> SHV Holdings' equity is controlled by the Fentener van Vlissingen family and
other members of the board of directors. Total equity is almost fls4.5 billion,
total assets fls13.5 billion and a workforce of 56,000 makes it one of the
largest companies in the Netherlands. A company spokesman says it is not
considering a flotation.

<P> <B>Blokker</B> A large retailer selling mass market household goods and toys,
Blokker has a dominant position in the Netherlands, with 430 stores. It controls
more than half the market for toys and a large part of the household goods
market. "Blokker is a good example of a family company which people say should
list," said a Dutch companies analyst. "It has a strong market presence and would
be a success if it floated." The company declined to make any comment.

<P> <B>Ireland</B>

<P> <B>Dunnes Stores</B> A market-leading Irish supermarket chain owned by the
Dunnes family, Dunnes Stores trades mainly in Northern Ireland. The sector is
highly competitive but dominated by a small number of companies: the top-five
retail organizations account for 71% of market share. Family-owned companies
still control most retailing, but analysts expect this to change as foreign
supermarket chains expand in Ireland. Listed UK supermarket chains Sainsbury and
Asda have both indicated a desire to expand into Ireland and Tesco is likely to
do so soon. The large reserves set aside by these companies for investment far
outweigh the resources of Irish supermarket companies. A flotation by Dunnes
Stores could be a realistic way of financing competition, but the company denies
that it has been considering such a strategy.&#009;*

<H2> <B>Friends of the family</B> </H2> <P> European family-owned companies
considering initial public offerings (IPOs) are beginning to look beyond domestic
exchanges. With the advent of Easdaq (European Association of Securities Dealers
Automated Quotation) and Euro NM, the two new pan-European exchanges, and the
longer-established US trading system Nasdaq (National Association of Securities
Dealers Automated Quotation), there is now greater choice. All three systems are
actively marketing themselves to European small-cap to mid-cap growth companies.
Many family-owned businesses fall into this category. But the national exchanges
are also realizing the importance of attracting family businesses that might not
feel comfortable with a full listing. In particular, second markets around Europe
are an obvious choice for family companies.

<P> Easdaq is a screen-based trading platform using multiple market-making. It
opened on September 26 and expects to have 15 companies listed by the end of the
year. Investors are able to buy Easdaq-listed stock from broker-dealer members in
15 European countries and the US.

<P> Euro NM is a joint venture between the French Nouveau March&eacute;, the
German Neuer Markt and the Belgian Nouveau March&eacute;. The Dutch second
market, the New Market Amsterdam, was set up in September this year. It will
apply for access to Euro NM. The three existing Euro NM member exchanges have
developed joint marketing and common regulations and will move towards joint
front-end technology for members.

<P> US trading platform Nasdaq lists more than 90 European companies. Fifteen of
these joined in the first eight months of this year, making Nasdaq a serious
challenge to the ambitions of Euro NM and of Easdaq, in which Nasdaq holds a
share. There is no dual-listing agreement between Nasdaq and Easdaq, but if a
company has a Nasdaq listing it will find it easier to get one on Easdaq.

<P> National exchanges still attract companies for reasons of familiarity and
history and some stock exchanges are marketing themselves specifically to
family-owned businesses. The Antwerp stock exchange has been concentrating on
building a relationship with Belgian family companies. Michel Neerink, head of
marketing for the exchange, says the Antwerp exchange aims to be the main Belgian
exchange for the listing of family-owned companies. "We are not looking for
high-tech companies," he says. "We have developed an entirely new stock exchange
system with very attractive procedures for family companies: low cost and high
liquidity." The exchange is not open for trading at the moment, but has amassed a
database of over 700 Belgian family-owned companies that look like suitable
candidates.

<P> The new pan-European exchanges are unlikely to stimulate new listings that
have not already been thought through by companies. Before it started trading,
Easdaq commissioned research from consultants Coopers &amp; Lybrand into the
number and type of companies that were likely to consider listing on it. Coopers
found that almost half the firms surveyed had already considered an IPO and were
the sort of candidates Easdaq was seeking to attract. The decision to list had
been made regardless of the opening of Easdaq and Euro NM. Charles Kirwan-Taylor,
managing director of equity capital markets at London-based investment bank BZW,
supports this view: "Euro NM and Easdaq are a response to the desires of the
companies listing. I don't think that setting up an exchange will necessarily
provoke the selling of a business, which is often an intimate decision made
within the family."

<P> Stanlislas Yassukovich, chairman of Easdaq, agrees with this analysis. "They
tend to be companies that have outgrown their local market and have products and
services that start to have a Europe-wide audience. They then have to contemplate
giving up 100% family control in order to raise that capital. That, amongst other
reasons, is one of the main motives behind the whole Easdaq project."

<P> Yassukovich is confident that Easdaq can thrive in an environment which is
well provided with stock markets. He believes Easdaq may end up taking business
away from the national exchanges: "Ultimately, there could be a degree of
migration amongst large and mature companies from the national exchanges to
Easdaq. I think that will only happen when Easdaq has built a network of
broker-dealer membership and a critical mass which makes it an attractive
alternative to national exchanges." But for the first few years of its operation
Easdaq expects to focus on the high-growth, high-tech sector that has found such
success on Nasdaq. A major European software giant comparable to Netscape or
Microsoft would help Easdaq raise its present low profile and convince companies
it is a viable alternative to national exchanges.

<P> In the UK, AIM (the Alternative Investment Market), the London Stock
Exchange's second market has 13 foreign company listings and is looking to add
more. The experience of Ulrik Urban (main story) in turning to AIM is an
indication that the exchange could attract many other continental European
companies since its listing requirements are relatively relaxed. It also has a
higher profile among investors than continental European second markets and so
greater liquidity.

<P> There are complex decisions to be made by companies as more alternative
markets come on stream but one thing that will be uppermost in the minds of CEOs
and their investment banking advisers is the need to go where the money is. What
is good for the Swiss computer software manufacturer that wants to reach the
widest possible selection of investment managers may not be good for the Italian
pasta company for which the number of investors is less important than how
focused they are and how well they understand the peculiarities of the business.
UK property companies, for instance, make up a disproportionate number of
AIM-listed companies since property investment by fund managers is more developed
in the UK than elsewhere in Europe. For a property company there may be no
advantage in tapping into the investment opportunities offered by a pan-European
exchange. The widest possible pool of potential investors is always a good thing,
but that pool could well be found in a company's own country. In fact BZW's
Kirwan-Taylor does not expect small to medium-sized European family companies to
stray too far from their local exchanges. "In a European context, unless there is
a particular reason for going to a foreign bourse &#173; like being involved in a
high-tech sector &#173; most companies would probably attract greatest interest
through their local exchange." The undercapitalized pasta maker in central Italy
may still find that going where the money is means a listing on the Milan Stock
Exchange.

