<H3> EDITORIAL </H3>


<H2> <B>This time it's for real</B> </H2> 

<P> It is easy to be cynical about
Japan's professed keenness to liberalize its financial system.

<P> Recently <I>Euromoney</I> met the chief executive of one of the country's big
securities firms. He argued vehemently in favour of radical deregulation. But
when <I>Euromoney</I> asked whether he supported deregulation of fixed stock
commissions, he argued equally vehemently that this would be disastrous.

<P> All too often in Japan, policy changes such as this are decided purely on the
basis of which interest groups are able to exert influence &#173; rather than
what is best for the country. The securities industry, for example, has great
sway over the ministry of finance and therefore has been able to defeat attempts
to liberalize commissions for two decades.

<P> But last month new finance minister Hiroshi Mitsuzuka announced a Big Bang
for the Japanese financial system &#173; including the freeing of commissions.

<P> This time it could happen. Although Mitsuzuka's proposals were sketchy, there
is a growing consensus in Japan that change &#173; and probably radical change
&#173; is inevitable.

<P> Taboos are being challenged for the first time. The most widely reported one
is the tentative plan to split up the ministry of finance, perhaps spinning off
an office of banking supervision. But no-one thinks this will do much to reduce
the power of the MoF. Indeed, many ministry officials believe that, on the
contrary, it will increase their power by creating a "colony" which they would
dominate.

<P> More potentially significant are the reforms of public institutions which are
under discussion. The financial activities of public bodies (from city
governments to bodies such as the Japan Development Bank) are minutely controlled
by central government. This has made them inefficient, and skewed the market.

<P> The key is what happens to post office savings. At present, the post office
pays above-market rates to its depositors; the funds are forcibly on-lent by the
MoF to public bodies. That has hampered the development of Japan's banks (and
forced them into risky businesses &#173; with well-known consequences) and
concentrated too much power in the hands of the MoF.

<P> Why are we surer that this time reforms will be implemented and will make a
difference? First, political consensus has swung behind this theme. All major
parties in last month's election supported administrative reform.

<P> There is a realization that Japan cannot go on as it is. The economy is
stagnating &#173; economists predict that long-term growth is unlikely to go
higher than 1 1/2%. The government is embarrassed that Japan's financial
institutions are so backward by international standards.

<P> But, most importantly, there are the first signs that some politicians are
beginning to think strategically about what system would be best for Japan &#173;
rather than merely mediating in the battle between interest groups.

<P> Can Japan silence the cynics who doubt that it can change? For the next few
months, events in Tokyo will be worth watching.

<H2> <B>Russia gets it right</B> </H2> <P> It is very easy to be cynical about
Russia too. Its economy and political system don't yet work like those of a
developed country. That makes it easy to poke fun at.

<P> But give Russia its due. When it came to the bond market for the first time
last month, its debut issue was probably the best ever by a sovereign borrower.
That was, to a large extent, due to the professional way the Russian government
handled the transaction; it also reflected the growing perception of investors
that Russia is on the path to steady economic development.

<P> When lead managers JP Morgan and SBC Warburg began final preparations for the
issue, it looked possible that the best the issuer could expect was a $500
million bond, with a maturity of only three years, and pricing at a humiliating
500 basis points over US treasuries. In the event, such was the excitement
generated by the transaction that the issue size was increased to $1 billion, the
tenor to five years and the pricing was 345bp over &#173; cheaper even than the
formal price-talk range.

<P> Syndicate managers say the Russian finance ministry did everything right. It
waited until after the presidential election and the publication of credit
ratings for the country, rather than rush ahead with the issue at the beginning
of the year. Officials soon learned the importance of sending the finance
minister on roadshows, despite initial reluctance.

<P> Improving economic fundamentals in Russia helped. Annual inflation is down to
6.5% (from 2,642% in 1992) and the rouble has been stable for months.

<P> The creation of a benchmark issue has its minuses too. It will be the chosen
vehicle for many investors to take a view on Russia. Want to know how Russia is
perceived? Just check the level of the 9 1/4 of 2001.

<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

