<H3> MARKET MONITOR </H3>



<BR> <B>Edited by Peter Lee </B>

<H4> <B>MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES</B> </H4> <H2> <B>Play it, SAM</B> </H2> <P>
Fancy a bond secured on a zero-interest, interest-only, life-long loan? With the
Bank of Scotland, you can now borrow 25% of the value of your house and not repay
a penny for the rest of your life. SBC Warburg is securitizing the mortgage and
foretells this brand-new market will soon be worth hundreds of billions of
dollars worldwide.

<P> The shared appreciation mortgage (SAM) has just been launched by the Bank of
Scotland, fully refinanced by SBC Warburg in advance of a securitization in the
first quarter of 1997. But how interested will investors be in the securitization
of an asset with no track record &#173; because it has not existed before.

<P> The concept is simple: the homeowner pays zero or low interest; the bank, in
return, gets participation in any increase in the value of the house when it is
sold. In the case of the zero-interest SAM, as opposed to a low-interest SAM, the
bank sees a return on the original loan of three times the increase in house
values. So if Bank of Scotland lends a homeowner 25% of the value of a property,
it will receive 75% of any increase in value when the home is sold, plus the
original 25% loan. If the homeowner pays 5.75% interest, then the 3:1 ratio
reduces to 1:1. A mortgagee might borrow 65% of the value of a property and pay
5.75% interest on that for life.

<P> When the property is sold, the Bank of Scotland gets 65% of the increase in
value along with its loan back. In short, the homeowner, as well as issuing debt,
issues equity.

<P> This is the kind of risk which investors might well be happy with, but which
no bank would like to see on its balance sheet. So SBC Warburg is securitizing
it.

<P> Craig Corn, director of global residential property markets at SBC Warburg,
has been working on this project for the past two years. He brought in Bank of
Scotland about a year ago. He's evangelical about the benefits of the SAM. "For
most people," he says, "the future value of their houses is not at the front of
their mind. What they need is cash flow. People need money to top up their
pensions, to pay school fees, or something less financially responsible, like
going on a cruise. At the moment, 80% of most homeowners' portfolios is house:
they really ought to diversify, especially given that historically equities have
performed much better than house prices."

<P> Corn is banking on there being a lot of investors who want direct exposure to
the retail property market. They've never been able to have this before, having
to rely on substitutes such as equity in construction companies. Pension funds
should be interested, because historically house prices have not only
outperformed inflation, but matched increases in earnings; most pension fund
liabilities are earnings-linked. Property funds should certainly be interested.
And there's enough equity in the bonds to encourage some equity investors as
well, although the mortgages are being sold on the basis that stock markets have
historically outperformed house prices.

<P> Corn claims that the structure of the mortgage has been carefully designed to
encourage holders to make improvements to their house and to maximize its value.
And they won't be able to buy high and sell low, doing sweetheart deals on the
side, because the repayment amount is based on valuations and not capital gains.
The equity participation is based on the difference between two prices: the lower
of the buying price and the value of the property when the mortgage is taken out,
and the value of the property when the mortgage is paid off. From this figure is
subtracted any increase in value directly attributable to improvements made by
the homeowner after taking out the mortgage.

<P> The SAM has been designed as a remortgaging vehicle, rather than a
house-buying instrument. It is aimed especially at pensioners, who may want a
higher income but are not so interested in capital gains on their home on their
death.

<P> The 5.75% SAMs will be securitized into fixed-rate notes with a coupon of
about 55% of the 10-year gilt yield; the zero-interest SAMs will be securitized
into floating-rate notes with a coupon of about 60% of three-month Libor. Both
will then pay a quarterly coupon of all the income from the mortgages that
quarter, both capital repayment and shared appreciation. The maturities will be
more than 50 years, although SBC Warburg will be able to "sweep up" outstanding
bonds when 80% of the underlying assets are sold.

<P> The reason that the zero-interest SAMs can pay floating-rate is that, by the
time they are securitized, they will have been deleveraged. Sixty per cent of the
price of the bond is invested in Libor-yielding securities, thus accounting
directly for the coupon. This doesn't add anything to the bond: it makes it look
a little more like the securities investors already know.

<P> But it isn't like anything the capital markets have seen before. "It's a
convertible bond wrapped up in a securitization vehicle," says Corn, who does
find it difficult finding a useful analogy. "It's a property-linked bond." "It's
an equity securitization." "It's a mortgage-backed security." "It's equity in
retail housing." "If I had to pick one bond which it was like, I'd say it was
most like an index-linked gilt, linked to house prices instead of inflation."

<P> In fact, it's a curious hybrid. The underlying assets are a combination of
debt (the original loan) and equity (the shared appreciation). If this market
takes off, it's inevitable that the equity will be stripped out and traded
separately; at the beginning, however, the two come together. The Bank of
Scotland is taking no interest at all in its loans: 100% of the debt and equity
from them goes to bondholders, with the Bank of Scotland receiving only a fee.

<P> Trying to value the debt part of the bonds alone will be horrendously
difficult. It's secured on lifetime interest-only loans which have never been
issued before, so there's no data on when the sort of people who take out these
loans either sell or die, or how good their credit is.

<P> With typical mortgage-backed securities, the danger is prepayment of loans;
here, it's more likely to be the opposite. Furthermore, says Corn, "the
prepayment rate is very different from normal prepayment rates. Normally, it's
driven by interest rates. Here, it's driven by home turnover."

<P> But if trying to value a zero-coupon bond when you don't know the maturity
date is difficult, then trying to come up with a vaguely scientific method for
predicting future house price rises is even harder. "The value of the bonds is
the value of any appreciation in house prices plus the net present value of any
future appreciation," explains Corn. "The pricing is a trade-off between interest
rates, house prices, actuarial calculations and other factors. But the main
factor driving the market price of these securities will be what investors think
house prices are going to do in the future." He predicts a rosy future for
housing analysts with experience of the hitherto largely useless art of working
out what drives retail property prices.

<P> The initial pricing will be based largely on SBC Warburg research, because
few investors will be able to price the bonds themselves. This research will
depend on a detailed breakdown from Bank of Scotland of who has bought the
mortgages. The fixed income and equity desks at SBC Warburg will sell the
securities. Eventually, however, the bonds will be traded more like equity, on
price/earnings and debt/equity ratios.

<P> SBC Warburg promises to make a market in its bonds, although they won't be
actively traded at first &#173; Corn likens them to illiquid corporate debentures
in this respect. He's confident, however, that the market will become very large
very quickly. "Look at the UK alone," he says. "There's &#163;1.2 trillion ($2
trillion) of property value, of which &#163;800 billion is net wealth." Once SBC
Warburg has started to tap this resource, other banks will want to get in on the
act.

<P> To do so, however, will require sophisticated risk management systems and a
lot of capital. The mortgages have to be refinanced by the bank before they are
securitized. At the moment, SBC Warburg is refinancing up to &#163;100 million of
very peculiar Bank of Scotland mortgages (&#163;150 million to &#163;200 million
of bonds after deleveraging) with no guarantee that it will ever be able to shift
them off balance-sheet.

<P> But Corn is convinced that this will be a huge part of the international
capital markets, from Europe to Asia and even the US, where the domestic housing
market is worth $11 trillion. He foresees people being able to buy houses worth a
higher multiple of earnings, because it's not the amount of debt that lenders are
worried about so much as the level of repayments.<B>Felix Salmon </B>

<H3> <B>UK house prices versus inflation and earnings</B> </H3> <IMG
SRC="Images/em.96.12.13a.gif" WIDTH=258 HEIGHT=157>


<H4> <B>CORPORATE BONDS</B> </H4> <H2> <B>Putting on a natural hedge</B> </H2>
<P> The surge in investment-grade corporate puttable bonds this year, which
Securities Data estimates totalled nearly $15 billion at the end of November, up
from $8.9 billion last year, is being driven by investors who've turned to
puttable bonds as the hedge of choice for their unpredictable mortgage-backed
securities portfolios. That is providing bond issuers with the means to cut their
funding costs through various put structures.

<P> Big investors, including for the first time insurance companies, are turning
to puttable bonds to reduce the negative convexity in their fixed income
portfolios.

<P> Greg Hopper, a portfolio manager for Bankers Trust Global Investment
Management, explains: "If you bought something that has an embedded call option
in it, like a callable corporate or a mortgage bond, where the underlying
mortgages can prepay, what will happen is that as the market rallies the bond has
a higher chance of being prepaid," says Hopper. "The bond will not keep up with
the rally. Then as the market declines, he notes, "there is less likelihood of it
being prepaid so it will go down much more quickly." In other words, callable
bonds may offer a higher yield but they underperform straight bonds in a bull
market and perform even worse in a falling market.

<P> The traditional remedy for this problem is what's called a delta hedge. That
requires buying treasuries as the market goes up to maintain the overall duration
of the portfolio. Duration, a combination of an issue's maturity and coupon, is a
measure of the sensitivity of a bond's price to movements in interest rates.

<P> In practice, delta hedging can be difficult and expensive particularly in the
choppy and volatile markets of recent years. If the market rallies by half a
point, and an investor<B> </B>buys the treasuries, but then the market declines,
"then you bought at the top and are losing money on the hedge", says one
investor.

<P> Puttable bonds, on the other hand, are "sort of a natural delta hedge,"
claims Hopper. If an investor buys a 30-year bond, with the right to put it in 10
years, it will cost only about 20 more basis points than a 10-year bond. Some
yield is sacrificed. But if interest rates start falling, the puttable bond will
rise in value, extending the portfolio's duration. "The whole problem of duration
has become such a hot topic and so important to portfolio managers over the past
few years, that they've discovered this tool," Hopper says.

<P> In the past embedded options have been undervalued. And since market
volatilities have been higher than the assumptions on which the puts have been
priced, "buyers are getting a better deal than the issuers", argues Salomon
Brothers bond strategist Dennis Adler.

<P> Adler notes that historically high levels of puttable bond issuance have
occurred during periods of low interest rates and flat yield curves. In such an
environment, if rates go up, the bond will be put. In the case of, say, a 30-year
bond with a 10-year put, the issuer will have got, say, 10-year money, for 20
basis points less than if he had issued a straight 10-year bond.

<P> In the past, the lower yields associated with puttable bonds have been
anathema for many investors, particularly the insurers. "Two or three years ago,
they would not have wanted to give up the yield. It's a sea change of thinking
for them," says Adler. Much of the new interest in puttable bonds has been
foisted on the insurers, however. It is driven by a capital charge the rating
agency Standard &amp; Poor's began calculating in early 1995 when assessing the
creditworthiness of life insurance companies. "The reason there's a demand for
puttable bonds is because of S&amp;P's convexity test. It only started after we
said 'look what's going on here'," says Patricia McWeeney, the director of
insurance rating services. "When you see what the numbers look like, it makes
sense to hedge it." S&amp;P's methodology attempted to extract the option risk in
the mortgage-backed securities by stressing interest rates and comparing them to
single-A non-callable corporates under the same conditions.

<P> Life insurers are snapping up the puts to help cover the inherest risk of
their mortgage-backed securities. Their aggregate investment in those securities
amounted to over $273 billion at the end of 1994, according to S&amp;P. With the
outstanding puts at about $30 billion, estimates Adler, there's plenty of room
for more puttable bond issuance.

<P> Insurers started buying the mortgage-backed securities in the early 1990s,
after being stung by the credit risks associated with the real estate downturn
and a deterioration in the credit of high-yield bonds. At that time, insurance
companies were being forced by regulators to capitalize their credit risk only,
not the interest risk, making the securities attractive investments.

<P> Before the mortgage-backed securities market meltdown in 1994, many insurers
had about 50% of their portfolio in mortgage-backed securities. Today the
percentage is between 15-25%, with the largest firms having a higher percentage,
estimates S&amp;P.

<P> The 1994-95 markets hurt the performance of insurers' portfolios, says
McWeeney. During 1994, interest rates rose dramatically, causing the securities
to underperform. "During 1994, insurers were losing 2-10% on the mortgage-backed
securities relative to corporates," she says. The following year, rates rose,
creating a surge of prepayments. "The numbers were larger than people expected."
Holders of callables were hit hard by negative convexity.

<P> This year has been relatively calm. But with the 10-year treasuries below
6.25%, that could trigger a surge of refinancings by homeowners who bought their
homes some time during the past two years, says John Nolan, portfolio manager for
Bankers Trust Global Investment Management.

<P> Puttable bonds have been particularly useful for portfolio managers who don't
want to sell the mortgage-backed securities they may be holding, particularly if
it would mean booking a loss. Moreover, when puttable bonds are designed to be a
mirror image of what a mortgage security does, "you can create something like a
traditional bond with a lot more yield," says Nolan.

<P> While the puts themselves have a lower yield than a regular bond would, when
combined with another security, that's not the case. He says the combined yield
might be 20-40 basis points higher than a traditional bond. "The pitch has been
that there's value there," says Nolan, adding that's because "there's some risk
because there's not an exact fit between the two."

<P> Nolan notes that a lot of mortgage securities act like a three-year security
in a rally, and a 10-year one when rates rise, he says. If such a security was
paired with a 10-year bond with a put at three years, the combination of the two
would offset each other. However, most puts aren't designed that way. The most
popular this year has been a 30-year bond with a 10-year put, although bankers
are coming up with a variety of structures that might prove more useful to
investors.

<P> The most interesting are "step-ups," in which the coupon is increased if not
put, or multiple-year puttable bonds. Deutsche Morgan Grenfell's 30-year bond for
the Province of Quebec, which is puttable every year after 10 years, or Morgan
Stanley's Tennessee Valley Authority bond, which matures in 2036, but is puttable
at years two and 10 &#173; the so-called put-put bond &#173; are the types of
structures investors are clamouring for.

<B>Michelle Celarier</B>

<H4> <B>EURO COMMERCIAL PAPER</B> </H4> <H2> <B>Back from the dead</B> </H2> <P>
Euro commercial paper (ECP) always seems to get a raw deal. It's forever regarded
as the poor relation of its American cousin, and is only known for the withdrawal
from the market of several major banks at the turn of the 1990s, and its very
tight margins. These usually represent no more than two or three basis points of
a deal.

<P> Two more banks left the ECP market this year: Chase started to pull out at
the time of the merger with Chemical in March, and Bank of America pulled out
over the summer. While this might appear to bode ill for the market, the
remaining banks are hopeful that it will help to alleviate chronic overbroking:
"We're not looking for a cartel," said one dealer. "But we do want the market to
be as economical as possible."

<P> This year has seen other developments to encourage the remaining
participants. The latest figures released by Euroclear show ECP outstandings for
the first 10 months of 1996 at $106 billion: not a large amount compared to the
US market which has $750 billion outstanding, but it does represent an increase
of 18% over 1995. It has moved the market away from the stasis of $80 billion
which had dogged it since 1991.

<P> There is also an impression of shortage of supply. Pieter van Dyck, director
and product manager of ECP and EMTNs at SBC Warburg, widely regarded as the ECP
market leader, estimates this could be as much as $100 billion, although the
present excess demand is limited to certain high-grade names.

<P> Those banks still active in ECP maintain they have a strategic commitment to
what they regard as an essential part of the capital markets. "Any house that is
serious about offering a comprehensive service to its customers must have a
strong ECP desk," says Warburg's van Dyck, . "The ECP market offers such a
diversity of short-term product that all investors with significant cash balances
want to be in it. Also, in respect of mergers and acquisitions, ECP is
increasingly becoming part of the scene, so how can you act as an M&amp;A adviser
if you don't have an ECP desk?"

<P> One reason for the increase in outstanding paper is the expansion in the
number of issuing currencies over the past four years. The main change has been
the loss in market share of dollar-denominated paper in favour of European
currencies, especially the Deutschmark and sterling. The dollar share has
declined to 55% this year from 84% in 1992, according to SBC Warburg.
Non-European currencies have also grown in importance, especially the Australian
dollar, the yen, and the Korean won, which is seen as relatively low risk since
Korea was granted OECD associate status. Most of the main ECP houses expect
issues in other Asian currencies such as the Thai baht and the Malaysian ringgit
to become more frequent as investors begin to search for paper yielding more than
the traditional currencies.

<P> The diversity of currencies has led to a deeper ECP market: up to 50% of the
market is now based on synthetic ECP, allowing participants to arbitrage spot and
forward foreign exchange.

<P> ECP is also becoming a more competitive and attractive source of funding.
Dominic Surry, executive director and head of CP and FRNs at Lehman, mentions one
aspect: "This year we have seen increasing demand from central banks for ECP as
new sovereign programmes have come on line and comparable investments have become
less attractive. The huge net redemptions and increasingly tight spreads,
relative to Libor, in the floating rate note market are a major factor
contributing to this trend."

<P> Commercial paper should also benefit from the growth of the repo market:
"With the Bank of England making the repo market its intervention tool of choice,
the importance of eligible bills will probably be reduced," says Jonathan Boyd,
head of money markets and repo at Deutsche Morgan Grenfell (DMG). "So bank
appetite for holding them, especially bills of acceptance, will drop and they
will not be such a cheap source of funding for corporates. Commercial paper would
be the ideal alternative."

 <B>Antony Currie</B>

