<td valign=top align=left> 


<H3> DIARY OF AN INTERNATIONAL INVESTMENT BANKER  </H3>



<H2> <B>A new way to calculate bonuses </H2>

<H4> Ingersoll and Komarovsky learn to suffer while Iceberg preserves his golf swing</B> </H4>

<P> JJ Ingersoll, our
head of global focus, looks distraught. I walk into his office where the NFL
playoffs dominate his 25 screen info-revolution wall. "Are you running a book on
this?" I ask, looking at the spread on the score. JJ rolls his eyes, upwards and
onwards, almost beating the elevator to the 85th floor. 

 <P> He passes me an
immaculate ready-for-publication piece of paper, topped with the firm's new logo,
a harpsichord inside a US dollar sign, and its new global-slogan message, coined
by our new head of global scansion, Kristina Onomatopeia-a-Stasis. I look at it:
"Banking was founded on a bench in Renaissance Italy," it reads. "Black Knight
&#173; the art of banking. Call freefone 123-Glasso-Steagallo." Beneath is a
disclaimer:<I>This message is not intended to sell you anything. Consult local
regulators for details. Corporate headquarters in Delaware.</I>

<P> "More of the same", I comment. "No," JJ hisses, "not that client crap &#173;
the memo beneath." The catchy new slogan and global-image-presence had taken my
eye momentarily off the ball, or rather the memo from our chairman, Ace Iceberg,
which reads:

<P> <I>November 30, 1996. To all general and limited
partners, and other liabilities</I>. <I>Subject: killing two birds with one
club.</I> It's at this time of year that my usually excellent golf swing starts
to seize up. You know why? I believe, and local golf pros corroborate my
conclusions, that it's because I spend so much of the month of November signing
bonus checks. This is not good for my wrist, and causes a slicing action to
develop. While my golfing partners appear to have got used to this annual
dropping-off in my game, I haven't.

<P> So when myself and the little guy, Halmchinkel Maladroit Analretentive, were
out at Madame Fou-fou's last week we came up with an idea. I think it's excellent
and I'm sure you will too.

<P> This year I'm going to take all them checks to the driving range, attach a
pen to the end of my club and play through them, one by one.

<P> With a handicap like mine you can be sure that some of those checks will be
invalidated. This, however, will be good for the bottom line. So don't get too
disappointed if you receive an envelope containing ripped pieces of starchy paper
rather than the sum you were expecting.

<P> Just to be fair, I'm getting Arnold Palmer to sign my $8.5 million on a
putting green somewhere in Santa Monica four inches from the cup. The full board
will be there to watch and get his autograph afterwards."

<P> As if this was not bad enough, says JJ, and it is, Iceberg's personal
assistant, Cutter Ensign, has introduced a whole series of algebraic formulas to
make the process of bonus determination more account-friendly.

<P> These as you can imagine are fantastically complex.

<P> The calculation goes something like this. Every department
is divided according to its contribution to pre-tax net revenues, and then
compartmentalized according to its proximity to elevator shafts, its number of
desks, and the ratio of how many cups of coffee to Dr Peppers it drinks during
Asian trading hours. A department's collective weight (with shoes on), is used to
fine tune the process, and kicks-in a depreciation factor for the erosive effects
on carpet-weave of the chief trader's 300 pounds, and the number of times per
hour the graduate trainees are sent out for burgers.

<P> This provides the initial "cut", and determines which departments get zip.

<P> Departmental heads then rank staff on a score of one to 60.8, divide the
result by the wind speed (in West Ridge, Iowa), square the result, examine
individual wear and tear on computer keyboards penalizing heavy-finger users on a
four-point scale, factor in vending-machine costs, lactation room overheads,
overhead airline pollution, internal memo production costs, state skyscraper
taxes, stock tips for the window cleaner (or natural light enhancement
consultants, as they now wish to be called), write-offs for rogue traders, and
finally add 100, subtract 101, divide by four, and multiply by two, amortize in a
microwave for two minutes, then convert any distance-error from yards into
millimetres, discounting the cashflow completely.

<P> The result is an amazingly accurate figure for an
employee's output accurate to four decimal places across the 325 trading days
(before Christmas). It excludes occupational risk, breathing space constraints,
and Whelk's law of motion. Otherwise, it's perfect.

<P> Though no one has yet seen the fruits of the new system, all of those who
aren't going to leave anyway, are every bit as concerned by Cutter Ensign's so
called equal and opposite initiative to slash costs "beyond the bone, taking out
just enough marrow to keep the patient alive and able to write tickets," as he
was heard telling someone in the gents. The memo arrived last Friday.

<P> <I>To all staff, including jj Ingersoll</I>: It has
come to my attention that expenses are too high based on our forecast profits of
$997 million for the year. I have some ideas:

<P> 1&#009;Telephones. I sometimes wish we could return to the days of two paper
cups attached by a piece of string. Alas the cost of a piece of string from New
York to Tokyo is even more expensive than present arrangements. But staff should
restrict greetings to "Hi [shorter than hello], this is x at Black Knight." Then
say, "I hear the kids are alright. Listen I think we can do a bit of business for
you."

<P> 2&#009;Decaff coffee is expensive. Can't you just drink it at home and behave
like a normal person at work?

<P> 3&#009;It is, of course, permissible to use a cellular phone in cases of
family tragedy, but just to phone up and say Hi, I'm alive, how's your day been
honey, is completely unnecessary. Our phone operator has been instructed to
disconnect any call where the words "honey", "baby", "darlin" or "squidgy" occur.

<P> 4&#009;Fax machines. Surely there must be a more cost-efficient way of
dealing with clients? I suggest the Internet, and I have just employed a
consultant on a $6 million retainer to show us how.

<P> 5&#009;Expense claims are sloppy and often lacking in justification. Bribing
Italian &#173; as I saw on one recent claim &#173; is hardly acceptable. For tax
purposes we need to know<I> which</I> Italian.

<P> 6&#009;My next memo will offer suggestions on how to make business travel
more efficient. For example, if we all took our family holidays at airport
Sheratons we'd get fantastically competitive block deals. The food is much better
in airports than it used to be, so have a think about it.

<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

