<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra11.gif" alt="Column">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 


<H3> THE MOORGATE SAGA  </H3>


<H3> <B>Catchgrouch</B> </H3> 

<P> <B>Last National Bank of Boot Hill, Moorgate,
London EC2</B>

<P>

<IMG SRC="Images/em.96.12.20a.gif" WIDTH=168 HEIGHT=40 ALIGN=TOP>


<P> The trouble starts as usual with Harvey Q Schicklgruber III.V, who is our
senior vice president (strategy and forward planning), in most corporations this
title means the guy has no place in their strategic forward plans, but Harvey is
the favourite great nephew of old Mr Schicklgruber, our president, you look at
him and wonder what the other great nephews are like.

<P> It seems Harvey reads in <I>Loaded</I> or the <I>Tombstone Epitaph</I> or
some such blatt how Europe has this scheme for a new currency, replacing all the
others, to be called the euro or emu and be managed out of Frankfurt by a guy
called Duisenberg they hire from Rentadutchman, so Harvey wishes to know in broad
strategic outline what the bank's international presence in the London office
plans to do about this.

<P> Like if there is only one currency around here what do our
foreign exchange dealers find to do all day, and how do we know if these euro
notes fit in our teller machines, and can we be first off the blocks with some
euro innovation, or at least sponsor a seminar, by invitation only, Harvey
fancies Cannes in May, and besides, how soon can we up sticks from Moorgate and
relocate to Frankfurt where the action is?

<P> Mom, if Harvey ever goes to Frankfurt looking for some action he had better
not go on a Tuesday, because that is the day she goes to Wiesbaden to see her
aunt, or so the guys in Guten Morgen Grenfell tell me, it is why they go to so
much trouble  to set up shop in London, even if they now get told the place lacks
discipline.

<P> But about this euro or emu or whatever, the Brits' official line is to lie
down and hope the whole thing goes away, which saves them making up their minds,
and meanwhile the Bank of England says that London is prepared for anything, so
nobody need worry, tho' the old hands in the Bankers Club figure when the Bank
says this it is the signal to start worrying.

<P> I take a straw poll there at the Martini hour, where the mood is we all look
forward to the euro because then we can go short of it, remember the ERM, just
think of the money we make shorting sterling, and even more money betting that
the whole shebang breaks up, and when it does this gets blamed on an Anglo Saxon
conspiracy of guys in red suspenders, fame at last!

<P> The keenest guy of all is Stani, who looks in for a glass or two for old
sake's sake, he says once this euro gets started all the Brits need to do is stay
out, then London can become the centre of the euro euro market, this is how we
get started all these years ago, he says, maybe it is not too late to reinvent
White Weld.

<P> Even so I am not sure this is the line to take with Harvey, in his game he
gets his ideas at airport bookstands, for six bucks some snake oil merchant
passes on the secret of how to get a seven digit bonus out of corporate strategic
creativity, so Harvey expects to see inspiring prose with bullet points and
executive summaries, tho' maybe for him they need summarizing.

<P> I figure our experienced public relations adviser must know who can write
this sort of junk for us and dress it up as a report, sure he can, over lunch at
the Dealmakers Arms he offers to find a foundation that commissions a research
shop to call up some economist and see if he has anything in his word processor
that fits the bill, and then all we need (he says) is a design consultant and a
print buyer, it mounts up, of course, no point in trying to do these things on
the cheap, Angelo, I say, can you give the liqueur cart a fair wind, there is a
drought round here.

<P> He has a deal, at that, I figure it is well worth three months' revenues if I
get Harvey off my back, all I insist is this economist of his looks in on me and
tells the story like it is, the unsanitized version, just in case I ever need to
know, but afterwards I feel just like the guy who goes to see John Foster Dulles,
on account he is confused about the State Department's policy, and when he comes
out he is still confused, but on a much higher level.

<P> The way I get it from him, this euro club means different things to different
players, for the French it is a plan for coping with the Germans, after the plans
they try in 1870 and 1914 and 1940 they figure it is time for a new one, and this
suits the Germans too, like this they dress up as good Europeans and can throw
their weight around and look respectable.

<P> Then the Belgians hope they can palm off their national debt on the Germans,
and the Irish vote for anything so long as their monthly check keeps on coming
from Brussels, and the Club Med agrees, most of all the Italians, they figure if
they can get their finances out of the grasp of Italian governments this must be
an improvement, and their government feels that way too, and of course it rigs
the books in this good cause, or one set of books, on account Italy is the
birthplace of double entry book keeping.

<P> This becomes a matter of national pride, every country
must show that it qualifies, the French help themselves to $6 billion out of a
pension fund to put their books straight and get their guy in Brussels to certify
that this is quite OK, and this euro or emu begins to look less like a proof
strength currency and more like a fruit cocktail.

<P> By now, my economist says, the penny is starting to drop in the markets, the
search is on for safe havens, like the Swiss franc and even sterling, the closer
you look at this euro club the more it looks like the club that Groucho Marx
declines to join, who would want to join if it admits the candidates it has lined
up?

<P> I just hope the guy can rewrite this in an airport bookstand style so it
keeps Harvey quiet, but I dare say strategy and forward planning are what land
Europe in this mess in the first place, much love from

<P> Your clubbable son

<IMG SRC="Images/em.96.12.20b.gif" WIDTH=300 HEIGHT=50>


<P> <B>Herbie's report is ghost-written by Christopher Fildes </B>

<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

