<td valign=top align=left>
<H3>A SUPPLEMENT TO EUROMONEY/DECEMBER 1996</H3> <BR>

<H3> Asian property: reaching ever higher </H3> <BR>

<H3> Supply and foreign demand </H3> 

<H4> <B>Foreign companies are driving top-end property prices ever higher. </B> 


<B>But will underlying demand keep pace with development plans? Gill Baker reports on the property
markets of Asia</B> </H4> 

<P> The ebb and flow of foreign confidence in Asian
countries has had a dramatic affect on demand for Asian property. While domestic
fortunes will always constitute the core of underlying demand for property, it is
overseas players which are driving the top end of the market.

<P> Hong Kong remains the powerhouse of Asia's property markets and the 1997
hand-over to China was well and truly factored into the market a long time ago.
Hong Kong's success looks set to spill into mainland China's property market,
with massive growth forecast in office supply. In China foreigners are propping
up the commercial and top-end residential market in the key centres of Shanghai,
Beijing and Guangzhou.

<P> But restrictions in a number of Asian countries on foreign ownership of
property have kept most foreigners firmly in the leasehold and rented end of both
the residential and commercial markets.

<P> Where market regulations are more liberal, foreign commercial demand for
business property has led to growing investment from developers, often from
neighbouring Asian countries. Singapore-listed Wing Tai Holdings is a typical
example in its attempt to replicate its transformation from garment manufacturer
to property developer in Singapore through its 45% owned Malaysian associate DNP
Holdings. Analysts say DNP holdings has amassed 10.6 million square feet of
residential and commercial land in Kuala Lumpur, Penang and Prai in Malaysia.

<P> Many Asian property markets have started to mature. Research and valuation
are taken ever more seriously and large-scale property development and investment
companies have entered even the smaller markets. But a shortage of experienced
analysts dogs Asia's property market &#173; a surprising number of research
houses still do not cover the sector.

<P> Opportunities for speculation abound in Asia's diverse property markets. Hong
Kong is riding another boom, Singapore is slowing down, while some say Thailand
is on the brink of collapse.

<P> <B>Hong Kong </B>

<P> The Mass Transit Railway Corporation project and the hand-over to mainland
China are old news in Hong Kong. Land reclamation is now the largest single
factor affecting Hong Kong's cramped property market. Although the market is at
its crest, the island's encroachment into the sea could be its eventual downfall.
Analysts fear that land reclamation and continuing property development will
cause an over-supply in the market. Listed Sun Hung Kai Properties, the largest
property company in the territory, has said it will spend HK$14 billion ($1.7
billion) on development in the current financial year to June.

<P> Most analysts still agree that Hong Kong's property market is the one to
watch.  "Hong Kong is one of the best markets in Asia because of the shortage of
supply and substantial demand, particularly in the top-end luxury residential
market, and that will continue throughout 1997," says David Runciman, Asia
chairman for international property consultancy and estate agency Richard Ellis.
Residential prices in Hong Kong have been hitting the highs reached in the 1984
boom at the peak of the last property cycle, and the bull run is expected to
continue according to ING Barings.

<P> Residential and non-residential sales rose an impressive 31.7% month-on-month
in October, with 13,889 agreements signed for property across the board,
according to latest Land Registry figures. Apartment sales alone were valued at
HK$18 billion.

<P> The performance of Hong Kong's commercial sector, however, is open to debate.
"There is a lot of speculation going on and some hope that Chinese money will
come into the market," says an analyst at ING Barings. In the long-term, however,
there is still the spectre of over-supply in the office market in particular. The
question is whether or not there will be sufficient demand in the future.

<P> The Hong Kong and Chinese economies have been slowing relative to their
heydays of double digit growth, yet property prices are still rising. Rents in
Wan Chai North, Admiralty, Causeway Bay and North Point rose in October according
to the Vigers/Bridge Hong Kong property index.

<P> <B>Singapore</B>

<P> Singapore's property market appears to be defying the economic signals,
remaining steady despite the slowing economy.

<P> Although sentiment is weak in the residential market, according to Tan Khow
Siong, property analyst at Deutsche Morgan Grenfell, the standstill between
buyers and sellers has kept prices stable. Research by Richard Ellis describes
the deadlock between buyers and sellers as "a temporary disparity in expectations
between sellers and buyers as both wait for a clearer direction of the market".

<P> Says Scott Poland, a London-based analyst at Citibank's real estate division:
"There has been a lot of speculation on the residential side, and that is where
the concern is going to be. It's going to be a tough year in 1997."

<P> The Singapore government's measures to curb speculation, introduced in May,
had, and continue to have an impact. Applications to buy private properties fell
40% from May to June this year. The measures include restrictions on housing
loans and the introduction of a tax on income gains from property sold within
three years.

<P> But despite the crackdown, there were 11,000 applications for the 592 units
in Pidemco Land's new executive condominium developments of Eastvale and
Westmere. And the market saw the launch of 15 new private residential
developments in the third quarter, putting an extra 2,300 units onto the market.
Richard Ellis still expects to see a 10% average price increase for the full
year.

<P> The market is likely to remain patchy for the rest of the year unless the
price deadlock can be resolved. But with the hand-over of Hong Kong, Singapore
will continue to attract more business, and money.

<P> <B>Philippines</B>

<P> "We are in a sort of a limbo at the moment. We entered 1996 relatively
bullishly but towards mid year there crept in more anxiety about supply," says
Raffy Manalaysay, director of research at broker Crosby UBP Securities in Manila.
"Now people are waiting for the so-called bubble to burst," he adds.

<P> Manalaysay is concerned by the rapid price rises of the past three years. But
Crosby believes that no such bubble exists, just isolated problem areas,
particularly in the high-end luxury residential market.  The market has become
fragmented with office and residential markets going their own separate ways.

<P> "Our biggest area of concern is the high-end vertical residential market,"
says Manalaysay. The ambitious Fort Bonifacio development, a 214 hectare former
state-owned site which is being developed into Manila's third business centre, is
expected to have another dozen or so projects under way in the next six to nine
months, many of them high-rise luxury residential buildings. But Manalaysay
dismisses its effect, and that of satellite development Filinvest Corporate City,
as discounted in the market already.

<P> As a whole, the Philippine property market looks fairly healthy: the economy
is expanding and finance is available for end-users. While office development
continues apace in Manila's business districts of Makati and Ortigas, there are
also signs of growth in the pocket development north of Metro Manila. Says
Citibank's Poland: "The question is whether in two or three years time [Manila]
will be overbuilt. The question then will be whether there are enough companies
relocating to Manila. I seriously doubt it."

<P> <B>Malaysia</B>

<P> Tighter monetary policy, which has cooled Malaysia's economy, has also put a
curb on the property market.

<P> Malaysia's residential property sales index, produced by Malayan Banking
Corporation and the Rating Agency of Malaysia, rose from 100 to 163.86 points
from 1994 to the end of the second quarter of this year, but fell in the second
quarter as the government's credit tightening measures came into force.

<P> Government curbs include a M$100,000 ($40,000) levy on property purchases by
foreigners and an increase in property gains tax to a range of between 15% and
30% for residents and a flat 30% for non-residents.

<P> At Crosby Research in Kuala Lumpur, property analyst Lynne Chiang is cautious
about the high-end residential market, particularly in the context of government
restrictions on foreign purchases, and over-supply in the sector for the last two
years. Chiang is also worried about the latest Malaysian bandwagon of bungalow
lots &#173; high cost second home resorts. Medium-cost residential property,
however, is still looking good, supported by domestic demand. But, says Chiang:
"We don't have any screaming buys. Everyone is waiting for the cycle to slow
down."

<P> The commercial property market is less healthy as over-supply poses a major
problem. Although a number of businesses are moving from older buildings to newer
offices, tempted by incentives such as rent-free periods and reduced service
charges, Crosby sees occupancy rates falling from a current level of 90% to
around 85%.

<P> <B>Thailand </B>

<P> Thailand's property developers have not had an easy ride this year. The
marked slowdown of the economy and a massive drop in the stock market have
squeezed many firms to the brink of collapse. Small-scale residential developers
have been hardest hit, but bigger players are also struggling.

<P> But office construction continues and this is likely to add to the market's
problems in the future. The residential sector has remained static because of
oversupply. Bank of Thailand measures to keep a rein on inflation and liquidity
have also hit the property market, especially its curb on lending for property
development.

<P> The industry has also been rattled by the arrest of Prasong Panitpakdee,
managing director of listed Somprasong Land, who, now out on bail, has been
accused of falsifying financial statements. He has yet to plead. Commentators
believe there is widespread fiddling by many property companies. The most popular
scam is to book down-payments for houses as completed sales.

<P> Lack of cash flow is also causing problems for property companies' debt
repayments, and this is likely to have a knock-on effect on the country's banks
and finance companies, a number of which are linked to their borrowers through
family groups.

<P> Among the troubled property companies, Rattana Real Estate and Country
(Thailand) faces delisting from the Stock Exchange of Thailand after reporting
losses for three consecutive years. Even Land and Houses, one of the country's
strongest developers, reported a 15.7% drop in third quarter profit to Baht437
million ($17 million).

<P> Thai authorities have spent the year devising ways to stimulate the property
market, including a proposal to allow for listed property trusts. The latest plan
is to create a secondary mortgage corporation, majority owned by the government,
which would enable lenders to sell their portfolios in the event of a liquidity
crisis. But setting up a committee, and drafting the necessary legislation could
be a lengthy process.

<P>

<H3> China's two-tier market </H3> 

<P> The old Chinese rule of
thumb is: keep a third of your wealth in property, a third in gold and a third in
cash. But that maxim could be thrown on its head as foreign investors start to
circle the markets of Shanghai, Beijing and Guangzhou.

<P> Hong Kong property companies, led by the listed Henderson Land spin-off,
Henderson China, are making serious investments in the People's Republic of
China. This is a growth market as foreign companies set up business in China and
look for office and residential space. Research by Morgan Stanley estimates
demand for additional office space at 70 million square feet in Shanghai and 60
million square feet in Beijing. But it is becoming a two-tier market: in Shanghai
rental and capital values of poor quality buildings are falling as prospective
tenants become more discerning.

<P> China's transition to the free market is not over yet and Morgan Stanley
sounds a note of caution: "The property market in China is a relatively new
phenomenon, with, as yet, a less-than-well established legal planning and
regulatory framework; and what framework there is may be changed in the future."

<P> Foreign developers such as Henderson China are selling most of their property
to foreign buyers, usually in US or HK dollars. Henderson China reported net
profit of HK$564 million for the full year to June 1996, with an estimated HK$477
million derived from office and residential sales at the Beijing Henderson
Centre, where prices average HK$2,560 (US$330) per square foot. Henderson China's
property portfolio is valued at around HK$12.5 billion, with 22 projects signed
and under construction or clearance. But, warns Morgan Stanley, the property
market for foreign buyers is finite. Long-term success will depend on the ability
to sell to the local market.

<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

