<br>



<center>
<A NAME="punters"><HR width=80%></A>
<br>
<img width=134 height=20 border=0 src="images/updat2.gif" alt="Punters Corner">
</center>
<br>
<DL>

<DD><P>
<B> Dateline: Monday, January 6 </B>
<P>



Recommendation:  Long GBP versus CHF <BR>                                      
Take Profit: CHF 2.33<BR>
<P>

Trying to establish underlying currency trends around the turn of the year is always dangerous due to the lack of liquidity in most markets and consequent scope for erratic and meaningless swings in prices.  However, it does seem that the appetite to short the low cost currencies remains intact.  The CHF has already given up considerable ground over the last few weeks, but we see room for further declines before the unit stands any realistic chance of a recovery.  This week's employment report should see offer additional proof of what should again be the worst performing European economy in 1997.  Indeed, it is significant that despite the slide in the CHF, local interest rates have fallen recently in response to the ongoing downturn in the domestic activity.  It costs nearly nothing to sell the currency and with the SNB clearly delighted with the unit's fall, there is minimal risk of any policy inspired reversal.  At the same time, UK data continue to point to an already robust economy that is still gaining momentum.  The pre-Xmas current account figures were reassuring and interest rates are on the up soon - quite possibly next week.  Monetary tightening may well be discounted in the futures market, but confirmation should still leave the GBP all the more attractive on a yield spread basis.  The outlook for a stronger USD should also have beneficial knock-on effects for the UK currency.
</DL>
<BR>



<A NAME="market"><HR width=80%></A>
<br>
<center>
<img width=159 height=20 border=0 src="images/updat3.gif" alt="Market
Highlights"></A>
<br><br>

<nobr>
<a href="#forex"><img width=105 height=17 border=0 src="images/updat5.gif"
alt="Forex"></a>
<img border=0 src="images/bullet.gif">
<a href="#mm"><img width=105 height=17 hspace=30 border=0 src="images/updat6.gif"
alt="Money Markets"></a>
<img border=0 src="images/bullet.gif">
<a href="#bonds"><img width=105 height=17 border=0 src="images/updat7.gif"
alt="Bonds"></a>
</nobr>

</center>
<br>
<A NAME="forex"></A><img width=105 height=17 border=0 src="images/updat5.gif"
alt="Forex">
<UL>
<P>
<B> Dateline:  Monday, January 6  </B>
<P>

<li>USD to make additional headway against the JPY and Europe on sustained low BoJ interest rates and hopes for a mini BBK ease.  However, USD-JPY now well into politically dangerous territory and very vulnerable to any hint of BoJ tightening.  USD-DEM good for DEM1.60, but needs confidence in the EMU process and stability in US asset markets. 
<li>DEM downside favoured within the EMS, but scope for additional weakness limited with the BBK now indicating contentment with current extent of correction. 
<li>GBP a near term buy below DEM2.65, with good medium term upside potential to DEM2.70.   Politics still messy, but election likely to be of only limited importance and relative fundamentals attractive enough to accommodate at least a degree of overshooting.
<li>CHF to continue to weaken despite recent sharp adjustment.  Cross to test 88 centime level soon, 90 on the cards before mid-year.  
</UL>


<A NAME="money"></A><img width=105 height=17 hspace=30 border=0
src="images/updat6.gif" alt="Money Markets">
<UL>

<P>
<B> Dateline:  Monday, January 6 </B>
<P>

<li>Fed policy on hold and no change expected at next (February 4-5) FOMC meeting.  However, pick-up in the recent data increases the risk of a tightening in 1H97, especially if the stock market continues to perform strongly.
<li>BBK policy expected steady for now, but signs of renewed weakness in the 4Q96 economy and absence of inflation pressures to provide room for small repo cut this quarter.
<li>BoE rate hike still favoured at next Clarke/George meeting on January 15, but risk of no change if government opts for an early election.
<li>Other European interest rates on hold for now, but still good medium term rate cut potential in Italy, Spain and to a lesser extent, Sweden.
</UL>

<A NAME="bonds"></A><img width=105 height=17 border=0 src="images/updat7.gif"
alt="Bonds">
<UL>

<P>
<B> Dateline:  Monday, January 6 </B>
<P>

<li>US Treasury market bias down on signs that the 4Q96 economy was stronger than originally expected and consequent renewed concerns about Fed tightening.  However, upcoming inflation data expected friendly and December employment report will have to be genuinely strong to induce tightening speculation at the February FOMC meeting. 
<li>Bunds to outperform Treasuries on favourable domestic economic data and rate cut hopes.  However, heavy 1Q96 supply schedule a drag and EMU convergence trades a negative.   
<li>Higher yielders still favoured medium term over hard core EMS, but vulnerable to any USD downturn and BTPs in need of a rate cut soon to avoid serious disappointment.
<li>Gilt market still expected to struggle until next rate hike out of the way and inflation picture becomes brighter.  Medium term bund spread target of 200 remains in place. 
</UL>




<br>
<A NAME="americadata"><HR width=80%></A>
<br>
<center>
<img width=220 height=34 border=0 src="images/updat8.gif" alt="American
Data"></A>
<br><br>
</center>


<UL>

<P>
<B> Dateline:  Monday, January 6 </B>
<P>
<li>US data to indicate still subdued pipeline inflation pressures, but point to a pick-up in growth in 4Q96.  December employment report expected moderate, wages as important as the payroll.
<li>Canadian data to show a sluggish December employment report, stable housing market but a jump in raw materials prices.  
</UL>

<br>
<A NAME="eurodata"><HR width=80%></A>
<br>
<center>
<img width=220 height=34 border=0 src="images/updat9.gif" alt="European
Data"></A>
<br><br>
</center>

<UL>

<P>
<B> Dateline:  Monday, January 6 </B>
<P>

<li>German calendar 1996 GDP to confirm sharp slowdown in growth, and indicate renewed sluggishness at year end.  December unemployment to underline softness of the labour market, but final CPI to reinforce low inflation scenario. 
<li>UK data to indicate sustained strong narrow money growth and provide further evidence of a solid recovery in manufacturing activity.
<li>French data to show subdued inflation in December and still weak level of consumer confidence in November.
<li>Italian December CPI to be confirmed at a lowly 2.6%.
<li>Other European data to paint a weak picture of the New Year Swiss labour market but show further signs of improvement in Denmark.
</UL>


<br>
<A NAME="asiadata"><HR width=80%></A>
<br>
<center>
<img width=220 height=34 border=0 src="images/updat10.gif" alt="Asian Data"></A>
<br><br>
</center>


<UL>

<P>
<B> Dateline:  Monday, January 6 </B>
<P>
 
<li>Japanese data to begin to highlight the impact of a weak JPY and higher energy prices via a jump in the December WPI.  November current account surplus to underline recent stalling in the external adjustment process.  
<li>Australian data to indicate some softening in consumer demand in November through slower growth in retail trade and a fall in housing building approvals.  November credit growth also expected to ease. 
</UL>


<br>
<A NAME="events"><HR width=80%></A>
<br>
<center>
<img width=220 height=34 border=0 src="images/updat11.gif" alt="Events"></A>
<br><br>
</center>


<UL>

<P>
<B> Dateline:  Monday, January 6 </B>
<P>

<li>BBK council to hold rates steady at their first meeting in 1997.
<li>Resumption of US-Japan civil air talks to underline political sensitivity of a weak JPY.  
<li>French National Assembly leader Seguin to highlight parliamentary split over EMU.
<li>Dutch press conference to mark beginning of EU presidential term to reinforce political momentum behind EMU. 
<li>EMI to outline plans for future ECB's monetary policy instruments - some room for disagreement over the role of minimum reserves.

</UL>
<br>
</blockquote>

<HR width=90%>

