Title: EMWL: DG BANK
</DOCHDR>
<TABLE WIDTH=530>
<CENTER><TR><TD>


<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
EMWL: DG BANK
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body background="dgbank.symbol.bg.gif" vlink="7C1568" text="000000" link="7C1568">

<blockquote>
<blockquote>
<table>
<tr>
<td align=right valign=top>
<nobr>
<a href="http://www.emwl.com/index.html" name="top">
<A NAME="Introduction"><img  width=69 height=45 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../images/spon1.gif" alt="EMWL"></a><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</nobr>
</td>
</tr>



<tr>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img border=0 src="dgbank.logo.1.gif" alt="DG Bank Logo">
</td></tr>
</table>
</blockquote>
</blockquote>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>



<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD ALGIN=LEFT>




<CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<img border=0 src="dgbank.symbol.4.gif" alt="introduction">
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
</CENTER>

<blockquote>
DG Bank is a corporation under public law and the central financial institution
of the German cooperative banking system, which forms one of the most close-knit
banking networks in Europe. The network provides a broad range of financial
services from retail banking via the over 2,500 local cooperative banks
(Volksbanken, Raiffeisenbanken) to fund management, insurance, etc.
<BR>
<BR>
With a balance-sheet-total of some DEM 300 bn (December 31, 1995) and over 10,000
employees in its Frankfurt headquarters and a number of branches and offices in
Germany and key financial centers all over the world, DG BANK is one of the top 10
banks in Germany. As a universal bank it offers both classical financial and innovative
tailor-made solutions to a broad range of financing problems to the members of
the network and to other institutional clients. Its capital market activities
make DG BANK one of the major players in the DEM sector.
 

</blockquote>

<BR><BR>
<BR><BR>
<HR>
<center><img border=0 width=520 height=3 hspace=0 src="horizontalrule.gif"></center>

<BR><BR>
<BR><BR>










<CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A NAME="FX-market"><img border=0 src="dgbank.symbol.1.gif" alt="FX-market"></A>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>

<H3>13-17 January, Weekly commentary</CENTER></H3>

<blockquote>
Last week, the dollar bulls roared as the bullish sentiment finally led to some
USD purchases by institutional investors. The USD's rise was helped by the
weakness of the DM in Europe which was the result of renewed interest rate
speculation after the rather weak employment data. In contrast, strong US
employment data were perceived in the market as raising the odds for a rate hike
in mid-March. US-data this week (CPI, industrial production, trade) might dampen
this speculation somewhat. Furthermore, the USD would have to overcome the strong
resistance zone between DM 1,5850-1,6100 to clear the way for further gains. We
do not expect this to happen, at least not yet. Also, the DM's weakness in Europe
should not be taken much further as Central banks have already begun to
intervene.

<BR>
<BR>
<B>
For further information please contact: <BR>
Ulrich Jacoby, phone:+49 69 7447 2787 or <BR>
Gerhard Hechler, phone: +49 69 7447 6072 </B>
</blockquote>

<BR><BR>
<BR><BR>
<HR>
