<BR><BR>
<BR><BR>




<CENTER>

<A NAME="Bond market"><img border=0 src="dgbank.symbol.2.gif" alt="Bond market"></A>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<H3>13-17 January, Weekly commentary</CENTER></H3>

<blockquote>
The bund future broke the psychological resistance of 100 and stabilised well
above. This week's highlight: release of IFO business climate for December, which
should show a slight increase towards year end. Wholesale prices and retail
figures (both for December) will not have a major impact on the market. In the
US, investors should focus on the release (Tuesday) of December retail figures
and CPI data. Retail turnover should have risen significantly. Corresponding to
the recently published PPI data, consumer prices should show an increase of 0.3%
with an even smaller increase in the core rate. In contrast, capacity utilisation
and industrial production to be released on Friday might be a burden for the
market if they confirm investor's expectations of higher economic growth.

<BR>
<BR>
<B>
For further information please contact: <BR>
Rainer Lenz, phone: +49 69 7447 2839</B>
</blockquote>

<BR><BR>
<BR><BR>
<HR>
<center><img border=0 width=520 height=3 hspace=0 src="horizontalrule.gif"></center>

<BR><BR>
<BR><BR>




<CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A NAME="German equities"><img border=0 src="dgbank.symbol.3.gif" alt="German equities"></A>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BR>

<H3>13-17 January, Weekly commentary</CENTER></H3>

<blockquote>
At the beginning of the new year the surprisingly good US economic data
re-ignited inflation fears and the subsequent weakness on Wall Street caused
German share prices to drop, too. In view of prevailing uncertainties, new
purchases should only be made on slow days. The first reports on companies'
results in the past business year will come out from mid-January on. At present,
we do not recommend investments in companies with a strong domestic base, in
particular in consumption and construction as we do not rule out further declines
in this sector. We continue to favor automobile and chemical stocks, as these
should profit strongly from the current export boom and the ongoing weakness of
the DM.

<BR>
<BR>
<B>
For further information please contact: <BR>
Patrick Thielmann, phone: +49 69 7447 6710<BR>
</B>
<BR>
