<HEAD>
<TITLE>
EMWL: Bank Austria
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body background="images/bg1.gif" vlink="7C1568" text="000000" link="7C1568">

<blockquote>

<center>

<table border=0>
<tr><td align=right>
<a href="http://www.emwl.com/index.html" name="top">
<img  width=69 height=45 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../images/spon1.gif" alt="EMWL"></a>
</td></tr>

<tr><td align=center>
<a name="intro" href="http://www.telecom.at/ba/s17.htm">
<img border=0 width=256 height=32 src="images/logo.gif" alt="Bank Austria Logo">
</a>
<br><br><br>
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<font size=3>

Bank Austria was created in October 1991 with the merger of Oesterreichische Laenderbank AG (at that time the second largest Austrian commercial bank) and Zentralsparkasse und Kommerzialbank, Wien AG  (Austria's largest savings bank). <br><br>
The merger resulted in the creation of the largest financial institution in Austria with a market share of between 12 and 20 percent. Bank Austria ranks 121 in a listing amongst the world's top 200 banks (EUROMONEY, June 1996). <br><br>
Bank Austria is Austria's leading bank in the retail banking, corporate banking, investment banking and treasury sectors. <br><br>
The bank's economic strength and significance are reflected in international ratings. Due to its excellent capitalization (own funds in relation to risk volumes weighted amount to 10,3%, about 3/4 thereof as tier I capital), its earnings potential and the assumption of the bank's liabilities by the City of Vienna, Bank Austria  - as the only commercial bank in Austria belongs to an exclusive group of banks which has been awarded a "Aaa" rating by Moody's. Global Finance ranked Bank Austria 17th based on a comparable rating of the world's 250 safest banks. <br><br>
The bank has won international recognition for the high quality of its services. EUROMONEY recently named Bank Austria "Best Bank in Austria" and "Best Security Firm in Austria" - as it did for 1993, 1994 and 1995. <br><br>
Bank Austria's success has not gone unnoticed abroad. After thorough analysis of the Austrian market, Westdeutsche Landesbank Girozentrale (West LB) signed a cooperation agreement with Bank Austria in December 1995. This strategic alliance, in which WestLB took a 9.1% interest in the bank's share capital by way of a capital increase effected in spring 1996, is without a doubt a milestone in the history of Bank Austria. Each institution has declared the other to be its preferred partner for cross-border financial transactions focusing primarily on foreign commercial transactions, foreign money transfers, currency clearing, the securities business, investment banking and business in Central and Eastern Europe. It should also be mentioned in  this regard, that Cariplo, Bank Austria's large Italian shareholder, further increased its holdings in Bank Austria to the agreed-upon 5.6%.
<br><br>

