<br><br>

</blockquote>
<center>
<img width=400 height=236 border=0 src="images/share.gif">
<br><br>
</center>
<blockquote>

<a name="Business"><hr width=80%></a>
<br>
<center>
<img border=0 width=464 height=41 src="images/banbus.gif" alt="Banking Business Banner">
</center>
<br><br>
Bank Austria is active in all fields of banking business. <b>Retail banking</b> is the core business of the bank: Bank Austria maintains a domestic retail network of more than 300 branches, manages more than 5 mn customer accounts and has by far the largest share of primary funds in Austria. 
<br><br>

<center>
<table>
<tr><td align=left valign=top>
Contacts:	
</td><td align=left valign=top>
Friedrich TUPY<br>
A-1030 Vienna, Rennweg 46-50,<br>
Tel.: (43+1) 711 91 2280<br>
</td></tr></table>
</center>

<br><br>

In <b>corporate banking</b>, Bank Austria is the leading institution for lending, structured finance, export finance and products tailored to the needs of corporates. Of the top 2,000 enterprises in Austria, 40 % rate Bank Austria as their major banking partner. 
<br><br>

<center>
<table>
<tr><td align=left valign=top>
Contacts:	
</td><td align=left valign=top>
Wolfgang FEUCHTMULLER<br>
A-1010 Vienna, Am Hof 2,<br>
Tel.: (43+1) 711 91 6810<br>
</td></tr></table>
</center>

<br><br>

In <b>securities business</b>, the Bank Austria Group is the leader in the placement of new issues, in the underwriting of government bonds and in the trading of Austrian equity and debt instruments. 
<br><br>
With its long tradition as a securities bank, Bank Austria provides facilities ranging from discretionary management to the asset management of funds invested by major investors. 
<br><br>

<center>
<table>
<tr><td align=left valign=top>
Contacts:	
</td><td align=left valign=top>
Stefan ZAPOTOCKY<br>
A-1010 Wien, Renngasse 2,<br>
Tel.: (43+1) 711 91 5700<br>
</td></tr></table>
</center>

<br><br>

Bank Austria is not only the driving force behind the Austrian banking industry, but also a major <b>regional player on all international markets</b> where the institutional and geographical advantages offered by the Austrian financial market can be utilized by the bank.
<br><br>
Because of Austria's history and geographical location, Bank Austria sees itself as a Central European institution with a strong focus on the neighboring Central and Eastern European countries. 
<br><br>
Its location in the heart of Europe and the expertise of its predecessor banks in East-West trade are particular strengths which the bank brings to bear on its international operations. In 1992, for example, Bank Austria became the first foreign bank to receive a banking license to operate a branch in Moscow. It has subsidiaries in Switzerland, the Czech and Slovak Republics, Hungary and Slovenia. 
<br><br>
The bank maintains branches in the world's leading financial centers (New York, London, Hongkong, Singapore) as well as representative offices in  most countries in Western and Eastern Europe and in the Far East. 
<br><br>

<center>
<table>
<tr><td align=left valign=top>
