<HEAD>
<TITLE>
EMWL: World Link Magazine: May/June 1996
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="7C1568" text="000000" link="7C1568">

<center>
<font size=3>
<table border=0>
<tr>
<td colspan=2 align=left>
<nobr>
<img width=199 height=44 name="top" border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../images/conban8.gif" alt="World Link Magazine"><a href="../../../../../index.html"><img width=141 height=45 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../../images/conban1.gif" alt="EMWL Home"></a>
</nobr>
<br>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<h2>
May/June 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra9.gif" alt="Feature">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>
<H2>MY CENTURY </H2>
<H4><I>T</I>he 20th century is about to end, a blink in time when humankind
searched for revolutionary means of self-enrichment and discovered instead
the means of self-destruction, writes Nadime Gordimer </H4>
In terms of human life, 100 years is the largest unit we can grasp: after
that, quantification begins again. It is not without significance that life
is renewed in Sleeping Beauty's family castle after this span. The turn
of a century is the prince's kiss of time. On the first morning of the year
2000 the world will be awakened to a new calendar, perhaps a new life. <BR>
<BR>
Living in the 20th century, we cannot look upon it from the pretence of
another perspective; nor should we try to if we are to discover what only
we know best, if only secretly: the truth about ourselves and our time.
The brief conception of our century I propose here is inevitably subjective:
each of you will substitute or add your own, but there are surely many which
we share, shaped by the same period. <BR>
<BR>
At once there arises from a flash brighter than a thousand suns the mushroom
cloud that hangs over our century. Exploded almost exactly at the half-century
mark, the atomic bombs that destroyed Hiroshima and Nagasaki rise as unsurpassed
evil done by human decision. This in a century where more humans have been
killed or allowed to die of starvation and disease than ever before in history
and where the Nazi holocaust, 50 years on, has become as much the household
word of horror as ethnic cleansing in the Balkans and Africa. <BR>
<BR>
Foremost of the &quot;firsts&quot; our century can claim is that for the
first time man invented a power of destruction which surpasses any natural
catastrophe &shyp; earthquake, volcano, flood. Thus the final conquest of
nature, an aim pursued with the object of human benefit since the invention
of agriculture in the Stone Age, has been achieved in our discovery of how
to wipe ourselves out more quickly and efficiently than any force of nature.
The demonic vow of our century seems to come from Virgil: &quot;If I cannot
move Heaven, I will stir up Hell&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Treating weapons as toys </B><BR>
<BR>
The signing of a nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty is brokered among nations
and the threat of an atomic war, which for 40 years depended on the press
of a button in the Pentagon or Kremlin, is complacently half-forgotten since
one protagonist in a Cold War is <I>hors de combat</I>. But the French have
been trying out their nuclear capacity as if these loathsome apocalyptic
weapons were now old toys a safe world can play with. The prediction of
poet TS Eliot was that we would end with a whimper; our own is that we could
go out with a bang. The mushroom cloud still hangs over us: will it be there
as a bequest to the new century? <BR>
<BR>
The strange relation between the forces of Good and Evil has been part of
the mystery of human existence since we evolved as the only self-regarding
creatures in the animal world. With the great leaps that have been made
into what was formerly beyond human experience, the relation surely has
become more profoundly relevant and inexplicable than ever. Einstein, exiled
from his home country by the evil force of Nazism, deciphered one of the
greatest secrets of nature and split the atom. What was intended to enrich
humankind with an extension of knowledge of its cosmic existence produced
out of Good the malediction of our time: atomic capability. <BR>
<BR>
What is more puzzling, and far more trouble, is an apparent symbiosis of
Good and Evil, passing from one into the other through some transparency
we cannot fathom. We try to apply moral precepts to processes that function
according to quite other laws, laws in which morality does not exist at
all: a sober contemplation for an age characterised by revolutionary scientific
discovery. <BR>
<BR>
If we turn away from the absolutes of opposing Good and Evil, as we must
see them if human values are to survive, we come to the lower level, that
of paradox. We have made spectacular advances in discoveries that have made
life more bearable for some and more pleasurable for others. We have eliminated
many epidemics and alleviated pain with new drugs; we have raised the dead
in a real sense, by taking vital organs and planting them to function again
in the living. <BR>
<BR>
Aircraft have revolutionised the possibility of physical presence. The bundle
of telecommunications &shyp; computer, fax, email, cellular phone &shyp;
has speeded up communication by the spoken and written word. We have lifted
the burden of manual workers and housewives by machines programmed to do
onerous tasks: with other devices we have brought music and moving images
into every house. We have broken the sound barrier, explored space and entered
the angels' realm, the sphere of the heavens. Most of us have enjoyed some
of these embellishments of life. <BR>
<BR>
The Italian Futurist painters in the early decades of our age depicted a
world of sleek cars whirling unhampered through streets, planes buzzing
like happy bees, gathering the nectar of a new age between skyscrapers and
rainbows in a radiantly clear sky. <BR>
<BR>
Their paintings look to us now like the work of a Grandma Moses of industrialisation,
yet we shared their innocent ignorance of pollution and lacked, as they
did, the true vision of a future: which was that we would begin to choke
on our technological progress, suffocate in our cities in our own foul breath
of fumes and carcinogenic vapours. We have achieved much, but we have not
always stayed at the controls of purpose. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The ordeal of dread banished </B><BR>
<BR>
It is also intriguing to observe how technology has intervened in the intangible,
telescoping our emotions. Those antipodean states, dread and anticipation,
have been practically outdated. The ordeal of dread is banished by instant
full communication from anywhere to anywhere. Anticipation has become instant
gratification. So, not for the first or last time, the advances of technology
contradict theories of human satisfaction expounded by the savants of that
advance in knowledge that has dramatically distinguished our century, psychoanalysis.
Apart from its purely sexual application, Sigmund Freud's deferred pleasure
as a refinement of emotional experience does not compare with the immediate
joy of hearing a lover's voice, or getting a friend's reply to a letter
at once by email. <BR>
<BR>
Even adventurism has been transformed by technology. The intrepid now walk
on the moon and dangle in space instead of &quot;discovering&quot; jungles
and rivers that the indigenous inhabitants have known as home since the
time pinpointed by their personal creation myths. Through weightlessness,
the new adventurers actually experience extinction while still alive, becoming
phantoms whose feet cannot touch earth. They are the successors to the angels
in whom we no longer believe because we have probed outer space and found
no heaven. <BR>
<BR>
Technology is the means by which one of the positive, progressive consequences
of this century's revolutions &shyp; a determination to break open the elitism
of the arts &shyp; has been made practical. From the era of actors' troupes
and exhibitions travelling through the villages of Russia after the October
Revolution, to this decade of the '90s when even squatter camps in Africa,
India, or the Middle East have transistor radios, culture in its most easily
assimilable form has been democratised. Technology has redistributed intellectual
privilege. <BR>
<BR>
Music from pop to opera has been brought to the masses by discs and broadcasts
which may be heard on the humblest of radios. And by the same means, an
appreciation of the musical forms of the east and Africa, from the <I>ragas</I>
of Ravi Shankar to South Africa's <I>kwela</I> and <I>mbaganga</I>, have
spread internationally. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Watching replaces the real thing </B><BR>
<BR>
But it is television that has brought about the overwhelming cultural transformation.
Television has altered human perception and changed the means of knowing
and receiving the world. Of the five senses, sight now outstrips all others;
watching is the primary form of comprehension. Although television speaks,
it is its endless stream of images out of which the child, the youth and
even the mature and old construct reality. The visual other-world of television
is renewed like a palimpsest day after day, for millions the last vision
before sleep and the first woken to in the morning. <BR>
<BR>
Every workshop of young painters in my country show strikingly the imprinting
of artists' creativity by television's imagery and iconography, its visual
hierarchy of what is meaningful in our life. Television has empowered the
visual far beyond the capacity of cinema, the art which democratised enjoyment
of leisure before the television box entered our homes. Through television,
the service of technology to art developed in our century, we have produced
a human mutation that substitutes vicarious experience for the real thing.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;In our time the destiny of man presents its meaning in political terms,&quot;
wrote Thomas Mann, who interpreted human experience through his own personal
experience of the century's physical displacements and upheavals of perception.
But we are not only children of our time, we are also of our place. My own
consciousness and subconscious comes from a destiny shaped by the historico-political
matrix into which I was born. My personal sense of the defining events of
our century is dominated by two such events: the fall of communism and the
end of colonialism. And the two are linked subjectively, even contradictorily.
<BR>
<BR>
I was born a second-generation colonial in a capitalist-racist society.
As I grew up I looked to the left as the solution to the oppression of the
poor and powerless all around me, at home and abroad. When I was a toddler
I was taken to wave a flag at the Prince of Wales, the future Edward VIII,
on his visit to the British dominion of South Africa. I was told again and
again as I grew up of this momentous occasion, with a sense of values to
be inculcated: loyalty in homage to imperial power. <BR>
<BR>
Nobody mentioned the fact that the Indian leader Mohandas Gandhi had developed
his philosophy in the country where I was born and was to live my life:
a man who was to leave behind principles of non-violent liberation that
were to be important to the struggle for freedom by black people, unacknowledged
by the values of the whites. <BR>
<BR>
It has become a truism to shake one's head in wonder at the end of apartheid
and the emergence of a free South Africa. But it was indeed a miracle and
it came at the time when a new miracle was needed to compensate for the
flickering of the Red Star, that miracle promised in the first quarter of
the century. <BR>
<BR>
Human beings will always believe in the possibility of a better world of
their own making. In the words of Jean-Paul Sartre, socialism was seen as
&quot;man in the process of creating himself&quot;. It is a sense of abandonment
that the collapse of the Soviet Union brings to our century among those
to whom the ideals of socialism remain, rather than the disillusion many
in the west would triumphantly claim. <BR>
<BR>
For whatever one's judgement of its consequences, the most momentous single
date in the social organisation of our century was the October Revolution:
one third of humankind found itself living under regimes derived from that
event. Has the disintegration of the Soviet world before the end of the
same century brought the triumph of democracy? Perhaps it is only the return
of the liberalism that failed, after World War I, to prevent the people
of Italy and Germany from turning to fascism as the solution of their straightened
circumstances, a condition which exists again in many parts of our world
today. <BR>
<BR>
In South Africa, the left's revelation of the class and economic basis of
racial discrimination was one of the formative influences that, along with
Pan-Africanism, joined a natural national will towards liberation. The other
formative influence is the one mentioned above, Gandhi. He was one of the
truly great individuals of our century whose lifetime we set against the
monsters, from Hitler to Pol Pot, whom the century has produced. Gandhi
was an original thinker on the nature of power, as distinct from power confined
to the purely political tool for liberation, yet able to serve this tool
as part of a high moral consciousness. His philosophy of <I>satyagraha</I>
&quot;the force which is born of truth and love&quot;, is perhaps the only
genuine spiritual advance in an era of religious decline marked by crackpot
distortions of faith and savage fundamentalism. <BR>
<BR>
What Gandhi began, out of a philosophy formulated in South Africa and applied
tactically in India to bring about freedom from imperial rule, Nelson Mandela
has concluded. For Mandela's prestige and honour in the world today is recognition
not only of his achievement in the defeat of the dire experiment in social
engineering called apartheid. It is recognition that other ghastly forms
of social engineering tried in our century were defeated where they had
taken refuge, for apartheid with its blatant racist laws was an avatar of
Nazism. And finally, it is homage paid to Mandela in recognition that at
stake was something far greater than the fate of a single country; it was
final victory gained for humankind over centuries-old bondage of colonisation.
<BR>
<BR>
The sum of our century may be looked at in a number of ways: the wars that
were fought, the military defeats that turned into economic victories, the
ideologies that rose and fell, the technology that telescoped time and distance.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Write oil on the window of time </B><BR>
<BR>
We could dip a finger in a dark viscous substance and write on the window
of our time &quot;oil&quot;. Oil became more precious than gold: it has
been the &quot;why&quot; of many wars of our day. Repressive regimes go
unreproached by democratic countries who are dependent on them for oil;
men, women and children die for oil without knowing why. <BR>
<BR>
In intimate human relations, we have won sexual freedom and lost it &shyp;
to Aids. Freud changed emotional cognition and self-perception. Another
kind of perception moved from Picasso's <I>Guernica</I> to Andy Warhol's
Campbell's Soup can, to the Reichstag wrapped in plastic, illustrating our
cycles: worship of force, worship of materialism, the desire to cover up
and forget the choices we have made. <BR>
<BR>
Now that the deeds are done &shyp; the 100 years ready to seal what will
be recorded of us &shyp; our last achievement could be in the spirit of
taking up, in Jawaharlal Nehru's words, &quot;the ceaseless adventure of
man&quot; which is control of our achievements, questioning honestly and
reflecting upon the truth of what has been lived through. There is no other
base on which to found the 21st century with the chance to make it a better
one.* <BR>
<BR>
<I>The author was Nobel prizewinner in Literature in 1991 and a longstanding
campaigner against apartheid in her native South Africa</I> 
<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

