<td valign=top align=left>
<H2>GAUTENG</H2>
<H4>The changes of recent years have altered the face of South Africa's
industrial and financial powerhouse, Gautang province, which includes Johannesburg
and the capital Pretoria. National problems have a special impact here,
so recent foreign scepticism about government policy and the fall of the
rand have hit hard. But there are already signs of returning business confidence
and hope for the future <BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#engineroom">AFRICA'S ENGINEROOM</A> <BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#jacaranda">JACARANDA STREETS</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#future-steel">STEELED FOR THE FUTURE</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#investment">TIDES OF INVESTMENT</A><BR>
</H4>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="engineroom"></A>AFRICA'S ENGINE ROOM </H3>
<B>There are signs of an up-turn in business activity but the region must
tackle the same problems as the country <BR>
<BR>
</B><I>By Marek Garztecki <BR>
<BR>
</I>&quot;If you want to [sense] the state of the economy of South Africa
you will get it in Gauteng. It is the best barometer. If the business climate
here is depressed you will generally find it depressed in the rest of the
country. Gauteng is already the New York of Southern Africa,&quot; declares
Pieter van Huyssteen, the chief executive of PW Corporate Finance, a member
firm of the international Price Waterhouse group. <BR>
<BR>
The increasing activity of his company, located right in the middle of Gauteng
in a leafy suburb of Johannesburg, suggests that after a long period of
stormy weather the local business climate is beginning to recover. <BR>
<BR>
Whether it can be insulated from national trends is another matter. Industrial
strife, exchange controls and a controversial new finance minister sent
the rand plunging to its lowest level against the dollar in April. Market
sentiment is sceptical of the government's ability to restrain public spending
and prevent future currency outflows. <BR>
<BR>
Nonetheless, like the rest of South Africa Gauteng has reaped some benefits
from the remarkable political and economic changes of the past six years
since the end of apartheid and the formation of President Nelson Mandela's
government of national unity. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The return to planet Earth <BR>
<BR>
</B>While the new South Africa was able to re-enter the world political
arena almost immediately, economic progress was far slower. &quot;Five years
ago only the brave moved into South Africa,&quot; reflects Collin Wright,
head of the privately sponsored International Resource Centre in Johannesburg.
&quot;Most adopted the 'wait and see' attitude. Some of the companies that
divested from South Africa [during the sanctions era] were not encouraged
to study country's economic potential, they thought it futile if they could
not follow it with investment and a presence here. They lost track.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Wright, who doubles as the director of commerce and industry for Greater
Johannesburg Metropolitan Council, has spent a great part of the past few
years travelling around the world, meeting businessmen and decision-makers
in an effort to preach his gospel. &quot;Johannesburg has a very interesting
economy,&quot; he says, &quot;it has one of the most diversified economies
that you will find in any one metropolitan area in the world. It is almost
a national economy in its own right.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Pretoria, the country's political centre and Johannesburg, its commercial
centre, constitute the bulk of Gauteng province. Although it constitutes
just 1.5% of the country's land area, Gauteng contains almost 20% of its
population and accounts for nearly 40% of South African GDP. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;If Gauteng was a country it would have the third largest economy in
Africa, after the rump of South Africa and Algeria,&quot; says Philip Clayton,
senior economist with the Standard Bank of South Africa. &quot;It would
be bigger than Nigeria, bigger than Kenya, in fact bigger than any other
country in Africa you care to mention. Gauteng is the financial, manufacturing,
retailing powerhouse of South Africa and indeed of the whole continent.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
The province has considerable powers. According to Andrew Feinstein, a member
of the Provincial Legislature and the chairman of its Economic Affairs Committee,
the post-apartheid authorities intended the new provincial arrangement to
enhance local self-government. &quot;The provinces have a very important
role to play. One example is small business development. We have almost
no culture of small business. We have a national enabling act and provincial
acts that deal with the circumstances of each province,&quot; he says. <BR>
<BR>
The promotion, spearheaded by the indefatigable Collin Wright, eventually
drew an international response. The first came from European countries with
historical ties to South Africa such as Germany and Holland: France and
Italy also joined. Not that the Germans ever left: Car firms like BMW and
Volkswagen stayed throughout the sanctions period unlike most US firms.
<BR>
<BR>
Less traditional investors have also arrived. There have been 75 trade delegations
from mainland China and as a result about 20 companies and joint ventures
were set up with total investment of almost 1 billion Rand ($225 million).
They cover a wide range of products from the arms industry to electronics.
There is also substantial property investment from east Asia. <BR>
<BR>
The return of the British, once the country's colonial rulers, took the
form of huge investments on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange (JSE), multiplying
its trading volume in the process (see page 67). Although some expressed
misgivings because of fears of speculative behaviour, the JSE executive
president RC Andersen has welcomed the trend. &quot;Foreign money may easy
come and easy go,&quot; he acknowledges, &quot;but it forces discipline
on local politicians and businessmen, making sure that they are fiscally
responsible and maintain monetary discipline.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>Where first and third worlds meet <BR>
<BR>
</B>Whatever their entry strategy, Collin Wright believes that an increasing
number of foreign investors are convinced that South Africa offers opportunities.
It has a good infrastructure and operates as a modern economy, providing
a good base on which to build. <BR>
<BR>
Philip Clayton concurs: &quot;Our electronic banking systems are among the
best in the world and the services that we can provide to corporate clients
are on par. The technical skills may not be up to west European standards
but are certainly far superior to those available in African countries.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Most people think of South Africa in terms of Third World economies,&quot;
complains Wright, &quot;but it has islands of brilliance in high-tech knowledge
which need to be commercialised. For example, in the jewellery industry
we have developed the first ever 24-carat hard-gold technology. We can produce
24-carat gold at the hardness of 9-carat gold.&quot; Wright concedes that
finding niche markets in which value could be added locally, such as platinum
enrichment, is a real challenge. <BR>
<BR>
During the period of sanctions in the jewellery and diamond industry a lot
of activity moved out of South Africa to Hong Kong and New York. The local
authorities are trying to entice it back. Recently a &quot;jewel city&quot;
was opened in downtown Johannesburg, intended as a value-added centre. Some
250 companies have already located there. <BR>
<BR>
While the international boycott lasted, internal industrialisation was spurred
by the need to manufacture import replacements. Now that the local market
is opening up to the outside world two things can happen. &quot;The existing
industrial base can be killed off by the international competition or, if
you give enough advantage to international players to enter into joint ventures,
it may serve as a base for exports into the rest of Africa as well as other
markets,&quot; Wright says. <BR>
<BR>
<B>As good production, if not better <BR>
<BR>
</B>Joint ventures aimed at updating local technology, in areas ranging
from battery manufacture to pumps and valves, give some hope that the second
option will prevail. Foreign manufacturers assembling in South Africa, such
as Land Rover, substantially increased local content when they realised
that its quality not only equals but in some cases surpasses the levels
of some developed countries. <BR>
<BR>
South Africa is now becoming a focal point for African industrial machinery
buyers. African trade missions that would once have gone to Europe now go
to Johannesburg first. <BR>
<BR>
Gauteng is also the main regional transport hub. Some 97% of all South African
air freight enters via Johannesburg and over 50% of all the ship freight
that comes to southern African ports ends up here for redistribution. <BR>
<BR>
But this also adds to social and crime problems. &quot;As the markets open,
so enters international crime and all the social ills,&quot; complains one
politician. He accuses neighbouring countries of a failure to control their
own criminal element, which he alleges heads for &quot;the honey-pot of
the continent&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
Others say crime is predominantly home-grown. &quot;The biggest problem
locally is the high unemployment level. Unofficial figures suggest that
about half the black population lacks formal job opportunities. If you do
not have a job or prospects of finding it, you start getting involved in
criminal activities. This is something that we have to focus on before anything
else,&quot; says Wright. <BR>
<BR>
During the past few years, formerly exclusive white areas such as Hillbrow
and Berea have been virtually taken over by poor blacks. In cosy white suburbs
stories abound about violent attacks and &quot;no-go areas&quot;. All the
same, wanton, racially motivated attacks of the sort that occur in &quot;civilised&quot;
European capitals are virtually unknown. <BR>
<BR>
Probably the greatest mythology surrounds the South Western Township (Soweto)
near Johannesburg. Soweto is in fact a town in his own right, and probably
&shyp; no reliable population census was ever taken &shyp; the biggest in
Gauteng. Created during the apartheid era as a tool of white supremacy,
this gigantic shantytown became one of the centres of black resistance.
Unlit and unpaved streets of Soweto scare most whites away. Yet as any visitor
can experience at first hand, local people are perfectly friendly. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Soweto's black music labels <BR>
<BR>
</B>Soweto is also home to some fine clubs and musicians. Some of them are
truly original, as those who heard the Soweto String Quartet during the
1995 World Economic Forum meeting in Davos can attest. Unfortunately the
authorities do not understand the need to promote local artists, according
to label manager Lance McCormack from the South African subsidiary of BMG
Records. <BR>
<BR>
On the other hand there has been a considerable official effort put into
plans to aid the black population as a whole, who often suffer most from
change. &quot;The process of restructuring is going to result in further
job losses,&quot; Feinstein says. &quot;We have seen it already. The textile
sector is one example; 17,000 jobs have been lost in the past two and a
half or three years. We have got to be conscious, given our recent political
history, of the need to maintain social stability.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
While economic restructuring is the government's medium-term objective,
it tries to alleviate the consequences. The majority of the black population
between 17 and 27 have never had a job. &quot;We are not going to eliminate
unemployment but we have at least to halve the present levels in a short
to medium term,&quot; Feinstein says. <BR>
<BR>
The chosen mechanism is the grandly named Reconstruction and Development
Programme, RDP. Despite being given significant resources and even a separate
ministry to implement it, RDP has been a great disappointment so far and
has fallen well short of its stated goals. A recent reorganisation may improve
matters. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The whole country is running around the RDP,&quot; says Joan Joffe,
group executive of the country's largest cellular network provider Vodacom.
&quot;Everybody is aware that as the result of apartheid there are disadvantaged
communities and areas: we know we have to make amends.&quot; As a result,
the company says, it will install 22,000 phones in such areas over a five-year
period. <BR>
<BR>
Even literacy, an obvious tool for social advancement, may not provide the
expected results, believes Philip Clayton. &quot;Education was used as a
political football, initially by the whites, to keep blacks uneducated.
By the time the white government realised that it needed to upgrade black
skills because there were simply not enough whites to fill the jobs available
in the economy, there was a cry of 'liberation now, education later' that
led to a whole lost generation. The process of upgrading black skills here
will take a little while, given the heritage of apartheid,&quot; he says.
<BR>
<BR>
Pressure from the growing migrant population may soon stretch Gauteng's
infrastructure to breaking point. In the white suburbs electricity supply,
water, sewage and other services may still be compared to European rather
than African standards. But the cost of extending them to townships and
squatter camps fazes many businessmen. There is a clear danger of a New
York-type financial trap whereby the high taxes required to maintain a crumbling
infrastructure have the effect of scaring away lucrative corporate tenants.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Living with the siege mentality <BR>
<BR>
</B>Regula Niehus, the regional communications manager, points out to a
different obstacle. &quot;What I realised here in South Africa is that most
of the people still live with the siege mentality. They have not yet understood
that the competition is coming in and if they want to survive they must
leave their closed environment and start exporting. To get companies to
be export-orientated is really an extremely difficult task,&quot; she believes.
Yet even she is optimistic about the country's economic future. <BR>
<BR>
Joan Joffe agrees. &quot;The potential is here, we have got the knowledge,
things work here. The transition has been a miracle, people are getting
on with one another, socialising, working together. There is a good spirit
in the country.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The busy entrepreneurial spirit of the new South Africa finds its earthly
form in Sandy Lowitt, the youthful director of economic policy, trade and
investment promotion of the Gauteng Provincial Government. <BR>
<BR>
Despite the chaos of the new office, Lowitt cheerfully greeted one vistor
with documents full of facts and figures as well as spades of positive attitude.
The office is home to the Gauteng Economic Development Agency, a one-stop
shop for foreign investors. The air of excitement is palpable.<BR><BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3><A NAME="jacaranda"></A>STREETS OF JACARANDA</H3>
<H4>Pretoria's streets house the usual attractions as well as a diamond
mine and African art galleries </H4>
<H1></H1>
&quot;It is safe, it is clean!&quot; exclaims Peet du Preez, when asked
about the main attractions of the South African capital. As the marketing
and communications director for Pretoria City Council, he predictably parades
all the benefits that the city has to offer a potential investor, trader
or tourist. Yet the businesslike efficiency of his presentation barely hides
an almost indecent enthusiasm for his subject. <BR>
<BR>
Much the same can be said for tourism officer Veronica Shrives. Facts, place
names and figures roll quickly from her tongue. Pretoria has 35 museums,
old buildings, a diamond mine, many art galleries and some of the world's
finest collections of African and ethnic art. There are also 50 restaurants
and wine bars located along its orderly, jacaranda-lined streets. And Pretoria
is strategically located in terms of nearby attractions like the Eastern
Transvaal, Northern Transvaal, Kruger Park and Sun City. Many nature reserves
are only an hour's drive away and operators can provide custom-made tours.
<BR>
<BR>
While admitting that industrial Johannesburg is hardly a holiday attraction,
parliamentarian Andrew Feinstein points to the benefits gained from the
impressive 15% annual growth in regional tourism. &quot;For every 30 foreign
tourists that come to this country we create one direct or two indirect
jobs,&quot; he says. &quot;We have to find more of those sectors that will
provide employment, particularly to those economically marginalised, like
the young.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
As everywhere in South Africa, job creation is a priority. &quot;We have
semi-skilled, semi-literate people and we have to help them make a living,&quot;
stresses Victor Mathale, the small business manager of Pretoria City Council.
&quot;At the same time we need high-tech, highly skilled investment. As
the level of literacy increases people can progress to high-tech jobs.&quot;
&quot;We manufacture more than 45% of South African motor vehicles,&quot;
says Du Preez. While this may not amount to a serious challenge to Detroit,
the expected economic revival of Southern Africa should help it to become
at least a regional automotive centre. As Du Preez points out, local authorities
do not want to attract investors at any price. Only those providing the
best fit for the region have any prospect of help. <BR>
<BR>
High on the list is brainpower. Pretoria is the country's educational system
with its three universities, plus the world's largest distant-learning institution,
UNISA and more than 35 research institutes. <BR>
<BR>
Yet there is general agreement that tourism is one of the top two growth
areas. The dramatic increase in the number of international visitors during
the past few years has exposed all the deficiencies of the country's infrastructure.
<BR>
<BR>
This situation will be partially addressed by two five-star hotels being
built now. One is probably the biggest single foreign investment project
in South Africa. But the need for more beds in the &quot;Jacaranda City&quot;,
admits, has yet to be rectified.<BR><BR> 
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3><A NAME="future-steel"></A>STEELED FOR THE FUTURE</H3>
<H4><BR>
The steel company Iscor used foreign sanctions to carve out new markets
in east Asia and is now ready to expand </H4>
<H3></H3>
<I>By Marek Garztecki <BR>
<BR>
</I>With manufacturing making up almost a third of GDP and mining accounting
for 5.5%, Gauteng is not only an industrial powerhouse for the country but
also an economic giant on a continental scale. Metaphorically speaking,
Gauteng's industrial heart is made of gold and its muscles of steel. <BR>
<BR>
Gold mining accounts for almost 10% of the region's gross geographical product,
a local measure of GDP. In 1992 Gauteng mines accounted for 39% of the gold
ore milled in South Africa and the metal is by far the country's most valuable
export. <BR>
<BR>
There is also a large iron and steel industry. &quot;As a company and private
organisation, to survive we have to be profitable,&quot; says Ernest Webb-Stock,
the divisional manager of Iscor, the country's largest steel producer. This
would be a rather ordinary statement if it were not for the fact that until
1989 Iscor was an almost monopolistic state-owned firm more reminiscent
of the Soviet Union than a free market. <BR>
<BR>
Even so, South Africa aggressively developed new markets in Asia and the
Pacific Rim and kept pace with technological change. &quot;This happened
in the sanctions era, when Europe and America were closed to our steel,&quot;
says Webb-Stock. &quot;We had to develop the Far Eastern markets and they
still remain our biggest clients.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Having been forced to enter one of the world's toughest markets, the South
African steel industry can boast today of its ability to compete with the
Koreans, unlike European rivals. Iscor is now opening a new 600-job Saldanha
plant in the Western Cape. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Attacking neighbouring markets <BR>
<BR>
</B>The company can also afford to be choosy. &quot;We will maintain a presence
on the markets where we get the best prices,&quot; Webb-Stock maintains.
With the steel cycle on the way down, Iscor looks at Africa as the market
of the future. &quot;We are already exporting to neighbouring countries
like Zimbabwe, Botswana and Malawi but it is done on a commercial basis,
even if we see it as a moral obligation to help with the development of
Africa,&quot; he insists. <BR>
<BR>
Modernisation, job creation and northward expansion into Africa are the
three main themes dominating conversation with almost any South African
industrialist. For politicians, fighting unemployment comes as a priority,
especially as international competition forces local firms into further
rationalisation and shedding of labour. While in the short term these two
trends seem mutually exclusive, in the long run they can complement each
other, believes provincial legislature economic affairs committee chairman
Andrew Feinstein. That is why the legislature has commissioned studies to
identify the most promising growth areas. <BR>
<BR>
Although the official results of the studies are not yet published Feinstein
envisages that they will single out &quot;the production of motor vehicles,
including component parts, fabricated metals, certain types of iron and
steel, construction and infrastructure generally, food processing and certain
downstream chemical products,&quot; he says. &quot;South Africa has a potential
that it has never attained for obvious political reasons,&quot; adds Feinstein.
&quot;In the medium term we would like to see some niche sectors, industrial
manufacturing sectors that we believe can be competitive either in the global
sense, or in certain specific markets where it makes more sense to service
them from South Africa than other destinations. I do not think it is realistic
to expect us to compete with the Germanys and the Japans,&quot; he says.
<BR>
<BR>
The changes have enticed back a number of international industrial giants,
like the Zurich-based conglomerate ABB which has chosen Gauteng as the site
of its sub-Saharan Africa headquarters. &quot;We have definitive plans for
the development of manufacturing capacity in South Africa,&quot; declares
ABB regional communications manager Regula Niehus. <BR>
<BR>
While old and new industries are not generally seen as compatible, in Gauteng
they are able to feed one another, with the modernisation of the steel and
manufacturing industry vastly expanding the market for information technology
and telecommunications. The impressive growth of the Vodacom cellular network
is the most obvious case. <BR>
<BR>
Established firms like Iscor are also seeking to expand. Not content with
an almost 75% share of the local market it is now seeking to expand abroad
according to Webb-Stock.
<BR><BR> <HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="investment"></A>TIDES OF INVESTMENT </H3>
<B>The changes have ushered in reforms for the Jo'burg stock exchange and
mergers for the country's banks <BR>
<BR>
</B><I>By Marek Garztecki <BR>
<BR>
</I>Johannesburg does for Africa what New York does for the world: it is
the continental centre for commerce and finance. With a stock exchange that
is by far the largest in Africa, a comprehensive, modern banking network
and a host of well developed financial services, the city is one of the
southern hemisphere's biggest money-boxes. The political and economic changes
of the last few years have further strengthened its dominant position. <BR>
<BR>
Paul G Bigler II, the vice president of Citibank in South Africa, says that
the most dramatic change, has been the growing internationalisation and
openness of the local financial markets. He also singles out the abolition
of a dual currency system last year as another crucial change. <BR>
<BR>
Ray C Andersen, the executive president of the Johannesburg Stock Exchange
(JSE), concurs: &quot;The changes have been absolutely fundamental. The
abolition of sanctions and the ending of the apartheid era has opened world
markets to South Africa and it has also opened Africa to South Africa.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
In practical terms, this has meant a substantial inflow of foreign capital
into South African securities. In 1994 net foreign indirect investment amounted
to just R200 million ($45 million), a year later it jumped to more than
22-fold to R4.5 billion. In the first three months of this year alone, it
has reached R2.5 billion. <BR>
<BR>
According to Andersen, foreign investment now accounts for over half the
trading on the JSE. At the same time, it has been restructured. &quot;We
have opened the membership worldwide,&quot; he points out, &quot;where previously
it was restricted to South African citizens. Of our 47 broking firms, nine
are now owned by foreign banks. &quot; <BR>
<BR>
The JSE listings requirements are now based on those used by the London
Stock Exchange. The capital adequacy regime for brokers is now based on
a European Union directive. An automated trading system is being installed.
&quot;We are one industry that is adapting to South Africa's opening to
the world,&quot; says Andersen. <BR>
<BR>
A similar process is taking place in the banking world. &quot;Opening the
economy also means the opening of many foreign banks,&quot; says Philip
Clayton, senior economist at the Standard Bank of South Africa. &quot;We
have seen that challenge, we noticed the massive down-scaling of jobs in
the British banking sector, we have seen that they are bringing down the
cost-revenue ratios. We know what the benchmarks are, we are aiming for
it,&quot; he says. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The consultants cometh <BR>
<BR>
</B>In the case of Standard, the second-biggest local bank, this meant a
re-structuring which involved merging its merchant house and the corporate
market division to create Standard Corporate &amp; Merchant Bank. Management
consultants McKinsey were brought in and 700 redundancies in the head office
are to follow. <BR>
<BR>
Other local banks are consolidating. Four of them &shyp; Allied, TrustBank,
United and Volkskas &shyp; have merged to form ABSA Bank, the country's
largest home-grown operation. The history of Standard Bank, created as a
result of the divestment of the Standard Chartered Bank during the period
of sanctions, is more typical. Similarly, the First National Bank of Southern
Africa is a result of a divestment by Barclays. This has strengthened the
local banking sector against foreign competition. <BR>
<BR>
According to Clayton, the top four South African banks rank in the top 20
in the world by asset base, close to those of Poland and Russia. <BR>
<BR>
Huge industrial conglomerates, another legacy of the past, are also facing
restructuring. Andersen says: &quot;During the sanctions period, when foreign
companies disinvested, it tended to be the local conglomerates who bought
the companies that were shed. What we are finding now is a natural tendency
towards unbundling.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Andersen believes that as institutions begin to invest offshore, they will
focus on a more limited number of core businesses. Their present shape,
spanning a wide range of industries, partly reflects the lack of investment
opportunities abroad. Already two local giants, Gencor and the Johannesburg
Consolidated Investments Group are in the process of unbundling. <BR>
<BR>
Another familiar feature of a country with an newly opened economy is a
privatisation programme, although ANC politicians insist on calling it a
restructuring. The executive president of the JSE can afford to be a bit
more blunt. He believes that the government is finalising its privatisation
strategy, quietly negotiating with the trade unions to smooth the process.
In the meantime, the parastatals are converting from government-controlled
to limited liability companies. &quot;The issue of nationalisation was taken
off the agenda long before the elections,&quot; Andersen says for those
who remember past ANC slogans. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;This is really an old perception. All utterances by the government
of national unity are about free markets, good fiscal and monetary discipline.
Privatisation is definitely on the agenda: the only thing that is being
debated is how and when, not if.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>A special programme for the poor <BR>
<BR>
</B>Andrew Feinstein, ANC member and a leading parliamentarian in the Provincial
Legislature readily agrees along with other politicians and many (still
mainly white) business people, who would also like to see privatisation
used to aid the black empowerment programme and offer shares at a discount
to the less well-off. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Twelve months ago there were only three black-controlled companies
listed on the stock exchange; today there are 14, with a market capitalisation
of about R8 billion,&quot; says the JSE president. <BR>
<BR>
Wide share distribution is all the more important, he believes, as South
Africa lacks a middle class. &quot;The wealth is very much distributed to
a thin veneer at the top, often racially defined,&quot; Andersen says. The
stock exchange reacted to this need by bringing special listings requirements
to help raise capital for the Reconstruction &amp; Development Programme
(RDP), which raises funds for investment in emerging businesses. One of
the biggest South African conglomerates, Anglo-American, is already making
opportunities available for black investors. <BR>
<BR>
Some bankers and business people privately admit that there is also pressure
to bring about a speedier change in the racial balance among South African
managers. According to Pieter van Huyssteen, chief executive of PW Corporate
Finance: &quot;We have a huge shortage of skills and professional and managerial
manpower. This has created a tremendous pressure. One professional can provide
jobs for a number of unskilled people, limiting the number of people that
can be employed. This is a typical South African problem.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Another obstacle in the way of a truly free financial sector is the continued
imposition of exchange controls. Although most expect them to be lifted
within the next 12 months, they are not only an irritant but also a serious
impediment to the growth of the local financial sector. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;For our subsidiary bank to finance a trade deal between Tanzania and
Zimbabwe from South Africa is virtually impossible,&quot; Clayton complains.
Neither is his bank able to finance a privatisation abroad, except in some
limited circumstances, where an immediate benefit to South Africa can be
proved. &quot;In comparison with our competitors from the US or Great Britain,
we are working with one hand tied behind our backs,&quot; he says. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Producing better products <BR>
<BR>
</B>This elicits an emphatic rebuke from Citibank's Bigler. A subsidiary
of a foreign bank incorporated in South Africa is subject to the same restrictions
as the native banks but has to operate with the disadvantage of a much smaller
capital base. It is the global reach of large organisations and their products
that give them the edge, he insists. <BR>
<BR>
But both the foreign and the local banker agree on the financial sector's
promising future. &quot;Will there be stability here? Yes. How long will
it take? Who knows?&quot; asks Bigler, &quot;But our return, broadly speaking,
is a vote of confidence in the opportunities we see to further our African
business.&quot; <p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
