<td valign=top align=left>
<H2>FRANCE </H2>
<H4>The country's new conservative president and government saw a record
drop in popularity and a series of sharp confrontations with workers in
their first year of office, after ditching over-ambitious election promises.
Now they are more at ease with themselves and are finally imposing tough
economic constraints. although state support for key sectors of the economy
remains strong <BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#overview">OVERVIEW</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#company-promise">COMPANY PROMISE</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#foriegn-investment">FOREIGN INVESTMENT</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#grand-alliance">THE GRAND ALLIANCE</A></H4>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3><A NAME="overview"></A>THE RETURN TO ORTHODOXY </H3>
<B>After a painful year of hardship and upheaval, President Chirac's government
is beginning to find its feet <BR>
<BR>
</B><I>By Diana Geddes </I><BR>
<BR>
&quot;We will ultimately be judged on our ability to produce a deep and
lasting movement of job creation,&quot; declared Alain Jupp&eacute;, France's
newly appointed Gaullist prime minister, last June after unveiling a 50
billion franc ($9.8 billion) package to create 700,000 jobs by the end of
this year. <BR>
<BR>
It always seemed an ambitious goal: now it looks plain crazy. Whereas 115,000
jobs were created in the first half of last year, <I>before</I> the present
government came to power, a mere 25,000 were created in the second half.
The official forecast for the first six months of this year is for zero
job creation at best and there is the strong possibility of an actual decline.
Unemployment, having fallen steadily from a peak of 12.5% in March 1994
to 11.4% last August, has since been on the rise again and is expected to
top 12% by June. This will give France the highest jobless rate for any
large developed nation except Italy. <BR>
<BR>
This helps explain the catastrophic fall in popularity of President Jacques
Chirac and his prime minister. Within four months of coming to power in
May last year, their initial high poll ratings with around two-thirds of
the population had been halved. <BR>
<BR>
Not since the beginning of the Fifth Republic in 1958 had a French president
lost so much popularity so fast. Since the beginning of this year, Chirac's
approval ratings have begun to rise (to around 40-46% in April), but those
of Jupp&eacute; have remained at around 30-33%. <BR>
<BR>
During his presidential campaign, Chirac had led the French to believe that
he could do what everyone else maintained was impossible: cut unemployment,
raise wages, lower taxes, increase welfare spending and slash the near-record
public deficit, all at the same time. But within five months of his arrival
at the Elys&eacute;e, he admitted there was &quot;no magic wand&quot;. Expectations
were sky-high: the ensuing disappointment was correspondingly deep. <BR>
<BR>
No one, of course, believed that he could really do all that he set out
to do. But few had expected him to do the exact opposite of what he had
promised. Taxes, instead of going down, have risen sharply by some FFr100
billion a year to a record 45.7% of GDP, one of the highest rates in the
western world. <BR>
<BR>
The promised war on unemployment, once billed as the government's &quot;priority
of priorities&quot;, was replaced by the battle to reduce the public deficit
in line with the Maastricht criteria for membership of economic and monetary
union (EMU). Wages have been frozen for public sector workers, despite Chirac's
conviction that this leads to more unemployment. <BR>
<BR>
But it was last November's plans for an overhaul of the extravagant and
inefficient social welfare system which proved the last straw for many.
Not only were they to be subjected to hefty new welfare charges and sharp
cuts in health spending, but public sector workers were also asked to work
longer in order to qualify for a full state pension. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Change or decline </B><BR>
<BR>
Some days after the government's announcement the railway workers, who were
also facing a painful restructuring of the debt-ridden state railways, and
public transport workers went on strike, sparking off the worst bout of
industrial unrest France had seen since <I>les &eacute;v&eacute;nements</I>
of May 1968. In the midst of the strike, which soon spread to the whole
public sector and brought much of the country's economic life to a standstill,
Jupp&eacute; went on television. &quot;France is at a crossroads&quot;,
he declared: &quot;Its only choice is between change or decline... Reform
is needed now.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The trouble was that the government had already erred when it failed to
make the most of the honeymoon period between a newly elected president
and the electorate to push through much-needed but unpopular reforms. Rarely
could there have been a more propitious moment to act. In addition to the
presidency, the right was now in control of over 80% of the seats in the
National Assembly, two-thirds of the Senate, 20 of the 22 regional councils,
four-fifths of the departmental councils and about half the big towns. Never
before had there been such a concentration of power under the Fifth Republic.
Yet the government dithered. <BR>
<BR>
A few days after his brave words about the need for change, Jupp&eacute;
was forced to climb down. The reform of public sector pensions was shelved,
the particularly generous pension schemes for rail and public transport
workers left untouched and the controversial railways restructuring plan
&quot;frozen&quot;. Action on the separate but equally explosive issue of
reforming a complex and outmoded fiscal system was postponed. <BR>
<BR>
But the public health reforms, constituting the heart of the government's
welfare reform package, remained intact as did the deeply unpopular welfare
charges. These are now gradually being introduced with surprisingly little
fuss and should be fully in place by June. Union threats of a new &quot;social
explosion&quot; have so far failed to materialise. <BR>
<BR>
For the moment, the government is anxious to avoid introducing further controversial
reforms. But it remains adamant about the need to reduce its massive public
deficit, heading for a near-record 5.7% of GDP when the administration came
to power, to 3% by the end of next year to meet the Maastricht convergence
criteria. <BR>
<BR>
With the government's new promise of no further tax hikes, coupled with
a dramatic slow-down in the economy (growth forecasts have halved to just
1.3% this year), this will prove extremely difficult, or impossible. But
there is no longer any doubt about the government's or Chirac's determination.
<BR>
<BR>
It was not always so. In 1978 Chirac made his &quot;appel de Cochin&quot;
from a bed in the Cochin hospital after a car accident, castigating the
then-president Val&eacute;ry Giscard d'Estaing's supporters as the &quot;foreigners'
party&quot; because of their pro-European views. Ever since then, Chirac
has appeared a waverer on Europe, alternately blowing lukewarm and cold.
But the construction of Europe and, with it, the realisation of a single
currency is now emerging as one of the great causes of his presidency. <BR>
<BR>
Chirac has turned from a hesitant European into a convinced European. <I>Le
Monde</I>, the left-wing newspaper not usually known for its support of
the president, has suggested that he could become the new &quot;prophet
of Europe&quot;. Even Jacques Delors, the former socialist president of
the European Commission and leading French Europhile, recently felt moved
to pay tribute to Chirac's &quot;evolution&quot;. Chirac remains a pragmatist
but like his predecessors he has come to believe that the only viable future
for France is in a strong and more closely integrated Europe. <BR>
<BR>
The collapse of the Soviet empire and the reunification of Germany affected
France more than most western countries. It suddenly found itself deprived
both of its self-assigned role as a neutral balancing force between the
two superpowers and of its supremacy in Europe. For a long time it floundered,
uncertain of how to preserve its self-claimed role as a leading actor on
the world scene. <BR>
<BR>
Ironically, it is the Gaullist Chirac who has become the first to accept
that France no longer has the financial means, political weight or military
force to continue with its traditional, Gaullist &quot;go-it-alone&quot;
approach to foreign policy. Bosnia has brought that home with force. He
appears increasingly convinced that it is only by giving some of France's
jealously guarded independence and by working more in cooperation with others
that France, a medium-sized industrial power, can hope to maintain its place
at the top table of nations. That means closer cooperation with Nato and
Europe. <BR>
<BR>
France's decision last December to resume its seat on Nato's military committee
and allow its defence minister to take part regularly in Nato meetings,
thereby ending a 30-year Gaullist boycott, is of great significance in this
respect. So, too, is its agreement to discuss the formerly taboo subject
of nuclear deterrence within Nato. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The march back to Nato </B><BR>
<BR>
The move is seen as a logical follow-up to France's offer last autumn to
extend the French nuclear umbrella to the whole of Europe. In return for
its closer cooperation with Nato, France is hoping to win American acceptance
for a distinct &quot;European defence pillar&quot; within the Alliance which
would be able to act on its own &shyp; with American logistic back-up &shyp;
when the US did not wish to become directly involved. <BR>
<BR>
The proposed shake-up of France's defence system is intended to aid these
developments. Under bold plans announced by Chirac in February, conscription
is to be phased out, the armed forces cut by a third and France's fragmented
and inefficient arms industry totally restructured. <BR>
<BR>
After a year in office, the Chirac administration is beginning to find its
feet. The president himself seems less unpredictable and clearer about where
he is going, both on the economic and foreign policy fronts. Since his television
statement last October, spelling out for the first time his unambiguous
commitment to a policy of economic rigour, a strong franc and EMU, there
has been no more talk of slashing interest rates and allowing the franc
to float, thereby effectively abandoning hope of EMU membership. <BR>
<BR>
As for his ratings in the opinion polls, Chirac remains stoical. Had he
not confounded the pollsters before? After all, six months before the presidential
election his ratings were so low that many thought he would be forced to
bow out of the race altogether. <BR>
<BR>
Jupp&eacute;, once described by Chirac as &quot;the best amongst us&quot;,
is a different matter. But, despite Jupp&eacute;'s continuing deep unpopularity,
Chirac will be reluctant to get rid of so trusted and able a colleague.
None of the suggested alternatives looks any better or even as good. <BR>
<BR>
So for the moment, Jupp&eacute; stays. But the way ahead does not look easy.
More sacrifices may be required of the French public if the government is
to reduce its deficits in time to qualify for the single currency. The continuing
upward trend in unemployment remains a particular worry. If things have
not improved by early next year, Chirac may well decide to bring in someone
new to head his government and lead the right into the next legislative
elections, due in the spring of 1998.<BR><BR> <HR WIDTH=60%>
<BR>
<H3><A NAME="company-promise"></A>NO PAIN, NO GAIN </H3>
<B>Private companies are now returning to profit. But they have yet to prove
their competitive vigour abroad <BR>
<BR>
</B><I>By Andrew Rosenbaum </I><BR>
<BR>
&quot;For a year, France dreamed,&quot; says Daniel Bouton, managing director
of the bank Societe Generale, &quot;and the account books stayed closed.
Now we are looking at them.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Many observers say that France is enduring a kind of post-electoral depression
that frustrates business. The year-long presidential elections of 1995 allowed
politicians to create a feeling of reverie, giving the French a sense that
unemployment would be overcome and growth would follow. <BR>
<BR>
Reality was just around the corner. The government increased taxes and threatened
massive spending cuts. Then the absence of growth and worsening unemployment
frightened consumers and businessmen, according to Julian Jessop, an economist
specialising in France with the HSBC Midland investment bank in London.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We are clearly entering a period of prudent, cautious behaviour,&quot;
says Alexander Lagayette, president of the government public debt agency,
the Caisse des Depots et Consignations. <BR>
<BR>
Despite these difficult conditions, private companies are enjoying a slow
return to profit. Many of the country's largest firms, from industrial giants
like Saint-Gobain to insurance companies like the Union des Assurances de
Paris, have enjoyed good results in the past year. A few like Michelin have
even performed exceptionally. Large French industry is successfully down-sizing,
adding value and becoming ever-more competitive on foreign markets. But
job-creation will remain virtually stagnant throughout this year which means
domestic demand will remain slack. <BR>
<BR>
Not everyone believes the upturn will last. &quot;The largest French companies
are following a conservative strategy that may not apply well to a troubled
economy,&quot; says Jacques Loussert, chief French equities analyst at the
Kleinwort Benson investment bank in Paris. <BR>
<BR>
Investment abroad has helped some large French companies, but a number have
invested heavily in Europe, often in Germany and central Europe, missing
higher growth in Asia and the US. <BR>
<BR>
As a result, the fraught question of European Monetary Union is now crucial
to their survival. Some observers, like Bouton at Societe Generale, insist
that the target date of 1999 will not be missed. But the question remains
a source of anxiety. <BR>
<BR>
French companies may be extremely competitive abroad, as last year's balance-of-payments
surplus shows. But growth is flat and unemployment is high at almost 13%.
Nor are prospects good. &quot;France can look forward to a marked rise in
GNP growth in the second half of 1996 for technical reasons,&quot; says
Francoise Milewski, assistant director of the economic statistics department
at the Observatoire Francais des Conjonctures Economiques (OFCE, the French
Economic Observatory). But he says 1996 growth will probably amount to 1%
or less. <BR>
<BR>
Milewski says the government faces some acute problems. &quot;There is little
chance that the Maastricht goals [for European Monetary Union] can be obtained
if the government does not find another way to raise revenue. &quot;Yet
if more taxes are in store, economic growth will be smothered,&quot; he
says. <BR>
<BR>
While inflation is low, close to 1% according to the OFCE, interest rates
remain relatively high. Because of the close link between the deutschmark
and franc the Banque de France cannot lower interest rates to stimulate
the economy unless Germany does. So bank loans are expensive and companies
loathe to invest. But unless enterprise invests and creates jobs, household
spending will remain depressed and growth will stay sluggish. <BR>
<BR>
There are other problems. Financing for start-ups has declined drastically
over the past four years, according to Christian Baillet, director of the
venture capital fund QUILMES in Paris. &quot;In the late '80s there was
a boom of venture capital finance, imitating that of the US. Unfortunately,
a large majority of these businesses failed. Now we financiers have become
extremely cautious,&quot; he says. <BR>
<BR>
Most entrepreneurs also suffer a lack of business training. &quot;The highly
trained <I>cadres</I> who graduate from France's best schools want corporate
jobs; they think that starting a business will get their hands dirty,&quot;
comments Alexander Lagayette of the CDC. &quot;Yet the less-educated small
business people who do take the leap don't really grasp the difficulties.&quot;
New reforms of the universities, may help close the training gap. <BR>
<BR>
Local initiatives taken by the government are beginning to bear fruit in
this critical area. &quot;Small enterprise has to be aided with a microeconomic
effort, so that the problems of different regions of the country can be
taken into account,&quot; Lagayette adds. <BR>
<BR>
Another challenge for ministers is reform of the public sector. &quot;It
is absolutely essential that the government be relieved of the burden of
the state-owned enterprises,&quot; Bouton says. The best part of French
state industry has already been privatised. But deeply troubled firms remain
like Air France and bank Credit Lyonnais. <BR>
<BR>
There are areas where government economic reform is likely to succeed. Changes
in the armed forces, launched this year, will help control spending and
the defence sector is being rationalised, through the merger of the efficient
private Dassault firm with the loss-making public giant Aerospatiale. <BR>
<BR>
Other public sector problems clamour for attention. In April, the <I>fonctionnaires</I>
or state employees who run the vast state telecommunications monopoly France
Telecom provoked a major strike &shyp; the second in six months &shyp; over
privatisation proposals. <BR>
<BR>
A growing and voluable public resentment against such actions began to make
itself heard. &quot;I have to keep my store open regardless of how difficult
they make it,&quot; comments Antoine Bordenave, a vintner in the centre
of Paris. &quot;They have nothing to worry about, because they cannot lose
their jobs. I can lose everything.&quot; A <I>fonctionnaire</I> at France
Telecom is practically exempt from the danger of being fired or laid off
and enjoys considerable perks unavailable to private sector staff. <BR>
<BR>
Bordenave's attitude indicates growing private sector anger towards the
public sector, says Patrick Rozenblatt, a sociologist and economist at the
Centre National de Recherche Scientifique (National Research Centre).But
even with falling public support, it will not be easy to reform public enterprise.
&quot;The <I>fonctionnaire</I> at France Telecom, or the Air France employee,
believes he is the victim of an injustice. He feels that he works for the
French state with its glorious principles of liberty and equality,&quot;
Rozenblatt says. &quot;He sees himself as a direct descendant from the heroes
of 1792 and believes that liberty means the right to work for the state.
What does he care about the 'globalisation' of the economy and the free-market
forces that are threatening his protected status?&quot; <BR>
<BR>
With <I>fonctionnaires</I> and the employees of state-owned companies making
up almost a quarter of the total workforce, the government is going to be
hard-pressed to push through the reforms it needs so much. This goes a long
way to explaining why the privatisation of France Telecom has been delayed
year after year. <BR>
<BR>
Will all these formidable obstacles be overcome? &quot;French industry is
increasingly competitive abroad and that is where the future lies,&quot;
according to one French government official. <BR>
<BR>
Given all the difficulties at home, it remains to be seen just how well
the country will fare. <BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%><BR>
<H3><A NAME="foriegn-investment"></A>THE DOLLAR MAGNET </H3>
<B>France is now a major target for foreign funds seeking a home within
the European single market <BR>
</B><BR>
The unstable economy in France and Europe as a whole, combined with noisy
strikes in the public sector, has only slightly affected investment in France
according to the Ministry of Economy. By contrast, French investment abroad
has declined markedly but should pick up again in the coming two years.
<BR>
<BR>
France is still the third largest target for foreign direct investment,
according to the World Competitiveness Report. It comes just after the UK,
but it must be said that there is some controversy over the statistics.
&quot;Certainly the two are still close&quot;, comments Peter Hall, a director
of mergers and acquisitions at Chase Manhattan bank in London. &quot;France
may appear more attractive to companies which are seeking a &THORN;rst foothold
close to the heart of a united Europe,&quot; Hall explains. The UK's endless
debates on its future in Europe create uncertainty in the minds of investors
and make some companies steer clear. <BR>
<BR>
The high-technology sector made up most of the $150 billion France attracted
in FDI last year. &quot;Technology and the high standard of workforce education
are the keys,&quot; comments Jean-Daniel Tordjman, ambassador-at-large for
international investment at the Ministry of the Economy. The most important
projects have involved high-tech companies like IBM which invested $1 billion
at Corbeil (near Paris) in a research centre, or the American AMTEL semi-conductor
firm which put $700 million into a production plant at Marseilles. Motorola
will soon employ 500 scientists at a facility near Toulouse whose job will
be to coordinate the company's telecommunications activities in Russia and
India. <BR>
<BR>
The US is by far the leader in French FDI while Japan is still timid, concerned
about the country's structural problems. The great barrier confronting those
who would invest in France is the rigidity of the country's labour laws.
&quot;The French are doing everything right,&quot; says Christian Marriot,
an analyst of international mergers and acquisitions with the London-based
trade magazine <I>Acquisitions Monthly</I>. &quot;But there is still one
basic advantage of investing in the UK: you can sack everyone you need to.&quot;
In France, labour law makes downsizing much more difficult. <BR>
<BR>
Tordjman admits that there are still problems facing would-be investors,
but says that much red tape has been eliminated. &quot;There is no longer
any need to obtain an authorisation from the French government for any acquisition
outside the defence area. And we at the ministry are bringing foreign investors
together with local authorities to help eliminate any provincial restrictions.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Certainly, as far as Tordjman is concerned, France's image problem has been
solved. &quot;We are no longer perceived as arrogant by foreign investors.
We are, on the contrary, famous for working well with them.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
French investments abroad, often in Germany and central Europe, have been
less successful and many &THORN;rms still rue the decisions they made at
the peak of Euro-enthusiasm. <BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%><BR>
<H3><A NAME="grand-alliance"></A>THE GRAND ALLIANCE </H3>
<B>Enthusiasm for all things private has made an impact in France. But state
industries will remain important <BR>
<BR>
</B><I>By Andrew Rosenbaum </I><BR>
<BR>
For two years Jean-Claude Leny fought to halt the privatisation of his company
Framatome, one of the world's largest constructors of nuclear energy plants
and the sole nuclear power station constructor for the state electricity
company El&eacute;ctricit&eacute; De France (EDF). He won late in 1994.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Our company is in a specialised line of business,&quot; Leny says.
&quot;The government has realised that Framatome is special and a move into
the private sector and therefore its separation from the French nuclear
complex would amount to the beginning of its dismantling.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Leny's critics complain that there is nothing particularly out of the ordinary
about his company and argue that bringing a little competition to the sector,
as in the UK and in the US, could do no harm although even in the Anglo-Saxon
world it is far removed from the sort of competition seen in the telecommunications
market. <BR>
<BR>
But Leny had some strong cards to play. Framatome is not an uncompetitive,
overstaffed state agency. Analysts say it is lean and mean, its prices are
reasonable and it is a wolfish competitor for export business. &quot;Framatome
is a tough competitor with the highest standard of technology,&quot; comments
Dick Kovan of <I>Nuclear Engineering</I>, an industry trade magazine based
in Sutton in the UK. &quot;It is one of the market leaders for nuclear energy
in Asia.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Leny's Framatome is only one of a number of French companies, some virtual
monopolies, whose operations are profitable both inside and outside France.
It is a special French model called &quot;High-Tech Colbertism,&quot; the
title of a book by one of its principal experts Elie Cohen, director of
the state research centre, the Centre National de Recherche Scientifique.
It takes its name from Jean-Baptiste Colbert who directed the French economy
under Louis XIV. <BR>
<BR>
As Cohen, one of France's well-known management theorists, puts it: &quot;The
rhetoric for privatisation has lagged well behind economic reality in France.&quot;
His book details the considerable success this model has enjoyed, although
he is sceptical about its future. <BR>
<BR>
Apart from national monuments like the state-owned electricity monopoly
EDF and telecommunications monopoly, France Telecom, there are companies
with huge privileges granted by the state like Alcatel-Alsthom. Altogether,
according to the Paris-based research agency the Observatoire Francaise
des Conjonctures Economiques, state &THORN;rms and those with approved monopolies
account for close to 10% of French GNP. Their role in France's total exports
is also crucial. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Prime example of state model </B><BR>
<BR>
In fact, despite the wave of privatisations in France &shyp; many of them
companies that were already partially private &shyp; nothing is likely to
be done about key sectors like telecommunications and electricity production.
The argument, in the terms that the French government has adopted, is that
the state should continue to enjoy the profits these companies produce.
Framatome presents a good example of this type of company. It saw FFr20
billion ($3.9 billion) in sales and FFr1 billion ($196 million) in profits
in 1994. Success on the export markets, according to French theory and practice,
justify the state support it enjoys. <BR>
<BR>
The result, complains Ashley Finch, marketing manager for Taiwan and China
at British Nuclear Fuels in Lilyhall, Cumbria, &quot;is that Framatome has
developed a more complete offer of nuclear services than we can, not having
such state support.&quot; Finch explains that some nuclear services are
uneconomic, and most companies from other countries in the industry cannot
compete. &quot;Even giants like Siemens and Westinghouse cannot manage it,&quot;
he says. <BR>
<BR>
With only one supplier of nuclear technology, the price of electricity should
be higher in France than elsewhere. But in fact, consumers pay slightly
less. A good case for maintaining state monopolies? The answer is sometimes.
Consumers do not always enjoy advantages as the example of France Telecom
shows. Telephone rates are higher in France than elsewhere, although the
system has been much improved since the '70s.<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

