<td valign=top align=left> 
<H2>LYON </H2>
<H4>Host of the next G7 economic summit, Lyon is working hard to realise
its promise. The city is seeking to entice foreign investors with tax breaks
and practical advice, offering a strong industrial and research base and
superior style of life. At the same time, it is trying to modify its focus
on the French capital and look to the rest of Europe for a prosperous future.
<BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#alternative-capital">ALTERNATIVE CAPITAL</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#film-developments">FILM DEVELOPMENTS</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#research-industry">RESEARCH FOR INDUSTRY</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#raymond-barre">RAYMOND BARRE</A><BR>
</H4>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="alternative-capital"></A>AN ALTERNATIVE CAPITAL </H3>
<B>Lyon is challenging the capital and other French cities for the title
of ideal location for foreign investors <BR>
<BR>
</B><I>By Elisabeth Faure </I><BR>
<BR>
Lyon, like all other big cities away from the capital, feels resentful about
its provincial status but this common inferiority complex is made worse
by its particular history. Tension with Paris dates from the end of the
16th century, a time when Lyon was not only more important but also considered
the possible site of a new capital by King Francois I. As Europe continues
the onward (albeit fractious) march towards integration, there is some sense
that the city may now be ready to regain some of its old prominence. <BR>
<BR>
Its image certainly needs to change. In recent times Lyon has struggled
with a reputation as an isolated city of passage. This is acknowledged by
Andr&eacute; Soulier, deputy mayor of Lyon, who believes the <I>syndrome
des tunnels, </I>a phrase derived from the large number of road and rail
tunnels in the region, is outdated and must be changed. &quot;Lyon still
relies on Paris for its identity and it is time the city looked away from
the capital toward the international community,&quot; he says. &quot;The
city will become a regional capital of Europe.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
So far, however, Lyon is far from achieving this status and its charming,
relaxed pace suggests a parochial self-satisfaction. Nor is Lyon the only
city in France with ambitions to be a regional capital within the new Europe:
it is in direct competition with others including Montpellier, Toulouse
and Geneva in Switzerland. <BR>
<BR>
City and regional officials agree that attracting foreign investment is
a priority if the city is to be transformed. As a result, an organised support
network has been established for foreign firms seeking a presence. Entreprise
Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes International (ERAI), which was created two years ago
and is financed by the regional government, is the organisation in charge
of attracting foreign investors to the Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes region. It conducts
marketing studies, works out transport costs and logistics and serves as
agent, introducing potential investors to possible partners. &quot;A large
foreign presence will cause a snowball effect, attracting more foreign investors,&quot;
says managing director Thierry Bernard. <BR>
<BR>
The current emphasis is on attracting medium-sized foreign companies to
the region since they are &quot;a stabilising force in the economy and easier
to control&quot;, says Bernard. He points out that with larger companies
like Hewlett-Packard, decisions about local branches are made far away.
If a decision is taken to close, &quot;no one can stop them and the damage
to the local economy would be enormous&quot;. With medium-sized firms, on
the other hand, if problems arise &quot;it may be easier to negotiate solutions
to encourage them to stay&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
<B>A base for foreign companies </B><BR>
<BR>
Over the past two years, ERAI has attracted firms in this category such
as Casals, Galletas and Cuetara from Spain, winning against Parisian complacency
&quot;because of ERAI's tailor-made approach to business&quot;. When the
Casals hardware<B> </B>company first established itself in Lyon, for example,
it was given space in ERAI'S building for the first months of business until
it could find offices. &quot;If there had not been room at ERAI to house
the company, I would have taken them into my own home,&quot; insists Bernard.
<BR>
<BR>
The Association pour le D&eacute;veloppement Economique de la R&eacute;gion
Lyonnaise (ADERLY) also seeks to support foreign investors. ADERLY has attracted
116 foreign firms over the past 10 years making investments worth FFr310
million ($61 million). Some 79 of these companies arrived over the past
five years, including the multilingual European television channel Euronews.
<BR>
<BR>
The agency also serves as something akin to an expatriate counselling service,
helping employees to find accommodation and suitable childcare or assisting
with the French bureaucracy. <BR>
<BR>
Robert Maury, director of ADERLY, is proud of the Euronews catch, secured
by offering tax advantages in the face of &quot;intense competition from
a dozen other cities including Munich, Valencia, Brussels and Berlin&quot;.
<BR>
<BR>
Investors have also been offered the enticement of infrastructure development
projects. Lyon has its own airport and there is a motorway network linking
it directly to Paris, Marseille, Toulon, Barcelona, Turin and Milan. In
addition, the Rh&ocirc;ne has been opened to navigation by large vessels
from Lyon to Marseilles in one direction and to the Seine and the Moselle
in the other. <BR>
<BR>
Feasibility studies are being carried out on the <I>Liaison Transalpine</I>,
a project linking Paris via Lyon to Italy's Piedmont region via a new, high-speed
rail network which would halve the rail travel time between Paris and Turin
to just over three hours. If the estimated FFr250 billion ($49 billion)
can be found, it could become the EU's single largest rail infrastructure
project. In another bid to attract foreign investment, the vast modern business
quarter known as Eurocity was completed last year, near Satolas airport.
<BR>
<BR>
Other efforts include the construction of an international <I>lyc&eacute;e</I>
or secondary school. In addition the &Eacute;cole Superieure de Commerce,
a well-regarded higher education establishment, organises exchange programmes
with universities abroad. &quot;The graduates are highly competent: I recruit
a large proportion of my staff from the university,&quot; says Phillipe
Bailly, director at Coopers &amp; Lybrand in Lyon. <BR>
<BR>
Lyon also has natural qualities which appeal to business. The city has a
strong industrial base, leading France in textiles, metallurgy, machine
tools, mining equipment and plastics processing. Some large groups in the
region such as the pharmaceutical firm Rh&ocirc;ne-Poulenc, the M&eacute;rieux
medical institute, small electrical goods manufacturer Seb and producer
of industrial glass BSN have achieved international status. They have not
only helped the city's output reach around 10% of French GDP but also give
it a resilience which provides some shelter from any economic storms buffeting
the rest of France. <BR>
<BR>
Location is a further attraction for those foreign companies wishing to
gain access to southern Europe. Andr&eacute; Soulier describes Lyon as the
&quot;last capital of the north and the first capital of the south&quot;.
Daniel Jacq, director of IBM in Lyon, remarks: &quot;If a company is serious
about doing business in France it has to have operations in Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes
as well as Paris.&quot; His company's activities in Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes represent
up to 15% of all of IBM's business in France. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Companies have more negotiating power than they think,&quot; Jacq
states. &quot;Since all big cities in France are competing for foreign contracts,
firms can play one city off against another to lower their costs, particularly
with regard to taxation. Any firm wishing to settle in the region must take
its time choosing a location and negotiate as much as possible.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
A number of potential barriers remain to the city's development, however.
Satolas airport, for example, does not run enough international charter
flights according to Christoph Radke, a partner at Lamy Veron Ribeyre, the
biggest law firm in Lyon. &quot;In this respect, Satolas is not even as
international as Manchester. It would have been better to expand Satolas
rather than build a third international airport in Paris,&quot; he comments.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>What Lyon still needs </B><BR>
<BR>
There is also a risk that the Lyon region will become saturated with traffic
unless further investment is made. The surrounding roads cannot take more
than 13,000 lorries a day and there are already up to 9,000 circulating
daily. In addition, there are only four foreign exchange offices in the
city and there is no luxury prestigious hotels which might attract conferences
and tourists. <BR>
<BR>
The city's two-hour link to Paris via France's high speed TGV train makes
it quicker for decisions made in Paris to be executed in Lyon, but some
consider it an obstacle to Lyon's progress. &quot;The TGV has a centralising
effect, making it easier for people to escape to Paris,&quot; complains
Christian Boussuges, director at the Banque de France and lecturer at the
&Eacute;cole Superieure de Commerce. &quot;A TGV linking Lyon to Turin and
Strasbourg would be much more beneficial.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Thierry Bernard feels that there is also a problem of rhetoric. For the
past few years local officials have been increasingly referring to 'Lyon
International'. &quot;This will not in itself change anything and is more
likely to draw attention to the fact that Lyon is not yet international,&quot;
he says. &quot;One does not need to refer to 'Barcelona international' or
'Frankfurt international', for example.&quot; The solution is to host a
big project or event, bigger than the G7 summit due in July: &quot;If asked,
most people would not be able to remember where the last G7 took place,&quot;
he observes. &quot;An event such as the Olympics would be more beneficial
for Lyon in the long run.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Jacq of IBM points out that the lack of official unity in the Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes
region is potentially damaging, caused by reported tension between the different
authorities. For example the two development agencies ADERLY and ERAI frequently
conflict about where foreign firms should establish themselves: while ADERLY
pushes for firms to settle in Lyon, ERAI is more concerned with promoting
the region as a whole. <BR>
<BR>
<B>A suspicion of change </B><BR>
<BR>
Furthermore, some complain that the mentality of people in Lyon is too insular
and conservative, particularly within the well established medical industry
although Alain M&eacute;rieux, director of the M&eacute;rieux Institute,
says this is changing. Things are comfortable for established families and
change would disturb all that. &quot;I would prefer to see Lyon develop
steadily and consistently rather than dramatically,&quot; observes Olivier
Gachon, director of ORI, a large land agency. &quot;By becoming a cosmopolitan
city, Lyon may lose its quality of life.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Besides problems particular to Lyon, there are other barriers to development
which are generally French in nature such as the chronic rivalry between
Paris and the regions. The British government was responsible for putting
Lyon forward as a candidate to house the Central European Bank, for example:
not the French. According to Jacq, for example, &quot;the lack of local
decision-making in the city tends to slow things down as many firms in Lyon,
particularly those in the more traditional sectors such as Rh&ocirc;ne-Poulenc,
have headquarters in Paris. If one wants to progress in a career it is not
possible to stay in Lyon. Many managers commute from Lyon to Paris, leaving
their families here to benefit from a better quality of life and lower cost
of living.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Most officials would like the city to develop a more decentralised, German-style
relationship with the capital but the postwar autonomy of Germany's <I>l&auml;nde</I>
is unique in Europe and as long as France's centralist tradition persists,
such a relationship is unlikely. Robert Maury says he is convinced that
France's high degree of centralisation &quot;paralyses Paris as well as
the regions: Paris has too much fat&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
Another generally French problem for foreign companies, particularly the
smaller ones, is the high cost of telecommunications in France &shyp; about
three to four times higher than in the UK. Gillette opened offices in Annecy
recently but had to move to London shortly afterwards because such costs
were unmanageable. <BR>
<BR>
Despite these problems, however, foreign direct investment (FDI) in the
region has increased. According to the regional branch of the statistical
office Ins&eacute;e, FDI in the Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes region rose from FFr1.9
billion in 1986 to FFr3.9 billion in 1990, before falling back to FFr3.6
billion in 1992, the most recent estimate. The figure for France as a whole
in 1992 was FFr42.5 billion. A large proportion of Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes FDI
has been aimed at Lyon. There are a total of 189 foreign firms in the city
representing over a third of foreign companies in the entire Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes
region. <BR>
<BR>
Christian Leroi, a director at Ernst &amp; Young in Lyon, has witnessed
this increase in foreign activity: &quot;The consultancy has had to develop
a complete service for foreign firms establishing themselves in the region.
Five years ago there was no demand for expatriate services while today we
receive approximately FFr1 million in fees from these services and secure
up to 12 projects from foreign firms every year.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>An outlet for distributors </B><BR>
<BR>
Christoph Radke has also noticed an increase, particularly since the end
of 1994: &quot;Most of the new arrivals have taken the form of distribution
outlets and takeovers. Using Lyon as a base for distributing goods in southern
Europe, while keeping production in the country of origin, is usually the
first-step, low-risk option for foreign companies.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
A number of Lyon observers feel that the city's current political situation
helps promote the city. Jacq at IBM considers Raymond Barre,<B> </B>former
French prime minister and now mayor of Lyon, is a positive force: &quot;He
is well known and serves as ambassador. Since his arrival last year, he
has been building links within the Rhone-Alpes region as well as with officials
in Paris and abroad.&quot; The fact that Barre is both mayor of Lyon and
president of the local government body, the Communaut&eacute; Urbaine, means
that tensions between the region and the city may be reduced. Such feelings
of optimism are fuelled as much by a dislike of his predecessor Michel Noir,
who has been barred from local politics after being charged with accepting
bribes, as they are by faith in the mayor himself. <BR>
<BR>
Officials are proud of the small but symbolic changes that have been made
recently to the city's image. Jo&euml;l Madile, head of communications at
the town hall, says: &quot;Before I took office last year, there were 48
different logos representing the city, far too many.&quot; She has chosen
one, a red lion, as Lyon's symbol. Neon displays throughout Lyon now give
residents and visitors information about the pollution level, traffic congestion
and the time, and a free monthly magazine was launched in October. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The G7 circus comes to town </B><BR>
<BR>
More substantially, perhaps, Lyon is hoping the G7 summit will boost tourism.
More than 5,000 people will be attending the summit, 2,000 of them journalists.
Amaury de Varax, director of tourism, wants to capitalise on the event and
plans to build a G7 museum. They would do well to remember the potential
pitfalls to this kind of promotional campaign: when the world's journalists
descended on Lyons in 1987 for the trial of Nazi Klaus Barbie for crimes
against humanity, Lyons gave them lavish material on the city's culinary
reputation. For their efforts, they were lambasted in the international
media for being in bad taste. <BR>
<BR>
The tourism budget has increased from FFr6 million to FFr19 million over
the past 15 years. Although there has been an increase in tourism of 25%
during the same period, Lyon is still far from being a well-known tourist
spot. <BR>
<BR>
The city's beauty is unarguable, however. Two rivers meet in the centre,
each with its own character: the narrow, convivial Sa&ocirc;ne, lined with
traditional Italian renaissance buildings, and the broader Rh&ocirc;ne,
bordered with modern blue and white structures. <BR>
<BR>
This imaginative approach to architecture can best be seen in the recently
renovated opera house; its domed roof has red lights which intensify with
the musical pitch inside. The weather is good, the city clean, transport
efficient and the food famous for its excellence. If all goes well and a
&quot;Europe of the regions&quot; is created, in which nation states diminish
in importance, Lyon has a good chance of becoming a key city, complementary
to Paris rather than at odds with the capital.<BR><BR> <HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="film-developments"></A>DEVELOPMENT OF FILM </H3>
<B>The unstoppable inventiveness of two brothers brought fame to them and
a huge industry to Lyon <BR>
</B><BR>
The name of a street in Lyon, <I>Rue du Premier Film</I>, is a loud and
public demonstration of the city's claim to be the birthplace of the modern
film industry. Although the centennial of cinema is being widely celebrated
this year, there is a rival orthodoxy that a vital step in the development
of the cinematic process was taken in Lyon as early as 1880. <BR>
<BR>
In that year, the brothers Louis and Auguste Lumi&egrave;re succeeded in
photographing 18 images a second, a record at that time. Their undisputed
claim to fame, however, is for the first public screening of a film in cinematic
history, on December 28, 1895 in the Grand Caf&eacute;, Boulevard des Capucines
in Paris. <BR>
<BR>
The film, entitled <I>Sortie des Usines Lumi&egrave;res </I>(Leaving the
Lumi&egrave;re Factories) was made by the Lumi&egrave;re brothers in Lyon
in 1895. It was screened using their invention the hand-cranked Cinematograph,
which made it possible for the first time to project a moving image to a
roomful of people. An ornate villa in the Street of the First Film now houses
the Lumi&egrave;re Institute and the hangar which served as the set for
the film has been preserved there. <BR>
<BR>
With their father Antoine Lumi&egrave;re, the brothers ran a photographic
studio in Lyon. Louis then developed an improved photographic plate, the
instant or dry plate. The family started commercial production of the invention
under the brand name <I>Etiquette Bleue</I> on the outskirts of the city.
By 1890 the Lumi&egrave;re factories employed 300 workers; by 1894 the firm
was the most important photographic enterprise in Europe and heavily reliant
on the region's chemicals industry. <BR>
<BR>
According to Frederique Ponsart, communications director at the Lumi&egrave;re
Institute, &quot;Lyon's chemical industry was key in manufacturing the plates,
providing a solid framework for the Lumi&egrave;re factories&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
Despite commercial success, &quot;the brothers continued to be passionate
about research,&quot; Ponsart says, &quot;and in 1900, invented coloured
photographs&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
The institute's 19th century home was the base of the Lumi&egrave;re company
and to this day preserves the prolific output of Luis and Auguste. Under
the institute's president, French film director Bernard Tavernier, it is
energetic in promoting the work of the Lumi&egrave;re brothers and film
culture as a whole. It organises exhibitions and sceenings and houses a
documentation centre, an education service and a publishing section. <BR>
<BR>
There has been some contention as to whether the Lumi&egrave;re brothers
were indeed the inventors of cinema. Frederique Ponsart stresses that &quot;any
invention is only a step among many, a turning point within a movement.
The invention of the plate was a natural progression but revolutionary&quot;.
The centenary celebrations held last year to commemorate the first public
screening of a film in 1895 consolidated the brothers' claim to this record.
<BR>
<BR>
The night before the start of the G7 summit, journalists will be entertained
at the Lumi&egrave;re Institute, and shown the first films ever made there.
<BR>
<BR>
Even to this day, Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes is a region that attracts film-makers.
Some 40 films have been made there over the past five years and the region's
production company is second in importance within France only to that of
Paris. Philip Kaufmann's adaption <I>The Unbearable Lightness of Being </I>and
more recently Claude Lelouch's <I>Tout &Ccedil;a pour &Ccedil;a</I> were
both produced in Lyon. <BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="research-industry"></A>THE ENGINE OF INDUSTRY </H3>
<B>An exceptionally dense group of research centres feeds an industrial
and scientific community <BR>
</B><BR>
Lyon is the birthplace of an impressive number of inventors and academics:
Alexis Carrel who won the Nobel prize for medicine in 1912, Victor Grignard,
Nobel prizewinner for chemistry in the same year and A M Amp&egrave;re,
the physicist whose name has been given to a unit of electrical current.
In 1958, Michel Jouvet was the first to prove the existence of paradoxical
sleep, the intermediate stage between being awake and asleep, a time when
most people dream. He went on to found the Lyon school of neuroscience,
one of the world's outstanding institutions in its field. <BR>
<BR>
The engine for the French high speed train or TGV was also developed in
Lyon. <BR>
<BR>
Industrial growth in the region relies heavily on research. There are 450
public and private laboratories in greater Lyon. The city has the highest
national density of public chemical research centres and private research
is expanding. Rh&ocirc;ne-Poulenc has seven sites with half its French potential
and the Elf Acquitaine oil giant employs 300 researchers in its regional
office. <BR>
<BR>
The region has a particular expertise in medical research. Significant medical
projects include the use of proteins to treat Alzheimer's and Parkinson's
disease and the city is an international base for cancer research. Consciousness,
gravity and magnetism are also being studied. <BR>
<BR>
Lyon is a world capital for homeopathy and has encouraged this alternative
practice since 1799.Boiron, manufacturer of homeopathic medicine with 60%
of the French market, is based in the city. The first university diploma
in homeopathy was introduced in Lyon in 1976. <BR>
<BR>
But Thierry Bernard, director of the inward investment agency ERAI, believes
that &quot;the region must focus more on developing its expertise in medical
research and not be too tempted to diversify its research activities&quot;.
<BR>
<BR>
Existing research projects in Lyon cover mathematics, data processing, materials,
earth and cosmic sciences and nuclear physics. In the postwar period, the
French government located a large part of its nuclear research effort around
Grenoble nearby. The European Synchrotron radiation facility is also based
there as is the national Atomic Energy Commission, which employs 2,600 people.
<BR>
<BR>
Public research in the area has attracted private companies both French
and foreign. According to a <I>Financial Times</I> survey on Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes,
15,000 private-sector jobs have been created around the research sector
in electronics, computer software and hardware. Many of the foreign companies
in Grenoble, such as the American firms Sun Micro Systems and SCI Systems,
are electronics specialists. <BR>
<BR>
The density of research institutes is possible at least in part because
of the number of high-quality educational establishments. Lyon 1 university
has laboratories for industrial chemistry, physical organic chemistry and
process engineering. The National Applied Sciences Institute INSA has industrial
physico-chemistry and organic chemistry laboratories. <BR>
<BR>
Some schools share their expertise and equipment with industrialists. These
include ESCIL (Lyon Chemistry Engineering School), ISPC (Industrial Physics
&amp; Chemistry Institute) and ITECH (Textile &amp; Chemical Institute).
An Ecole Normale Superieure Scientifique was founded in 1987. <BR>
<BR>
Companies in the region invest about FFr9 billion a year in research and
development. Pasteur-M&eacute;rieux, for instance, devotes 16% of its annual
turnover to research, employing 800 researchers. <BR>
<BR>
Rh&ocirc;ne-M&eacute;rieux was one of the first companies to produce vaccines
through genetic engineering. Between 1986-90, 3,107 patents originated in
the region (16.4% of the national figure) and 320 European research and
development contracts for public laboratories were signed. <BR>
<BR>
Bernard of ERAI, says this commitment to research is crucial. &quot;This
is typical of the region and the scientific environment encourages industrialists
to think in this way,&quot; he says.<BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="raymond-barre"></A>BARRE'S BALANCING ACT </H3>
<B>The mayor is just as confident of solving social problems as he is in
the competitiveness of Lyon's industry <BR>
<BR>
</B><I>By Andrew Rosenbaum </I><BR>
<BR>
For its mayor, Raymond Barre, running a city as complex as Lyon is a kind
of juggling act. &quot;You have to be able to balance all the different
demands made on you by different groups, and give each their due,&quot;
says the former French prime minister, who has spent much of his career
in Paris as a cabinet minister and parliamentarian and who is accustomed
to moving on the world stage. <BR>
<BR>
Lyon is a prosperous but troubled city, where the economic success of industry
is offset by high unemployment, large numbers of poor immigrants and one
of the highest crime rates in the country. Demands for government investment
in social issues are great. &quot;So it's a question of setting priorities,&quot;
Barre says. &quot;We will spend money on social causes where it is most
necessary, but we will not sacrifice development of the city.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Crime is clearly a priority. &quot;There is a sense of insecurity in some
areas of the city, and we intend to change that. Ours is an adaptive city,
and we will do what is necessary to keep crime in check,&quot; he says.
The city has a new high<B> </B>court to help it cope with being the third-busiest
circuit in the country<B>.</B> &quot;It is urgent that our city have a modern
judicial facility which [is able to] perform with great efficiency,&quot;
he says. <BR>
<BR>
The mayor believes the siting<B> </B>of courts in under-privileged areas
such as the eighth arrondissement is essential. In these areas, he says,
a kind of partnership is being established between educational bodies, business
groups and the courts in order both to prevent juvenile delinquency and
to help the return to employment of ex-offenders. <BR>
<BR>
On the integration of Lyon's large North African immigrant community, he
says: &quot;I have been heartened by the increasing dialogue between our
police and the Islamic community... when police were recently accused of
mistreatment, the local mayor was able to create a dialogue between the
Muslim community and the authorities. It shows that progress is being made.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
One of the things Barre has focused on is the development of the so-called
<I>friches industrielles</I>, an area of abandoned industrial buildings
and land in areas such as the Vaise district and the eighth arrondissement.
Barre is committed to redeveloping these districts, believing that will
help create jobs and cut crime. There are also what he calls the &quot;leftovers
from the '60s&quot;, the huge housing estates built at that time in otherwise
empty areas on the city's periphery. &quot;These need to be integrated into
the life of the city,&quot; Barre insists. Lyon even boasts a thriving agricultural
area on the outskirts of the city which Barre intends to preserve and support.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Riding French economic waves </B><BR>
<BR>
France's economic crisis has not spared Lyon. &quot;It took longer to reach
us, perhaps, but it has hit the city harder than elsewhere,&quot; Barre
says. But he thinks that the skill of Lyon's exporters will be able to overcome
the problems posed by the crisis:&quot;Our business is much better at reaching
foreign markets than is the case in many other French cities.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Even the <I>franc fort</I>, the strong French franc, has not created a barrier
to Lyonnaise exports, he adds ethusiastically. <BR>
<BR>
The statistics bear him out. According to the independent Observatoire Francais
de la Conjoncture Economique, Lyonnaise industry has benefited considerably
from investment in nearby Italy and exports there with considerable success.
&quot;The productivity and research capacity of our industry more than compensates
for a difficult economy,&quot; Barre says. &quot;Hard work makes a difference.&quot;
Adaptation is the key, he believes. For example, fhe city's successful companies
run programmes to train the unemployed. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Lyon is a kind of intelligence centre,because there is so much high-tech
research going on. The highly trained unemployed have a good chance of finding
their way into another skilled job.&quot; To maintain this, education is
a top priority. &quot;We have budgeted FFr111 million for education &shyp;
it is the second largest budget area for the city,&quot; Barre explains.
Attacked because he has reduced the budget for foreign language instruction,
he points out that education as a whole is still a priority but this particular
area must await more support from central government. <BR>
<BR>
Certainly small industry is created faster and on a better footing in Lyon
than it is in many other cities. &quot;The survival rate for small business
is higher in Lyon than it is elsewhere,&quot; Barre says. &quot;This is
because our entrepreneurs are better trained: indeed they grow up in an
environment where it is prestigious to run a small business.&quot; And small
businesses do expand into larger ones in Lyon at a faster rate than in most
cities. <BR>
<BR>
Barre is trying to link Lyon's successful businesses into a network of transregional
corporations. He sees the city as a part of a great regional economic area
stretching from Barcelona to Marseille to Genoa: Europe's great south-west.
&quot;To link Lyon not just with nearby Grenoble, but with an entire group
of cities including the likes of Geneva and Turin, is one of the great goals
I have set for myself as mayor,&quot; he says.<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

