<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra17.gif" alt="Area Profile">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>

<H2>TURKEY </H2>
<H4>Turkey has produced some impressive growth over the last 20 years. Even
so, the country currently faces a raft of serious political, economic, social
and military problems. Popular anti-western feeling has grown and political
leaders are fending off calls for the country to turn away from Europe.
But Turkish business has just been given the opportunity it has long waited
for: a customs union with the EU<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#eu-embrace">EU's CLOSER EMBRACE</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#president-demirel">PRESIDENT DEMRIEL</A></H4>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3><A NAME="eu-embrace"></A>A CLOSER EMBRACE </H3>
<B>If Turkey manages to create a strong democracy, the European Union is
promising priviliged treatment </B><BR>
<BR>
In language so plain that no one in the audience could mistake the message,
EU ambassador in Ankara Michael Lake recently spelled out to Turkey's leaders
the onerous responsibilities they are taking by signing up to an enhanced
customs union. &quot;If democracy were to falter or be threatened in Turkey
the customs union, the fate of the Turkish economy, would be immediately
called into question,&quot; he said. <BR>
<BR>
The customs union, which took effect on January 1 this year, could mark
a big step forward in realising Turkey's dream of taking its place at the
heart of Europe. Ambassador Lake called it an irreversible step, although
Greece has blocked further progress because of confrontation between the
two countries over sovereignty in the Aegean. <BR>
<BR>
Lake says the consequences of a failure would be awful. There would be financial
paralysis, a collapsing currency, a regime of severe austerity and a possible
freeze on investment with an accompanying loss of jobs and trade opportunities.
Turkey would be plunged back into economic isolation and protectionism.
No doubt stung by the impressive vote for the anti-western Islamic Welfare
Party in last year's elections, the ambassador sought to chart an alternative
path. If Turkey can live up to its obligations under the treaty, he promised
that it will enjoy the most intimate relationship with the EU of any country
in the world. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Past days of growth </B><BR>
<BR>
At almost any other time in its modern history, since the founding of the
present state in 1923 by Kemal Ataturk, the customs union might well have
been greeted with equanimity. Indeed, in the period from 1970 to 1993 Turkey
enjoyed high growth rates and a highly successful world economy. <BR>
<BR>
And while many believe that Turkey's closer integration with Europe will
again help to make it one of the strongest emerging market economies, the
timing of the long-awaited customs union could have been better. In the
short term, the country faces a daunting agenda of economic, social and
political problems that will take courage and vision to overcome. <BR>
<BR>
Ataturk's vision was to build and foster a modern industrial state through
government enterprises that would be transferred to the private sector once
they were up and running. More than 70 years later, and despite the incredible
growth of the economy as a whole, most enterprises remain in state hands
and are inefficiently run, over-staffed and kept afloat only with costly
government subsidies. <BR>
<BR>
A financial crisis dogging the state social security system is adding to
the intense pressures on the Turkish Treasury. These have reverberated through
the economy, fuelling levels of inflation 25 times those in the EU. The
average year-to-year increase in the consumer price index over the past
15 years has been between 60% and 65% and is currently over 80%. Some leading
businessmen predict a figure in excess of 100%. <BR>
<BR>
The extent of the government's domestic budget deficit, around $23 billion,
compares quite favourably with some European nations and is not in itself
cataclysmic. But in order to raise the cash to finance its obligations,
the treasury has had to resort to ever shorter terms and ever-higher interest
rates for its T-bills. Three-month bills carry a real interest rate of 25%
- among the highest in the world. <BR>
<BR>
There is the glimmer of a silver lining since high interest rates on Turkish
lira instruments have eased demand from domestic investors for dollars and
deutschmarks. This has allowed the central bank to start rebuilding its
foreign reserves. Other indicators are not so reassuring: last year saw
a widening trade gap. Analysts believe that without rigid austerity measures
the deficit will continue to grow this year. The government estimated a
balance of payments deficit last year at $300 million. In fact, it was more
like $1.5 billion. <BR>
<BR>
Given the nature and scope of the problems it is not surprising that some
political leaders look for a magic wand. For many on the right the answer
is privatisation, but although a privatisation law was passed in 1994 only
a few companies have been sold off and the issue remains highly controversial.
<BR>
<BR>
A prerequisite for major reforms is stable government, but December's election
results produced no clear winner. After weeks of party political bickering,
an uneasy coalition of the business-dominated Motherland Party and agrarian-based
True Path movement led by former Prime Minister Tansu Ciller was formed
in March. <BR>
<BR>
Calling it a personal sacrifice for stability, Ciller - Turkey's first
woman leader - agreed to step aside in favour of Mesut Yilmaz, the
leader of her minority partner Motherland. He will serve as prime minister
for the rest of the year on the understanding she takes the helm again next
year. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Islam's message to the poor </B><BR>
<BR>
The problem is that the coalition is 15 seats short of an overall majority
and its survival will depend on the compliance, or lack of it, of former
prime minister Bulent Ecevit's Democratic Left Party. Waiting in the wings
is the Islamicist Welfare Party led by Necmettin Erbakan, whose policies
would pull Turkey out of the European orbit. <BR>
<BR>
In his search for a coalition partner, Yilmaz flirted briefly with the Islamicists
who already run the city governments in Istanbul and Ankara and who have
achieved wide popularity among the poor. Yilmaz was reportedly warned off
by the Turkish military, a secular force deeply involved in politics. <BR>
<BR>
Whatever the prospects for their marriage of convenience, leaders of the
new government are insisting that their chances of achieving reforms are
better than those of Ciller's previous administration, whose efforts at
tackling social security and privatisation got bogged down in disputes with
her coalition partner, the Democratic Left. Foreign minister Emre Gonensay,
an academic and former adviser to Ciller, says that despite the reported
bitter rivalry between her and the prime minister the coalition parties
&quot;certainly can live together. They see eye to eye on most issues. Their
[election] programmes were almost identical, so it took only a couple of
hours to put a government programme together.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
From his vantage point, President Demirel appears less sanguine about the
government's chances than some ministers. &quot;As long as it is successful,
it will be stable,&quot; he said in an interview with <I>World Link</I>.
&quot;If it is not successful, no matter how it is set up, it will not be
stable. We are just at the start, we don't know how things will go. I think
we should be somewhat patient.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
But time may not be on Turkey's side. Prime Minister Yilmaz is making an
aggressive start on the privatisation process but he has barely eight months
of his mandate left and he faces public reservations about the benefits
of a switch to a full market economy, as well as resistance from politicians
used to running the state enterprises. <BR>
<BR>
As Gonensay puts it: &quot;The major opposition comes from vested interests,
from people who will lose their privileged positions either within the enterprise
itself or people who obtain cheap services from these enterprises.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Even President Demirel, a late convert to privatisation, spells out why
resistance remains strong: &quot;It is not easy to get understanding for
privatisation in the first place,&quot; he says. &quot;In state enterprises
there are working people [who wonder] what will happen to their future.
The state enterprises are an accumulation of our national wealth. They are
built with tax money and for years we have been proud of them. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Times have changed and [we] started selling [the enterprises] and
the people are looking at us and saying, 'Why are you selling?' It takes
time [to get the idea across] that we are not giving them away, that we
are not just making some people rich... But I think people are beginning
to realise that [for the state] to continue to operate them is going to
create lots of hardship on the treasury and that is causing inflation.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Gonensay, also a former adviser to the president, is among those who regard
privatisation as a panacea for the nation's economic ills. Asked whether
privatisation alone cure the economic ills, he says: &quot;It will, it will.
Because if it takes care of the accumulated government debt, then the debt
becomes smaller in relation to the financial assets market and interest
rates go down, and that cures most things in the economy.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>Difficult economic choices </B><BR>
<BR>
But foreign diplomats and economic analysts say that while privatisation
undoubtedly offers long-term benefits, it is not a cure-all. They argue
for immediate swingeing cuts in a bloated government bureaucracy and agricultural
subsidies, an end to the lira's artificially high value against foreign
currencies, and urgent reform of the tax system to tackle endemic tax avoidance.
It is not an easy choice. Any or all of these options will add to the strains
on a country in which the gap between rich and poor is widening and in which
huge migration to overcrowded cities is weakening family and religious ties,
adding to support for extreme political movements. It is estimated that
three million people exist on the monthly minimum wage of $86, only a quarter
of the amount necessary to enjoy a reasonable standard of living. More than
15% of all households fall below the poverty line. Meanwhile, the creation
of what has been dubbed a &quot;financial parasite class&quot; - those,
for example, with enough spare cash to benefit from overnight bank interest
rates as high as 100% - are adding to social problems. Recent studies
suggest that the wealthiest share more than 60% of the national income.
<BR>
<BR>
Poverty is most extreme in the south-east where the 12-year-old armed struggle
continues against &quot;terrorists&quot; of the Kurdistan Workers' Party
(PKK), who are bent on setting up their own separatist state. International
human rights organisations have documented atrocities on both sides in the
conflict which is a further massive drain on Turkey's resources: the government's
military budget dwarfs funds available for health and education. <BR>
<BR>
Turkey's Human Rights Association (IHD) says the conflict claimed 3,894
lives last year alone. Foreign Minister Gonensay sums up the prevailing
attitude when he says: &quot;The PKK is a terrorist organisation fighting
to dismantle Turkey and there is no case for talking to them.&quot; And
PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan, who seems to have a safe haven in neighbouring
Syria, has begun issuing ominous warnings of Hamas-style suicide attacks.
<BR>
<BR>
Despite the PKK's blood-curdling rhetoric, it is Turkey itself that has
borne the brunt of criticism from its European allies over human rights
abuses, not just in the Kurdish conflict. A recent European visitor to a
carpet factory outside Istanbul was shocked to find girls as young as six
working the looms to produce silk carpets. <BR>
<BR>
According to leading Istanbul banker and former academic Professor Celik
Kurdogu, a founder member of the Foreign Economic Relations Council, says
the root of the problem is a lack of culture and education. What he calls
the &quot;illiteracy&quot; of some police officers leads them to perform
actions that &quot;do not necessarily reflect the views of the ministry
of the interior&quot; or, indeed, of the public at large. In this context,
the professor welcomes a new frankness in the debate about police methods.
<BR>
<BR>
Even so Yavuz Onen, president of the Human Rights Association, remains unconvinced
that the necessary reforms are being made. &quot;In general terms, human
rights violations are continuing and increasing.&quot; he wrote recently.
This sort of criticism is certain to fuel the debate at home and abroad
on the nature of Turkish democracy. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The area's only democratic Muslim state </B><BR>
<BR>
It is hard not to feel some sympathy for the problems facing Turkey in its
determination to succeed as a democratic, secular state with an open market
economy and guaranteed human rights a gateway of ideas and trade between
east and west. It is the only democratic Muslim state in the region, however
fallible its institutions. On its easternmost flank lie the volatile former
Soviet republics of Armenia, Azerbaijan and Georgia. To the south, Iraq
stumbles along under a murderous dictator while Syria sets its own agenda.
In the north, Bulgaria struggles to regain national consciousness and to
the west Greece feels suspicious and threatened. <BR>
<BR>
Despite its present troubles, a World Bank study shows that over the 23-year
period from 1970 Turkey had the third largest growth rate of 22 large economies
in the world. While GDP grew 35.8 times in South Korea and 19.7 times in
Japan, it rose an impressive 12.7 times in Turkey. The country's 1970 GNP
of $11.4 billion rose to $156.4 billion by 1993. Obviously this has produced
some success stories. Petkim, for example, is a publicly owned petrochemical
giant. Although the government still holds a 96% stake, the company under
president Meral Oztekin has begun to function much like a private enterprise,
developing overseas markets to sell realistically priced products. As a
result, the company reported a 469% rise in net profit over 1994 to about
$500 million, after losing $140 million in 1993. The company is now scheduled
for privatisation. <BR>
<BR>
Another bright spot is tourism which has continued to outperform even the
usually over-optimistic official forecasts. After a bumper year in 1995
in which 7.9 million tourists generated $5.l billion in revenue - almost
15% of the country's annual foreign exchange earnings - the government
expects a record 9.5 million visitors this year and $6.5 billion revenue.
<BR>
<BR>
Turkey's car-makers, gearing up for the prospect of increased imports under
the customs union, nevertheless had a good year in 1995. Exports were worth
$272.3 million, an increase of 259%. <BR>
<BR>
Among political and business leaders, there is a optimism that the customs
union will push Turkey into adapting its democratic institutions and business
practices in a push for full EU membership. President Demirel says: &quot;The
customs union will crown Turkey's process of integration with the world
economy. It will help rationalise and modernise Turkey's economic structure
and increased competition will improve the efficiency of its firms. The
opening of the European market will, on the other hand, enable industry
to reach economies of higher scale.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The president is equally aware of the disruptions the union is likely to
cause among Turkey's most vulnerable firms. &quot;There may be some negative
effects in the short run, especially on small and medium-sized enterprises,&quot;
he says. &quot;However, EU [aid will help] support these enterprises.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Foreign Minister Gonensay is just as bullish. &quot;It opens up tremendous
opportunities. That is why the automotive sector has signed an agreement
concurrently with the customs union so that, for example, there will be
a specific Italian world model [of Fiat] manufactured in Turkey alone.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
True to the tradition of Ataturk, President Demirel displays a personal
interest in the huge southeast Anatolia water project (GAP), a massive government-funded
infrastructure programme to dam and use the waters of the Tigris and Euphrates
rivers and hopefully stimulate the poverty-stricken region. The project,
which will regulate the flow of water to Turkey's southern neighbours, is
drawing protests from Syria but Demirel insists it will go ahead to completion.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It has nothing to do with the Arabs,&quot; the president says. &quot;Definitely
we are going to use some part of the flow but no matter how much we use,
they will have [enough]. We are people of goodwill, we are not going to
cause any hardship to those countries. But when you have the border crossing
rivers, you cannot talk about equality, you can talk about equity.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Braced for short-term pain </B><BR>
<BR>
Despite hopes for a greater regional role for Turkey, current efforts to
develop regional economic co-operation between Black Sea states are making
little progress. <BR>
<BR>
But the major need is to get the nation's domestic economic house in order.
That could mean further short-term pain. Despite some immediate public sector
price hikes imposed by the new government, business leaders say more sweeping
austerity measures are required. Many, such as the prestigious Association
of Turkish Industrialists and Businessmen, take a gloomy view of their prospects.
They forecast annual growth this year of just 3.3%, compared to 6.8% last
year. Other analysts predict a further decline next year to a mere 1.2%,
making Turkey the slowest growing country in Europe. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The first impact [of the customs union] may be negative,&quot; says
EU ambassador Lake. &quot;The removal of [tariff] protection need not be
an overnight shock. But there will undoubtedly be a J-curve as things get
worse in the short-term before they get better.&quot; Lake's optimism is
echoed by another foreign envoy who says: &quot;Turkey has tremendous structural
problems in the short term. But it has a dynamic private sector that will
make it one of the biggest emerging market economies of the 21st century.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
The eventual wider goal for Turkey, says Gonensay, &quot;is to become part
of Europe and at the same time to extend it: extending the values, the system,
the democracy of Europe gradually towards the east. Europe cannot overlook
the potential problems. We should work together to eliminate these potential
dangers and bring prosperity, peace and stability to this region. It is
a tall order, but it must be done, it cannot be neglected.&quot; <BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3><A NAME="president-demirel"></A>AN EXPERIENCED HAND</H3>
<B>President Suleyman Demirel will need his wealth of experience to lead
the country through a tough period </B><BR>
<BR>
Opponents of Turkey's closer integration with Europe exist both within the
country and outside, and it is important for Turkey's friends and allies
to bear that in mind, says the 72-year-old president, Suleyman Demirel.
<BR>
<BR>
In an interview with <I>World Link</I> at the presidential palace in Ankara,
the veteran statesman and seven-times prime minister said that Turkey's
historic ties with Europe will be strengthened by its recently signed customs
union with the EU. But he warned that while no one should have misconceptions
about Turkey's &quot;irreversible&quot; commitment to a democratic and secular
market democracy, outsiders should realise that the development and perfection
of democratic institutions is a continuing process. <BR>
<BR>
The president insists that Turkey is a peace-loving republic with only goodwill
for its neighbours. He says no one should mistake Turkey's good intentions
for weakness and promises that the country will defend its interests as
necessary. &quot;There are opponents of integration with the west in Turkey
and strong opposition in some neighbouring countries... who will take advantage
of tension in our relations with the west,&quot; the president said. <BR>
<BR>
Demirel, who was elevated to the presidency on the sudden death of Turgut
Ozal in 1993, enjoys limited powers under the Turkish constitution but is
an active foreign ambassador in the cause of Middle East peace and economic
cooperation with the countries of the former Soviet Union. He frequently
reminds his audiences of Turkey's unique position in the region as the only
Muslim state committed to Europe, a free market and the development of a
functioning democracy. On occasion he has shown frustration over attempts
from outside to dictate the pace of Turkey's reform. <BR>
<BR>
He admits to &quot;imperfections&quot; in the present system, but says:
&quot;What we expect from our friends in the west is an understanding that
we are making a genuine effort to correct those imperfections... and that
we have been successful in preserving our democratic life while confronting
the threat of terrorism.&quot; The reference is to the 12-year-old conflict
in southeastern Turkey where the country's armed forces are engaged in a
bitter struggle to put down a rebellion by Kurdish &quot;terrorists&quot;
of the Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK) whose goal is the establishment of
a separate state. <BR>
<BR>
International human rights agencies and other foreign organisations have
long criticised both the Turkish forces and the rebels for their alleged
frequent and widespread use of torture and summary executions of soldiers
and civilians. The EU made it a condition of the customs union that Turkey
amend anti-terrorist laws that made it a crime to speak out against government
policy. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Turkey is being pictured as an incomplete democracy,&quot; the president
complains. &quot;That is the main misconception. However, democracies are
regimes of gradual and sustained search for perfection. We are aware of
our responsibilities and obligations in the field of democracy. It is a
matter of great pride for us that the Turkish people have irreversibly opted
for democracy.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
On the question of how Turkey should handle the PKK conflict, the head of
state says that when people of goodwill offer advice, &quot;instead of telling
them to mind their own business we tell them what our trouble is [and] if
they know the solution they should tell us&quot;. Democracy is a continuing
process: &quot;The participation of the people in this process and realisation
of their aspirations are essential for a standard and workable democracy.
That is what is happening in Turkey. What is also important is to find remedies
for progress when faced with the deficiencies arising from ever-changing
social, economic and political conditions. &quot;As long as this mechanism
works, advancement of a healthy democratic regime is secured. Turkish democracy
is well established and strong enough to overcome difficulties. I have full
confidence in the future of democracy in our country,&quot; he says. <BR>
<BR>
Speaking of his country's role in foreign affairs, the president says the
emergence of new states in the former Soviet Union presents new possibilities,
challenges and opportunities and &quot;Turkey is going to be the link between
Europe and this new continent.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The Middle East also offers opportunities for Turkey and the country is
actively supporting the peace process. &quot;Iraq should become a part of
the international community,&quot; he says. &quot;The whole Arabian peninsula
will eventually come to work together, and here again Turkey is a gateway
to those countries.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Territorial disputes with Greece in the Aegean, which have recently hit
the world's headlines, were not of modern origin but &quot;inherited from
history&quot;, he said. Turkey handed the Dodacanese Islands to Italy before
the Second World War, a decision Ankara says was made under duress. The
victorious powers granted Greece sovereignty in 1947. Athens says Turkey
should refer to dispute to the International Court of Justice in The Hague.
&quot;We have disputes with Greece over shoreline and continental shelf
and air space and some of the islands close to Turkey. Turkey is a peace-loving
country [but] if we want peace no one should interpret that as weakness.
It is not weakness, it is wisdom. I do not think anyone should make a miscalculation
over how powerful [the country] is.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
President Demirel says that the customs union must become a solid base on
which to build Turkey's fuller integration with Europe. &quot;In order to
achieve a properly functioning customs union, Turkey should participate
in the EU's decision-making process on an equal footing.&quot; The customs
union, stemming from a 1963 EC/Turkey agreement and a 1971 protocol, is
seen by Ankara as an important step in the whole process. <BR>
<BR>
He says that for the past 50 years, Turkey has participated in practically
all bodies aimed at enhancing European integration and the principal elements
of Turkish foreign policy have converged with those of the EU. &quot;Turkey
will be a genuine part of the economic integration represented by the EU,&quot;
he says. &quot;Successful implementation of the customs union will prepare
Turkey for full membership.&quot;  
<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

