<td valign=top align=left>
<H3>FROM THE EDITOR</H3>
<H2>Aim for a national best</H2>

<H4>Hubris is not just a Greek word; all countries must struggle to balance
the demands of the head and heart</H4>


This issue's cover story illustrates a basic point about national entities
which has universal implications. It is that nations, like individuals,
are not always motivated by rational self-interest and do not always &shyp;
correction: rarely &shyp; do what is best for them. Naturally, there is
always a debate about how to de&THORN;ne &quot;best&quot; but often it comes
down to a simple contest between the head and heart. <BR>
<BR>
The head knows that a course of action would make the nation better-off
through trade and increased ties, or create the kind of goodwill which stores
up friends for when you need them most. But the heart cannot help itself,
it simply reacts: responding to events in familiar old ways, de&THORN;ning
itself by opposition or eccentricity: we are good because they are bad,
for example, or: we are not rich or popular, but by god we're special. <BR>
<BR>
Western foreign policy analysts are accustomed to musing about exotic places
with apparently mystifying priorities. Greece, however, is a member of mainstream
institutions and umbilically linked to the history of western civilisation.
As Francis Harris shows, Greece could become a richer and in&THORN;nitely
more in&thorn;uential power if it let go of paranoia and old enmities, hubris
of the past. The country is at a moment of choice: we hope it will choose
well, for its own sake and that of the whole region. <BR>
<BR>
Greece is not the only one in this position. Perhaps every country has a
de&THORN;ning moment in its history which is played out over and over again,
often complicating its progress. Indeed, history turned into &THORN;erce
bloodshed among its Yugoslav neighbours. France still has a complex about
wartime collaboration. Britain arguably gets less out of Europe because
of unresolved memories of empire and its historic hostility to Germany.
The sense of failure suffered in Washington since the Vietnam War &shyp;
admittedly a much more recent memory than the occupation of Athens by Turkey
&shyp; puts a recurrent wrinkle in its foreign policy, stopping it from
intervening when it ought because it once intervened when it ought not have
done so. Quebec and other entities feel the urge to separate from their
larger, largely benevolent partners even if it would leave them worse off.
<BR>
<BR>
It is not a simple matter of bare economic calculation: collective memory
and shared principles are very important to a nation's standing and purpose
and should enter the equation of national interest along with winning contracts
and jobs. Nor is the choice always between head and heart: the range of
the former is sometimes de&THORN;ned in such narrow monetary terms that
it excludes other important and equally rational factors, undermining any
serious development of the concept of national interest. The trick is to
&THORN;nd a balance, to identify what things from the past can help and
what can hinder. <BR>
<BR>
This argument has a very timely application, the latest explosion of &THORN;ghting
in the Middle East. The &quot;grapes of wrath&quot; falling on southern
Lebanon may make the Israeli public feel good, for a while, but like all
other examples of disproportionate force it has signally failed to teach
the enemy a &quot;lesson&quot;. Instead, it has given that enemy another
de&THORN;ning moment which will help keep enmities alive. <BR>
<BR>
Just over a year ago, on this page, our magazine took up the fresh events
of the Barings Bank collapse. We argued then that it showed why all organisations
need good internal controls, unbureaucratic lines of responsibility and
a proper balance between ambition and reality. One year on, the same lessons
are underlined in <I>World Link </I>by the Bank of England's Howard Davies,
who also urges on regulators the kind of cooperation across frontiers which
could match the global scale and reach of business. They are all simple
but key points which bear repeating. <p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

