<tr>
<td>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<h2>
May/June 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>
<H3>REVIEW</H3> 
<H2><I>Russia's leap</I> </H2>
<H4>The Political History of Economic Reform in Russia, 1985-1994 </H4>
<I>By Vladimir Mau<BR>
Social Market Foundation, &#163;9.95 </I>
<H4>The Success of Russian Economic Reforms </H4>
<I>By Brigitte Granville<BR>
RIIA, &#163;12.95 </I>
<H4>How Russia Became a Market Economy </H4>
<I>By Anders Aslund<BR>
Brookings Institute, $18.95 <BR>
<BR>
<B>Reviewed by John Lloyd</B></I><B> </B><BR>
<BR>
&quot;Either&quot;, writes Yegor Gaidar, Russia's first economic reformer,
&quot;we shall be able to make a breakthrough into an efficient economic
and political system, open to the world, and Russian citizens will be integrated
into international economic and political relations as equal partners...
or power will pass into the hands of forces intent on building a system
of 'nationally oriented capitalism' cut off from the rest of the world.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Of the three books on review, only Vladimir Mau seriously considers the
possibility that the economic, and not just the political, reforms are reversible.
Tellingly, it is the only one written by a Russian. But even Mau, Gaidar's
closest colleague, shares his view that the choice now is between different
sorts of capitalism, the one liberal, the other dependent upon and haltered
by &quot;close state tutelage&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
The other two books are both written by westerners deeply involved in the
process of Russian economic reform: Brigitte Granville, a French economist
working on macroeconomic themes and Anders Aslund, a former Swedish diplomat
turned academic and one-time consultant to Russian ministers. Aslund, together
with Professor Jeffrey Sachs, resigned from his advisory function when Gaidar
left government a month after the shocking electoral success of Vladimir
Zhirinovsky's Liberal Democratic Party in December 1993. Aslund forecast
(wrongly) a sharp turn for the worse in economic policy. <BR>
<BR>
They are thus all <I>parti pris </I>, and must be read in that light. But
their position puts them inside the process of policy-making and allows
their judgements to be both transparent and informed, a rarity in descriptions
of Russian reform. <BR>
<BR>
The authors all point to how the Gorbachevian reforms, so liberating in
the political and foreign relations fields, rendered the Soviet economy
simply unfunctional, destroying the momentum of the command system without
substituting another. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The economic crisis&quot;, writes Mau, &quot;(was) passing into the
stage of the disintegration of the economic system&quot;. Aslund writes
that: &quot;The national income had fallen at least 20% from the last quarter
of 1991 over that of 1990, and was accelerating. Fear of famine was widespread...
when Gorbachev finally stepped down in December 1991, he left behind a country
in a state of complete and utter collapse.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The second of their services is to call attention to the limited range of
options which faced the first reformers and still face their successors
now. Not one of the former communist states had an easy way out of the command
economy or could have stayed within the system once it began imploding in
the late '80s. The price and labour distortions were so great, the &quot;fit&quot;
with the capitalist world so bad, the competition posed by countries like
China and India so threatening, that they could not continue to mark time.
<BR>
<BR>
But in changing, they had to go through various painful hoops, worse than
any previous capitalist birth. First, they had to get rid of an ideology
which had a grip not just on the elite, a section of which proved open to
change, but also on the population at large. Russia was the toughest nut
in this respect: a people used to the securities of socialism preserved
a dislike of speculation, market behaviour and open inequalities. <BR>
<BR>
This has created an open field for the very large class of Russian political
demagogues to the left and right as Mau, more concerned with the political
dimension than the other two authors, points out very well. Yet this has
been less due to the failures and mistakes of reform of which there have
been many, detailed in all three books, than to the successes: higher prices,
the speed of Russian privatisation, tight monetary policies and the sudden
access to wealth by a conspicuous few. <BR>
<BR>
Are such reactions likely to deliver a communist or authoritarian nationalist
to the Kremlin this June - and will he then usher in capitalism &quot;under
state tutelage&quot; or worse? Naturally the books, all finished by early
last year, neither answer these questions nor speculate. But they all point
to the constraints any such figure will face. For Russia is now continuing
a rather stumbling reform in a straitjacket of support from the IMF: its
officials have already said that they are prepared to work with any Russian
president but will only continue support if he conforms to the conditions
already agreed with President Boris Yeltsin and his government. <BR>
<BR>
Naturally, a communist or nationalist government is free to decline this
support. But the effect of doing so would require more than state tutelage.
To avoid collapse, it would require an even greater sacrifice by the population
than they have experienced so far. As dissatisfaction took hold and spread,
there would have to be increasing state control over not just economic lives
but over society as a whole. <BR>
<BR>
It has been, as Granville notes, &quot;a very Russian success story&quot;.
The leap in the dark has been made, in a typically hasty Russian way. Russia's
most likely course is to continue to try to find its way to the light, not
to return to the heart of darkness. <BR>
<BR>
<I>John Lloyd, formerly The Financial Times bureau chief in Moscow, is currently
writing a book on the new Russia</I> <BR>
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3><I>Barings cheek</I> </H3>
<H4>The Collapse of Barings </H4>
<I>By Stephen Fay<BR>
Richard Cohen Books, &#163;20 <BR>
<BR>
<B>Reviewed by Paul Durman</B></I><B> </B><BR>
<BR>
When Nick Leeson finally emerges from his Singaporean jail, he could do
worse than consider a new career in public relations. Leeson is the financial
trader whose fraudulent dealings racked up &#163;860 million of losses and
bankrupted one of Britain's oldest investment banks. From this inauspicious
start to life in the public eye, he has secured a remarkably sympathetic
press. With the help of his wife and lawyers, he has managed to cast himself
as the victim of the men who ran Barings. <BR>
<BR>
Leeson has blamed himself for &quot;trying to help people too much&quot;,
in other words for striving too hard to earn the profits on which his colleagues
relied for their bonuses. His own lively account of his downfall (<I>Rogue
Trader</I>, published by Little, Brown at &#163;16.99) has become a bestseller.
<BR>
<BR>
Stephen Fay does not buy Leeson's account. In <I>The Collapse of Barings</I>,
he sets out the case for the prosecution. He rejects Leeson's claim that
he slipped into illicit trading gradually after first trying to cover up
a colleague's mistake. Instead, he argues that Leeson started to cheat and
deceive almost as soon as he arrived in Singapore. <BR>
<BR>
This is an extraordinary tale. From the outside the investment banking and
securities industry seems a tightly regulated world, tied up in rules, watched
over by a host of compliance officers and auditors. Yet Leeson cut through
all this with tactics of startling simplicity. <BR>
<BR>
He conducted unauthorised trading in futures and options contracts through
an error account, supposedly intended for sorting out small discrepancies.
By arranging trades between the memorably numbered 88888 account and other
in-house accounts, he created huge bogus profits for Barings. He also used
it to dump his mounting losses. Within two years of transferring from his
job as a humble settlements clerk, Leeson had become one of Singapore's
star traders. Barings eventually sent hundreds of millions of pounds to
support a little understood operation run by an inexperienced 27-year-old.
<BR>
<BR>
Fay has many acid remarks to make about the Barings executives who failed
to pick up the numerous warning signals and who readily accepted Leeson's
clumsy forgeries and inconsistent explanations. However, he rightly dismisses
the conspiracy theorists who believe Leeson acted with others. Belief in
a conspiracy is strongest among those who are anxious to play down their
own role in the disaster, including some of Barings' senior managers and
the Singaporean financial authorities. <BR>
<BR>
According to Fay, the bank's demise was made possible by its recent history.
The culture clash between the conservative risk-shy bankers of Baring Brothers
and the entrepreneurial traders of Baring Securities - phenomenally
successful in the '80s - was unresolved. The merger put executives
with little experience of futures and options in key positions. It also
obscured some of the financial exposures within Baring Securities, a problem
compounded by a clumsy informal concession from the Bank of England which
made it unnecessary for Barings to monitor closely the scale of lending
to its securities business. <BR>
<BR>
Dealings with Singapore were complicated by the fierce independence of the
local senior management. Misunderstandings about the extent of Leeson's
responsibilities and disputes about chains of command allowed him to work
with minimal supervision. <BR>
<BR>
In a fundamental breach of best practice, Leeson was in charge of both futures
trading and settlement. Weaknesses in systems meant important financial
information was difficult or impossible to obtain. Finally, Leeson was helped
by the extraordinary willingness of his Singaporean staff to carry out his
instructions unquestioningly. <BR>
<BR>
What Fay cannot explain is why Leeson went off the rails in July 1992. Before
he went to Singapore, Leeson had made a good impression at Barings. <BR>
<BR>
Could there be a Barings II? Wrong question, says Fay. The extent of ignorance
about derivatives trading makes it safe to assume that similar disasters
are already developing. 
<H3><BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%><BR><I>Biology destiny</I> </H3>
<H4>What is Life? The Next 50 Years </H4>
<I>Edited by Michael Murphy and Luke O'Neill <BR>
Cambridge University Press, &#163;17.95 <BR>
<BR>
<B>Reviewed by Lance Knobel </B></I><BR>
<BR>
In February 1943, the Nobel-prize-winning physicist Erwin Schr&ouml;dinger
gave a series of lectures at Trinity College, Dublin. Instead of focusing
on his own field of theoretical physics (Schr&ouml;dinger was one of the
founders of quantum mechanics), the exile from Nazi-occupied Austria discussed
two themes: the nature of heredity and the thermodynamics of living systems.
<BR>
<BR>
Although he claimed to be a &quot;naive physicist&quot;, Schr&ouml;dinger
reached a prescient conclusion about the gene. He predicted the shape of
what he termed the &quot;aperiodic crystal&quot; and that it would store
a code within its structure. <BR>
<BR>
When the structure of DNA was discovered the following decade, Schr&ouml;dinger
was proved right. Published as <I>What is Life?</I> in 1944, Schr&ouml;dinger's
self-described &quot;little book&quot; was enormously influential. Both
Francis Crick and James Watson, the discoverers of the structure of DNA,
credit the book as a key influence in their decision to study the structure
of the gene. <BR>
<BR>
On the 50th anniversary of Schr&ouml;dinger's lectures, a group of eminent
scientists gathered in Dublin to ask fundamental questions of biology again.
The resulting book is again &quot;little&quot; (although nearly twice the
length of Schr&ouml;dinger's original), but it contains some fascinating
speculation on what scientists may be able to answer in the next 50 years.
This enquiry is particularly important because if the 20th century is seen
as the century when physics dramatically transformed the world - through
atomic weapons and nuclear power, solid-state physics leading to the computer,
the impact of relativistic thinking - the next century is likely to
be most affected by biology. <BR>
<BR>
According to the scientists in the current volume, however, the next 50
years could contain as many frustrations as successes. Embryologist Lewis
Wolpert does not believe that the egg will be entirely computable within
the next 50 years. In other words, even given complete understanding of
the initial conditions of the fertilised egg, the full development process
will not be predictable: the fine details are too complex. Manfred Eigen,
like some of the other authors, declines the long view and instead confines
himself to problems that will remain at the end of this century. One that
will be unsolved, he believes is the discovery of an effective AIDS therapy.
<BR>
<BR>
Jared Diamond looks at the evolution of human inventiveness. He convincingly
argues that what he calls the Great Leap Forward in human behaviour resulted
from the development of modern language. That, far more than brain size
or the ability to stand upright, separates us from our ape forebears. Diamond
believes the next 50 years should bring important advances in understanding
how language - and thus human creativity - originated. <BR>
<BR>
One of the essays is by a non-scientist, Ruth Braunizer, who is Schr&ouml;dinger's
daughter. She understandably does not offer any scientific speculation,
but hers may be the most revealing of essays. Reflecting on the influences
on Schr&ouml;dinger in early 20th century Vienna, Braunizer emphasises the
broad-based, humanistic education available to all children, including those
from very poor families. &quot;A member of that generation, whatever their
occupation... would, for instance, have been able to enjoy Plato or Seneca
in the original without seeking the help of a dictionary or a commentary.
Consequently, they were also masters of their own language,&quot; she writes.
<BR>
<BR>
By contrast, Braunizer reports on how she received a poorly written, mis-spelled
letter from a promising young physicist: &quot;Obviously in our time you
can get ahead without bothering about culture. The incident raises several
questions. Are we just looking at the result of specialisation? My father
dreaded specialisation and strove to be a generalist in every way. But this
was the mark of his generation.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Schr&ouml;dinger was a remarkable physicist, but he was particularly startling
in having such a profound influence outside his field with <I>What is Life?
</I>Given the global spread of specialisation, in science as well as in
other fields, the prospects for future Schr&ouml;dingers look bleak indeed.
<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
