<td valign=top align=left>
<H3>WORLD ECONOMIC FORUM</H3>
<H2>Insights</H2>
<H4> The World Economic Forum is today the foremost international membership
organization integrating leaders from business, government and academia into a
partnership committed to improving the state of the world. Through global,
efficient, direct, personalized and highest-level interaction, the World Economic
Forum serves its members and constituents to define their agenda for action. The
core community of the World Economic Forum are the 1,000 foremost global
companies.

Incorporated since 1971 as a foundation, the World Economic Forum is independent,
impartial and not-for-profit, tied to no political, partisan or national
interests. It has consultative status with the United Nations. The motto of the
World Economic Forum is "Entrepreneurship in the global public interest".</H4>
<IMG SRC= "images/wl.96.03.16.1.gif"
WIDTH= "91" HEIGHT="78" ALIGN="MIDDLE" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"> <H3>Membership <BR>
News <BR>
Future Meetings</H3> 
 Members of the World Economic Forum
are not individuals but companies, which are represented at the highest level of
management. Each member should be characterised by:<BR> <BR> * its global
dimension or the strategy to grow in that direction <BR> <BR> * a top management
that is forward-looking and of high reputation <BR> <BR> * a healthy organisation
- respected, growing and ethical.<BR> <BR> The World Economic Forum
currently has two categories of membership: <BR> <BR> <B>Foundation
Membership</B> <BR> <BR> In principle, Foundation membership is made up of the
1,000 foremost global enterprises. In addition to the above general criteria,
each is characterised by the following specific attributes:<BR> <BR> * a
significant role in shaping the future of its industry and/or region <BR> <BR> *
the ability and willingness of its top management to contribute to international
cooperation and economic and social progress. <BR> <BR> <B>Global Growth Company
Membership</B> <BR> <BR> Global Growth Companies are some of the world's
fastest-growing business groups. Each is characterised by the following specific
attributes:<BR> <BR> * a significant role in shaping its industry as a niche
producer, a technological leader or an entrepreneurial innovator <BR> <BR> * the
ability and willingness of its top management to network with like-minded
enterprises around the world. <BR> <BR> In order to integrate the advice of its
members into the decision-making process of the Foundation, the Council of the
World Economic Forum has been established. <BR> <BR> In 1996 the Council,
presided by George Mallinckrodt, is composed of Rahul Bajaj, Franco
Bernab&eacute;, John H. Bryan, Hubert Burda, T. Neal Chapman, Ronnie C. Chan,
Bertrand Collomb, Oscar Fanjul, Hermann O. Franz, M. Shafik Gabr, Joseph T.
Gorman, Cor A.J. Herkstroter, Jaakko V.A. Ihamuotila, E. Neville Isdell, Donald
R. Keough, Nemir A. Kirdar, Yoh Kurosawa, J. Martin K. Laing, Gernot A.
Langes-Swarovski, Kenneth L. Lay, Arne Martensson, Yuzaburo Mogi, Minoru
Murofushi, Masafumi Ohnishi, John B. Prescott, James J. Schiro, Christopher A.
Sinclair, Sarik Tara, Paulo D. Villares, John Zabriskie and Lorenzo H. Zambrano.
It reflects an optimal sectoral and regional representation of members. <H3>1996
Mercosur Economic Summit </H3> <H4>Buenos Aires </H4> <B>23-25 June </B><BR> <BR>
The second Mercosur Economic Summit will examine the trends in capital flows and
direct investment in the Mercosur region. What will be the impact of the recently
signed framework agreement between the European Union and the Mercosur nations?
Will it lead to the creation of the world's largest free-trade zone? Will this in
turn divert attention from the much touted hemispheric integration? <BR> <BR> We
will also look at some very real issues that today's chief executives must
confront to truly understand the region. What is the status of the Plano Real in
Brazil, and what will be done to sustain it? How can governments of the region
bridge the painful period of necessary economic reforms with the longer term
pay-off these reforms will bring to the greater public? What concrete steps are
being taken to increase domestic savings and investment? What kind of education
policy is needed to produce the high-quality goods and services that will be
competitive on global markets? This is especially relevant considering that the
Mercosur countries are currently contending with high unemployment. <H3>1996 Asia
Summits </H3> <B>Three exceptional Summits this autumn will bring businessmen up
to date on the latest economic, financial and business developments taking place
in the most dynamic part of the world.</B> <H3>China Business Summit </H3>
<H4>Beijing </H4> <B>16-18 September </B><BR> <BR> Bolstered by a sustained
period of growth, China must now contain inflationary pressures and rein in the
development of some of its most successful provinces. Our Summit will address the
most salient questions related to this new phase of economic maturity and the
place foreign investors can find for themselves in the newly reshaped
environment. As the handover of Hong Kong approaches, participants may also be
able to assess China's new role on the world's economic scene and the complexity
of its position among other fledgling markets in the Asia-Pacific region. <BR>
<BR> Senior government officials, top Chinese and foreign experts, Chinese
business leaders, as well as senior executives from companies involved in China,
will be the key discussion partners during the Summit. There will be ample time
for private contacts and dialogue between senior executives and heads of major
Chinese corporations and their foreign counterparts. The Summit is being held in
partnership with the China Enterprise Management Association (CEMA) under the
patronage of the State Economic and Trade Commission. <H3>India Economic Summit
</H3> <H4>New Delhi </H4> <B>27-29 October </B><BR> <BR> Following India's June
elections our Summit will be a unique opportunity to meet with key members of the
new cabinet and thus help to relieve foreign investors' uncertainties concerning
the future course of liberalization. <BR> <BR> Two key issues to be addressed at
the Summit (held in partnership with the Confederation of Indian Industry, CII)
will be identifying new opportunities for partnerships and cooperation and
improving the environment for domestic and foreign companies as the Indian
economy builds up on current strong results, especially in the industrial sector.
<H3>Europe/East Asia Economic Summit </H3> <H4>Hong Kong </H4> <B>18-20 November
</B><BR> <BR> &quot;Partnership in Growth&quot;: the fifth Europe/East Asia
Economic Summit (held in partnership with the Hong Kong Trade Development
Council) will reflect the enhanced business, trade, financial and technological
ties between these two industrialized poles and will thus constitute the most
welcome business complement to this year's government summit. Given the backing
of EU governments, European enterprises are now gearing up for overseas expansion
in an effort to boost their competitiveness in Asia. The Summit programme will
draw attention to some new trends in Asian investment in Europe. As the Summit
will be the last opportunity for high-level discussions before the WTO
ministerial meeting in Singapore, trade issues will feature prominently on the
agenda. <BR> <BR> Special sessions on provinces of China, Hong Kong and specific
regions and countries in Asia and Europe will provide participants with the
possibility to discuss economic prospects and new business openings. There will
also be sector-specific discussions and project presentations allowing
participants to promote new business projects and to identify potential partners.
<H3>1996 Central and Eastern European <BR> Economic Summit </H3> <H4>Salzburg
</H4> <B>7-9 July </B><BR> <BR> With high growth rates and favourable economic
indicators, the region of Central and Eastern Europe is one of the world's
greatest untapped markets and it stands on the threshold of rapid development and
business expansion. For years, the World Economic Forum has pioneered the opening
of the countries of this area and their integration into the global economy. Now,
the World Economic Forum welcomes the international business community to the
first Central and East European Economic Summit under the patronage of President
Thomas Klestil of Austria. <BR> <BR> The focus of the Summit is on the countries
of the region and their neighbours -- Austria, Germany and Russia. The Summit
will stress the importance of the region as a whole in the wider European
context. It will point to the need to develop both the infrastructure and the
business links capable of raising local capital, attracting foreign investment
and promoting trade and industry. We also will look closely at the thrust towards
European integration and the search for collective security arrangements. <BR>
<BR> High-ranking government and business leaders from all over the world will
discuss the prospects of the emerging market and conditions for achieving
permanent and stable growth. Looking at trade routes rather than national
boundaries, the Summit will pay special attention to private-sector initiatives
and cross-border projects that are transforming this eastern part of Europe into
a major global economic force. <H3>1996 Middle East/North Africa <BR> Economic
Summit </H3> <H4>Cairo </H4> <B>12-14 November </B><BR> <BR> The Middle
East/North Africa region is undergoing significant political, economic and social
changes. Despite political turbulence, the region as a whole remains dedicated to
the reconciliation process. In addition to ongoing economic reforms which are
intended to create an environment conducive to doing business, governments
together with the private sector are now exploring multilateral cooperation
projects. <BR> <BR> The emphasis of the 1996 Summit will be on new
outward-looking strategies required for the future. It will focus on the Middle
East/North Africa as an identifiable region, able and eager to compete in the
global economy. It will emphasize the need to develop both infrastructure and
business links capable of raising capital, attracting foreign investment and
promoting trade and industry. <H3>Spring 1996 </H3> <H4>France Meeting, Paris 5
June <BR> Mercosur Economic Summit, Buenos Aires <BR> 23-25 June <BR> Central and
Eastern European Economic Summit, Salzburg 7-9 July </H4> <H3>Autumn 1996 </H3>
<H4>China Business Summit, Beijing <BR> 16-18 September <BR> India Economic
Summit, New Delhi <BR> 27-29 October <BR> Middle East/North Africa Economic
Summit, Cairo 12-14 November <BR> Europe/East Asia Economic Summit, <BR> Hong
Kong 18-20 November </H4> <H2>Davos video </H2> A video showing highlights from
the World Economic Forum's 1996 Annual Meeting in Davos is available at a cost of
$49.95 ($5 p&amp;p). If you are interested please contact Kate Charters, Location
Specials Sales, Reuters Television Ltd, 85 Fleet Street, London EC4P 4AJ.
<HR width=60%><BR> <BR> <B>For further information on membership of the World Economic
Forum and on its meetings, please contact: <BR> <BR> Claude Smadja, <BR> Managing
Director, <BR> World Economic Forum, <BR> 53 chemin des Hauts-Cr&ecirc;ts, <BR>
1223 Cologny Geneva Switzerland<BR> Telephone: +41 22 869 1212 <BR> Telefax: +41
22 786 2744<BR> Email: contact@weforum.org</B>  
<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

