<tr>
<td>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<h2>
May/June 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>
<H3>TECHNOLOGY</H3> 
<H2>It wood save energy </H2>
<H4>Plant-burning is regarded as a primitive form of energy but new approaches
could make it a hot property</H4>
&quot;A century ago, nearly half of all agriculture was devoted to an energy
crop: the oats given to horses which we used for transport. Historically,
agriculture has always provided fuel, so why do people look at me as if
I'm mad when I say we could do it again?&quot; asks Peter Billins, head
of British Biogen. <BR>
<BR>
He is accustomed to defending what is often dismissed as an old-fashioned
approach to finding new sources of energy. His company searches for new
ways of producing power from burning crops and agricultural or forestry
waste and he is proud to call himself both green and a businessman. <BR>
<BR>
But people are usually surprised to learn that plant-burning, a form of
energy known as biomass, is not only environmentally acceptable but under
the right conditions highly beneficial. <BR>
<BR>
Doubts arise because of fears about global warming: even the most elementary
knowledge of chemistry suggests that wood-burning creates carbon dioxide,
which has identified as one of the principal causes of rising world temperatures.
The clearing of the rain forest, often called the lungs of the world because
the vital role plants play in creating oxygen, is another threat. But biomass
creates relatively few pollutants and its proponents say it is different
from energy-generating incineration schemes where contaminants such as heavy
metals are a potential problem. <BR>
<BR>
The science behind the current enthusiasm for biomass is sufficiently attractive
to appeal even to multinational oil companies such as the Anglo-Dutch giant
Shell, which is pumping millions of dollars into research projects, most
notably in Brazil. <BR>
<BR>
Like fossil fuels, biomass generates carbon dioxide, but this simply represents
the release of the gas which the plant absorbed as it grew. The burning
of fossil fuels, on the other hand, releases a reservoir of carbon stored
up millions of years ago alongside high levels of nitrogen and sulphur dioxide.
In addition, it is impossible to replace fossil fuel stocks. But if so-called
fuel crops are replaced, then biomass can be replenished indefinitely. <BR>
<BR>
Take wood. As long as new trees are replanted as older ones are felled,
the process is a simple energy cycle. As the tree grows, carbon dioxide
is broken down into oxygen and cellulose: as it burns the two recombine
to form the gas again. Unlike oil-burning, no new carbon is released and
the process becomes beneficial if the energy created replaces a fossil-fuel
alternative. <BR>
<BR>
So what materials are suitable? Forestry provides the most obvious fuel.
Burning wood has, after all, a long track-record as a source of energy production
and even today scientists estimate that some 16% of the world's energy demands
are met by wood. Unfortunately, the bulk of this is in the developing world
in countries such as Indonesia, where it may account for 70% of a poor nation's
fuel consumption. Most of this is burnt on inefficient stoves which are
used for both cooking and domestic heating. In practice this is often non-renewable,
since land cleared of trees usually becomes permanently agricultural. It
can also result in damaging erosion, as in the Himalayas. <BR>
<BR>
As nations develop, reliance on biomass tends to weaken: India receives
only half of its energy needs from biomass with the rest coming from oil,
coal and gas. Until recently economists have favoured this process. arguing
for cash-generating growth to fund the transition to oil, but now scientists
are developing alternative technologies which harness biomass more efficiently.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Trees that replace themselves </B><BR>
<BR>
In Europe, attention has centred on a new look at the centuries-old art
of coppicing, which harnesses the natural ability of many trees to regenerate
themselves from their roots. As anyone who has chopped down a willow knows,
within weeks of felling a problem tree, new withies spring from the stump.
Naturally, modern coppicing has refined traditional methods. Most important
is the use of new fast-growing hybrid strains of willow and poplar which
grow at up to four metres a year and can be harvested every two years. <BR>
<BR>
Using this young wood makes good economic and environmental sense because
a tree's growth is proportionately greatest during its early years. The
concept is sufficiently encouraging to draw EU funding for three research
projects in Denmark, Italy and the UK although Sweden leads the way with
9,000 hectares of deciduous coppice. <BR>
<BR>
In addition, its output can be boosted with forestry residues such as smaller
branches, roots, bark and mill-waste which are otherwise commercially valueless.
These are then chipped to make handling easier and to increase the efficiency
of the combustion process. Until recently this type of material would have
been burnt in a conventional generator, where the heat of combustion produces
the steam that drives a turbine. Now, however, new technology has been brought
in to improve efficiency. This uses intense heat and pressure to convert
the chips into gasses and it is these, rather than steam, which drive the
turbines. <BR>
<BR>
The results of research so far are encouraging, in particular that pioneered
by Shell at its Brazilian plant where forestry residues are used to fuel
a gassification process. The findings suggest up to nearly half of available
energy can be converted into electricity, compared with around a quarter
in a conventional coal plant, outstripping the inefficiencies of traditional
biomass production by a factor of at least four. <BR>
<BR>
A further attraction of the new biomass is that regardless of where the
technology is developed, the underlying efficiencies remain the same. To
be competitive against fossil fuels, plants have to find their bulky fuels
locally. A UK government study, for example, calculates that to make wood-burning
stations viable the timber would have to come from within a 15km radius
of the plant. Even a moderately sized 50mw facility would require 3,500
hectares of woodland to fuel it. As a result, across most of the developed
world there has been a reluctance to invest, because until farmers show
themselves prepared to grow fuel crops, no investor is likely to risk the
capital outlay that even a moderate power station requires. Conversely,
until a market is proven few farmers are prepared to risk the time and effort
on an experimental crop. <BR>
<BR>
So far, therefore, research has concentrated on small-output technology
ideal for poorer nations. In Indonesia, whose population of some 200 million
is spread over 17,500 islands, conventional power distribution networks
are less useful and nearly half of all villages are without electrical power.
The country is not short of biomass, however, hosting plentiful supplies
of forestry and agricultural waste which can be used to fuel small local
generators. <BR>
<BR>
This in turn can be used to power cash-generating schemes such as floriculture
and higher-margin horticulture, such as irrigation pumps and greenhouse
cooling systems. <BR>
<BR>
In a country such as Indonesia agricultural residues are the only way to
produce power for the mass of people, explains Roger King, chief executive
of the consultancy Ecosolve which helps convert EU aid grants into working
projects in Indonesia, Malaysia and India. In particular, sugar cane produces
a wealth of burnable by-products: &quot;For a long time sugar factories
have generated enough energy for their own needs but it has been very wasteful,
not to mention polluting,&quot; King says. <BR>
<BR>
The industry produces four categories of waste: cane tops, fibrous residue
left in the presses, filter cake from clarifiers and liquid waste full of
nitrogen, phosphates and potassium nutrients. Conventionally, the first
of these were used as animal feeds while the remaining waste has all too
often been left to rot or simply drain into the nearest river system. <BR>
<BR>
Using modern but relatively simple technology, however, these can be processed
to produce both power and fertiliser, using a combination of gassification,
composting and anaerobic digestion. Better still, the schemes can markedly
improve the local environment. Many of the potential fuels such as tapioca
trimmings are otherwise very polluting, having a high chemical oxygen demand
(COD), which means they require a lot of oxygen to break down and emit methane,
one of the worst greenhouse gases. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Turning harmful waste to use </B><BR>
<BR>
Ecosolve tackles the problems of high COD-value crops by stewing the minced
waste in an anaerobic digestor. This produces methane, which is burnt in
a small generator, and slurry which can be used as a fertiliser: &quot;You
avoid pollution while creating two valuable products for local farmers,&quot;
says King. &quot;Its all rather beautiful, really.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Another vast potential source of electricity across the Pacific Basin comes
from rice husks: one conservative estimate puts India's annual production
of this otherwise useless agricultural waste at 15 million tonnes. <BR>
<BR>
Change certainly seems to be in the air. The World Bank seems to agree that
biomass requires serious attention and is currently funding trials into
sugar waste with five projects in Indonesia alone. Estimates put the level
of new, efficient, biomass currently being created around the world at about
15,000 to 20,000mw. This is not much, but enough to suggest the possible
beginnings of a trend. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;I am sure there is a growing role for biomass,&quot; says Billins
confidently. &quot;After all, most people are surprised to learn some 5%
of America's energy comes from wood and Oregon relies on forestry for 40%
of its electricity. Better still, the most recent advances are being spearheaded
by both the US and developing nations. I think the rest of the world will
want to follow.&quot;  
<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
