<td valign=top>
<h2>
May/June 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>
<H3>TIME OUT</H3>
<H2>Vlad the imbiber </H2>
<H4>Food and drink in the colourful port city on the eastern edge of Russia
is beginning to reflect its Pacific variety </H4>

Think of a city on the coast of a great continent, its population close
to a million. Place it at the end of one of the world's most famous railways.
Make it a great port and naval headquarters, a centre of trade, transport
and culture. For the final touch of spice imagine the city's cosmopolitan
history, followed by half a century of secrecy in which foreigners were
unable to visit. <BR>
<BR>
Sound like an exciting place to be? Well, Vladivostok is exciting. As a
place to work there is never a dull moment. As somewhere to live, it is
more than redeemed from the drearyness of its Soviet-style outskirts by
the crumbling turn-of-the-century town centre, with wonderful views across
the port, the shipyards and the Pacific Ocean. <BR>
<BR>
But for those wanting a good time, or even just a relaxing evening in a
pleasant restaurant, things are a bit more complicated. Vladivostok has
the image of a mafia-run &quot;Wild East&quot; frontier town. Visitors from
outside debate in hushed tones whether it is safe to go out at night. &quot;Isn't
this the most crime-ridden city in Russia?&quot; they ask. <BR>
<BR>
Fortunately for the average visitor, the truth is that it does not matter.
The crime rate may be high but most of it is economic, linked to dodgy port
dealings such as smuggling or illegal immigration, especially from China.
Unless you are involved with the mafia, violent crime is much less prevalent
than in comparable cities in the US or Europe. <BR>
<BR>
That being said, the notion of mafia in its widest Russian definition -
<I>biznizmen</I> of varying degrees of honesty and their associates -
is useful for the visitor when it comes to the choice of an evening hangout.
A place frequented by the mafia is known by locals as <I>krutoi</I>. Sadly
for the ordinary folk of Vladivostok the <I>krutoi</I> category has greatly
outpaced the non-<I>krutoi</I> in recent years. <BR>
<BR>
Unlike Moscow and St Petersburg, where Russian and western fast-food venues
or modest bistros and cafes have sprung up to cater for the middle market,
Vladivostok eateries are few and affordable mostly by the rich and foreign.
For ordinary folk entertainment remains largely home-based, with the occasional
shindig put on by the workplace for special occasions. <BR>
<BR>
There are exceptions. The city now has a real coffee bar, opened last year
by a woman who, according to rumour, got her espresso machine from her son
in Italy. The tiny bar serves such delights as cappuccino, latte and espresso
and received harsh reviews in the local newspaper for its ban on smoking.
<BR>
<BR>
There is also a genuine pizza joint, around the back of the Gorky Theatre.
Those who know this obscure corner of town will find that $10 buys a delicious
pie, made by trained chefs in authentic pizza ovens. Apart from the frequent
power cuts, which afflict all but the most upmarket restaurants, there is
just one catch: the Pearl Pizzeria can run out of such ingredients as mushrooms
and tomatoes. It is still aeons ahead of the longer-established Magic Burger,
Vladivostok's first attempt at a fast-food restaurant. Fabulously situated
on Svetlanskaya Street, the city's main drag, the restaurant serves cheap,
unsightly burgers and huge slabs of soggy pizza to hungry shoppers. <BR>
<BR>
There is supposedly another fast-food restaurant in the Hotel Primorye,
recently opened as a Russian-Korean joint venture and promising to cater
to the average Vlad citizen. The managers said they would serve American,
Chinese and Korean fast food in addition to the usual Russian fare. What
is more, a notice on the door declares unheard-of opening times: from 7am
to midnight. But a visitor would be unwise to rely on such information.
The Restaurant Primorye has frequently been closed at 8pm and even on its
opening night suffered the indignity of a long power cut. <BR>
<BR>
Among regular restaurants the choice is essentially between Russian and
oriental cuisine. Looking at Vladivostok, a perfectly ordinary Russian city
with an almost entirely Russian population, it is easy to forget that this
is east Asia. Moscow is an eight-hour flight away, while China and Korea
are on the doorstep and Japan just across the sea. <BR>
<BR>
Signs of Vlad's Pacific Rim location are everywhere in the business and trading
relationships that have sprung up since the city opened up to the world
four years ago. Shops and kiosks are filled with imports from South Korea,
Japan and China, with Australia and the US next in line. The majority of
cars are secondhand Japanese, and far outnumber Russian ones. The foreign
business community is made up primarily of Japanese and Koreans. There is
scarcely a European country whose expatriate numbers reach double figures.
Britain just makes it, thanks to the croupiers at the Casino Club Versailles.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Hidden but good </B><BR>
<BR>
With all Vlad restaurants, you should eat by nine in the evening or you
may have a problem. The Versailles Hotel, an elegantly restored establishment
partly owned by the Far Eastern Shipping Company - and still the only
quality place to remain in the town centre - may be persuaded to serve
guests until the advertised time of ten-thirty but only under protest. <BR>
<BR>
It is worth persevering. By Vladivostok standards, the Versailles's food
is good and the menu more imaginative than the usual variations on chicken
and chips, meat and chips, fish and chips or the traditional Russian meat
dumplings known as <I>pelmeni</I> that form the standard menu in most restaurants.
<BR>
<BR>
Round the corner from the Versailles is another well-hidden restaurant in
the capacious Okean cinema complex. Until recently it was run by a couple
of foreigners with a regional Fosters beer concession but they gave up after
struggling with turning a profit with so many hands reaching into the till.
<BR>
<BR>
Even under Russian management, however, the Okean is pleasantly different
from most Vlad establishments. For one thing it has panoramic windows overlooking
the ocean and a bright, spacious dining room with pretty wooden furniture.
Nets and sea shells hanging from the ceiling place it on the cheerful side
of tacky, while the unpretentious atmosphere keeps away the <I>krutoi</I>
contingent. The English translations on the menu have taken a dive since
the change in management, but most people can work out what &quot;mashrooms&quot;
and &quot;sheece&quot; mean. The scallops in walnut sauce are definitely
to be recommended. <BR>
<BR>
Finding good fish is one of the many puzzles of Vladivostok, for although
fishing is a significant part of the local economy, much of the finest seafood
is exported. Furthermore, since fishing like everything else in the former
Soviet Union was organised on a huge scale, it is much more difficult than
you would expect to find seafood that is fresh as opposed to canned or frozen.
<BR>
<BR>
Excellent seafood platters are available at the fancier restaurants. But
perhaps the best in town is served at the Vlad Motor Inn, highly priced
and the only hotel under foreign management. Planted in the wooded area
packed with weekend <I>dachas</I>, about 20 kilometres outside the city,
the Russian-Canadian joint-venture motel is a favourite expat and New Russian
hangout. <BR>
<BR>
This collection of pre-fabricated buildings includes guest rooms, a business
centre, a small restaurant and a bar. In Canada it would not attract a second
look. But in Vladivostok it is best hotel in the area, home to the entire
expatriate staff of the US consulate and other international business people.
The restaurant is locally famous for such luxuries as American steaks, Diet
Coke and that great Russian rarity, smiling waitresses. It also serves a
fantastic Kamchatka crab, which arrives on an outsized platter that barely
accommodates the creature's 30cm legs. <BR>
<BR>
But it will be some time before visiting Vlad is a culinary or socially
pleasurable experience. Food and nightlife, after all, are not what brings
most people to Russia.  
<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
