<tr>
<td>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<h2>
May/June 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 
<H3>BACKSEAT</H3>
<H3>Charles Darwent takes a stroll down the Via Veritas with famous fans
of the fermented grape </H3>
As the days draw out and sap quickens in the leaf, I would ask you to spare
a thought for Mr J&uuml;rgen Schrempp. <BR>
<BR>
Mr Schrempp, you will recall, is the chairman of German car manufacturers,
Daimler-Benz. It is not on this count that he is deserving of our sympathy,
however. If Mr Schrempp's name is familiar to you, it is less likely to
be because of his car-making proclivities than from press reports concerning
a recent business trip he made to Rome. <BR>
<BR>
While in the Italian capital Mr Schrempp - like many a north European
before him - found his chilly veins suddenly enlivened by the hotter
blood of the <I>dolce vita</I>: more specifically, by the particular therms
to be found in that beaker-full of the warm South beloved of the poet Keats.
<BR>
<BR>
Indeed, an admirably thorough-minded Mr Schrempp would appear to have worked
his way through a number of such beakers in the course of his researches
into Keatsian thermodynamics: a fact that led the Roman police to pull him
over as he wove his way, in an allegedly erratic fashion, back to his hotel
one sultry night. <BR>
<BR>
Not unnaturally, the German plutocrat viewed the attentions of the <I>carabanieri</I>
as tending to the unpoetic and told them so. In fact, if police reports
are to be believed, Mr Schrempp called into question the marital status
of his interlocutors' various parents and then suggested they perform a
physical act which, while doubtless satisfying in its way, might have caused
a raising of the eyebrows among any passers-by on the Via Condotti. <BR>
<BR>
The notable thing about this story is not so much the shockingly ungallant
behaviour of the Roman police as the way it was subsequently reported in
the world's press. When, some 20 years before, the British politician George
Brown was accused by the London constabulary of being in a similarly poetic
state, the parliamentarian's riposte - that he was &quot;tired and
emotional&quot; - won him more instant popularity with the nation's
journalists than any amount of tax-cutting. <BR>
<BR>
Here, reasoned British scribblers, was precisely the kind of man whose (slightly
tremulous) hand was required to guide the national tiller: not just the
sort of chap who knew a good thing when he drank it, but one who could summon
up the wit to brazen things out, even if he had done so more frequently
than might usually be considered wise. In the course of time, George Brown
was duly elevated to the peerage as Lord George Brown and the phrase &quot;tired
and emotional&quot; to its equivalent philological pantheon, the Oxford
English Dictionary. <BR>
<BR>
Not so the unfortunate Schrempp. Twenty years on, the sound that echoed
around the world's editorial offices when news of the German's unexpected
interest in viniculture clattered over the wire was not that of thighs being
slapped, but of lips being pursed. There were calls among the more censorious
of German titles for his resignation. Happy to relate, the heroic company
chief refused to do any such thing, thus narrowly avoiding becoming a sort
of St Sebastian of the chianti bottle. <BR>
<BR>
For this Mr Schrempp deserves our thanks. Time was when the correlation
between corporate seniority and the <I>vie luxe</I> was an automatic one.
With promotion to the board came keys to those dual (and by no means unconnected)
symbols of executive success, the directors' lavatory and the boardroom
drinks cabinet. Until recently, anthropologists on Wall Street or Threadneedle
Street could chart the progression of their subjects through the plutocratic
ranks by the growing redness of their noses. <BR>
<BR>
Were one to look for a single Darwinian apophthegm to describe this process,
it might be the phrase &quot;the survival of the fattest&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
No more. Where a distinctly plump Sir Winston Churchill could lead Britain
to wartime victory on a diet whose alcohol-by-volume would have killed the
average navvy stone dead, Mr Bill Clinton is a teetotaller who escapes the
arduousness of life in the Oval Office by going jogging. <BR>
<BR>
Where the Great, Good and Merely Very Rich were once recognisable by their
expensively purchased avoirdupois, aspirant golddiggers nowadays turn their
attentions to the most cadaverous person in any gilded room. Society, from
New York to New Zealand, is dominated by the &quot;social xray&quot;, as
Mr Tom Wolfe describes it in his novel, <I>Bonfire of the Vanities</I>:
a wraith-like figure subsisting entirely on lo-cal canapes and aerated mineral
water. Such pockets of resistance to this New Puritanism as stubbornly persist
- one thinks with particular fondness of Russia's president Mr Boris
Yeltsin in this regard - are far flung and (like Mr Yeltsin) under
threat of imminent extinction. <BR>
<BR>
Future historians will doubtless muse over why the millennium should have
chosen to celebrate itself (if that is the word) with this curious inversion
of natural order. An anti-humanist disgust with visceral man? Or the re-emergence
of that sanguine belief, long dead in the west, that humankind is (all evidence
to the contrary) perfectible? <BR>
<BR>
It is, at any rate, a cheerless process, as Mr Schrempp would doubtless
concur, and it may be more than that too. The point about drinking is that
it inspires not merely the writing of Keatsian odes but conviviality. Strapping
yourself to a Nautilus machine may make you a leaner executive but does
it make you a better one? A silhouette intended to emit the semiotic signal
&quot;efficient&quot; might, after all, equally well be translated as &quot;self-absorbed&quot;.
<BR>
<BR>
Contrariwise, broken veins and a tendency to stagger suggest a commendable
capacity in their owner for loving one's fellow man (just ask any drunk).
With management gurus increasingly including the word &quot;nice&quot; in
their armoury, this quality may yet come to be recognised as more valuable
in a corporate warrior than the flatness of his tummy. If this seems unlikely,
then observe the growing ferocity with which the tigers of Tokyo and Taipei
now insist on their employees drinking sake and singing karaoke. You have
been warned. Let us raise a glass to Mr Schrempp. Or two. Or three.  
<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
<nobr>
<a href="index.html" onMouseOver="window.status='Back a Page';return true"><img width=22 height=22 border=0 src="../../../../../images/navt1.gif" alt="Back"></a>
<a href="../../../../../services/faqs.html" onMouseOver="window.status='Help';return true"><img width=22 height=22 hspace=90 border=0 src="../../../../../images/navt2.gif" alt="Help"></a>
<a href="#top" onMouseOver="window.status='Top of the Page';return true"><img  width=22 height=22 border=0 src="../../../../../images/navt3.gif" alt="Top"></a>
</nobr>
<br><br>

<nobr>
<a href="../../../../../alert/index.html" onMouseOver="window.status='ALERT - Discussion Groups, Latest News, Site Updates, Sponsors and Events Diary';return true"><img width=120 height=31 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../../../images/nav1.gif" alt="Alert"></a><a href="../../../../../search/index.html" onMouseOver="window.status='SEARCH - Keyword and Structured Searches';return true"><img width=120 height=31 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../../../images/nav2.gif" alt="Search"></a><a href="../../../../../services/index.html" onMouseOver="window.status='SERVICES - FAQs, Feedback, Problems and EMWL Team';return true"><img width=120 height=31 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../../../images/nav3.gif" alt="Services"></a><a href="../../../../../contents/index.html" onMouseOver="window.status='CONTENTS - Publications, World Map, Product Sections and Data';return true"><img width=120 height=31 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../../../images/nav44.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
</nobr>
</font>

<br><br>
