<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra5.gif" alt="Cover Story">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 
<H2>WATER THE NEXT SOURCE OF TROUBLE </H2>
<H4>Daniel Butler on the clouds looming over access to a truly essential
commodity </H4>
&quot;Many of the wars this century were about oil, but those of the next
century will be over water.&quot; The announcement by Ismail Serageldin,
vice-president of the World Bank, made headlines across the western world
this summer, but it was old news to much of the globe. Chronic water shortages
affect 80 nations and 40% of the world's population. Demand for water is
increasing at more than 2% annually, which means it doubles every 21 years.
The crisis will get still worse. <BR>
<BR>
Not that there is any shortage of water as such: after all, two-thirds of
the globe is covered with the stuff. As American hydrologist Robert Ambroggi
confirms: &quot;The total quantity of water on earth exceeds all conceivable
needs of the human population.&quot; The problem is that it is not evenly
distributed and for many of the world's poorest countries, finding drinkable
water is a costly exercise. <BR>
<BR>
Not surprisingly, for many countries the security of water sources is already
one of the most important elements in foreign policy, far outstripping oil.
After all, alternative energies can always be found be they gas, coal or
nuclear, but without water life itself is impossible. To make matters worse,
it is a resource which respects no man-made borders. The rivers from which
most people get their water have a tendency to meander across frontiers.
<BR>
<BR>
Governments are acutely aware of the subject's potential for conflict. Defence
experts point to Egypt's disputes with Sudan over both politics and water
before noting Egypt's new jungle warfare unit; strange for a mainly desert
country with no forests. <BR>
<BR>
According to Peter Gleik of California's Pacific Institute for Studies in
Development, Environment and Security, almost half the world's population
lives in 250 river basins shared by several nations. For example, Botswana,
Bulgaria, Cambodia, the Congo, Gambia, Sudan and Syria all receive more
than three-quarters of their water from rivers which flow across borders
with potentially hostile neighbours. <BR>
<BR>
Exacerbating the crisis is the world's rapid population growth. Today there
are over 5 billion people on earth, but by 2025 there will be 8 billion
struggling for available water. Not surprisingly, as demand increases, so
do the pressures on supplies and thus the scope for conflicts. Indeed, according
to the former Israeli general Ariel Sharon, it has already played its part
in one major war. &quot;People generally regard June 5, 1967 as the day
the Six-Day War began,&quot; he replied to a journalist's question. &quot;That
is the official date, but in reality it started two-and-a-half years earlier
on the day Israel decided to act against the diversion of the Jordan.&quot;
Sharon, later to become a hawkish Likud defence minister, was referring
to the 1964 decision by neighbouring Arab states to re-route the waters
of the River Jordan. This was abandoned after Israel mounted long-range
bombing missions into Syria. <BR>
<BR>
Water continues to play a pivotal role in the region's politics and nowhere
is the potential for a water war greater than the Middle East. Indeed, it
is the weapon currently being used in Iraq by Saddam Hussein to cow the
rebellious Marsh Arabs. By constructing the 565km Third River canal in six
months following the Gulf War, Baghdad is draining marshes in the south
of the country, depriving inhabitants of their livelihoods and protection
from attack. <BR>
<BR>
The Jordan basin is probably the region's biggest source of dispute, however.
It is the main potential source of fresh water for four nations on its way
to the Dead Sea, although in practice it has been in Israeli hands since
the capture of the Golan Heights in 1967. This was reinforced when Israel
occupied southern Lebanon in 1978 and so won control of the river's source.
<BR>
<BR>
Today it remains pivotal to the politics of the region and is at the heart
of the underlying impasse in the Palestinian/Israeli peace deal, along with
the West Bank aquifers. These are the vast underground stores of water,
built up over centuries as rainwater trickles down through the soil to be
stored in minute gaps in the rock and soil. Every year Israel pumps 600
million cubic metres (m3) of water (a third of its needs) from what are
effectively giant geological sponges underneath the West Bank. Of this,
a fifth goes to the 1.4 million local Arabs (82 m3 per capita), while the
130,000 Jewish settlers get 30 million m3 (almost five times more per person).
<BR>
<BR>
The Yarkon-Taninim is the largest disputed aquifer with a capacity of some
500 million m3 . It flows west and north east from the West Bank mountain
ranges, and stretches from Tel Aviv in the west to the Arab village of Tulkarm
in the east. Since 1967 the Palestinians have been banned from tapping it
by digging new wells or renovating old ones, but with peace in the air they
now want their share. Israel baulks at the idea: &quot;If the Palestinians
drill new wells in Tulkarm, they take away water going to Tel Aviv, it's
as simple as that,&quot; says Yaacov Tsur, Israel's agriculture minister.
They prefer to point to the 150 million m3 of water which flows east in
other aquifers and is largely unexploited by the Palestinians, mainly because
it lies deep beneath hard bedrock. <BR>
<BR>
Overall, however, the Israelis concede the issue of water ownership is vital
for everyone. Their preferred solution is to consider resources in terms
of future needs rather than legal ownership: &quot;We are now negotiating
over the levels of water each side needs, not about water rights,&quot;
foreign minister Shimon Peres told Yasser Arafat in July. Indeed, so problematic
is the issue that the negotiators have postponed a final deal until the
very end of the peace process in 1997, in an attempt to make progress elsewhere
(see Prince, page 11). <BR>
<BR>
Likewise, the Lebanese are unhappy with what they see as the theft of their
water. Last year an official complaint was made to the UN about apparent
Israeli poaching of the Litani and Wazzani rivers in southern Lebanon. After
spotting what appeared to be construction work, they claimed Israel intended
to pipe off water for the arid region north of Galilee. Israel denies this
but adds that both rivers are underused and says the region's water supplies
should be put into a &quot;water bank&quot; to be shared according to needs.
It claims that currently all countries, apart from itself, have more than
enough water provided it is properly used. <BR>
<BR>
While the ownership of available resources may be hotly contested, there
is unanimity about the gravity of the long-term situation. According to
a recent report, by 2020 the water available to each Israeli will have fallen
by more than half but for Gaza the future is even bleaker: one estimate
suggests it will run totally dry by the year 2000. Likewise the Jordanians
have every reason to be worried: The country is already one of the driest
in the world and its supplies will have dropped by two-thirds within a generation.
Most of the country gets under 200mm of rain a year, less per head than
Saudi Arabia and far less than any Saharan state. Historically most of its
water came from the River Jordan, but this was lost in 1967. Instead the
Jordanians had to turn to damming desert rivers or <I>wadis</I> to trap
the limited water available there and tapping their own aquifers. <BR>
<BR>
Unfortunately, both sources are finite. The largest aquifer feeds the Azraq
Oasis to the east of Amman, supplied by 20 million m3 of water trickling
underground from the Syrian Druz mountains annually. For the past 40 years
this has been tapped to supply the capital, and at present more than double
the amount fed by the oasis is being extracted: &quot;The current rate of
pumping is more than twice the safe yield,&quot; confirms Muhammed Shatanawi,
director of water and environment research at the University of Jordan.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Exhaustion of water underneath Jordan </B><BR>
<BR>
Economic problems resulting from this unsustainable mining are already apparent.
Until the '60s the oasis was the largest expanse of fresh water in the Middle
East, with 3,000 m3 an hour bubbling up to produce fertile grazing and water
for wandering Bedouins and their flocks. By 1992 the last spring dried up
totally. The same goes for the aquifer under Amman, albeit on a smaller
scale, and official estimates predict it will be exhausted in 25 years.
Indeed, some prophets of doom go further. When Germany's Friedrich Ebert
Institute assessed the problem in 1993 it concluded that even if distribution
and irrigation were made more efficient, Jordan's rapidly expanding population
of 4 million would exhaust available supplies by the turn of the century.
<BR>
<BR>
Not surprisingly, the results are already beginning to show: this year was
the fifth in a row that water rationing has been imposed on the capital
and the country only manages one crop a year, compared with Israel's three.
<BR>
<BR>
Naturally, the authorities are aware of the problem and have put forward
a range of solutions. King Hussein favours capital intensive measures, for
example. One solution is to tap the southern Disi aquifer which straddles
the border area with Saudi Arabia. This would yield 100 million m3 of water
a year, but would involve the construction of a 350km pipeline and cost
some $450 million. <BR>
<BR>
A simpler solution would be to dam the Yarmuk, which flows from Syria into
the Jordan. Although dry most of the year, it contributes to nearly half
of the country's surface water and could supply a large percentage of its
water needs. Until now hostilities made this impossible: Israeli troops
destroyed an early dam attempt during the Six-Day War. Recent peace talks
have changed all this, however, and Israel is keen to offer its expertise
in stretching water use to the limits as part of a deal. <BR>
<BR>
More grandiose still is the Red-Dead Canal, which would pipe sea water from
Aqaba on the Red Sea to the Dead Sea. Until recently, the latter lay 392
metres below sea level, its water loss through evaporation topped up by
the River Jordan. Thanks to exploitation of the latter, however, the water
level has dropped 17 metres and its surface has shrunk by a third. Experts
predict that if something drastic is not done soon, it will have vanished
entirely within the next half century. <BR>
<BR>
So the Jordanian king proposes a 240km pipeline, carrying 1,900 million
m3 of water annually, to raise the Dead Sea to its former level within a
decade. From then on it would carry 1,200 million m3 , so allowing the River
Jordan to be exploited fully by man. Because of the difference in height
between the the sea and the river, the pipeline could house a hydroelectric
power plant. Although two-thirds of the power generated would be needed
to pump the water over its first hurdle, a 220-metre climb north of Aqaba,
there would still be enough power left to desalinate 800 million m3 of sea
water. The drawback? Apart from uncertainty over the environmental effects
of pumping sea water into the already highly saline Dead Sea, the cost looks
prohibitive. The World Bank estimates that the project would take a decade
and cost between $3 billion and $4 billion: beyond the pocket of a country
devoid of oil and with few natural resources, with an average per capita
income of just $1,700 per year. <BR>
<BR>
Another volatile problem occurs to the north, along the Tigris and the Euphrates.
Both rivers have their sources in the mountains of Turkey, before meandering
across Syria and Iraq to the Gulf. Although Turkey allows a reasonable supply
into Syria under a 1987 protocol, supporting the latter's agriculture and
hydroelectric schemes, the Syrian government is still unsatisfied. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Dissatisfaction downstream </B><BR>
<BR>
Downstream, Iraq is also dissatisfied by its share of the flow, which has
shrunk to just over half of the volume leaving Turkey. Both nations' protests
have met with a frosty response in Ankara: &quot;Neither Syria nor Iraq
can lay claim to Turkey's rivers, any more than Ankara could claim their
oil,&quot; announced Turkey's President Suleyman Demirel after one such
protest. &quot;We have a right to do anything we like.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The president has a personal interest in the subject. He masterminded the
ambitious GAP programme of water schemes, including dams on the Tigris and
Euphrates rivers, hydroelectric plants and irrigation canals. In theory
around a fifth of Turkey's total cultivable terrain, or an area 10 times
the size of Belgium, could be brought into production. This would increase
agricultural production fourfold, generate over a fifth of its total hydroelectric
potential, create over 3 million jobs, increase per capita incomes fivefold
and create exports worth $6 billion a year. <BR>
<BR>
Since its inception in the '50s, Turkey has spent $11 billion on GAP and
has plans to pump twice that much again into the scheme. So far almost all
the money has come from Turkey itself; the World Bank fought shy of providing
funds because of the concerns felt downstream in Syria and Iraq. Some of
these fears appeared to be confirmed in 1989 with the opening of the Atat&uuml;rk
dam on the Euphrates: filling it stopped the river's flow entirely for a
month. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Water-for-Kurds deal </B><BR>
<BR>
There are glimmers of hope for the Iraqis and Syrians, however. Turkey has
many sources of water but has a problem with Kurdish separatists who flit
across borders. In return for help against the Kurds, Turkey's foreign minister
Ferhat Ataman has strongly hinted, future supplies could be increased. <BR>
<BR>
In the late '80s, Turkey's late president Turgut Ozal proposed a vast scheme
known as the &quot;peace pipeline&quot; to carry an annual 2,200 million
m3 of water to neighbours from its Seyhan and Ceyhan rivers. Although potential
customers are not keen to be dependant on foreign water, the idea caught
on in Ankara and prime minister Tansu &Ccedil;iller now wants to sell water
to Israel by piping it southwards from the Mediterranean port of Antalya.
<BR>
<BR>
Africa too has immense problems. According to Norman Myers, a fellow of
Green College, Oxford and consultant to the World Bank, within the next
decade Egypt's water supply per person will drop by a third, Nigeria's by
two-fifths, and Kenya's by half. The problem is especially acute in Africa
because people are cutting down water-saving forests as populations grow.
<BR>
<BR>
The Nile is unquestionably the biggest potential source of trouble. Egypt
in particular depends on the river for almost all its water and is understandably
sensitive about what happens upstream. In theory a 50-year-old treaty gives
Cairo a major say in use of Lake Victoria's waters and a 1959 deal allows
Egyptian experts to be based in Sudan. &quot;Egypt's annual per capita share
of water is below 1,000 cubic metres - that is to say below the poverty
line. It is expected to drop, as the population grows, to 600 by 2025,&quot;
announced Abdel-Hadi Radi, Egypt's minister of public works and water resources.
He is particularly worried about irrigation schemes planned further up the
Nile in Sudan and Ethiopia. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Transferring water beyond the Nile basin could have grave consequences.
Once established, such a precedent would give all parties a right to dispose
of the water as they wished... Any scheme involving Nile water must take
into consideration the aspirations and welfare of all Nile basin countries,&quot;
he says. He has cause to be concerned, for there are signs the accords are
breaking down. Earlier this year several Khartoum-based Egyptian officials
were arrested by the Sudanese authorities and their property confiscated.
This prompted a major diplomatic row and concern that a water dispute could
exacerbate tensions between the two nations, already running high thanks
to the fundamentalist leanings of Khartoum. <BR>
<BR>
In reality, however, agriculture lies behind most of the water problems
across the Arab world. Although Middle Eastern states share less than 1%
of world's water supplies, for political reasons most of them have a policy
of self-sufficiency in food. This explains why 90% of the water they use
annually goes on agriculture. In order to green the desert, these states
are tapping aquifers and exploiting them far faster than they can be replenished.
Saudi Arabia, for example, has 1,800 boreholes on the Wajid aquifer 700km
south-west of Riyadh. Each irrigates eight hectares, enough to fill 10 good-sized
swimming pools. As a result the Saudis, who until a decade ago imported
half their food, are now self-sufficient in food and exporting 2 million
tonnes of wheat a year. Meanwhile the aquifer is falling by 10 metres a
year and extraction is calculated as 100 times the sustainable level. <BR>
<BR>
Likewise, although only a fraction of Jordan is under cultivation, agriculture
is responsible for the waste of vast amounts of water. In the Azraq basin,
for example, millions of cubic metres are lost through leaking pipes and
inefficient distribution systems such as spray irrigation, which wastes
far more than trickle systems. This represents about a third of the total
supplies available. Underlying this waste is the low cost of water, a fraction
of the prices charged to the relatively water-wealthy Israelis. For example,
Jordanian farmers pay nothing towards capital projects and support only
half of the operating costs. Thus there is no incentive to conserve water
and little interest in irrigating fields with semi-treated sewage, known
as brown water, as in Israel. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The threat of thirsty tourism </B><BR>
<BR>
The impending crisis has further worrying implications for long-term development
in the region. Since peace was first announced in 1993, for example, many
oil-poor countries have begun to look to tourism as a future source of revenue,
talking grandiosely of the &quot;heritage tourism trail&quot; which would
take high-spending western visitors across borders to visit the historic
sights of the Holy Land. <BR>
<BR>
Unfortunately, tourism is the most water-intensive industry of all. According
to the UN's Food and Agriculture Organisation, the same amount of water
needed to irrigate one hectare of high-yielding rice can support 100 urban
families for two years, or keep 100 luxury hotel guests going for just 55
days. <BR>
<BR>
Water problems can be found around the globe. Until the '60s, for example,
the Aral Sea in formerly Soviet central Asia was the world's fourth largest
store of fresh water and supported a thriving fishing industry. In 1958,
however, Soviet scientists began to divert water flowing into the Sea to
produce rice and cotton in the naturally barren Turkmenistan. The result
has been one of the world's greatest ecological disasters: by 1993 the Aral
had lost three-quarters of its water and had been transformed into three
highly saline lakes, killing virtually all sea life. Ports such as Muynak
in Uzbekistan, which used to support a fishing industry employing thousands
of people, are now separated from what is left of the Aral by up to 145km
of desert. Worse, pollution from heavy metals and pesticides, formerly trapped
in the sea mud, is now whipped up by the desert winds. As a result a recent
survey showed three-quarters of the town to be suffering from different
cancers. <BR>
<BR>
Not surprisingly, tempers are running high. Moscow &quot;demanded 6 million
tonnes of cotton from us and the entire socialist camp lived off that cotton,&quot;
announced Islam Karimov, president of newly independent Uzbekistan, at a
recent conference on the problem. &quot;They put pressure on [us] to...
feed Cuba, Korea and the whole socialist camp with cotton. It was this barbaric
use of water which led to the Aral tragedy.&quot; He is now demanding that
Russia, centre of the former Soviet empire, make a major contribution in
money and expertise to solving the problem. <BR>
<BR>
The dry regions of Asia and Africa do not have a monopoly in water disputes.
In Europe, for example, Hungary and Slovakia are embroiled in a row over
the latter's damming of the Danube at Gabcikovo-Nagymaros as part of a combined
irrigation and hydroelectric scheme. Hungary is incensed and has appealed
to the International Court of Justice. <BR>
<BR>
Not even the wealthy US is immune. The farms of the mid-west, wrested from
the buffalo and Indians a century ago, are drying up thanks to unsustainable
tapping of aquifers. In Kansas alone, more than 1,127km of formerly perennial
streams have run dry permanently. This is due to unrestrained tapping of
the main aquifer, the Ogallala, whose level is falling at the rate of 17
metres a year. This is also reflected in wells to the west of the state,
where water levels have declined by two-thirds since 1940. The culprit,
yet again, is agriculture: Plains farmers use a third of all US water, mainly
to produce subsidised crops. There must be doubts over the future, however,
as the cost of extraction rises rapidly and already many are going out of
business. Indeed, some agricultural scientists are now recommending that
the Plains be returned to the buffalo in the form of ranches before the
little remaining water runs out. <BR>
<BR>
In California, the struggle to find water goes one step further, with two
conflicting interests squabbling over supplies. In a state where rainfall
is a paltry 355mm<B> </B>a year, water-based disputes between farmers and
Los Angeles are a longstanding problem - remember Jack Nicholson in
the film <I>Chinatown</I>. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Water fights in California </B><BR>
<BR>
Under a Federal Law of 1902, farms of under 400 hectares are guaranteed
cheap water. As Los Angeles' need for water continues to grow, however,
there are rumblings from urban-based politicians and now the Clinton administration
is proposing to change the law, which could mean prices rising as much as
five times. Not for first time, the powerful farming lobby is up in arms.
<BR>
<BR>
The World Bank believes one solution for the general problem lies in valuing
water as an economic resource. Proper pricing would do much, it says, to
reduce waste and focus minds. While this may have a part to play, it is
also highly controversial. For a start it ignores the spiritual and cultural
values which many religions put on water. Ignoring the obvious example of
a river such as the Ganges in India, even nominally secular rivers can have
great political significance. Egypt's president Anwar Sadat experienced
this shortly after the Camp David Accord, when he proposed piping a small
portion of the Nile up to the Negev desert in Israel, possibly extending
the scheme to Lebanon, Syria or Jordan. The Nile is rich with symbolism
to many Egyptians, however, and the dream was rapidly abandoned when it
prompted an army assassination plot. <BR>
<BR>
Likewise, the prospect of realistic water prices upsets many liberals, who
regard access to water as a basic human right. Nor are such beliefs confined
to the political left: &quot;Our target must be for all citizens to be able
to afford, without government subsidies... water and waste services,&quot;
says Crown Prince Hassan of Jordan. &quot;These are essential components
of the basic right to a decent standard of life.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
In addition to water pricing, the World Bank calls for heavy investment.
Although this does not come cheap, it says even small projects are worthwhile.
For example, a 10-week cholera outbreak in Peru earlier this year is believed
to have cost the equivalent of three times the amount invested in water
projects in the country over the last decade. <BR>
<BR>
For many countries, however, the level of expenditure required to tackle
the problem is overwhelming. For a start, the most suitable sites for dams
in those countries crying out for water have usually already been exploited.
As a result, hydrologists and civil engineers are forced to turn to more
complicated or grandiose schemes, which are expensive. The World Bank itself
calculates that the $36 billion invested over the past 45 years will have
to be doubled over next decade to keep pace with demand, and even then it
would be unlikely to satisfy demand in some of the more desperate cases.
They tend to have high human costs too: over the past few years 16 million
people have lost homes to reservoirs in India alone, while a further million
will have to move to make way for the Three Gorges scheme on the Yangtze.
<BR>
<BR>
In fact, most experts advise thrift over grandiose schemes. In Jordan, for
example, in spite of the desperate need for water the approach to existing,
dwindling stocks is lax. Official figures say over half of the water which
goes into Amman's supply system is unaccounted for: leaks are thought to
account for half these losses. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Water everywhere, but not to drink </B><BR>
<BR>
Indeed, in spite of its call for investment worth $600 billion over the
next decade, equivalent to a quarter of its loan budget, even the Bank concedes
that controlling demand will prove far more cost-effective than the grandiose
capital-intensive schemes loved by politicians. Desalination works, for
example, are popular in oil-rich Gulf states but are expensive and demand
large amounts of energy. For Saudi Arabia, with a quarter of the world's
proven oil supplies, this may be no problem but for poor states like Jordan
or Syria it is not an option. <BR>
<BR>
The one possible exception is the Red-Dead canal scheme. Although even its
proponents agree that it is too costly for farming, it could be exactly
what the region needs. It would force realistic pricing, which in turn would
force everyone to adopt more responsible conservation methods. <BR>
<BR>
More importantly, however, it would tie Israel and Jordan into a huge shared
project. With the pipeline threading across both sides of the border, its
very vulnerability would be a powerful force for continuing cooperation.
In a world of dwindling water supplies, that can only be a good thing.
<H4>TALES FROM THE RIVERBANKS</H4>
Mekong A growing rate of industrialisation means rows have increased tension
between Laos, Vietnam and Thailand. <BR>
<BR>
Bramaputra Deforestation in Nepal and Bangladesh is causing a build-up of
silt in the Bay of Bengal. This is creating an island which both India and
Bangladesh are intent on claiming as their own. <BR>
<BR>
Ganges 300 million Indian farmers depend on the river, but tree-felling
in the Himalayan foothills is disrupting the flow and causing increasingly
serious floods in Bangladesh. <BR>
<BR>
Indus Pakistan is dependent on the river, two of whose main tributaries
are used by India to water the Punjab grain basket. <BR>
<BR>
Jordan Arguably the world's most valued and disputed river, it rises in
the Israeli-occupied southern Lebanon and the nominally Syrian Golan Heights.
From here it flows south to the Dead Sea, via Jordan and the occupied West
Bank. On its way, Israel taps 83% of available water. Its use is strongly
disputed by Jordanians, Palestinians and Israelis. Although peace negotiators
have postponed a deal on eventual ownership until 1997, this is likely to
be an intractable problem. <BR>
<BR>
Tigris/Euphrates Rising in Turkey, these two rivers flow south east through
Syria and Iraq, a fertile crescent known as the cradle of civilisation where
it is thought pre-historic man first turned to agriculture. Turkey's recent
grandiose gap-irrigation and hydroelectric schemes have diverted much of
the rivers' volume, generating deep concern in Syria and Iraq. Comparatively
water-rich Turkey seems prepared to compromise on the issue in return for
its neighbours' help with Kurdish rebels. <BR>
<BR>
Nile Flows through 10 countries. Provides almost all of Egypt's water. Egypt
and Sudan have an agreement over use of the river but water projects upstream
in Sudan, Kenya, Rwanda, Burundi, Uganda, Tanzania and Zaire could threaten
Egypt's survival. <BR>
<BR>
Kufrah aquifer Libya's great man-made river, which exploits the southern
Kufrah aquifer for use in the arid north, is causing alarm in Cairo. The
Egyptians fear that as the water table drops, the Nile could leak westwards,
either through subterranean aquifers or overland. In this case Egypt has
military contingency plans to seize a portion of southern Libya and stop
the leaks. <BR>
<BR>
Zambeze Zambia, Zimbabwe and South Africa are all heavily reliant on the
river and squabbles are already beginning. <BR>
<BR>
Danube Slovakia's combined irrigation and hydroelectric scheme at Gabcikovo
on the Danube has incensed Hungary and caused concern in other countries
downstream on one of Europe's greatest rivers. Hungary has appealed to the
International Court of Justice. <BR>
<BR>
Rio Grande The slightest hint of a dry spell provokes tension between US
and Mexican farmers over the water flow in this, the major source of water
for most of the arid southern American states and for much of northern Mexico.
<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

