<td valign=top align=left> 
<H2>RHONE-ALPS </H2>
<H4>Although it did not come into existence as a political entity until
the early '70s, the French Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes region has become famous trading
on existing traditions of commercial savvy and simple industriousness. Despite
unemployment and recent high-profile scandals, the success of smaller companies
and the positive business climate are succeeding in attracting a range of
foreign investors <BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#overview">OVERVIEW</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#chemical-solution">CHEMICAL SOLUTION</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#premier-barre">PREMIER BARRE</A></H4>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3><A NAME="overview"></A>SHREWD AND DILIGENT </H3>
The strength of industries based on know-how and added value helps insultate
exports from le franc fort <BR>
<BR>
<I>By Andrew Rosenbaum </I><BR>
<BR>
What makes a region? In 1972 the French president of the day, Georges Pompidou,
sliced the country up into new pieces, an act viewed at the time as a great
piece of administrative daring. Since then, the name Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes has
entered everyday use but as local people admit themselves, it has not always
been easy to figure out what makes someone Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpine. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The eight <I>d&eacute;partements</I> of the Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes do not
have the unifying history and culture of a territory like the Limousin,&quot;
admits Mark Varlet, MD of the Chambre Regionale de Commerce et d'Industrie
Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes. &quot;We have a piece of Provence, a bit of Burgundy,
the Savoie - which was Italian only a little over a century ago - and the
west, which is really part of the Massif Centrale. At first glance, there
is not much pulling our 5.5 million people together.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Of course, it is not that simple. &quot;There are a few characteristics
which many of us have in common,&quot; Varlet continues. &quot;One thing
you find throughout the Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes are people with business skills,
a certain know-how. They like to form family businesses for which they are
very good at finding specialised markets. Then, they like to work hard and
enjoy the finer aspects of our natural surroundings when they are not working.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Know-how but no heavy industry </B><BR>
<BR>
This is, indeed the character on which the Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpine economy is
based. By some great coincidence (some say design) no area in the region
has the heavy industry that one finds in Germany's Ruhr valley or in the
lowlands of Scotland. As Christian Bossuges, assistant director of the Lyon
Regional Office of the Banque de France, points out: &quot;Instead, technical
activities that involve a considerable level of know-how were worked out
by local businessmen.&quot; The savvy, local entrepreneur can be found from
the Alps to Provence; there are about 150,000 companies in the region and
75% of them employ fewer them 10 people, according to the Chambre Regionale
de Commerce. <BR>
<BR>
Just how savvy is this Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpine? Well, he is better at exporting
what he makes than entrepreneurs in most of the other French regions. The
FFr138.63 billion [$47.9 billion] in products he sells to other countries
beats all the others except the Paris region. The Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpine tends
to deal in goods with a high value-added content so that his export sales
have not been hurt by the highly valued franc. To give an idea of the influence
of large industry, consider the chemicals industry in Lyon which employs
32,000 people; 10 times as many depend on it for their livelihood). <BR>
<BR>
Exports are helped by the fact that the Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes region has one
of the best-developed transport infrastructures in France including the
high speed TGV train from Paris and beyond. A planned extension of the service
to Turin will make exporting even easier. &quot;Good communications give
an advantage to the many dynamic companies found there,&quot; enthuses Bernard
Weymuller, vice-president for corporate banking in France and Belgium at
Chase Manhattan. <BR>
<BR>
Apart from exports, production is also key: the region accounts for about
10% of total French GNP and claims to produce more than 10% in areas such
as electronics or mechanical engineering. The downside is that those sectors
which depend on subcontracting can suffer along with the industries they
depend on, although residents say they are broadening their client base.
For example the Vall&eacute;e de l'Arve, near Geneva, is almost completely
dependent on Renault Industrial Vehicles for which it carries out a specialised
metal preparation. When Renault does well, as now, the valley prospers.
When it does not, clouds loom. <BR>
<BR>
In general, however, Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpine businesses have chosen their field
carefully. Lyon houses a cluster of specialised chemicals, pharmaceuticals,
biotechnology and nuclear energy - France is one of the world leaders in
this field and the region is home to the recently re-started Superph&eacute;nix
reactor. Closer to Grenoble, the emphasis shifts to computers and electronics,
plastics, new materials or scientific research. Up in the mountains the
ski industry predominates; Chamonix and the Val d'Is&egrave;re are considerable
attractions for tourists. There is still plenty of subcontracting in metallurgy
and mechanical engineering throughout the region, and farming takes up a
noticeable percentage of total activity. Textiles continue to play a minor
role. Services are of increasing importance. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Fallout from fall of textiles </B><BR>
<BR>
Despite the phenomenon of the Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpine entrepreneur, there is
still excessive unemployment in the region. &quot;Many unemployed people
were part of formerly flourishing industries, like textiles,&quot; explains
Philippe Albert, vice-president of the Lyon business school &Eacute;cole
Superieure de Commerce. &quot;Others have not yet been able to make the
necessary switch from a traditional family trade to something else.&quot;
The current unemployment rate for the region is 11.5%, some 5% lower than
the French total. But it is shedding jobs at a rate slightly faster than
the French average, economists here say. <BR>
<BR>
The area has been suffering lately from other problems. A series of nasty
and highly publicised political scandals have been rocking city halls. The
mayor of Grenoble has been under investigation for corruption and Lyon's
deputy-mayor Michel Noir, an extremely popular local conservative politician,
was charged with accepting gifts from local businessman Michel Botton two
years ago. Botton's companies allegedly helped Noir lead the high life and
although it has never been established that Botton received anything in
return, relations between the two were just too close for the judges to
accept. Noir has been barred from local politics and the city is trying
to live the scandal down. <BR>
<BR>
The Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpine entrepreneur does not always succeed but when he
does, he seems to be able to make good use of the region's special characteristics,
its numerous small industry and its good work ethic. Philippe Foriel-Destezet
provides a perfect example. <BR>
<BR>
In 1964 he was working as a commercial director in a Lyonnais machine shop
when he decided to make a change and founded a temporary employment agency
in the outskirts of Lyon. Two big British and US agencies already had offices
in town, but Foriel-Destezet had ideas of his own. He installed his agencies
in cheaper, outlying areas where smaller industries actually had their workshops.
The strategy of keeping close to the customer worked, and in a few years
Foriel-Destezet's Ecco went on to apply his strategy in France and around
the world. Ecco is now the second-biggest temporary employment agency in
the world, grossing about FFr20 billion a year. Not surprisingly, Foriel-Destezet
is a believer in the region and maintains the European headquarters of his
company at Lyon. <BR>
<BR>
<B>flow of foreign investors </B><BR>
<BR>
Foreign investors have not been slow to take advantage of the region's dynamic
entrepreneurs: Hewlett-Packard, for example, has located its headquarters
at the Isle d'Abeau near Lyon. While statistics are not availiable on the
exact amount of regional foreign direct investment (FDI), according to Robert
Maury, director of the Association pour le developpement &eacute;conomique
de la region lyonnaise, it attracts several hundred million dollars every
year. &quot;Foreigners are attracted by the low cost of services in the
region,&quot; Maury says. &quot;Electricity is cheaper here than anywhere
else in Europe; water is cheap too and we've got plenty. If you compare
us with northern Europe, we are well ahead.&quot; Albert of the business
school adds: &quot;Being in the Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes puts them right at the
centre of Europe.&quot; While this may well be exaggerated, it is certainly
possible to travel easily to almost anywhere on the continent. <BR>
<BR>
Most investment in the Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes comes from the EU, according to
the association: European investment is behind 278 establishments in the
region. The US follows with 118, non-EU European investment accounts for
56 and Japan is responsible for 10. In terms of employee numbers, however,
the US is the largest investor, creating about 27,000 jobs. The mechanical
and electrical equipment sectors attract the most foreign investment, followed
by metals and chemicals, and services are attracting increasing interest,
Maury says. Weymuller at Chase Manhattan agrees that this is where future
job growth is likely to come: &quot;Pharmaceuticals and electronics are
among the areas expected to see the most foreign investment in the years
to come.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
According to Maury, 15 years ago the Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes ranked about 11th
in France for FDI: now it is at least third and possibly second. Last year
International Pepper invested $50 million in a liquid packaging unit for
Europe; the Japanese auto equipment maker Koyosueko also put in a considerable
sum for a plant and Ikea built a logistics centre nearby. &quot;This investment
has direct consequences,&quot; Maury says. &quot;We create about 1,000 jobs
every year.&quot; The Franco-Italian joint venture in microelectronics,
SGS-Thomson, is not exactly foreign but did not hesitate. It chose to build
one of its most important semiconductor plants at Crolles just 15km outside
Grenoble at the end of 1993, an investment of $600 million. The city was
chosen because Grenoble is already one of the most important centres of
scientific and technical research in France, with a ready supply of specially
trained personnel. <BR>
<BR>
One sector that foreign investors in Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes have favoured little
in the past is that of tourism. This is surprising since Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes
is France's second-most important tourist destination and one of the area's
most important industries, bringing in close to FFr14.7 billion per year,
according to Vincent Rains, director of the region's tourism committee.
&quot;We are pedalling a myth here,&quot; Rains insists. Chamonix and the
Val d'Is&egrave;re are among the most famous ski destinations in the world
and the committee is spending considerable sums to promote its resorts in
the US and Japan. &quot;We are hoping to attract more of these tourists
since their individual spending is higher than that of Europeans,&quot;
Rains explains. <BR>
<BR>
Another activity the region is hoping to develop is rural tourism. An increasingly
popular formula in France involves taking the family to spend a week on
the farm. Rains hopes that this will become ever more popular, because it
helps the region fight against the so-called <I>desertification </I>- complete
abandonment - of small rural towns. <BR>
<BR>
As one would expect of such a lively region, Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes has ambitions
including a bid to host the summer Olympic games in 2004. &quot;We will
be seeing some tough competition including Capetown and several American
cities but we can offer the most agreeable surroundings,&quot; says Michel
Rivoire, advisor to the president of the Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes regional council.
&quot;Few regions enjoy such a high and continuing level of cultural activity.&quot;
Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes is also famous for its good food, so Rivoire's claim may
not be overdone. <BR>
<BR>
A preliminary study shows that the cost of holding the games should not
place an excessive burden on the local authorities, he adds. But why has
the region decided to take on the task now? The cities are already working
together, Rivoire says, &quot;but if we win the Olympic games, we will see
a huge cooperative effort from the whole region. That is just what we want
to encourage.&quot; <BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3><A NAME="chemical-solution"></A>CHEMICAL SOLUTION </H3>
<B>The region's traditional base in chemistry gives Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes a
competitive edge over other areas </B><BR>
<BR>
The Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes region has a long history of involvement with chemicals.
As a medical centre since the Middle Ages, Lyon has always had scientific
schools, and until the beginning of this century the silk trade called for
chemists to mix dyes and provide new fabrics. The people of Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes
have been building on their chemical knowledge ever since. &quot;It's one
of our most valued skills: if you need to build a new molecule, come to
Lyon,&quot; says Xavier Patrouillard, regional manager of Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes'
largest industrial company Rh&ocirc;ne-Poulenc. <BR>
<BR>
The figures are impressive. With sales of about FFr50 billion [$10 billion]
a year, the chemical industry is one of the largest sectors in the region,
contributing close to 25% of the region's total sales of manufactured goods.
What makes it such a hotbed of chemical research is the even balance between
traditional chemistry and detailed, cutting-edge areas like parachemistry
and pharmaceuticals. This gives it an advantage over competing centres such
as Paris, where traditional chemicals outweigh the more specialised fields.
<BR>
<BR>
The area's tradition as a crucible for both chemistry and research has produced
a vast quantity of small, flexible businesses. &quot;These companies often
have considerable need for financing new projects,&quot; comments Christian
Bossuges, assistant director of the Lyon office of the Banque de France.
&quot;I hope the region will work out a way to aid financing them.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
But financing start-ups is only one part of the problem. It is as important
for these companies that a whole slew of consulting experts work locally,
largely in the area between Lyon and Grenoble. These boffins maintain centres
for r&amp;d, which stay in regular contact with public and private scientific
laboratories and speed up the pace of innovation in the region. <BR>
<BR>
A crisis has dogged the industry for the past three years. Although Patrouillard
says that Rh&ocirc;ne-Poulenc has weathered the storm, the company is still
not hiring in Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes. &quot;We have spent the past few years
seeking to gain productivity,&quot; he says, &quot;so we are hoping to enjoy
the fruits of that effort now.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Last year Rh&ocirc;ne-Poulenc spent FFr500 million in the region developing
an effective cure for animal parasites like fleas and ticks. A much greater
sum is being put into the development of silicone products. Other projects
under way include the development of tyres which save energy in use. The
company is particularly looking for growth in pharmaceuticals and speciality
chemicals, as part of a group-wide strategy to reorient away from base chemicals.
<BR>
<BR>
With two rivers to supply the large quantity of water required for chemical
processing, Lyon is well-suited to the industry. But environmentally, chemical
companies have a poor public image and much of Rh&ocirc;ne-Poulenc's recent
investment has gone towards tackling this. &quot;People still say that we're
polluting the rivers and leave bad smells,&quot; complains Patrouillard.
&quot;As a result the entire Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpine chemicals industry has made
a formal commitment to see that nothing of that sort occurs anymore.&quot;
For the time being, industry is cleaning itself up but in time, Patrouillard
says, the company will invest once more in the production side of its activities
in the region.<BR><BR> <HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3><A NAME="premier-barre"></A>COINS FOR STACKING </H3>
<B>Lyon mayor Raymond Barre, a man used to standing on the world stage,
is bullish about prospects for his city <BR>
<BR>
</B><I>By Andrew Rosenbaum </I><BR>
<BR>
Lyon mayor and former French prime minister Raymond Barre is the grand old
man of both local and national French politics. As someone used to strutting
on the international stage he can look at the smaller picture and say with
pride: &quot;Our regional unity is in the process of being forged.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Barre is a man who has spent much of his career as a cabinet minister and
parliamentarian in Paris, but in the 19th century gilt salon of the Lyon
H&ocirc;tel de Ville he is uninhibited in his enthusiasm when he talks about
his home turf. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The eight <I>d&eacute;partements </I>included in Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes
share... common interests, especially in the reinforcement of our network
of cities which are beginning to work together. Their companies already
have many joint projects,&quot; he explains. I recently met with the mayor
of Grenoble to work out a variety of projects that involved the two cities'
universities. This kind of cooperation is proving extremely fruitful and
it's happening more and more often.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Cooperation is fruitful, Barre says, because the people of Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes
are natural entrepreneurs. &quot;That's the one common culture that underlies
all of the different histories that make up the region. They have always
faced tough competition and they have had to make it much on their own.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Province without provincialism </B><BR>
<BR>
Entrepreneurialism is coupled with a shrewd and thrifty nature. &quot;When
I had just been elected deputy, I saw a <I>guignol</I>, a puppet show, in
which a Lyonnais husband was criticising his wife,&quot; he adds. &quot;He
said, 'Look, coins are milled round but that's not for rolling, that's for
stacking'.&quot; These characteristics will attract the foreign investor.
&quot;That, and the favourable reception which foreign industry gets. There
is no provincialism here. Look at the way [US computer company] Hewlett-Packard
settled into our Isle d'Abeau,&quot; Barre says. <BR>
<BR>
There is a downside to internationalisation and Barre admits that some of
the region's industries have been buffeted. &quot;Our textile industry has
undergone a profound restructuring over the past 20 years,&quot; he says.
&quot;Now it is becoming competitive again.&quot; As an example, he points
to the creation of the remarkably successful Premiere Vision textile show
in Paris, produced by Lyonnais entrepreneurs. <BR>
<BR>
Local industriousness is best portrayed by the plethora of subcontractors
in the region who supply large industry, Barre says: &quot;The quality of
the work here is absolutely first-rate, especially in the areas of advanced
electronics, chemistry, energy and the health industries. There is an enormous
wealth of industrial <I>savoir faire</I>. [The area] is a kind of greenhouse
for young enterprises because the level of local business culture and skills
is so high.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Barre continues that the region's geographical position makes it a &quot;bridge
between north and south.&quot; Much of the region's development is intended
to extend this function with considerable investment in infrastructure.
&quot;Then there's plenty of space left to build even in our fairly densely
populated region. There is room to grow,&quot; he adds. Barre is not interested
in seeing the national government use up that room. &quot;What we don't
want is the installation of some state industry.&quot; This would take up
space without providing benefits, as much of the labour force would come
from elsewhere. <BR>
<BR>
The region is growing, he insists, although the figures may not show it:
&quot;We are tied to national trends here in Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes and overall
growth prospects for France are not spectacular for the coming year.&quot;
But Barre remains indomitable and exhibits a bit of regional patriotism:
&quot;Of course, Rh&ocirc;ne-Alpes will keep up with the rest of the country
- and it will probably do several percentage points better.&quot; <p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
