<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra17.gif" alt="Area Profile">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 
<H2>SANTA CATARINA</H2>
<H4>A balmy, unpolluted state in southern Brazil, Santa Catarina is keen
to take advantage of its central position in the new Mercosur South American
trade grouping to get a share of the action and open up to the world's investors
and tourists. While it waits for key tax and constitutional reforms to be
passed by the central government in Bras&iacute;lia, it has work to do on
its own services and infrastructure <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#crest-wave">CREST OF A WAVE</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#tourism-tech">TOURISM AND TECH</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#road-recovery">ROADS TO RECOVERY</A></H4>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3><A NAME="crest-wave"></A>ON THE CREST OF A WAVE </H3>
<B>A state bracing for welcome change as Mercosur pushes Brazil's centre
of economic gravity southwards <BR>
<BR>
</B><I>By Noll Scott </I><BR>
<BR>
Like a surfer eyeing the next wave powering in from the ocean, the Brazilian
state of Santa Catarina is in an expectant condition. After the lost decade
of the '80s, the state's tidal defences against foreign investment and competition
are coming down in anticipation of the coming crest. But there are fears
that Santa Catarina's more experienced competitors, like S&atilde;o Paulo,
may elbow it aside just as the big one breaks. <BR>
<BR>
Such metaphors come readily to mind in Santa Catarina, whose splendid Atlantic
coastline is an established mecca for surfers from around the world. The
seaside attractions also bring millions of tourists each year from Brazil,
Uruguay, Paraguay, and above all Argentina. <BR>
<BR>
<B>A penchant for lederhosen </B><BR>
<BR>
Yet to most of the outside world, Santa Catarina is known as just another
state in the Brazilian south, an agricultural backwater servicing one of
the world's biggest industrial heartlands a few hundred kilometres to the
north. More quaintly, the state is famous as the home of isolated German
immigrant communities, some of whom even today speak their language of origin
and wear <I>Lederhosen</I> during festivals. <BR>
<BR>
In a big federation like Brazil with 14 states, it is easy for member states
to fade into relative anonymity. Santa Catarina has an output double that
of nearby Uruguay, it has no separate entry in the reference books. Even
within Brazil itself, individual states have not always been able to shout
loud enough for their interests to be heeded, especially when they lie outside
the traditional centres of power. The people of Santa Catarina are used
to getting by on their own. <BR>
<BR>
Now, however, that picture is changing. The integration of Brazil, Uruguay,
Argentina and Paraguay within the south American common market Mercosur
is shifting the regional centre of economic gravity southwards. It is a
process which many believe could transform Santa Catarina - less than an
hour by air from Buenos Aires, Montevideo, Asunci&oacute;n, S&atilde;o Paulo
and Rio - from a peripheral player to the epicentre of regional development.
<BR>
<BR>
Complementing its newfound geographical good fortune, Santa Catarina has
a strong exporting tradition which places it in a good position to seize
on the new sales opportunities. Exports to the Mercosur countries grew from
$52 million to $288.5 million between 1990 and 1994 alone. This year, despite
unfavourable exchange rates which left Brazil's overall trading balance
in deficit, Santa Catarina's export expansion to Mercosur shows every sign
of continuing with a further 14% leap in the first half of this year compared
to the same period last year. <BR>
<BR>
But the state's entrepreneurs and administrators know there are limits to
expanding sales on the back of existing installations - Santa Catarina's
industries are already running at 83% of capacity, the highest for any Brazilian
state. They are now eager to lure new investment, preferably from abroad.
&quot;The stage in which Santa Catarina was establishing itself as a state
which specialised in supplying goods and services can be considered at an
end,&quot; says Pedro Sirotsky, vice-president of the Rede Brasil Sul broadcasting
and publishing empire which dominates the states of Santa Catarina, Paran&aacute;
and Rio Grande do Sul. &quot;We need to attract companies from outside,
to take advantage of our open spaces, our qualified labour force and our
internal market.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Here lies the crux of the issue. While Santa Catarina does have some impressive
credentials to offer would-be foreign investors, as well as generous tax
incentives to help them make up their minds, so far the state has yet to
sign up a single big-name foreign company. <BR>
<BR>
Apart from a central position within Mercosur, what are these credentials?
&quot;We have everything an entrepreneur could desire,&quot; answers state
governor Paulo Afonso Vieira, at 38 the youngest governor in the union.
&quot;Quality of life, infrastructure and a population which is disposed
to do everything to achieve a better future.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The first and third of these claims is beyond dispute. The state's education
system is highly rated and its workforce among the most productive in the
country. Santa Catarina also enjoys a benevolent sub-tropical climate, a
beautiful coastline and an agricultural interior of variety and immense
fertility. Its towns and villages, kempt and prosperous, are strongly reminiscent
of a rural Europe to which the overwhelming majority of the state's inhabitants
can trace their origins, earning the state the nickname Brazil's Europe.
Like its southern neighbours, Santa Catarina's public services are efficient.
The jewel in the crown is the capital Florian&oacute;polis, which stands
on an idyllic island unspoiled by industry. To sit 10 minutes' drive from
the city centre by a lagoon, eating fresh seafood and drinking in the view,
is a privilege no visitor should be allowed to miss. <BR>
<BR>
Santa Catarina's population is the most evenly spread in Brazil, an advantage
in an age when high technology demands decentralisation None of the state's
industrial and economic centres has more than 500,000 people, offering endless
possibilities for expansion. Only eight of the state's cities are larger
than 100,000 people. In striking contrast to the choking urban sprawls of
S&atilde;o Paulo and Rio, this decentralisation reinforces a lifestyle that
other Brazilians envy. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Infrastructure needs </B><BR>
<BR>
Vieira's second claim, about his state's infrastructure, is more questionable.
Following recent enabling legislation by the government in Bras&iacute;lia,
the state's major utilities - power, sewage and telecommunications - are
eagerly seeking private sector partnerships to help improve services The
state power company Celesc estimates it will need to invest $1 billion over
the next five years to meet demand which is growing at 5.5% a year. Celesc
plans to raise at least $400 million through a bond issue on the New York
stock exchange in the near future. <BR>
<BR>
In the transport sector, Santa Catarina's three ports are likely to move
towards privatisation in the next couple of years. Under the control of
the local municipal authority one of them, Itaja&iacute;, has invested in
handling machinery, cut costs and improved services. It has a lively partnership
with a number of major customers including the food processing and soya
bean giant Ceval, which is now financing the construction of its own berths
at the harbour. <BR>
<BR>
Glauco Jose Corta is executive vice-president of Santa Catarina's second
largest company Portobello, which produces ceramics, floor tiles and sugar:
he is among those who believe much more needs to be done to improve the
state's infrastructure including the road and rail network. &quot;This is
the critical element in making our industries competitive,&quot; he says.
&quot;As long as it costs four times as much to make an international telephone
call from Brazil to Europe as from Europe to Brazil, we are always going
to be at a disadvantage.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>Costly delay in reform </B><BR>
<BR>
What of the future? Osvaldo Moreira Douat, president of the Santa Catarina
State Federation of Industry (ESC) believes foreign investors will wait
for the country's constitutional changes to complete their slow passage
to the statute books before they take advantage of the new opportunities.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Half a million jobs are being lost through the country's slowness
in passing the reforms,&quot; Douat estimates. Brazil's share of world trade
has slipped to 0.8% from 1.4% in 1985, with total volume now in excess of
$4 trillion, suggesting that &quot;there is a potential for expansion of
$24 billion a year&quot;. Santa Catarina's share of the jackpot would be
an increase of $1.3 billion. Douat, who joined Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso on a recent state visit to Germany and accompanied Vieira
to France, returned convinced that European business is now willing to invest
in Latin America, especially Brazil. He reckons that the emphasis has shifted
away from wholly owned subsidiaries towards joint ventures. <BR>
<BR>
The long-awaited administrative, taxation and state welfare reforms are
expected to be passed by congress next summer. For Vieira, this cannot come
soon enough if they clarify the muddled financial relationship between Brazil's
federal administration and the individual state administrations. &quot;We
need to make the taxpayer's life easier,&quot; he says, arguing for income
taxes to be levied at federal level, consumption taxes at state level and
property taxes at the local or municipal level. But he is alarmed by signs
that the central government may take over taxes on goods and services, until
now the regional state's main source of income. <BR>
<BR>
Vieira, a member of the centrist Brazilian Democratic Movement Party, was
elected in October 1994 with the backing of a coalition of parties including
the federal president's Brazilian Social Democratic Party and the right-wing
Liberal Front Party, the core of the alliance which also dominates the national
parliament. Like President Cardoso at national level, he has had to work
hard to win backing in the state legislature where his supporters do not
enjoy an automatic majority. Of the 22 proposals he sent for approval in
the first six months of his mandate, only 14 were passed without delay.
<BR>
<BR>
In the medium-term the state's prospects depend heavily on the <I>Plan Real</I>,
the government's stabilisation programme, introduced in the middle of last
year. While slashing inflation from 50% 18 months ago to around 1% a month,
the <I>Plan Real </I>has seen interest rates rise to record levels. At the
same time a high exchange rate has hit exports and a dramatic relaxation
of Brazil's former restrictions has unleashed a flood of cheaper imports,
wreaking havoc in a wide number of sectors including textiles, ceramics,
shoes and agriculture. <BR>
<BR>
Although Douat is one of many urging the central government to bring down
interest and exchange rates, he feels the stability achieved so far outweighs
the &quot;negative factors&quot; which he regards as merely temporary: &quot;Our
involvement in Mercosur and the developed market economies points to an
increasing role for our state's industry in the coming years.&quot;Hans
Meyer, president of the chamber of industry and commerce in the state's
second largest town Blumenau, agrees: &quot;We are living with all the pluses
and minuses of the <I>Plan Real</I>,&quot; he says. &quot;But it's the best
plan we've had yet.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>Call for lower interest rates </B><BR>
<BR>
Others, like Jorge Ronaldo Pohl, who leads the state retailers' federation,
are less sanguine and note the growth of indebtedness among retailers from
3% to 15% in the past year. When the <I>Plan Real </I>was first introduced,
he says, &quot;we went through a period of euphoria... everyone seemed to
have money. Then, as sales fell, we started to do any deals that came along
without a careful look at the consumer's situation. The only way the sector
will recover is if the government brings down the base rate, which will
bring down interest rates as well.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Angela Amin Helou of the right-wing Progressive Reform Party, who ran for
election as state governor last year, sums up the situation: &quot;It is
undeniable that the <I>Plan Real</I>, by freeing imports and the overvalued
exchange rate, brought undesirable consequences to the economy of Santa
Catarina. The textile, shoe and furniture sectors, for example, are going
through worrying times and small businesses are suffering from lack of credit.
But bad times were never a reason for [us] to get discouraged. We are an
economy that is built to seek efficiency, quality, productivity.&quot; <BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3>FINGER ON THE PULSE </H3>
<B>Santa Catarina's largest company, the biggest processor of soya beans
in Latin America, is expanding </B><BR>
<BR>
Santa Catarina's largest company, the Ceval Alimentos agroindustrial company,
was created 23 years ago as an offshoot of Latin America's dominant textile
company. The firm owes its origins to the then military government which
in the early '70s offered generous tax incentives to encourage diversification.
<BR>
<BR>
It was not long before Ceval had overtaken its parent company. Now it is
Santa Catarina's single largest enterprise, the second largest producer
of chicken and pork products in Brazil, the biggest processor of soya beans
in the whole of Latin America and the fourth largest in the world. Export
revenues last year totalled $960 million and domestic sales brought in $1.18
billion. <BR>
<BR>
Based at Gaspar in Santa Catarina's Itaja&iacute; valley (its name is an
abbreviation of &quot;cereals of the valley&quot;), Ceval started out by
producing sugar but swiftly moved into soya. By 1985 exports accounted for
80% of its business, but as the company has further diversified into meat
products the domestic Brazilian market has steadily grown in importance.
Last year domestic sales overtook exports, a tendency which has dramatically
accelerated this year with the drastic revaluation of the Brazilian currency,
the real. <BR>
<BR>
Indeed, the virtual stagnation of Ceval's export earnings, coinciding with
a striking surge in domestic sales, is typical of the Brazilian economy
as a whole since the advent of the <I>Plan Real</I> stabilisation programme.
To maintain exports in the face of the country's overvalued currency (they
grew just 0.8% in the second quarter of this year, compared to the same
period last year), the company has been forced to sell for little or no
profit. &quot;It has taken us years to win these markets. We're not going
to let our customers down now,&quot; says Herculano Danicio Martins, Ceval's
marketing manager. <BR>
<BR>
As compensation, the dramatic rise in the volume of domestic demand has
led to an enormous increase in the company's sales of consumer products,
which over the same period grew 67.8%. <BR>
<BR>
Today the Ceval empire stretches across 14 states of Brazil and is beginning
to reach abroad, with the acquisition this year of the Argentinean soya
and peanut company, Guipeba, for $60 million. It now has four bases in Argentina.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Altogether we expect to reach $2.48 billion in revenue this year,&quot;
says Ceval directory general Vilmar de Oliveira Schurmann. Meeting this
target would represent an increase of 16% over last year, a considerable
feat given that takings grew by a phenomenal 64%. <BR>
<BR>
At the moment, Ceval's biggest planned investments are concentrated in the
meat products division, with plans to boost revenues from $558 million last
year to around $2 billion by the year 2000. Altogether the company's expansion
plan foresees investments of $326 million between now and 1998, of which
$201 million will be directed towards doubling its existing processing capacity
for pork and chicken, and $38 million towards vegetable oils. <BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="tourism-tech"></A>A BRAZILIAN TECHNOPOLIS  </H3>
<B>The lack of heavy industry makes the state an ideal place to attract
high-tech companies and talent <BR>
<BR>
</B><I>By Noll Scott </I><BR>
<BR>
Santa Catarina, though the smallest of Brazil's southern states, is the
one on which nature has bestowed the greatest variety, making it the leader
in drawing tourists from inside Brazil or abroad. More than 1.5 million
tourists a year come to enjoy its beaches, mountains, waterfalls and medicinal
spas. <BR>
<BR>
It is the capital Florian&oacute;polis that stands out as the most spectacular
attraction. Sited on a long, thin island, Florian&oacute;polis is joined
to the mainland by two bridges: one a modern double-span affair, the other
an 80-year-old British-designed construction of iron and wood. This is the
capital's best known monument although structural problems have closed it
even to pedestrians for the past decade. The geography of the island (confusingly,
also called Santa Catarina), offers 42 beaches on two coastlines - the rougher
shore to the east facing the open ocean, a favourite haunt of surfers, and
the calmer west coast which faces the mainland. Between the two shores are
spectacular freshwater lagoons, perfect for windsurfing and yachting, ringed
by restaurants offering fresh seafood. <BR>
<BR>
It is part of the region's charm that most of its accommodation consists
of informal guest houses and weekend cottage rentals rather than luxurious
hotels, but visitors have to be ready to put up with minor inconveniences
as a result. As Adolfo Ern Filho, director of the Santa Catarina Tourist
authority Santur, acknowledges, there is plenty of room for improvement
in tourist services. &quot;We are working hard to improve the skills of
both the workforce and management,&quot; he says. <BR>
<BR>
A city of around 400,000 people, Florian&oacute;polis has never developed
a serious industrial base and its population is mostly employed in administration
and services, giving the city a placid atmosphere largely free of the pollution
which threatens to engulf many of Brazil's bigger centres. &quot;There is
no place here for heavy industry because it would affect Florian&oacute;polis'
primary industry which is tourism,&quot; says Pedro Sirotsky, vice-president
of the Rede Brasil Sul media network. The state government is therefore
promoting the city as the natural home of new technology, or technopolis.
With its relaxing atmosphere it is not hard to imagine the city becoming
a San Diego of the southern hemisphere, and there would be little problem
in attracting talent: in recent opinion polls, Florian&oacute;polis is the
one Brazilian city that young middle-class graduates say they would like
to live in one day. <BR>
<BR>
Away from Florian&oacute;polis, the state can be divided into five economic
regions. The far west is the home of agro-industry and smallholdings producing
pigs and chicken, which are marketed across Brazil and abroad by large concerns
like Ceval. The region also produces large quantities of soya, garlic, onions,
rice, beans, maize and tobacco. Of these products, poultry ($372 million)
and soya ($289 million) were high on the list of Santa Catarina's exports
to the outside world in 1994. <BR>
<BR>
The south of the state is the traditional home of ceramics such as tiles
and flooring materials, which produced exports worth $97.4 million in 1994.
The Itaja&iacute; Valley, which runs into the ocean about 150km north of
Florian&oacute;polis, is the base for the state's textile industry, whose
output accounted for $295.8 million of exports last year. Engineering, plastics
and chemicals are produced in the north around Joinville, the state's biggest
city, and were responsible for $311 million in overseas sales last year.
Finally, the highlands of the north near the border with the state of Paran&aacute;,
are a booming area for wood and related products, including paper, cellulose
and furniture. Sales of these amounted to $306 million last year.<BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%> 
<H3><A NAME="road-recovery"></A>STOP AND GO POLICIES </H3>
<B>The new highway may only be 25 kilometres long, but it represents a much
longer journey on the road to recovery <BR>
<BR>
</B><I>By Noll Scott </I><BR>
<BR>
At a grand ceremony in the rural heart of Santa Catarina's Itaja&iacute;
valley, all the leading dignitaries of the southern Brazilian state are
on hand to welcome the national president, Fernando Henrique Cardoso. Beside
a temporary stage erected in the middle of the countryside, a brass band
of the ceremonial guard in full dress uniform stands by to play the national
anthem while loudspeakers entertain the swelling crowds with Brazilian rock,
samba and reggae. <BR>
<BR>
By the time a prolonged volley of firecrackers bursts into the evening sky,
a throng of several thousand is gathered in party mood. It is, after all,
the first presidential visit to the state since Fernando Henrique was elected
precisely a year ago, in October 1994. <BR>
<BR>
And the cause of all the fuss? Two decades after it was first initiated,
a new road is finally being inaugurated. The new road links the small town
of Gaspar in the Itaja&iacute; valley with the neighbouring seaside municipality
of Navegantes. Known as the BR-470, it is just 25 kilometres long. <BR>
<BR>
It would be far too easy to describe this ceremony as overkill, especially
when young state governor Paulo Afonso Vieira portentously proclaims this
short stretch of paved highway to be &quot;the most important public work
of the past 10 years in Brazil&quot; - a country, we hardly need remind
ourselves, of 150 million people and the ninth largest economy in the world.
<BR>
<BR>
To be fair, these 25 kilometres mean a great deal more than just a handy
new link between two neighbouring municipalities. They significantly enhance
the existing road connection which links the Itaja&iacute; valley, one of
Santa Catarina's most important industrial regions, to the agricultural
hinterland to the west and to the expanding port of Itaja&iacute; itself,
where the river runs into the Atlantic Ocean. <BR>
<BR>
But one soon senses the real reason for the fanfare. Rather than the inflated
celebration, this ceremony turns out to be a heartfelt expression of relief
that the sorry saga of delays, escalating budgets and lack of political
will is finally over, a sign of hope that the recent distortions bedevilling
public policy in Brazil are coming to an end. <BR>
<BR>
There are good reasons for the delay. The crisis of military rule from the
late '70s and the subsequent transition to democratic civilian government
coincided with the debt crisis of the '80s. Soaring inflation climaxed at
50% a month as recently as last year, making a mockery of even the most
honest efforts at strategic infrastructural investment. Thus the stop-go
policies of the past two decades have turned out to be a great deal more
stop and a lot less go. <BR>
<BR>
A climate of rampant corruption in which public works were often promoted
and contracts awarded on the basis of bribery, resulted in a full-blown
constitutional crisis and the impeachment of president Fernando Collor in
1992. Inevitably, this played a big part in setting back Brazilian development.
With the central state regularly dishing out federal funds as favours to
the regions, the art of local politics has often appeared indistinguishable
from crude influence-peddling. <BR>
<BR>
<B>A new departure for the state </B><BR>
<BR>
The inauguration of BR-470 turns out to be a new departure in this respect.
Strictly speaking part of the federal road network, its construction was
the responsibility of central government. But in this case, Bras&iacute;lia
was prevailed upon to devolve responsibility: over the past five years,
it has been the Santa Catarina authorities themselves who have had to provide
the lion's share of funds to complete the development. And they have done
so partly by raising private sector finance and partly out of their own
municipal budget. Accordingly, the key political moment of the day comes
when the president reaffirms his campaign promise that the far more strategic
artery crossing Santa Catarina state from north to south, the accident-ridden
BR-101, will be transformed into a modern dual carriageway. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Model for state-business cooperation </B><BR>
<BR>
The present nightmare reality of this highway is summed up in its popular
name, the <I>caminho da morte</I> or road of death. The president adds,
to loud cheers, a promise that the undertaking will be completed before
he leaves office at the end of 1998. <BR>
<BR>
The BR-101 was built two decades ago to handle 6,000 vehicles a day. More
than 20,000 cars and lorries now use it to rumble daily through the state,
whether northwards towards S&atilde;o Paulo or southwards towards Brazil's
southernmost state Rio Grande do Sul and the Uruguayan border. Effusive
in his praise for the &quot;exemplary partnership&quot; of central government,
the Santa Catarina authorities and the private sector in building the Itajai
road, the president adds that the north-south artery will be upgraded using
the same principles. <BR>
<BR>
Down at the end of the new road in Itaja&iacute; itself, these principles
are already being put into effect by the municipal administration, the third
tier of Brazilian government. Since June, Itaja&iacute; has had the unique
responsibility of running its own port, after decades of control by the
S&atilde;o Paulo ports authority CEDESP. In a curious hangover from the
years of military rule, CEDESP remains in charge of most other ports throughout
the country. The authority has won an unenviable reputation for maladminstration,
overmanning, delays, congestion, high charges and corruption. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Port privatisation likely </B><BR>
<BR>
Itaja&iacute;, the largest port in Santa Catarina, handles the fourth largest
volume of freight in the country. The mayor, Arnaldo Schmitt Jr, says efficiency
at the port has &quot;dramatically increased&quot; since its services were
put under local control. Pointing to examples across Europe, he argues that
it should continue to be run as a public utility in close partnership with
local private industry. <BR>
<BR>
But the consensus among Santa Catarina's business community, including senior
executives at companies which make heavy use of Itaja&iacute;, is that costs
would come down further if the port were to be privatised, making that appear
the most probable outcome in the future. <BR>
<BR>
Itaja&iacute; also contains the southern headquarters of the national oil
company Petrobras. It handles administration and offshore supplies for the
oil industry between Angra, in Rio de Janeiro state and the southern frontier
with Uruguay, housing a number of terminals for oil and its derivatives.<BR>
<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
