<td valign=top>
<h2>
November/December 1995
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>
<H3>FROM THE EDITOR</H3> 
<H2>Tale of two cities</H2>

<H4>Middle East and western states must recognise that peace and growth means
relinquishing central power</H4>
Two summit meetings are taking place around the same time, of key importance
to the Middle East. In theory they are both economic in purpose, but both
have a political agenda. The Barcelona Euromed summit in November aims to
promote that most economic of goals, a free trade zone linking the Middle
East to Europe, but foreign ministers alone are attending what is essentially
a political event. The EU is trying to succeed in the Mediterranean where
it failed in Bosnia, and pre-empt serious unrest which could spill over
into its territory. <BR>
<BR>
In contrast it is economic and finance ministers joining their business
counterparts at the World Economic Forum's Middle East/North Africa (MENA)
economic summit, hosted by King Hussein in Amman in late October. But in
deciding how to promote an economic partnership, participants face the geopolitical
question whether it will be the US or Europe which provides leadership.
<BR>
<BR>
In the meantime, the basic issues remain. Will these efforts help deliver
a peace dividend and create the economic prosperity that could reverse the
region's instability, compounded by unemployment, high population growth
and disillusionment with the political status quo? <BR>
<BR>
Some critics argue that the EU's free trade medicine may kill the patient
but it is offering a real benefit: access to its 15 member-states' markets.
At Amman, the priority for participants is to see that the projects announced
there break the mould of classic big-is-beautiful development dominated
by the state, and favour the private sector instead. The region's governments
must come to terms with the fact that more private sector growth -
the only kind that will help break the current patterns of popular disillusionment
- means less state patronage. <BR>
<BR>
Unfortunately, both western and Middle Eastern players are still addicted
to politics rather than economics: either conflict with outsiders or the
internal struggle for power. It is still rare to find authorities paying
attention to their emerging but struggling Arab business elites and asking
them, What do you want? <BR>
<BR>
There are many things to applaud since the first MENA summit in Casablanca
last autumn. The fact that Amman is happening at all is positive, coming
after a fraught Israeli-Palestinian peace process which has only just been
confirmed by a new deal on West Bank self-rule. Israel has also signed a
peace treaty with Jordan and has won wider acceptance by third parties such
as China and Japan, even though the Arab League boycott is not quite lifted.
Joint development of Red Sea tourism has gone ahead, although it remains
something of a showpiece exception. And Amman will put the spotlight on
some striking new possibilities such as the Qatari gas deal with Israel,
initiated under that Gulf state's new leader. <BR>
<BR>
At the time of going to press, however, the proposed regional development
bank championed by Jordan, Israel and the US was still in the balance. Most
objections come from Europe which argues that existing institutions could
take on the role. This is true in theory, but not in practice. The EBRD,
cited as an unpromising model, has now found its feet and is taking the
sort of imaginative approach from which the Middle East could profit with
its own bank. <BR>
<BR>
There is also still no peace deal with Syria. People at Amman will say it
is on the way but more than anyone, Assad's regime needs an outside enemy.
Syria might have hesitated because it expects a bigger reward for peace:
those who have cooperated, like Jordan, have not conspicuously benefited,
despite risking the wrath of a well-organised Islamist opposition. <BR>
<BR>
All parties need to make sure that goodwill is not eroded by small disappointments.
It should be built up by both small, practical successes and basic, bold
moves which make peace pay.<BR>
<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

