<tr>
<td>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<h2>
November/December 1995
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra17.gif" alt="Area Profile">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>
<H3>ON THE MOVE</H3> 
<H4>EUROPE IN ASIA </H4>
<H2>The China syndrome </H2>
Singapore's elder statesman Lee Kuan Yew, opening this year's Europe-Asia
summit on September 20, returned to his trademark theme: the need to integrate
an unpredictable China into the international community rather than punish
it with trade restrictions, as Washington has shown signs of doing in the
face of human rights and commercial abuses by Beijing. He went on to urge
Europe to become a full partner with east Asia to help reduce US-China tensions,
a goal likely to be advanced by the planned meeting of European and Asian
leaders in Bangkok in March. <BR>
<BR>
Even with an increasingly rich and powerful east Asia, he argued, it was
in everyone's strategic interests for the US to maintain a regional presence
as a countervailing power to Japan and China: &quot;If this triangular relationship
is in balance, the rest of east Asia will be stable,&quot; he concluded.
<BR>
<BR>
Better to establish good relations with China now, before it achieves its
potential, than throw obstacles in the way which will only delay the process
and enrage the future giant. &quot;Integration will build up strong vested
interests in China to play by international rules and increase China's interdependence
for trade,&quot; he said, adding later during questions: &quot;If Asia,
having gained muscle, decides to settle scores, it's going to be a nasty
world.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The Norwegian Prime Minister, Gro Harlem Brundtland, responded to this challenge
by agreeing that Asia would simply &quot;go it alone&quot; if Europe stayed
away, but argued that the region would &quot;manage its transition period
better and more effectively if you make full use of what Europe has to offer&quot;.
<BR>
<BR>
This included a willingness to engage in public debate: &quot;We cannot
isolate our economic relations from wider mutual general curiosity... people
in the west have opinions and will express [them] about the countries of
east Asia as they have - and do - about their own countries,&quot;
she said. <BR>
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4>REGIONAL RELATIONS </H4>
<H2>Apec and beyond </H2>
Much discussion in Singapore centred on the structures needed to enhance
relations between Asia and Europe. Korean Prime Minister Hong-Koo Lee said
the two should work &quot;to maintain and strengthen the multilateral trading
system... prevent proliferation of closed regional [trade groups and] make
an effort to keep the existing ones open&quot; so they do not discriminate
against non-members. &quot;East Asia should strive to ensure that Apec adheres
to this principle,&quot; as should the European Union its own single market,
he added. <BR>
<BR>
The Australian foreign minister, Gareth Evans, praised the growth in both
members and scope seen by since the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum
over six years but said it still lacked substance and purpose, describing
Apec as &quot;four adjectives in search of a noun&quot;. He called on its
members to flesh out existing agreements when they meet again this November
in Osaka: <BR>
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4>BUSINESS GUIDE </H4>
<H2>Ten steps to Asian success </H2>
Ian Buchanan, vice-president of Booz, Allen &amp; Hamilton, distilled his
consultancy's accumulated wisdom about doing business in the Asia Pacific
region in a quick 10-point summary laced with gritty humour: 
<H4><BR>
* Have a clear corporate vision and role for the Asia Pacific. <BR>
<BR>
* Look before you leap as the region contains a diverse portfolio. <BR>
<BR>
* Follow Asian ways: work like a farmer, not a hunter-gatherer. <BR>
<BR>
* Know-who is just as important as know-how. <BR>
<BR>
* Build a capability to take on allies, but have an exit strategy. <BR>
<BR>
* Promise only what you can deliver, and deliver what you promise. News
travels fast: step on someone's toes in Java, they will hear about it in
Thailand. <BR>
<BR>
* The guy closest to the market has to make the decisions. <BR>
<BR>
* Find the right people to bridge the gap between HQ and the field. They
are probably employees in their 50s with the grey hair Asians take seriously.
<BR>
<BR>
* The contract is just the beginning of the relationship. Making it happen
requires supervision. <BR>
<BR>
* Have a good time! You are going to come across plenty of problems so enjoy
yourself. <BR>
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%><BR>MEXICAN INVESTMENT FORUM </H4>
<H2>Guarded optimism </H2>
Meeting with participants at the first-ever Global Investment Forum in September
at his official residence Los Pinos (above), Mexican president Ernesto Zedillo
gave advance details of his country's newly liberalised investment regime,
confirming that he would attach no strings to foreign portfolio investment
and would not be copying Chile's restrictive measures which require foreign
capital to stay in the country for over a year. He also promised incentives
for domestic saving. <BR>
<BR>
The forum, organised by <I>World Link</I> together with Euromoney Conferences,
was attended by key Mexican ministers and over 500 participants from 18
different countries. It was hosted by the Mexican Investment Board. <BR>
<BR>
At a brainstorming session on the outlook for the Mexican economy, led by
Rafael Piccolo of Hewlett Packard in Mexico and Frank Lysy, chief economist
at the World Bank for Mexico and Venezuela, the consensus was one of guarded
optimism. However many participants called on government speakers to say
more about the acute political problems threatening Mexico's economic recovery.
<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
