<!--created by Oyster Systems-->
<!--May 1996-->
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
EMWL: World Link Magazine: November/December 1995
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<!--START_TAG_SPACE-->
<!--00002400 Geopolitics -->
<!--END_TAG_SPACE-->
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="7C1568" text="000000" link="7C1568">

<center>
<font size=3>
<table border=0>
<tr>
<td colspan=2 align=left>
<nobr>
<img width=199 height=44 name="top" border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../images/conban8.gif" alt="World Link Magazine"><a href="../../../../../index.html"><img width=141 height=45 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../../images/conban1.gif" alt="EMWL Home"></a>
</nobr>
<br>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<h2>
November/December 1995
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>
<H3>COMMENT</H3> 

<H2>Peace and dishonour </H2>
<H4>The US peace plan may stop fighting in Bosnia but it could encourage
future proxy wars in the Balkans </H4>
<I>By Jonathan Eyal, director of studies at London's Royal United Services
Institute </I><BR>
<BR>
The vicious circle in the Balkans is going around; after another bout of
fighting peace talks are under way once again. This time, however, there
is a major difference: the Croats and to some extent the Bosnian Muslims
are holding the upper hand over the Serbs, the real culprits in starting
the war. Significantly, the US is now taking a lead in both brokering a
settlement and enforcing it through the power of Nato, the North Atlantic
military alliance. Yet despite this novelty, mayhem is guaranteed unless
the fundamental questions posed by the break-up of Yugoslavia receive an
answer. The problem is not only the Croat-Serb dispute (which has reached
a deadlock of sorts) but the future of Bosnian Muslim territory. <BR>
<BR>
Although hundreds of thousands of Croats and Serbs have been uprooted during
the last four years, no nation has suffered as much as the Muslims. Unlike
the leaders of Croatia and Serbia, who went into the war anticipating violence
with equanimity, President Alija Izetbegovic of Bosnia did not plan for
war and asked for no one else's territory. The Muslims have been accused
of some atrocities, but few are prepared to compare their behaviour to the
Serbs' premeditated murder campaigns or the vicious behaviour of Croat militia.
<BR>
<BR>
Bosnia stands for more than just a particularly gruesome Balkan tale. In
essence, it was Yugoslavia writ small - a republic in which no ethnic
group held a numeric majority but where Orthodox Serbs, Catholic Croats
and Muslims lived in peace. <BR>
<BR>
Islamic states have shown great interest in the Bosnian crisis. The fate
of Croatia and Serbia appeared initially to be the concern of Europe alone.
However, the fact that a state run by a Muslim-dominated government tried
and failed to preserve its territorial integrity and was even threatened
with complete annihilation, while Europe did nothing, fed long-held suspicions
held in the Middle East and Africa about the perfidy of western governments
and their hostility to an Islamic state in Europe. <BR>
<BR>
The broader question, therefore, is this: will the question of Bosnia have
a long-lasting impact on western relations with Islamic states? The answer
depends on whether a settlement in the Balkans can be followed by the institution
of a regional security system guaranteeing Bosnia's survival as an independent
state. Even if a peace deal does emerge this autumn, the task of repairing
western relations with Islamic states will only just have begun. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Repairing western relations with Islam </B><BR>
<BR>
President Izetbegovic himself is religious, but like many Bosnian Muslims
he is not as devout as his Serb and Croat enemies would suggest in their
desire to perpetuate religious stereotypes. Izetbegovic's official goal
remains that of the traditional, multi-ethnic Bosnia, not an Islamic state.
Many throughout the Middle East who are now championing his cause would
be horrified by Izetbegovic's visions of a multi-ethnic state. It is a vision
which most Islamic governments consider unacceptable and, at best, unworkable.
<BR>
<BR>
The reaction of many Muslim states is related more to a fight for influence,
chiefly between Saudi Arabia, Iran, Turkey, Egypt and Malaysia, than to
the search for a Balkan solution. <BR>
<BR>
It is not true that, had Bosnia not been a Muslim country, Europe would
have fought to save it long ago. The west did nothing to help Catholic Croatia
when the Yugoslav war began. This was because the EU believed Yugoslavia
did not really matter, not because it did not want a Muslim state in Europe.
In any case, the Bosnian government never claimed it wanted such a state
in the first place. <BR>
<BR>
Since 1991, those major powers striving for a solution have pursued different
aims. The British and the French governments sent troops to the country
without knowing what they were meant to be achieving, because they wanted
to do something to appease enraged public opinion at home, without doing
much in particular. The result was a UN peace-keeping operation which had
no peace to keep, striving to impose a peace which could not be imposed.
<BR>
<BR>
The Russians were equally disinterested in the conflict but, the moment
the west Europeans arrived on the scene, Moscow was determined to be present
in an area the Russians still consider within their sphere of influence.
And then came the US and Germany, two major powers with no soldiers on the
ground but with great principles which the international community was supposed
to uphold. <BR>
<BR>
The result was a disaster, a tussle between Europeans who wanted an end
to the war on any terms and Americans who wanted to give the Serbs a bloody
nose, preferably by using someone else's soldiers. While this foolish debate
proceeded the Serbs carved up Croatia, split Bosnia into pieces, uprooted
hundreds of thousands of Muslims in the name of ethnic cleansing and humiliated
the UN. On every crisis, the reaction of western governments has been too
feeble, too late, or both. This has been the history of the Yugoslav war.
<BR>
<BR>
Recent Croat offensives in eastern Croatia and western Bosnia, characterised
by lightening speed and huge success, altered the entire Balkan game. There
is no question that the Croats had received arms from the US, although this
was illegal under UN resolutions. For more than two years, the Americans
have brokered a federation between the Croats and Muslims of Bosnia. They
armed both secretly, hoping that this federation would stand up to the Serbs.
<BR>
<BR>
But Washington operated under one serious misconception. Although the Serbs
and Croats will fight each other, they are potential allies in keeping Muslim
Bosnia down. Paradoxically, therefore, the Muslims' survival has always
depended on confrontation between Croats and Serbs; the moment this confrontation
ends, the division of the Muslim Bosnians between their two neighbours becomes
inevitable. <BR>
<BR>
The current American proposals resurrect old Bosnian territorial division
plans, with the Croat-Muslim federation receiving 51% of the land and the
Serbs the rest. The Serbs will be asked to give up territory around the
besieged Bosnian capital of Sarajevo. If the Serbs accept the plan, they
will be rewarded with the abolition of the international economic embargo
which cripples their country. If they reject it, more western air strikes
on Serb positions look inevitable and the re-arming of the Muslims may be
just around the corner. If the Muslims reject the proposals, they face the
withdrawal of UN forces from the republic and they will unable to count
on American assistance. In reality, the plan would satisfy nobody. <BR>
<BR>
The Serbs may be willing to settle: they have more territory than they need
and are desperately keen to break their international isolation. But why
should the Muslims accept such proposals now? In effect, the Americans are
expecting the Bosnians to become reconciled not only to a large loss of
territory, but also to becoming a Croat satellite. And significantly, the
Croats may be tempted by more war. The prize for the Muslims and Croats
is further conquests in western Bosnia, an area controlled by the Serbs.
<BR>
<BR>
If this takes place, Washington can do little: if the principle of liberating
and cleansing Serb-occupied territory is accepted in Croatia, why should
it not be acceptable now in Bosnia? The Croats and the Muslims are unlikely
to give up the struggle when they can get more by continuing to fight. The
idea of arming the Croats and Muslims just enough to defeat the Serbs, but
not too much - to leave the defeat incomplete - is something only
US strategists can conceive of from the comfort of their armchairs in Washington.
<BR>
<BR>
Since the war began the Americans have always sought to achieve a balance
of power in the Balkans. They have failed for a simple reason: the fighting
in Yugoslavia was not only about ethnic purity but also about land. Ethnic
cleansing on its own cannot sort out frontiers. The outlines of a deal are
in place: Serbia will have less land than it had, Croatia more than it envisaged
and Bosnian Muslim independence will remain a dream. But the dividing lines
between Serbs and Croats are unlikely to be settled by western diplomats.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Frustration in London and Paris </B><BR>
<BR>
There is worse to come. Britain and France, with the most peace-keeping
troops on the ground, are becoming increasingly frustrated by American and
German encouragement for the Croats. Sitting on the fence while the US supplies
weapons to one side for the fighting to continue is unappealing. More importantly,
the Russians still want to be taken seriously in the Balkans. <BR>
<BR>
The collective will of the EU has been exposed as a sham and so has the
UN's effort. Washington is now drafting peace plans without consulting people
in the region and it makes threats of force without any reference to the
UN. Everyone still talks about inviolable frontiers while, in practice,
proposing to carve up a state according to plans hurriedly scribbled by
diplomats on cigarette packets. <BR>
<BR>
On one issue, however, the Americans can still claim triumph: they have
positioned themselves as the ally of the Bosnian Muslims, not a bad position
for a government that wants to promote stability in the Islamic world at
large. But President Clinton's administration can succeed in brokering a
deal only if it rams its plans down Bosnia's throat. In the end, the US
will not be thanked for its efforts. <BR>
<BR>
A peace with honour is no longer achievable in the Balkans. Slowly, the
entire area is reverting to its history as a region where the bigger powers
support proxy wars, not because they have any interest in the natives but
because they have bigger scores to settle with each other. These are murky
waters which may tempt Islamic fundamentalists throughout the world. And
the chances are that such a gloomy scenario can no longer be avoided.<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
