<td valign=top>
<h2>
November/December 1995
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>
<H3>REVIEW</H3> 
<H2>Grave and profane </H2>
<H4>The Moor's Last Sigh </H4>
<I>by Salman Rushdie<BR>
Jonathan Cape, &#163;15.99 <BR>
<BR>
<B>Reviewed by Adel Darwish, The Independent</B></I><B> </B><BR>
<BR>
On this novel's very first page there is a subtle reference to the world-famous
predicament faced by the author, who is sometimes accused of needlessly
provoking the Ayatollah's death sentence for blasphemy imposed on him six
years ago, and still in force today. <BR>
<BR>
Describing the final flight of his protagonist Moraes (Moor) Zogoiby, in
a parallel story of the last leader to leave Moorish Spain, he writes in
one of many Lutheran references: &quot;When my pursuers have followed the
trail they'll find me waiting... Here I stand. Couldn't've done it differently.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
It is a small defiance: the bigger one is Rushdie's persistence in treating
controversial themes. Presenting his latest work to the public, he worked
hard to remind everyone that he is a novelist not a politician but Rushdie's
work was always imbued with a sharp awareness of political foibles. Before
the Islamic <I>fatwa</I>, the main criticism levelled at his work was at
its unreadability. It was always more accessible for those whose experience,
like that of this reviewer, was marked by the same mixed identities and
cultural transplantations. <BR>
<BR>
This newest work is fun to read, while keeping Rushdie's usual panoramic
style. In what has become his trademark, he has fun with the names of characters
who mirror real-life politicians. The book contains a ribald caricature
of Hindu fundamentalist Bal Thackeray, leader of the extremist (and worryingly
popular) party Shiv Sena and regarded by many as the unofficial ruler of
Bombay, Rushdie's city of birth. In the book Thackeray is named after another
English novelist, Fielding, and portrayed as a vicious and crazed stormtrooper
with a weakness for beautiful women. Bombay's Maharashtra state is considering
banning it. <BR>
<BR>
<I>The Moor's Last Sigh</I> is Rushdie's latest attempt to catch up with
Indian history since his first novel <I>Midnight's Children</I>, now rather
dated in its focus on Indira Gandhi's state of emergency in the mid-70s.
In a similar vein to Lord Byron's <I>Don Juan</I>, Rushdie mixes the gravest
of events with obscenities. While Byron produced an epic narrative of the
French revolution and the inception of the rights of man, his preoccupation
is with the Hindu/Muslim conflict. This bawdy approach to sacred events
banned Byron from civilised society and led Rushdie to experience fundamentalism
as a form of literary criticism. But the combination of the grave and the
profane remains the secret of both mens' brilliance and an essential tool
in interpreting human history. <BR>
<BR>
<I>The Moor's Last Sigh</I> traces the fate of a wealthy family of spice
merchants through the last century. Moor is the sole survivor of his line.
He is a baffled innocent who entered the world after only four and a half
months' gestation and is cursed to grow at double speed. At the age of 10
he is a strapping, fully grown man. At 36 he resembles an asthmatic 72-year-old.
A typically grotesque Rushdie hero, Moor's right hand is a deformed clubbed
fist. <BR>
<BR>
The central female character is of Catholic Portuguese blood yet Indian
in sentiment. The artist Aurora has children out of wedlock with an Indian
Jew dubbed with an Arab name. She could not have lived and survived in any
other age or continent but Rushdie's Bombay. Alongside Aurora, Bombay becomes
a living character. Like the traumatic love of one who adores a partner,
yet hates them when they do not live up to expectations, Rushdie himself
loves the city and can still hate it when corruption and violence blow it
apart. <BR>
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H2>Euro-whimsy </H2>
<H4>Winnie-the-Pooh on Management </H4>
<I>by Roger Allen<BR>
Methuen, &#163;6.95 </I>
<H4>Mind Your Manners </H4>
<I>by John Mole<BR>
Nicholas Brealey Publishing, &#163;9.99 <BR>
<BR>
<B>Reviewed by Andrew Clark</B></I><B> </B><BR>
<BR>
This is the final indignity for Pooh Bear, the much-loved children's character
created by English writer AA Milne. In <I>Winnie-the-Pooh on Management</I>,
a management consultant arrives to rationalise Pooh and his friends in the
Hundred Acre Wood. Pooh, by his own admission a &quot;Bear of Very Little
Brain&quot;, discovers how directionless he is and sets out on the road
to streamlining his activities which consist mainly of a search for his
favourite food, honey. Even his appearance gets a make-over from the image
consultants, to give him more authority as he supervises the activities
of Piglet and Tigger. <BR>
<BR>
Roger Allen's book is an attempt to present management theory in the simplest
possible way. According to him, study of Japanese management techniques
and zero-base budgeting have obscured the basic principles of effective
leadership. Pooh's consultant stresses the need for clarity of objectives
and sets universal guidelines for good leadership. Information should be
as clear and complete as possible, relevant to the person receiving it and
given in several different ways to ensure understanding. Always confirm that
the information has been absorbed, Allen advises, and remember that actions
speak louder than words. Pooh learns similar guidelines for motivation,
delegation, setting objectives, developing people and anticipating problems.
<BR>
<BR>
<I>Winnie-the-Pooh on Management</I> is lightly written and at times amusing
in a whimsical way. The advice can help clear an untidy mind and need not
only apply to business: it could be of use to any individual wanting to
organise a hectic private life. It is a common-sense introduction to those
who have rarely given a thought to the practice of management. And to CEOs
it could be a breath of fresh air, questioning all the assumptions which
can become blurred as a job becomes more complicated. <BR>
<BR>
The limitations of Pooh's common-sense approach are brought out in a new
edition of <I>Mind Your Manners</I>, an updated edition of John Mole's guide
to the different business cultures to be found in the members-states of
the European Union, a useful reference book for anyone expanding their business
in the region based on his own personal experiences. The guide devotes a
chapter to each country, explaining local decision-making practices, company
structures, etiquette and business-related legislation. <BR>
<BR>
Mole's description of an everyday business meeting provides clues to the
minefield that can await even the simplest task. A German will have studied
any briefing circulated before a meeting and will contribute only when he
or she feels qualified to do so: a Briton may have only glanced through
the briefing and will consider it normal for everyone to chip in with on-the-spot
suggestions on any topic. The French prefer an adversarial style, expecting
to be contradicted but also expecting to win the argument with logic and
rationality. But Spaniards will be desperately embarrassed at being contradicted
and will only speak if sure of their ground. In Portugal and Luxembourg,
meetings are for briefing and discussion only, whereas for the Dutch a meeting
which ends without a firm decision is a failure. Although these are stereotypes,
Mole argues that without understanding such details, firms cannot work together.
Common sense is not enough. <BR>
<BR>
There is a tendency to lapse into truisms in any survey of national characteristics
but Mole's book contains much solid information, including tips on when
humour is appropriate and when to be punctual. For a party at 7pm, for example,
polite guests in Japan may arrive an hour early and in Germany they will
come on the dot, while they will be 15 minutes late in Britain and arrive
close to midnight in Greece. <BR>
<BR>
Mole concludes by identifying two dimensions for firms and cultures. The
organisation as a mix ranges from the organic, in which the firm evolves
with little planning, to the systematic in which rigid, logically constructed
rules determine all business practices. The other dimension is leadership,
which ranges in style from individual and autocratic to group orientated,
consultative and flexible. He argues that the position of any firm can be
plotted on these two axes and guides us to where firms in each country are
likely to lie. <BR>
<BR>
Mole's map theory is simple but brings out the complexity and heterogeneity
existing in the world of management. Winnie the Pooh's theory is equally
simple but assumes that the world is as uncomplicated and friendly as the
Hundred-Acre Wood. <BR>
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H2>Germ warfare </H2>
<H4>The Coming Plague </H4>
<I>By Laurie Garrett<BR>
Farrar Straus Giroux, $25.00 <BR>
<BR>
<B>Reviewed by Lance Knobel <BR>
<BR>
</B>The Coming Plague</I> combines a series of remarkable adventure yarns,
scientific detective stories and carefully paced horror stories. Uniting
this unexpected amalgam is an urgent polemic directed at policymakers around
the world. Laurie Garrett persuasively and meticulously makes the case for
more attention - and money - to worldwide issues of public health
and what she terms microbial ecology. Garrett's plea is provoked by the
fact that in the competition between people and microbes, the microbes are
winning. <BR>
<BR>
As Nobel prizewinner and World Economic Forum fellow Joshua Lederberg says
in the book, &quot;We're not alone at the top of the food chain.&quot; Such
statements are on the surface sensational. But <I>The Coming Plague</I>,
despite its alarmist title, is not a sensationalist work. The power of Garrett's
argument comes from the evidence of cool research demonstrated, for example,
by 104 pages of footnotes. <BR>
<BR>
It is a difficult book at times, but it repays the reader with extraordinary
tales. At the centre are what Garrett calls the &quot;disease cowboys&quot;,
virologists and epidemiologists who at considerable personal risk go into
the field to track down a mysterious disease and find a cure. The cowboys
arrive in the Bolivian rainforest to deal with an outbreak of hemorrhagic
fever, in Liberia to confront Lassa fever and most dramatically in Zaire
to tackle Ebola. <BR>
<BR>
With limited resources, virtually no supporting infrastructure, in conditions
of enormous local tension and stress and not infrequently facing political
hostility, scientists like Karl Johnson, Joe McCormick, Peter Piot and Uwe
Brinkmann manage to hunt down disease vectors (the means of transmission),
collect and study blood samples and try, in the midst of everything, to
find ways to control outbreaks of at times horrifying illnesses. <BR>
<BR>
Such heroics fill roughly the first third of the book. The middle third
is concerned with the origins of Aids, which becomes a recurrent theme in
the final chapters. At first, the switch in focus is jarring. But for Garrett
and her scientific witnesses the global Aids epidemic is both the largest
current health challenge and a very visible example of the challenges humanity
faces with previously unknown diseases. <BR>
<BR>
The optimism that most infectious diseases could be eradicated worldwide
reigned well into the '60s and '70s in the health policymaking community.
Intelligent observers, according to Garrett, began to doubt the rosy predictions
as a host of diseases, from malaria to tuberculosis and measles, not only
persisted but became ever more serious problems as resistant strains evolved
to confound scientists. Aids marked the climactic puncturing of the optimists'
bubble. <BR>
<BR>
Low-end estimates of HIV infection rates in sub-Saharan Africa start at
20% of the population; many sober estimates push beyond 50%. The same pattern
is being repeated in parts of Asia, notably in Thailand and India. And the
stricken population is typically the most economically active portion. The
result is - or soon will be - monopolisation of already overstretched
health budgets and a dramatic impact on economic growth rates, trimming
up to several per cent a year from GDP growth. <BR>
<BR>
The World Health Organisation (WHO) predicts a total economic burden in
Thailand from Aids of $9 billion by the year 2000; the US Census Bureau
predicts that by 2010 Thailand will have 25 million fewer people than it
would have had without Aids. <BR>
<BR>
Despite this litany of grim statistics and even grimmer prognostications,
Garrett does offer possible solutions: a new understanding of the importance
of public health efforts and continuing improvements to basic health care,
sanitation and water supplies in the developing world. Garrett describes
other possible steps. What is shocking is their financial modesty. <BR>
<BR>
American physician Donald Henderson, who led the successful programme that
eradicated smallpox worldwide, has called for $150 million to be spent annually
for a surveillance network of 15 tropical outpost laboratories, staffed
by local health professionals and scientists from the US Centres for Disease
Control (CDC) in preference to the UN's WHO, which Henderson considers hopelessly
bureaucratic. <BR>
<BR>
In October this year, the WHO finally agreed to set up an early-warning
system and rapid reaction force. The plan echoes many of Garrett's suggestions.
Let us hope her strictures about the UN body's inefficiencies prove false.
<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
