<tr>
<td>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<h2>
November/December 1995
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>
<H3>WORLD ECONOMIC FORUM</H3> 
<H2>Forum insights</H2>
<BR>
<B>The World Economic Forum is today the foremost international membership
organization integrating leaders from business, government and academia
into a partnership committed to improving the state of the world. It provides
a platform for interaction that is direct, efficient, global and personalised
on the highest level. <BR>
The World Economic Forum is a foundation serving the global public interest.
It is independent, impartial and not-for-profit, tied to no political, partisan
or regional interests.</B><BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3>Members day </H3>
Usually an anniversary is a time to reflect on the past. Not so for the World
Economic Forum. Our first ever Members Day, which took place in late August,
proved the perfect opportunity to share with our members the vision that
will be guiding the Forum during the next quarter century. About 100 member
companies from around the world were represented during the two-day event,
mixing in genuine Forum fashion some very serious work with equally memorable
cultural and social highlights. 
<H3>Four principal strategies for the future </H3>
Klaus Schwab, founder and President of the World Economic Forum, focused
during the working session on four principal strategies. <BR>
<BR>
<B>1. The digital information and communication revolutions: WELCOM</B>
<BR>
<BR>
The natural evolution for the Forum - after becoming the world leader
in face-to-face, personalised, high level networking - is to lead our
members into the age of digital, virtual interaction and to create an exclusive
global WELCOM (<B>W</B>orld <B>El</B>ectronic <B>Com</B>munity). This will
strengthen our position as the world leader in high-level peer interaction.
<BR>
<BR>
In its design philosophy, services and custom features, WELCOM will go far
beyond the technical attractiveness of standard desk-top, on-line systems.
It will integrate personal video communication technology with data-conferencing
features that will allow members to improve dramatically the quality of
their dialogue with peers and to access a range of high value-added information.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>2. Added value and strength of purpose will reinforce global networking</B><BR>
<BR>
Creating a network is one thing, sustaining it with meaningful content is
another. Over the last 25 years we have been pioneers in building global
communities. These communities are now well established and interact regularly
(at the moment through meetings, later also through WELCOM). On a number
of fronts, the Forum intends to increase the quality of its work, and an
important focus will be to maintain and improve the calibre of our permanent
staff. To be truly at the cutting edge of new thinking, for example we will
continue our Forum Fellows programme so that the network includes the world's
leading authorities on all subjects of interest to our members - the
global business community. <BR>
<BR>
<B>3. Twin pillars of membership <BR>
<BR>
</B>We have already established a core group of members that represent the
1000 foremost global enterprises. Taking into account that the global economy
is increasingly influenced by more nimble, niche-oriented companies, we have
begun building a second pillar of membership: the Global Growth Companies.
GGCs are distinguished by their high growth rates, global thinking and critical
mass (roughly US$ 100-750 million in turnover) which already make them key
players in their industries and regions. They are the companies active in
the industries of tomorrow (such as information technologies), hidden champions
(innovative firms in mature industries) and emerging market pioneers. GGCs
will have an annual meeting each year at the Industry Summit and will of
course be key participants in WELCOM. <BR>
<BR>
<B>4. A members-driven foundation</B> <BR>
<BR>
The first twenty-five years of the World Economic Forum were, without doubt,
founder-driven; the challenge now is to transform the organisation into
one which institutionalises the role of our member companies. Thus, in addition
to strengthening the Executive Board as the main managerial instrument of
the foundation, we will create the Council of the World Economic Forum,
to include some of the most prominent chief executives of our member companies.
<H3>Mixing work with pleasure </H3>
The highly interactive working session led to much feedback and reactions,
and a lively debate followed. With a number of useful suggestions from our
members, the Forums Executive Board was able to refine these strategies.
<BR>
<BR>
The afternoon was spent with a brief visit to the Bodmeriana Library in
Cologny, one of the world's most extensive private collections of rare and
antique books, and visits to the European Organisation for Nuclear Research
(CERN) and the new World Trade Organisation (WTO). High level, Forum-style
discussions took place with leaders of both organisations. <BR>
<BR>
A special dinner that evening marked the occasion, gathering members and
their spouses, heads of Geneva-based international organisations and the
local Geneva state councillors. The next day a sightseeing tour of some
of the local Swiss sites, such as the Chateau de Chillon and the cheese-making
village of Gruyeres capped an event which the World Economic Forum was proud
to dedicate to its core constituency, the chief executives of its member
companies. <BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3>1995 Europe/East Asia Economic Summit Singapore 20-22 September 1995
</H3>
There were fewer criticisms from both sides in the World Economic Forum
1995 Europe/East Asia Summit, noted former French Prime Minister Raymond
Barre at the closing session of the fourth annual economic summit. <BR>
<BR>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister Amnuay Viravan did remark that Europe should
&quot;listen to the market rather than attempt to prop up industries that
are no longer competitive&quot;. But references to &quot;fortress&quot;
Europe, on the whole, were hardly heard in this year's summit. <BR>
<BR>
Perhaps East Asia and Europe have come to a better understanding of one
another since last year's summit. <BR>
<BR>
The final proposal read out by Mr Barre called on the two sides to broaden
their political dialogue - including on issues like social and human
rights. But it emphasised that the dialogue &quot;should be based on the
principles of strict non-interference in domestic affairs and mutual respect.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
East Asia, however, continued to urge for stronger ties with Europe. &quot;Singapore
would like to see Asia's links with Europe increased,&quot; said Prime Minister
Goh Chok Tong in a keynote address. &quot;They will never be as close as
the links between Europe and the North but they can be better than now.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Asian leaders, in particular, would like to see the first Asia-Europe Meeting
(ASEM) in Thailand next year develop in parallel with the Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation forum (APEC) to promote global free trade. European Commission's
Vice-President Leon Brittan agreed: &quot;Above all, Asia and Europe have
the same trade and investment agenda. This must be the bedrock of our continued
relationship.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Indonesia's President Soeharto reaffirmed his country's commitment to free
trade and gave added assurance to Europeans that Indonesia would not exclude
them from the gains of its tariff reductions. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Some of Asia's most important economic partners lie outside (APEC)
or AFTA (Asean Free Trade Area),&quot; he said. &quot;More than 15 per cent
of Indonesia's exports went to Europe in 1994, while Europe accounted for
roughly 20 per cent of our imports and foreign investments. As a result,
Indonesia adhered to the most favoured nation principle in all our reduction
to trade barriers and urged others to follow.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Vice-President Manuel Marin of the European Commission went a step further
to push for more comprehensive ties, involving citizens, businessmen, researchers
and students. &quot;The Asia-Europe Meeting of spring 1996 will be a historical
occasion enhancing our mutual understanding, but no amount of policy dialogue
can replace solid economic and cultural links,&quot; he said. <BR>
<BR>
He noted that the EU was already working on two significant linkage projects:
<BR>
<BR>
* A high-level cultural forum which would gather 30 Asian and 30 European
intellectuals to discuss philosophy, religion, technological and cultural
exchanges and managerial approaches. <BR>
<BR>
* A pilot exchange programme for 1,000 young Europeans and Asean managers.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We can create the framework and provide the impetus, but the actual
construction of a working partnership can only be based on the efforts of
our people,&quot; Mr Marin said. <BR>
<BR>
Norwegian Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland, in her address at the opening
dinner, said that efforts are being made in Europe to better understand
Asia. But she added: &quot;As much as we Europeans must learn more about
Asia, Asian countries should reflect on what they can do to explain better
the roots of their own cultures and why it is, and what it is, that makes
us different.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
East Asians also want Europe to step up its presence in the region, especially
in the area of investments. &quot;No major European MNC can afford to be
left out of the dynamic growth in East Asia, Singapore's Senior Minister
Lee Kuan Yew said in his keynote address. &quot;The next 30 years will witness
a Pacific revival, a renaissance.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Mr Lee also made a case in geo-political terms: &quot;Europe's participation
(in East Asia) will reduce the economic impact of any China-US turbulence
in the rest of the region.&quot; European companies' willingness to impart
technology would give them an edge over Japanese rivals in East Asia, he
said. <BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3>Regional Activities India Meeting </H3>
<H4>New Delhi, 3-5 December 1995 in partnership with the Confederation of
Indian Industry (CII) </H4>
<I>India: an economic giant in the making</I> India is now a priority partner
for international investors with its dynamic and buoyant private sector,
with expanding infrastructure needs and a growing, quality-demanding middle
class. Our meeting will focus on four areas of primary importance for business
activity in India: the economic, financial and social situation; the growing
importance of Indian states in promoting business activities; the most promising
industry sectors for foreign and domestic investment; contact with senior
policy-making officials in boardroom-style meetings. Also on the agenda will
be India's position at the heart of a revived South Asian trading bloc and
an emerging Ocean Rim economic grouping. <BR>
<BR>
We shall also assess the political situation of the country following the
reverses that the ruling Congress Party has recently suffered in State Elections
and the outlook for the general elections which will take place before June
1996.<BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%> 
<H3>For your 1996 agenda </H3>
<H4>The Industry Summit, <BR>
Chicago, 12-14 May 1996 <BR>
<BR>
Southern Africa Economic Summit, <BR>
Cape Town, 22-24 May 1996 <BR>
<BR>
Mercosur Economic Summit, <BR>
Buenos Aires, 23-25 June 1996 <BR>
<BR>
Central/Eastern Europe Economic Summit, <BR>
7-9 July 1996 <BR>
<BR>
Europe/East Asia Economic Summit, <BR>
Hong Kong, 16-18 October 1996 </H4>
In addition, the 1996 Middle East/North Africa Economic Summit will take
place during the autumn. 
<H3>1996 Annual Meeting of the World Economic Forum </H3>
<H4>Davos, 1-6 February </H4>
As in past years, the goal of the Annual Meeting will be to define, at the
beginning of the new year, corporate, national, regional and international
priorities, and set forth an action agenda for business and governments
world-wide. The Annual Meeting will once again be hosting the chief executives
of its member companies, many heads of state and other political leaders,
as well as numerous scientific, economic and business academics and experts.
<BR>
<BR>
This year's Annual Meeting will focus on the complex relations between man,
mankind and markets. Discussions will address the many pressing issues facing
the individual, as well as the global business and policy-making community.
Specific topics will include the growing inequality brought about by our
information society, the changing nature of employment, the increasing concern
over personal, regional and global security systems. Also planned are a
number of intellectually stimulating and philosophical treks into the essence
of life and its very foundations. 
<H3>1996 Industry Summit </H3>
<H4>Chicago, 12-14 May </H4>
The World Economic Forum's on-campus gathering of corporate and entrepreneurial
leaders, tapping the world's foremost knowledge on industry, management
and technology issues hosted by the University of Chicago in collaboration
with Northwestern University and the Chicago Council on Foreign Relations.
<BR>
<BR>
Many corporate leaders recognise that we are entering an increasingly fast-moving
business environment where <I>knowledge</I> will be the key and where the
ability to find, understand and act on the most relevant knowledge will make
the difference between success and failure. To provide these leaders with
a highly time-efficient way to explore the latest knowledge connected with
their industries, the World Economic Forum created the Industry Summit concept.
<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

