<h2>
November/December 1995
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>
<H3>TIME OUT</H3> 

<H2>The real high-fliers </H2>
<H4>Time, trust and a love of nature are the rare qualities needed for the
lofty sport of falconry</H4>
<I>By Daniel Butler </I><BR>
<BR>
&quot;Falconry and Zen Buddhism are the two most important influences on
my attitude to life,&quot; pronounces Yvon Chouinard, president of the Californian-based
company Patagonia, a leading manufacturer of sports equipment and leisurewear.
The mountaineer-turned-businessman, aged 57, does not bat an eyelid as he
makes this surprising statement. &quot;From these, I learned infinite patience
and that reward is the only motivation,&quot; he adds seriously. <BR>
<BR>
Forget golf and squash, advises Chouinard, get hooked on hawks. He is not
alone; this ancient sport which harnesses the bird's natural hunting abilities
has a dedicated global following, notably in central Asia, Europe and the
US. Its greatest exponents, however, are found in the Arab world, where
for many urban Bedouins the traditional desert hawking safari or <I>shikar</I>
is a vital link with a lost nomadic past. <BR>
<BR>
Indeed, for many Arabs gifts of falcons and accessories are still an important
part of doing business, as British craftsman Martin Jones readily testifies:
&quot;Half my furniture [falconry equipment] goes to the Gulf.&quot; Ornate
hoods, used to pacify the birds, comprise the bulk of his orders. He also
sells made-to-measure gloves, special perches and radio-tracking devices,
useful for birds which can fly at 80kph on the flat and well over 200kph
in a dive. <BR>
<BR>
Such telemetry is a rare 20th century intrusion into a sport which dates
from China's Hia dynasty, circa 2200BC. From here it spread westwards, reaching
Babylon by 1700BC and becoming popular in Europe in about the 9th century
AD. For the next millennium, until reliable firearms supplanted it, falconry
was one of the most efficient forms of hunting. <BR>
<BR>
But its appeal was always much more than a means of filling the pot. Birds
of prey or raptors are powerful symbols. The Athenians adopted the owl as
their mascot, which explains its undeserved association with wisdom. Attila
the Hun destroyed the Roman Empire with a goshawk on his helmet. Others
harnessed the image in heraldry. Both the Habsburgs and Romanovs, for example,
took the double-headed eagle as their symbol while the US uses the bald
eagle. <BR>
<BR>
Falconry reinforced these images, its social cachet underlined when the
Holy Roman Emperor Frederick II wrote the first treatise on the subject
in 1247. At about the same time Richard the Lionheart went on crusade with
300 hawks, providing his warriors with something to do during sieges. As
late as the 18th century, Catherine the Great was a devotee of lark hawking.
Although the sport subsequently declined, peregrines were used successfully
during both the 1871 siege of Paris and World War Two to intercept messenger
pigeons - an early version of Internet hacking. Even today some airforces
use them to discourage other birds from the runway, where they may collide
expensively and dangerously with jet engines. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Fed up and in a bate </B><BR>
<BR>
Perhaps unsurprisingly, a sport which dominated European culture for so
long has left its mark on the English language. A bate, for example, is
a hawk's tantrum. To gorge comes from the French for throat, since a hawk's
crop is located in the neck which swells as it eats. But perhaps the most
common expression is &quot;fed up&quot;. A replete human is neither grumpy
nor bored, but full of bonhomie. Similarly, a hawk which has eaten will
be contented but the impact of this on its bond with the falconer is dramatic.
A bird which is fed up loses its appetite and the incentive to please its
trainer. It wants to find a lofty perch where it can digest in peace, ignoring
the frustrated whistles from below. <BR>
<BR>
Some of the terms can be confusing, however. For example, a hawk is a general
term covering any raptor but also specifically refers to true hawks such
as the Japanese favourite, the goshawk. True hawks live in forests and are
characterised by their short wings. In contrast a falcon is one of the long-winged
high-flyers which hunt over open ground such as the peregrine, merlin or
saker. To the outsider such distinctions may seem pedantic, but they are
critical to falconers. True hawks are the workhorses of falconry: early
writers dubbed the goshawk as the cook's bird thanks to its rapacious skill.
But it is the speed, height and power of a falcon which makes it the ultimate
hunting bird. <BR>
<BR>
Whatever the type, the principles are the same. Controlling the bird's diet
has always remained the key. Where other primitive hunting practices now
seem barbaric, falconry's underlying principle is a kind of social contract.
Food is the key with which the wild bird is coaxed into accepting the presence
of man, then goaded to eat on the fist, before gradually being persuaded
to fly to the falconer for food. The bird is never punished - meat
is merely withheld until it behaves correctly. This is what Chouinard means
by &quot;reward as the only motivation&quot;. Eventually trust is established
for the hawk to fly free while the falconer flushes quarry for it. <BR>
<BR>
What this reward might be depends on the hawk and the locality. For the
Arabs nothing beats houbara, a goose-sized desert bird, as a target for
saker falcons. In Europe catching red grouse with peregrines is the sport's
pinnacle, while in central Asia it is traditional to hunt foxes and wolves
on horseback with eagles. Nor should one forget the US, where enthusiasts
hand-rear chicks to establish parent-child relationships and organise competitions
where the birds win points for speed and style. <BR>
<BR>
Persuading a wild loner like a hawk to co-operate with the human requires
infinite patience, a point which explains Chouinard's philosophical claim.
In his case falconry helped to determine the whole course of his life, beginning
with the time when he played truant as a youth to climb cliffs in search
of prairie falcons (even well-trained hawks revert rapidly to the wild and
losses are high). From this he became hooked on mountaineering, only to
find his expertise outstripping the available equipment. In frustration
he began to make his own and the rest, as they say, is history. <BR>
<BR>
Although the hawks are neither scarce nor expensive, and the cost of equipment
negligible, the patience needed for falconry makes it a hobby of the affluent.
A pair or cast of peregrines are together worth only about $1,000, for example.
But to fly them at grouse one needs a good moor, obedient dogs and, crucially,
time. Hawks need at least two weeks to become fit. Serious falconers spend
two months hunting, during which use of the moor alone can be hugely expensive.
When time is money, few can afford such a long break. <BR>
<BR>
Such fanatics do exist, however. One committed group of Italian peregrine
enthusiasts makes an annual summer pilgrimage to Scotland, while a band
of Germans flies eagles at east European hares each winter. But pride of
place goes to the Arabs, who still approach falconry in the same style as
the medieval kings of Europe. A serious <I>shikar</I> involves dozens of
falcons, handlers, jeeps and tents and can last for months, deep in a desert
anywhere between Pakistan and Algeria. <BR>
<BR>
The sport is also rare in offering a modern outdoor pastime which is environmentally
beneficial. Unlike most field sports it depends completely on both prey
and predators. Thus its practitioners have always been among the most passionate
conservationists, in marked contrast to shooting or fishing enthusiasts.
Just as medieval kings penalised disturbances at hawk's nests, there are
modern equivalents. <BR>
<BR>
The Abu Dhabi royal family spends heavily on conservation, for example.
Last year its National Avian Research Centre released 123 satellite-tagged
Khazak sakers, of which one was followed to Kenya. The same centre also
funded a study of Pakistani luggers, useless for falconry, which are endangered.
And it was US falconers who first noticed the devastating impact of agricultural
pesticides on peregrines and then bred birds in captivity. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Breeding hybrids in captivity </B><BR>
<BR>
Such projects have revolutionised this, the most traditional of sports.
Until recently all hawks came from the wild: either as chicks from a nest,
as in Europe, or adult birds captured while migrating, as preferred by the
Arabs. A dramatic drop in wild populations 30 years ago forced falconers
to turn to captive-breeding. This soon led to the production of hybrids:
mating two species to produce a bird which does not occur in the wild. Falconers
found that such youngsters could often out-perform their parents when they
combined, for example, the high-flying of the traditional European peregrine
with the size and power of an Arab saker. <BR>
<BR>
The results have impressed even the Abu Dhabi royal family, a former bastion
of traditional falconry. The family now funds a New Zealander, Nick Fox,
to produce hybrids to order in Britain, since it is too hot for falcons
to breed successfully in the Gulf. <BR>
<BR>
Once a year he boards a specially chartered plane with 50 young hybrids
in tow: &quot;There's one handler to every two birds, so it's quite a procession
across the tarmac!&quot; he says. <BR>
<BR>
Regardless of hawk, region or quarry, should you be lucky enough to be invited
to watch this sport, seize the opportunity. This is corporate entertainment
at its most spectacular: only a philistine could remain impervious to the
sight of a hawk in hot pursuit. Sadly, such an experience is likely to be
only too fleeting. The pressures of modern life mean few of us will find
our lives as revolutionised as Patagonia's Chouinard.  <p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
