<tr>
<td>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<h2>
November/December 1995
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 
<H3>BACKSEAT</H3>
<H4>Charles Darwent peers through his windows at the murky world of business
espionage </H4>
The more observant among <I>Backseat</I>'s readers may have been aware of
the launch of a new product by an American computer software company, intended
to corner the world market in systems or programs or whatever it is that
makes personal computers gobble up 8,000 words of finely honed prose seconds
before you remember to press the save button. <BR>
<BR>
To describe this product launch as epic is scarcely to exaggerate. The chairman
of the corporation that had wrought this wonder was proclaimed by the evangelists
of the world's press as a new messiah. <BR>
<BR>
The software, meanwhile, was the stuff of which miracles are born. If it
could not actually help the lame to walk or the blind to see, its allegedly
foolproof format could allow even journalists on bimonthly magazines to
master the arcana of downloading or up-booting or whatever else might be
required of them in this post-carbon-paper world. It was also rumoured to
make a mean gazpacho. <BR>
<BR>
So loud, indeed, was the jingling noise of the world press caravanserai
that one minor facet of this heart-warming story somehow came to be overlooked.
For all the obvious desirabilities of the new gospel of plug 'n' play -
computeristes would seem to be painfully susceptible to the charms of alliteration
- a peculiarly similar product was already on the market. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Waiter, there's a download in my soup </B><BR>
<BR>
The search for a personal computerspeak that could be mastered by those
without post-doctoral degrees in Sanskrit had been largely pioneered by
a rival US company during the preceding decade. A series of economic reverses
had simply meant that the digital David in question could not afford (as
could the new messiah) the billion or so dollars needed to bring these joyous
tidings to all the world by dint of buying up the entire daily print-run
of selected national newspapers. It was left to the syndicated US cartoonist
Garry Trudeau to mention the unmentionable. In the seditious words of <I>Doonesbury</I>
the gospel of plug 'n' play was nothing new. <BR>
<BR>
One senses that, whatever his artistic talents, Mr Trudeau may not have
attended one of the better business schools. Had he done so, he would have
realised the laughable na&iuml;vety of his satire. The barbs aimed at alleged
plagiarists missed the mark. There is a more sophisticated idiom favoured
by those sensitive graduates of Cambridge, Mass, Fontainebleau and Stanford
to describe the process of profiting from other people's hard work. That
idiom is &quot;gathering competitor intelligence&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
For those na&iuml;fs, like Mr Trudeau, who may find the difference between
the two concepts bewilderingly slight, help is at hand. A new <I>Financial
Times</I> book, <I>Perfectly Legal Competitor Intelligence</I> (a title
that may in itself strike the uninitiated as exuding a distant whiff of
illegality) defines intelligence-gathering in the world of business as: &quot;A
process that transforms disaggregated competitor data into actionable strategic
knowledge about competitors' capabilities, intentions, performance and position&quot;.
<BR>
<BR>
From this you will see that any initial resemblance between what MBA lecturers
call competitor intelligence (CI to <I>aficionados</I>) and what your teacher
at school will quaintly have termed &quot;cheating&quot; is entirely coincidental.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Term prize for peeping </B><BR>
<BR>
Had you, during those laughably illogical days of childhood, been caught
peeping over the shoulder of your neighbour during Latin lessons, you might
well have expected to be rewarded with a rap across the knuckles and 100
lines on the virtuous nature of Lars Porsena of Clusium. Do so during your
MBA finals, and you will presumably find yourself clapped warmly on the
back by your college principal and awarded a term prize for imaginative
disaggregated data gathering. <BR>
<BR>
It will be a useful addition to your CV, for garnering competitor intelligence
is not merely a question of feeding off big business. In this year of grace,
CI has become big business of its own. According to a survey by security
consultants Control Risks, an unwitting 70% of western firms have had apparently
confidential information gathered from them in the past 12 months. <BR>
<BR>
This of course suggests that a further and entirely witting 70% of firms
will have paid for the information to be gathered in the first place. Since
there is presumably what we Venn diagramistes call a high degree of overlap
between the two groups, and since the cost of gathering intelligence from
others while simultaneously ensuring that none is gathered from oneself
may, for a major transnational, run into many millions of dollars annually,
bemused readers of <I>Perfectly Legal etc</I> may find themselves wondering
why companies do not just agree to come clean with their disaggregated data
and have done with it. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Gingrich and embroidery </B><BR>
<BR>
Since this is about as likely as to happen as Mr Newt Gingrich taking up
<I>petit point</I>, it might at least seem reasonable to ask why CI is not
more rigorously policed. Disaggregated data does not aggregate itself spontaneously.
<BR>
<BR>
Cracking down on the balaclava'd middlemen who arrange the involuntary transfer
of data might well provide members of national security services -- masters
at espionage, and with considerable time on their hands since the decease
of the Cold War - with something useful to do. <BR>
<BR>
A recent classified advertisement in <I>The</I> <I>Economist</I> may provide
an answer. Placed by a corporation claiming to &quot;want to be representative
of America&quot;, the ad offers &quot;the Ultimate Overseas Career&quot;
to &quot;candidates with strong interpersonal skills&quot;. These eager
candidates must also be able to demonstrate &quot;a burning interest in
international business&quot;. And is this champion of American free enterprise
General Motors? The Coca-Cola Corporation? Not quite. The advertisement
in question was placed by the Central Intelligence Agency. <p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
