<!--May 1996-->
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
EMWL: World Link Magazine:January/February 1996
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<!--START_TAG_SPACE-->
<!--00018800 Japan -->
<!--00003000 Management Theory -->
<!--END_TAG_SPACE-->
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="7C1568" text="000000" link="7C1568">

<center>
<font size=3>
<table border=0>
<tr>
<td colspan=2 align=left>
<nobr>
<img width=199 height=44 name="top" border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../images/conban8.gif" alt="World Link Magazine"><a href="../../../../../index.html"><img width=141 height=45 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../../images/conban1.gif" alt="EMWL Home"></a>
</nobr>
<br>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<h2>
January/February 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra14.gif" alt="Davos 1996">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>
<H2>HOW BUSINESS CAN HELP JAPAN </H2>
<H4>BY SOICHIRO TOYODA </H4>
Japan is finally beginning to come to terms with the serious economic issues
that it faces. Economic growth has been less than 1% a year for the past
three years. Personal consumption has been weak and so has capital spending.
Japan's unemployment rate has reached 3.2%, not high by European standards
but in Japan the highest level since records began. Another big problem
is that of bad loans and financial scandals. <BR>
<BR>
These problems have obscured the fundamental strength of the Japanese economy,
so our most pressing job is to reaffirm that strength and to get the economy
growing again. An economically healthier Japan will be a better partner
for Europe, better able to cooperate actively and effectively in pursuing
common interests both with Europe and around the world. <BR>
<BR>
Following pressure from the powerful <I>keidanren</I> industrial associations
and other members of the private sector, the government is taking strong
action. Since 1992 it has pushed through six packages of fiscal stimuli,
including a 45 trillion yen [$44.5 billion]<B> </B>increase in spending
on public works projects. The latest package, announced in September, is
the biggest of its kind ever implemented in Japan. It includes 8 trillion
yen in fiscal measures that will generate real demand within one year and
promises to make a significant contribution to economic recovery. <BR>
<BR>
An economic upturn will get under way gradually this year if the government
implements these fiscal measures fully. Production will increase in some
sectors and capital spending and personal consumption will begin to recover.
This, of course, assumes that the yen does not appreciate again to a ridiculous
level: Japan's recovery would falter if the yen went back to the absurd
level it reached last April. Indeed, the Japanese government cannot solve
the problem alone. The monetary authorities in leading nations must work
together to maintain stable exchange rates. <BR>
<BR>
In the meantime Japan's government and banks are working out a plan for
dealing with the problem of bad loans. They are beginning with measures
for reorganising the so-called <I>Jusen</I> lenders. These are the large
institutions which were supposed to specialise in home loans but which are
now in trouble through unwise lending. Clearly, this crisis needs to be
resolved sooner rather than later or it will only get worse. <BR>
<BR>
We industrialists of the <I>keidanren</I> are in favour of using public
money to help resolve the crisis, but support this measure only to the extent
necessary to protect depositors at failed banks. The banking system has
more than enough liquidity overall to cover bad loans: indeed, if they wished,
some of the bigger banks could write off all their bad loans at once. In
that sense the Daiwa Bank scandal, which notched up trading losses of $1.1
billion<B> </B>last autumn and cast doubt on the stability of all Japanese
banks, happened at an especially bad time. But we must remember that this
scandal had nothing to do with the problem of bad loans. <BR>
<BR>
Japan's banks and financial authorities need to move ahead with concrete
measures to restore confidence in our financial system. There should be
a focus on disclosure and transparency, giving top priority to letting the
market mechanism work. That includes the radical step of making all participants
fully responsible for the consequences of their business and financial decisions.
<BR>
<BR>
These may all be individual issues, but they represent part of a much larger
challenge for Japan. The country must first become a more pleasant place
to live and second a more attractive place for international companies to
do business. Of course Japan is the second biggest economy in the world,
but that growth has not brought a corresponding improvement in Japanese
lifestyle. The country needs a major shift in its economic and social life.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>A vision that encompasses the world </B><BR>
<BR>
At the <I>keidanren</I>, we are drawing up proposals to bring about that
kind of shift. People in the private sector, in academia and in the arts
must work together to shape a more fulfilling social framework, a society
where people in all walks of life can participate freely and actively. <BR>
<BR>
Our vision must encompass the world and the place of Japan in the world
and we must work with the industrialised nations of Europe and North America
to build and maintain a global framework for peace and prosperity. We must
share our skills and resources freely in tackling global issues with those
nations and in supporting sustainable development. To do this Japan needs
to become more open. The biggest obstacle to this is the over-regulation
of the Japanese economy. <BR>
<BR>
As a chairman of <B>a</B> <I>keidanren</I>, I have made deregulation my
highest priority. We cannot revitalise our economy and build a globally
viable nation without drawing fully on the energy of the private sector.
We must tap that energy by clearing away regulations that stand in the way
of healthy private sector activity and we must encourage venture capital
to nurture new industries and markets. Regulation must give way to the free
market and government must give way to the private sector. <BR>
<BR>
Deregulation is the key both to Japan fulfilling its international responsibilities
and to revitalising its economy. It will make Japan more open to foreign
products and investment and will create business opportunities for companies
around the world. <BR>
<BR>
The Japanese government took a step forward in March when it announced a
five-year programme to eliminate or relax regulations on over 1,000 items.
This is already opening up the market and making life easier for Japanese
consumers. It took a further step forward when it accelerated that programme
to take place over three years: under the new timetable, almost two-thirds
of the measures will be in place by the end of this fiscal year. <BR>
<BR>
A relaxation of rules on acquiring cellular telephones, for example, has
led to explosive growth in that market and further deregulation is on the
way. Japan is moving to deregulate domestic airfares which will bring fares
down to levels close to those in other nations. In another sector, the government
will eliminate restrictions on retail price competition in over-the-counter
health products. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Still too many restrictions on market access </B><BR>
<BR>
The present three-year programme is a step forward, but only one step: we
need to review and expand it each year. The present measures do not go nearly
far enough in the finance and agriculture sectors and still leave too many
restrictions on pricing and market access. Those restrictions reflect the
false belief that the state should be responsible for managing the balance
between supply and demand. People in Europe and North America have expressed
their concern that deregulation in Japan could founder in the face of bureaucratic
opposition and a lack of political leadership. They have good cause for
concern but can rest assured that the private sector will do everything
possible to make sure deregulation moves ahead. <BR>
<BR>
That brings me to the issue of Euro-Japanese relations. The EU is the most
advanced in a series of regional economic groupings that have taken shape
in the world. These groupings can help promote free trade and investment,
as long as we all remain committed to multilateral free trade. The EU and
Japan share a strong common interest in strengthening the system of world
trade through the World Trade Organisation and should work together to coordinate
regional initiatives with its larger goals and guidelines. <BR>
<BR>
The US-Japan car industry talks earlier this year reminded me of the importance
of Japan's partnership with Europe. European nations exercised a good influence
on those negotiations, speaking forcefully about the importance of free
trade when the US government threatened unilateral sanctions. We must work
to resolve business issues in the private sector and keep them from becoming
political. <BR>
<BR>
Some of my European friends have suggested that Japan concentrates too much
on the US. I think we will see a better balance in Japan's international
relations as we cultivate closer ties with Europe at the corporate and industry
level. And we can improve that balance still further by promoting equally
vigorous exchanges in non-business sectors such as science, education and
culture. <BR>
<BR>
In all our cooperation, we should be careful to maintain a global perspective.
Reinforcing the WTO framework will depend heavily on promoting free trade
and investment in the Asia Pacific region where countries continue to display
the most dynamic growth in the world, driven by trade and investment among
private companies. It is free and vigorous economic activity that transcends
national borders. <BR>
<BR>
Members of Apec [the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum] reaffirmed
their commitment to free and open trade and investment last October in Osaka.
They drew up a plan for implementing the Bogor Declaration, which aims to
help open markets completely by the year 2010 in the industrialised economies
and by the year 2020 in the developing economies. Apec is a loose regional
grouping led by the private sector, completely open to all nations in all
other regions. Its purpose is to improve the business environment for private-sector
companies and Japan needs to lead the way. The most important consideration
is to translate prosperity and progress in the Asia Pacific region into
progress for the entire world. I hope that Apec members can develop a dialogue
with European nations and the EU's executive Commission. I hope they can
work together on a framework and rules for multilateral trade and investment
in the context of the World Trade Organisation. <p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

