<HEAD>
<TITLE>
EMWL: World Link Magazine:January/February 1996
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="7C1568" text="000000" link="7C1568">

<center>
<font size=3>
<table border=0>
<tr>
<td colspan=2 align=left>
<nobr>
<img width=199 height=44 name="top" border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../images/conban8.gif" alt="World Link Magazine"><a href="../../../../../index.html"><img width=141 height=45 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../../images/conban1.gif" alt="EMWL Home"></a>
</nobr>
<br>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<h2>
January/February 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra14.gif" alt="Davos 1996">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>

<H2>WHY THE WORLD NEEDS UNIONS </H2>
<B>BY BILL JORDAN </B><BR><BR>
The world has changed beyond recognition in the last few years for everyone,
but especially for trade unions and business. In the late '70s two-thirds
of the world's population lived in economies shielded from the risks - and
potential benefits - of international trade and investment. By 2000, the
World Bank estimates that perhaps only a tenth of the world's workers will
be outside the economic mainstream. <BR>
<BR>
This new world economy, undergoing what is sometimes termed globalisation,
has not been kind to ordinary working people. Many have lost their jobs
and the security they enjoyed in the battle for new markets. <BR>
<BR>
How quickly people forget. Everyone remembers the fall of the Berlin Wall
in 1989 and the sense of liberation in Europe which then spread out across
the rest of the world. But few recall the wave of strikes the previous summer
and autumn, when the Polish trade union movement Solidarity re-emerged from
years of repression to lead talks which led to the first genuine elections
in a Soviet bloc country for 50 years. Solidarity has good reason to claim
that its members helped make the world safe for business. <BR>
<BR>
Trade unions have been heading the pressure for change throughout the world,
from Chile to Korea and Romania to Zambia. Yet many feel betrayed, because
their newly elected governments are unable to tackle the huge backlog of
urgent social problems without the approval of a handful of Washington-based
technocrats. Participation in the international economy, with all the conditions
set by the IMF and other institutions, limits the ability of governments
to negotiate with trade unions. <BR>
<BR>
In the wealthier countries, unions face governments that blame the pressures
of international finance for their inability to enter into real dialogue
over key issues like the social security system or public service pay and
jobs. The jargon of convergence criteria, interest and exchange rates and
the public deficit boils down to the fact that finance ministers have become
mere proxies for market sentiment. <BR>
<BR>
Although unions have found it more difficult to make their presence felt,
the problems they pinpoint still remain. The world's new and sometimes triumphalist
economic elite has allowed social and political tensions to fester. Old
and new frustrations are fusing, creating fertile ground for extremist politicians
to launch populist and economically illiterate campaigns. These often include
disturbing racist and xenophobic overtones which undermine both democracy
and international cooperation. <BR>
<BR>
Globalisation is not only changing the relationship between workers and
employers, it has altered the role of the state and transformed the three-way
relations between government, employers and unions. This has forced unions
to look for new ways of bargaining and new ways to influence the labour
market internationally. <BR>
<BR>
However momentous the globalisation process appears, the basic power imbalance
remains. The individual worker is still at a considerable disadvantage to
an employer without the collective support of others through a trade union.
This does not have to be a confrontational process. Many firms accept that
success comes from cooperation between a strong union and imaginative management,
both committed to the long-term prosperity of the business. The basic human
right to join a union and so negotiate a fair return for labour is a foundation
for constructive competition. The purpose of collective bargaining is to
avoid potential conflict and promote sustained cooperation. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Stability needs collective bargaining </B><BR>
<BR>
This positive view is not reported by the media. If world leaders formed
their views about economics and politics from newspapers and television,
they would probably think of trade unions as relics of the pre-globalisation
age. Most media coverage of our work still focuses on the occasional big
strike or protest, as with the recent dispute in France. It is time to reassess
the stereotype and look more deeply at where trade unions fit into the realities
of an interdependent world, driven by intense competition for new markets.
<BR>
<BR>
Some companies recognise that the labour-management power imbalance undermines
the relationship of trust that is essential to the new systems of strategic
planning and organisation. Others deny its importance, fearing either a
dilution of managerial control or the costs of investing in the managerial
practices that a team approach requires. <BR>
<BR>
In a world of liberalised capital markets and tight monetary policies, strong
institutions are vital to the development of the social solidarity that
can counteract growing inequality and insecurity. It is increasingly clear
to trade unions that collective bargaining and wide-ranging tripartite discussions
on economic and social policy are essential components of national and international
efforts to build the stability needed for growth. <BR>
<BR>
Business leaders have a different perspective on these problems. They are
concerned with the survival and profitability of their companies. The technological
revolution has led most companies to rethink how they organise work and
to change old hierarchical and compartmentalised systems in order to meet
the competition. This has spawned a whole new set of management theories
based on ideas such as employee involvement and partnership. For trade unionists
these trends pose a new set of challenges. The classic collective agreement
led to a sharing of responsibilities between unions and management over
basic employment contract issues such as pay, hours of work, holidays and
so on. At the same time, company strategy was left largely in the hands
of management. There were exceptions such as the <I>Mitbestimmung </I>system
in Germany, where representatives have a wider role in company planning,
but in general it was assumed that workers and their unions could not be
trusted with a say in anything beyond the terms of their employment contracts.
<BR>
<BR>
But now the impetus for change is coming from management as interest grows
in new forms of employee involvement. This process is far from accepted
by many workforces which tend to view it as a quick route to the dole queue
because of the legacy of years of mistrust. They fear that gains in productivity
will simply leads to redundancies, now euphemistically called downsizing
or rightsizing. They also see companies spinning off operations to subcontractors,
often in other countries, leaving a small core of winners and a large group
of losers with jobs that are insecure and low-paid. <BR>
<BR>
The main flaw in the thinking of many managers is the tendency to gloss
over the significance of the unequal power relationship on which the contract
of employment between a worker and a company is based. This is bound to
continue unless the relationship is evened up through legal rights and collective
bargaining agreements. <BR>
<BR>
But unions can do more than this. Suspicion needs to be replaced by mutual
respect and trust, otherwise employee involvement will lead to workers acting
merely as agents of feedback, telling managers what they think managers
want to hear. Workers unsure about job security are unlikely to risk telling
managers what is wrong with the way they run the business. Unions can help
remove feelings of insecurity and assure workers that they do not have to
gamble on believing management's promises. Unions can also help workers
see the whole picture of a company's operations and use their expertise
to question it. Such scrutiny tests and strengthens the credibility of management.
<BR>
<BR>
The more that companies involve union representatives in their strategic
thinking, the more they will gain from employee involvement. If you doubt
it, look at some of the world's most successful unionised companies. This
approach has gained some acceptance in the EU, where European Works Councils
establish consultation structures for the ever-growing number of companies
with transnational operations. These new councils have the potential to
promote cross-fertilisation of ideas across national boundaries and encourage
a much-needed reassessment within the many companies still suffering from
them-and-us attitudes. There is no need to limit the strategy to Europe.
<BR>
<BR>
But companies can go further by accepting that they do not operate in a
vacuum and that they are part of a wider community. Quality products do
not emerge from low-quality communities. At the local level, employers'
organisations should get their members involved in efforts to improve the
environment, strengthen local schools and health care and other such goals.
This is not charity work but an investment which should be planned as such.
Unions can help companies get a good return on such investments. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Sound industrial relations make deregulation easier </B><BR>
<BR>
The challenge for trade unions in the era of trade globalisation is to ensure
that necessary and rapid changes in the nature of work and the labour market
are achieved without compromising full employment and social justice. We
have to convince governments that it is essential to act urgently to increase
the size and spread of world economic growth. <BR>
<BR>
The wholesale deregulation of labour markets increases the problems countries
face in adapting to change. Problems are solved where governments, trade
unions and employers focus together on strengthening labour market institutions,
so that people can benefit from training and job-creation schemes. We know,
but must convince others, that sound industrial relations and a well-functioning
tripartite consultation system are the best means of ensuring that the labour
market responds to change with the least social dislocation. They are also
the best means of making tough choices about the distribution of scarce
resources without destabilising government budgets and within the restraints
of global competitive pressures. <BR>
<BR>
The more optimistic advocates of market liberalisation foresee a new golden
age of rapid growth which will spread prosperity all over the world. The
reality for many millions of working people is very different. Trade unions
have a duty to warn world leaders that they risk blinding themselves with
their own rhetoric to the unemployment, poverty and social dislocation that
are the unfortunate underside of globalisation. <BR>
<BR>
We also have a responsibility to attempt to work with employers and governments
and achieve a new balance between competition and social cohesion. If we
are to play that role, the attitude of hostility to unions that became fashionable
in the '80s must change - the sooner this happens, the better for all of
us. <p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
