<td valign=top>
<h2>
January/February 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra14.gif" alt="Davos 1996">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left><H2>LIFE AFTER HISTORY </H2>
<H4>The market does not have all the answers, after all. Provocative analyst
Francis Fukuyama tells Susan Greenberg why culture has such an important,
but intangible, effect on our prosperity</H4>
The Rand Corporation's Washington office is a surprisingly no-fuss place,
more like the cramped corridors of a university than a prestigious policy
think-tank. Rand senior researcher Francis Fukuyama is also deceptively
unassuming: his first book <I>The end of history and the Last Man</I> caused
a small uproar several years ago and the latest one, <I>Trust: The social
virtues and the creation of prosperity,</I> shows a similar ability to tap
popular concerns. <BR>
<BR>
Fukuyama was criticised as triumphalist in <I>The end of history</I> for
arguing that history as defined by Hegel and Marx had &quot;ended&quot;
with the Cold War: the difference was that it had ended not with proletarian
revolution but the triumph of liberal democracy and the market economy.
In <I>Trust</I> he tackles some of the doubts surrounding this system and
makes the case for the importance of &quot;inherited ethical habit&quot;
to economic well-being, arguing that the cultural characteristic of trust
gives rise to &quot;social capital&quot;, a measure of people's ability
to work together for a common purpose. <BR>
<BR>
Fukuyama met <I>World Link</I> in Washington to explore these themes, which
are of core interest to many of our readers. <BR>
<BR>
<I>You have complained of misunderstandings over your first book: have any
major problems arisen over the new one?</I> <BR>
<BR>
The biggest problem is that people misunderstand the purpose of the argument.
James Fallows of <I>Atlantic Monthly</I> was typical: he said I was presenting
an alternative macroeconomic growth model [even though] economists understand
the sources of growth and they are not cultural. I never made that claim:
I am not trying to attack the whole foundation of modern economics. I think
that foundation is secure, the existing growth models are quite accurate
and the policy prescriptions are ones I am generally sympathetic with. But
even by the assumptions of modern neoclassical economics the models only
account for up to 70% of observed growth in the world, so there's a very
important residual... which cannot be explained by them. To get into this
residual you need cultural explanations, you cannot develop theories that
are empirically verifiable to the same degree. <BR>
<BR>
This is the meaning of the end of history. We understand the big principles
about how to organise a modern society: you can make adjustments but the
essence - a liberal democracy and regulated markets - is not up for grabs
any longer. This means that interest shifts from those big factors to the
residual ones, and that's where social capital is important. <BR>
<BR>
The second common mistake is when people say there is no point to my theory
because the figures show low-trust countries can grow as fast as high-trust
ones. I have said explicitly that trust is not an important factor as a
predictor of GDP aggregate growth: what it does is help us understand the
global division of labour, for example why the state needs to step in to
create large organisations in low-trust societies like France, where the
private sector is not capable of doing so. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Does the latest crisis in Paris illustrate your book's point about the
gulf in France between the ruler and ruled?</I> <BR>
<BR>
French democracy has always been defective, and you can see why in the latest
crisis. Here in Washington, the government shut down because there was a
deadlock over the budget. In France, the government is able to decree an
austerity package much stiffer than the American one: there is no discussion
in the legislature, they just spring it on everyone. The result is that
everyone asks, &quot;What about us, the people that elected you?&quot; It
is not a new insight... that throughout French history there has been an
alternation between the two extremes [of hyper-centralised and excessively
decentralised authority]. <BR>
<BR>
<I>I was interested in the book's link between a strong emphasis on family
business and corruption, as seen in Chinese societies and Italy.</I> <BR>
<BR>
I have been rung up by quite a few Italian journalists. I expected hostility
but they say the book gives an accurate description of politics in Italy,
where there's a high degree of corruption due to a low sense of public morality
outside the family: economic success depends on the family business and
everything else is run by the state. This is also the pattern throughout
Latin America. There are two separate sets of moral rules, one for the family
and one for street, and the standards for the street are considerably lower.
If you get elected to public office, to some extent your first moral obligation
is to steal on behalf of your family. <BR>
<BR>
<I>The theory may also apply in eastern Europe, where there was a saying
that if you did not steal from the state you were stealing from your family.
People there also tend to be more passive in the public domain.</I> <BR>
<BR>
The future of many of those former communist countries, including Russia,
is going to look more like Italy than any other model: a weak and ineffective
state and poorly organised civil society, a lurching back and forth between
unstable governments and attempts to impose order, and in the meantime the
growth of criminal gangs. <BR>
<BR>
I have proposed a study of the former communist world parallel to my book,
because I think cultural factors explain many transition trajectories. Totalitarianism
was supposed to homogenise those societies but they are all different. The
most successful were those like Lithuania which produced fairly deep non-communist
leaderships right away, people who just came out of the woodwork. There
were people with similar social backgrounds in Ukraine as well and yet none
took part in political life there after communism. <BR>
<BR>
In the Baltics, for example, hatred of the Russians is at least as deep
as ethnic hatreds in the Balkans and yet not a drop of blood was spilt in
that transition. When you ask why, people cite northern Europe culture.
That's obviously true but it is not clear by which mechanism such a culture
was transmitted over the generations: the nobility was non-indiginous and
local people were all peasants a few generations ago. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Doesn't that also highlight the inadequacy of explanations about Balkan
conflict being based on &quot;centuries-old rivalries&quot;? </I><BR>
<BR>
Especially when these centuries-old rivalries tend to be quiescent for centuries!
Then suddenly they flare up and people say, &quot;Oh yes, it's that centuries-old
rivalry&quot;. They said a lot of ridiculous stuff about the Iran-Iraq war:
it was the old Sunni-Shia rivalry or Arab-Persian rivalry. <BR>
<BR>
<I>In The end of history you say liberal democracy and capitalism has &quot;won&quot;
but it is coming under intense question at home. There may not be a clearly
articulated alternative yet but the current confusion may be part of a new,
still-hidden process. As Alan Bloom comments in The closing of the American
mind, economics deals only with the bourgeois who fears violent death while
humans are perverse and do not always wish to be comfortable.</I> <BR>
<BR>
There is obviously a lot of unhappiness in the democratic world... but nobody
questions the basic foundations of the liberal solution, or tinkers with
economic nationalism or socialism as an alternative. The problem is mainly
at a sub-institutional level, to do with cultural questions of identity.
In my view the capitalist marketplace substitutes for those older forms
of struggle in many ways but... the problem with the Last Man [identified
by the philosopher Friedrich Nietsche] is that people [get to the point
where they] do not want rational consumption. But again, I don't think that's
the problem with the Balkans: it is not as if they had rational consumption
and got bored with it, as if they decided to tear it all up and have some
excitement. <BR>
<BR>
There is a long-term theoretical incoherence about liberalism. The American
system is based on the idea of inalienable rights, which Jefferson declares
are &quot;self-evident&quot;. But no serious modern philosopher would consider
them self-evident today because the 20th century tradition of relativism
categories them as specific cultural traditions rather than a statement
about humanity as such. You can see this in the fight with the Singaporean
leader Lee Kuan Yew over human rights in Asia. <BR>
<BR>
<I>The book appears to be arguing in two directions. One is towards the
fears within US society that lead western businessmen, for example, to praise
authoritarian societies abroad. The other is to non-westerners defending
those societies who crow, &quot;we are doing better than you&quot;. </I><BR>
<BR>
Yes, there is a fundamental misunderstanding. It can be right that democracy
is superior as a universal system of governing for modern society but it
can also be right that there are aspects of society in Singapore, for example,
which are superior to the US. I think the big disservice Lee Kuan Yew has
done is that he links the big institutions to social decay and says: &quot;All
America's urban problems are due to democracy <I>per se</I>, if you want
to avoid them you need an authoritarian system like ours.&quot; I think
that's just nonsense. <BR>
<BR>
The basic argument in <I>Trust</I> is that the big institutions have to
be supplemented by a moral framework and a set of pre-modern values to make
them work. If you go back to Alexis De Tocqueville [who wrote the classic
<I>Democracy in America</I> in the republic's early years] he understood
very well that you cannot create a liveable society based simply on the
self-interested interactions of individuals. My book makes a parallel argument
in the economic sphere: markets do not work without some kind of moral structure.
Modern institutions have to coexist with traditional forms of moral behaviour,
reciprocity and trust. <BR>
<BR>
The businessman that admires Singapore sees the social discipline and authoritarianism
and assumes the two are necessarily interconnected. Although many difficulties
in the US stem from the nature of its democracy, it is not by any means
a necessary outgrowth. Just take the difference between the US and Europe
in the way rights are interpreted, which accounts for a lot of our problems.
<BR>
<BR>
Every European democracy that enumerates a set of individual rights also
enumerates duties to the community and none of the rights is interpreted
absolutely. In that sense the American Bill of Rights is unique in that
it does not enumerate any positive duties to the community. You sees this
in constitutional law, in attitudes towards pornography or gun control.
The right to own a gun is seen as such an absolute right that people favouring
it think the most modest abridgement means the end of the right as a whole.
Similarly, it seems to me you can control pornography and still have freedom
of speech, but the way the civil libertarians talk you'll be banning James
Joyce if you ban an X-rated movie. <BR>
<BR>
Many US problems have to do with a specific history surrounding race. The
civil rights movement of the '60s brought about many necessary changes but
set a pattern for all subsequent activism which has not been helpful. There
were always two patterns for upward mobility in the US: the one used by
Jews and Asians was mobility through the economic system, self-employment,
education and so on. The other was pioneered by the Irish but used by the
blacks, to capture political power and use it to pull yourself up. The Irish
did it through the local political machine, the blacks through the courts
which are more powerful than in Europe. The latter were very successful
and every subsequent group with a grievance has taken the rights approach
as a model. <BR>
<BR>
In the '60s there was a campaign to get rid of the corrupt Tammany Halls.
The problem is that after you destroy the local machines people used in
their climb to the top it all became federalised, either by the courts or
in anti-poverty programmes. <BR>
<BR>
The Hispanic community is an interesting case, because culturally it is
not that different from the southern Italians who flooded in at the turn
of the century and who relied on self-help rather than the courts. All the
Mexicans coming in now could follow that pattern, except that their political
leadership has this post-civil rights strategy. <BR>
<BR>
<I>The book argues against multicultural extremism and says America should
continue to impose a set of core values if it is to avoid legislating for
every aspect of life. What kind of reaction has there been to this theme?
</I><BR>
<BR>
In this country we are getting to a point where people are beginning to
see that the path towards multiculturalism and ethnic balkanisation has
gone too far and needs to be cut short to some degree. The cultural revolution
of the '60s took at least a generation to happen, and like all revolutions
is producing a counter-revolution which will take at least another generation.
That generation is not going to set things back to the way they were in
1963 - we will get some kind of uneasy synthesis - but I think the shift
is going to happen and in the same way, [as] a movement sparked by what
people think about their parents, the government... <BR>
<BR>
The reason I am guardedly optimistic is that for a great many ethnic groups
in the US the assimilationist engine is still working pretty well. Asians
are now 6% of the population. Hispanic groups want to learn English and
become Americans for traditional reasons: the rate of intermarriage is so
high that the whole category may disappear, just as it is hard to separate
Germans or Swedes. The most problematic group has been that of African-Americans
where assimilation has not worked as hoped and is going backwards at a fairly
rapid pace, but it is possible that this may be cautionary message to other
groups. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Your book aims to be even-handed, but I had the impression you put more
emphasis on attacking the US left's civil rights mentality than on the new
threat from the far right. </I><BR>
<BR>
I think criticism of the civil rights revolution is not just criticism of
the left. One interesting development in this country is the way the rights
culture has migrated from left to right. In the '60s the right liked authority,
the FBI and the Pentagon: it was the left which had all these lunatic conspiracy
theories. Now it is the [anti-federal] militia people who have conspiracy
theories about the FBI and so on. Even the way people dress - earrings and
ponytails, once the exclusive province of the left in the '60s - has migrated.
There always was this anti-statist extremism that goes back to the founding
of the country: what is new is a willingness to entertain elaborate conspiracy
theories. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Are mainstream conservative politicians failing to draw a line between
&quot;small government&quot; and the paranoia of more extremist groups?
After all, the federal government is one expression of working for the common
good, which you consider so vital.</I> <BR>
<BR>
I agree people go overboard in their anti-statism. There are things only
states can do, like enforcing security and property rights. We have gone
through periods like this before: the pendulum will swing the other way.
For example, radical proposals to deregulate the banks were put on hold
by the Daiwa scandal. <BR>
<BR>
There is a deeper argument that you need to draw a line between the state
and civil society, that there is a common good but various ways of reaching
that common good. Smarter Republicans like [House speaker] Newt Gingrich
and William Kristol see this quite clearly. They would argue that the state
can injure the ability of people to work together for common ends and want
to cut back the role of the state, not so that the individual has maximum
freedom - they are not libertarians in that sense - but so that they can
give back to civil society what should be in its own province. <BR>
<BR>
The problem is that they only have half the formula. They got the cutting-back-of-the-state
part of it, but there is really no guarantee that civil society will simply
spontaneously spring back into the vacuum. You can see that most clearly
in welfare reform. There's no question that the AFDC (Aid to Families with
Dependent Children) programme has undermined the family in poor neighbourhoods.
It was designed during the '30s depression to help widows over a transition
period, but became a major source of support for single teenage mothers
and had a major destabilising role [providing a work disincentive]. Congress
has voted to abolish it, but abolishing that bad incentive does not recreate
the family when you've had a couple of generations of men who do not know
what it is to be a father. <BR>
<BR>
<I>You say the market is not enough. Yet in Britain, anyone who takes this
line is usually labelled left-wing and it was former Conservative leader
Margaret Thatcher who said there was no such thing as society</I> <BR>
<BR>
In the US there is a difference between Gingrich and [former President Ronald]
Reagan, the counterpart of Thatcher, who never articulated the civil society
argument. In this post-Reagan generation you really do have a realisation,
at least among certain conservatives, that there is a layer of society in-between
[the family and state]. Besides Gingrich, William Bennett argues that a
sense of civic duty is necessary for the functioning of society but he continues
to be anti-statist. <BR>
<BR>
<I>The debate about trust moved into management theory even before your
book appeared. Does such an approach work, since it is not often reciprocal?</I>
<BR>
<BR>
It's funny, because management theorists were much more sympathetic to my
book than the economists. There is a very broad move from low-trust to high-trust
organisations across the board, from hierarchical to flat organisations.
When you flatten an organisation you devolve authority to the bottom and
you need to trust people there to take responsibilities and use their judgement.
Historically, this is a good way of dealing with uncertainty and lack of
information, which usually exists at the bottom level and which gets lost
if it has to make a two-way trip up and down the hierarchy. <BR>
<BR>
There are a couple of problems with this. It is not going to work if people
at the bottom are not given the wherewithal to assume these greater responsibilities,
such as training, but that component is often missing. In Germany, the other
part of the package is to do with job security. That's where the real problem
lies in the US flat revolution. Many companies here reorganise and then
fire half their workers, leaving the remaining workforce demoralised and
distrustful. The last thing people are going to do is use their initiative
if they've just seen half their co-workers laid off. <BR>
<BR>
Both the Germans and Japanese have lifetime employment systems but it is
not as rigid as you would think. The company, knowing it cannot just lay
off people, takes responsibility for retraining. If you're a manager and
your labour is a fixed cost, it is in your interest to make it able to generate
value. It does not work in the US because if one company started retraining
its workers, others could poach them. In Germany everyone pays into the
training kitty and in Japan there is social ostracism for jumping ship.
<BR>
<BR>
<I>The term &quot;end of history&quot; became widely used but also widely
criticised. Do you have any regrets about it?</I> <BR>
<BR>
I regret the fact that it was so widely misunderstood. After the fuss over
my original article I thought I would write a longer book to explain this
concept of history [which has] a very precise meaning if you're Hegelian.
But it did not do any good, because people just could not get past their
initial impression. It's funny because the most sympathetic readers of the
book were all Marxists: the <I>New Left Review</I> did a long series of
essays by British Marxists who were critical but good because they did not
have this hang-up over the word history. <BR>
<BR>
<I>The strongest negative reaction came from people familiar with eastern
Europe, where history was being unfrozen. The end of the Cold War resolved
some things but made others more uncertain. Did you take that into account?</I>
<BR>
<BR>
Nothing that's happened in eastern Europe has run contrary to the basic
idea of the end of history. What happened in that part of the world would
falsify the hypothesis only if what you were doing is constructing a genuinely
new system that had never existed before. <BR>
<BR>
I do not see that happening. I see a lot of troubled societies having a
hard time, stuck between an old and new set of institutions. But that is
a troubled transition, that is not the same thing as restarting history.
<p>
</td>
</tr>
