<td valign=top align=left> 
<H2>SPEED BUMPS </H2>
<H3>A WEEK IN THE LIFE OF A VW PRODUCTIVITY WORKSHOP </H3>
<H4>In its bid to boost productivity, VW is inviting workers to bare their
souls. Adrian Murdoch sits in on a session at Wolfsburg </H4>
&quot;To rank as world class, European manufacturers need to double productivity&quot;:
that is the brutal conclusion of the Economist Intelligence Unit in its
survey of the European motor business. Since the onslaught of the Japanese
in the '80s, European car manufacturers have been fighting a rearguard battle
against competitors who have made more cars than them, of better quality
and with more choice. <BR>
<BR>
Between 1982 and 1990 alone, Japanese car manufacturers doubled their product
portfolio. Over the same period European manufacturers actually reduced
their portfolio and the results have been felt on the bottom line with declining
profits and market share. The impact is intensified by the growing trend
to source and produce globally. <BR>
<BR>
The country hardest hit is Germany and the company that is having the most
difficulty adjusting to the new world order is Volkswagen. Admired throughout
the '50s and '60s, the Beetle became the world's best-selling car in the
early '70s as the company produced high-quality compact cars at a price
that everyone could afford. At the same time its workers' high wages and
long holidays were envied as Volkswagen proved year after year that its
social capitalism could produce high profits. <BR>
<BR>
In the harsh climate of the '90s, however, the Volkswagen engine has not
been turning over quite as it should. The company's market share in Europe
has slipped to 10.2% and although net profits in the first half of last
year - DM113 million ($78.2 million) - reversed the DM209 million loss it
had suffered the year before, the company is due for a full service. <BR>
<BR>
The VW engine has begun to stall for two important reasons. The first is
a general manufacturing problem in Germany. Wages account for 70% of the
cost of building a car and German workers are the most expensive in Europe
with an average industrial wage of $31.08 per hour, almost half of that
made up by social costs. This makes them twice as expensive as British workers,
for example (figure 1). <BR>
<BR>
The second problem has to do with VW's unwillingness and inability to reduce
the workforce. As the effects of the recession began to be felt in the early
'90s, VW introduced a four-day week in 1993 as a means of saving jobs and
maintaining its paternal image, following chairman Ferdinand Pi&euml;ch's
threat that 30,000 jobs would have to go. What was effectively a job-sharing
arrangement was briefly touted as a new paradigm for a caring decade. The
regional government of Lower Saxony, which holds a 20% stake in the company,
was happy with this solution because it kept unemployment figures down just
before the elections. The company management was happy because it had avoided
redundancy payments and bad public relations. The powerful union IG Metall,
which has a seat on the supervisory board, was happy because it could feel
it had looked after the rights of its members. <BR>
<BR>
The four-day week helped secure around 25,000 jobs but was still of limited
help in improving VW's competitive position, trying to squeeze flexibility
into a rigid system. Quite how limited was seen during last September's
pay negotiations between VW and IG Metall. After walkouts that cost the
company DM300 million in lost production, VW effectively won on many of
the issues with one crucial rider: no workers were to be fired for the next
two years. In other words it is still employing more people than it needs
and natural wastage alone will not transform the situation. This combination
of factors has conspired to make Wolfsburg, VW's flagship factory in the
central Germany state of Lower Saxony, one of the most inefficient auto
plants in the world. It produces only 40% of the number of cars per employee
as General Motors/Opel does in its state-of-the-art factory in the east
German town of Eisenach and only 18% as many as Toyota at its Takaoka plant
(figure 2). &quot;Wolfsburg is a plant where the size itself is a problem,&quot;
admits Willem Admiraal, head of the productivity centre at Wolfsburg, whose
brief it is to stop the rot. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Volkswagen was a very successful company until two, three years ago
and people there have a deep-seated mentality that the way we have always
done things is the right way... They have been so successful for the last
30-40 years that they ask, why change a winning team?&quot; he says. &quot;They
are right, they did incredible things... but there are [also] things we
need to change.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The productivity team has been busy, working out how to produce more cars
with the same number of workers or the same number of cars with fewer workers.
The auto industry became aware of the potential of this approach in the
early '90s when Jos&eacute; Ignacio Lopez, then General Motors' vice-president
of purchasing, touted efficiency gains of between 50% and 150% through productivity
workshops. Admiraal, son-in-law of Lopez and another refugee from GM, is
clear on his definition of productivity. &quot;It is not a guy sweating
away, coming home and collapsing into a chair because he is so tired. That
is not productivity, that is killing your people. We can only reach productivity
by eliminating waste... improving quality and productivity at the same time.
That is the only way to go forward.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>Employees have the answers </B><BR>
<BR>
A new five-day workshop was introduced in which GM and its suppliers jointly
decided what changes were needed. Picos or Purchased Input Concept Optimisation
with Suppliers, as it was first called, aimed to help suppliers eliminate
waste and meet customer satisfaction goals, focusing on three key areas
- quality, service and price. <BR>
<BR>
In April 1993 Volkswagen introduced Lopez and KVP2 - the <I>Kontinuierlicher
Verbesserungs Proze&szlig; quadrat</I> or Continuous Improvement Process
squared. Then as now, the objective of a workshop was to develop manufacturing
that was focused on the customer rather than on production by asking the
one group of people who knew many of the answers - the employees. In other
words, the aim was to focus on the tiny, incremental improvements which
add up to productivity and break down existing barriers between workers
and management, be-tween different departments and between the producer
and its suppliers. This means, among other things, adding value to operations,
eliminating the root cause of defects, eliminating inventory and using just-in-time
production, letting information flow and emphasising teamwork and good relations
with employees. <BR>
<BR>
From tentative beginnings at VW's Salzgitter factory and at Audi, by the
end of 1993 some 16,000 workers had taken part in 2,000 workshops. By the
end of 1994, 60,000 workers had taken part in 6,300 workshops. In its first
year alone, Lopez claimed an across-the-board productivity increase of 20%,
others in the company and industry are more cautious. <BR>
<BR>
<I>World Link</I> was invited to observe one of these workshops in the seat
production department, to see at first-hand the challenges a company faces
in putting productivity into practice. In the comfort of an office it is
easy to see productivity merely as a strategic issue, but as the workshop
shows, it often comes down to apparently minor incremental improvements
which can be very difficult to achieve. <BR>
<BR>
Stepping off the train at Wolfsburg, the first thing you see are the four
smokestacks of a VW power plant and the company's massive blue and white
logo. Wolfsburg is one of the last great company towns in Europe and VW
dominates the 150,000 people who live there in a way rarely seen today:
not even Mercedes' star shines as brightly in Stuttgart. To drive any other
car than a VW is regarded as bad manners. <BR>
<BR>
Four-day workshops run throughout the year, with the theme announced a week
beforehand. An effort is made to include someone from every shift, to get
ideas across to as many people as possible, but KVP2 cannot force people
to come. Melanie Cain, moderator of the KVP2 workshop, admits that it has
been difficult at times getting people to come, partly because staff &quot;think
it is a way of getting rid of people&quot;. The workshop itself can confirm
their worst fears: a poster on the workshop wall asks, &quot;Why are we
doing KVP2? To secure our jobs&quot;. But participants are won over on learning
that 90% of suggestions made during the workshop are implemented, eventually.
<BR>
<BR>
Although trust is increasing there is a longer-term problem for the moderators
themselves: they exist because of the will of Pi&euml;ch and Lopez. More
than two years on from the launch of the workshops there is still no official
structure for these people, who are picked from the production line and
thrown into the job after only a week's intensive training, no official
job description and, say some, no real recognition given the essential but
unquantifiable soft skills that moderators need. As Uwe Bothe of KVP2 administration
says, they are &quot;not moderators in the classic sense: they lead the
questions [and] are responsible for the results&quot;. Cain is sanguine
but is still doing exams in her spare time which will qualify her as foreman.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>VW needs to make a quantum leap </B><BR>
<BR>
The group from the seat production department met on Monday morning, at
7.30 sharp, in Halle 8 where the Polo is assembled. The Polo has been one
of VW's most successful models: bought by 3.8 million people over 19 years
of production, it now accounts for 28% of total sales. The luxurious and
prize-winning third-generation Polo was unveiled in Paris in August 1994
and VW hopes to produce around 350,000 cars annually. But with current delivery
times as long as 12 weeks, there is clearly much that can be done. <BR>
<BR>
Moderator Cain is chairing the sessions with Roman Delau from the industrial
engineering department. Participants include four people from the shopfloor:
Peter, a foreman who plays peacemaker in many of the week's arguments; Stefan
and Henrik, both frustrated at not having a voice and Maik, a union representative
who has been on workshops before and is sceptical about the changes promised.
<BR>
<BR>
The session starts with a presentation on the car industry and the aims
of KVP2. Delau outlines the world's current annual overcapacity of 10.4
million cars: VW must ensure that its own cars are the ones that are bought.
At the moment its cars are improving only at the same rate as Japanese ones,
so VW need to make a quantum leap to win. <BR>
<BR>
To increase quality, service and price the company must eliminate waste,
he says, but asks: &quot;Where is the waste? Is it time, training, organisation
or the reliability of suppliers?&quot; To explain the importance of looking
at real rather than superficial reasons for waste, he gives the example
of a machine examined in a previous workshop. At first it seemed that the
machine was not working properly because of a defective circuit board. Then
someone noticed there was too little air coming out of the cooling system.
The solution was not to replace expensive circuitry but simply to clean
dust from the filters regularly. <BR>
<BR>
Delau asks participants to identify waste in the seat production department.
Peter says their worry is not physical waste, but waste of time: if a seat
does not fit, for example, they have to make it fit, and that is what takes
time. &quot;If we threw away every part that wasn't an exact fit, we wouldn't
build any cars,&quot; says Maik bitterly. The workers then start voicing
their complaints about the workshop and the company in general. Stefan is
disillusioned, questioning the whole point of being there. He appreciates
that VW has started to ask the opinions of its workers but says it does
not implement the solutions that emerge. <BR>
<BR>
At 10.15, after a short break, it is time for the brainstorming. Cain tells
everyone to shout out anything that irritates them about the job and write
it up on a board. Once she emphasises that nothing they say will go out
of the room, the complaints come thick and fast. &quot;The Polo is thrown
together here, any old way, that is how it looks to me,&quot; says Cain
dryly. <BR>
<BR>
When this is done, the points raised are put together under topic headings
on huge purple posters. The idea is to identify the specific difficulties
the workers have in doing their job as efficiently as possible and what
they see as the solution. If the problem lies outside their department,
it identifies when to call in the relevant experts to explain why it is
done that way and what, if anything, can be done. <BR>
<BR>
By far the greatest problem the Polo seat workers face is the poor quality
of carpets, which they say has existed since the birth of the Polo. They
complain about &quot;permanent wrinkling&quot; and the way supervisors pass
the buck, leaving it to be fixed in post-assembly. &quot;The carpet problem
will be sorted out by the end of the year,&quot; says Cain reassuringly.
&quot;If you can do that, you are a magician,&quot; says Henrik. <BR>
<BR>
They list what they see as the specific problems. The mats do not lie properly;
the carpet is positioned too high up; it is not properly cut and does not
lie over the seat rails. Because of this, seats tear the carpet as they
are installed. Also, by the time the cars get to the seat department the
carpets have been dirtied by other teams, materials or wiring are left under
the carpet or it is simply the wrong colour. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Productivity and quality go hand in hand </B><BR>
<BR>
The solutions are typically simple: to identify the problem with carpet
shape, to make sure the carpet team does its job more carefully and to pass
on information to the other teams that dirty carpets have become a problem.
The foreman responsible is called in. He is sympathetic, asking the right
questions. He explains that the problem is not that they are badly cut,
but they are outsourced and there seems to be a design flaw. <BR>
<BR>
To get to the bottom of the design problem, the quality foreman comes in.
He describes the carpets supplied as &quot;rubbish, absolute rubbish&quot;
and says that out of 50 sets that are supplied, one has to be thrown away
because of bad packaging. But although he sympathises he cannot change anything.
&quot;I cost money, I don't bring it in,&quot; he explains. The group decides
that the only way to get to the bottom of the problem is to set up a meeting
between the department manager and the suppliers. <BR>
<BR>
The next two points discussed are comparatively straightforward. The seat
teams find that further up the production line others were leaving the cars
dirty with wax, paper paint, stains and litter, everything from screws to
Coke cans. The solution is to pass that inform-ation around until the practice
stops. They also complain that the screws they have to use are too oily.
Some have the oil drained off beforehand, others do not and they are left
scrabbling around in a pool of oil trying to find a screw as the car moves
down the production line. <BR>
<BR>
The final issue raised that day is one at the heart of the worries of both
productivity supervisors and workers - a lack of time. Productivity and
quality go hand in hand and Admiraal is keen to emphasise this: &quot;If
someone is running quicker he is going to make errors. We should make sure
that people are not running quicker, we should make sure that people have
to walk less.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The aim of the workshop is to see if the number in each production team
can be reduced by between one and three people at the speed they are working
at now, or if the production line can be speeded up with the same number
of workers. <BR>
<BR>
At the beginning of a shift the production line is set a speed which is
displayed on a huge board above the shop floor, the number of cars that
should run off the line at the end of a 300-minute shift. The target is
to match the Golf line and produce 510 Polos a day, which amounts to a 300-minute-shift
speed of 170. But Halle 8 is a long way off that. In September the average
speed was 140 or 9,194 cars in 22 working days and the fastest managed so
far is 156. For the seat production team, an average of 140 means fitting
30 seats in 70 minutes. <BR>
<BR>
Workers are riled by any comparisons with the Golf line as that is more
mechanised. &quot;I am working as fast as I can,&quot; complains Maik. &quot;Of
course I am going to say that you can [speed up production] if all the other
problems are solved, because they never will be.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
At the beginning of day two there is a recap. Much of the sullenness and
suspicion of the day before has been replaced, if not by optimism, then
at least by cautious openness. Peter says he is happy with the way things
have gone: Stefan is also pleased, provided something gets done. Henrik
says he would be happy if just some of their problems are solved and Maik
is in a bad mood after dropping a flowerpot on his foot that morning. <BR>
<BR>
Without further ado the issue of the seat production work area is addressed.
There are complaints about lack of space, a slippery floor, rain through
the roof. The team also complains about the fact that the tables slip when
car seats are placed on them for greasing, about badly designed shelves
and toolboxes which are too short so that pieces stick out - Maik goes to
fetch one for illustration. In addition, they say, people stand in the way
when they work and the people who deliver parts drive dangerously. <BR>
<BR>
In perhaps the quickest fix of the week, the foreman in charge of tables
is called in and agrees to fix them within the week. The head of the subdivision
for drivers comes in too. He says he will talk to the drivers straightaway
and they could consider it done. <BR>
<BR>
The issue of the toolboxes is a thornier problem. They are currently 420mm
long and ideally should be 480-500mm long. With a proper toolbox each member
of the team could work on up to 15 cars without going back for supplies,
whereas at the moment they have to do so for every car. Various solutions
are considered. Ordering new boxes is rejected as too expensive so the workers
say they will see if they can design one themselves from existing parts.
Two men from the planning department come in. They say they will not commission
another firm to make a bigger box but they agree to see if the current supplier
makes one the right size. By-passing the bureaucracy, over the lunch break
Maik makes one himself. <BR>
<BR>
Another difficulty for KVP2 to overcome is that of middle management inflexibility.
Those at the top of the corporate ladder enthuse about productivity because
a successful company reflects well on them, while on the shop-floor workers
know the problems and want changes which will make their lives easier. But
middle management's main interest is in preserving the status quo. When
the head of the subdivision in Halle 8 comes to the productivity workshop,
to every point raised he replies, &quot;It's not a real problem&quot; or
&quot;tough, that's the way it is done&quot;. Participants are spoiling
for a fight and savage him for two hours. Nevertheless, they are encouraged
by the appearance of the different experts and managers and their enthusiasm
is rising. <BR>
<BR>
Admiraal sighs when the middle management issue is raised but speaks with
understanding of their reaction to change. &quot;People in middle management
get excited when they know they are going to get something out of it. A
manager wants to see something coming out of it for him. We should show
that KVP2 can help him and his people reach his goals, not to see KVP2 as
something extra.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
By Wednesday morning the group is getting tired. But the workshop becomes
less theoretical as participants are brought back onto the shopfloor to
see the difficulties in practice. Peter points out the tables sliding around,
mechanical obstacles and the lack of space. &quot;It's awful, really awful,&quot;
says Cain. <BR>
<BR>
Back in the meeting room, there are more visitors. Friedrich Grebe from
the works committee comes in to discuss ways of speeding up production.
He warns against being too hasty about raising unrealistic expectations
by putting concrete figures on the potential for improvement: &quot;If all
the changes are implemented and it is still not possible [for a shift to
work with three men at 130 rather than four at 140], then heads will roll.&quot;
He also agrees to have a word with the middle manager who proved difficult
the day before. The manager concerned comes in later, an apparently transformed
person, and agrees to look at the issues. <BR>
<BR>
The designer comes in to discuss the carpets and says he will try and set
up a meeting with the heads of the two firms that supply the carpets. He
points out that to change the design would cost in the region of DM12,500.
&quot;But we can't not pay it and let quality go down the drain,&quot; protests
Maik. The designer promises to nail down the problem but the group is sceptical,
pointing out that people from the two firms have come in before for discussions
and nothing has happened. <BR>
<BR>
The final morning is spent going through the result sheet (figure 3). The
conclusion is that if all the suggested changes are implemented, they can
increase production by 10 cars a day. A workshop for suppliers is also proposed.
At 13.00 they present the result sheet to the relevant heads of department,
including Hans-Joachim Paul, head of VW Wolfsburg. Maik, the most gregarious,
makes the presentation, running through the problems identified, the solutions
agreed upon and the timetable for implementing the changes. He finished
with the concrete benefits for VW - a 31% increase in production. Everyone
leaves with the comment from Paul, only partly in jest: &quot;The problem
won't be solved tomorrow. After all, we are in Wolfsburg.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
A month later, at the first follow-up meeting, the mood is ugly. The problems
were certainly not solved tomorrow and even by Wolfsburg's standards are
taking a long time. The workers are disillusioned and the enthusiasm generated
by the workshop is somewhat dissipated. &quot;It's worse than before,&quot;
says Stefan. &quot;There's no point,&quot; says Maik. Going through the
result sheet it soon becomes apparent why. Almost every point that was raised
has not been addressed. <BR>
<BR>
Mats are still loose and heating cables are still under carpets which are
still the wrong colour. Henrik says these problems occurred about five times
the previous week on his shift alone. The floors are still slippery and
the workers must re-explain the points they raised a month ago to a still-credulous
head of the subdivision. An increasingly dour Cain says simply: &quot;We
will have to write another letter.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
There is some good news. Work tables have been fixed to the floor and a
date set for the shelves to be put up. Communication in general is now better
and workers do have access to the relevant telephone and beeper numbers.
The information flow has improved, although Maik is still annoyed that issues
which are indirectly relevant to the section are either not discussed with
them or not passed on at all. The department is also getting new supplies
of non-oily screws on January 6. <BR>
<BR>
Most importantly, the meeting between VW and the carpet suppliers did take
place on November 9. Both the five-door and three-door models were discussed
and the design changed. In the four-door model the new cut is 5mm shorter
than the old one while in the two-door the gap for seat rails has been increased
by 2mm. The other coup is that three workshops for suppliers have been pencilled
in for next year - for metal, upholstery and synthetic parts. <BR>
<BR>
Cain says she understands that the workers are disappointed at the moment,
but promises that something will get done before the next follow-up meeting,
planned for the week of January 22. The workers leave disappointed but still
hopeful. <BR>
<BR>
Since 1993 KVP2 workshops have been applied to all aspects of the Volkwagen
organisation, from administration to suppliers, each with difficulties of
its own. But the process has been a boon for suppliers: average productivity
has increased by 77% for 1,046 firms where VW held workshops between 1993
and late 1995. In fact, the system has been so successful that KVP2 coaching
has been spun off into a separate management consultant-type division, set
to work for organisations ranging from the chemicals giant Bayer to the
German army. <BR>
<BR>
What makes the workshops successful is not only the changes in physical
processes on the shopfloor, but the dissolution of barriers between the
different players in the production process. Should there be another problem
with the carpet design, the workers can prime their foreman to talk directly
to a named designer, not a faceless voice at the end of a telephone. <BR>
<BR>
Nevertheless, although productivity's converts enthuse about what Admiraal
calls his &quot;religion&quot;, achieving world-class productivity in Germany's
auto plants remains elusive. When - or whether - VW can make its necessary
quantum leap is still an open question.<HR> 
<H4>Figure1: cost and productivity per hour in industry</H4>
<BR>
<TABLE BORDER=1 CELLPADDING=1 CELLSPACING=1> <TR><TD><I>Country</I></TD>
