<H4>A VW WORKER IS FOR LIFE </H4>
In its major decisions, Volkswagen must reckon with several parties whose
interests can be diametrically opposed to the reformers in the KVP2 team.
The so-called <I>Mitbestimmung</I> system which gives unions a place on
the supervisory board of the larger companies has contributed to Germany's
industrial success. The system has been valuable in helping to avoid confrontation
between workers and management. But in the case of Volkswagen, the metalworkers'
union IG Metall and the state of Lower Saxony have a blocking vote on the
board and a vital say on issues such as redundancy. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The state <BR>
<BR>
</B>The Wolfsburg workers have a guardian angel in the person of Gerhard
Schr&ouml;der, the high-profile SPD president of Lower Saxony. The state
owns 20% VW's shares, giving Schr&ouml;der a seat on the supervisory board.
The opposition CDU party has said that should it come to power, there would
be no question of it selling off the share. <BR>
<BR>
Mindful of the implications of such power, Daimler-Benz chairman J&uuml;rgen
Schrempp recently rejected a proposal by the mayor of Hamburg for the state
to buy back the company's troubled aerospace arm Dasa, to prevent further
job losses. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The unions <BR>
<BR>
</B>German trade unions have traditionally wielded more influence than their
European colleagues and Klaus Zwickel, president of the metalworkers' union
IG Metall, has a seat on the board. Its high-profile influence is also reflected
in the posters adorning the factory which proclaim, &quot;The breaks stay
as they are,&quot; and in the fact that union duties are carried out during
the working day rather than after it, as at most factories. <BR>
<BR>
The September round of pay negotiations was a hard struggle and VW estimates
that it lost DM300 million due to walkouts. It won the battle, but whether
it will win the war remains to be seen. The union compromised on overtime
pay for Saturday shifts, reducing the five-minute break per hour to two-and-a-half
minutes, and on the flexibility of weekly shifts which can range from 28.8
to 38.8 hours. But in return Volkswagen has agreed not to fire any workers
for the next two years. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The structures - not just the official but also the informal ones
- have been growing over the years and it is hard to get in there,&quot;
says Willem Admiraal at KVP2 management. In any organisation the size of
Volkswagen, factionalism is a factor. Jos&eacute; Ignacio Lopez is director
of production optimisation and purchasing and not director of production
on the board of VW Group. It is a nuance that has much to do with the old
guard. <p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

