<td valign=top align=left> 
<H2>WHO'S AFRAID OF RUSSIA? </H2>
<H4>Russia's surge in support for old-style communists has generated comment
and concern in the west. Stay calm, advises Anatol Lieven </H4>
When journalists use the phrase &quot;critical period&quot; or &quot;vital
turning point&quot;, it usually means that they have run out of things to
say. The difference with Russia is that the critical periods really have
been critical - and another one is on the way. The coming months are likely
to decide whether Russia continues on the halting path of semi-democracy,
swings to some form of overt authoritarianism or, in the worst case, descends
into political violence. <BR>
<BR>
This process is guaranteed to be alarming for many observers. As November's
US presidential elections come closer, accompanied by the usual flood of
stern foreign policy rhetoric, policymakers may well over-react to events
in Russia and in the process help produce exactly the results feared. For
while there is not much the west can do to influence Russian affairs for
the better, there is a lot it can do to make them worse. The key message
is: don't panic. <BR>
<BR>
Not everyone did panic after December 1995's elections to the parliament
or Duma, when the communists emerged as the biggest single party by far.
This is partly because the Duma's powers are limited and partly because
there were mixed messages. Although Zhirinovsky's ultra-nationalists, the
so-called Liberal Democrats, saw their vote halved they still came second
and remain the most prominent of the nationalist groups. More predictably,
the genuine liberal parties were trounced with only Grigory Yavlinsky's
party jumping the 5% hurdle to reach parliament. Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin
was beaten into third place, diminishing his chances of succeeding Boris
Yeltsin in June's presidential elections. <BR>
<BR>
Residual western fear of Russia remains strong and is constantly stoked
by a variety of right-wing politicians and lobbies. The outcome of the parliamentary
poll was enough to reinforce the belief among this group that they face
a return of the Soviet menace which must be countered by faster Nato expansion
into central Europe, rearmament and a &quot;strengthening&quot; of the former
Soviet republics. If they hold sway, relations with Russia will be sucked
into a downward spiral with unforseeable effects on regional stability.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Between dream and ambition </B><BR>
<BR>
In my view, none of this is necessary. While it is obvious that the Russians
retain an ambition to dominate the former Soviet region, it is much more
questionable whether they have the military or economic resources to do
so. Despite his vote Zhirinovsky is probably no longer a presidential threat,
while other leading contenders are fundamentally rational figures who understand
the limitations of Russian power. Given Moscow's economic dependence on
the west and the interest of key elites in retaining stable relations, even
a government playing an authoritarian card at home is unlikely to risk sanctions
by indulging in outright aggression. It will, however, react to what it
sees as Nato aggression. <BR>
<BR>
So who is likely to occupy the Kremlin after June? If the elections are
held as scheduled, such is the dislike and contempt for Yeltsin among ordinary
Russians that an opposition victory is a strong possibility. Yeltsin's unpopularity
is hardly surprising. No politician, least of all a western one, would win
a free election after presiding over the impoverishment of much of his population,
the erosion of his country's status in the world, a massive explosion of
crime and a bloody and unnecessary military debacle on home ground. <BR>
<BR>
Yet the December elections have made it far from clear who is best placed
to challenge Yeltsin. It was formerly thought that General Alexander Lebed
was running ahead of the pack, but his party was badly beaten at the polls.
Throughout, the army showed itself both naive and divided as generals stood
as candidates for different parties and many other ranks voted for the hopeless
Zhirinovsky. Even so, it is probably a mistake to see Lebed as a busted
flush. He received a big vote in his own constituency and has plenty of
time to make himself better known in the rest of the country. For Yeltsin,
the dream opponent from the nationalist camp would be Zhirinovsky if the
election went to a second round. The president's camp knows that many Russians
would not vote for him under any circumstances. <BR>
<BR>
Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov probably lacks the charisma to win: journalists
who spoke to communist voters in December found many saying explicitly that
they would not back Zyuganov for the presidency. There are other possible
candidates in the pro-communist camp including the hardline but impressive
Siberian industrialist Pyotr Romanov and the former Soviet premier Nikolai
Ryzhkov, who is seen as decent and honest. Yet it is doubtful whether Zyuganov
would just meekly step aside for either of these men, raising the prospect
of a damaging split in the victorious communist ranks. <BR>
<BR>
To avoid such an outcome Yeltsin or his close aides, such as the Kremlin
Guard commander General Alexander Korzhakov, might be tempted to violate
the constitution and postpone or cancel the elections. Both the guard and
forces of the Federal Security Service, the successor to the KGB which is
run by Korzhakov's crony General Barsukov, could conceivably be used for
this. It is a risky option, however, which might lead to mass protests,
violence and even attempted <I>coups d'&eacute;tat</I>, although it is also
possible that Yeltsin's opponents would wait in the expectation that his
failing health will save them the trouble. <BR>
<BR>
Of all possible developments, the only one likely to soothe western fears
would be a smooth and democratic handover of power from Yeltsin to Prime
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, a man foreign governments know they can work
with. This is not just because of Chernomyrdin's cautious, pragmatic and
bureaucratic character but because the former energy minister's main support
comes from the oil and gas industries. The energy sector depends utterly
on continued exports to the west and would back no foreign adventure which
might lead to western sanctions against Russia. The only other outcome likely
to be actively welcomed by the west would be victory for the liberal opposition
figure Grigory Yavlinsky. This is possible but very unlikely. Every other
likely outcome would send western commentators scrambling for their word
processors to declare that Russia is fast returning to totalitarianism,
militarism, or imperialism and that defences must be strengthened to meet
the renewed threat. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Growing suspicion of the west </B><BR>
<BR>
But how much of a threat does Russia really present? The new partnership
between Moscow and the west, so trumpeted at the dusk of Gorbachov and dawn
of Yeltsin, is looking decidedly tattered but is not yet completely dead.
Russian participation with the US in the joint Bosnian peacekeeping force,
Russia's membership of Nato's Partnership for Peace and the west's support
for major new IMF loans to Moscow show that both sides retain an interest
in cooperation - albeit from a desire to limit the other side's bad behaviour
rather than from a sense of shared objectives. <BR>
<BR>
However, virtually all the main Russian political groups are now suspicious
of the west. The only major political figure to survive from the old democratic
camp of 1991 is Grigory Yavlinsky. Yet even his political partner, former
ambassador Vladimir Lukin, has been a strong and articulate critic of Nato's
proposed eastward expansion. Indeed, opposition to Nato expansion is now
a universally held view within the Russian establishment. <BR>
<BR>
It is underpinned by a strong belief that in recent years the west has used
the language of universal values and international cooperation to trick
Russia into making unnecessary concessions, for example over defending the
civic rights of Russians in the Baltic states or selling armaments to unstable
areas of the world, and then betraying those ideals whenever its own interests
have so demanded. <BR>
<BR>
According to this new consensus, Russian foreign policy must be guided by
a cold assessment of its own national interests. This does not necessarily
imply cultural anti-western or anti-democratic feeling. <BR>
<BR>
If sensitivity to outside criticism is widespread, so too is the belief
that Russia has a vital interest in retaining some kind of sphere of influence
in the former Soviet Union, at least to the extent of preventing any other
great power or alliance from gaining a military foothold there. In principle,
most Russian leaders would also like to draw all or some of the other former
Soviet republics (with the exception of the Baltic states) into a loose
confederation under Russian hegemony. These open ambitions have become the
stuff of western arguments for Nato expansion, arguments that are likely
to grow much stronger if the political process in Russia throws up a military
president, a communist administration or a Yeltsin dictatorship. <BR>
<BR>
For the west, the main questions to explore are the following: <BR>
<BR>
*Would a victory of the communist or nationalist opposition lead to a violently
anti-western foreign policy and/or strong attempts to subjugate other former
Soviet republics, most notably the economically important Ukraine? <BR>
<BR>
*Would it lead to a massive rolling-back of economic reforms and a renationalisation
of much or all of the private sector, involving a destruction of those business
elements with a stake in continued economic links with the west? <BR>
<BR>
*Is there a greater threat of authoritarian rule from Yeltsin or from the
communist/nationalist opposition and how extreme might such authoritarianism
become? <BR>
<BR>
*How great is the danger that, torn between these currents, central government
in Russia may become effectively paralysed leading to an effective break-up
of Russia along regional lines, a greater criminalisation of society or
even a new civil war? <BR>
<BR>
*What if anything can we do to help? <BR>
<BR>
<B>The land which ideology forgot </B><BR>
<BR>
The first point to keep in mind is that while there is a real threat of
authoritarianism in Russia it will remain limited. There is no possibility
whatsoever that it will lead to renewed totalitarianism, either of the pre-Gorbachev
communist variety or in some new nationalist form. This is because, even
if a developed ideology were to hand, the central Russian state simply does
not have the resources to impose such an ideology on society. <BR>
<BR>
Far too much power has devolved to the regions and republics or lies in
the hands of new social groups. There is no omnipresent, tightly organised
party which could help the state overcome local resistance. The communists
are by far the best organised party - which is why they have done so well
electorally - but to think that they could restore the ideological and social
apparatus of Soviet times is a fantasy. <BR>
<BR>
So too is any thought that Russia could generate a new ideology of world
conquest in the foreseeable future. The Russian communists may not have
become &quot;social democrats&quot; like their equivalents in Poland or
Hungary, but they are very far from being Bolsheviks. They simply do not
have the necessary spirit and are generally much too old. <BR>
<BR>
Russia, if less democratic than many had hoped, is also a great deal more
stable than many had feared. Among the nationalists, neither the relatively
centrist Lebed nor <BR>
the more extreme Alexander Rutskoi and Zhirinovsky possess even the germ
of a <BR>
mass movement akin to that of the Nazis, a necessary condition if the popular
analogy with prewar Weimar Germany were to make any sense. The vast majority
of ordinary Russians are far too apathetic, far too obsessed with economic
survival and far too cynical about politicians in general to be mobilised
in this way. <BR>
<BR>
Seventy years of communist rule led to an immense boredom with the whole
idea of party membership, symbolic marches and demonstrations, party slogans
and so on. This is especially true of educated younger people, among whom
the idea of communism had died long before the reformist Mikail Gorbachov
took power. Today most Russians cannot even tell one political party from
another - not surprising since most party programmes are meaningless and
interchangeable. <BR>
<BR>
It is true that the great majority of Russians hold more or less nationalist
beliefs, often with an imperial tinge. But here one needs to distinguish
between the bar-room sentiments which produced some success for Zhirinovsky
in Duma elections and the actual willingness of ordinary Russians to sacrifice
blood or money to achieve their supposed goals. Opinion polls have shown
most Russians to be opposed or thoroughly unenthusiastic about the use of
the army in Chechnya, for example, despite a traditional deep dislike for
the Chechens which led many observers (and perhaps the Russian government)
to assume that any intervention would be popular. The war has also been
deeply unpopular in the army itself and demoralisation of the Russian troops
in Chechnya was obvious from the very beginning. <BR>
<BR>
The threat of authoritarianism is now a very real one, mainly because authoritarian
rule under the right leadership would be extremely popular in a country
yearning for a crackdown on crime and the restoration of certain basic services
and social guarantees. Democratic values are often barely skin-deep, even
among so-called liberals. Business supporters of President Yeltsin, fearful
of a return of the communists, have begun to talk of the need for a &quot;Russian
Pinochet&quot; to guarantee the continuation of free market reform or, as
their critics believe, the continuation of ill-gotten gains. From the opposition,
General Lebed has argued in the same terms. So far, however, moves in this
direction have been very limited, as shown by the generally unsuccessful
attempts at censorship during the Chechen fighting. While the free media
is endangered, it is still genuinely free: the independent television station
NTV continues to broadcast its satirical puppet show &quot;Kukhli&quot;
with its savage portrayals of Yeltsin and his staff. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Letting inflation off the leash </B><BR>
<BR>
An authoritarian regime could undoubtedly do a good deal of economic damage,
not least by letting inflation off the leash once again. But however populist
its rhetoric, it could not possibly set about renationalising most of the
property privatised over the past three years. <BR>
<BR>
The key once again is the regions. Any central government now has to rule
through the regional administrative and managerial elites which have profited
immensely from privatisation and which are thoroughly intertwined with the
banks and corporate sector. They would simply not tolerate any return to
the <I>status quo ante</I>. <BR>
<BR>
Private business is now backing every single major party. General Lebed's
main political partner, former deputy premier Yuri Skokov, is closely linked
to the military-industrial complex whose senior managers have been made
rich by privatisation and the sometimes illegal sale of <I>materiel </I>to
the west. Even the communists have at least two big businessmen on their
electoral list, including a representative of the huge Most Bank conglomerate
which has put its eggs in several political baskets. <BR>
<BR>
Despite such strong business links, any new regime might still conduct a
highly public review of some privatisation cases and might select a few
symbolic businessmen for punishment. This is one reason why those businessmen
seen as close to the Yeltsin regime are worried sick, appealing to western
sympathisers and journalists to support an authoritarian &quot;rescue&quot;
of the economic reform process. Given the way many of them acquired their
wealth and how they like to spend it, however, there is no need to feel
very much personal sympathy for these people. <BR>
<BR>
Would a more authoritarian domestic regime be more likely to pursue an aggressive
external policy? If it were in the hands of unstable extremists such as
Zhirinovsky or Rutskoi, the answer would certainly be yes. Fortunately,
however, their victory looks unlikely. If Yeltsin is replaced it will be
either by some pragmatic figure from within the regime, a communist-backed
candidate or a relatively moderate nationalist like Lebed. <BR>
<BR>
More importantly, for the foreseeable future any Russian regime will be
subject to extremely tight constraints beyond the country's borders as superpower
status is a thing of the past. The extent of Russian weakness has been harshly
demonstrated by its failure to prevent or even influence American actions
in Bosnia. As commentator Dmitri Babich put it: &quot;Russia has been forced
to concoct the most absurd excuses in order to conceal the deplorable fact
of its own impotence.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
In their private arguments against Nato expansion, diplomats have been reduced
to warning that Russia will be powerful again some time in the future and
the west should therefore be careful not to throw away its friendship unnecessarily:
&quot;You will need us again if China turns nasty&quot; is a common refrain.
As a matter of fact this makes good sense, but an argument based on what
might be the case several years from now fails to cut much ice with western
policymakers worried about more immediate pressures. <BR>
<BR>
Even if Russia had the ideology and leadership to carry out a major act
of aggression, there is no money to bankroll such an adventure. The central
state is chronically short of money because of a large-scale collapse in
the collection of revenue, in the face of massive tax evasion and official
corruption. If a new government can recreate an effective state apparatus,
the Russian state might again become a formidable force in 10 years' time.
At the moment, however, corruption and criminality have become so embedded
that for the foreseeable future it looks likely to preside ineffectually
over a semi-anarchy. The effects of revenue shortfalls on the armed forces
were starkly revealed by the engagement in Chechnya, where bad training
and equipment intensified troop demoralisation and lack of discipline. An
effective Russian army would need to be subjected to a major campaign against
pervasive corruption and receive a massive inflow of funds to make the forces
professional. <BR>
<BR>
There is also no will at present to subjugate the former Soviet republics
of Ukraine and the Baltic states by force, nor indeed for the kind of massive
financial sacrifices necessary to draw Ukraine into a closer economic union
with Russia. Moscow has even refused to create a currency union with Belarus,
despite pleas from Minsk. Put plainly, Russia is close to bankruptcy. The
money to subsidise a new imperium is simply not available. <BR>
<BR>
Ukraine, a valuable and historically key part of the former Soviet empire,
has been a particular flashpoint. But it is simply too big a morsel to be
swallowed, while most Russians regard the Ukrainians as erring brothers.
The Yeltsin administration has pursued an extremely cautious policy over
discontented ethnic Russians living in Crimea and has not allowed a dispute
over the Black Sea fleet to get out of hand. <BR>
<BR>
Even in the divided and embattled Transcaucasus Moscow has been more cautious
than many analysts appreciate, if only because there is in fact no Caucasian
policy as such. Every ministry and interest group has pursued its own agenda.
Moscow's recent agreement to an oil pipeline from Azerbaijan passing through
Georgia and Turkey, rather than Russian territory, is a welcome indication
that pragmatists can still get their way. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Surprises and how to avoid them </B><BR>
<BR>
It is my belief that in the end, Russia will accept Nato membership for
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic as long as Nato makes clear it is
not going to expand any further, and as long as Russia receives some kind
of compensation in other fields. But for this process of gradual acceptance
to continue, the expansion itself must be gradual and exclude surprise moves
such as the US declaration of support for Nato expansion in November 1994.
<BR>
<BR>
But there are some scenarios which would change everything. A rushed invitation
for central Europe to join Nato could generate Russian aggression over the
Baltic states, particularly if it looked as if they too might join a fearful
stampede. Western European officials have repeatedly assured the Russians
in private that there is no chance of this happening, but the Russians feel
that they have been tricked so often that they have no great faith left
in western promises. The Russian army in particular regards the possibility
of Nato expansion into Ukraine and Russia as a mortal geopolitical threat.
Lebed is a prime representative of this element in society and has expressed
himself in almost hysterical terms on the subject, warning in the event
of a &quot;Third World War&quot;. Yet he strongly opposed military operations
in Chechnya and Tajikistan and has told me that he regards the notion of
war with Ukraine for Crimea as &quot;inconceivable&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
This illustrates a key point for the west: there is no will in the Russian
establishment to take the risks of a drive westwards, unless this is seen
as an essential response to Nato's advance eastwards. If the eastern half
of Europe becomes destabilised in the next year, it will be the doing of
the west, not Russia. <BR>
<BR>
The other possible major western mistake would be to allow fear of Lebed,
the army or the communists to panic policymakers into overt or tacit support
for a suspension of democracy by Yeltsin's team. In October 1993, western
support for Yeltsin's bloody military assault on rebels in the parliament
could be justified in terms of his own democratic legitimacy, the threat
of chaos or a truly hardline backlash. But for the west today to support
the installation of a Yeltsin dictatorship would be something very different.
To support a coup engineered by the former hardmen of the Soviet system,
the KGB and their newfound friends in the private sector would be utterly
wrong and would destroy what remains of western moral influence in Russia.
<BR>
<BR>
The best western policy in the months to come should be to watch and wait,
while continuing a dialogue with Russia wherever this seems useful. In diplomacy
as in life, if you're not sure what to do, there is a strong case for doing
nothing.<BR>
<BR>
<I>Anatol Lieven is a correspondent for The Times in Moscow. His previous
postings included the Baltic states, Czechoslovakia and Afghanistan</I><BR><BR>
<HR width=60%>
<H3>THE MAGNIFICENT 7 </H3>
<H4>Seven crucial figures in this year's battle for control of the Kremlin </H4>
<B>Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin </B><BR><BR>
A former apparatchik and cautious pragmatic, Chernomyrdin is now regarded
by western governments as a man they can do business with. Critics accuse
him of using his official positions to acquire immense private wealth through
undeclared shares in the huge semi-privatised gas company Gasprom which
he used to head. His strongest support, both political and financial, continues
to come from the oil and gas sector. Among the Russian public he is not
actively unpopular, like Boris Yeltsin, but he is an uninspiring figure
and it is difficult to say how he would do in a free presidential election.<BR><BR>
<B>Lt General Alexander Korzhakov </B><BR>
A former KGB officer assigned to guard Yeltsin when Gorbachev first moved
him to Moscow in 1985 and since then his closest friend: Yeltsin writes
glowingly of Korzhakov in the latest volume of his autobiography and he
is now generally regarded as the president's closest adviser. Today Korzhakov
commands the presidential guard, which on paper at least has a strength
of 40,000 men. He is also very close to Mikhail Barsukov, chief of the Federal
Security Service, the former KGB. During Yeltsin's latest bout of heart
trouble in October, Korzhakov was often the only aide allowed access for
more than a few minutes. He must know that if Yeltsin goes, he goes too
and might then face imprisonment for various alleged abuses of authority.
According to reports, he has urged Yeltsin to hang on at all costs.<BR><BR> 
<B>Lt General Alexander Lebed </B><BR>
Joint leader of the opposition Congress of Russian Communities (KRO), originally
founded to defend ethnic Russians beyond the republic's borders but now
a broad umbrella group including both hardline nationalists and minority
Tatar and Bashkin groups. An alarming-looking figure, whose name means swan
but whose face and voice are more reminiscent of a gorilla, he is apparently
regarded by Yeltsin's staff as their most dangerous opponent. He is certainly
the most charismatic of all the potential candidates and appeals to the
current longing for &quot;order&quot; and a strong hand. From his time as
commander of the 14th Army in the troubled region of Moldova, he has won
a reputation for incorruptibility, discipline and moral courage. But he
has to contend with the traditional Russian distrust of Bonapartist figures.
Moreover, he has shown signs of being out of his depth in the new world
of politics, leading to explosions of anger which could harm his image as
a sober leader.<BR><BR> 
<B>Yuri Skokov </B><BR>
Joint leader of KRO and a grey figure from the old Soviet state. He was
deputy premier from 1991 to 1993 but was sacked by Yeltsin for opposing
his moves against the hostile parliament of the time. He is closely linked
to heavy industry, the military-industrial complex and provincial leaders
in the Volga region. Without Skokov's support Lebed would probably not have
the establishment backing or financial support to run for president. However,
Skokov has also been close to Yeltsin's chief of staff Viktor Ilyushin.
In one scenario, there have been backstage negotiations about Yeltsin sacking
Chernomyrdin and appointing Skokov in his place to help the current president
hang onto power. Skokov himself would then have a good chance of winning
the presidency when Yeltsin finally drops off his perch.<BR><BR> 
<B>Grigory Yavlinsky </B><BR>
Leader of the Yabloka party and the last major liberal to retain any mass
popularity, largely because he was out of power when Yegor Gaidar implemented
bitterly unpopular free market reforms in 1992. Yavlinsky is determined
to run for president, but as a Jewish Muscovite intellectual is thought
unlikely to succeed in winning many votes in the provinces.<BR><BR> 
<B>Vladimir Zhirinovsky </B><BR>
Leader of the grotesquely misnamed &quot;Liberal Democratic Party&quot;,
he is half neo-fascist, half clown. He remains prominent but has seen his
support badly reduced by competition from Lebed and Alexander Rutskoi, both
of whom appeal to the same electorate in a more sober way. Zhirinovsky has
been discredited by public drunkenness, brawling, hooliganism, allegations
of homosexuality, an electoral list containing numerous criminals - you
name it. However, such is the mixture of apathy and disgust with politics
among many Russians that he could still do surprisingly well. There is also
word of calculations among Yeltsin's staff that a second-round presidential
election run-off between Yeltsin and Zhirinovsky might produce a surge of
support for Yeltsin, both among voters and in the west.<BR><BR> 
<B>Valery Zyuganov </B><BR>
Leader of the Communist Party of the Russian Federation, the main successor
to the old Soviet Communist party and by far the best organised party in
Russia today, Zyuganov has recently been making efforts to portray his party
as social democratic,like former communists in central Europe. At a meeting
with US businessmen in October, he said he wanted to reverse illegal and
corrupt privatisations and restore social welfare rather than re-nationalise
the entire economy. Not all of his audience were convinced, remembering
past fiery communist rhetoric. Zyuganov's problem is that while his party
is strong, he himself is an uncharismatic figure generally thought to stand
little chance of winning an election. He may therefore decide to stand back
and back a more promising candidate, such as Gorbachev's former prime minister<BR><BR>
Nikolai Ryzhkov<.p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

