<td valign=top align=left>
<H2>JAPAN MARKET WHAT MARKET?</H2>
<H4>Orthodox economists have ignored a key institution, born in war, which
makes concepts like profit close to irrelevant. Karel van Wolferen explains
why </H4>
Japan scares economists. It is a horror story for the few who have not ignored
it because the more trained they are in economic orthodoxy, the less capable
they are of understanding the dynamics of the Japanese economy. With their
market-centred thinking, mainstream economists cannot possibly make sense
of what is, in effect, a war economy operating in peacetime. <BR>
<BR>
The world's second largest economy remains a blur on the periphery of most
people's vision, including those in positions which require it to be in
clear focus. Rather than improving as interaction with Japan intensified,
this odd phenomenon has only worsened: since reports of serious financial
and industrial trouble began to circulate some years ago, confusion has
been the norm. Conflicting images coexist, sometimes in the minds of the
same observers, of impending doom and of a Japan consolidating its forces
in a peacetime &quot;greater co-prosperity sphere.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Puzzlement is mixed with a new ambivalence, particularly among US financial
authorities, about the intentions and trustworthiness of Japan's economic
guardians. In Tokyo, officials of the Ministry of Finance (MOF) appear determined
to ensure that Japanese financial institutions do nothing to help trigger
any increase in US interest rates, especially in an American presidential
election year. Yet the failure of these same officials to inform their US
colleagues about the irregularities perpetrated by Daiwa Bank angered the
Federal Reserve enough for it to shut down all of Daiwa's American operations.
<BR>
<BR>
What is the story on Japan? Do alarming suggestions of an impending financial
meltdown have any foundation? Are Americans and Europeans right in asserting
that Japanese industrial might is no longer a serious challenge? Does Japan's
longest postwar period of sluggishness indicate fundamental difficulties
for which the formerly resourceful bureaucrats have no solution? What is
one to think of an economy whose main stockmarket recently lost about half
its value in less than a year, but which busily continues to invest in skyscrapers?
<BR>
<BR>
The main reason for this confusion is the existence of conceptual filters
that make invisible many of Japan's essentials: in particular that of mainstream
economics which tells us that markets are pivotal institutions in determining
economic outcomes. This filter is imposed by all but a very few university
economic courses and maintained by publications such as <I>The Wall Street
Journal</I>, <I>The Economist</I> and <I>The Financial Times</I> whose reports
are echoed all over the world. Allegiance to the conceptual world thus created
is a fundamental requirement for appointment and promotion in Anglo-Saxon
academia and for membership of many western political elites. <BR>
<BR>
But Japan is too important to remain so blurred. We need to look at an economic
institution other than the market which will allow us to make better sense
of it. This institution, brought to a high level of effectiveness by Japan's
economic guardians, does not yet have a name but I propose to call it credit
ordering. It works through highly coordinated credit creation, credit denial
and credit allocation. It is rooted in wartime financing methods and wartime
restrictions on entrepeneurism. Since 1945 it has been pivotal in determining
economic outcomes in Japan. <BR>
<BR>
The most important result of credit ordering has been the removal of credit
risk for large corporations. Totally socialised credit risk provides entire
sectors with the wherewithal to engage in massive expansion and campaigns
to enlarge international market share without regard to demand or profitability.
Credit ordering also ensures the hierarchical order of Japanese industry
and has become a condition for the survival of a highly effective industrial
organisation. <BR>
<BR>
One reason why this crucial phenomenon has barely attracted attention in
the west, why it has remained invisible in economic theory and why it easily
eludes our conceptual grasp is that it does not rest on any theoretical
underpinnings. It evolved through trial and error under the guidance of
officials, many of whom had managed Japan's industrial effort during 15
years of war in Asia. Their main concern was that nothing should ever stand
in the way of building ever-greater productive capacity. Credit ordering
operates in an economy in which transactions are based, in the final analysis,
not on economic considerations of profit-making but on political ones of
mutual protection and long-term expansionist goals. <BR>
<BR>
To make sense of credit ordering we need to understand the way two huge
intersecting structures ensure order among Japan's large corporations: the
horizontal <I>keiretsu</I> and the web of federations or industrial associations
in every branch of industry. They perform powerful complementary functions
that are extralegal and frequently at odds with official regulations, such
as the anti-trust laws enforced in theory by Japan's Fair Trade Commission.
The six large <I>keiretsu</I> that tie together companies in different industrial
sectors only began to draw attention in the US around 1989; the many associations
that coordinate the activities of companies in the same industry have remained
largely ignored. <BR>
<BR>
Details differ considerably from one <I>keiretsu </I>to the next, but typically
it groups large manufacturers in major branches of industry, clustered around
a bank and a trading company. Non-life and life insurance firms also belong.
Corporate policies are not dictated to individual members by an all-powerful
<I>keiretsu</I> centre since no such entity exists. But the assertive tendencies
of each firm are strongly curtailed by the informal commands of group integration,
mistakenly represented in Japanese parlance as loyalty - mistakenly,
because they have no choice. A few very powerful companies - Toyota
comes immediately to mind - need not worry much about fellow <I>keiretsu</I>
members but the rest must obey what the group decides, regardless of any
disadvantage to themselves. Such companies own each other, making orthodox
notions of ownership close to irrelevant. Power in Japan's large corporations
is diffuse to a point where accountability is practically non-existent.
The fact that no one is ultimately in charge of the <I>keiretsu</I> clusters
nor ultimately responsible for them means they are sufficiently amorphous
to permit industry-wide bureaucratic interference. <BR>
<BR>
Instead of emanating directly from government ministries, interference is
mostly channelled through the industrial associations. Sometimes dominated
by one or two of the largest corporations, these monitor and control all
industrial sectors, coordinate production plans in developing or shrinking
sectors, help with collective technology acquisition and give direction
to development at the highest levels. Top officials are frequently retired
bureaucrats from government agencies administering that sector. Major decisions
are as binding as if they were law. Since non-membership means virtual exclusion
from the economic mainstream, and Japanese firms do not in practice have
recourse to legal means of asserting themselves, all companies fall under
the informal jurisdiction of these cartel-like structures. <BR>
<BR>
Contrary to popular belief, <I>keiretsu</I> are not simply postwar versions
of the earlier <I>zaibatsu</I>. They are a novel form of industrial organisation,
considerably more dependent on support from the bureaucracy. The <I>zaibatsu</I>
had been largely reluctant participants in Japan's war in China and against
the US, and in the final years of fighting the government found it necessary
to introduce ways of tying Japan's manufacturing more closely to the war
effort. <BR>
<BR>
This paved the way for a set of industrial relationships that made the postwar
credit ordering possible. The Bank of Japan gained control over the commercial
banks with the establishment of the Monetary Control Association in 1942.
A year later, bureaucrats in the MOF and Ministry of Munitions (institutional
parent of MITI, the ministry of trade and industry) designed a system of
&quot;authorised financial institutions&quot; to pay for the war. The <I>zaibatsu</I>
banks were selected for this purpose, along with the government's Industrial
Bank of Japan. Backed by 56 smaller banks designated to &quot;absorb funds
from the private sector,&quot; insurers and the savings system, together
they ensured an unimpeded flow of funds to firms ordered to meet the requirements
of the military. These arrangements became the basis for the postwar &quot;main
bank&quot; system which guarantees that large corporations never go bankrupt.
And they foreshadowed the <I>keiretsu</I> banks' function as inexhaustible
money pumps during the high-growth '50s and '60s. <BR>
<BR>
The occupying American authorities inadvertently promoted bureaucratic power
over business when they disbanded the holding companies which had been the
control centres of the <I>zaibatsu</I>. This removed potential opposition
to government officials, who in the late '40s began applying at home what
they had learned from the forced industrial development of their wartime
Manchurian colony. Without the holding companies, economic decision-making
was transferred from bureaucracies in private hands to a bureaucracy guided
by financial mandarins in government, with decisive power over the allocation
of scarce capital. <BR>
<BR>
Shortly after the departure of the occupying US authorities, a practice
known as &quot;overloan&quot; and &quot;overborrowing&quot; became common,
radically changing the financing of Japanese industry. Inspired by the wartime
financing of munition companies, the large banks increased their lending
to companies belonging to their group (only later did the term <I>keiretsu</I>
emerge) without being required to make proportionately larger deposits with
the central bank. <BR>
<BR>
Japan has been the only major industrial country in which, for most of its
high growth period, loans from and discounts with the central bank exceeded
the deposits of the commercial banks. Whereas the prewar average rate of
borrowed money fluctuated between just under and just over a third of the
total assets of Japanese companies (roughly similar to the postwar pattern
in western industrialised countries), between the '50s and the end of the
'70s it rose to four-fifths of capital of an average company. <BR>
<BR>
The unleashing of postwar entrepreneurial enthusiasm was undoubtedly important
for what became known as Japan's economic miracle. But at the same time
many rules curtailed entrepreneurial freedom, most of them informal and
extralegal. The private sector became thoroughly dependent on the central
bureaucracy while methods of forced economic development were applied to
the rebuilding of Japan's war-devastated economy. The dependency of big
business on central coordination and protection increased further as the
policies of postwar reconstruction evolved into an unofficial policy of
unlimited industrial expansion. This national policy was never examined
by the Japanese parliament, nor explicitly discussed in any public forum.
<BR>
<BR>
As a result, Japan's industrial organisation is less similar today to those
of traditional free enterprise countries than it was in the '20s. The greatest
difference is that besides enforcing property rights as a fundamental economic
role of government, Japan's officialdom also enforces what may be called
credit rights. Consumer credit remained virtually unknown until the '70s
and continues to be restrained, rigged by custom in favour of retailers.
Rigid sluices in the financial system have ensured that the comparatively
large pool of household savings is made available for industrial investment.
<BR>
<BR>
Prices in the Japanese consumer economy are almost wholly fixed, and allow
for a very heavy <I>de facto </I>tax with which Japanese households help
subsidise export industries considered &quot;strategic&quot;. Over the last
25 years, as the value of the yen against the dollar increased fourfold,
Japan's exporters have seen their profit-margins dwindle to almost nothing,
requiring the systematic subsidy of Japanese industry by the <I>keiretsu</I>
banks. Until 1990 such banks showed positive results on their books only
because of the impact of inflationary equity and real estate markets. Contrary
to frequent reports of diminishing bureaucratic influence and greater independence
in the private sector, the past two decades have seen a consolidation of
power by the <I>keiretsu</I> and industrial association system. The natural
result has been the erasure, for all practical purposes, of any division
between private and public sectors. <BR>
<BR>
Dissatisfied western trading partners have long decried Japanese government
interference, creating artificial economic advantage for the country's firms,
and have applauded plans for deregulation. But in Japan deregulation is
normally replaced by informal arrangements that accomplish the same protective
aims, as the entire system has no choice but to strive for Japanese advantage.
There are no impartial regulators scrutinising important economic transactions
and wrong-doing in this realm is not subject to legal process. Neither the
Bank of Japan, nor the MOF which controls it, function as a referee. They
are fundamentally different institutions compared to central banks elsewhere
in the industrialised world. Hence it should be no surprise that the MOF
felt no compelling need to inform the world's central bankers what Daiwa
Bank had been up to. <BR>
<BR>
Outside the bank-supported core of Japanese industrial organisation there
is little opportunity for a solitary entrepreneur dependent on long-term
domestic investment to flourish. Capital markets comparable to those of
Europe or the US do not exist. Only a few medium-sized companies can establish
a market niche allowing them the freedom to make their own decisions. Small
companies in service sector areas considered marginal, such as hairdressers,
fashion businesses and small retailers, have access to more expensive funding
but find significant expansion almost impossible without linking up in some
way with a <I>keiretsu</I> or smaller <I>keiretsu</I>-like cluster. <BR>
<BR>
The relations smaller manufacturers have with their &quot;mother&quot; firms
is the sole determinant of their creditworthiness. Many retailers are wholly
or partly ensconced in so-called distribution <I>keiretsu</I>: dealer associations
with which manufacturers control their domestic market shares, a system
especially visible in the consumer electronics sector. <BR>
<BR>
Large manufacturers are themselves often the stellar centres of huge planetary
systems, with 100 or more subcontractors, known as vertical <I>keiretsu</I>.
The upper tier of well-known names rests on a thick pile of shock-absorbing
factories and sweatshops, parts-makers that go bankrupt in large numbers
in times of economic shifts and reappear making different items. Their credit
needs are looked after not by the banks but by the <I>keiretsu</I> trading
companies. These organisations, which might better be termed business brokers,
strengthen still further the system of centralised control and operate as
huge industrial information centres capable of calculating risk in nearly
every area of economic activity. <BR>
<BR>
The enforcement of credit rights is more or less accepted as a fact of nature
by Japanese businessmen. But one example of credit denial was spectacularly
demonstrated by the Lion's Oil case in the summer of 1984. A maverick entrepreneur
saw a potential fortune in importing refined oil from Singapore. There were
no official guidelines to suggest it could not be done, because neither
MITI nor the Japan's oil refiners' association had anticipated that anyone
would ever have the temerity to disturb an order based on informal agreement
whereby all refining had to take place in Japan. MITI's reaction to Lion's
Oil experimentation was instantaneous: its domestic credit lines were cut.
And such was the ministry's influence in Singapore, its fiat was enforced
there too. <BR>
<BR>
Japan's authorities have had the advantage of not being held back by theory
as they tried to face the challenge of limited scarce resources. In applying
credit ordering they have simply followed methods that worked in practice.
They derive their legitimacy in the eyes of the business world from the
fact that they have always been able to make things go around, which is
why they cannot afford to let even small financial institutions go bankrupt.
<BR>
<BR>
Japan's extraordinary industrial interdependence has all but eliminated
any parties that voice their own, conflicting, ideas about what constitutes
economic reality. As a result the mandarins have frequently accomplished
feats that westerners would automatically believe impossible. In the second
half of the '80s, during the so-called bubble economy, Japan's large corporations
had access to nearly free capital as the doubling or tripling of real estate
values appeared to justify the rise of Japanese equities to astronomical
levels, and vice versa. The common assumption among western commentators,
governments and businessmen was that this was due to waves of wild speculation
by independent investors, but such a view only highlights the systematic
misinterpretation of Japanese economic reality. Speculators were exploiting
the situation, to be sure, but they were marginal and many were ruined.
<BR>
<BR>
What Japan experienced was not a bubble in the accepted meaning of the term.
The bubble never burst and the authorities, initiators of the bubble-blowing,
managed a gradual and controlled deflation. It began in 1985, when the MOF
implicitly encouraged banks to increase their lending significantly. Until
then year-on-year growth in Japanese bank lending had roughly tracked that
of nominal GNP, but it suddenly soared to much higher levels. Between 1986
and 1991 total bank lending doubled. At the peak of the bubble, land in
Tokyo and three adjoining suburban prefectures was worth as much as all
land in the us, which is 26 times bigger, plus the net worth of all companies
listed on the New York stock exchange. Price-earnings ratios on the Tokyo
stockmarket climbed in this period to between 4 and 6 times their level
in London and New York. <BR>
<BR>
Such huge additions to the paper wealth of Japan's large corporations, created
in the absence of whistle-blowing from within the bureaucratic/business
elite, were used as collateral for a variety of financing methods which
effectively brought the real cost of capital down to practically nothing.
Such methods - equity warrant bonds on the Euromarket were a favourite
- enabled industry to offset the dire effects of the huge yen appreciation
as it launched the largest wave of plant and equipment investment in history.
Credit ordering operations during the bubble accelerated the steady transfer
of wealth from the household to the industrial sector. The bubble was fed
by family savings that found their way to the stockmarket through insurance
companies and trust banks. After the mandarins decided on a guided deflation
and the market shrunk dramatically, Japanese households and financial intermediaries
saw trillions of yen wiped out, but industry still possesses the assets
that these investments financed. <BR>
<BR>
Today Japan's financial system is beset with problems as a result of unpayable
loans dating from the bubble period, combined with global economic sluggishness
that has caused huge overcapacity. But what should hold the attention of
the world's economists is the extraordinary story, not of its problems,
but of its survival. Japan's financial mandarins, financiers and top industrialists
have so much informal control over the economy that they were able to insulate
horrendous inflation in capital assets from the consumer economy and then
prevent economic collapse when the stockmarket lost over a third of its
value in six months. To top it all, they have until now staved off the collapse
of a banking system that is technically bankrupt, saddled as it is with
the equivalent of perhaps a trillion dollars or more in problem loans (no
one knows exactly -- the semi-official figure has grown from 10 trillion
to 40 trillion yen). And while there has been talk of a Japanese banking
crisis, it is not a genuine crisis of the kind leading to fundamental reforms
in the way an economy is managed. <BR>
<BR>
So why is Japan's credit ordering not better known as an institution, and
why do Japan's leaders not explicitly acknowledge its existence? Part of
the answer is that the Japanese economy would be undermined if its built-in
hierarchical preferences were made official, and thereby a target for potential
protest. <BR>
<BR>
Firms that took part in the original bubble-blowing were rewarded by systematic
compensation, paid for by securities houses as a hedge against major losses.
When this became known it caused a scandal, showing that important aspects
of Japan's credit ordering must be kept out of sight if it is to survive.
Another reason why the institution is not acknowledged explicitly must be
the lack of a conceptual language with which the Japanese can explain it
to themselves. In the absence of an ongoing public debate about social and
political desirables, Japanese explanations are never forced to reach a
level of realism. Academics, media commmentators and officialdom in Japan
excel in forcing round pegs into square holes as they explain developments
almost entirely in terms of conventional market-centred economics. But imperfections
of the market -- to use orthodox terminology for privileged access to resources
and buyers -- are so omnipresent in Japan that the market can only perform
a subsidiary function. <BR>
<BR>
The Japanese market is an administered market. Prices, not mainly dependent
on supply and demand, are set by sellers on the basis of schemes that serve
a goal other than economic efficiency. At the lower levels, market forces
tend to be more significant but competition remains highly controlled. In
sectors affected by rapidly developing technology, corporate rivalry is
sometimes actively stimulated and can become fierce, but when the controlling
agents have decided that &quot;excessive competition&quot; is harmful to
the industrial order, pressure is exerted for the parties concerned to accept
existing market shares. Incentive structures in Japanese industry deviate
widely from what is taken for granted in mainstream economics. The main
bodies animating Japan's economy frequently behave with utter disregard
for conventional market considerations. While profitmaking is ultimately
considered desirable, it has in practice not been a primary concern for
the large <I>keiretsu</I> corporations. <BR>
<BR>
The Japanese economy should exhilarate economists, since it could throw
light on old controversies in their field and inspire new ideas. Their most
important conclusion should be that sound economic theory cannot accept
the market as the universally pivotal institution of economies. But orthodoxy
and its sustaining institutions are stronger than the human thirst for knowledge.
Stymied by their trained incapacity to understand an economy in which the
market does not regulate production, all but a handful of economists have
turned their backs on the second largest industrial power in the world,
a neglect that can be confirmed by going through the indices of economic
theoretical works or textbooks. <BR>
<BR>
Japan's credit ordering has major international repercussions. One of its
consequences is that several areas of industry are reserved at an early
stage in their development to become a Japanese monopoly in the future,
as they are unlikely to attract US or European investments. Credit ordering
has also become a dominant factor in the geopolitically critical US-Japan
relationship. Japanese planners have enjoyed a great advantage from US policies
inspired by free trade ideology, while at the same time depending heavily
on an American protective diplomatic and strategic shield. Japan would not
have been such a successful industrial power had the US not accepted its
walled-off financial system and the rapid expansion of Japanese shares in
its own market, to the considerable disadvantage of American industry. <BR>
<BR>
During the Cold War the bilateral bargain consisted of Japan constituting
what former prime minister Yasuhiro Nakasone once called an &quot;unsinkable
aircraft-carrier&quot; moored off the coasts of the Soviet Union and China.
This function has become significantly less compelling as an argument for
American indulgence of Japanese methods. <BR>
<BR>
A new bargain has been struck, rooted in the discovery by the Reagan administration
that Japan would finance the US budget deficit. In the late '80s the MOF
ordered institutional investors to continue buying US treasury bonds, notwithstanding
predictably huge exchange rate losses. According to some estimates, the
US financial system is dependent on Japan for roughly 10% of its credit
needs, as American banks also borrow short-term from Japanese banks, and
MOF &quot;guidance&quot; plays a decisive part in keeping down US interest
rates. In turn, to accommodate the desires of the MOF, in August 1995 the
US treasury secretary helped engineer a temporary reversal in the yen's
rise against the dollar. This new bargain is unlikely to ensure a stable
relationship, as the forces involved are too volatile and the two governments
cannot openly discuss its details. Future officials in Washington may not
understand it and misjudge it. And the American authorities already have
doubts about the soundness of Japan's financial system, as realisation dawns
about its extraordinary character. <BR>
<BR>
Japan's financial mandarins face being caught in a horrible dilemma. They
know that they cannot make urgently needed adjustments to industrial and
financial structures without diminishing their own control over these structures.
But the assertion that Japan's officials are currently being defeated &quot;by
the market&quot; are, to put it mildly, premature. The majority of economists
will never get Japan straight, because market-centred economics is a faith.
But for those who want to study how a war economy works in peacetime, for
the foreseeable future Japan is likely to remain the ideal laboratory.<BR>
<BR>
<I>Karel van Wolferen is author of The Enigma of Japanese Power (Knopf),
and books in Japanese on civil society and citizenship. He is currently
writing on the bureaucratisation of the world. </I><p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
