<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra9.gif" alt="Feature">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 
<H2>RELIEF INC </H2>
<H4>A battle for the soul of the aid industry is being fought as it moves
on from high street jumble sales and collecting tins to become an fully
fledged industry, says Nick Cater </H4>
In flowing robes and suits they came from every part of the world to discuss
the future of their business, a multinational with 128 million workers and
a fast-growing annual turnover of around $19 billion in 163 countries from<BR>
America to Zimbabwe. <BR>
<BR>
But the hundreds of managers gathering in Geneva in December had no profit
forecasts to read. Instead, at the quadrennial conference of the International
Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement, the packed agenda covered war and hunger,
refugees and disease and how to help the 250 million people affected every
year by conflict, famine and flood. <BR>
<BR>
The movement is the world's most experienced, extensive humanitarian network.
Its unique role is recognised by governments. Yet alongside fundamental
principles of humanity and neutrality, it is increasingly run like a major
global enterprise with professional marketers, accountants and managers,
taskforces and strategic business plans. <BR>
<BR>
While the new professionalism is to be applauded, however, it is part of
the struggle now raging for the soul of the aid industry. For although the
relief agencies have much to learn from business, their work involves ethical
decisions which need values and principles to back them up. In many cases
the market model is irrelevant since &quot;consumers&quot; are the poor
and powerless and decisions are made by people giving the money, not taking
it. As charities seeking efficiency become like companies and companies
seeking the &quot;halo effect&quot; offer aid, both must be keenly honest
about where their respective strengths lie and must find new ways of working
together if we are to get aid which is both low-cost and purposeful. <BR>
<BR>
Like other industries the aid business is evolving fast and becoming increasingly
complex, the greatest change of all being the growing market for disasters.
Take the intricacy of a Washington-funded deployment of an operation involving
the US Army and a commercial Californian contractor, Portable Water Supply
Systems (PWSS), to provide clean water in Zaire at the height of the 1994
cholera emergency. The contractor worked closely with the UN and non-governmental
organisations (NGOS) and was vigorous in delivering water and promoting
its success. The water company said it had halted a cholera epidemic and
saved 140,000 lives at a cost of seven cents per life saved, claims which
probably irritated relief agencies present in the camps at Goma. <BR>
<BR>
Global television channels such as CNN International have helped force disasters
onto domestic political agendas. With conflict more visible, emergency aid
is booming: at least 5.8% or $3.2 billion of overseas development assistance
goes on emergencies, and the figure could be as much as $8 billion. In 1971
OECD emergency aid was $200 million; in 1994, $1 billion went on Rwanda
alone. <BR>
<BR>
The average number of people affected by disasters is growing by roughly
10 million a year. War is a new field: until 1989 the UN and most aid agencies
avoided battlefields but flak-jacketed aid workers now see plenty of action.
In 1994, there were some 50 conflicts to choose from which killed around
250,000 people and left more than 40 million refugees and displaced people.
For the moment the aid industry receives a minimal amount of media scrutiny
yet in this all-but-unregulated market the mistakes do not just die, their
corpses can end up on the evening news as evidence that agencies should
be given more money. <BR>
<BR>
These increasingly demanding situations have ended the age of the charity
amateur, <BR>
calling for injections of commercial experience and instincts in the relief
world just as it has in privatised industries, health, education, social
welfare and even the police. Such developments take place against a background
of deregulation as governments effectively privatise aid by channeling functions
from the state to agencies and private companies, and the creation of a
market in which diverse relief providers compete for contracts. <BR>
<BR>
Some relief agencies subcontract work to others. The UN High Commissioner
for Refugees, for example, employed charities to run camps for Rwandan refugees
during the 1994 refugee crisis and paid commercial firms to truck their
food. Indeed, UN agencies are building massive rosters of accredited private
suppliers for services such as nutrition advice and goods such as blankets.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Companies work with charities </B><BR>
<BR>
Some smaller NGOS service the needs of larger bodies, like the high-profile
M&eacute;decins Sans Fronti&egrave;res which takes grants from the EU's
Humanitarian Office for work in the Caucasus or former Yugoslavia. Suppliers
to the US Agency for International Development have formed their own lobby
group. And in Europe, national Red Cross societies coordinate bids for EU
funds through their own Brussels office. <BR>
<BR>
Many others have trading companies, mail-order firms or retail empires.
Oxfam UK's 850 shops selling secondhand clothes and &quot;fair trade&quot;
goods from developing countries are part of a trading arm which raised almost
20% of the charity's &#163;100 million ($154 million) turnover in the year
1994-5. And the global greeting card sales of the UN Children's Fund made
a profit of $63.4 million in 1993-4. <BR>
<BR>
The transformation is not going unresisted. The practice of agencies performing
set services for a fee rather than raising and spending their own cash,
for example, has been furiously denounced. &quot;The emergence of a media-dependent
international rescue and crisis management industry is degrading the quality
of humanitarian space,&quot; complained Nick Stockton, Oxfam UK and Ireland
relief coordinator, at an aid conference last year. &quot;The commercial
necessity to portray contractual achievement, harnessed by the [developed
world's] political demand for triumphant televisual humanitarian interventions,
helps fashion a contract culture where success is imperative. Thus, even
while the collective impact of the new humanitarian industry falls below
established international humanitarian minimum standards, accountability
for this, by apparent mutual agreement, goes <BR>
unremarked and disregarded.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Stockton, arguing that markets are incapable of meeting universal values,
went on to condemn the &quot;designer flags, T-shirts, watches, flak jackets
and other branded apparel of the new humanitarian workers&quot; and suggested
that Rwanda, where agencies jostled for a high television profile amid a
growing contract culture, showed the need for some sort of independent aid
inspectorate. <BR>
<BR>
There are efforts to improve standards: several years ago, a group of agencies
introduced a simple 10-point code of conduct for disaster relief asserting
the primacy of aid over politics, independence from governments, respect
for any local culture or economy and involvement of local personnel. Now
there are moves to take that further, for example by introducing standardisation
of disaster kits and procedures. Every part of the aid market, however,
has new teams refusing to play by the rules. <BR>
<BR>
In Goma, for example, a medical free-for-all allowed rampant cholera to
build swift resistance to most available drugs. Controls on drug use, although
hard to impose in the chaos of different aid agencies, would have saved
more lives but equally might have prompted rows about clinical freedom and
protests against &quot;protectionism&quot; by pharmaceutical suppliers.
<BR>
<BR>
Other business-related dilemmas abound. Companies which make landmines,
devices that continue wounding the public years after a conflict subsides,
are logically also good at locating and defusing them. But it sticks in
the craw of some observers when former landmine manufacturers such as Britain's
Royal Ordnance profit by winning valuable clearance contracts from relief
agencies, against competition from anti-mine campaigners such as the Halo
Trust. The UN children's agency UNICEF has just joined the UNHCR in refusing
to do business with companies that make or distribute landmines or related
components. Hunting Technical Services, rural development subsidiary of
the British firm Hunting pPLC, last year pulled out of an EU-funded food-for-work
contract in mine-strewn Cambodia after protests about a weapon made by another
subsidiary, Hunting Engineering. Despite insisting that the weapon - a Gulf
War &quot;airstrip buster&quot; bomb with integral anti-vehicle mines -
was nothing like the anti-personnel mines targeted by campaigners, the firm
pulled out of Cambodia with little argument. <BR>
<BR>
Just as aid agencies adopt business practices, many businesses look for
the halo effect of charity links to burnish their corporate image and increase
sales. One classic spin-off is the affinity credit card, now raising money
for everything from US wildlife to political prisoners. The advertising
industry is the latest halo recruit. The HelpAd scheme from the Red Cross,
looking to raise $500 million or more, offers brands the synergy of advertising
on the packaging of complimentary products such as corn flakes on milk or
toys on nappy packs. Charter clients include Richard Branson's Virgin, American
Express, SmithKline Beecham and Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation. <BR>
<BR>
Mike Kiernan of the US agency umbrella body InterAction notes that dynamic
sponsorship deals by American companies and agencies, such as CARE and the
coffee firm Starbucks, help charities build public support when government
funding is fragile. He says: &quot;US relief and development organisations
are catching up with environment and population groups and becoming far
more sophisticated in social marketing and corporate partnerships, and are
looking to business for support.&quot; Business is looking back at them.
The Washington-based Business for Social Responsibility has 800 corporate
members, from AT&amp;T to Federal Express, Honeywell and Time Warner. <BR>
<BR>
Even with rising corporate sponsorship, the largest proportion of aid comes
not from local jumble sales or collecting tins, which raised about $5.4
billion in 1994, but from governments sending cash overseas, looking to
buy influence, maintain friends in power and subsidise exports as well as
help the disadvantaged. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Japan's generosity eclipses the West </B><BR>
<BR>
The developed countries that make up the OECD together provide up to 95%
of all aid. The most recent figures for official development assistance
show 1994 spending of $59 billion, up from $56 billion in 1993 but down
from $60.6 billion in 1992. Generosity is fading: in 1993, developed states
gave just 0.3% of OECD gross domestic product, a 20-year low. Among donors
only Sweden, Norway, Denmark and the Netherlands exceed the UN's long-standing
target of 0.7% of GDP. While aid from the US is faltering and EU aid is
expanding, Japan has become the largest national donor. <BR>
<BR>
On average, between a quarter and half of OECD aid is fully tied to spending
by the recipient on donor goods and services, although few go as far as
Luxembourg where project implementation is the <I>de facto </I>monopoly
of a commercial firm Lux-Development. The OECD itself reckons that tied
aid was on average 15% overpriced, a $2.7 billion annual windfall for donor-country
companies. <BR>
<BR>
The first conference dedicated to the business opportunities of this multi-billion-dollar
market took place in Cyprus in November, where procurement chiefs from major
agencies explained how to tender for contracts in sectors as diverse as
food, clothing, construction, medicines, transport and communications. Before
the conference the UN's London representative, Alexander Borg Oliver, said
opportunities for the private sector were enormous. <BR>
<BR>
So enormous that Geneva's vast Palexpo complex will provide the venue for
World Aid '96 in September, offering the emergency aid business its first
trade fair and conference rolled into one. George Reid of World Aid '96,
himself an aid veteran, warns of a tough new world for charities, especially
with competition prompted by privatisation. <BR>
<BR>
The latter has picked up pace as governments see a need for organisations
which can take on tough jobs without complaint, often replacing military
forces which carry their own political limitations and heavy costs. When
aid agencies proved reluctant to get shot at driving trucks through Bosnia,
Britain's Overseas Development Administration (ODA) hired Crown Agents -
once a government department, now a public corporation on its way to privatisation
- to do the job instead. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Humanitarian aid is the growth industry of the '90s,&quot; says Andy
Bearpark, the ODA's head of emergency aid. &quot;Our use of NGOS has expanded
because they are [now] far more professional and produce better work. The
cost-effectiveness is positive but the problem is that they can lose something
of the [old] NGO ethos and ability to reach the grassroots. We also use
British businesses for certain jobs that might once have been the role of
NGOS because those companies were cost-effective and better.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Private enterprise is better prepared for such a role than many may imagine.
Company consciences were awakened by the green movement and the US fashion
for mission statements and ethical standards. Today, many companies are
moving from environmental awareness to social welfare, education, health
and more. The tasks involved include US firms teaching trainees to read
and a charge-card company fostering tourism skills in eastern Europe. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Trade-off between efficiency and halo effect </B><BR>
<BR>
Companies are being forced to reconsider these issues because pressures
of technology and communications will increasingly make all products similarly
fault-free, high-performance, low-cost and custom-made. When products are
identical, little is left to distinguish brands other than intangible, non-economic
factors such as values. <BR>
<BR>
David Logan, of the London consultancy Corporate Citizenship International,
advises multinationals on corporate responsibility. He argues that companies
operating in the developing world should think in broad terms about their
responsibilities. &quot;In developing countries, companies have a short-term
direct self interest in ensuring a healthy workforce, prosperous communities
and stable societies. In Aids and family planning these interests are obvious,
since the cost of not taking these issues seriously can be seen immediately,&quot;
he says. <BR>
<BR>
Logan argues that aid agencies must become more businesslike by working
with companies as partners. People outside business do not know enough about
creating markets and selling a variety of different products, be it soft
drinks or safe sex. &quot;India needs a massive campaign right now about
Aids. Who would do it better - the government or Coca-Cola? The answer is
obvious.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The involvement of big business is being encouraged by the World Bank. It
has joined a series of transatlantic meetings and video conferences with
multinational members of the London-based Prince of Wales Business Leaders'
Forum. Big-name participants include Coca-Cola, 3M, British Gas, Cable &amp;
Wireless and IBM. One project being examined in some detail is BP's work
on small-scale social development in Colombia. In this programme, BP has
sought to sustain health, education and social welfare services in a region
125 km north- east of Bogata, where the government has little impact. The
company and the bank are considering collaboration on a childcare centre
at Tauramena in Casanare province, site of BP's oil and gas exploration,
where incomes are low, unemployment is typically high and guerrillas active.
<BR>
<BR>
Chris Marsden, of BP's international community affairs department, says:
&quot;Governments are tending to do less, which creates opportunities for
partnerships of growing importance between the private sector and NGOs.
What BP does may be regarded as enlightened self interest but it is done
for business reasons. We are hardnosed about it. It is part of what we call
our licence to operate from the local community. This is particularly important
in developing countries where we are a major factor in the national economy
and the local community.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
He says the firm has skills which give advantages over NGOS: &quot;We are
efficient managers - our guys in Colombia can turn round a micro-enterprise
project in seven days that might take an NGO seven months if not years.
Some companies have charitable foundations and a lot of us firms take a
philanthropic point of view but we believe in demonstrating the business
case. We certainly see the results.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
In Namibia, mining firm Rossing Uranium saw the way the wind was blowing
in 1979 and started its own charity. Some $30 million later the Rossing
Foundation is fully independent and raises money from governments, the EU
and other aid agencies to spend on small-scale projects in education, training,
health, enterprise and farming. Its director David Godfrey, a former officer
in a British Gurkha regiment, offers his ideas for multinationals with a
mission: &quot;Things need to change and the best way forward is to combine
the financial discipline of big business, in my case a multinational, with
the sensitivity of a development organisation. Multinationals... can afford
it. It's their duty. Lobby your local companies, demand a humanitarian return
for your shares.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>Pitfalls of aid profit </B><BR>
<BR>
Of course some firms do not want a mission, they want cash. In Japan a price-fixing
scandal has just been uncovered involving major companies exploiting the
government aid budget, at $11.26 billion the world's largest. Japan's Fair
Trade Commission fined 37 companies - including Kanematsu, Mitsubishi, Mitsui,
Itochu, Sumitomo, Nissho Iwai, Tomen, Nichimen and Marubeni - just over
$1.5 million for running an illegal bid-rigging cartel since 1987 to exploit
tied aid. <BR>
<BR>
Purist aid agencies continue to stress the value of unbusiness-like values
like honesty, justice and human rights, while insisting that they are responsive
to both donors at home and &quot;beneficiaries&quot; in the field. But how
can they out-perform the private firms that will increasingly compete with
them for aid contracts? <BR>
<BR>
One way would be to show that they can also make markets work. In the &quot;market&quot;
of northern Iraq, for example, &quot;customers&quot; or displaced people
are being given vouchers to &quot;buy&quot; capital goods (livestock, building
materials), albeit through a single supplier, Britain's Save The Children
Fund, with a grant from the government Overseas Development Agency. The
next step is obvious: how long will it be before these clients are guaranteed
a choice of aid agency to deliver what they need? <BR>
<BR>
<I>International media consultant Nick Cater is <BR>
external editor of the annual World Disasters Report from the International
Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies.</I>
