<td valign=top>
<h2>
January/February 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra9.gif" alt="Feature">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left><H2>GLOBAL LEADERS FOR TOMORROW </H2>
<BR>
As the years' cumulative number of Global Leaders for Tomorrow reaches 500,
it is possible to draw a breath and look back with some satisfaction at
a project well in its stride. Four years on, its ideals remain exactly the
same as they were at the beginning: to identify the new generation of men
and women at or near the peak of their careers in business, finance, politics
and the public sector. Global Leaders for Tomorrow have been selected on
a number of strict criteria: they must be 42 or younger, they must already
be in a clear position of responsibility, they must have multifarious interests
and talents and they must have demonstrated that they are genuine players
in the global community. Those who have demonstrated their abilities in
a number of fields - such as in both public and private sectors - are given
especial weight. <BR>
<BR>
Over the years the selection process has been rigorous, and remains so.
As in previous years, a great number of nominations were received from member
companies of the World Economic Forum, from friends at Forum meetings, from
readers of World Link and from detailed, expert, independent research. But
this year it has been particularly welcome to see so many nominations made
by former GLT titleholders themselves. Nominations were weighed up and debated
by the Forum's executive board and World Link's editorial board, and selection
was continued by an external committee of senior public and business figures.
 <BR>
<BR>
The project was initiated by the World Economic Forum and has been made
possible with the help of Donald Keogh, former president of The Coca-Cola
Company, and Ferdinand Pi&euml;ch, chairman of Volkswagen AG. <BR>
<BR>
If there is one major change in composition of the group over the years,
it is that the number of women has almost doubled to 24 this year from 13
in 1994. In January 1993, World Link rather despondently wrote: &quot;More
women will undoubtedly be leaders in the coming decades, but many of those
individuals are still working a notch or two below the global leaders.&quot;
With high profile and talented leaders like Enron Development Corporation
chairman Rebecca Mark, Irene Saez, the mayor of Chacao in Venezuela, and
Ugandan politician Winnie Byanyima, this has started to change and as predicted
women have begun to reach the top of the corporate ladder. <BR>
<BR>
The geographical spread of this year's Global Leaders for Tomorrow is as
diverse as always, with leaders from countries as far apart as Ukraine,
Peru and Mongolia. Socio-cultural differences within the group remain, however,
and this is reflected in the make-up of the leaders. Western Europe and
North America have slightly larger contingents than usual (28 from each
continent) which continues to reflect the entrepreneurial spirit in those
areas and more specifically the number of high-tech companies represented,
which traditionally have younger chief executives. Nevertheless, Latin America
is growing in strength with nine Global Leaders for Tomorrow this year.
Other emerging markets are well represented but the social mores of south-east
Asia, where seniority in many cases equals age, still pose problems for
the young potential leader. It would be difficult to imagine a Marc Andreessen
or Lars Windhorst in south-east Asia, for example. The rapid changes now
taking place within these markets may demand the new perspectives and inputs
that younger leaders can bring to problems, or risk damaging regional prospects.
<BR>
<BR>
The 100 people in this new generation of Global Leaders for Tomorrow join
the 100 from 1995 and 1994 respectively and 200 from 1993. Just as their
colleagues from previous years, they have been invited to take part in a
special programme at this year's Annual Meeting at Davos. In addition, the
leaders will be involved in World Economic Forum summits throughout the
year. It is gratifying to see the enthusiasm that has grown up among the
special programme for Chinese Global Leaders for Tomorrow at the annual
Beijing meeting. The hope is that this group of participants will strengthen
and will continue to develop into a network of individuals who can reinforce
each others' strengths and create a vigorous dialogue across the continents
of the world. <BR>
<BR>
The strength and vigour of what is now a 500-strong group of Global Leaders
for Tomorrow will hopefully be demonstrated in Davos and throughout the
year by their continuing achievements and efforts, even if the context,
the role or even the sphere of activity changes over the coming years.<BR>
 <p><br>
<H3>GLOBAL LEADERS FOR TOMORROW</H3> 

<H4>World Link and the World Economic Forum, for the fourth year, profile 100
men and women from around the world who have made their mark and will lead
business, finance, politics, public and non-profit sectors and academia
into the 21st century </H4>
<P>MADE POSSIBLE WITH THE HELP AND INVOLVEMENT OF DONALD KEOUGH,
FORMER PRESIDENT 
OF THE COCA-COLA COMPANY AND FERDINAND PIECH, CHAIRMAN OF VOLKSWAGEN AG
