<td valign=top align=left> 
<H2>INDIA </H2>
<H4>Ministers are spending their way through the middle of Premier Narashima
Rao's economic programme in the run-up to April's elections. But growth
is still positive, exports are soaring and foreign investors continue to
promise investments</H4>
<H4>Economic overview<BR>
<BR>
Politics<BR>
<BR>
Manmohan Singh<BR>
<BR>
BJP leader LK Advani<BR>
<BR>
Entry strategies<BR>
<BR>
The Enron saga<BR>
<BR>
Where to locate<BR>
<BR>
Auto sector<BR>
<BR>
Telecommunications</H4>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3>PROMISES, PROMISES </H3>
<H4>A looming macroeconomic crisis looks set to hamper India's attempts
to achieve its enormous potential </H4>
<I>By Meenakshi Behara </I><BR>
<BR>
Early in January, Singapore's elder statesman Lee Kuan Yew spoke to Indian
industrialists in New Delhi and exhorted them to push harder for growth
and open more willingly to foreign investment. Lee believed India could
be on its way to a consistent annual growth rate of over 7%. Lee's optimism
was provoked by both India's immense potential and the recent performance
of the economy. <BR>
<BR>
By early December last year, government economists had started talking of
a possible 6% GDP growth rate in the current fiscal year. Coming after the
6.2% growth recorded in the previous year, that appears very impressive.
Contributing to this year's exceptional performance has been the consistent
record of industry: by the end of September industrial growth was running
above 11%. Tight control on monetary expansion has helped keep inflation
reined in: by India's standards current inflation rates of under 7% look
good. Government revenues are buoyant, indirect tax revenues were up almost
17% for the period up to November and direct tax revenues rose 28%. <BR>
<BR>
But there is a flip side. Agriculture's performance has been lacklustre.
Current independent estimates suggest that agriculture could witness a major
slowdown and food production may grow by less than 10%. Tidings on the trade
and external front are also bleak. The trade deficit for the period from
April to November nearly doubled over corresponding months in 1994. The
rupee has been under considerable pressure since August and has effectively
depreciated over 10%. And foreign debt has been estimated at up to $109
billion. <BR>
<BR>
Much of the blame is naturally being placed at the government's door. Its
macroeconomic stabilisation policy is in tatters with Prime Minister Narasimha
Rao's government trying to attack problems through government spending.
There is widespread disillusionment with his government's record on corruption,
as well as problems of law and order and a general breakdown in administration.
The result has been a precipitous fall in Rao's popularity. His hope, no
doubt, is that spending programmes will enable him to buy votes come the
general elections expected in April, though clearly that may fail. A very
real prospect, however, is that the government may find itself faced with
a macroeconomic crisis of even larger proportions than it inherited in 1991.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Public sector reforms not working </B><BR>
<BR>
The government's record on generating revenues has been questioned. One
recent study suggests that tax revenues as a proportion of GDP have actually
declined despite the introduction of extensive tax reforms and a rationalisation
of the tax administration, although economists understood such a decline
in the initial years of reform, the hint of a trend is disconcerting. <BR>
<BR>
Not that the government has had much success in improving non-tax revenues.
The much-touted reform of the public sector in a bid to generate savings
from the government sector has not really worked. In 1992 the government
set out a major public sector divestment programme, intended both to raise
government revenues and impart a new dynamism into the sector. Neither of
these goals has been achieved to any significant degree. <BR>
<BR>
The dismantling of the industrial policy regime and the abolition of state
monopolies in certain sectors exposed public sector undertakings (PSUs)
to greater competition. &quot;This exerted a pressure on PSUs to tone up
their performance. I think Steel Authority of India is an excellent example
of this,&quot; notes Rakesh Mohan, economic adviser in the industry ministry.
<BR>
<BR>
Unarguably, aggregate PSU profits went up. But the main contributors have
stayed almost the same: the petroleum sector monopolies, the state electricity
monopoly, Bharat Heavy Electricals, the power generation monolith National
Thermal Power Corporation and the telecommunications monopolies. But the
laggards remained and revenues from the public sector are still an insignificant
portion of total revenues of the government. <BR>
<BR>
Strapped for increased revenues, the government's borrowing programme has
become much larger than intended. The huge government borrowing programme
for the fiscal year 1995-96 has pushed real interest rates to a new high
of over 10%, up from 3% last year. It has also drained the markets of liquidity.
Industry is feeling the heat. <BR>
<BR>
Even as higher interest rates worsen the government's fiscal situation,
rampant populism has pushed subsidies and other giveaways to a new high.
Capital expenditures have been the first victims in the drive to maintain
fiscal deficit targets. Over the past five years, government's capital expenditure
as a proportion of GDP has fallen from 6% to 3.5% according to one recent
study. Budgetary support to the India's five-year central plan, particularly
the core sectors, has been slashed by an estimated 15% in the current year.
In real terms this could be the lowest level of capital expenditure so far
in post-independence Indian economic history. Reports suggest that social
sectors have been spared further cuts but even in this sector real spending
has fallen over the past five years, not counting any possible eve-of-poll
handouts. <BR>
<BR>
Core sector projects could be seriously impaired. As project funding is
cut, an estimated 80 railway projects, 30 coal mining projects and 10 power
projects are already behind schedule and could slip further. Cost overruns,
which are currently 40%, will be aggravated. <BR>
<BR>
The government wants to believe that the private sector, both indigenous
and foreign, has taken up the slack in investment. In fact, nothing could
be further from the truth. Procedural snags continue to bedevil investments
in core sectors. Despite the simplification of procedures, private investors
still need about 45 different clearances from bureaucrats to get started.
In areas like the privatisation of the roads and ports, a number of amendments
to existing legislation that are essential to facilitate private sector
participation have not been passed. In the power sector, bungling in the
Enron case (see page 135) has damaged the country's reputation with prospective
foreign investors. The telecommunications sector is also problematical (see
page 144) thanks to what appears to be an ever-shifting official position.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>The problems of party dissent </B><BR>
<BR>
Despite the most sincere intentions, the government seems to have been at
a loss to decide how to proceed. This is often attributed to Rao's ambivalent
stand on crucial issues in the face of intraparty dissent in the Congress
Party. <BR>
<BR>
In industry, however, there has been an impressive show of investment interest.
Since mid-1991 investment intentions indicated to the government have amounted
to over $150 billion. Foreign direct investment approvals have totted up
to $12 billion. But actual investments still run at under $1 billion and
there seems to be little urgency to get the inflow of investments to rise
sharply. Though central government clearances have become nearly automatic,
state level delays can be frustrating. <BR>
<BR>
The other major area of reform, the external sector, has continued to show
significant growth. From the months of April to November last year, exports
registered an impressive 24.5% growth and reached $19.8 billion. For the
politicians, people like commerce minister P Chidambaram who is one of the
architects of India's free trade policy, these figures are a vindication
of the new policy regime that was unveiled in 1991. &quot;I had said then
it would take 18 months for any new policy to bear fruit. Clearly liberalisation
has even accelerated the rate of growth of exports.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>Dreams of soaring exports </B><BR>
<BR>
Chidambaram has often cited a dream $75 billion export target for the year
2000. From the $31 billion this year, this target would require sustained
20% compound annual growth rate. He acknowledges difficulties but says it
is a fair target, &quot;that kind of growth is possible having regard to
the forces that have been unleashed&quot; in recent years.* <HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3><A NAME="politics"></A>RESILIENT MR RAO </H3>
<H4>Narasimha Rao's Congress Party has held on to power since 1991 but new
political forces threaten his majority </H4>
<I>By Meenakshi Behara </I><BR>
<BR>
The most noteworthy aspect of Prime Minister Narasimha Rao's government
has been its amazing ability to survive. It was after the brutal assassination
of Rajiv Gandhi that Rao came to power, with a huge sympathy vote for the
Congress Party in the second round of polling in 1991. He then led India's
first post-poll minority Congress government and seemed to have only a slender
chance of survival. <BR>
<BR>
But Rao has confounded most political observers. His grasp of <I>Realpolitik</I>
has helped him buy support from regional parties, engineer defections from
others and keep his own flock together despite constant dissent. <BR>
<BR>
However, apart from an impressive political victory in Punjab, Rao's record
of governance has been lacklustre. His government's ineptitude in handling
one crisis culminated in the December 1992 demolition of a shrine in a small
town in Uttar Pradesh, believed to be the birthplace of Lord Rama by Hindu
zealots. The incident triggered some ugly sectarian violence and left the
country with an alarming legacy of social and political polarisation. <BR>
<BR>
Although Congress has not quite vacated the secular middle ground, it has
done little about the growth of both Hindu and Muslim religious fundamentalism.
Kashmir remains a problem because Rao has lacked the courage to confront
Pakistan over its alleged role in sponsoring terrorism in the valley. The
law and order situation across the country has deteriorated because of the
nexus between politicians, bureaucrats and criminals that is now acknowledged
even in government reports. <BR>
<BR>
That Rao's government has managed to survive despite everything underscores
the absence of any very credible alternative. The non-Congress government
was a rag-tag coalition of various political hues that came to power in
1989 under VP Singh and lasted less than a year. But political observers
are not convinced that Rao will stay in power after the general elections
expected in April. Clearly he has been preparing for the elections since
last August. He has directed his government to throw all fiscal prudence
to the wind through populist schemes like salaries for Muslim clerics, bank
loans to women and midday meals for children, although it is hard to know
what kind of electoral impact they may have. At the same time, a number
of scandals involving top Congress politicians have surfaced, with the infrastructure
ministries in particular being viewed with cynicism and suspicion. There
are few reserves of goodwill Rao can now hope to draw on. <BR>
<BR>
Many observers believe Congress is almost totally alienated from the people
after its defeats in last year's state elections. In Maharashtra and Gujarat
in the west, Congress was routed by the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP). In
Karnataka and in the southern state of Andhra Pradesh, the party was severely
mauled by Janata Dal and the Telugu Desam, two members of the National Front/Left
Front alliance often referred to as the Third Alternative. Congress now
governs states with less than a quarter of the population. <BR>
<BR>
Two new political forces seem set to share centre stage. Resurgent Hindu
nationalism represented by the BJP has emerged as the most potent political
force since 1990 and the party is now in control of the prosperous, industrially
advanced western states of Maharashtra, Gujarat and Rajasthan. In addition,
it holds considerable sway among the urban masses of Uttar Pradesh, a state
which accounts for almost 15% of the country's electorate. The party's recent
victory in civic elections underlined its support in the state. Simultaneously,
the party has a growing presence in the south, particularly in the states
of Karnataka and Andhra Pradesh. <BR>
<BR>
The other major political stream, essentially based on caste, is represented
by an alliance of the Janata Dal, Samajwadi and Bahujan Samaj parties. Originally
non-sectarian, this group has attracted the support of the Muslim community
which has rapidly veered away from Congress since 1992. It holds sway over
India's most populous, economically backward and ill-governed states: large
parts of rural Uttar Pradesh and the whole of Bihar. <BR>
<BR>
Some of the grouping's leaders are rather dubious in their commitment to
the niceties of parliamentary democracy, the electoral process and even
the rule of law. Nevertheless, the front could provide a major rallying
point for the poorer castes. Together with the Marxists in West Bengal and
Kerala and the regional parties in Tamil Nadu and Andhra Pradesh, these
parties form the National Front/Left Front. <BR>
<BR>
The three-way fracture of the body politic may well yield a hung parliament,
bringing all the uncertainties of coalition politics. Congress has tried
to project itself as the only stable, centrist option but this may not be
enough to attract votes. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Sonia Gandhi waits in the wings </B><BR>
<BR>
The one unused weapon in the Congress armoury is Rajiv Gandhi's Italian-born
widow Sonia. Despite a number of public denials, she has remained keenly
interested in the goings-on of the Congress Party and government and could
well be a star attraction if she ventures onto the election trail, particularly
in the Hindu &quot;cowbelt&quot; states of Uttar Pradesh, Bihar, Madhya
Pradesh and Rajasthan which together account for 40% of all seats in parliament.
Whether Rao will use her services is another matter. A Congress resurgence
in the north could derail the political aspirations of the less populous
but more prosperous western and southern regions (Rao's power base) and
end his hopes of continuing as prime minister if Congress wins the election.
<BR>
<BR>
Although Congress is unlikely to win a majority in the elections, other
contenders seem equally unlikely to be able to form a government on their
own. Undeniably, the other parties will do well in their core constituencies
- the Hindu vote in the case of the BJP and the poorer castes and Muslims
for Janata Dal - but a hung parliament may well be the result. <BR>
<BR>
Conventional wisdom suggests Congress may then band together with elements
of the Janata Dal-led National Front. At least in principle they share a
secular platform. Congress could count on support from the southern regional
parties and the Marxists in West Bengal and Kerala. <BR>
<BR>
<B>When cynics are realists </B><BR>
<BR>
More cynical observers have even speculated about a future coalition between
Congress and the BJP. It does seem possible that less secular elements in
Congress, perhaps including Rao himself, may push for just such an alliance.
Sitaram Yechury, a member of the politburo of the Communist Party, uses
the imagery of Hindu politics when he says: &quot;A pale saffron government
may not be entirely implausible if Narasimha Rao takes on BJP support to
form his government, in the event that he is unable to secure a majority
on his own.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The implications of another coalition for the economic reforms are now emerging.
Coalition politics did seem to work when Rao assumed office in 1991, primarily
because the enormity of the economic crisis encouraged the opposition to
be relatively constructive in parliament. But competing economic aspirations
from different coalition parties would affect the reforms. While there is
no doubt of the commitment of the Congress leadership to economic change,
the rank and file of the party still seems unsure about dismantling the
command economy. Congress derived a disproportionate share of the spoils
from the all-pervasive licensing regime of the past. Elements in Janata
Dal and the regional parties are also against reforms, for the same reasons.
A coalition of Congress, Janata Dal and the Communist Party might therefore
proceed only haltingly towards deregulation. Elements in Janata Dal will
push for open foreign investment, but a more cogent economic ideology has
yet to emerge from the party. Meanwhile, the Communist administration in
West Bengal has successfully wooed investors back to the state. The party
could become a major influence on the nation's economic policy.* <HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3>A SINGH OF THE TIMES</H3>
<H4>The man behind India's reform programme says reform's greatest success is acceptance of the need for change </H4>
<B>Finance minister Manmohan Singh has received a large amount of the credit for the dramatic economic reforms of the last four years. He spoke to World Link's Meenakshi Behara in his office in the grand North Block of the government buildings in New Delhi in early January. </B>
<BR><BR>
What do you consider the most significant economic achievement of your government
in the last four and a half years? 
<BR><BR>
To have succeeded in changing the mindset of the people with regard to how
the economy ought to be managed. We had gone in one direction [for] 42 years
- there were lots of achievements, the economic structure was diversified
- but after a period of time we had evolved an over-bureaucratised set-up
which was counter-productive. It suppressed the creativity and underlying
productivity of our economy and polity and a major overhaul of our economic
policy framework was essential. 
<BR><BR>
When we started this was a controversial issue, but in the last four and
a half years the prime minister has been remarkably successful in hammering
out a broad national consensus [on] how the economy ought to be managed.
I think today there is great support across parties [for] more competition,
[for the idea] that the public sector does not have to be expanded, the
licensing system is not necessary, that India needs to welcome foreign investment.
<BR><BR>
Although some parties like the Bharatiya Janata Party would say that we
don't want foreign investment in [some sectors], I don't think that's really
typical of the mood of India. Politicians should be judged not by what they
say but by what they do. And by that criteria all political parties in different
states are, on economic policy issues, largely pursuing the same policy
as our government. That's the biggest achievement. 
<BR><BR>
For all of the economic achievements, there remain areas where improvement
seems to have been slow. What about the profitability of the public sector?
<BR><BR>
Structural changes are bound to take time. The Chinese have the same problem
with their public enterprises. But we have not allowed losses of public
enterprises as a proportion of GDP to become a growing problem. We have
reduced them. We have not allowed subsidies in the central budget to go
up as a proportion of GDP. We've kept them constant at about 1% of GDP.
So the trend is in the right direction although the pace may not be as fast
as we would have liked. 
<BR><BR>
Has the government addressed structural issues in the public sector? <BR>
<BR>
True, we haven't been able to do everything. But our first problem was to
calm the fears of workers in public sector enterprises. There were fears
that the whole programme would lead to large-scale unemployment and if workers
were not reassured the whole programme could be derailed. We have gone at
a rate at which society can absorb the effect of reform but we must not
underestimate the effect of divestment. The very fact that many public sector
enterprises today have the public at large as their shareholders has created
a cost consciousness and new incentives to look at profitability. Even workers
and trade unions today have different mindsets. They worry about the loss
of jobs, efficiency and profitability. Before 1991, they never thought it
was their problem. They thought that year after year they could get higher
wages. Now, for the first time, they are becoming aware that there is such
a thing as underlying productivity which will determine paying capacity.
<BR>
<BR>
What should the government do to speed private investment in infrastructure?
<BR>
<BR>
There is no single solution: problems vary from sector to sector. In power,
for example, if the state electricity boards are to retain their monopoly
of distribution, their financial health should inspire confidence among
those who generate private power. That means they must charge tariffs that
are cost-based. Or we might think of giving some high tension consuming
areas to those who produce power, like the SEBs. We have to experiment in
a country as large as ours. <BR>
<BR>
There are problems of learning by doing since we had no experience in dealing
with private investment. If we were starting again we may have done it differently:
important lessons have been learned and in the next five years we'll see
a lot more aggressive involvement of the private sector in these areas.
Getting legislatures to approve changes in policy... all of it takes time.
<BR>
<BR>
How do you react to accusations that the rupee's fall shows the failure
of your economic policy? <BR>
<BR>
There is no truth in that. The exchange rate is a price and we have to keep
prices at a level which would help our balance of payments to remain strong.
In the final analysis we have to finance our imports essentially by exports
and a sustainable inflow of capital. If we keep the exchange rate artificially
overvalued, that will do no service to India's economy. I believe we have
greatly improved the export incentives in the last four years. Before we
came to office, only 50-60% of India's imports were covered by exports.
Today about 90% of imports are covered. India is, in that sense, more self-reliant,
less vulnerable to fluctuations from abroad than before.<HR WIDTH=60%> 
<H3>ONE'S OWN COUNTRY </H3>
<H4>The Bharatiya Janata Party has a vision of a self-reliant India but
not a xenophobic one, claims its leader Advani </H4>
<B>Lal Krishna Advani MP is president of the Bharatiya Janata Party, the
main rival of the ruling Congress Party in the forthcoming general elections.
To many foreign observers, the nationalistic rhetoric of the BJP raises
concerns about the breakdown of India's secular democracy and a newly hostile
attitude towards foreign investment. Interviewed by World Link's Meenakshi
Behara in the party's spartan Delhi offices, Advani was eager to display
his party's liberal economic credentials. </B><BR>
<BR>
What will be the Bharatiya Janata Party's main election plank this time?
<BR>
<BR>
I hold that today the level of political debate among the masses is such
that economic policy would be debated only in a small segment, whereas the
economic situation would be debated all over. And our stand is that the
economic situation has been very bad considering the potential of this country.
The country has not been given leadership to utilise that potential fully,
firstly because of incorrect policies and more importantly because of lack
of integrity. I regard it as singularly unfortunate that the change of policy,
the U-turn taken by the Congress Party in 1991, has been synchronised with
a series of scandals and scams which have communicated the wrong message.
It is as if these scams are due to the change in policy. I do not subscribe
to that. My party has always been of the view that the command economy strategy
the Congress inflicted on the country was not right. <BR>
<BR>
How do you summarise the Bharatiya Janata Party's economic policy? <BR>
<BR>
We are in favour of liberalisation: there are no two opinions on that. But
we focus on internal liberalisation, delicensing and doing away with unnecessary
controls and proceed more rapidly in that direction. We welcome foreign
investment but only in some areas and would be wary of this in the consumer
goods sector and in the self-employed sector. Maybe after five years this
would change. We don't want a situation in which even firms like the Tatas
are gobbled up. India can wait for [western luxury products like] Camay
soaps for a few years. <BR>
<BR>
If you were voted to power... <BR>
<BR>
There have been many foreign companies in the consumer goods sector that
have been apprehensive about what would happen to them only because one
important company [Coca-Cola] was asked to pack up and go back [by a previous
government]<B>.</B> Every party that subscribes to a parliamentary democracy
is conscious of the fact that government is a continuity. Therefore, if
there are radical changes in policy, those changes will as a rule be prospective,
not retrospective. <BR>
<BR>
Do you agree that India needs foreign investment in infrastructure? <BR>
<BR>
This emphasis in the last five years, that unless we get foreign capital
we are doomed, is misplaced. Foreign capital comes here not to benefit us.
They have no market: this is the market, it's huge. They come for their
own interests. But on the other hand a climate has been created by our own
government saying that the present economic crisis is very grim, very acute,
that unless there is foreign investment we are doomed. I don't see it this
way. <BR>
<BR>
When we talk of <I>swadeshi</I> [a Hindi word meaning &quot;of one's own
country&quot;] we essentially stress the dimensions of self-reliance, not
self-sufficiency. We have the potential and we have many overseas Indians
who are a potential source of investment. In China, the bulk of foreign
investments have come from [overseas] Chinese. <BR>
<BR>
Do you believe in international trade and the feasibility of trade-led growth?
<BR>
<BR>
My party doesn't favour isolation. We do not suffer from xenophobia. But
at the same time we feel it is wrong [to think] that unless the world led
by the IMF and World Bank helps us we have no future. In this context, the
fall in the value of the rupee in the last few months has caused great concern
and is a reflection of the failure of the government's policy. <BR>
<BR>
Does your party see India as part of the global market? <BR>
<BR>
We cannot disregard the impact of global forces and we have to be part of
the global market. But movement towards that has to be cautious. <BR>
<BR>
How will you deal with the problem of poor returns on investment in the
public sector, given the size of the investments? <BR>
<BR>
We favour disinvestment but not at the rates at which it has been done,
at throwaway prices. We were unhappy with the valuation of PSU [public sector
undertakings] shares when the first disinvestment exercise was done in 1992.
You could say that we were on a leaning curve or that there were policy
imperatives [to bridge the fiscal deficit] but somehow we feel the government
had ulterior motives in disposing of those shares at unrealistically low
prices. <BR>
<BR>
As regards return on investment, with the constraints that have been imposed
on the public sector, what do you expect? Today, they cannot submit tenders
even in telephone services. A foreign public sector company can come here
and form a nexus with an Indian private sector company, but an Indian public
sector company cannot join hands with a foreign company which can give it
technological expertise. This needs to be thought through. <HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3>POINTS OF ARRIVAL </H3>
<H4>Foreign firms are increasingly tempted to avoid joint ventures and plump
for wholly owned subsidiaries 
</H4><I>By Meenakshi Behara </I><BR>
<BR>
The strategies foreign companies develop in order to enter India are in
a state of flux. Joint ventures, which only a few years ago were the norm,
seem to be falling out of favour. The wholly owned subsidiary is increasingly
common and new hybrid methods are regularly announced. For example, Volvo's
decision to enter the Indian market did not come as a surprise, but the
mode of entry that the conservative Nordic vehicle corporation proposed
caught most observers unawares. <BR>
<BR>
Early in December, Volvo applied to the Foreign Investment Promotion Board
(FIPB) seeking permission to establish a wholly owned subsidiary which would
in turn set up two subsidiaries, one to manufacture trucks and buses and
another at a later stage to manufacture cars. The first phase of operations
is expected to entail an investment of up to $80 million. The proposal also
indicated that &quot;if all projects envisaged in the second phase of operations
materialise, the investment is expected to increase to $300 million&quot;.
<BR>
<BR>
Volvo indicated that the passenger car manufacturing subsidiary (unlike
the truck-producing subsidiary) would be majority-owned by the Swedish parent
company, with a minority stake held by Indian capital. <BR>
<BR>
Close on Volvo's heels, Korean conglomerate Hyundai announced its intention
to set up a car manufacturing facility in India. Initially a wholly owned
venture, the entity expects to offer 40% of its equity to the Indian public
when it starts the second phase of its capacity expansion programme. In
an industry where conventional wisdom has always favoured tie-ups with local
manufacturers in a bid to gain overnight access to distribution and support
networks, these different approaches have attracted much interest. <BR>
<BR>
Toyota and Daihatsu are both currently considering entry strategies for
India, although Toyota's apparently unhappy experience with an Indian joint
venture in an earlier light commercial vehicle manufacturing project could
weigh heavily in the decision-making process. Sid Khanna, a managing partner
with Andersen Consulting, says: &quot;These companies have developed world-class
product and manufacturing technologies. They feel there is no reason for
them to share control. They feel they are not being properly remunerated
for what they are bringing in.&quot; Auto industry observers concede Khanna's
point of view. The global giants also bring brand equity and hardly need
an equity contribution from an Indian partner. <BR>
<BR>
<B>That was then and this is now </B><BR>
<BR>
Yezdi Malegam senior partner at SB Billimoria, part of the Ernst &amp; Young
global network, is one of India's most respected financial advisers. He
says: &quot;In the past you needed an Indian partner. In the regulatory
framework of the past, you could not get permits and licences without knowing
your way around, and the Indian partner helped with that. Now, except for
some relatively minor state government level clearances, the entire framework
is far more transparent. It obviates the need for an Indian partner.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Indian businessmen, however, point out that an Indian face can still be
an important asset. An understanding of the local ethos could ensure that
multinationals entering the country skirt round political quicksand. <BR>
<BR>
There is no hard-and-fast rule. &quot;If any project is pushed through in
what might appear an arbitrary manner, [anything] lacking in transparency
or seen as militating against overall social interests is bound to run into
trouble irrespective of whether it's wholly foreign owned or a joint venture.
It can't be rescued just because there is an Indian business involved,&quot;
says one observer. <BR>
<BR>
Denise Leonard, the head of the International Finance Corporation's south
Asia regional mission, strongly advises foreign investors to consider the
possibility of joint ventures. Speaking at the World Economic Forum's Delhi
meeting in December, she commended joint ventures because of the Indian
partners' knowledge of local business practices, market conditions and the
customer base. <BR>
<BR>
Mahindra Chugh, senior vice-president of the Industrial Credit &amp; Investment
Corporation of India, has advised a wide range of multinationals on entry
strategies. He takes the point further and advises intending investors to
&quot;carefully consider the demonstrated capabilities of many Indian joint
venture partners in the product adaptation and quality and productivity
upgrading processes that can often be the key to success in the Indian market&quot;.
Corporate advisers have suggested the joint venture route for a variety
of other reasons including the entrepreneurial mindset of many local business
families, their ability to manage Indian technical and managerial staff
and their competence in financing. <BR>
<BR>
But the growing list of foreign companies wanting to go it alone in the
Indian market suggests that they see it differently. Typically, strategic
freedom, technology and product patent protection top the list. For instance
pharmaceutical companies find the low cost of research and clinical trials,
often without stringent western safeguards, a very alluring prospect although
they need to ensure the highest levels of confidentiality. Increasingly
the high risk, cost of brand-building and equally high potential rewards
are encouraging foreign companies to choose 100% ownership. <BR>
<BR>
Even foreign companies which diluted their equity stake to 40% in their
Indian operations under the requirements of the old Foreign Exchange Regulation
Act in the '70s, and then raised their stakes again to 51% or more through
preferential equity issues, are now setting up fully owned subsidiaries
to take on new activities in India. <BR>
<BR>
One corporate adviser observes: &quot;Particularly in consumer goods industry
multinationals will typically want control and so joint ventures and partnerships
may not be the preferred route in the future - barring of course any serious
government rethinking.&quot; Even those who favour joint ventures concede
that the cultural issues are handled just as well by professional local
executives as by families. &quot;Groups like the [industrial conglomerate]
Tatas or the various multinationals that have been operating in India for
a while, such as Lever's are proof enough of this,&quot; observes Chugh.
<BR>
<BR>
In a recent example, a major European conglomerate was advised to consider
holding just 75% in its Indian subsidiary, offer 20% to the Indian public
and financial institutions and keep the balance of 5% as stock options in
order to attract the best managerial talent. Typically, new foreign entrants
face problems centring around understanding the dynamics of the Indian marketplace
and the psychology of the local workforce. Nowadays investors veer increasingly
to the view that knowledge and experience can be directly hired without
having an Indian partner anywhere in the picture. &quot;The multinational
already has access to everything else - technology, finance and a global
brand equity,&quot; notes one corporate adviser, drawing attention to the
management teams of highly successful and profitable foreign operations
in India. <BR>
<BR>
Widespread western-style technical and management education, along with
good accounting standards and corporate law, effectively ensure that multinationals'
Indian operations can be run with a high degree of operational and strategic
independence. For example, Anglo-Dutch giant Unilever's Indian operations
have had an Indian national as chief executive for the past 30 years. <BR>
<BR>
The experience of a range of high-growth, high-profit companies in industries
ranging from pharmaceuticals to precision engineering is similar. Although
Andersen's Khanna feels that management in India lacks experience in operating
within a competitive market environment, and that there is a case for the
return of expatriate Indians who often settle in well, few analysts of the
Indian business scene would agree. They point out that just as Indian expatriate
managers are often culturally out of their depth in the west, they are equally
likely to find themselves professionally out of their depth in India. <BR>
<BR>
<B>More creative, direct approach </B><BR>
<BR>
Immediate access to a well-established distribution network is often a major
reason for preferring a joint venture particularly in areas like automobiles
and consumer electronics. In fact, advisers to a major proposed automobile
start-up have suggested a creative approach to distribution that could actually
take the company closer to the consumer and avoid the dissonance associated
with a traditional automobile distribution network. <BR>
<BR>
The government is being very accommodating, whatever the strategy. &quot;We
are effectively clearing all applications except those that impinge on our
national interest or the interest of our domestic industry,&quot; notes
RK Sinha, secretary at the industry ministry. <BR>
<BR>
It is apparent that a clear-cut approach to wholly owned subsidiaries is
in the making. &quot;Increasingly there appears a feeling among India's
decision-makers that multinational entry should not be purely on the basis
of their ability to bring investible resources. This is one mistake a lot
of multinationals are making. They will have to create product and technology
development capabilities within the country. It makes sense to invite them
only if they make investments in manufacturing facilities and research and
development,&quot; says Chugh <BR>
<BR>
The FIPB has been watchful. In a bid to prevent global consumer goods giants
from swamping the Indian market via wholly owned subsidiaries, the board
clears only a specific product or product line. In addition, where a holding
company is established, it is precluded from a direct involvement in manufacturing
activities. And trading companies are still denied permission. The FIPB
is also known to have sought specific commitments that companies already
operating in India ensure that the new subsidiaries do not grow at the expense
of existing ones. <BR>
<BR>
The wholly owned subsidiary is here to stay. Malegam notes: &quot;Pure joint
ventures will gradually disappear. Foreign companies want to acquire control
and the Indian partner will find he has no role left.&quot; Then he forecasts
how things may change: &quot;In some conditions, the ideal entry strategy
may even entail acquisition of existing mid-sized Indian companies.&quot;
The advantages of a quick start-up and some sort of distribution network
aside, such a move may also become necessary to create a barrier against
a later entry by another global competitor. But with the takeover code still
in its infancy, any such move, particularly if it is hostile, could be a
messy and bitter way to commence what ought to be a long and mutually rewarding
passage through India.
<br> 
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3>LESSONS FROM ENRON</H3>
<H4>The name of US power firm has become a byword for India's resistance
to change. But no longer </H4>
No foreign project has been as controversial as US energy group Enron's
scheme to build a power station south of Bombay, in the state of Maharashtra.
The Dabhol project, under negotiation since 1992, was for a two-stage gas-fired
power plant. But the need to increase India's power-generating capacity
meant that the project was awarded in a non-competitive process that lacked
transparency. <BR>
<BR>
The Dabhol project became a political rallying cry for the Bharatiya Janata
Party/Shiv Sena grouping that seized control of the state in elections last
August. Once in power, the $2 billion project was noisily cancelled by chief
minister Manohar Joshi. In early January, however, a renegotiated deal was
announced that allowed both the state and Enron to claim success: the new
agreement lowered the tariff from Rs2.40 to Rs1.86 per unit and the total
project cost from Rs90.6 billion to Rs64.2 billion. According to Enron,
the tariff cuts are possible thanks to greater economies of scale following
an agreement to raise output and the capital cost has fallen after spinning
off a $300 million regasification plant into a separate commercial venture.
<BR>
<BR>
Despite the eventual resolution of the dispute, the Dabhol brouhaha raised
the spectre of major foreign investments being held to ransom by rival political
interests. The eventual effect may take years to assess. <BR>
<BR>
Rebecca Mark, chief executive of Enron Development Corporation, has often
been attacked for her allegedly superior approach. She is miffed at the
way &quot;the largest single foreign investor in India&quot; has been treated.
However, she is probably the best placed to advise intending investors on
what to expect when setting up a project. &quot;I wish I could say there
was some way we could have avoided this, but I honestly don't think there
was. I think that this is a kind of threshold for Indians - be it the public,
business and government - to decide whether or not reform is going to take
place or whether it's going to be business as usual. At the end of the day,
there are lessons for both of us. We certainly could never have anticipated
this kind of a reaction to have occurred but it did. It's important that
we understand these things have very serious implications and can't be brushed
aside. It has served a purpose in terms of the public because they now understand
the seriousness... of not having this type of an investment occur, particularly
in the power sector. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Caution is warranted. There are two concerns that we have. One is
the speed with which the state electricity boards and people in government
acquire the understanding of how these large transactions work so that they
can effectively deal with [foreigners]. A second area is the opposition
put forward by Indian companies who are used to a fairly protective environment
and don't wish to have different kinds of new entrants into the market.
And that resistance is fairly well entrenched because there is a great deal
of linkage between business and government both at the state and the national
levels. <HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3>IINDIA'S WANNABE'S </H3>
<H4>The relatively modern, hi-tech Bangalore and other states are seeking
to emulate the success of Singapore
</H4><I>By Meenakshi Behara </I><BR>
<BR>
Every visitor to Bangalore, the capital of Karnataka, is welcomed at the
airport with a rose. Step outside the terminal and a large hoarding welcomes
you to IBM City. An aerospace research establishment just outside the airport
serves to reinforce the high-tech image of the city that has become home
to a clutch of global giants in information technology, telecommunications,
electronics and precision engineering. Then you drive into ill-managed traffic,
learn to live with repeated power failures through the day and prepare to
return. <BR>
<BR>
<B>After dark in Bangalore's dust bowl </B><BR>
<BR>
But the late evening scene at Bangalore's airport is unbelievable. Eight
aircraft, all scheduled to leave within minutes of each other crowd an apron
that was probably designed to handle just three. The terminal building has
plenty of dust but no air-conditioning and is bursting at the seams with
passengers. Every flight out is packed with businessmen and professionals
of varied nationalities. The public address system gawks unintelligibly.
The lighting outside is so inadequate you wish you had brought a torch to
help you find the aircraft. There is one consolation, though: Bangalore's
famous draught beer is on tap at the terminal's little snack bar. <BR>
<BR>
Bangalore has all the features of a gold-rush town. Frequent travellers
to China assure you things are worse there. But Bangalore is not competing
with China: it is India's own Singapore wannabe. That said, at first sight
the contrast with Singapore is so marked that you might be excused for laughing.
What was once one of India's best planned cities is now suffering as ill-considered
new office developments spring up, making traffic jams a commonplace in
the business districts. <BR>
<BR>
Even the most elementary traffic management is notable by its absence. The
traffic lights go off thanks to the state's acute power crisis. And pollution
from car exhausts reaches new highs every day, helped along by India's equivalent
of the East German Trabant, a ubiquitous smoke-belching vehicle which has
a two-stroke engine and three wheels and which is proudly produced for the
nation by Bajaj Auto. <BR>
<BR>
India's high-tech capital needs enormous help with its infrastructure -
its power, its roads and its water supply. It needs to curb property speculators
and ensure orderly development of world class office complexes. But that
is where the dissimilarities with Singapore end. <BR>
<BR>
Like Singapore, Bangalore's highly trained human resource base has proved
particularly adept at highly skilled jobs. Were it not for the frequent
powercuts, productivity in Bangalore's high-tech industry could compare
well with world standards. And despite all its inconveniences, it still
remains among India's most liveable cities. The government is finally making
an effort to make sure it remains that way. After years of dithering, a
power purchasing agreement for the Cogentrix power project has almost been
signed. Officials in Bangalore expect financing to be completed by the middle
of this year. <BR>
<BR>
Equally important, the state government has just signed a memorandum of
understanding with India's giant Tata group and Singapore's Changi Airport
Authority on building a new international airport. For investors in technology,
telecommunications, electronics, precision engineering and apparel manufacture,
Bangalore is by far India's best location, retaining the laurels it first
won in <I>World Link</I>'s rankings two years ago. But its dominance in
these areas in threatened by Pune in Maharashtra, a city which has many
of Bangalore's advantages, but which is close to India's financial centre
Bombay and which is better supplied with power. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Ford steps out of line </B><BR>
<BR>
Notwithstanding Ford's decision to locate its proposed passenger car manufacturing
joint venture in the state of Tamil Nadu, the Bombay-Pune-Nasik triangle
also continues to remain as the most often chosen location for investments
in the automobile industry, auto components industry and other metal bashing
industries. <BR>
<BR>
Although Bombay (now renamed Mumbai) could prove an extremely expensive
location for all but the financial services sector, industrial area developments
around New Bombay, close to the modern Jawaharial Nehru Port and on the
road to Pune, could be attractive new locations. Despite the Enron fracas,
Maharashtra's government is clearly among the most progressive and the state's
infrastructure development and the availability of trained manpower makes
it a particularly good choice. <BR>
<BR>
Tamil Nadu remains in second position for the mechanical engineering, automobile
and auto component industries despite the extremely well-developed cluster
around Madras city and Hosur (which is effectively a suburb of Bangalore).
The decision-making process of the Tamil Nadu's government often tends to
put off investors, although this could improve. <BR>
<BR>
Gujarat still continues to retain top spot as a location for industries
like chemicals and petrochemicals. Other states like Punjab, Haryana, West
Bengal, Madhya Pradesh, Rajasthan and Andhra Pradesh have also been popular
locations. Both Madhya Pradesh and Rajasthan have earned a reputation for
very progressive state bureaucracies and would, whatever the political hue
of any incumbent government, remain ideal sites for resource industries.
Punjab and Haryana could be attractive for agroprocessing and light engineering.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Kerala tries to balance Bangalore </B><BR>
<BR>
Despite their efforts, it is difficult to envisage either state being able
to provide significant location advantages for skills-based industries and
electronics. Andhra Pradesh and West Bengal appear to foster a mixed bag
of industries, which is perhaps their greatest attraction. Interestingly,
the southern state of Kerala has begun to attract some attention as a possible
industrial location, but this is mainly because the incumbent central government
industry minister is pushing its case. Before he moved to Delhi, as chief
minister of Kerala, K Karunakaran worked to set up a software technology
park in an attempt to create a counterweight to Bangalore. Kerala has an
abundance of manpower which it has always supplied to the rest of the country
and the Middle East. But progress elsewhere in the state has been tardy.
<BR>
<BR>
Some states still lag behind the pacesetters. Thus western Uttar Pradesh
has seen a spurt in industrial investment, but this is more the result of
proximity to Delhi than due to the efforts of the UP government. Both UP
and Bihar continue to be seen as industry locations of last resort. <BR>
<BR>
Surveys looking for the most attractive industrial locations, now conducted
regularly by a number of independent agencies, provide a reasonable picture
to potential investors. A survey on investor-friendliness carried out by
the Indian Institute of Foreign Trade early last year placed Gujarat top
of the pile with Maharastra, Haryana, Punjab and Karnataka also in the first
group. Second division states included Uttar Pradesh, Andhra Pradesh, Rajasthan,
West Bengal and Madhya Pradesh. <BR>
<BR>
A more sophisticated survey conducted across the country by <I>Business
World</I> and the Marketing and Research Group (MARG) has attracted notice.
Respondents enumerated a variety of factors that qualified a state as an
attractive industrial location and listed manpower availability, power supply,
the availability of raw materials and transport facilities and the availability
of subsidies and incentives as the six most crucial. Foreign investors would
need to add quality of life to that list. There is little reason to question
the importance of most other factors, but analysts believe that investors
looking too closely at fiscal incentives and subsidies could be making a
mistake. Even if a state like Bihar were to give land away free along with
a sales tax deferment for 10 years, Maharashtra could be a significantly
better location because of other factors. States which spend on infrastructure
and create an atmosphere conducive to growth are definitely a better location
option than those which hand out gifts. <BR>
<BR>
Ultimately the <I>Business World</I>/MARG survey came up with few surprises
(see table, p136). As expected, the overall ratings put Maharashtra on top
followed by Gujarat, Karnataka, Tamil Nadu and Punjab. But when investors
begin to consider government attitudes the rankings seem to change, sometimes
very dramatically. Andersen's Sid Khanna says: &quot;Government can at times
be the biggest barrier. State approvals are easier promised than obtained.
We hear horror stories of corruption.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
A recent survey by the National Council of Applied Economic Research (see
table below) attempted to find out the extent of delays by government authorities
in according necessary approval to firms setting up new units and the necessity
or otherwise of making unofficial payments to obtain expeditions clearances,
had some startling results. Respondent firms reported that most time was
needed in the case of power supply and effluent discharge. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The price of surly inefficiency </B><BR>
<BR>
The states of Tamil Nadu and Madhya Pradesh were quickest and Karnataka
and West Bengal were slowest in giving approval. Of greater concern, perhaps,
is the finding that the incidence of unofficial payments was highest in
Delhi, Punjab, Haryana and Karnataka, lowest in Madhya Pradesh and Gujarat
and West Bengal. Respondent firms also noticed a significant improvement
in administration in a group of states including Madhya Pradesh and Punjab
and no improvement at all in Delhi, Haryana and Karnataka, although they
are likely to contest virtually every aspect of the survey from composition
of the sample onwards. Clearly, state governments must pay attention to
these results. With each assiduously wooing investment, governments can
afford to tolerate surly, inefficient and corrupt bureaucracies only at
the risk of driving away intending investors.* 
