<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3>ENGINES FOR GROWTH </H3>
<H4>India is now one of the world automobile industry's prime targets and
sales are continuing their steep rise 
</H4><I>By Meenakshi Behara </I><BR>
<BR>
For India's big spenders, it was the automobile event of the year. Last
October, Mercedes Benz finally made its debut in India with a locally assembled
product. It barely mattered that the product was a jaded series that had
just been phased out in Europe. <BR>
<BR>
Just a few months earlier, India's car buyers encountered another modern,
if less luxurious and expensive manufacturer, when the Korean firm Daewoo
launched its Cielo. And that was just the beginning. Peugeot, Fiat and General
Motors are all set to launch products in India. Some time next year Ford
may introduce its Escort, while Honda plans to bring in its Civic. Hyundai
is also interested and Volkswagen is taking a long hard look, as are BMW,
Daihatsu and Toyota. Last year was the year of the automobile in India.
<BR>
<BR>
Few markets have generated as much interest for the world's car makers in
recent years. India's economic growth has meant an explosive increase in
sales. After growing at over 27% for two years, sales growth of 30% is now
expected. This could push sales past 350,000. <BR>
<BR>
And there is still room for more expansion, according to industry insiders.
RC Bhargava, managing director of Suzuki's Indian affiliate Maruti Udyog,
observes: &quot;Our studies suggest that the market for cars could be of
the order of 750,000 to 800,000 by the year 2000.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
That would mean annual growth of 20% until the end of the century. Many
believe this is feasible. Some, like research firm DRI McGraw Hill do not.
The firm estimates a much more conservative 450,000 for the year 2000. One
bullish industry insider restorts: &quot;At best their numbers suggest a
definition problem, at worst it's an issue of not understanding the market.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
It has been pointed out that different vehicles are needed for urban and
non-urban areas and only a combination of both would represent the true
size of the market for personal transport. Combining both, the demand for
cars this year could top 450,000. <BR>
<BR>
Strong growth has also meant healthy profits. Maruti Udyog ended last year
made a pre-tax profit of Rs2.45 billion (US$70 million) and the firm could,
according to Bhargava, post a record figure of Rs6.6 billion for the current
year. Utility vehicles manufacturer Mahindra &amp; Mahindra is displaying
a similar impressive rise in profits. And Tatas Engineering and Locomotive
Company (Telco), which spans both public and personal transport, recorded
Rs4.5 billion in March and hopes to end March 1996 with a profit of over
Rs8 billion. Little wonder then that India's automobile market looks so
attractive to global corporations. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Foreigners heading up-market </B><BR>
<BR>
Along with the growth in numbers, the market is segmenting and maturing.
The entry-level or basic car remains the monopoly of Maruti, with most foreign
firms so far avoiding that sector. Anand Mahindra, deputy managing director
of Mahindra &amp; Mahindra, says: &quot;No one can today provide a value
package comparable to the Maruti 800 in the entry level segment.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Though Daewoo makes a Suzuki variant in Korea, it has so far been reluctant
to produce the model in India. Japan's small car maker Daihatsu has conducted
a pre-feasibility study jointly with the Hinduja group, although they have
not decided on any specific strategy. But industry observers believe two
home-grown giants, truckmaker Telco and light vehicle manufacturer Bajaj
Auto, could enter the fray. <BR>
<BR>
Bhargava is unfazed at the prospects and remarks: &quot;Any new entrant
will have to buy market share. Being truly competitive would call for a
high local content and high production volumes.&quot; Entrants would find
it difficult, he believes, to match the material costs for the Maruti 800,
currently under $2,800, or its final cost of about $3,600. <BR>
<BR>
But Bajaj may manage to do just that through a tie-up with Fuji, maker of
the Subaru, Bajaj is expected to enter into direct competition with Maruti.
The company's expertise in low-cost, high-volume production gained in the
light vehicle business could come in very handy. And its distribution and
sales network is vast. <BR>
<BR>
Telco's approach is expected to hinge on radically altering the concept
of entry-level cars to suit Indian needs. Telco could bring in diesel engine
technology to create a competitive edge, even if it means a more expensive
product than the Maruti offering. Most crucially Maruti's complete reliance
on Japanese partner Suzuki for even the most minor product development could
slow its response to competition. The entry level Maruti already looks outdated
and is in urgent need of upgrading. Anand Mahindra, whose company has a
50:50 joint venture with Ford is waiting for just such a development: &quot;The
price position of an upgrade of the Maruti 800 will be the level to attack.
The Ford Fiesta will attempt to do precisely that,&quot; he says. <BR>
<BR>
Industry analysts believe the Ford/Mahindra positioning strategy could be
successful and that the Fiesta could prove much more of a draw than the
smaller Suzuki Alto (christened Zen in India) or the Fiat Uno, which is
already more than a decade old. <BR>
<BR>
The market for medium-sized cars looks overcrowded. With Daewoo, Peugeot,
General Motors, Honda and Ford joining Maruti, analysts predict that bloodletting
could be just around the corner. Hyundai and Toyota could well join that
list. Daewoo's initial efforts have already been labelled a monumental marketing
disaster, perhaps prematurely. Few believe that even Peugeot can withstand
the pressure. Mahindra for one believes that &quot;Ford and General Motors
will ultimately be the only survivors in this segment.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
For that, the two giants will have to establish a loyal supporter base.
Maruti, which clung to the government's petticoats for years extracting
all manner of protection and advantage, has now learned to erect entry barriers
of its own. In a swift move, it persuaded most of its component suppliers
to sign exclusivity clauses. Ford and GM may use their existing global component
suppliers, but breaching the barrier will prove difficult for many other
firms. <BR>
<BR>
Daewoo has moved aggressively into India. Along with its car manufacturing
operations, the company has invested an estimated $1 billion in the component
sector. India could then become a global sourcing point for both components
and final products. The strategy should enable Daewoo to keep Indian products
technologically in line with global offerings. The latest Korean entrant,
Hyundai, has indicated a similar strategy for its Indian operations. <BR>
<BR>
All the other entrants, including Mercedes Benz, have invested export earnings,
either from component or product exports. That became necessary when the
government saw the flood of hopefuls wanting a piece of the Indian action.
Worried officials realised that imports of knock-down kits (CKD) could cost
$1 billion annually in foreign exchange outflows. The import of plants and
equipment could only add to that figure. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Government pieces deal together </B><BR>
<BR>
After a great deal of procrastination and confusion, the government allowed
the start-ups to import equipment and CKD kits. But the firms had to agree
to offset the imports by exporting components as well as final products
from India, under conditions reviewed regularly by the central government
in Delhi. <BR>
<BR>
Even so, it is questionable whether the the export commitments can be met,
particularly in relation to finished products. Bhargava contends that &quot;the
import content of Maruti's exports is approximately 60%&quot;, the other
imports make that figure much higher. Some even contend that the Alto, which
accounts for over half Maruti's exports, could include imports worth more
than the price of the car. <BR>
<BR>
Increasingly, global majors are paying heed to the industry's weaknesses.
Ford Motor Credit has announced a financing joint venture that could help
develop the used car market. Growth in that area is vital for continued
growth in the car sales and the health of the automotive sector in India.*
<HR>
<H3>HANGING ON THE TELEPHONE</H3>
<H4>The long-running story of bungled telecom company sell-offs is a warning
example of how not to privatise 
</H4><I>By Meenakshi Behara </I><BR>
<BR>
The fact that foreign investors stress the need for predictability and a
clearly defined framework when dealing with the Indian government is understandable.
Recent events in India's telecommunications sector have highlighted just
how unpredictable the ways of Indian policymakers can be. <BR>
<BR>
India's ambitious telecommunications growth plans first attracted international
attention when in 1984 the Department of Telecom prepared its first Perspective
Plan. This plan envisaged total telephone line demand reaching 30 million
by the year 2000 and aimed at providing connections practically on demand.
The planned capacity increase would also have required an improvement in
the technology used in switching and transmission facilities. <BR>
<BR>
Realising the enormity of the task at hand, the government first moved to
privatise telecoms equipment production. It then corporatised its two most
profitable service operations, international switching and transmission
and the telephone systems of Bombay and Delhi, and then divested part of
its shareholding in both entities. This was to pay for the planned expansion
in services in other parts of the country. The DoT then grew even more ambitious.
With a view to increase telephone lines from the abysmal 6 per 1,000 in
1993 to 40 per 1,000 by the year 2000 it decided to involve the private
sector in providing a variety of services. <BR>
<BR>
According to RK Takkar, chairman of the Telecom Commission: &quot;An expansion
of that order would have required an investment of almost $30 billion in
basic services alone.&quot; The government decided, therefore, to privatise
value added services including voice mail, paging services and cellular
telephone services. The first major initiative to provide cellular phones
in four major cities ran aground after unsuccessful bidders took legal action
to protest against the selection process. The award of radio-paging contracts
fared no better. Problems were said to have arisen because the tenders were
issued without framing adequate rules or procedures governing the issue
of licences. <BR>
<BR>
The government continued to blunder along. It decided to divest through
a global depository receipt (GDR), its holdings in VSNL, the state corporation
which handles international services. It believed the proceeds of the GDR
would pay for a rapid expansion in basic services and the government monopoly
could effectively be retained even while meeting ambitious growth targets.
The VSNL GDR proved a fiasco, failing to raise the hoped-for sum. <BR>
<BR>
Stumped for cash, the DoT then decided to lease switches in the hope of
reducing its capital costs. It ended up paying much higher lease rates than
corporates could have managed in a year of historic lows in interest rates.
In May 1994, the National Telecom policy was announced and the basic services
were thrown open to the private sector. &quot;Our entire model has been
unique. We decided that basic services needed to be opened up particularly
where telephone density is low, then we could move into opening regional
services and ultimately long-distance ones too,&quot; says Takkar. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Hell breaks loose on the telephones </B><BR>
<BR>
In January last year the tenders were offered, allowing the private sector
to operate basic telecom services in 21 areas grouped into three categories
based on revenue potential. Industry observers said the government was biting
off more than it could chew. Takkar defends the DoT's move and observes:
&quot;We did consider a staggered process, realising we were on a learning
curve and that there was a possibility of getting higher bids with each
subsequent tender. But then we'd have been accused of regional discrimination.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
The trouble really started when the 81 bids from 16 groupings were finally
evaluated. A little-known hardware supplier, Himachal Futuristic Communications,
with an annual turnover of $35 million joined with Bezeq of Israel and Shinawatra
of Thailand to bid an astounding $27 billion licence fee to be paid over
15 years. Unsurprisingly, it topped the tender in nine states and pushed
joint ventures with global telecoms operators out of the reckoning. All
hell broke loose. <BR>
<BR>
After a various twists and turns the rules were changed so that bidders
were confined to a maximum number of zones, raising suspicions that the
government was more interested in protecting its own intraregional service
monopoly. The HFCL picked three contiguous areas (Delhi, Haryana and eastern
Uttar Pradesh) committing licence fees of just over $7 billion. The government
rejected bids in 10 zones as too low, which forced a second round. <BR>
<BR>
This tender for 13 zones produced competing bids in only one, Punjab, and
uncontested bids in four zones. Eight zones failed to attract any bids.
All the winners were combinations of large Indian groups and international
telecoms operators: Tatas and Bell Canada in Andhra Pradesh, RP Goenka and
Japan's NTT in Tamil Nadu, Essar and Bell Atlantic in Punjab, Reliance Industries
and Nynex in Gujarat and Usha Group and Moscow Telecom in Bihar. There may
now be a third round of bids, although the legality of the whole process
under legal challenge. <BR>
<BR>
Takkar puts up a brave front. &quot;We are not going through with a distress
sale. We can afford to wait and go for a third round,&quot; he says. What
Takkar and the DoT seem unconcerned about is just how bidders will react.
Ten previous bidding consortia opted out of the second round. Responses
to the third round could be even more lukewarm. With continuous and bungling
rule-fixing, the DoT has not covered itself with glory. Now pessimists shudder
at the thought of a telecoms sector where competent service providers stay
away while the sector metamorphoses from an inefficient monopoly to an inefficient
and expensive duopoly.<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

