<H2>SWEDEN </H2>
<H4>Until the 80's, Sweden's triumphs in industrial production and social
capitalism were the envy of the world. But the shining example became tarnished
by the first signs of social upheaval, tax evasion on a massive scale and
economic crisis. Much support remains for cherished ideals of the Swedish
model, but there is broad acceptance of the need for a leaner form of welfare
state <BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#overview">OVERVIEW</A>  <BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#premier-persson">PREMIER PERSSON</A>  <BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#eastward-bound">EASTWARD VIEW</A>  <BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#swedish-design">SWEDISH DESIGN  </A></H4><BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%><BR><BR>

<H3><A NAME="overview"></A>GOODBYE TO A MODEL LIFE</H3>
<B>In the aftermath of economic crisis, Sweden has learned to live with
doubt about its much-envied welfare ideals </B>
<I>By Marek Garztecki </I><BR>
<BR>
The Swedes apparently had it all: a sophisticated industrial production
and clean environment, low unemployment and full welfare provisions, an
egalitarian society and sexual freedom. The Swedish model was the envy and
aspiration of many countries. Sure, there were some drawbacks such as high
taxation and state intrusiveness, but they were considered minor irritants
compared with the benefits derived. <BR>
<BR>
So when things went wrong - and they went dreadfully wrong - there was a
sense of <I>Schadenfreude</I> among many European commentators. There were
no special economic and social laws, after all, that applied only to Sweden
and excluded the rest of humanity. <BR>
<BR>
The beginnings of the Swedish model go back to the interwar period. The
experience of World War I and the example of the Bolshevik revolution may
have helped the Social Democratic Party to power, but it was the Great Depression
that encouraged the creation of the all-encompassing welfare state. And
the Swedes went for social engineering on a decisive scale. <BR>
<BR>
Neutrality during World War II helped Sweden avoid the armed combat that
destroyed most of Europe and draw economic benefits from its position, lifting
the relatively poor country to the status of one of the world's richest
nations. By then Keynesian economics, only just introduced on a larger scale
in the rest of Europe, was already part of the Swedish model. <BR>
<BR>
In the postwar confrontation that developed between the west and the Soviet
bloc, Sweden steadfastly maintained its political neutrality and combined
it with a very vigorous democracy. There was never any doubt that the country
was firmly in the free-market camp, even if it was combined with pervasive
state intervention. <BR>
<BR>
A high tax regime was intended not only to cover the needs of state administration
but also to redistribute wealth more fairly. The consistency of that policy
was ensured by 50 years of almost uninterrupted rule by the Social Democratic
Party. Swedish socialists practised what the communists in the Soviet bloc
only preached. Far from being an adversary, as was the case in most other
western countries, Swedish business was a willing partner in this system.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The labour government has never hindered business,&quot; says Bertil
Thorngren, senior vice-president of the Telia telecommunications group.
&quot;The deal was this: if you businessmen do not interfere with politics,
we politicians will not interfere with business.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Initially a wide social security net, statutory education and high wages
yielded the desired effects. Industrial peace and social cohesion alongside
elevated living standards became the country's hallmarks. A high-quality
state school system with its emphasis on technology and applied science
produced numerous engineers for eagerly awaiting employers. This human capital,
according to Invest in Sweden agency chief Kai Hammerich, still gives his
country an important competitive advantage. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Global guidance and Nobel prizes </B><BR>
<BR>
Benefiting from this advantage, high-tech Swedish companies such as Asea
- the Swedish part of the conglomerate Asea Brown Boveri - Atlas Coptic
and ball-bearing manufacturer SKF surged ahead, becoming world leaders in
their chosen fields and turning into multinational corporations in the process.
<BR>
<BR>
The international pre-eminence of electronic giant Ericsson was established
by the one-piece Ericophone, a telephone that became one of the design icons
of the postwar era. Volvo cars became a by-word for safety and quality.
With booming production and increasing wealth came self-assurance and a
creeping smugness. Suddenly, it was not enough to dish out Nobel prizes
to the rest of the planet: Swedish leaders found themselves lecturing the
so-called Great Powers on how to run their international affairs. Companies
also discovered new overseas markets and places where they could produce
goods cheaply. <BR>
<BR>
But there were difficulties ahead that did not reveal themselves until several
years later. &quot;Swedish economic problems became apparent in the early
'90s, but the groundwork for them was laid much earlier,&quot; explains
G&ouml;ran Ennerfelt, president and chief executive of Axel Johnson AB,
Sweden's largest retail group. &quot;Throughout the '70s and '80s we built
a certain degree of inflexibility and rather high cost levels into our economy.
This was partly public policy but, if we are honest, it was also done with
the complicity of the business sector. We were over-generous with our social
security system and the way we tried to provide for our citizens. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;During the '80s we were growing more slowly than other countries because
of this inflexibility and were less able to adjust to change. Our political
leaders were proud of what they had achieved and even small adjustments
to [the Swedish model] were seen as an admission of defeat.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
In the early '80s the country experienced substantial devaluation of the
krona and it gradually became apparent that an era was coming to an end.
Although the country's 15 or so large corporations were still doing nicely
the growth of the small and medium-sized enterprises ground to a halt, stifled
by high taxes, red tape and unfavourable labour laws. &quot;Tax fiddles
became a national norm,&quot; claims one small producer of electronic components.
&quot;If you were not doing it, you were only harming yourselves because
everyone else did.&quot; Yet even today, three years after giving up the
business he still refuses to be quoted on-the-record, fearing the revenge
of the fiscal authorities. <BR>
<BR>
Worse was yet to come. The still unexplained assassination of the popular
prime minister Olof Palme in 1986 revealed a dark undercurrent in Swedish
society. Youth disturbances, an alarming growth in drug abuse and well-publicised
attacks on immigrant communities were proof that the Swedish model was fraying
at the edges. <BR>
<BR>
According to Ennerfelt, the opening up of the Swedish economy which came
when it moved to harmonise laws with those of its prospective European partners
proved to have some undesirable short-term consequences. Exchange controls
in place since the war were lifted and the tax system changed, cutting high
tax rates of up to 85% but also eliminating the generous expense deductions<B>
</B>which had meant that the real level of tax paid under the old system
was far lower than it appeared. <BR>
<BR>
Ennerfelt believes that several factors contributed to the subsequent financial
bubble that hit Sweden's banking system: &quot;In our inflationary economy
it paid to borrow money as one could always count on property and stock
prices going up. Once exchange controls were removed property companies
went abroad and by the turn of the '90s Swedish investors were the biggest
players on the European market. They were like calves in a spring meadow
for the first time, making all the mistakes it was possible to make. When
the tax system changed, the real cost of borrowing money suddenly became
apparent. The inflation rate went down and the real cost of interest increased.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
At the beginning of 1993 all but one of the main Swedish banks applied for
state aid. Two of them, Nordbanken and Gota Bank, had to be taken over by
the state because they were practically insolvent and the conservative government
of the day was forced to provide a blanket guarantee for the whole sector.
The move steadied the confidence of the market but could hardly be described
as an example of the free-market non-interventionism the conservatives were
preaching. Not all bankers were impressed. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We were the only bank in Sweden, Norway and Finland that did not ask
for government support,&quot; declares Arne Martensson, president and CEO
of the Svenska Handelsbanken. &quot;My criticism is not that the government
took care of the troubled banks but that its help went too far. They cleaned-up
the balance sheets so now those banks are in a better position than any
other bank in Scandinavia. The most prudent ones ended as the biggest losers.
That certainly distorted the competition.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
For such active intervention to take place under Carl Bildt's premiership
is not without its ironies. Bildt came to power in 1991 as a head of Sweden's
second non-socialist government. He saw his mission as a Thatcherite one
to dismantle suffocating welfare provisions, cut taxes and reduce state
intervention.<B> </B>His was the first postwar generation that did not believe
fully in the Swedish model. Sweden was now to take a bite of humble pie
and learn from countries like Britain or Germany how to run its public finances.
<BR>
<BR>
The banking crisis forced the Bildt government to re-order its priorities.
The economy went into a nose-dive and between the second quarter of 1990
and the first quarter of 1993 GPD declined on average by 2.2% per year.
In the same period unemployment rose from 1% to 8.2%: almost 13% if participants
in state programmes were counted. As revenue contracted, the cost of unemployment
benefits skyrocketed. The ratio of government debt to GDP climbed from 45%
in 1990 to 85% in 1994. Measured by per capita GDP Sweden slipped from third
place in the table of the world's richest nations in 1970 to 16th in the
mid-'90s. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Winners as well as losers </B><BR>
<BR>
But there were winners as well as losers as some companies, such as Handelsbanken,
used the retrenchment period and relative weakness of competitors to their
advantage. &quot;We started to expand in 1990 in Norway and Finland,&quot;
explains Martensson. &quot;We now have 13 branches in Norway employing 300
people and a similar number in Finland. In years to come we will see more
of that, while other Nordic banks will go into the Swedish market. Today
we are the largest commercial bank in the Nordic area.&quot; The enforced
devaluation of the krona provided a much-needed shot in the arm for industry.
By 1994 exports were growing fast again year on year, to 13.3% on the previous
year, up from 2.3% in 1992. This provided a backdrop to two important events
of that year, the general election and the referendum on joining the EU.
<BR>
<BR>
In September 1994 the Swedish Social Democratic leader Ingvar Carlsson returned
to the prime minister's office with a programme to restore the welfare state.
Soon he and finance minister G&ouml;ran Persson were to realise that economic
realities left them with little room for manoeuvre. Shortly after assuming
his post, Persson presented a &quot;budget reinforcement programme&quot;
to the <I>Riksdag</I> or parliament of additional fiscal measures including
new taxes and spending cuts totalling SKR57 billion. The total package adopted
was worth SKR118 billion or 7.5% of GDP. <BR>
<BR>
By the end of last year evidence showed that the bitter medicine was having
the desired effect. According to government statistics, annual GDP growth
in 1994-95 was estimated at 4%. Growth rates for the next two years were
officially expected to be in the 2% to 2.5% range. Both short- and long-term
interest rates were expected to move downwards, with the five-year rate
at 7.5% by the second half of 1997. <BR>
<BR>
Job creation is to remain a government priority with a 1.8% growth in employment
this year despite further overall productivity gains. The most dramatic
progress, however, is expected in the reduction of the budget deficit, that
is to fall below 7% of GDP in 1995 from 13.4% in the previous year. This
should also help to reduce state debt. <BR>
<BR>
With the economic crisis over, did the Swedish model weather the storm?
Persson has few doubts. &quot;Yes, there is room for the Swedish model and
I am committed to it,&quot; he says.&quot;The mistake we made during the
'70s was that the welfare state was not built on sound public finances.
We were borrowing money to keep the model going and that was unacceptable.
After going through this hard period Sweden should still come out with a
significantly large public sector. We will still have rather high taxes,
but we will have a balanced situation with low inflation and interest rates
on a European level.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>A more realistic welfare state </B><BR>
<BR>
&quot;The Swedish model is basically a pretty good one,&quot; agrees Ennerfelt.
&quot;The proof of the pudding is that most countries around the world have
done precisely what Sweden has done. Sweden was ahead of others and we overshot
by making our system so attractive that in some cases it paid more not to
work than to work productively in the economy. If you create disincentives
of this type, of course you will find it difficult keeping the economy growing.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The adjustments that we are now making are not the dismantling of
the welfare state but trimming it back to more realistic levels. Sweden
is now regaining one of its most important advantages, of adapting very
quickly. The reason for that is that we have a highly educated workforce
and a management that is questioning. Labour unions support the change.
This has made it possible for large companies, including our own, to make
drastic changes that have led to changes in the labour force without causing
disruptions in the system,&quot; he says. <BR>
<BR>
Handelsbanken president Martensson, who questions the continuing validity
of the Swedish model, nevertheless admits to good labour relations in his
own company and to his own great reluctance to fire staff: &quot;This is
not a part of our corporate culture,&quot; he concedes. A well-educated,
flexible workforce, good industrial relations and trade unions that are
tough but willing to assist employers in restructuring are quoted by Hammerich
as some of the best features of Swedish business. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;What is not generally known is that while Sweden was a high-cost country
in the '80s, we have become a low-cost country today,&quot; declares Hammerich.
He expects Sweden to remain so: &quot;The political intention is to stay
that way, to keep inflation down. We have a lower rate of inflation now
than most countries in Europe.&quot; <BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>

<H3><A NAME="premier-persson"></A>MAN IN A PRIME POSITION</H3>
<B>G&ouml;ran Persson said he would best serve his country as finance minister,
but that was before the top job came up<BR>
<BR>
</B><I>By Marek Garztecki </I><BR>
<BR>
On the eve of this issue going to press the news broke that, despite the
protestations he made in an interview with <I>World Link</I>, Swedish finance
minister G&ouml;ran Persson was in fact due to succeed Ingvar Carlsson as
leader of the ruling Social Democrats, and hence as prime minister, this
March. The views he expresses will have perforce changed. <BR>
<BR>
Persson has undergone a baptism of fire. He took up the post of finance
minister in the middle of his country's worst financial crisis for 50 years.
Now, after 15 months in office, his problems are still far from over and
on the eve of the interview a public row broke out between Persson and another
minister about Sweden's private pension funds. <BR>
<BR>
It is not the first time that the ruling Social Democratic Party has given
the impression of having more than one policy in financial matters but,
sitting in his Stockholm office, Persson was confidence itself. &quot;Yes,
we had a really difficult period for the last three to four weeks,&quot;
he admitted. &quot;Yet, if you look at the markets, they have not reacted
to it at all, they are still confident in our ability to handle the situation.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
With the impending retirement of Ingvar Carlsson, Persson was long tipped
as Sweden's next prime minister but in the interview he strenuously denied
this ambition: &quot;I have firmly declared that I am not running for the
prime minister's post. I will stay at my present one and make sure that
the financial policy stays firm.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>Second in importance </B><BR>
<BR>
Presented with an argument that a prime minister with a firm grasp of financial
matters may be the best choice to steady the nerves of the international
business community, he retorted that there was also a need for a strong
minister of finance. &quot;Were the ruling party to change both the prime
minister and the minister of finance at the same time, it would cause even
more uncertainty,&quot; he claimed. &quot;In Sweden the finance minister
has always had a very strong position in the government, especially the
Social Democratic ones. Traditionally he is second in importance only to
the prime minister. There is no doubt in my mind that I should stay and
help the next prime minister. The candidates that have been mentioned are
all committed to the same policies as I am.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
A year earlier, his predictions for imminent improvements in the economy
were greeted with widespread scepticism. Did he feel vindicated now? &quot;Yes,
of course,&quot; came the quick answer. &quot;At the same time it is important
to stress that we are still in a dangerous position. Our debt is too large
to say that there are no risks. A year ago I was criticised by some who
argued that the recovery programme was not bold enough, while others said
it was too bold. Yet it turned out to be of exactly the right magnitude.
I presented the right package and I was able to take it through parliament,
something that was questioned a year ago. It is also important to remember
that it was done by a minority government.&quot; The programme, euphemistically
called a &quot;budgetary reinforcement&quot; was a bitter diet of taxes,
spending cuts and austerity measures. But how far will he be able to take
the electorate with him if there are differences of opinion even within
his own party? The answer was firm: &quot;The programme will be taken all
the way because this is necessary. We have already taken all necessary decisions
and carried out two thirds of the programme. A new wave will start in January
1996 and another in January 1997.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>Drop in popularity </B><BR>
<BR>
Persson admits that his party suffered a big drop in popularity in the opinion
polls because of the programme but he is still optimistic: &quot;We have
still three years to go to the next elections and this is a very long time.
We have also an extremely strong position in parliament, with many other
parties supporting our programme. They are calculating that if we succeed
they want to be on the right side, sharing the reward from the electorate.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Persson concedes that the task facing him now is to convince his own parliamentary
group to line up behind the programme unanimously. At first many observers
questioned the ability of the Social Democratic government to reduce the
size of the public debt, something that eluded their conservative predecessors.
But the minister points to a typically Swedish paradox: &quot;In our society
there is very strong support for values, like solidarity, that underpin
the whole Swedish model. So if you have to adjust this model and the level
of public expenditure it must be done by those political forces that have
built it. Only [our party] could gain enough broad support to do it.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
The reduction in public debt, planned by the finance minister, is equally
ambitious. &quot;We have already achieved stabilisation of the public debt
as a ratio to GDP in 1995, something we thought we would only be able to
do in 1998. This is partly because of the recovery in the business cycle,&quot;
he admits, pointing also to the strong effect of the reinforcement programme.
&quot;Our problem was not the debt itself but its rapid growth, which started
in the period 92-94. That, I can say, is now under control.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>Pragmatic attitude to privatisation </B><BR>
<BR>
While Persson's free-market credentials are not in doubt, some claim that
the Social Democratic government is less than enthusiastic about the privatisation
of some state-owned companies. &quot;We are neither in favour nor against
privatisation on ideological grounds,&quot; said Persson. &quot;We have
a pragmatic attitude; we will do it if we get a good price and if, after
privatisation, companies will be in a better condition to fulfil their tasks.
My reinforcement programme is not dependent on privatisation revenues, they
come on top of it. All my budgetary calculations are without taking them
into account and that also concerns meeting the [Maastricht] convergence
criteria.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The Swedish government currently pursues a dual-track policy. While being
officially non-committal about future membership of the EMU, it is striving
to achieve all the convergence criteria in time. Persson himself is more
forthright: &quot;I myself want Sweden to be a member. This, of course,
is up to Swedish parliament but when the time comes for it to take a decision
we want to be in a position strong enough to allow us the freedom of choice.
I believe we will meet the criteria in 1997, something that nobody thought
possible even a year ago. We could be in the first group of countries that
will form the third phase of the EMU process.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
At the same time all polls indicate a growing public opposition to Swedish
membership of the EU. Yet Persson is convinced that were Sweden to stay
outside, its weak economy and an almost disastrous state of public finances
would be hit even harder. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;You could say that we are divided about the EMU process and about
the membership of the EU,&quot; he confessed. &quot;But this is a situation
in almost any European country today. Those politicians who want the membership
of the EMU , have to challenge the electorate and tell it what they are
going to do.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
&quot;In Sweden today public opinion is strongly against membership of the
monetary union. Who can say that this will also be the case in a year or
two? You have to stand up and argue your case. The same process will have
to take place in France, Germany, the UK, everywhere. This is especially
true of countries that have a strong currency, where it is a symbol. I still
believe that there will be a monetary union on January 1, 1999 and that
is the Swedish planning horizon.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>Sweden's contribution to Europe </B><BR>
<BR>
Persson also has firm views about the future role Sweden can play in Europe.
&quot;I look upon it as an opportunity for a small country, with a strong
international tradition, to take part in political discussions about how
this fantastic continent of Europe should be developed,&quot; he enthused.
He has a vision of a just society, one that he would also like to see in
a European context. He also sees the need for a new EU agricultural policy,
one that is compatible with the growth of east and central Europe. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The enlargement is something that is extremely important,&quot; he
said. &quot;When the initial six countries of what is today the EU got together,
their main aim was to ensure peace. Today the support for development of
democracy and market economy in central and eastern Europe also advances
the idea of peace in Europe. We have so much to do and so much in common
that if we do not take up this chance we will be punished by history,&quot;
he concludes.<BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="eastward-bound"></A>VITAL ACCESS TO THE EAST</H3>
<B>Sweden is forging business links with its eastern neighbours and paving
the way for others </B><BR>
<BR>
The Swedish map of the world, based on economic links, would have America
right at the Norwegian border with Germany and Holland a short distance
away. Southern Europe would slip right to the edge of the atlas and east
of Finland would show a vast emptiness. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Our trading geography hardly resembles the physical one,&quot; says
G&ouml;ran Ennerfelt, president of the largest Swedish retail group Axel
Johnson AB and chair of the Russian-Swedish Chamber of Commerce. He would
like to see the map he describes changed and business links forged with
Sweden's immediate neighbours. <BR>
<BR>
The end of the Cold War and the expansion of the EU has opened up new possibilities.
Sweden is still predominately a manufacturing country but its service sector
is growing. <BR>
<BR>
A telling example is the Handelsbanken: widely regarded as a rather conservative
banking institution, it has grown faster than it intended. Already the number
one commercial bank in the Nordic area, Handelsbanken is eyeing the Baltic
States, in addition to having maintained an office in Moscow for 20 years
now. The collapse of a bank in Latvia has proved that there is plenty of
cash chasing all too few safe accounts, although some of that money may
be of dubious origin. <BR>
<BR>
Changes in manufacturing patterns were instigated by the furniture giant
IKEA in the mid-'70s. IKEA outsourced part of its manufacturing to Poland
and the Soviet Union. It provided its modern designs for the factories to
work to then bought the finished products, selling them worldwide through
its own retail outlets. The consumer buys Swedish design, usually unaware
that the product has been manufactured cheaply in <BR>
Eastern Europe. <BR>
<BR>
The IKEA model is one on which Sweden wants to build. Kai Hammerich, head
of the Invest in Sweden agency, compares the country's relationship with
its eastern neighbours to the role Hong Kong plays for mainland China. &quot;Outsourcing
production in Russia and the Baltic States cuts costs enormously,&quot;
he claims. &quot;Our trade with that area is booming, its increase is higher
than with any other region, but of course it is starting from a very low
base.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The biggest increase in our exports relates to central and eastern
Europe,&quot; agrees Ulf Dinkelspiel, who heads the Swedish Trade Council.
&quot;Last year it rose by 50%.&quot; The engineering giant ABB was the
first western company to make significant investments in Poland, buying
the newly privatised turbine and generator manufacturing plants. <BR>
<BR>
Banking, telecoms, environmental protection and services that are still
vastly underdeveloped in the formerly communist states are precisely the
areas where Sweden has acknowledged expertise. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Being in northern Europe we may have a geographical handicap, but
it is an important area of four countries with a population of 20 million.
Sweden is in the middle of this region,&quot; declares Hammerich. &quot;Include
St. Petersburg, Estonia, Latvia and so on and we are talking about a market
<BR>
of about 40 to 50 million people in our proximity,&quot; &quot;If you want
to have access to eastern Europe and the Baltic States without going there
directly, you have a hub here.&quot;<BR><BR> <HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="swedish-design"></A>A HIGH-TECH PIONEER </H3>
<B>Swedish design is respected the world over, with a flair for style matched
by a pragmatic approach to production <BR>
<BR>
</B><I>By Marek Garztecki </I><BR>
<BR>
From IKEA furniture to Esselte office materials, from Ericsson mobile telephones
to the ubiquitous Tetra-Pak juice carton and Volvo cars, the industrialised
world is full of Swedish consumer goods. A sizeable proportion of them are
probably made in south-east Asia or eastern Europe yet the products or their
manufacturers are generally recognised as Swedish and this fact greatly
contributes to their appeal. <BR>
<BR>
For a medium-sized country at the northern edge of the continent with a
population of less than 9 million, this is no mean achievement. Sweden developed
a successful industry oriented towards exports with a high-technology content
long before the &quot;high-tech&quot; tag was devised. <BR>
<BR>
Probably the first Swedish manufacturer to achieve international fame was
Alfred Nobel who, before founding a prestigious peace prize, vastly contributed
to the calamities of World War I through his invention of dynamite. Soon
after that Ivar Kreuger, &quot;the matchstick's king&quot;, created the
country's first multinational business empire whose collapse during the
Great Depression prolonged its duration. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Inventions into marketable products </B><BR>
<BR>
An inventor-manufacturer provided the first impetus to several of Sweden's
most famous companies. Gustav de Lavala, who patented the first centrifugal
cream separator in 1880s, also started the Alfa Laval industrial group that
is still a major international force today. The development of a three-phase
alternating current for transmitting electricity by Jonas Wenstrom, also
in the 1880s, was the foundation on which Asea of the multinational Asea
Brown Boveri (ABB) was built. <BR>
<BR>
Another famous engineering name, SKF, was founded in 1907 to exploit Sven
Winquist's invention of the self-aligning spherical roller bearing or ball-bearing.
Soon after, Victor Hasselblad gave his name to a camera generally recognised
as the Rolls-Royce of photography. The Hasselblad captured the first view
of the earth from space as well as the dark side of the moon. <BR>
<BR>
The ability of Swedish engineers not only to invent things but to turn them
into excellent, marketable products is, according to Kai Hammerich of the
Invest in Sweden agency, his country's main selling point. He believes that
a heavy emphasis on technology in the country's education system is the
main contributing factor. &quot;The proof of our international competitiveness
in that area are our 15 or so multinational companies. They have become
global today but they all have their origins in those areas of technology
we developed here.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
There is no doubt that Swedish goods display the traits to be found in the
proverbial Swedish personality: they are thought to be solid, functional
and honest. The Volvo car is a classic example, its very name a by-word
for quality of build and motoring safety. Heavy trucks made by Scania enjoy
a parallel reputation in their market segment. <BR>
<BR>
The combination of simple but sturdy designs with an emphasis on practicality
has resulted in a astonishing number of style icons such as the AGA stove,
Ericsson one-piece telephone sets or Kosta-Boda glasses that have found
their way not only to millions of homes all over the world but also art
exhibitions and museums. The commercial success of Absolut Vodka, which
in a few years conquered the white spirits market, has now become a textbook
case of effective marketing. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Exploring r&amp;d competence </B><BR>
<BR>
Sweden now intends to explore its r&amp;d competence in other areas by offering
its services to foreign companies. &quot;A researcher here costs half the
price of one in Switzerland or Germany,&quot; says Hammerich, whose agency
has identified 12 areas of expertise including information technology, recycling
and environmental technology, biotechnology and pharmaceuticals. <BR>
<BR>
Ulf Dinkelspiel, head of the Swedish Trade Council, says that they already
get between 200,000 and 300,000 enquiries a year. &quot;Roughly 10% lead
to the establishment of business links. It will eventually be difficult
to distinguish between exports, imports and the transfer of technical know-how,
especially in the services sector. It will be increasingly difficult to
say if something has crossed the border or not. We will be assisting Swedish
companies in the process of internationalisation, rather than solely helping
them export,&quot; predicts Dinkelspiel.<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
<nobr>
