<td valign=top align=left> 
<H2>PERU </H2>
<H4>Although President Alberto Fujimori's centralised rule can cause logjams
at the top, his economic policies and campaign against terrorism are enjoying
success. Rich mineral deposits, privatisation and a growing stock exchange
are attracting attention from foreign investors but further growth depends
on the country putting more emphasis on training and closing social disparities
<BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#overview">OVERVIEW</A> <BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#banks-sale">BANKS FOR SALE</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#mining">RICH SEAMS TO MINE </A> <BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#busy-bourse">BUSY BOURSE </A></H4>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="overview"></A>DIVIDED BUT GROWING </H3>
<BR>
<B>Having escaped a period of terrorism and anarchy, Peru has found itself
with a booming economy </B><I><BR>
<BR>
by Andrew Rosenbaum </I><BR>
<BR>
Some say there are two Perus, or even more, and the fusion of this varied
country into a working whole has always been crucial to its successful development.
&quot;Peru is a country of great disparities and complexity,&quot; says
Javier de la Rocha Marie, director general of the Banco Central de Reserva
del Peru. <BR>
<BR>
The first Peru, which consists of the affluent, educated and largely urban
classes who participate in the formal economy, is now enjoying a remarkable
turnaround. For them, a period of 15 years of terrorism has come to an end
and the official economy now offers enviable rewards. <BR>
<BR>
But for the 46% of Peruvians who still live below the poverty line, little
has changed. These citizens, who mostly live in rural areas, do not participate
in either the economic or political life of the country. The number of marginalised
has risen by 4% since 1990, regardless of the country's growth. <BR>
<BR>
Then there is the phenomenon that some including President Alberto Fujimoro,
have referred to as the &quot;third&quot; Peru. It consists of urban migrants
who populate the shanty towns at the edges of major cities who contribute
the lion's share to the country's thriving black economy. There are few
statistics available on this group but economists judge that they enjoy
incomes well above the poverty line and are becoming important economic
actors. <BR>
<BR>
The country has geographical as well as social divisions, its 1,285,216
square kilometres broken up into cities, mountains and jungle each with
very varied levels of development. Until now, the Fujimori government has
not really tried to pull the country together. Peru, like other countries
in Latin America, has a tradition of government from the top, for the top.
The Fujimoro government stands accused of ignoring development of democratic
institutions which would give everyone in Peru a voice. The government has
worked very successfully for economic reform yet experts say the reformed
economy may again be threatened by crime and terrorism if its disenfranchised
are not brought into the system. <BR>
<BR>
Fujimori has succeeded in rescuing Peru from the state of anarchy and collapse
to which it had fallen in 1990. Inflation, a horrific 7,650% per year in
1990, has been brought down to under 11% in 1995 and GDP, which hardly grew
at all in 1990, rose 12.7% in 1994 to $26.4 billion, the fastest growth
in the world. To keep the reins on inflation, the central bank is keeping
tight control of the money supply and growth should be limited to 5-7% per
year in the near future, according to De la Rocha Marie. <BR>
<BR>
Most important of all for the country's future, the Shining Path Maoist
revolutionary group recruited from the disenfranchised has been almost completely
defeated. It fell apart when its leader was arrested in 1992 and the number
of terrorist attacks has fallen from 2,000 in 1990 to less than 300 in 1995.
&quot;I used to keep shotguns in my home and in my office, even though I
didn't know how to use them,&quot; says Jose Carlos Luque Otero, president
of the Lima stockmarket. &quot;None of that is necessary any longer.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
The success of Fujimori's security programme is such that he won a landslide
victory in elections last April, guaranteeing him control of the congress.
And the official economy has attracted about $5 billion in foreign direct
investment in 1995, a sign of growing confidence in Peru. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;There is probably considerably more coming in than that,&quot; explains
economist Gilberto Moncada, who works for the Lima research and consulting
firm Cuanto SA. &quot;Requirements for registering foreign investment with
the ministry of the economy have been eliminated, so it is increasingly
difficult to keep track of the actual amount.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Out of all foreign investors, Spain continues to invest the most money in
Peru, sinking $2 billion in 1994 according to Cuanto: the takeover by Spain's
Telefonica of the Peruvian telecommunications provider helps account for
most of that large investment). The US, the Netherlands, Chile, and Britain
follow, with companies investing heavily in mining and energy. <BR>
<BR>
The government's privatisation programme accounts for most of that investment.
Since 1992 the government has seen $3.54 billion in receipts from its sales
of almost all state-owned industry. There are further large sales to come,
including the remaining shares in the telephone company, electric power
utilities and the oil company Perupetro. <BR>
<BR>
Foreign companies have accounted for about half of privatisation revenues
but the influx of capital has also posed a problem. Peru's current account
deficit, $2.1 billion in 1994, is growing rapidly as imports mount. &quot;There
is a genuine danger here of a crisis,&quot; says Moncada. &quot;If there
is a popular notion that the country's reserves are being depleted, a run
on the banks is always possible. This is part of the heritage of having
suffered high inflation.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The government insists that export generation will soon balance the trade
deficit. Says Peru's finance minister Jorge Camet: &quot;Some 32% of 1995
imports were capital goods. Investments in the mining sector are expected
to mature in two or three years time, thus generating a significant increase
in exports that will lead to a trade surplus before the end of the century.&quot;
Economists are less sure, and in any case are more concerned about the short
term. <BR>
<BR>
To its credit, the Fujimori government has earned a reputation for responsibility
in its monetary policies. The IMF praises the government for sticking to
planned spending cuts over a period of two years and Peru enjoys the advantage
of having finally normalised its commercial debt. <BR>
<BR>
Last summer the country came to an agreement with international bankers
to resettle payments on the $10 billion it owes. The accord means the end
of a dispute that has hurt the country's credit since 1983, when the preceding
Garcia administration declared a moratorium on debt servicing. <BR>
<BR>
A recent agreement under the Brady plan, named after a former US treasury
secretary, will allow Peru to begin servicing the debt again. A single payment
of $225 million has been determined to satisfy the bankers and servicing
will take place at the rate of about $22 million per quarter. This sizeable
discount will prevent repayments from becoming an intolerable burden. The
government calculates that overall commercial debt has been cut by about
half, an amount similar to the terms won by Ecuador and Poland in recent
Brady deals. <BR>
<BR>
When debt servicing does begin again in 1996, critics say it could have
a serious effect on growth. But the amount of money entering the country
through foreign investment seems to be <BR>
sufficient to compensate the drain. <BR>
<BR>
Until exports can be improved, the privatisation programme ensures that
the government will be able to maintain reserves. Currently, exports consist
mostly of raw materials like minerals, fish, and agricultural produce. Mining,
perhaps Peru's largest and most advanced industry, will enjoy close to $10
billion in investment to improve productivity in the next five years. But
little is being spent to improve other areas of the economy like high-tech
manufacturing. <BR>
<BR>
Here the problems created by the highly restrictive nature of Peru's economic
success become important: to make exports more competitive, the country
needs a larger, better-educated workforce. A greater number of competitive
enterprises must also be created and that also calls for more entrepreneurs
with education and skills. &quot;Unless the rewards of our booming economy
are used to invest in education and training, the boom could fizzle out,&quot;
says Moncada. <BR>
<BR>
The third Peru is the group that cries out for this kind of help. Today,
Andean migrants make up the majority of Lima's population and are a hotbed
of entrepreneurial talent. They are important as both consumers and producers:
one economist described them as having &quot;an unlimited amount of unsatisfied
appetites&quot;. Since the government simplified the rules for starting
new businesses last year, for example, some 450,000 new companies have been
registered, the vast majority from this sector. Fujimori himself has paid
tribute to their creativity, which he says is symbolised by the Gamarra
textile district in Lima. <BR>
<BR>
A segment of Peruvian business now targets this group. Companies like the
Lima-based Grupo Carsa are finding ways to give credit to migrants on the
black economy who are learning to get housing mortgages and financing for
business expansion. &quot;What the government is beginning to understand,&quot;
says Guido Lucioni, executive director of the Grupo Carsa, &quot;is that
this black economy complements, and does not necessarily conflict with,
the traditional economy.&quot; Yet there is little likelihood such people
will receive the training they need: the mechanisms that would provide training
do not yet exist, nor are there any plans to put them into place. <BR>
<BR>
The Fujimori government cannot be accused of neglecting social spending.
It has actually increased under Fujimori's regime, from $12 per capita in
1990 to $176 per capita this year. &quot;The government has placed special
emphasis on its social programme, which considers directing at least 40%
of the annual budget in social spending until the year 2,000,'' says finance
minister Camet. But the relief has been short-term - free meals, subsidised
jobs - at the expense of steps which would make the poor more self-reliant.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Frustration v prosperity </B><BR>
<BR>
The result is disenfranchisement. Despite Peru's phenomenal economic growth
in 1994, the distribution of wealth that year increased only 0.8% according
to Cuanto. The government claims growth in the next two years will spread
more wealth: &quot;The growth rate will be significantly higher than the
expected increase in population and will be enough to generate a real increase
in the population's living standards,&quot; says finance minister Camet.
But while terrorism is now under control, street crime is rising, especially
in the shantytowns around big cities. The frustration of the disenfranchised
mounts with other people's prosperity. <BR>
<BR>
Many of the problems are caused by a logjam at the top, as is so often the
case in a highly centralised regime. In the so-called coup of April 5, 1992,
Fujimori closed down the country's congress and took over every kind of
decision-making. Few Peruvians regret the uprising, since the congress had
a deserved reputation for corruption. But although democratic institutions
once again operate in the country, Fujimori has never really given back
all decision-making powers. Ministers reportedly fear taking steps without
express approval from the president who has shut down some regional governments
and begun naming regional presidents himself. There are still 37 provinces
in which military rule has never been replaced by a civilian administration.
<BR>
<BR>
The government insists that it will broaden democracy. Finance minister
Camet says: &quot;Democratic institutions play a key role in allowing Peruvians
to feel that the main issues and decisions are based on the majority's will.&quot;
Yet it is clear that political power at every level depends on Fujimori
himself. Although unable to run in the next presidential elections in 2005,
he is reportedly already choosing a successor. <BR>
<BR>
With all this, Peru's considerable economic success makes for optimism.
The government now has the means to guarantee stability and set change in
motion in many areas. &quot;We are enjoying peace and prosperity for the
first time in years,&quot; says one Lima businessman. &quot;We need time
to get used to it, and then we can get started on the rest of the work we
have to do.&quot;<BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="banks-sale"></A>SMART BANKS FOR SALE</H3>
<BR>
<B>Privatisation and looser regulation have begun to make banks very interesting
to foreign investors </B><BR>
<BR>
Peru was largely spared from the round of bank failures that many other
Latin American countries saw in 1994. Since 1992, the country has had a
strict law which obliges Peruvian banks to clean up bad loans and keep capital
ratios high. The result is that the banking sector has enjoyed the fruits
of the economic boom. &quot;Essentially, banks are profiting from the reaction
after 15 years of pent-up growth,&quot; says one local banker. <BR>
<BR>
At the moment, the sector is still comparatively small. The total amount
of bank-to-bank transactions accounts for only about 20% of the country's
GNP according to Cuanto SA, a Lima-based research and consulting firm, compared
to Chile's 40%. One problem is excessive concentration: just a handful of
banks account - mainly large state-owned institutions with privileged access
to credit - for more than half of total deposits. <BR>
<BR>
But this is changing rapidly. In 1993 Banco Internacional, the country's
fourth largest bank, was was sold to a Peruvian consortium with some foreign
interests for $51 million. Since then three other large state banks have
been privatised and more sales are planned.The country's privatisation programme
and booming economy have provoked considerable foreign interest while the
relatively high level of development of Peruvian banking, has offered a
further incentive. <BR>
<BR>
More than 20 foreign banks have set up representative offices in Lima in
the past year. Last April, a consortium led by Spain's Banco Bilbao Vizcaya
bought the former state-owned Banco Continental for nearly $200 million
and Spain's Banco Santander, which bid unsuccessfully for Continental, is
reportedly eyeing the smaller Banco Mercantil del Peru. Analysts expect
Santander to make several purchases to continue its strategy of regional
development. Citibank is already active in the country and the Netherland's
ING Group has also declared interest in making a purchase in Peru. <BR>
<BR>
Chilean groups set up three new banks in Lima in 1994: Banco del Libertador,
Banco Solventa, and Banco del Trabajo. A new Peruvian bank, Banco del Nuevo
Mundo, started operations in 1993. <BR>
<BR>
Commercial banking is the most developed area with 21 institutions currently
operating. The recent settlement of a large part of the nation's commercial
debt has opened the door to easier terms for corporate credit. Companies
are now paying high rates - up to 15% - on the very short-term loans available.
But banks are currently seeking funds to use in long-term loans at more
attractive rates. <BR>
<BR>
The state has recently taken measures to enable retail banks to offer consumer
credit at competitive rates and several Lima banks are already offering
such loans. Banks are also permitted to issue mortgage-backed notes for
up to 75% of property value and these are traded on Lima's secondary market:
techniques like securitisation have not yet found their way to Peru. Furthermore,
Visa has just installed 200,000 teller machines around the country to help
satisfy short-term credit demands. <BR>
<BR>
Peruvian banks are also moving into new areas of the capital markets that
been little cultivated so far in Latin America, such as derivatives. These
products, which are now growing fast, are typically interest rates and currency
related intruments linked to international capital market issues or spun
off from government or Brady bonds. The use of commodity-related derivatives
is also growing. The Lima bourse is currently working to create a better-regulated
trading environment for these products. <BR>
<BR>
All of Peru's major banks have been improving productivity, reorientating
employees to the priorities of a service industry. According to the Escuela
Superior de Economia y Negocios, a leading Lima business school, banks have
already raised productivity by an average 19% and operating costs are being
slashed. The Lima-based Banco Wiese leads the country's productivity league
table, according to the business school, followed closely by the largest
bank, Banco de Credito. <BR>
<BR>
Peru's banking boom is likely to last as long as the economic boom continues.
Still, with the entry of so many new players into a fairly small market,
analysts say a shakeout can be expected in the next two years. Peruvian
banks may now be getting lean and mean, but they will have to get even tougher
as growth slows in 1996 and 1997. <BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="mining"></A>GOLD, SILVER AND ZINC </H3>
<BR>
<B>The mining industry is ripe for adventurous investors, with many unexplored
areas rich with deposits </B><I><BR>
<BR>
by Andrew Rosenbaum </I><BR>
<BR>
One of the largest zinc mines in Latin America is being built in Peru. The
Isaycruz mine will begin operations in 1996, with a capacity of 60,000 tons,
heralding a positive future for the country's mining industry. <BR>
<BR>
The Peruvian economy already obtains a quarter of its total growth from
mining revenues, which come from gold, silver, copper and zinc <BR>
production. Mining accounts for 11% of GDP and the trickle-down effect of
investment in the sector is becoming increasingly important for the country.
&quot;Peru is becoming a Mecca for geologists and mining companies,&quot;
comments Ronald Cambre, president and CEO of Newmont Mining. <BR>
<BR>
The removal of state controls on industry has allowed the sector to develop
freely, and both investment and development are taking off. Procedures for
registering properties have been relaxed and foreign investors are offered
a tax stability contract, which guarantees the effective rate of taxation
on profits for the life of the project and which assures the entrepreneur
of unrestricted repatriation of profits. The government has also adopted
an environmental impact statement as a means of protecting natural resources
and standardising the procedure for project approval. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Acres of unexplored land </B><BR>
<BR>
Equally important is the existence of a highly skilled workforce. Peruvian
mining engineers, industry observers say, are thoroughly familiar with modern
techniques. Production is currently worth $1.6 billion and by the year 2003
this figure is expected to triple to $4.8 billion. In the past two years,
the number of registered applications for new mining ventures has increased
dramatically to more than 8,000. <BR>
<BR>
In total, the industry now covers 19 thousand hectares. Yet according to
the ministry of energy and mining, only 5% of the total area available for
the industry is being exploited. The ministry has details of thousands of
untouched deposits which are open to exploitation. The eastern part of the
country, which is reportedly rich with mining opportunities, has not yet
even been mapped. <BR>
<BR>
With all this potential the prospects for investment in Peruvian mining
look good, according to analysts. Investment of close to $9 billion is expected
over the next 10 years. One catalyst is the privatisation of Centromin,
the state-owned mining giant, which is scheduled for 1996. The company is
valued at more than $1 billion and owns gold, silver and other mines. It
produces much of the silver mined in the country, which itself is the third
largest producer of silver in the world. Its privatisation should stimulate
further investment in silver mining and provide the company with funds to
expand its current operations and exploration. Foreign companies like Cyprus
and Newmont mining are already present in the country and are keen to make
future investment. <BR>
<BR>
Centromin was a particular target of attacks by the Shining Path terrorist
group: in 1988 the company lost 8.3 million man-hours because of attacks.
It is now recuperating and produced 18.4 million ounces of silver in 1994.
<BR>
<BR>
Extensive exploration for gold deposits is taking place in the mountains.
Gold production is the largest sector of the mining industry, worth a total
$338 million in 1994, and it is expected to grow by more than half in 1995.
Peru boasts the largest and most profitable gold mine in Latin America,
the Minera Yanacocha, where two sites are now in production, which alone
produced close to 300,000 ounces in 1994. The amount is increasing through
high-tech chemical production methods. Two other mines were also recently
opened and should spur production. <BR>
<BR>
The smaller mining operations also present excellent investment opportunities,
as entrepreneurs in this sector lack capital to explore the vast wooded
areas of the mountains. <BR>
<BR>
Copper makes up 18% of Peru's total exports and there are reportedly large
areas of unexplored copper deposits in the eastern part of the country.
A gradual fall in the value of copper is expected in the long-term, but
this should not affect performance. Most of the country's copper comes from
two mines in the south of Peru. Both are mined by the Southern Peru Copper
Corporation, which is owned by a consortium of foreign and national companies.<BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="busy-bourse"></A>BOURSE BUSY WITH IDEAS </H3>
<B>The resurgent and welcoming Lima stock exchange is prospering, despite
weak laws controlling insider trading <BR>
<BR>
</B><I>by Andrew Rosenbaum </I><BR>
<BR>
When the Mexican crisis drove investors away from Latin America and emerging
markets in general, the Lima stockmarket suffered, experiencing an outflow
of several hundred million dollars. But the money came back to the exchange
within two months, in the fastest recovery in Latin America. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We had no 'tequila effect' here,&quot; says Jose Carlos Luque Otero,
president of the Lima stockmarket, referring to the knock-on effects of
the peso devaluation in December 1994 which hit other countries in the region
for months afterwards. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Star performer in Latin America </B><BR>
<BR>
The Lima bourse is a superb showcase for the government's economic reforms.
It acts an important instrument of monetary policy, enabling the economy
to absorb the vast funds that are flowing into the country via the privatisation
programme and other investments. <BR>
<BR>
The stockmarket has outperformed all other Latin American stockmarkets since
the Mexican crisis. In the past three years, share prices have risen more
then 10 times and the exchange's IGBVL index has risen from 130 in 1992
to a high of around 1500 in 1994. <BR>
<BR>
The government's privatisation programme has swollen total trading volume
which is expected to rise to $15 billion in 1996, up from $750 million six
in 1990. About half of that volume comes from foreign equity investment
through the purchase of shares of recently privatised companies. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;All of this is due to the government's achievement of economic and
social stability,&quot; says Luque Otero. &quot;And I think the stockmarket
will continue to develop as long as this lasts.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The most serious difficulty the exchange has faced came when Peru had armed
clashes with neighbouring Ecuador in 1995 over a border dispute. &quot;That
frightened investors but happily the war did not last very long.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Lima has had a stock exchange for the past 135 years, but under previous
governments its operations were hampered by a welter of regulations. &quot;When
we were given the go-ahead in 1991 we reorganised the exchange, modelling
it after Chicago and copying SEC rules,&quot; Luque Otero explains, refering
to the tough American Securities and Exchange Commission which regulates
the equity markets. <BR>
<BR>
The one important exception, however, is on insider trading where the Lima
market did not accept the American model, choosing instead to base its rules
on French law which is notoriously weak on the issue. This may help to explain
why no case on insider trading has ever been tried in Peru. Some analysts
have called this a serious weakness and have called for the Peruvian stockmarket
watchdog, the National Committee for Stocks and Bonds, to change the rule.
<BR>
<BR>
Apart from this lapse, the Lima market operates according to the highest
international standards, based on the Group of 15 recommendations that govern
the industry. Trading is entirely electronic and all the issues are dematerialised
- that is they exist only on computer. Settlement takes place two days after
a trade, which is the same as in many of the world's principal stockmarkets.
There is no market-making at present, although Luque Otero says that he
is studying the possibilities for its introduction. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The short queue of foreign brokers </B><BR>
<BR>
One of the Lima exchange's most unusual aspects is its openness to foreign
brokers. Foreign firms are allowed to become members and have unrestricted
access to trading on the Lima exchange, a fact which is true of very few
stockmarkets in developing countries around the world. <BR>
<BR>
Barings, Merrill Lynch and Salomon Brothers are already members. While Luque
Otero says foreign brokers are not exactly queuing up to join the exchange,
he insists that he is talking to other houses. <BR>
<BR>
The Lima stockmarket is expanding into new areas, building on its past progress
and good reputation. Last year a small market for corporate bonds, worth
no more than $5 million, made its appearance. The bond market is now worth
$500 million as corporations perceive that there is sufficient liquidity
on the exchange to make such fundraising operations worthwhile. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Worries about handling big money </B><BR>
<BR>
Some economists are concerned, however, that there are still not enough
large players present to handle ever-larger influxes of capital. &quot;The
bourse is helping the economy handle about $100 million per month,&quot;
says Waldemar de Moraes, director of the IMF office in Lima. &quot;But if
that goes to $200 million per month Peru will need another means to handle
the overflow.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Luque Otero does not entirely agree with this assessment: &quot;Given the
interest we've aroused in foreign investors, there are no limits to what
we can do. I foresee the exchange going to $100 <BR>
billion trading volume in a few years without any difficulty.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The stockmarket is also working to expand its second market, the Mesa del
Negociacion, a particular type of money market on which a few small companies
are traded as well. Today the Mesa del Negociacion sees about $3 to $4 million
of trading each day. <BR>
<BR>
Lima has no over-the-counter market but Luque Otero is trying to create
a small market for high-risk stocks, similar to those that exist in London
and Paris. The Lima stockmarket has already commissioned two technicians
to begin designing the new market but it is too early, he adds, to decide
how it will be organised. <BR>
<BR>
Accords have also been signed with exchanges in Thailand, Singapore, Barcelona
and Madrid for cooperation. But for the time being, the Lima stockmarket
does not contemplate placing terminals in other financial capitals such
as New York or London. <p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
