<td valign=top align=left> 
<H2>RUSSIA </H2>
<H4>Despite the worst predictions at home and abroad, Russia continues to
follow the reform road and develop a taste for enterprising contact with
the outside world, even in the least promising places. Now it is time for
both the new Russian elite and the west to shift emphasis from economy to
society, and raise public trust by making the new landscape more fair <BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#society-debt">DEBT TO SOCIETY</A> <BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#vladivostock">VLADIVOSTOCK SCENE  </A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#shipping">SHIPPING NEWS </A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#norilsk">NORILSK </A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#foreign-entry">FOREIGN ENTRY  </A></H3>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4> </H4>
<H3><A NAME="society-debt"></A>DEBT TO SOCIETY </H3>
<B>The state can learn from its own citizens, who often show real initative
and a healthy scepticism<BR>
<BR>
</B><I>by Craig Mellow </I><BR>
<BR>
The final irony of eastern Europe's liberation decade, it seems, is that
in most places it takes a communist election victory to launch definitively
the era of post-communist politics. If communists themselves do not dream
of bringing back communism, it must have gone for good. <BR>
<BR>
Gennady Zyuganov and his cohorts in the Communist Party of the Russian Federation
emerged as the biggest party in December's parliamentary election. But they
will not be able to turn the clock back. Three Russian parliaments in a
row have been accused of being soft on reform, since they axed the reformist
shock therapist Yegor Gaidar as prime minister in December 1992 and replaced
him with the supposed reactionary Viktor Chernomyrdin. Yet Russian reform
keeps rolling along. <BR>
<BR>
Even so, the Russian version of market democracy has been a poor advertisement
for that form of social organisation. The new order is no fairer than the
communist one but it is much greedier. It has created new opportunities
for those fastest on their feet but has temporarily diminished the prospects
for an average person seeking a decent education and dignified job. Democracy
has brought a traditionally egalitarian society to extremes of wealth and
poverty. To ordinary people, merit plays no part in this. <BR>
<BR>
The key to the next five years in Russia will lie in the behaviour of the
new elite which has consolidated power over the past five years. It is a
pan-ideological group of bankers and industry bosses, public officials and
criminals whose interests have drawn ever closer together. Its interests
are increasingly distant, however, from those of the population at large.
Dietmar Studemann, minister plenipotentiary at the German Embassy in Moscow,
recently commented: &quot;We are witnessing in the Russian elites a complete
lack of responsibility to society. Therefore I look at Russia's immediate
future without much optimism.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Measuring an elite's responsibility to society is much more complicated
than keeping tabs on budget deficits and inflation. Key indicators include
such subtleties as the struggle for the rule of law or maintaining an education
system which was the Soviet Union's finest achievement. If the new elite
does congeal into one more Russian court dividing the spoils secretly among
its members, the country will stagnate or worse. The new order has no mystical
veil of legitimacy like the Romanovs or communists, and the public is not
as ignorant as it used to be. <BR>
<BR>
The outlook may not be as gloomy as Studemann suggests. There is still room
at the middle, if not the top, for new faces with energy and talent and
there has been an unexpected explosion of entrepreneurial energy. Communism
was good at teaching people how to hustle for survival. Management skills
may not always be the most refined, but ordinary Russians have raced ahead
of their government. The state continues to live in terror of the mass unemployment
which is supposed to result from shutting bankrupt factories. But the workforce
at most plants is long gone, fending for itself elsewhere. Important exceptions
are company towns like Magnitogorsk or Norilsk (see page 191). <BR>
<BR>
Another positive element is the devolution of economic power from Moscow
ministries to factory floors. Few privatised Russian enterprises bear much
relation yet to investor-held corporations. But the local director now stands
a better chance of improving the company than a bureaucrat thousands of
miles away. Admittedly, the first instinct of many bosses was to exploit
their property. But with old inventories gone and the government tough on
credit, the smarter bosses are forced into a more businesslike approach.
<BR>
<BR>
Regional government is also wresting ever more revenue and power from the
centre, which foreign business representatives think all to the good. &quot;The
ministry men in Moscow can be totally removed from reality.&quot; observes
Stuart Swanson, Russia country manager for the US pharmaceutical firm Pfizer.
<BR>
<BR>
Then there are Russia's already strong links to the outside world. From
the industrial baron trotting the globe to the babushka who lives for her
daily episode of the American soap opera Santa Barbara, almost every citizen
has some reason to cherish the open borders of freedom. A Japanese television
set is material aspiration number one for the masses, while slightly better
earners dream of Italian washing machines and beach holidays in Turkey.
<BR>
<BR>
Russians are all for the national interest on abstract matters like Nato
expansion or selling the state oil companies. But to take away those things
which the world now offers would be bitterly unpopular. A further cause
for hope is the dismantling of much, if not all, of the totalitarian machine.
<BR>
<BR>
There are huge problems. While the violent criminality of gangsters grabs
the headlines it is the brazen criminality of the ruling authorities which
has most damaged the social fabric. The brief shining moment of 1990-91,
when for the first time in history Russians felt they might play a part
in their own government, has faded away. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Every week [the authorities] dream up some new agency,&quot; complains
a plastics factory director in the city of Rybinsk, north of Moscow. &quot;If
I make a red pail instead of a blue pail, I have to get approval for it.&quot;
To much of the population, the new order is perfect proof of what the communists
taught them all their lives -- that all riches are by definition stolen
from the poor. <BR>
<BR>
It is nearly impossible to obey the law and make a profit in Russia -- the
tax code sees to that. Excessive rates hurt the state because everybody
evades them. Worse still, they give officials and gangsters grounds to blackmail
virtually every business operator in the country. But despite everything,
businesses are normalising their operations and paying staff by bank transfer
rather than cash, making taxation at source more viable. Together with the
closure of other loopholes this could bring profits tax and VAT, currently
at 35% and 21% respectively, closer to European levels. <BR>
<BR>
At the company level, Russian manufacturers have largely failed to translate
their cheap labour into a cost advantage over imports. They continue to
make inferior goods at only slightly reduced prices, and entire sectors
have accordingly been wiped out. This cannot be blamed on the government,
whose tariff policy has walked a fairly reasonable line between producer
and consumer. <BR>
<BR>
The authorities are more directly at fault for continued stagnation in Russia's
huge agricultural sector, which still employs up to a quarter of the population.
An aggressive programme of credit for private farmers was quickly abandoned
as expensive and prone to fraud. The real reason was the hostility of the
powerful kolkhoz or collective farm lobby, which manages to suck plenty
of cash down its own black hole. <BR>
<BR>
The means of tackling these problems are yet to be developed. But the state
must find some way to put its officials beyond the reach of corruption and
establish trust between citizen and state. Apart from tax changes, both
commercial efficiency and social justice would be greatly served by strengthening
Russia's court system which the communists left a withered stump and which
the average citizen desperately needs as a watchdog. The world community
could do its bit by showing Russian lawyers some of the loving care, such
as know-how programmes, it has so far concentrated on economics. <BR>
<BR>
Above all, the outside world might best aid its cause by shifting support
from Russian reform to Russian democracy. Foreign business was jubilant
when the first parliament was crushed in October 1993 and Yeltsin ruled
by decree for nearly a year. Yet Russia's legislators have grown rapidly
in competence and sobriety while the Kremlin lives in an increasingly opaque
world. &quot;Personally I prefer dealing with the Duma,&quot; notes Vladimir
Volodin, president of the US-Russian consulting firm Impact Russia. &quot;I
can walk in the door, find a deputy and talk to him. Try doing that with
any ministry official above the level of toilet cleaner.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The country got a second chance at freedom because Yeltsin was big enough
not to take absolute power after the 1993 October Events. The December 1995
election was a fine display of democratic process. If this second chance
is muffed, the third may be a long time coming.<BR><BR> <HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="vladivostock"></A>MEET THE NEW RELATIONS </H3>
<B>With the collapse of Moscow-led central planning, Russia's eastern rim
is looking to its Asian neighbours</B> <BR>
<BR>
It is easy to forget just how big Russia is. The eastern outpost of Vladivostok,
seven time zones and more than 6,000 km away from Moscow, may be politically
and culturally European. But geographically, and now economically, this
is east Asia. <BR>
<BR>
With the collapse of central planning, distances inside the federation have
acquired an entirely new meaning. Gone are the days of cheap railway fares
and centralised distribution that tied Russia's Far East firmly to Europe.
This vast region, bordering China and North Korea and a short hop from Japan,
is increasingly looking to the Pacific rim countries for economic salvation.
<BR>
<BR>
The figures speak for themselves. In 1994 trade with China, Japan and South
Korea accounted for 77% of trade in Primorski krai, Russia's Far Eastern
maritime region of which Vladivostok is the capital. The evidence is everywhere
on the streets. There is hardly a left-hand drive car to be seen in Vladivostok.
Russian Volgas and Zhigulis were long ago outnumbered by Japanese-made Toyotas
and Hondas whose right-hand drive construction adds another ingredient to
the city's crazy traffic. <BR>
<BR>
A look at the shops reveals few of the European products that are everywhere
in Moscow or Petersburg. Instead Vladivostok has a Chinese market, kiosks
brimming with imports from Korea and shops full of consumer electronics
from Japan. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Miso soup, not hamburgers </B><BR>
<BR>
Seek out a hotel built to international standards and Vladivostok will offer
you one Canadian-owned motel and three joint ventures backed by Japanese
or Chinese money. The story is much the same in the city's restaurants.
If you want Miso soup, there is no problem; a decent hamburger or lasagne
is rather more complicated. Everywhere you look, it is east Asian products
that have hit the market first, with those of the US, Canada, Australia
and New Zealand following on. <BR>
<BR>
This is not surprising. Geography dictates that trade with the east is bound
to increase in importance although the west coast of the US and Canada have
recently woken up to the opportunities in the Russian Far East and there
are even flights from Vladivostok and Khabarovsk to Anchorage and Seattle.
Not only do Asian neighbours have the advantage of proximity, and thus price,
but they are also keenly aware of the region's importance as a route to
the vast Russian market and a source of the raw materials they crave. <BR>
<BR>
Timber, non-ferrous metals, soon-to-be developed oilfields in Sakhalin Island
and above all fish are among the Russian Far East's major resources. It
is home to some of the world's largest fishing companies and close to the
big fish markets of Japan and Korea. &quot;This year there was 30% growth
in the fishing industry, despite an overall fall in the country. We believe
this is one of the major opportunities in the region,&quot; says Victor
Tumanov, head of ING Bank's representative office in Vladivostok. <BR>
<BR>
Yet for all its massive potential the Far East is still firmly at the &quot;opportunities&quot;
stage, especially as far as ordinary citizen is concerned. Most trade earnings,
particularly in natural resources, have gone to a few companies, with no
noticeable gain for ordinary folk. <BR>
<BR>
Vladivostok has developed a &quot;wild east&quot; reputation as a crime-ridden
mafia gangland, often compared to Chicago in the '20s. Although this image
is often exaggerated, it is certainly true that a small group of individuals
continue to control a large proportion of the local economy and have little
interest in spreading prosperity to the community as a whole. Furthermore,
the region has suffered substantially from the collapse of traditional supply
lines and from being so distant from the seat of power. <BR>
<BR>
Even in relatively prosperous Vladivostok, the standard of living is below
much of western Russia. This is a region with very little agriculture or
industry of its own. But just as the region no longer sends its precious
resources westward, so western Russia and Siberia no longer provide the
goods sent to the Far East in Soviet times. <BR>
<BR>
The most obvious example is coal. Towns and villages in the region suffer
regular power cuts, sometimes for several hours a day, because the power
stations can no longer afford to buy and transport enough coal from other
parts of Russia. The story is similar with other Russian products, exacerbated
by an inefficient payments system within the country and high rates of interest.
As Andrew Fox, head of a Vladivostok-based broking and investment company,
puts it: &quot;Interest rates are a cost for distances in Russia. High interest
rates are a penalty for long distances.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>Former isolation made change harder </B><BR>
<BR>
It is also easy to forget, looking at Vladivostok today, that this was a
closed city just three years ago with restricted access not just for foreigners
but for non-native Russians. Vladivostok was the eastern fortress, home
to the powerful Pacific fleet. Everything else, including the development
of trade, was secondary, and this made economic change all the harder when
it came. There are other problems: this is still Russia, with all the attendant
difficulties of doing business like high taxes, lack of security and difficult
finance. <BR>
<BR>
For all these reasons the Far Eastern economy has developed more slowly
than some people hoped in the optimistic days of the early '90s. South Korean
giant Hyundai is by far the most active company in the region. The company
is building a $50 million complex of hotels, offices and shops in central
Vladivostok which it hopes will form the heart of the new business district.
But progress has been slow on the project, which began construction in July.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Our investment at this stage is just a matter of goodwill.,&quot;
says Oh Soo-Kwoon, Hyundai's manager in Vladivostok. &quot;We've already
had to pay $20 million in federal taxes. Nobody knows when the centre will
be finished, maybe in one and a half years. Our relationship with the local
administration is very good - we have an exemption from all local taxes
- but federal tax laws are very difficult.&quot; In addition, investment
and finance regulations have made most potential investors cautious about
the Far East. &quot;Other parts of Russia may have more government guarantees
and support,&quot; says ING's Tumanov. &quot;Here everything is just beginning.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Choi Yong Sam, South Korea's consul overseeing economic affairs in Vladivostok,
is also wary. &quot;Most Korean companies are not engaged directly in trade
but have Russian partners. The regulations here are very changeable and
it's difficult to make a strategy,&quot; he says. &quot;There are also security
problems in the port and in transit which make things difficult if Koreans
handle things directly,&quot; Choi adds in a diplomatic reference to mafia
influence at the port. <BR>
<BR>
But for all such teething problems almost everyone is optimistic, even bullish,
about the future of the Far East and port cities like Vladivostok and Nakhodka,
the main tanker terminal. The latter has a free zone area which is being
developed in conjunction with the South Korean government. The idea is to
attract more manufacturing and processing to the area and encourage further
development of the port. <BR>
<BR>
<B>More modest Tumen river project </B><BR>
<BR>
Meanwhile, there is a grand UN-sponsored project based around the river
Tuman at the point where the Russian, North Korean and Chinese borders meet
in southern Primorski krai. The Tuman river project was originally driven
by the Chinese, who wanted access to the sea via the Tuman river. But in
the five years since the project was mooted it has changed shape considerably.
The initial idea of building a brand new international port city on the
Tuman and dredging and widening the river has been abandoned as too expensive.
Now it concerns the construction of new rail links to existing ports in
North Korea and Russia which would then be further developed. <BR>
<BR>
An international project of this kind is seen as an excellent way of developing
the whole region by combining local resources, such as raw materials from
Russia, cheap labour from China and North Korea and know-how from more developed
South Korea. <BR>
<BR>
The Russian port of Zarubino in southern Primorski krai has been picked
for development because of its deep bay. Rail links to China are already
being built, using a Chinese railway gauge so that goods will not have to
be unloaded and reloaded at the border. Japan is particularly interested
in the Zarubino project as a route for Chinese grain to Japan. But in the
longer term Zarubino could also serve as an alternative route for east-west
trade, by offering a shorter route to Europe via China than the trans-Siberian
railway now on offer. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Still far from the power centre </B><BR>
<BR>
This is one reason why Russia has remained rather equivocal about the project,
while officially supporting it. &quot;Nakhodka and Vladivostok don't want
to see Zarubino developed,&quot; says Sergei Verolainin at the USAID office
in Vladivostok, who was involved with the scheme while in local government.
<BR>
<BR>
Verolainin also attributes Russia's foot-dragging to distance. &quot;Foreign
affairs people who know the project well do understand its significance,
but for most in the government it's not very important because it's small
and so far away,&quot; he says. <BR>
<BR>
This is symptomatic of another traditional issue in this part of the country:
the balance of power between the centre and the periphery. For all the erosion
of central authority Moscow still ultimately controls what goes on in the
regions, including the Far East. As the democratic process develops in Russia
and regional governors are elected rather than appointed by the president,
the balance of power is starting to shift. The process has begun already
with the election of Yevgeni Nazdratenko as governor of Primorski krai.
&quot;Being elected rather than appointed will help him to be more influential
in Moscow,&quot; says Tumanov. <BR>
<BR>
Shifts in power towards the regions could also speed development of the
local economy. There are occasional rumblings about greater autonomy or
even independence, but no serious moves in that direction. The great popularity
of Vladimir Zhirinovsky's ultra- nationalist party in the Far East in recent
elections is no accident. There may be some resentment against the Moscow
bosses, but the fear of a big neighbour like China is much stronger. <BR>
<BR>
Indeed, the Far East can feel more enthusiastic about its integration into
the Pacific rim economy because it is part of Russia. The region's major
trading partner is Japan, although most investment comes from Korean companies.
&quot;The Japanese and Americans are watching how it is going, they are
more risk-averse,&quot; says Choi at the Korean consulate. And he says there
is less baggage in relations between Russia and Korea, a reference to the
absence of old scores like the Cold War or Russia's dispute with Japan over
the Kuril Islands. <BR>
<BR>
The Korean government has placed considerable emphasis on the Russian Far
East. Government help with the Nakhodka Free Zone, for example, should bring
advantages for Korean companies when it comes to international bidding for
construction and other projects in a few years. Seoul is also looking to
the day when its northern Korean neighbour will open up and allow goods
and people to move directly to Russia, instead of having to take roundabout
routes which avoid the currently hardline communist north. <BR>
<BR>
For the time being such hopes and projects remain part of a rosy future.
But for all today's hardships the future should bring great prosperity to
this strategically placed region. As Tumanov puts it: &quot;Although people
are not always happy with the life they have at the moment, these are the
times we are living in. It's important to have the opportunity to improve
things, and we certainly have that here.&quot;* <BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="shipping"></A>SHIPPING NEWS <BR>
</H3>
<B>It is hard to find a venture in the Russian Far East in which the maritime
industry has no share</B>
It is the maritime sector that holds the greatest promise in the coastal
regions of the Russian Far East. The most powerful and successful companies
in the area are those involved in shipping, fishing and port facilities.
A handful of these major companies, like the Far Eastern Shipping Company
(Fesco), the Primorsk Shipping Company, DalMoreProdukt and the Vladivostok
and Nakhodka commercial ports, have such diversified investments that it
is hard to find a significant company or venture in the region free of their
involvement. <BR>
<BR>
Fesco, the region's premier company and Russia's largest dry cargo shipping
company, owns shares in Vladivostok's leading local bank, the fanciest hotel
in town, the Far East's biggest local newspaper group, the largest construction
company and a thriving regional airline. Moreover, this list is far from
exhaustive. <BR>
<BR>
Nevertheless, even companies like Fesco have had their share of problems
since the collapse of the Soviet Union. The region's fishing and shipping
companies have had problems finding the money to build new vessels, something
once centrally funded from Moscow. Fesco's fleet now has an average age
of 17.5 years says Mikhail Yakimenko, <BR>
vice-president of finance and planning. &quot;That is very bad: 10 or 11
years would be good.&quot; The company has received credits from the European
Bank of Reconstruction and Development, as well as a number of other western
institutions, but this has not solved the problem. <BR>
<BR>
To make matters worse, Russia has seen a sudden hike in the price of bunkers
or shipping fuel, from well below world prices a year or so ago to some
15% above it now. &quot;The main costs for a shipping company are bunkers,
the cost of finance and crew wages. Russian shipowners have been hit on
all three items, and have to deal with a punitive tax regime to boot,&quot;
says Gavin Stoddart, Vladivostok director for accountant and international
shipping specialist Moore Stephens. <BR>
<BR>
The financial problems of the shipping and fishing sector have meant a bonanza
for some, like those agents who buy ships for scrap. In the last couple
of years an unprecedented number of ships have found their way to breakers'
yards in India and Bangladesh from the Russian Far East. Some are well under
20 years old, sold off by companies desperate for the cash to renovate or
repair the rest of their fleets. <BR>
<BR>
Despite these problems, most agree that the maritime sector has enormous
potential. &quot;If we weren't optimistic we wouldn't be here,&quot; says
Stoddart. &quot;That goes for all the foreign companies moving in.&quot;
<BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3><A NAME="norilsk"></A>STILL US AND THEM? </H3>
A clever but controversial sell-off scheme at Norilsk Nickel prompted old
doubts - and a new consensus <BR>
<BR>
<I> by Craig Mellow </I><BR>
<BR>
They are suspicious of strangers at Norilsk Nickel; particularly these days.
This is part of the United Export-Import Bank, Oneksim, the fourth largest
and single most aggressive in a Russian financial world not renowned for
its corporate sissies. <BR>
<BR>
In November Oneksim - Unexim using the English abbreviation - bought 51%
of Norilsk Nickel's voting stock and 38% of total equity from the Russian
state at a cost of $170.1 million. Typically, the terms of the deal leave
it unclear whether Oneksim has become the company's owner, underwriter,
or lien-holder. But most people in Norilsk, and everybody in its management,
seems to prefer none of the above. <BR>
<BR>
You might think the climate in Norilsk, three degrees of latitude north
of the Arctic Circle, would keep the riff-raff out. A traveller touching
down on a December night is greeted by snow raging like a Sahara sandstorm.
The temperature might be unseasonably warm at -20&#186;C, but the wind is
elementally terrifying. Yet beneath this waste is one of the world's richest
seams of valuable metals. The company produces 20% of the world's nickel
supply, 40% of all metals in the platinum group and 70% of Russia's copper.
Vast stocks remain below the ground. As a result, ever since the city was
opened to outsiders under <I>perestroika</I>, the world has beaten a path
to Norilsk Nickel's door. <BR>
<BR>
The company's managers and workers, owners of most remaining shares, assume
that their <I>kombinat</I> is worth a fortune. In their minds only stupidity
and dirty dealing can explain the pittance that Oneksim paid. &quot;They
sold us, and sold us cheap,&quot; summarises Valery Glazkov, leader of Norilsk
Nickel's trade union. Immediately after the sale he and the city's new <I>Duma</I>
deputy, Viktor Sitnov, joined forces to collect proxy votes for an anticipated
showdown with Oneksim for control. <BR>
<BR>
Yet reason and finance do not always agree. Norilsk Nickel needs some expensive
repairs. Last winter a turbine cracked in the electric station which convict
labour threw up for emergency war production in 1942. The breakdown left
thousands of apartments without heat or electricity. The original nickel
smelter, also built during the war, still wheezes along. The copper works,
opened on Stalin's 70th birthday in 1949, is too small to accommodate contemporary
furnaces. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Monument to Soviet power </B><BR>
<BR>
The whole structure of Norilsk was a slap in the face to market economics.
It was dedicated as a monument to the capabilities of Soviet power. At a
dreadful cost, these did prove impressive. The town grew from naked tundra
in 1935 to a metropolitan area of 300,000 people with an excellent repertory
theatre, graduate institutes and one of Russia's best children's hospitals.
All of it is paid for by Norilsk Nickel and all of it, economically speaking,
is dead weight. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;At the Alaskan oil rigs there's nothing but some barracks for workers
who fly in temporarily,&quot; remarks one of the more thoughtful functionaries
at headquarters. &quot;Our model of the north, with families and kindergartens,
turns out to be mistaken.&quot; In Soviet times those families would stay
for three years and go home with enough money saved to buy a car. Or they
could stay 15 years and retire comfortably to somewhere warmer. Now, with
world prices holding sway on &quot;the mainland&quot; as the rest of the
land mass is known, they are trapped with nowhere to go. <BR>
<BR>
For all these reasons and more, financial logic holds that Oneksim Bank
paid a fair price for Norilsk Nickel, no more than $0.25 off the quoted
level of $3.80 per share. Norilsk Nickel is a bit extreme in location, but
essentially it is typical of the prize properties which the Moscow government
wants to transform in its second stage of privatisation: capital intensive
enterprises resemble a small kingdom as much as a corporation. They tend
to be hierarchical, conservative communities knit tightly together by survival
in harsh conditions, led by a proud but ageing management team which came
up through the ranks and which, while grudgingly admitting that outside
capital is essential, is determined to accept it on the enterprise's own
terms. <BR>
<BR>
Reformers in the Russian government have been running the industrial barons
to ground for years now. What is new and somewhat surprising is that resourceful
young banks have dealt themselves into the game as a potentially equal partner.
Free market ideologues will applaud this development as essential to the
efficiency of future investment. But given some of the questions still swirling
about the background and character of Oneksim and others like it, the citizens
of Norilsk are entitled to their doubts. <BR>
<BR>
Norilsk Nickel's management is bloated, employing 1,500 headquarters staff
for some 150,000 workers. Technically however, it is among the world's finest
and staff are head-hunted by far-flung competitors: the foreman who showed
this correspondent around the copper smelter had just been offered a job
in Chile at $8,000 per month, or at least 10 times his current salary. Norilsk
Nickel workers also have a better reputation than some for returning revenues
to the enterprise coffers. Yet they do have their blind spots, among which
is the idea that the <I>kombinat</I> could ever really slip out of their
control. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;You tell all the banks that in three years the window for investing
in us will be closed,&quot; growls no-nonsense deputy director Boris Kazakov.
&quot;And then we'll remember who helped us,&quot; chimes in a public relations
adjutant. These are vintage Soviet sentiments, innocent of the notion that
investment might somehow change the definition of &quot;us&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
Little innocence of any sort is to be found at the Moscow headquarters of
Oneksim Bank. This is a quintessential lair of the new Russia, full of harassed
executives who are 32 but look 45, men who become separated from their cellular
phones only in cases of national crisis. The bank's startling success since
opening its doors in 1993 seems to stem in equal parts from knowing what
it is doing and knowing whom to do it with. It married the capital of some
two dozen top hard-currency exporters, including Norilsk Nickel itself,
with the brightest young staff from the old Soviet Vneshekonombank among
other places. Government heavies including former finance minister Boris
Fyodorov presided over the wedding. <BR>
<BR>
<B>New but untried privatisation solution </B><BR>
<BR>
But the old boys created a monster beyond their control. This became more
apparent as the Russian government wrapped up its lightning voucher privatisation
programme and wondered how to move on to the second stage or cash privatisation.
The vouchers had more to do with decentralisation than privatisation. They
transferred control from ministries to managers, and sometimes well organised
employees, but failed to raise capital or change the way most plants were
run. Nor did the state make money from the process. <BR>
<BR>
Stage two was meant to be different, auctioning genuinely valuable enterprises
to actual investors for real money. Yet the government was caught between
two conflicting imperatives: the need to net a worthy sum from sale of the
crown jewels and the need to keep them out of foreign hands. With most Russia's
liquid capital secreted abroad, these conditions looked hard to fulfil.
<BR>
<BR>
Enter Oneksim Bank with its &quot;loans for shares&quot; scheme, a variation
of the debt-equity swop. The bank argued that the state could offload controlling
stakes in blue chip enterprises without dumping them on a market unprepared
to buy. Instead commercial banks would take the packets as &quot;collateral&quot;
on &quot;loans&quot; made to the government. The banks would then have three
years to create a secondary market, with 70% of any profit they made from
resale going back to the treasury. <BR>
<BR>
At first a consortium of nine banks proposed to take most of what was valuable
in Russia for a flat $2 billion. But this proved too much to stomach politically.
Instead, the state property committee decided to auction off the enterprises
separately. The bosses at Norilsk Nickel, like almost everywhere else, lobbied
Moscow hard to get off the list. They failed. <BR>
<BR>
The problem is that loans-for-shares is a complex procedure, unproved in
the Russian context, which no one has yet bothered to explain to the public.
The small minority which does grasp what is involved strongly suspects that
it has as much to do with securing senior bureaucrats' retirement nest-eggs
as with the national interest. <BR>
<BR>
The conduct of the early auctions hardly allayed that suspicion. Chaos became
inevitable when Oneksim Bank, already tipped as a major player, was also
charged with organising most of the bids. Trouble flared at the auction
when Oneksim helped disqualify a much higher bid ($355 million) from competitor
Rossiysky Kredit on the grounds that a central bank edict disqualified offers
in excess of the bidder's own capital. Given that Oneksim Bank quickly digested
oil giant Sidanco and still hungered for more, this logic seems niggling
at best. <BR>
<BR>
The next major auction, for the Yukos oil company, was also won by its organiser,
Bank Menatep. At this point Rossiysky Kredit, Inkombank and Alfa Bank, all
original consortium members, publicly demanded that the auctions be halted.
The squabbling, coming weeks before the December parliamentary elections,
was grist to the Communists' anti-market mill. <BR>
<BR>
The normally loquacious Oneksim Bank became defensive after the auction.
A spokesman insisted that the bank had not really bought the shares, but
had just taken them as security. At the same time, he sought to trumpet
a $1 billion investment plan developed jointly with the <I>kombinat</I>'s
management. Whose $1 billion this was and how exactly it would be used the
spokesman could not say. <BR>
<BR>
If Oneksim and the other banks cannot fulfill their pledges the state might
yet repurchase the shares and end the experiment. Yet the larger process
will not be so easily reversed. Boris Kazakov, the hard-bitten Arctic mining
boss, understands one thing that his trade unions do not: whatever hot air
is blown on the campaign trail, the Russian state will never again produce
the money which Norilsk Nickel needs. <BR>
<BR>
Nor does Kazakov want to be locked back up in a closed city with some central
committeeman from Moscow telling him how to run his business. So he swallows
his pride and flies off to hear the views of the Moscow bankers he so despises.
<BR>
<BR>
Back home in Norilsk, a glance through the classified ads shows that distance
cannot fend off what is happening all over Russia. Private estate agencies,
custom tailors, home repair contractors and stock brokers all hawk their
services. Travel agents offer junkets to destinations from Pattaya to Rome.
Like everywhere, sense is painfully drilling its way through the encrusted
layers of past insanity. <BR>
<BR>
Russia's natural riches require private capital made politically acceptable
by its Russian origins, put to work by local management and milked for tax
revenue by the state. Many of those involved already essentially accept
these ground rules. The state may waste a bit more time and money, but in
the end it is forced to do the same. A scant four years after the Soviet
Union's dissolution, such a degree of accord is quite an achievement in
itself.<BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3>THE SEVEN GENERALS </H3>
<B>Officially, the oil and gas industry is still in state hands, but its
leaders shaping up as potential partners </B><BR>
<BR>
When an oil spill by the state oil company Komineft caused one of history's
greatest ecological disasters last year in Russia's far north, management
reacted very curiously. It invited in the press, then petitioned the World
Bank for an emergency clean-up loan. The spill was mopped up within six
months, bank officials report. <BR>
<BR>
Such incidents signify a much larger trend. Phase one of the battle for
Russia's oil and gas wealth has largely ended. The inchoate, top-secret
state monolith has been broken down into six still-huge holding companies.
Although still formally in state hands, these firms call their own shots
and have privatisation very much on their minds. <BR>
<BR>
The comrades, seven of them if the gas industry behemoth Gazprom is included,
are far from models of modern management. Yet they provide a much firmer
base for partnership than a few years ago. And while they are quite capable
of wrapping themselves in the flag, they are keenly aware of the need to
attract capital from beyond Russia's borders. If the government ever tightens
up its tax and regulatory policy, large multinational energy projects may
become a reality over the next few years. <BR>
<BR>
When western firms arrived in Russia, the domestic industry's image was
one of helpless incompetence. Yet despite recent setbacks, the prevailing
spirit in Siberian oil towns like Nizhnevartovsk and Surgut is that of pioneering
pride, tersely expressed by Yuri Shafranik, Russia's energy minister and
former director of the production complex in Langepas. &quot;I built a city
from nothing, nil,&quot; Shafranik says. &quot;I'm not afraid of much.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
What they did not know about post-modern finance, the oil generals more
than compensated for with what they did know about Russian politics and
quietly stamped, sealed, and notarised their control over the nation's essential
wealth. <BR>
<BR>
Biggest, fastest and meanest of the oil companies is Lukoil, which merged
Shafranik's old Langepas enterprise with its giant neighbour at Kogalym
and a few smaller well heads. Lukoil has become Russian oil's face abroad,
most notably when it muscled its way into the $8 billion multinational consortium
wanting to drill in the Caspian Sea. Back home Lukoil has led the way in
bringing once independent downstream units to heel and attracting serious
equity investment. <BR>
<BR>
Yukos, whose core is the Siberian production centre of Nefteyugansk, has
been the most eager collaborator with new Russian financial institutions,
in particular Bank Menatep which took a majority stake in a loans-for-shares
auction with the company's blessing. Yukos' neighbour Surgutneftegaz is
the crusty, grudgingly respected conservative of the oil patch, running
a tight traditional ship and exercising extreme caution with outsiders,
foreign or domestic. Management arranged for its own pension fund to win
the loans-for-shares auction. <BR>
<BR>
The newest Siberian giant, Sidanco, is trying to live down a shady reputation
from its <BR>
ill-fated White Nights joint venture with America's Phibro. It has played
its cards in Moscow brilliantly, however, managing to expand from a single
drilling centre at Varyegan to full-fledged membership of the sisterhood.
<BR>
<BR>
The Nizhnevartovsk oil agglomeration is Siberia's sick man. Its gargantuan
Samotlor field, once the ultimate symbol of Soviet economic might, has become
a staggering example of crumbling infrastructure. Last comes Komineft, whose
interests include the resources of the Komi Autonomous Republic in European
Russia, and Gazprom. <BR>
<BR>
The fortunes of Gazprom, which single-handedly accounts for nearly 20% of
Russia's exports, have certainly been aided by the rise of former director
Viktor Chernomyrdin to the prime minister's chair. Indeed, foreign aid types
grumble about Gazprom's extraordinary record of tax exemptions. But the
premier's importance to the energy industry as a whole is often overstated.<BR><BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H3><A NAME="foreign-entry"></A>CASE FOR TREATMENT </H3>
The experience of Pfizer highlights some common, and not so common, challenges
facing foreign investors<BR>
<BR>
<I>by Craig Mellow </I><BR>
<BR>
Of the myriad statistics which course through a modern manager's mind, there
is one which gives Stuart Swanson the strength to get out of bed each morning.
Russia, where Swanson is country manager for US drug firm Pfizer International,
spent a mere $1.5 billion on wholesale pharmaceuticals in 1994. This is
the same amount as Poland, with a fourth of the population. It is not that
Russians are any healthier than Poles or, he believes, any poorer. Rather,
Russian doctors and hospitals are less informed about what is known in the
trade as pharma-economics. <BR>
<BR>
Swanson, an excited 30-something former US diplomat, reaches for nearby
scrap paper. &quot;Say the old drug costs $3.00 and my drug costs $15.00.
But with that drug you need two courses instead of one. And our drug gets
you back to work two days sooner. Or out of the hospital a day earlier.&quot;
In Russia, where patients commonly spend weeks in hospital for controllable
afflictions like high blood pressure, Swanson's logic seems compelling but
he sees little chance of a boom before 1997-98. <BR>
<BR>
It is clear now that few multinational companies will invest in Russia the
way they invested in China or Thailand, to produce cheap goods for re-export.
Russia's costs are not all that low any more, the distances between industrial
base and ports are vast and poorly navigated, quality is poor and the government
incorrigibly irritating. <BR>
<BR>
<B>More disposable income than predicted </B><BR>
<BR>
But Russia has proved unexpectedly attractive as a market to sell into.
Its 150 million people, plus as many again in the rest of the Commonwealth
of Independent States, consistently come up with more expendable income
than the statisticians predict. And the consumer landscape is a pre-modern
<I>terra incognita.</I> Multinationals bring products which are either new,
like videos and dishwashing liquid, or so superior in quality and packaging
that they form a new product category. <BR>
<BR>
Foreign drug firms walked into a void. Soviet economic planning alloted
production of most medicines to the central or east European satellites,
although bulk chemicals often came from plants in the Soviet Union. These
supply lines withered with the death of the Comecon trade bloc, leaving
Russia's pharmacies dependent on Indian medicines: cheap enough, but often
at least a generation out of date. <BR>
<BR>
Those foreign food, tobacco and detergent manufacturers who were wise enough
four years ago to disregard stories about a Russia in ruins have already
generated enough sales volume to justify local manufacturing. Mars and Proctor
&amp; Gamble, whose ads dominated the Russian airwaves a year back, now
feel confident enough to take a lower profile. <BR>
<BR>
Drug companies faced a more complicated task than their consumer goods colleagues.
The old ministerial procurement system, which Swanson says produced virtually
no sales for foreign firms, collapsed in 1992-93. Today the central government
makes less than 20% of Russia's drug purchases. The rest of the money is
spent by a patchwork of provincial health authorities, hospitals commanding
their own budgets and privatised pharmacies. <BR>
<BR>
Distribution was also revolutionised by private firms or joint-stock companies.
Taking the reins early in 1993, Swanson's first focus was getting Pfizer
products into these pipelines and the company's over-the-counter offerings
helped pave the way for much lower volume prescription drugs. Last year,
having created a supply line capable of delivering goods anywhere in Russia
within two days, Pfizer's attention shifted to the customer. Swanson hired
25 sales representatives in 15 cities to persuade doctors and administrators
of the efficiency of global profit leaders like Norvase (for cardiovascular
illnesses) and the anti-fungal Diflukan. <BR>
<BR>
There are signs of some progress. Pfizer's Moscow office has always paid
for itself out of sales which grew 120% last year to around $10 million:
not so much money relative to global revenues of $10 billion, but not so
bad while the company is establishing a presence. <BR>
<BR>
When dealing with the many layers of Russian bureaucracy, Swanson's guiding
principle is to &quot;avoid centres of incompetence&quot;. This was easier
said than done under the previous health minister Eduard Nechaev, replaced
in November: an army surgeon whose idea of protecting the public was to
issue every family with an infantryman's first aid kit. In such circumstances
Pfizer stuck to ground-level practitioners and local administrators wherever
possible. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Taking health in their own hands </B><BR>
<BR>
The new challenge is an official determination to protect the local pharmaceutical
industry, such as it is. The outgoing parliament passed a law last year
requiring punitive tariffs on all imported drugs whose &quot;equivalent&quot;
is made locally, quite a broad category if one chooses to define it that
way. Pfizer has nodded in the protectionists' direction by leasing manufacturing
time in a plant put up by Bristol-Myers Squibb. It is also building a small
facility of its own to produce veterinary drugs. But a dedicated factory
for human pharmaceuticals would require many times the current sales volume.
<BR>
<BR>
Swanson is sure time is on his side, not least because Russians are taking
health, like everything else, more into their own hands. Officially, medicine
remains a near-monopoly of the state but informally, &quot;people are already
even more accustomed to paying out of their own pocket than in a place like
Poland&quot;. Private insurance plans are slowly taking shape as well. <BR>
<BR>
Naturally, not everyone is so sure. Swanson has had trouble finding a replacement
for himself. &quot;In the food industry or banking, Moscow is already seen
as a post which can make your career,&quot; he explains. &quot;But our people
just haven't seen the numbers yet.&quot; <p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

