<td valign=top align=left> 
<H2>TATARSTAN </H2>
<H4>An autonomous republic within Russia, Tatarstan has maintained its distance
from Moscow and initiated a series of economic reform programmes designed
to attract foreign investors. At the same time the country's first-ever
president, Mintimer Shaimiev, has kept a firm grip and steered Tatarstan
away from the upheavals that have beset other Russian republics like faraway
Chechnya <BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="tatarstan.html#overview">OVERVIEW</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="tatarstan.html#kazan-pizza">KAZAN'S PIZZERIA</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="tatarstan.html#mintimer-shaimiev">MINTIMER SHAIMIEV</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="tatarstan.html#privatisation">PRIVATISATION</A></H4>
<HR>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="overview"></A>AFTER THE SOFT LANDING </H3>
<B>By opting for a gentler economic reform programme, the Volga republic
has avoided many of Russia's problems <BR>
<BR>
</B><I>By Margie Lindsay </I><BR>
<BR>
Proud of its special place in the Russian federation, the republic of Tatarstan
has managed to placate strong nationalist sentiments and has negotiated
a treaty with Russia which gives it special status within the federation.
Through sustained and unrelenting tough negotiating led by the republic's
first president, Mintimer Shaimiev, and perhaps more effectively through
the withholding of tax revenue owed to Moscow, Tatarstan was able to insist
on concessions and succeeded in winning a large degree of autonomy for its
mainly Muslim population of just over 3 million. <BR>
<BR>
Most importantly, the agreement gives Tatarstan the right to sell half of
its considerable oil reserves at market prices. In addition the country's
authorities are allowed to collect tax and pay only a proportion to the
federal budget. <BR>
<BR>
However, grey areas remain and it is unclear just how far Tatarstan can
pursue an independent policy. Although the republic has said that it is
not seeking full independence, it already conducts a limited foreign policy.
It was the first republic to be granted the right to carry out its own foreign
economic policy and has trade missions in Washington, Paris, Adelaide, Moscow
and St Petersburg. More offices are planned with other trade partners. <BR>
<BR>
Despite the headway made by the republic on political issues, progress on
economic reform has been slower. Tatarstan's leadership opted for a third
way between state socialism and the free market shock therapy applied in
Russia. Instead President Shaimiev plumped for what was dubbed a soft-landing
reform which involved using hard currency reserves and revenues from oil
and oil-related industries to keep the economy stable. <BR>
<BR>
To ensure that living standards did not fall too fast or by too much, the
government kept price controls in place for some goods - although all prices
are free now - ensured social security payments were maintained and kept
state companies afloat when threatened by bankruptcy. As a result, local
people are relatively happy with the reforms so far. Shops in the capital
city Kazan are full of goods, albeit at higher prices than before. Food
is plentiful and affordable. <BR>
<BR>
The reform programme is also designed to further a long-term strategy which
will employ oil money to make Tatarstan an investment-driven economy. The
programme aims to attract foreign and domestic investors through incentives
and guarantees. <BR>
<BR>
<B>A sedate privatisation programme </B><BR>
<BR>
With one of the most progressive laws on private land ownership in Russia,
Tatarstan may indeed be attractive for investors. The state property committee
has created financial-industrial groups which provide large stakes in privatised
enterprises and issue secondary shares, bonds and credits backed by shares.
<BR>
<BR>
The sedate pace of privatisation in Tatarstan stemmed from the government's
desire to avoid major bankruptcies, with the accompanying social and economic
problems seen elsewhere in Russia. But it has led to abuses, particularly
by keeping in place old-style managements, the sort of people who most often
oppose interference from foreign investors. Restructuring is still needed
in the industrial sector where Soviet-era enterprises need new management
techniques and know-how to meet the challenges of a market economy. <BR>
<BR>
Political and economic stability have made the ethnically mixed population
grateful to Shaimiev. Outside concerns that his style of leadership is closer
to dictatorship than democracy tend to be brushed aside by the man on the
street as well as senior politicians. The president is genuinely liked and
admired for his ability to cushion the Volga republic from the worst of
the depression and keep nationalist sentiment under control - unlike in
Chechnya. <BR>
<BR>
The downside is that budget problems are looming. Tatarstan's economics
minister, Alla Gabutdinova, is cagey about the exact state of the republic's
finances. Inflation is well over 200% for the year, slightly below the figure
for all Russia. But information about oil production is contradictory, with
Gabutdinova saying it totals around 24 million tonnes a year while the foreign
trade ministry says it is a steady 25 million. Oil revenue last year was
approximately $900 million and should stay at that level for the foreseeable
future. <BR>
<BR>
Chemical and petrochemical industries once accounted for a quarter of the
republic's entire industrial output. Since then it has collapsed, as it
has throughout Russia. Gabutdinova wants to see higher oil production and
revenues from the sector but this seems unlikely, given the current state
of the oilfields, many of which are in need of repair and new technology
if they are to be developed further. The government estimates the sector
needs $1.2 billion to boost capacity, modernise and install new technologies.
<BR>
<BR>
Tatarstan holds around 10% of Russia's total oil reserves, but production
peaked in 1973 at 104 million tonnes. Like other republics with oil supplies,
Tatarstan is eagerly waiting for the federal parliament to pass a production-sharing
law which will clear the way for investment in its declining oilfields.
Foreign trade officials are praying three projects will be implemented if
the law is passed which would enable Tatarstan to boost its chemical and
petrochemical exports as well. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Tatneft depository receipts on offer </B><BR>
<BR>
Tatneft, the republic's integrated oil company, has now been privatised
and the company needs foreign investment. But western companies are hesitating
until the production-sharing law is passed before committing themselves.
Tatneft has already obtained preliminary approval by the US Securities and
Exchange Commission for the issue of depository receipts to help raise capital
for the company. If it goes ahead the offer, probably around 10% of shares,
will be handled by Citibank. <BR>
<BR>
Tatneft also has three joint ventures with western companies aimed at transferring
advanced technology and better environmental controls to Tatarstan's industry.
The largest investment is by Total: the two others are Global Natural Resources
of the US and Germany's Mineraloil. However, in 1994 these three joint ventures
only produced 3 million tonnes of crude oil. <BR>
<BR>
Apart from substantial amounts of oil the republic holds massive reserves
of oil shale - approximately 20 billion tonnes - but so far it has proved
impossible to extract this without causing substantial ecological damage,
as the oil shale reserves are at shallow depths, immediately under the water
table. <BR>
<BR>
Natural gas is extracted in Tatarstan, but in much smaller quantities than
oil. There are also opportunities to produce natural bitumen in the regions
beyond the Kama River, where deposits are estimated at 12.5 billion tonnes.
Other fuel resources include peat and coal. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Urbanised by heavy industry </B><BR>
<BR>
Tatarstan is heavily urbanised, with three-quarters of the population living
in built-up areas, largely because of industries like oil and petrochemicals.
It contains the largest petrochemical plant in all Europe, Nizhnekamskneftekhim,
which manufactures a range of products including propane, isoprene-monomer,
ethylene and propylene. <BR>
<BR>
It needs modernisation, however, and the company is planning to build another
plant able to refine 7 million tonnes of oil a year. When this begins operating,
Tatarstan will be able to supply a range of consumers beyond the republic's
borders. A new refinery in Almetyevsk went into production last year and
will refine around 400,000 tonnes a year of crude oil, producing petrol,
diesel and bitumen for the republic's eastern regions. <BR>
<BR>
In manufacturing, Tatarstan is the centre of Russian truck production. The
monopoly producer Kamaz builds some 80% of all of Russia's freight vehicles.
A plant in Naberezhnnye Chelny, on the Kama River, became Russia's first
joint stock company in 1990, with the republic holding 11% of shares. Despite
severe financial and structural problems, Kamaz is making progress. Recently
the company signed a joint venture deal under which the US firm General
Motors will manufacture Chevrolet Blazer jeeps at Kamaz's Yelabuga car factory.
Around 50,000 cars are to be built in an investment worth around $300 million.
The Yelabuga plant is only half-built, an economic casualty of the ending
of state subsidies. The 50% joint venture, led by GM, has the blessing of
the Tatarstan government as well as Russian officials. Initially the Yelabuga
plant will assemble US-made parts but the plan is to move gradually towards
using more Russian components. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Kamaz open for more partners </B><BR>
<BR>
Before the GM deal, Kamaz formed a partnership with Cummins Engine Company
of the US and European Bank for Reconstruction and Development. A new engine
was to be developed and built by Kamaz for an investment of between $330-500
million but the project appears to have halted, partly because of a serious
fire in 1994 which knocked its expansion plans for some time. The firm also
says it is working with Rockwell International. Despite the fire Kamaz remains
determined to attract more foreign investors for component supply, product
assembly, technology transfer and axle manufacture. <BR>
<BR>
A related area which should offer entry opportunities is Tatarstan's defence
industry, now being converted to civilian production but still an important
sector along with aviation, space and shipbuilding. During World War II,
Soviet military production was moved from Moscow to Tatarstan to put it
beyond German reach. This legacy means there is still a high concentration
of defence-related industries in the republic, including research and design
bureaux. <BR>
<BR>
Many former defence establishments boast cutting-edge technology, including
the Kazan helicopter factory which recently unveiled its new light helicopter
at the Le Bourget airshow in France. The company plans to manufacture the
first prototype early next year of the helicopter, known as the Ansat, which
will be fitted with Pratt &amp; Whitney engines from its St Petersburg joint
venture. <BR>
<BR>
Tatarstan's defence conversion has opened up new areas of the economy. Two
agreements between Moscow and Tatarstan (signed in June 1993 and March 1994)
regulate relations in this sector but the absence of a coherent conversion
programme means that most enterprises are responsible for ensuring their
own futures. All military industrial enterprises belong to the government,
which should simplify negotiations with potential investors. <BR>
<BR>
The transport sector also offers openings. Kazan is the largest port on
the Volga River and has been a trade and transport centre between the Middle
East, European Russia and Scandinavia for centuries. Under the EU's Tacis
programme, a major infrastructure project to modernise the Volga port is
getting under way. <BR>
<BR>
An international terminal will operate as a free economic zone, providing
warehouse facilities plus the consignment and distribution of commodities.
Meanwhile the Gorky Shipyard in Zelenodolsk, which recently celebrated its
centenary, plans to expand and modernise production by manufacturing a new
high-speed hydroplane vessel. <BR>
<BR>
A major problem throughout the former Soviet Union is poor communications.
Tatarstan has begun to address this problem with a modern telephone system.
Kazan opened the first digital hybrid wireless system in Russia in July
when two major digital long-distance telephone exchanges also became operational.
The $60 million project by Hughes Network Systems and Alcatel-SEL raised
the number of telephones in the republic to 210,000. To help pay for the
better services on offer Tatarstan's telecommunications ministry, in conjunction
with the Kazan City Telephone Network company, recently issued 16,000 telephone
loan bonds which were sold to private individuals and included an entitlement
to quick connection to the telephone network. <BR>
<BR>
Apart from modernising its communications infrastructure, Tatarstan is also
improving air services. In November, British Aerospace Consultancy Services
signed a preliminary agreement to manage the upgrading of Kazan airport.
A new 3.7km runway complying with international standards is expected to
be operation by March and more direct international services are planned
for next year. <BR>
<BR>
Tatarstan's agricultural sector plays an important economic role. The area
of land available for agricultural use totals 4.4 million hectares, of which
3.6 million are arable land. Like most other areas in Russia, the republic
needs substantial investment in its food processing industry, along with
wholesale and retail sectors of agriculture. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Guarantees from the government </B><BR>
<BR>
Foreign investors are likely to find Tatarstan welcoming. A special presidential
decree has created a profit tax holiday ranging from between three and five
years and a three-year property tax holiday. The investment laws are relatively
liberal and are more inviting on several points than those on offer in the
Russian Federation. The government is willing to provide investors with
guarantees of property rights: the necessary legal framework has already
been put in place and guarantees are provided against changes in the law
or the termination of investment activity. <BR>
<BR>
One way the local government intends to promote investment is through its
ban on operations by Moscow banks. While Tatarstan banks are still at the
beginning of the learning curve, their distance from the more corrupt and
violent atmosphere in Moscow may make them more attractive joint venture
partners for western bankers. <BR>
<BR>
This could provide a new element to an already growing trend among foreign
investors to look beyond the Moscow-St Petersburg area for opportunities.
The coming years should see a shift in emphasis from the two main cities
to Russia's regions. Tatarstan could then offer investors a toe-hold in
the federation. The decision of GM to go ahead with its Kamaz deal should
help encourage others to follow its lead and come to Tatarstan. As a GM
executive remarks: &quot;Tatarstan is one of the best places in Russia to
do business. It has the critical elements: political stability, trained
personnel and a leadership committed to providing incentives and guarantees
for foreign investment.&quot; 

