 <BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>

<H3><A NAME="kazan-pizza"></A>PIZZERIA VERDI </H3>
<B>The story of how Tatarstan's first pizzeria opened in Kazan has all of
the makings of an Italian opera</B> <BR>
<BR>
Walking down the otherwise sombre streets of Kazan, an elegant but cheerful
pizzeria strikes an incongruous note. Known as Giuseppe's, it is owned by
Giuseppe Sparta, an Italian from Sicily who came to Tatarstan three years
ago. <BR>
<BR>
The story of how Sparta ended up in Tatarstan has all the makings of an
Italian opera. He first entered eastern Europe 28 years ago. Together with
a friend he saw the opportunities in Slovenia and quickly opened his first
pizzeria in Ljubljana. Moving eastward, Sparta next went to Budapest where
he became, as he modestly puts it, &quot;the king of pizzas&quot; in Hungary's
capital. From that small beginning he has built up a franchise operation
for his pizzerias as well as a profitable business supplying restaurant
and food processing equipment throughout east-central Europe and the Russian
Federation. <BR>
<BR>
A state visit to Budapest in 1992 of the Tatarstan government convinced
him that a visit to Kazan was needed. &quot;I liked the youth in Kazan.
I thought they would be successful,&quot; says Sparta, offering one reason
for staying. His other reasons were less idealistic. Seeing that Moscow
and St Petersburg were over-crowded with foreign restaurants, Sparta saw
his future in the less known regions. Kazan, he believed, was as good a
place as any to start. <BR>
<BR>
As the only foreign-owned restaurant in the capital - a 50:50 joint venture
owned by Sparta and the Kazan city government - the restaurant owner's contact
with both the expatriate community and government officials is wide. Such
contacts help smooth business problems, as well as keeping Sparta informed
of local gossip. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Everyone comes to Giuseppe's,&quot; says Sparta. This also includes
locals and students who are encouraged to use the pizzeria as a meeting
place and somewhere they can buy ice creams, cakes or coffees. <BR>
<BR>
But Sparta's beginnings in Kazan were not trouble-free. &quot;You have difficulties
everywhere. Repairs here were particularly troublesome as there were no
tools to do them with and no shops to buy things from,&quot; he says. The
pizzeria's Italian-style furnishings had to be imported, as did most of
the kitchen equipment. Extensive rewiring of the building was needed to
meet the owner's safety standards. While he still imports equipment and
a few provisions, most of the food used is local and he says he has few
problems with delivery or quality. <BR>
<BR>
The restaurant's success has led Sparta to open a further two branches of
Giuseppe's pizzerias in Kazan. Although he says he is just beginning to
make a profit he intends to stay, not least because he is now married to
a local woman: another big advantage to Tatarstan, he says. <BR>
<BR>
His advice to businessmen looking to invest in Tatarstan is simple: &quot;Find
the correct partner. Be very cautious to chose the best one. You need to
connect with government bodies and work together if you want to build a
factory. To produce here you need to come with specialists and live here.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Sparta is particularly keen on Tatarstan's youth as a potential workforce
for foreign projects. &quot;Young people here are very educated and talented.
If you bring new technology they will understand it quickly.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
He recognises that problems still remain, not just in the country but in
the Tatarstan region as well. &quot;You need to live here. You need to give
an example of how to act. One problem here is that when people make money
they buy the most expensive car they can to show off their wealth, rather
than reinvesting it. They often don't understand that even if you are the
owner, you must work hard and get your hands dirty.&quot; <BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="mintimer-shaimiev"></A>INDEPENDANT REFORM</H3>
<B>His skill in handling change and avoiding ethnic conflict has made President
Mintimer Shaimiev popular <BR>
<BR>
</B><I>By Margie Lindsay </I><BR>
<BR>
To many Mintimer Shaimiev, the president of Tatarstan, is a dictator. To
his people, however, he is the man who has kept civil war at bay and helped
steer them through the economic transition. <BR>
<BR>
Shaimiev presents himself as a loving grandfather but beneath the charm
and smiles lies a hardened career politician. He has steered a difficult
and dangerous course over the years since his election. When the Soviet
Union broke up in 1992, Tatar nationalists cried out for full independence.
Shaimiev negotiated hard with Russia and won the status of autonomous republic
for his country. The result was that he won a considerable amount of sovereignty
while keeping the republic firmly rooted within the Russian Federation.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Skills as negotiator </B><BR>
<BR>
At the same time, Shaimiev recognised that most nationalist sentiment was
fuelled by economic frustrations and easing such problems became a priority.
Following this approach, termed the &quot;soft landing&quot;, the president
maintained social protection and kept price controls on certain basic foods
to avoid shortages and soaring prices. These measures, coupled with his
political skill in calming the Tatar nationalists, has gained him widespread
popularity. <BR>
<BR>
More recently he has turned his negotiation skills beyond the republic,
acting as a would-be mediator between the warring parties in Chechnya and
Russia. A year ago he was considered one of the most influential figures
in Russia, yet he appears to have no ambitions outside his republic. Indeed,
Shaimiev is coy about whether he intends to stand for another term in this
year's Tatarstan presidential elections. He says he will give his answer
when the time is right. <BR>
<BR>
In the meantime the president is concentrating on those domestic difficulties
that remain. &quot;The policies we aimed at have strengthened the statehood
of Tatarstan. We now must deepen our economic reform and shorten our transition
period to the market,&quot; he says. &quot;Our main task is to stop the
fall in living standards. We have to achieve economic stability and increase
the volume of industrial production. We saw real growth in the second half
of last year. Now we have that growth we must preserve it in 1996.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Foreign trade relations are a high priority for the president. &quot;We
must strengthen relations with Russia and other countries. Over the past
year we have established relations with many countries: our main task is
to develop trade with them and create conditions for foreign investors.
We now plan to implement some investment projects with US and German companies
in particular, but the main thing is to create a favourable [overall] climate
for foreign investors,&quot; says Shaimiev. <BR>
<BR>
Tatarstan has already enacted measures which make investment in the republic
more attractive than many other places in Russia. Shaimiev explains: &quot;All
the natural resources on our territory belong to us and during the privatisation
process the majority of government shares in these will be used as guarantees
for investors. We are preparing about 100 projects where we will seek foreign
participation. We are giving foreign investors more and better information
than they can find elsewhere in Russia.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>Clarifying rights on land ownership </B><BR>
<BR>
He outlines the opportunities which the republic already offers: &quot;We
have made the rights on land ownership clear - foreign investors can buy
and sell land. We have published and adopted laws on investment which give
tax holidays. Through privatisation shares in some attractive industries,
like petrochemicals, will be offered.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Nevertheless, the president thinks the republic could do more to win the
much-needed capital, technology and know-how essential if Tatarstan wants
to build up its industrial base and help convert a largely defence-oriented
industry to civilian production. &quot;How do we improve the climate for
foreign investors? Well, for a start we can offer state guarantees for investors.
We have finished setting up a large investment company with the help of
foreign partners and for the first time we are beginning to organise insurance
policies for large enterprises. Of course our economic situation will also
help attract new investment.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
What the president would like investors to see as Tatarstan's trump card
is its political stability. Within a turbulent Russia, Tatarstan stands
out as the most politically and economically stable republic. &quot;The
first reason foreign investors should look here is because of our stability.
We have great national resources, especially oil, as well as other developed
industries such as chemicals, machine-building and those with high-technology
potential.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Although some people in Tatarstan still hanker after full independence,
Shaimiev is realistic about the future of his country. There are also worries
that the outcome of recent Russian parliamentary elections, in which the
once ruling communists became the single biggest party, and forthcoming
presidential elections may have a negative impact on Tatarstan. <BR>
<BR>
Nonetheless, President Shaimiev sounds confident. &quot;We want to help
the population to chose correctly, to make the right political priorities.
In our last elections the communists did not win a majority of the votes
and this trend will continue,&quot; he said, referring to a local parliamentary
poll. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Of course the communists use difficulties in the economy, particularly
with the elderly, to gain support. But the majority of the population is
moderate,&quot; he adds, citing broad support in Tatarstan for Our Home
is Russia, the party of Victor Chernomyrdin, Russia's prime minister at
the time of going to press. &quot;It seems natural for us to continue our
course of political reform. Our voters need to support us and I hope they
will,&quot; he concludes.*<BR><BR> <HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="privatisation"></A>FROM STABLE TO STABLE </H3>
<B>The former state-owned company Melita is learning the sometimes harsh
lessons of the free market </B><BR>
<BR>
&quot;In Russia fur clothing is not about prestige. We need it for our climate
- for military and civilian use,&quot; says Alexei Pakhomov, president of
Melita, one of Kazan's leading companies specialising in the processing
of skins. It handles nearly 5 million raw skins a year and manufactures
ready-made garments from different kinds of fur. <BR>
<BR>
The company - now privately owned by employees and management - is typical
of Kazan's former state industries. Since privatisation was completed in
1992, Melita has been free from state interference. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Without privatisation we would still be tied to the state,&quot; explains
Pakhomov. &quot;We have maintained our contacts and work closely with our
suppliers. Today our company processes one-third of Russia's fur production.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Leading a company in Russia is not easy, even in a republic as stable as
Tatarstan, confesses Melita's head. &quot;The situation changes constantly.
It is particularly difficult to finance expansion.&quot; Predictably enough,
the company has had to fend off protests from animal rights protesters.
&quot;We have had some disturbances, some difficulties in selling, but over
the last three years we have increased our sales volume,&quot; says Pakhomov.
<BR>
<BR>
Trusting more in his company's ability to finance expansion than in the
banks which charge high interest rates, Pakhomov has been investing in new
technology to help improve his firm's performance. &quot;We use chemistry
and modern technology from leading German, Swiss and Italian firms such
as Henkel, BASF, Stockhausen and Sandoz. Our professional skill is based
on more than 5,000 specialists working in 10 factories belonging to our
company. We try to pay particular attention to every detail and keep quality
high,&quot; he says. <BR>
<BR>
Melita co-operates closely with Russian buyers as well as those from Germany,
Switzerland, Italy, Spain and the US. Although none of Melita's furs are
actually exported, many of the company's products are bought in duty-free
shops in Russia. &quot;Everyone is eager to buy furs in Russia. People come
from all over the world to buy them. Our main task now is to make higher
quality furs. If you have good quality raw materials, then you can make
good quality clothing,&quot; says Pakhomov. <BR>
<BR>
He acknowledges that the right employee attitudes are essential to achieving
this. &quot;Through privatisation, people became more concerned with the
firm's future. We understand that high quality is what sells, so we have
implemented programmes to introduce more know-how and new equipment,&quot;
he says. <BR>
<BR>
Melita has reorganised production and begun to specialise. &quot;We trained
people abroad, in Italy for example, because we knew our technology was
bad and we wanted to improve it. We fired staff we no longer needed and
enlarged production. We have created a commercial and marketing section
which studies the markets and, unlike before, we take design into account,&quot;
concludes Pakhomov. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We are looking for investors from abroad. We have even looked at projects
with the EBRD. We need around $10 million, but we do not want participation
in our equity,&quot; says Pakhomov, speaking for many of Tatarstan's managers.
&quot;The most important thing for us is money.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Pakhomov sees several reasons why foreign investors should chose Tatarstan.
&quot;Our economy is more stable here than elsewhere in Russia. We are isolated
from Russia in many ways. Investors should look at Tatarstan because of
its stable enterprises and because the level of our profits is high.&quot;<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

