<td valign=top align=left> 
<H2>TYUMEN </H2 >
<H4>This vast region in western Siberia is blessed with equally vast oil
and gas reserves but must still resolve how to share the spoils, both within
its own territory and with the central government in Moscow. Meanwhile,
steps are being taken to make it easier for foreigners to enter the Russian
energy sector and give it the vital injection it needs of money and technology
<BR>
<A HREF="#overview"><BR>
OVERVIEW  <BR>
<BR>
</A><A HREF="#investor-stories">INVESTOR STORIES</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#governor-roketsky">GOVERNOR ROKETSKY </A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#food-industry">FOOD INDUSTRY</A>  <BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#oil-refining">OIL REFINING</A>  </H4>
<HR>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="overview"></A>SQUARING AN ARCTIC CIRCLE </H3>
<B>Tyumen's energy riches have brought economic success but also regional
disputes about division of the spoils</B> <BR>
<BR>
Tyumen, which stretches from the Arctic Circle in the north to the border
of Kazakhstan in the south, is one of Russia's most prosperous regions.
Average wages are two to three times higher than elsewhere. Shops are well
supplied and people on the streets of its capital, also called Tyumen, sport
expensive fur coats during the long, cold winter. The Siberian city has
always been a prosperous trading centre, as well as a place of internal
exile for troublesome Russians. <BR>
<BR>
But Tyumen is not as affluent as it would like to be. The region has substantial
oil and gas reserves and provides over half of federal budget revenues from
oil and gas. Yet very little money finds its way from Moscow back to the
area. Although its resources give Tyumen economic power, it lacks the political
muscle to argue for the concessions that other resource-rich regions such
as Tatarstan and Baskhortostan have negotiated for themselves. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Under the Kremlin's thumb </B><BR>
<BR>
This is because Moscow has adopted a divide-and-rule policy to keep the
potentially rebellious Tyumen region firmly under its thumb. The central
Russian government has created two autonomous national homelands or <I>okrugs</I>,
ostensibly to protect national minorities living locally although they make
up only a small part of the population. Yamal-Nenets comprises half the
land area of the region and holds most of Russia's gasfields but has a population
of only 500,000. Khanti-Mansi covers a third of land area and has a population
of 1.3 million but holds almost all of Tyumen's oil reserves. <BR>
<BR>
In the south is the region's capital and the smallest of the three districts,
accounting for only one-sixth of the region's land area but with a relatively
large population of 1.3 million. It is a relatively poor area of industry
and agriculture, with little of the oil and gas riches found in the two
northern districts.<I> </I>The capital is the centre of the region's political,
transport and communications structure but its ability to administer the
region and control the two autonomous homelands is constantly challenged.
More often than not its wishes are ignored by the <I>okrugs,</I> which are
loath to allow Tyumen's government to get its hands on what they see as
their wealth. While the Tyumen region as a whole is not agitating for independence,
Moscow appears happy to let the infighting continue. <BR>
<BR>
It is surprising that Tyumen is not better served by the federation, given
that the present minister of fuel was previously governor of the region
and that Russia's prime minister Viktor Chernomyrdin hails from Tyumen.
But politics in Russia are never simple. <BR>
<BR>
Ownership of natural resources is a sore subject. There is no transparency
in laws, the rules change constantly and there are serious contradictions
between regional and federal institutions. Currency tax regulations make
it difficult for the oil companies to make money at all. Tyumen's regional
authorities, led by its governor Leonid Roketsky, have tried to increase
taxes. But meanwhile the two autonomous national regions have made rival
claims, usually from the only real revenue source - oil and gas sales. Such
endless squabbles over tax have deterred foreign investors and as a resull
most of Russia's major oil companies are close to bankruptcy. <BR>
<BR>
One foreign investor which has ventured into the region, Total of France,
has pledged to put $1 billion into exploration of the Kharyaga oilfield
in Nenets district. British Gas has also signed a protocol with Gazprom,
Russia's gas company, to explore business opportunities. But both projects
are on hold, waiting for clarity on the tax situation and progress on a
federal oil and gas production-sharing law awaiting presidential approval,
which would allow foreigners to exploit and sell Russian ener for the first
time. <BR>
<BR>
There is unlikely to be progress on either, however, while Russia is in
the throes of political change ahead of a presidential ballot in the middle
of this year and and as the communist party resumes prime position in the
political arena. That means Tyumen and western investors will have to wait.
<BR>
<BR>
Nevertheless, Tyumen's wealth is worth fighting over. It still produces
a lot of oil, even though output has declined sharply from a peak in 1987.
One of the largest producers is Nizhnevartovskneftegaz, now part of the
newly formed Tyumen Oil Company. It has had to scale down its operations
and lay off staff in order to reduce an Rb750 billion (US$161 million) debt
to the federal budget. Drilling operations have been cut, contracts stopped
and the working week reduced to three days. Last year, in October and November
alone energy production there dropped by 17%, a fall which will cost the
federal budget an estimated Rb60 billion. <BR>
<BR>
<B>A declining output of oil </B><BR>
<BR>
The fall-off in oil production is due to a combination of factors. As prices
were deregulated throughout Russia, oil continued to be priced by the state
but the costs of recovery have grown. The oil industry is owed over Rb500
billion by former Soviet republics which continue to receive oil but are
unable to pay for it. State quotas are still set and deprive enterprises
of essential supplies of oil at free prices. There are considerable tax
disincentives to both the export of oil and sales internally at free prices.
<BR>
<BR>
Tyumen badly needs foreign investment in its oil and gas production. A Russian-American
Oil and Gas Technology Centre has been set up in Tyumen by the US government,
the regional authorities and the Russian oil and gas ministry. It is helping
to bring Russian and western companies together to discuss the problems
faced by the region's oil and gasfields. Environmental damage is high on
the list. &quot;When drilling in Europe we are obliged to build a pit and
put down cement, plastic or whatever to contain spills. If there is any
blow-out of accident, the leakage is contained. In western Siberia, you
put the rig down and that's it,&quot; says one western oilman in Tyumen.
But that is changing, as Tyumen's younger generation becomes more ecologically
aware. The World Bank and Russia have agreed a $500 million loan for the
rehabilitation of the oil industry in western Siberia. A credit of $174
million has also been agreed with European Bank for Reconstruction and Development
to restore 300 idle oil wells belonging to Purneftgas. <BR>
<BR>
In the gas sector, there are similar problems. At the moment, 93% of Russia's
gas comes from Tyumen, mainly from Yamal-Nenets and from the Urengoi, Medvezh
and Yamburg gasfields. Unlike oil, gas production has remained relatively
stable but it is now in decline. The state gas company Gazprom can only
realistically maintain and increase production by developing new fields,
also dependent upon the production-sharing law being passed. <BR>
<BR>
There are three major offshore gas projects, which are difficult to exploit.
One of these is the Yamal project on the Arctic coast, run by Gasprom, which
is due to start production in 1997 providing it can buy the high-technology
equipment required. New export pipelines need to be built too, offering
substantial opportunities for foreign businesses as do the World Bank's
new gas processing plants in Tyumen. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The Finnish connection </B><BR>
<BR>
Once oil and gas production takes off the Finnish construction company YIT
is hoping to go ahead with its long-awaited plans to work in the Tyumen
region. &quot;We started here under the Tsar, then we worked with the Soviets
and now we work again with the Russians. In the long run I can see a lot
of potential in this region. That's why our company is here. We didn't come
for quick money,&quot; says Ilkka Sinkkonen, head of YIT in Tyumen. The
Finnish company's experience in western Siberia is extensive. It has been
involved in the Yamburg Arctic gasfield, building a town for 9,000 people
including residential and service buildings, as well as earthworks for the
Ardalin oilfield development in the Timan Pechora area. <BR>
<BR>
Unusually for a non-Russian construction company, YIT uses local labour.
&quot;We use Russians, unlike the Turks or Yugoslavs who bring their workers
in. Sometimes even the Russians don't understand this. But we can assure
them it is possible to use Russian workers and have a good result. It is
only a question of management. Russians really are willing to learn and
want to do quality work. We find them very good,&quot; says Sinkkonen. <BR>
<BR>
The Tyumen regional government is also hoping to attract foreign investors
to boost timber production and processing. The industry is beset by a high
level of wastage, environmental damage and inefficiency. Tyumen has considerable
forests, covering about two thirds of its territory. Exploitable reserves
are put at 330,00sq km and contain 2.6 billion cubic metres of timber, 54%
of which are softwoods. Half of the production is exported in log form and
the rest is processed locally. But in the first quarter of this year the
output of commercial timber fell 27% compared with the same period in 1994.
<BR>
<BR>
Nearly all the region's agricultural production is based in the south, below
Tobolsk. Tyumen provides for half its own food needs but again, large-scale
pollution is a problem, particularly in the fishing industry. The privatisation
of farming itself is confused and overly bureaucratic. Food processing badly
needs modernisation as well as better management. There is also a range
of mechanical engineering and electrical equipment enterprises, mainly located
around Tyumen city. Most are also in need of modernisation. <BR>
<BR>
Despite the wealth of natural resources available, little processing is
done in the region. The challenge to the government is to provide a refinery
and petrochemical base to make the most of its resources. The Tobolsk Petrochemical
Plant at present produces a range of consumer goods such as bleacher Belizna,
medical preparations, footwear, PVCs and other products and has ambitious
plans for expansion. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Leave something for tomorrow </B><BR>
<BR>
Tobolsk president Vladimir Judin says the company has entered into over
10 joint ventures with western partners. Output is to go only to the Russian
market so, Judin adds with a smile, western producers can rest easy that
Tobolsk will be no competition. &quot;We only want to develop the processing
of crude oil and allow us to produce more wealth and fill in the local market.
Our doors remain open to all [foreign investment] offers,&quot; he adds.
<BR>
<BR>
However, Judin would like to see more government understanding for businessmen:
&quot;The first thing the Russian government should understand is that if
it squeezes businesses, companies will not make profits. It should think
how to provide as much incentive as possible to foreign investors so the
results will be bigger revenue flows later. Today's wish to eat everything
leaves nothing for tomorrow.&quot;<BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="investor-stories"></A>A FROSTY WELCOME </H3>
<B>The region's attempts to attract investment have been limited and have
met only mixed success <BR>
</B><BR>
&quot;Realistically Russia and Tyumen offer foreign businesses the biggest
opportunities in the world - maybe even greater than China. In the long
run firms with the cash flow to be able to justify a long-term presence
will ultimately succeed, but this is not a market for small companies coming
for the short term, especially if they are looking to invest,&quot; says
Joe Barraclough, a representative of the Alberta government in Canada and
resident in Tyumen for three years. <BR>
<BR>
He sees great potential in the area and stresses the many changes seen over
the past three years. But he says that while western businessmen have influenced
Russia, only the country itself can make its own choices. &quot;Russia is
deciding whether it continues the reform process and joins the international
community or if it wants isolation. My feeling is that Russians want to
live well. In the last five years Russian people have travelled to western
Europe, north America. They know what's out there. They don't want to go
back.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
For the time being, oil and gas dominate the investment scene. However,
future success will partly depend on Tyumen's ability to attract foreign
interest in other industries earmarked for development. <BR>
<BR>
Western investors coming to Tyumen region face several challenges, least
of all the weather. &quot;Be patient. It's not so easy here. Usually time
is needed to organise good business relations and that takes at least two
years. It means you can't just visit once a year - that's not enough. You
need to find a local organisation or technician and establish links with
an enterprise and follow through,&quot; advises Tom Haselton, executive
director of the Russian-American Oil and Gas Technology Centre in Tyumen.
The centre is helping to bring Russian and western companies together and
promote the sale of Russian technologies. <BR>
<BR>
Haselton sees oil and gas development as the economic engine for the region's
future. &quot;I've noticed changes, but they are very slow. The main problem
is oil and gas companies face is money. They have the experience, but they
don't have the equipment. They can sell only a small percentage of their
output themselves and the revenues they get are not enough. The government's
taxation is high and its pricing policy is not realistic.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Indeed, little has so far been done to attract investment in the oil and
gas sectors. In addition to the problems of an uncertain legal and tax environment,
some see the attitudes of local companies as a problem. &quot;They think
they don't need any help, but they do,&quot; says one western businessman
referring to Russia's oil companies. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;In their minds they believe the only problem is money and they think
they can do everything to stop the arrival of western companies in Siberia.
But the western companies have arrived and they are being asked for money.
But as long as the [oil and gas] production-sharing law is not passed, nothing
can happen,&quot; he concludes. <BR>
<BR>
Many of the oil and gasfields in Tyumen are old and need specific techniques
which are both sophisticated and costly. The industry faces other problems,
like pipeline corrosion caused by excessive water content in the oil going
through the lines. <BR>
<BR>
Most would-be investors are hopeful that big money will come into the region
to help develop Tyumen's substantial reserves. When that happens, service
industries as well as manufacturing should begin to develop in the region.
<BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="governor-roketsky"></A>OIL AND TROUBLE WATERS</H3>
<B>The governor must walk a tightrope, balancing the often conflicting demands
of his own region with Moscow <BR>
<BR>
</B><I>by Margie Lindsay </I><BR>
<BR>
Leonid Roketsky, the governor of Tyumen region, has a lot to contend with.
Politically, he has to balance power between his two internal autonomous
regions, as well as between the republic and the federal government in Moscow.
On the economic side he needs to steer a middle path through the transformation
process without causing too severe a decline in living standards. <BR>
<BR>
Everyone is eager to get their hands on Tyumen's oil and gas revenues. But
until power relations become clearer, Tyumen like many other Russian republics
faces an uncertain future. Meanwhile Roketsky walks a tightrope. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The laws we have today are not enough. We are drafting, changing and
developing the particulars of power-sharing. The local system is also under
reform. When thisis carried out, it will influence relations between the
region and the federal government and local relations, too,&quot; he says
in an interview. Democratic progress, however, is slow: &quot;We have some
of the structures, but we need to implement them.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Despite the questionmark over relations with the federal authorities, Roketsky
is sure of Tyumen's place within the federation. &quot;I will obey the Russian
constitution and make sure the population obeys federal laws. At the same
time I am satisfied that we can solve our problems by ourselves without
interference from federal bodies.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>One step forward, two steps back </B><BR>
<BR>
A major problem is distribution of taxes, admits Roketsky. &quot;Whenever
we go one step forward, another problem arises. Although the Tyumen region
is in the Russian federation and by law all regions and republics are equal,
some are more equal than others. This is an internal power struggle that
we must sort out ourselves.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The region's two autonomous districts in the north, Yamal-Nenets and Khanti-Mansi,
believe they deserve to keep the oil and gas found in their territory which
already makes them very rich. &quot;We're witnessing the same processes
in the Tyumen region as we see in Russia. The same issues confront us: fiscal
problems and federalism,&quot; Roketsky explains. Federalism can only go
so far, he insists. &quot;Tyumen is the capital of the region and ultimately
this is where the power is focused.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
At the same time he is aware that Tyumen's economic dependence on oil and
gas is dangerous and wants to use these resources to restructure the region's
industrial base. Pointing to a thick three-volume report, Roketsky describes
his plans to change the industrial profile of Tyumen region over the next
several years. &quot;Our main goal is to expand oil and gas processing first.
We want to develop the further use of petrochemicals for the production
of plastics, polymers for cars and consumer goods. For this we have a good
industrial base.&quot; He points in particular to a development at Tobolst,
where a refinery complex and petrochemical facilities are being constructed
and expanded. The project has seen considerable success in attracting investment
from the west. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Expanding into cellulose </B><BR>
<BR>
There are also plans to expand in other major industrial areas. &quot;Our
second major goal is to produce cellulose. We also are looking at developing
other industries, such as manufacturing of oil and gas equipment and machines,
aircraft engines, car batteries and medical instruments as well as pharmaceuticals.
In light industry we are developing woollen and ready-made clothes production.
As for food processing, we need new technology and investments.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
He says with pride that the region is already showing some signs of industrial
improvement. In the first 10 months of 1995 there was an 18% increase in
overall industrial output compared with the same 1994 period. This was achieved
even with a 3% drop in oil and gas production. <BR>
<BR>
Roketsky naturally places importance in the oil sector but is also keen
to diversify. &quot;Oil and gas will definately dominate our industry over
the next five years, but our desire is to stabilise that sector. Over the
next 10 years we expect oil output to be around 200 million tonnes a year
with gas production at around 550 billion cubic metres. At the same time
overall industrial production is likely to increase between 1.5% and 2%
a year over the next five years.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The governor wants to continue reforms in the agricultural sector as well
in the local administration. Roads and other aspects of infrastructure in
the region need improvement, as do health care and medical treatment. Telecommunications
is another area where a substantial amount of money will be spent over the
next five years. <BR>
<BR>
Foreign investors are expected to play a crucial role in helping the region
develop in the future: &quot;Considering the wealth in our region in natural
resources, we will be able to attract foreign investment. We want foreign
companies to come in to work with us, not just to sell us things. I think
we need to consider a better investment strategy for the region. We are
close to several markets outside Russia and investors could sell to those
areas.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>Concerns and hesitation </B><BR>
<BR>
But Roketsky has some sympathy for the reluctance of investors to come <BR>
forward, particularly after the unsettling outcome of recent parliamentary
elections and before the presidential ballot due in June: &quot;I understand
that the political stability of Russia is a concern for foreign investors.
But together we can build hotels, reconstruct airports and hospitals. By
their presence here foreign investors will ensure that the region's small
and medium-sized businesses develop.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
He stresses that he does not believe changes at the federal level will make
a difference to the region. &quot;I think any power will smell the oil and
the Tyumen region will always attract the attention of politicians, he concludes.
&quot;At the same time there is no way back. It is my opinion that the formation
of policy is being made by the president and the federal government whatever
parliament is elected, power will be balanced by the president. I rely on
the wisdom of my countrymen to elect the right people.&quot;<BR><BR><HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4></H4>
<H3><A NAME="food-industry"></A>MUSTARD TO CHOCOLATE </H3>
<B>One food processing firm has progressed from poor Soviet-style standards
to market success </B><BR>
<BR>
Vasiliy Kiselyov, general director of Malvinka food processing company,
is one of a new breed of Russian managers and heads one of the more progressive
plants in Tyumen. <BR>
<BR>
The plant used to produce low-quality alcoholic drinks under the epitome
of Soviet-style management: poor-quality products, sloppy working practices
and unsafe premises. <BR>
<BR>
Now staff at Malvinka, which produces a range of products from mustard to
chocolates, work in clean, well-kept premises. Courtyards that were previously
knee-deep in mud have been tarmacked. New wine-making facilities are spotless
and the newest addition to the plant, a mini-bakery, is a model of efficiency.
<BR>
<BR>
Kiselyov is understandably proud of his company, whose name spells out the
various products it makes. Before a joint employee and management buyout
of the plant three years ago, Malvinka's reputation was at rock bottom.
But under Kiselyov's leadership the product range has been broadened and
the staff increased from about 78 workers three years ago to 400. <BR>
<BR>
How did the change happen? &quot;Such growth is mainly due to the development
of new production lines and capacity. Over the three years we've introduced
mayonnaise and mustard, for example. We've started research and development
and organised a marketing department. Production over the last three years
has expanded,&quot; he explains. <BR>
<BR>
Kiselyov has spent his entire working life connected with the food processing
industry. &quot;I am personally devoted to food production industry. I graduated
from the food technology institute in central Russia and the greater part
of my life I have worked in the north of the Tyumen region,&quot; he explains.
<BR>
<BR>
Kiselyov has spent around $7 million introducing new technology, all of
which came from outside Russia, to improve efficiency and expand the product
range. Next he plans to buy equipment for soft drink manufacturing worth
around $2 million and install a second production line for cooking oil at
a cost of $1.8 million. A total of $10 million is planned to be invested
over the next three years. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;In future we plan to develop our capacity and introduce new products.
Two years from now I expect around 1,500 people to be employed here. We
plan to build a flour mill, to produce food oil and margarine from rapeseed
grown by local farmers. We want to add shampoo and soaps to our line,&quot;
he enthuses. <BR>
<BR>
Kiselyov is proud, too, that the company uses natural ingredients as far
as possible in production. For example, local strawberries, blackcurrants
and cloudberries are all used to produce a range of soft and alcoholic drinks.
<BR>
<BR>
So far all the expansion has been financed from working capital and profits:
bank loans, explains the company's general director, are too expensive.
Although he prefers to use his own resources, Kiselyov does not rule out
the possibility of linking with a foreign partner. &quot;We are positive
about foreign investors. We need a western company to help us, particularly
in the production of sweets, chocolates and confectionery. We cover the
needs of the Tyumen region for many products but we still have potential.
Yes, we are looking for a partner, but it is a <BR>
two-way process.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Going private was the best thing that could have happened to Malvinka, says
Kiselyov. &quot;As soon as the company became private we became free of
limitations. Now we're absolutely free to determine our production policies.
We do what we think is best for our company.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%> 
<H3><A NAME="oil-refining"></A>REFINING FOR RUSSIA </H3>
<B>Despite large debts and ageing equipment, the Tyumen Oil Company is willing
to find partners and expand<BR>
<BR>
</B><I>by Margie Lindsay </I><BR>
<BR>
Russia is restructuring its oil sector to create vertically integrated companies
based on the western model. Tyumen holds the majority of Russia's oil and
gas reserves yet only one of the new-style companies is based there: the
Tyumen Oil Company (TOC), which was set up in August 1995. The company has
an output of just over 20 million tonnes, a quarter of Russia's total production.
<BR>
<BR>
Basically, TOC is a holding company made up of firms allocated to it by
the government. The haste of its creation and a widely diverse portfolio
of daughter companies is proving a challenge for the new management, which
has yet to find an effective organisational structure for the new entity.
Indeed, many of its subsidiaries still act independently, ignoring central
control. <BR>
<BR>
Indeed, central control itself is still in flux. The company is in state
hands except for around 15% of its shares, which are held by employees and
management. The state's shares are held by various federal and regional
authorities but are gradually being sold at privatisation auctions. TOC
says some of the remaining state shares should be passed to the company,
but it is not clear when or how many. <BR>
<BR>
The holding company is made up of two oil production companies, one oil
refinery (Ryazan around 300km outside Moscow), and five distribution companies.
In addition TOC has a construction and geological company. <BR>
<BR>
One problems is that the company's oil refinery is over 2,000km away from
its oilfields. TOC would like to sell the Ryazan refinery and co-operate
either with a refinery closer to home or build its own facilities in Tyumen.
The capacity of the Ryazan refinery is 18 million tonnes a year but volume
in the first six months of 1995 totalled only 8.6 million tonnes. According
to a spokesman for the company, TOC would have preferred to work with Omsk
refinery, but that venture was given to another company in the reorganisation.
Many areas of TOC need modernisation. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The most important question we need to address is the reconstruction
of our largest oilfield, Samurtalosk,&quot; says a company spokesman. Over
the last 30 years production has declined and the old Soviet methods of
producing as much oil as possible with little regard to field conditions
or to the future means that recovery of secondary and tertiary oil reserves
is difficult. Western technology and know-how is needed to bring the field
back to full production. <BR>
<BR>
Added to this problem is heavy debt, caused partly by continued state control
of oil prices and partly by non-payment of debts from clients. The debt
run up by one production company, Nizhnevartovskneftegaz, is estimated at
well over Rb80.9 billion. Debts at TOC's other oil producing company, Tyumenneftegaz,
total over Rb893 billion. Along with other Russian oil companies in a similar
state, the firm is hoping to be rescued by the federal government. Indeed,
during a mid-summer visit the Russian prime minister Victor Chernomyrdin
promised some help, particularly with the repair of old wells. <BR>
<BR>
The TOC wants to expand its existing activities. Most of the region's petrol
stations and agricultural groups receive their products from TOC's distribution
companies. This could turn into an even more lucrative business as agricultural
and industrial production expand. <BR>
<BR>
The company is already developing 16 oilfields and has licences for 12 more.
But it says development of fields will be difficult because of complex geological
structures and extreme weather. <BR>
<BR>
Like other oil companies in Russia, TOC is waiting for an important oil-production
sharing law to pass parliament. Once adopted, TOC will be able to sign deals
for development of at least two new fields. &quot;But without a strong western
partner, we are not able to develop any new fields,&quot; admits a spokesman.<BR>
<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
