<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>
<H3>FROM THE EDITOR</H3> 
<H2>Search for inner balance</H2>
<H4>
Internal Clashes with the &quot;enemy within&quot;, rather than the clash
of different cultures, have clouded optimism
</H4>
As readers think of Davos and the 1996 Annual Meeting of the World Economic
Forum, taking place at the beginning of February, they may see a common
thread running through the agenda: ways of coping with our era's rapid pace
of change. Globalisation, the theme of this year's meeting, has become so
accepted as a description of the interconnected way we live, along with
the market as a basic economic institution, that attention is already shifting
to the problems that lurk under the surface of this consensus. <BR>
<BR>
In this discussion, we usually hear about the potential for conflict between
different cultures, even as their practical lives become more linked through
trade and contact. But looking at some of the most startling recent events,
such as the killing of Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin late last year,
it seems to be internal clashes rather than a clash of civilisations which
are clouding optimism most. <BR>
After Rabin's murder by a Jewish fundamentalist, as in the earlier Oklahoma
bombing by US anti-federal extremists, the reality of an attack by the so-called
enemy within was far more shocking than any attack by a foreign terrorist
would have been. And in both cases the perpetrators were accused of taking
succour from more moderate groups at the heart of the polity.<BR>
<BR>
Such violent action is usually associated with political landscapes where
there is no tradition of democracy to leaven people's desire for recognition.
But these two attacks were proof of a crisis of identity and consent in
two of the world's most debate-prone societies. In both cases they were
facing the challenges of change: in the case of Israel it was that of peace
with an old enemy and in America, the difficulties of leadership in a post-Cold
War world. Every change calls for a new equilibrium: the problem lies in
getting the balance right. <BR>
<BR>
As international trade unionist Bill Jordan writes in this issue, people
risk blinding themselves with their own rhetoric about the joys of a global
society which creates losers as well as winners. World Link's blow-by-blow
account of a Volkswagen productivity workshop, a crucial part of its bid
to stay competitive in world markets, shows how fear of unemployment can
weaken enthusiasm for improvement, even in Germany where job protection
is stronger than in most countries. <BR>
<BR>
The issue posed by these writers, and by several other experts in this Davos
edition, is that while markets are important they do not have all the answers.
As Nick Cater's work on disaster relief shows, some things cannot be run
on strict market lines without losing their very purpose. Karel van Wolferen
explains how in one very successful society, Japan, the market is heavily
overshadowed by other institutions born from a war economy which defy modern
free-market orthodoxy. Chile and other reforming, democratising societies
discussed in these pages acknowlege they are now focusing more on the social
dimension and the need to maintain popular support for change; the Czechs,
despite their tough market rhetoric, always did so and this helps explain
their success.<BR>
<BR>
In a special interview the US-based analyst Francis Fukuyama develops further
his argument that the big institutions need to be supplemented with something
more intangible, and that you cannot create a liveable society based on
the self-interested interactions of individuals alone. The state is not
the answer either but if you cut it back, he warns, there is no guarantee
that civil society will fill the vacuum. <BR>
The debate has definitively moved out of the old left-right political divide,
as a new generation understands the inadequacies of old categories and moves
towards a middle ground which balances rights and duties, individual and
civic values. The search is now on, in Davos and elsewhere, for a new equilibrium.
<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
