<td>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<h2>
January/February 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>
<H3>COMMENT</H3>
<H2>The universal challenge </H2> 
<H4>The rise and relative fall of American economic dominance offers a warning
lesson to the East </H4>

<I>By Harry Harding, dean of the Elliott School of International Affairs,
George Washington University </I><BR>
<BR>
I re-read a rather well-known book recently, written by someone from a society
that has customarily regarded itself as the most advanced on earth, both
morally and materially. But as that journalist looked across a great ocean
to the west, he saw another society on the rise which challenged the superiority
of his own. <BR>
<BR>
The superficial dimensions of that challenge were economic: more rapid rates
of growth, export surges, a burst of outward foreign investment and pre-eminence
in what the writer regarded as the strategic industries of the future. Looking
beneath the surface, however, the author identified the underlying values
and institutions that were producing such economic success. These included:
<BR>
<BR>
*Superior management, which enabled the challenger's industrial and commercial
enterprises to adapt successfully in a global economy. <BR>
<BR>
*A greater commitment to education, research, and development, as reflected
in higher levels of investment in these activities. <BR>
<BR>
*The promotion of an effective and creative partnership among government,
private business, and universities. <BR>
<BR>
*Systematic and organised government sponsorship of industries in the strategic
sectors of the economy. <BR>
<BR>
*A commitment to social equality, which in the long term contributed to
higher rates of economic growth. <BR>
<BR>
The author concluded that this challenge from across the ocean posed a stark
choice to his society between insulation and competition. He argued vigorously
for competition, proposing the creation of a broad political consensus to
learn from the challenger and a concerted effort at social and economic
revitalisation in an attempt to catch up. <BR>
<BR>
This argument should sound familiar. It would not be a bad summary of an
influential book, <I>Looking at the Sun</I>, written by prominent American
journalist James Fallows about the advance of the east Asian economies over
the last several decades and their competitive challenge to the us. But
the book I have just summarised is not <I>Looking at the Sun</I>, nor is
the author an American. <BR>
<BR>
The rising economy being described is not Japan, nor wider east Asia. The
book I am referring to was written in 1967 by a Frenchman, Jean-Jacques
Servan-Schreiber. The society that traditionally considered itself superior
was Europe, the ocean separating the new and old powers was the Atlantic
and the rising power was the US. The title of the book was <I>Le D&eacute;fi
Am&eacute;ricain</I>, or <I>The American Challenge</I>. <BR>
<BR>
I pay tribute to Servan-Schreiber in part because his book parallels and
reinforces my own thesis. His description of what made the US so competitive
reinforces my judgement that such values and institutions are not specifically
Asian, as argued by many analysts, but are universal concepts strongly correlated
with economic success wherever they are applied. And by posing the choice
between insulation and competition, he echoes my argument that the US now
faces its own choice between more creative or more costly responses to the
latest challenge from Asia. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The lesson of America </B><BR>
<BR>
Any re-reading of Servan-Schreiber suggests a somewhat paradoxical conclusion.
Today, almost 30 years after this book was published, the US has lost many
of the competitive advantages that it once enjoyed. <BR>
<BR>
In retrospect, the American challenge of the '60s did not merely act as
a spur to European competitiveness. It was also a challenge for the US to
remain competitive. The tragedy of contemporary American history is that
we responded to that challenge too slowly and have done so with only limited
effectiveness. In short, we became the victims of our own success. <BR>
<BR>
It follows that the success of east Asia poses a major challenge to the
region itself: to continue to adjust and adapt lest it become the victim
of its own economic miracle. Economically, Asia faces the challenge of liberalising
both its consumer and capital markets so it can move beyond the strategies
of protected industry and state guidance that have served so well until
now. <BR>
<BR>
The need for liberalisation stems from several considerations. First, as
I have already noted, the other two major economic regions, Europe and the
US, will increasingly insist on reciprocal trading arrangements and will
demand greater access to Asian markets in return for continued access to
their own. Second, as east Asia continues to grow, it will increasingly
serve as its own economic engine. No longer will the region's economies
look to the US as the market that supports their export-oriented strategies.
Instead, they will look to each other and that will require further enhancement
of opportunities for trade and investment within the region. <BR>
<BR>
Third, to attract foreign investment whether from outside the region or
from within it, requires products manufactured or assembled in one country
to have freer access to neighbouring markets. And most fundamentally, given
the faster pace of technological change, economies remain competitive only
if capital has the freedom to move and exploit exciting new opportunities.
<BR>
<BR>
To be sure economies like Hong Kong have always been open. Others, like
Taiwan, South Korea and China, are moving in that direction. The creation
of the Asean Free Trade Area and the promulgation of the Bogor Declaration
by APEC represent a commitment to regional trade and investment liberalisation
but progress has often been slow. The enormous economic difficulties faced
by Japan illustrate the dangers when adjustment is tardy or even deliberately
postponed. <BR>
<BR>
Strategically, the challenge to Asia is very similar to that which I have
described for the US. If east Asia is to remain stable, it must create a
greater sense of shared interests and mutual security among increasingly
powerful nations which remain mistrustful despite their growing interdependence.
<BR>
<BR>
There must be concerted action to integrate fully some of the outlying nations,
particularly North Korea, into that emerging Pacific community. And there
must also be efforts to resolve security problems that could give rise to
the use of force: arms races, territorial disputes, environmental problems,
ethnic groups that span state borders, as well as poverty and instability
that could give rise to migration across national frontiers. <BR>
<BR>
The US has some responsibility to create this sense of community. But the
principal obligation lies within Asia itself. The establishment of both
bilateral and multilateral security dialogue at both the official and the
unofficial levels (one aspect of what Kishore Mahbubani recently called
&quot;The Pacific Impulse&quot;) is a most welcome and promising development.
The nations of east Asia need to ensure these new mechanisms produce mutual
transparency, improved confidence, a culture of preventive diplomacy, conflict
resolution and crisis management. And if the US has the obligation to consult
with its allies, they have a parallel responsibility to present their views
honestly, to share the risk of policy initiatives and to accept the burden
of joint leadership. <BR>
<BR>
Intellectually, the challenge for Asia is a mirror image of that facing
the US. A one-sided emphasis on what are now being called Asian values and
institutions could prove to be as detrimental to Asia as a one-sided emphasis
on so-called western values and institutions has been to the US. If taken
to extremes, respect for authority can become a damper on creativity and
innovation: emphasis on community can come at the expense of individual
rights; insistence on harmony can lead to the suppression of diversity and
dissent and one-person institutions can fall victim to favouritism and corruption.
What is fascinating is to see a new generation of Asian leaders and intellectuals
arguing that pluralism and individualism have historic roots in Asian culture
and that modern Asia needs to give these values their proper role. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The temptations of success </B><BR>
<BR>
Asia, like the US, faces a psychocultural challenge as the result of its
enormous success. It would be understandable for Asian leaders and intellectuals,
especially those who have personally experienced western colonialism and
racism, to respond by seeking to turn the tables. They could define their
identity in narrow national or even pan-Asian terms. They could argue that
it is now time to establish another hierarchical cross-cultural relationship,
but this time one in which Asia teaches and the west learns. They could
adopt their own version of the clash of civilisations theory, in which they
assert that there should be no accommodation between the Asian ethic and
western values. They could, in short, advocate a form of Asian fundamentalism,
which could provoke a cultural clash between east and west. <BR>
<BR>
This would be not only a tragic mistake, but a needless repetition of one
of the worst features of western history. To use Noordin Sopiee's phrase
in a slightly different context, the Asian opportunity is to use its economic
resurgence to join the US and Europe in an equal partnership that is based
on mutual learning and mutual respect. <BR>
<BR>
Such an approach would not only avoid a wasteful clash of civilisations,
but would present the unique prospect of a fusion of civilisations that
in turn would be a major contribution toward building a global community
that incorporates all of humanity's greatest traditions.<BR>
<BR>
<I>Taken from the author's September 1995 Li and Fung lecture on commerce
and industry, sponsored by the MBA programmes at the Faculty of Business
Administration, the Chinese University of Hong Kong</I> <p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
