<!--created by Oyster Systems-->
<!--May 1996-->
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
EMWL: World Link Magazine:January/February 1996
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<!--START_TAG_SPACE-->
<!--00017200 India -->
<!--END_TAG_SPACE-->
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="7C1568" text="000000" link="7C1568">

<center>
<font size=3>
<table border=0>
<tr>
<td colspan=2 align=left>
<nobr>
<img width=199 height=44 name="top" border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../images/conban8.gif" alt="World Link Magazine"><a href="../../../../../index.html"><img width=141 height=45 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../../images/conban1.gif" alt="EMWL Home"></a>
</nobr>
<br>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<h2>
January/February 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 
<H3>ON THE MOVE</H3>
<H4>AMMAN SUMMIT </H4>
<H2>Last farewell in Amman </H2>
The Middle East/North Africa economic summit, held late October, will now
be remembered as the last meeting between Israel's architect of peace and
his Arab partners. Days after the close of the summit in Jordan's capital
Amman, Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin was murdered by a Jewish assassin.
<BR>
<BR>
The summit meeting of Arab, Israeli and other business people had emphasised
both the potential and limitations of Middle East peace. At one of the meeting's
most revealing sessions, &quot;Is the Middle East open for business?&quot;,
William Ryrie of Baring Holdings expressed a sentiment privately held by
a number of European and American delegates: &quot;The region cannot be
said to be open for business because of barriers between countries.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
He hoped the peace process would break down some of these barriers but others
stemmed from anti-market policies and it was not yet clear they had been
rejected. Regional stock markets had also missed out on major developments
in international capital flows, he added. But despite the doubts, &quot;with
the right attitude, the Middle East could again become a region for growth.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Paul Volcker, former chairman of the US Federal Reserve and the session
moderator, said the region had big potential but added that there were many
competitors, &quot;many of them frankly ahead of the Middle East&quot;.
Volcker also sounded a warning on the proposed development bank which he
said should be small and efficient. <BR>
<BR>
Volcker said tourism is an important way of providing jobs and development
in a hurry but Yossi Beilin, Israel's economy and planning minister, disagreed:
&quot;The hypothesis is that everyone wants more tourism, but when you know
the region you realise that this is not the case. Once you know what's possible
and what's impossible, it will be much easier to attract the world.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Addressing the session theme, Youssef Boutros Ghali, Egypt's minister of
state for international co-operation said: &quot;We are asked this question
about being open for business and it is my sincere hope that next year we
won't have to ask it.&quot; But for those expressing impatience, he reminded
the audience that the Camp David accord had taken time to produce results.
<BR>
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4>AMMAN: TRANSPORT </H4>
<H2>A line of steel in the sand </H2>
In some respects the Middle East's infrastructure is now worse than it was
during the Ottoman period, according to Ghassan Ali, vice-president of finance
at Royal Jordanian airlines. During the session on transport, Ali pointed
out that until World War I there had been a railway running from Turkey
to Egypt. The line, sabotaged by Arab forces during the war, had never been
reinstituted: &quot;It is very sad to see that 100 years ago a railway ran
through the Middle East and that it is no longer there.&quot; The region
needed a railway and north-south coastal highway, with branches peeling
off from the main trunk, he said. <BR>
<BR>
Asked whether there was a market for such an ambitious road, Ali conceded
there was probably insufficient traffic right now: &quot;But we are talking
about a new era. If these routes were feasible 100 years ago, I am sure
they would be feasible now.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
If such plans are still some way off, the session on joint regional projects
stressed some of the schemes which should be among the first fruits of the
peace process. Beilin referred to the construction of 40,000 hotel rooms
over the next few years, some of them in projects run jointly with Jordan
and Egypt. Both the Dead Sea and the TEAM area (the triangle formed by Taba,
Eilat and Aqaba) have been targeted for ambitious tourist projects. An airport
which would serve both Aqaba and Eilat is also planned to straddle the border
between Israel and Jordan. <BR>
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4>CHINA MEETING </H4>
<H2>Rural labour migration </H2>
&quot;A large segment of the rural population is feeling increasingly alienated
from what is happening in the rest of the country. Agriculture is today
one of most difficult sectors for the government to deal with,&quot; said
Claude Smadja at the opening session of the forum's annual China meeting,
held in Beijing at the end of October. <BR>
<BR>
The Swiss Broadcasting Corporation news director, soon to join the forum,
highlighted the widening gap between rural and urban income which is causing
dissatisfaction and, more importantly, internal migrations. <BR>
<BR>
By the end of 1994 there were 446 million people in the rural workforce.
Some 200 million are sufficient for agricultural production: a further 120
million work in township enterprises. This leaves well over 100 million
surplus to requirement and now on the road, flocking into cities and creating
a serious problem for social stability. <BR>
<BR>
Both Liu Jiang, minister of agriculture, and Du Ying, deputy director of
the research centre for rural economy, skirted around this theme in a packed
session devoted to reform and social stability in the agricultural sector.
<BR>
<BR>
Liu was keen to point out that agricultural production had increased substantially
- cotton production had doubled, meat had trebled and grain was up by more
than 40% - but admitted that this was not enough. &quot;Today, agriculture
as the base of China's national economy is relatively weak and lacking staying
power,&quot; he said. Liu identified the main pressures on the sector as
population growth and rural surplus labour. <BR>
<BR>
Du was swift to scotch any ideas that a migrant population might be causing
difficulties and blamed the media for exaggerating problems. He argued that
the rural and urban workforce complement each other, as most of the <I>mangliu</I>
(blind transients) work in construction where there is enough work to go
around. <BR>
<BR>
Second, he said, most workers go to the cities with the help of local government
or family and friends and third, there is no question of social instability
because most migration is seasonal. This is different from the situation
in other emerging countries where rural drift occurs because of drought
or because farmers have lost their land. <BR>
<BR>
Liu and Du were not in sharp disagreement, however: with the former repeating
some of Du's arguments. &quot;Labour migration not only provides large numbers
of low-cost workers for cities and developed regions to expedite their economic
development, but also reduces unemployment pressure in rural areas. It helps
farmers earn more income and learn new ideas and plays an important part
in vitalising the economy of labour exporting regions,&quot; he said. <BR>
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4>CHINA: POLLUTION </H4>
<H2>Environment protection </H2>
Xie Zhenhua, director of the National Environmental Protection Agency, gave
a full report on China's ecological concerns. &quot;A weak point in China's
environmental protection work today is that existing laws are not observed
and law enforcement is not strict,&quot; he told the meeting. <BR>
<BR>
His agency had pinpointed poor management as the problem and as a result
was working hard to clean up production and incorporate self-restraint into
the modern enterprise system. He cited the example of the Huaihe River basin,
where several companies had been closed down recently. <BR>
<BR>
The problem is now considerable. Although GNP has been growing, so too has
energy consumption - one of the main causes of pollution. Compared to developed
countries, China consumes more coal per head which produces a frightening
1.4 million tonnes of sulphur dioxide and 15 million tonnes of smoke. But
less than 0.8% of GNP was being spent on the prevention and treatment of
pollution. <BR>
<BR>
A four-step programme had been introduced to achieve the agency's objectives,
he explained. The first was to implement a sustainable development strategy.
The second was to set up an environmental legal system to punish criminal
behaviour and enforce those laws. The third was to strengthen industrial
pollution prevention in urban areas. And the fourth was to invest in the
environment and get international assistance. &quot;China will welcome and
support any cooperation and exchanges that help improve its environmental
quality,&quot; he said. <BR>
<BR>
In spite of the difficulties, Xie's conclusion was optimistic: &quot;Let
us advance hand in hand and create together a new era of green civilisation
for mankind.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H4>INDIA MEETING </H4>
<H2>Dream of an opportunity </H2>
No one among those present at the forum's India meeting, held in New Delhi
on December 3-5, was sceptical about the range and scale of opportunities
in the country. Instead, participants focused on the manner of welcome they
were likely to receive. Finance minister Manmohan Singh, who seemed to sense
these apprehensions, tried to put the assembled foreign delegates at ease.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;India is not going to go back to the old ways,&quot; he said. &quot;We
will continue to work towards the further opening of the Indian economy...
and create in our country an environment conducive to greater inflow of
foreign direct investment.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
All the signals emanating from Delhi over the past few months, however,
seemed clearly to suggest otherwise. Doubts on the incumbent Congress government's
ability to return to power with a clear majority after the general election,
due in the middle of this year, were freely expressed by delegates at the
Delhi meeting. Political expediency, many noted, has meant putting the macroeconomic
stabilisation programme on the back burner and economic reform back in the
freezer. The old ways are startlingly in evidence. And even as the WEF meeting
was in session, the country's claim to an &quot;open system&quot; was put
to the test with opposition parties insisting on the repeal of licences
being sought by prospective basic telecom operators. Nor have the problems
faced by Kentucky Fried Chicken, whose Delhi outlet was closed apparently
for hygiene reasons, provided evidence of a &quot;conducive environment&quot;.
<BR>
<BR>
Delegates looking at the possibility of investing in India were even taken
through a DIY session that concentrated on the pros and cons of entry as
well as the partner selection process. But most concerns remained unanswered.
<BR>
<BR>
The other main architect of the economic reform programme, commerce minister
P Chidambaram, addressed delegates at the opening dinner and as usual exuded
confidence on prospects for the Indian economy. <BR>
<BR>
Data on industrial production and foreign trade looked healthy enough, he
noted. Chidambaram forecast that trade-led GDP growth could reach 8% annually
by the turn of the century and even top 10% thereafter. &quot;With a dream
and a little luck, Indian exports could cross the $75 billion line by 2000,&quot;
he said, although recognising that at present the country's infrastructure
was inadequate for that dream to come true. Most delegates at the sectoral
workshops bemoaned infrastructural constraints but offered little by way
of solutions. <BR>
<BR>
India. traditionally Eurocentric, at last appears to realise the potential
benefits of a broad-spectrum partnership with its Asean neighbours. Both
minister for external affairs Pranab Mukherji and his articulate minister
of state, Salman Khurshid, appeared to commit India firmly to regional economic
institutions. <BR>
<BR>
Notwithstanding the observations of the former deputy prime minister of
Thailand, Supachai Panitchpakdi, substantial ground remains to be covered
before that becomes a reality. Asean looks at India with a hint of hesitation
bordering on suspicion, justifiable or otherwise. <BR>
<BR>
A more consistent interaction of business leaders of the region could help
mend matters. <BR>
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H2>SOUNDBITES</H2>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;If we call the tendency towards peace 'rushing', then Egypt preceded
us in this by 17 years.&quot; King Hussein of Jordan following remarks by
Egyptian foreign minister Amre Moussa, implying criticism of the speed of
improved relations between Amman and Jerusalem <BR>
<BR>
&quot;That was only a passage in the speech and I want everybody to understand
that it was not directed against Jordan or any other country.&quot;Amre
Moussa speaking in reply to King Hussein of Jordan <BR>
<BR>
&quot;I arrived in Amman hours ago from Jerusalem, the capital of Israel.&quot;<BR>
Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, speaking days before his murder <BR>
<BR>
&quot;For too long this has been a region of warriors and widows. It once
again should become a region of builders and traders.&quot; Warren Christopher,
US Secretary of State, speaking about the Middle East <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We hope Jerusalem will be the symbol of peace among the sons of Abraham.&quot;
King Hussein of Jordan <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The egalitarian income distribution approach of eating from the same
big pot has been basically abandoned.&quot; <BR>
Sun Shangqing, director, Development Research Centre of the State Council,
China <BR>
<BR>
&quot;China is a large country with complicated conditions: our reforms
must proceed steadily and step by step.&quot;<BR>
Xiang Huaicheng, deputy director-general, State Administration of Taxation
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The Chinese security market is in the stage of turning from exploring
to standardising.&quot;<BR>
Wang Hua, deputy managing director, Hainan Provincial Securities </BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

