<td valign=top>
<h2>
January/February 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>
<H3>REVIEW</H3>
<H2>Lucid chaos </H2>
<H4>Nature's Numbers </H4>
<I>By Ian Stewart<BR>
Weidenfeld &amp; Nicolson &#163;9.99 </I>
<B>Five Golden Rules: Great Theories of 20th Century Mathematics -
and Why They Matter </B>
<I>By John Casti<BR>
Wiley $24.95/&#163;16.99 <BR>
<BR>
<B>Reviewed by Lance Knobel </B></I><BR>
<BR>
Mathematics has preserved its power to terrorise a large portion of the
adult population, who recall youthful struggles with equations and dry,
uninteresting teachers. At my university - where undergraduates were
required to learn a foreign language, take at least a year of natural sciences
and obtain a basic grounding in history and literature - the so-called
arts faculty annually defeated scientist-led proposals to require at least
one year of mathematics for every student. <BR>
<BR>
The scientists persisted in their annual battle because they understood
that mathematics provides the basis for understanding much of our world.
In fact mathematics' encroachment into other realms has been accelerating:
it conquered physics early in this century (or in Newton's time, depending
on your viewpoint), chemistry succumbed by mid-century and biology has become
truly infused by mathematics only within the last 20 years. The power of
our desktop computers and the programs which run on them rests entirely
on mathematical manipulations. <BR>
<BR>
But the importance of mathematics stems not from its applications but from
its essence: its logic, its adherence to rigorous proof, its ability to
construct an internally consistent world from nothing more than intellectual
power. The popular hostility to mathematics arises from the rarity with
which teachers or writers can convey its sheer beauty. Fortunately, two
recent books do much to right the wrongs of bad teachers past. <BR>
<BR>
Ian Stewart's <I>Nature's Numbers</I> is part of the excellent Science Masters
series in which leading practitioners provide a lucid account of contemporary
thinking in their field. Stewart's own work deals chiefly with the effects
of symmetry on dynamics, with applications to pattern formation and chaos
theory. The book does not attempt to embrace all mathematics, but focuses
instead on patterns in nature and the ways mathematics can help us explain
and understand them. He writes: &quot;Between the behaviour we observe and
the laws that produce it is a crevasse, which the human mind can bridge
only by mathematical calculations.&quot; The examples he cites are wide-ranging:
from the evolution of the eye to the dynamics of the solar system. Unsurprisingly,
given his own professional interests, the best parts of the book deal with
chaos and complexity. The extended discussion of how water drips from a
tap, in particular, conveys some key insights of so-called chaoticians better
than the old saw about a butterfly flapping its wings in China. <BR>
<BR>
In the gentlest possible way, Stewart also introduces the reader to some
mathematics, such as the calculus that Newton developed for his laws of
motion. But Stewart steers away from anything so frightening as equations.
He presumably took the advice of Stephen Hawking's editor that every equation
in a book cuts its sales in half. <BR>
<BR>
Casti, author of <I>Five Golden Rules</I>, has no such qualms. He plainly
states in his preface that his ideal reader has a &quot;sophisticated&quot;
background in mathematics: &quot;The book is for anyone who's not afraid
to confront real mathematical <I>ideas</I> - head-on.&quot; According
to Casti, high school algebra or geometry should suffice; I was glad to
have completed two years of university-level maths. <BR>
<BR>
That said, for those willing to persevere Casti's book is immensely rewarding.
In pithy language and with a modicum of well-explained equations, he introduces
the reader to the Minimax Theorem from which much of game theory derives,
the Brouwer Fixed Point Theorem on topology, Morse's Theorem on singularity
or catastrophe theory, the Halting Theorem on the theory of computation
and the Simplex Method on optimisation theory. According to Casti, these
five theorems pass the tests of significance, beauty and scope, application,
proof method and philosophical implications. <BR>
<BR>
To the non-mathematician, virtually everything in the book will be new.
But Casti worries that readers will complain that he is dealing with old
mathematics: the most recent theorem, the Simplex Method, dates from the
late 1940s. The self-stated answer to these concerns is that the theorems
gave rise to great theories which are still evolving. &quot;Generally speaking,
it seems to take at least a generation or two for a great theorem to 'grow
up', that is, to be recognised as the seed from which a great theory has
subsequently grown,&quot; he writes. <BR>
<BR>
Some idea of the brilliant span of this book can be gauged by the series
of examples that crop up in the discussion of singularity theory: why bridges
collapse, developmental biology and the mathematics of joke-telling. Even
as a mathematically inclined layperson, I had believed that contemporary
mathematics was rapidly straying completely out of reach for the non-professional.
Casti proves otherwise. <I>Five Golden Rules</I> is probably the most difficult
book you will read this year, but it may also be the most exhilarating.
<BR>
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H2>Failed dreams </H2>
<H4>Start Up </H4>
<I>By Jerry Kaplan<BR>
Houghton Mifflin, $22.95 <BR>
<BR>
<B>Reviewed by Andrew Clark</B></I><B> </B><BR>
<BR>
In 1987, Gerry Kaplan thought he had an idea which would transform the computer
industry. It was to develop a laptop onto which the user could write directly
with a pen, without any need for a keyboard. The result would be small enough
to fit in a briefcase which the jet-setting executive could use like a notebook.
In <I>Start Up</I> Kaplan chronicles the birth and eventual death of the
company he set up to market this idea. He gives a detailed insight into
the trials of a small venture trying to succeed in an unsentimental market.
On the way, he dishes the dirt on many major players in the computer industry.
<BR>
<BR>
The pen computer has not taken off, but Kaplan regarded himself as a pioneer
in almost evangelical pursuit of his dream. At times he overdoes the &quot;vision
thing&quot;. When he first has the idea, on a corporate jet somewhere over
the Rocky Mountains, he writes: &quot;This unique emotion - the modern
scientific version of religious epiphany - is startling in its raw
power and purity.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Although this frankness is corny it is also the great strength of the book.
As the vision disintegrates Kaplan allows all his petulant bitterness to
come through. Among those particularly targeted is Microsoft chairman Bill
Gates. Through Kaplan's eyes, Gates appears petty, scheming and utterly
obsessed with point-scoring. He adds: &quot;Gates always seemed to be trying
to prove that he was smarter than everyone else, and this competitiveness
pervaded the entire company.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
There follows a description of how Microsoft quietly developed a rival pen
computing system to rival GO, Kaplan's company. The allegations he then
details were made available to the US Federal Trade Commission in an investigation
of anti-trust violations by Microsoft. They cannot be detailed here because
of British libel laws. <BR>
<BR>
In general, Kaplan tends to regard large corporations as ideologically impure.
He criticises IBM, saying its developmental help was marked by delays which
made the relationship a millstone around the neck of the small company.
Apple, which aggressively promotes its own pen computer, is also assailed.
<BR>
<BR>
<I>Start Up</I> manages to build up a surprising amount of dramatic tension
for a corporate biography and is interesting both as an inside view of the
computer industry and as a portrait of a small and often unorthodox company
run by a man with an enthusiastic, hands-on technique. Although Kaplan's
story is not a wholly happy one, it does not put one off starting up with
an bright idea. <BR>
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H2>Matter over mind </H2>
<H4>Landscape and Memory </H4>
<I>By Simon Schama <BR>
HarperCollins, &#163;30 <BR>
<BR>
<B>Reviewed by Susan Greenberg</B></I><B> </B><BR>
<BR>
For people who do not like their reading to come in narrow categories, the
name of this author has become an instant recommendation. Schama, professor
of humanities at Columbia University, always approaches history at a fresh
angle, his projects crammed with observations that show the scope of his
comparative mind. <BR>
<BR>
His theme this time, the human relationship to landscape and nature, is
not as obviously controversial as the French revolution, the subject of
the earlier work <I>Citizens</I> which challenged accepted notions of modernity,
but as millenial gloom gathers about the future of the planet it is the
environmentalist criticism of progress which looms large on the western
political scene. <BR>
<BR>
Schama engages with this and reminds us, as any good historian should, that
the things we take for granted in fact shift constantly in our own memory,
including the current widespread perception of nature and society as separate
and antagonistic, with only cave-dwellers exempt from original sin. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;If the entire history of landscape in the west is indeed just a mindless
race toward a machine-driven universe, uncomplicated by myth, metaphor and
allegory... then we are indeed trapped in the engine of our self-destruction,&quot;
he writes. But despite the real damage done to the world, the human occupation
of the landscape should be cause for celebration: &quot;Landscapes are culture
before they are nature; constructs of the imagination projected onto wood
and water and rock.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The book is divided into three main parts covering those three elements.
There are plenty of insights throughout, including on how nature is reflected
in art (see painting above), but the best section deals with the forest
which in Germany embodied militaristic spirit, in France the passion for
order, in England liberty and in Poland the struggle for national freedom.
<BR>
<BR>
Schama uses what his old teacher called &quot;the archive of the feet&quot;
and visits the landscape of his lumberjack Jewish ancestors in northeastern
Poland, &quot;a country where frontiers march back and forth to the abrupt
commands of history&quot;. He charts how the forest became a carrier of
national memory following the 18th century carve-up of Poland. In one interesting
cross-reference, Schama describes a meeting in 1829 between the exiled Polish
romantic<B> </B>writer Adam<B> </B>Mickiewicz with his American counterpart
James Fennimore Cooper, Polish sympathiser and author of <I>Last of the
Mohicans</I> which marked the dying and suppressed native American culture.
<BR>
<BR>
During a brief period of nationhood before Poland was swallowed up again,
its leaders tried to wine and dine Adolf Hitler's most compulsive hunter
Hermann G&ouml;ring at the Bielawieza forest lodge. G&ouml;ring typified
the Nazi obsession with the idea of a pure German woodland warrior race:
in the Third Reich vivisection was punished by the concentration camp &quot;where
the medical staff was less fussy about operating on humans than hounds&quot;.
<BR>
<BR>
Schama resists reducing the fabled German relationship to the forest to
simple bleakness, however, through a detailed account of the hunt for a
German identity. It starts with the first century Roman historian Cornelius
Tacitus whose work <I>Germania, On the Origin and Situation of the Germans</I>,
a picture of a fighting forest people, became the &quot;birth certificate
of the German race&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
In Britain woodland is a more cosy and inhabited place where the &quot;blood
pact turned into mere bloody-mindedness&quot;. The fable of Robin Hood dates
from a 1308 story about a yeoman who rebelled when obliged to pay for wood
gathered in the earl's forest. <BR>
<BR>
When ship timber became the stuff of empire, the native oak tree became
the symbol of British liberty, like its people seen as &quot;tight-pored,
tough-grained, inhospitable to pests, watertight and long-lived&quot;. In
a race with rival France for ship timber, Britain complained that because
of the many common liberties limiting royal rule, it could not compete with
King Louis' centralised powers to conscript his own forest by fiat, &quot;as
if conscripting militia&quot;, a familiar complaint to modern ears. <BR>
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H2>Party propaganda </H2>
<H4>The Aachen Memorandum </H4>
<I>By Andrew Roberts<BR>
Weidenfeld &amp; Nicholson, &#163;15.99 </I>
<B>Michael Portillo: The Future of the Right </B>
<I>By Michael Gove<BR>
Fourth Estate, &#163;20 <BR>
<BR>
<B>Reviewed by Adrian Murdoch</B></I><B> </B><BR>
<BR>
In the British Clubland novel of the '20s and '30s, the bogeymen were Germans,
Jews and industrialists. Since World War II they have been Americans and
Russians in more or less equal quantities. In the '90s, the target is fast
becoming Europe. In Britain at least, Brussels has become the Pavlovian
trigger for the church-going, monarchy-supporting and country-loving part
of the population to start foaming at the mouth. The writers of both of
these books, from the Euro-sceptic right-wing of the Conservative Party,
do for closer European integration what George Orwell did for communism
in the political satire <I>Animal Farm</I>. Although the former work masquerades
as a futuristic thriller and the latter as a biography of a leading young
British politician, it is no coincidence that both were released on the
eve of a Conservative Party conference and the authors thank each other
in their prefaces. <BR>
<BR>
<I>The Aachen Memorandum</I> is perhaps the more credible of the two and
owes something in style to Robert Harris' bestseller <I>Fatherland</I> .
Set in 2045 on the 100th anniversary of the end of World War II in the British
region of the European superstate, it tells of the skulduggery uncovered
by the hero Horatio Lestoq over the ratification of the final surrender
to Europe 30 years previously. From the murder of an old admiral to a climax
which brings down the superstate in London's Hyde Park involving King William,
who now rules only in New Zealand, this book is likely to send Euro-sceptics
off into a protracted series of ecstatic shudders. <BR>
<BR>
But Roberts is describing less an Orwellian vision of the future than the
dangers of the modern-day Europe run from Brussels, and indeed the author's
political friends have publicly compared EU commissioners to Nazi <I>gauleiters.
</I>He tugs shamelessly at loyalty to icons of Britain's national heritage
and identity. The hero is self-consciously named Horatio after Admiral Nelson,
slayer of the French, the Houses of Parliament renamed the Westminster Heritage,
Amenity and Leisuredrome and Buckingham Palace - now the regional headquarters
of the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development - is dubbed
Attali House after the former much-criticised EBRD chief. It is interesting
to ponder whether any other country in Europe would get away with such blatant,
although in this case amusing, tub-thumping. <BR>
<BR>
Whereas Roberts succeeds by virtue of historical legerdemain and fantasy
- he is a historian by training from Cambridge - Oxford-educated
Gove has less success writing on Michael Portillo, Britain's defence secretary.
Many would argue that a biography of a young politician, even one as charismatic
as Portillo, is premature. With chapters that amble through his Spanish
origins (he is known to relatives as <I>Miguelito</I>)<I>, </I>Cambridge
and his conversion to Conservatism, his time as chief secretary at the Treasury
up to his recent posting at the defence ministry, it seems curious that
anyone would spend &#163;20 on a book about a politician whose career is
probably only starting. <BR>
<BR>
Nevertheless there are few politicians on the European stage who incite
such violent feeling in both directions. One journalist cited halfway through
the book comments: &quot;Portillo is cold, sensual and superior and smart
enough to know that those qualities can work for him. The Castilian stallion
excites men with the smack of firm government and has every woman in the
land reaching for the basque separates.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
What would make the book genuinely interesting is its subtitle, &quot;The
Future of the Right of the Right&quot;. Sadly this is the issue Gove hardly
touches, not even questioning whether the right has a future at all. There
is little on economics, nothing on the first recession of 1982 and only
one paragraph on the late '80s crash. In fact the book raises more questions
than it answers. Why is Portillo the future? How clever can a man be who
gaffed by suggesting that foreigners buy their A-levels ? Those looking
for answers will be disappointed. <BR>
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=60%>
<H2>Kafka's lover </H2>
<H4>Kafka, Love and Courage: the life of Milena Jesenska </H4>
<I>By Mary Hockaday<BR>
Andre Deutsch, &#163;17.99 <BR>
<BR>
<B>Reviewed by Francis Harris</B></I><B> </B><BR>
<BR>
Franz Kafka is not widely regarded as one of the century's wittiest men.
Yet in love and in private, he had his moments. Writing to his Czech lover
Milena Jesenska, he describes a dream: &quot;You were completely lost to
me. In my despair I made several very cunning attempts which, however, I
don't know why, were not carried through and of which I remember only one.
I wrote on an envelope 'Milena', and under it, 'I beg that this letter be
delivered otherwise the Ministry of Finance will suffer an enormous loss'.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Kafka's intuitive sense of 20th century madness is easier to understand
through his letters to Milena, although sadly her replies have been lost.
The correspondence is well known, yet the woman who inspired Kafka's confidence
has been a rather shadowy figure. This is a shame because Milena Jesenska,
Prague bourgeois, wild child, unhappy wife and wartime resister, was a talented
and remarkable woman. <BR>
<BR>
In fact, her relationship with Kafka occupied no more than a chapter of
her short but busy life. They met in Prague during World War I, on the caf&eacute;
circuit in one of Europe's oldest and most vibrant communities where Czechs,
Germans and Jews shared a city, if not a culture, a Slav woman and Jewish
man discovering an all-too-rare common ground before the arrival of war
<BR>
<BR>
At one level, Milena and Kafka charted an alternative to the approaching
holocaust. &quot;German is my mother tongue and therefore natural to me,&quot;
he wrote to her just after the first war ended. &quot;But Czech feels to
me far more intimate, which is why your letter dispels many an uncertainty.
I see you clearer, the movements of your body, your hands, so quick, so
determined, it's almost a meeting, although when I try to raise my eyes
to your face, then in the flow of the letter - what a story! -
fire breaks out and I see nothing but fire.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Although the couple barely spent any time together (four intense days in
Vienna and an unsuccessful day in Gmund), and although the relationship
was unconsummated, this was a passionate love affair with enough heat to
turn Plato's hair white. Without a clear goal, suffering the burden of his
neurotic anxiety and her conflicting desires, the relationship soon burned
itself out. Four years later, he was dead of physical sickness and mental
anguish, provoking a last tribute from his former lover who wrote of a Kafka
&quot;so painfully conscious that he heard even where others, the deaf,
felt safe&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
Journalism provided a new living as Milena shed her husband and returned
to Prague from Vienna. Milena and her newly created country of Czechoslovakia
did not have long. In 1938 the young democracy was sold out by Britain and
France to Hitler at Munich and the Czechs were alone and friendless in a
brutal world. Enlightened nationalists like Milena faced an appalling dilemma
of whether to resist and die, go into barren exile or collaborate with the
enemy. <BR>
<BR>
She chose resistance, helping Jews to escape, and died in Ravensbruck concentration
camp in 1944 mourned by many of those who had known her. A true heroine
for her necessarily faithless times, she had rejected both communism and
Nazism and instead chose to answer only to her heart. <BR>
<BR>
The author became my friend when we were correspondents in Prague covering
the revolution that ended communism. She has done justice not only to a
difficult and complicated subject but also to the fascinating wealth of
central European society and its sad and too-often realised potential for
unrelieved evil. <p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
