<td valign=top align=left>
<H3>WORLD ECONOMIC FORUM</H3> 
<H2>Forum Insights</H2>
<H4>1995 China Meeting </H4>
<B>Beijing October 30 to November 1 </B><BR>
<BR>
The two-day meeting brought together some 90 participants from China and
over 100 business leaders from abroad for discussions entitled China's new
economic challenges, focusing on the government's moves to stabilise the
economy, to push for reform and to create new impetus for the agricultural
sector. <BR>
<BR>
In addition to Economic and Trade Commission Chairman Wang Zhongyu, Agriculture
Minister Liu Jiang and Internal Trade Minister Chen Bangzhu, over 40 Chinese
academics, government and business personalities took an active role in
the programme. Foreign personalities included Swiss economy minister Jean-Pascal
Delamuraz, Japan External Trade Organisation Executive Director Takehiko
Kondo and Klaus Regling, Director General of the German Ministry of Finance.
Co-chairs for the meeting from the Chinese side were Zhao Weichen, Chairman
of China United Telecommunications Corporation, and Pan Chenglie, Deputy
Director General of the China Enterprise Management Association (CEMA),
the World Economic Forum's host partner. <BR>
<BR>
One session was devoted to the government's key challenge of ensuring a
better balance between regions competing for investment: in addition to
vice-mayors from Beijing and Dalian, the mayors of Qiqihar (Heilongjiang
Province) and Wujin City (Jiangsu Province), the vice-governor of Gansu
Province enthusiastically presented the attractions of his region. Another
session looked at the obstacles remaining in China's path before joining
the WTO. Three priority areas for foreign partnership will be the ambitious
programme for telecommunications, infrastructure development and the reform
of the financial sector. <BR>
<BR>
Participants were pleased to be received at the Great Hall of the People
for the traditional Official Call by the newly appointed vice-premier Wu
Bangguo, in charge of industry and transportation. Addressing participants'
concerns, Mr Wu spoke of the need to reform and improve the efficiency of
state-owned enterprises, one of the government priorities set out in the
latest Five-Year Plan (1996-2000). What will be the impact on social stability?
<BR>
<BR>
Anyone interested in further details of the programme should contact Colette
Mathur, Director of the World Economic Forum, who is responsible for our
activities in China. <BR>
<BR>
<HR>
<H4>1995 Middle East/ North Africa Economic Summit </H4>
<BR>
<B>October 29-31, Amman, Jordan <BR>
<BR>
Amman Declaration</B><BR>
<BR>
On October 29-31 1995, the second Middle East/North Africa Economic Summit
was held in Amman, Jordan under the patronage of His Majesty King Hussein
bin Talal. The Summit, co-sponsored by the United States and the Russian
Federation, with the support of the European Union, Canada and Japan, brought
together government and business leaders from the Middle East and North
Africa, Europe, the Americas and Asia. <BR>
<BR>
Summit participants thank His Majesty King Hussein for his able leadership
and for the extraordinary efforts by the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan to
make this Summit a success. The participants also expressed their appreciation
for the partnership of the World Economic Forum, which assisted so ably
in organising this event. <BR>
<BR>
The goals of the Summit were to facilitate the expansion of private sector
investment in the region, to cement a public-private partnership which will
ensure that end, and to work to enhance regional cooperation and development.
<BR>
<BR>
In this spirit, business leaders from the Middle East, North Africa and
other regions were able to conclude a number of significant commercial and
business transactions at the Summit that will help augment the productive
capacity of the region and contribute to its broad-based economic development.
These ventures involved projects in the fields of tourism, telecommunications
and transportation. Reflecting this public-private partnership, a number
of these ventures will benefit from government guarantees, technical assistance
and other support from the international community. <BR>
<BR>
Government representatives conducted a series of negotiations over the past
year on institutional arrangements as called for in the Casablanca Declaration
which would help underpin the peace process. In this respect, the following
agreements have been reached: <BR>
<BR>
* A Bank for Economic Cooperation and Development in the Middle East and
North Africa will be established in Cairo. The Bank - as described
in its draft articles - will be structured to promote development of
the private sector, support regional infrastructure projects and provide
a Forum to promote regional economic cooperation. The Task Force will finalise
its negotiations by December 31, 1995 and will continue to explore proposals
for the creation of a project preparation and financial intermediation facility.
Those wishing to join the Bank will begin their national ratification processes
thereafter. Others wish to leave open the option of joining the Bank at
a later date, in light of the evolution of institutional arrangements and
other developments. The Economic Summit will review this issue at its next
meeting. <BR>
<BR>
* The establishment of a Regional Tourism Board, the Middle East-Mediterranean
Travel and Tourism Association, to facilitate tourism and promote the region
as a unique and attractive tourist destination. The Board will include both
public and private representatives. <BR>
<BR>
* The establishment of a Regional Business Council to promote cooperation
and trade among the private sectors of the countries of the region. <BR>
<BR>
* The formal inauguration of the Economic Summit Executive Secretariat,
which is located in Rabat and works to advance the public-private partnership,
promoting contacts, sharing data and fostering private sector investment
in the region. The participants expressed their appreciation to the Moroccan
Government for its contribution to this effort, and confirmed their support
for its ongoing activities. <BR>
<BR>
As a complement to the regional institutions called for at Casablanca, the
Steering Group of the Multilateral Peace Negotiations has decided to establish
REDWG Monitoring Committee Secretariat as a permanent regional economic
institution to be based in Amman. All participating parties have agreed
that this institution will promote and strengthen regional economic cooperation
in the Middle East and North Africa. The regional parties strongly recommend
that the Secretariat's activities will cover the range of sectors within
the REDWG Monitoring Committee's work, i.e. infrastructure, tourism, trade,
finance, and areas within the Copenhagen Plan of Action. The core parties
in close consultation with the European Union and other members of the Monitoring
Committee undertake to finalise the appropriate document on the structure
and operational functions of this institution, which will be submitted to
the next meeting of the REDWG plenary, with a view to the commencement of
the institution's activities in the first half of 1996. This REDWG plenary
will consider the matter, take appropriate action and report to the upcoming
meeting of the Multilateral Steering Group. <BR>
<BR>
The participants at the Summit expressed their strong support for continued
progress in the peace process begun at Madrid exactly four years ago, and
the importance of achieving a comprehensive peace. Participants took particular
note of advances made in the past year. Summit participants welcomed the
signing of the Israeli-Palestinian Interim Agreement in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, and took favourable note of the significant progress made in
implementing the Treaty of Peace between Israel and Jordan. The Summit welcomed
the decision to organise in Paris, in December 1995, the Ministerial Conference
on Economic Assistance for the Palestinians. <BR>
<BR>
The Summit also took note of the positive contribution made towards peace
by multilateral working groups. While welcoming an increasingly positive
atmosphere of openness in the region, the Summit recognised that the circle
of peace needs to be widened. Participants expressed the hope that peace
agreements between Israel and Syria and Israel and Lebanon would be concluded
as soon as possible. The Summit welcomed significant steps taken by regional
parties to the Taba Declaration and by the GCC with regard to lifting the
boycott on Israel, and expressed its support for additional efforts to end
the boycott. <BR>
<BR>
The participants at the Summit declared their intent to implement as soon
as possible the understandings reached in Amman. With respect to commercial
activities, the business representatives reaffirmed their intention to follow
through on the commercial ventures reached here and to explore new opportunities
to expand trade and investment in the region. On the part of government,
the officials attending the Summit declared their intention to support the
activities of the private sector, most particularly by getting the new institutions
established in Amman up and running as soon as possible. The participants
also welcomed the measures taken by regional parties to open their economies
and join the global economy. <BR>
<BR>
To continue such a process whose blueprint and institutions have been established
here, in Amman today, two brotherly countries announced their interest to
host the next session of the MENA Summit. They are Qatar and Egypt. <BR>
<BR>
His Majesty King Hussein conducted the necessary consultations with the
distinguished representatives of the two brotherly states, as well as with
other interested parties. He gladly announced that Qatar has graciously
conceded its offer to host the next summit in favour of Egypt, who will
host it. And it has been agreed by all, including Jordan, the present host,
as well as Egypt and others, that Qatar will be the venue of the Middle
East/North Africa Economic Summit in 1997. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The Business Interactive Group</B> <BR>
<BR>
The Middle East/North Africa Economic Summit in Amman launches one of the
world's most crucial regions on the path towards sustained economic development.
It also testifies to the region's determination to claim its place in the
global village by speaking with deeds rather than with words. The international
business community welcomes the fact that the Summit created regional institutions
to foster economic cooperation and develop and exploit the region's vast
business opportunities. By doing so, it sends a strong message: &quot;The
Middle East is opening up for business.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Yet, recognising that peace is good for business is not sufficient to attract
the foreign investment needed to rebuild and restructure the Middle East
and North Africa. Governments must also demonstrate that they realise that
business is good for peace. They must do so quickly if they wish to compete
with other regions of the world. To achieve this, governments must ensure
political stability and create an environment conducive to business in which
foreign investors feel both welcome and secure. This requires seemingly
simple demands, which in practice could involve radical change. <BR>
<BR>
Politically, Middle Eastern and North African governments must <BR>
<BR>
* project themselves as a cohesive unit eager to compete with other emerging
markets of the world <BR>
<BR>
* eliminate all restrictions on trade including the Arab boycott of Israel
<BR>
<BR>
* develop regional networks backed by sovereign guarantees in areas such
as petroleum pipelines, electricity generation and distribution, communications,
tourism and water <BR>
<BR>
* create mechanisms to shield business from political risk <BR>
<BR>
* foster broad acceptance of a free-market mentality, which views profit-making
as a virtue. <BR>
<BR>
To attract foreign investment, governments must also demonstrate that they
endorse the principles of good government and the rule of law. They can
do so by <BR>
<BR>
* stamping out corruption - a factor influencing business investment
decisions worldwide <BR>
<BR>
* enforcing universally sound and fair business ethics and practices <BR>
<BR>
* streamlining government to become cost efficient and customer oriented
<BR>
<BR>
* adopting transparency and accountability as the guiding principles of
their operations <BR>
<BR>
* creating mechanisms for resolving commercial disputes <BR>
<BR>
* promoting management as a professional skill <BR>
<BR>
* developing national and regional marketing and sales skills. <BR>
<BR>
Last but not least, to create an investor-friendly climate, governments
must <BR>
<BR>
* lift all controls from prices to foreign exchange to interest rates <BR>
<BR>
* lift all restrictions on foreign ownership <BR>
<BR>
* adopt international standards <BR>
<BR>
* introduce stable and well-defined monetary policies <BR>
<BR>
* accelerate privatisation and ensure broad-based public participation.
<BR>
<BR>
<HR>
<H4>FUTURE MEETINGS<BR>
1996 <BR>
Special Trip to the Greater Mekong Region </H4>
<B>(Hanoi, Phnom Penh, Yangon) 31 March-5 April <BR>
Industry Summit  <BR>
Chicago 12-15 May  <BR>
Southern Africa Economic Summit  <BR>
Cape Town 22-24 May  <BR>
Mercosur Economic Summit  <BR>
Buenos Aires 23-25 June  <BR>
Central/Eastern Europe Economic Summit  <BR>
7-9 July  <BR>
China Economic Summit  <BR>
Beijing 23-25 September <BR>
Europe/East Asia Economic Summit  <BR>
Hong Kong 18-20 November <BR>
India Economic Summit  <BR>
27-29 October <BR>
1996 Industry Summit </B> <BR><BR>
The Industry Summit is the World Economic Forum's on-campus gathering of
Global Growth Companies and Foundation Members to tap the world's foremost
business knowledge and intelligence on industry, management and technology
issues hosted by the University of Chicago in collaboration with Northwestern
University and the Chicago Council on Foreign Relations. <BR>
<BR>
Senior executives from the world's most distinctive and innovative companies
will be present in Chicago, allowing an extraordinary occasion to network
at the highest level. Plenary sessions of the 1996 Summit will deal with
the main driving forces affecting industry and technology and set the framework
through which business leaders can gain new perspectives on current challenges.
Thematic sessions will draw upon the richness of the outstanding ideas of
the host and collaborating universities, concentrating on high interaction
and direct exchange of ideas and perspectives with and among participants.
Taking advantage of the Chicago venue, visits of various sites linked to
sectors covered in the Summit will be included. Focused, in-depth peer discussions
on specific industries will also be featured. 
<H4>Special Trip to the Greater Mekong Region </H4>
<B>31 March-5 April 1996 </B>
The World Economic Forum's second trip to the Greater Mekong Region will
begin in Hanoi where participants will be able to assess the progress achieved
towards a greater integration of Vietnam in the region, the economic situation
and business climate of the country and the implementation of some of the
ambitious infrastructure projects involving two or more countries of the
region. <BR>
<BR>
Participants will then travel to Phnom Penh to discuss the latest reforms
in Cambodia and the economic policies put in place by the government in
order to move towards a market oriented economy and encourage foreign investors
to join the country's efforts to upgrade its industries and introduce needed
technology. The final stop will be in Yangon, which will be our second visit
to Myanmar, where we will investigate the progress achieved towards a more
open and less regulated economy. With members of the government and the
business community we will explore opportunities for investors looking at
the objectives and priorities of the government to improve the business
environment and encourage foreign investors to identify partners and areas
for cooperation. 
<H4>1995 Southern Africa Economic Summit </H4>
<B>Cape Town 22-24 May </B>
Once again we will meet with Southern Africa's political and business leadership
for in-depth private discussions to investigate concrete business opportunities
and to further strengthen the public/private sector partnership that is
vital for carrying the region towards growth and stability. Participants
will gain firsthand knowledge of what can be expected in terms of reforms,
privatisation and regional integration. <BR>
<BR>
Last year participants made a series of concrete recommendations necessary
to build a strong and vibrant economy to Southern Africa's government leaders.
In 1996 chief executives and senior board members from around the world
will evaluate what progress has been achieved since last year in these areas.
The leaders of the relevant international and regional organisations will
also join us to contribute to our business-driven programme. <BR>
<BR>
Although we will look at policy issues facing the region, the backbone of
our programme will be to match Southern African business leaders with their
international counterparts. Heavy emphasis will also be placed on presenting
concrete projects open for investment in both national and regional dimensions.
<H3></H3>
<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

