<HEAD>
<TITLE>
EMWL: World Link Magazine:January/February 1996
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="7C1568" text="000000" link="7C1568">

<center>
<font size=3>
<table border=0>
<tr>
<td colspan=2 align=left>
<nobr>
<img width=199 height=44 name="top" border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../images/conban8.gif" alt="World Link Magazine"><a href="../../../../../index.html"><img width=141 height=45 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../../images/conban1.gif" alt="EMWL Home"></a>
</nobr>
<br>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<h2>
January/February 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>
<H3>TECHNOLOGY</H3> 

<H2>Sleep and be merry </H2>
<H4>Sleep is now recognised as essential for a healthy and efficient life,
but macho preconceptions still exist </H4>
<I>By Andrew Clark </I><BR>
<BR>
The world record-holder for wakefulness, a 17-year-old student from San
Diego, lasted 11 days before succumbing to slumber. During this time he
experienced blurred vision, confusion about his identity, memory lapses,
irritability and the odd hallucination. Happily, he suffered no long-term
effects from the experiment. <BR>
<BR>
Many of us would no doubt prefer to sleep for 11 days than to challenge
this masochistic record. For most of us, tiredness is an all-too-familiar
feeling. In the morning, you feel heavy-limbed and your head aches. Later
in the day your eyelids itch and start to burn and you have to fight to
keep them open. Work suddenly seems far more complicated and far less interesting.
A common reaction is to grab a coffee. You may catch up on your sleep debt
at the weekend or ride the storm until a less hectic period arrives. <BR>
<BR>
For many working people, tiredness is a chronic condition. Working hours
are inexorably increasing, as firms lay off workers to become more efficient.
According to the American Management Association, days lasting 13 or 14
hours are not uncommon. Add to this any sort of social life and sleep goes
out of the window. Around 58% of Americans grab on average less than seven
hours' sleep per night and this pattern is mirrored around the world. Robert
Farney, of the Intermountain Sleep Disorders Centre in Salt Lake City, is
worried. He stresses that between seven and eight hours' sleep per night
is optimal: &quot;We tend to be a sleep-deprived, caffeine-driven society.
When we cut something out, we cut out sleep.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
We are all aware that insufficient sleep can impair our alertness, affecting
our work capacity and often making us moody. Now some researchers suspect
that long-term physical health problems can result. There is little doubt
that heart disease is more common among overworked and under-rested executives
but whether this is down to sleep deficiency is uncertain. Recent research
has involved keeping rats awake around the clock to observe the effect on
their bodies. Exhausted and emaciated, they all died within a month, showing
similar symptoms to patients suffering from Aids and cancer. <BR>
<BR>
So could this happen to you? James Kiley, director of the Washington-based
National Centre on Sleep Disorders Research, says sleep is like any other
vital bodily function. &quot;If you don't eat or don't drink, eventually
there will be a collapse of your body organs: you can't do without it.&quot;
Sleep deprivation, he says, causes a breakdown in the immune system and
severely aggravates any existing disease present in the body. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Sleep theories on the brain </B><BR>
<BR>
James Horn, professor and director of the sleep research centre at Loughborough
University, is sceptical about the evidence for this. He points out that
it is less than common for people to go without sleep for a month like the
experimental rats. Given the degree of sleep deprivation even the most over-worked
individual may experience, he says, &quot;there is no evidence that sleep
deprivation causes problems with any body function from the neck down. The
only effect is on the brain.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Horn is adamant that the dangers of tiredness lie in the stress surrounding
hectic lifestyles. He maintains that the health risk of overwork depends
on the individuals' attitudes to their jobs. &quot;A 12-hour day is silly
but it depends on the job. There are times when work can be very relaxing.
If you're on top of your work and enjoying it, it's not stressful.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
The Californian adolescent referred to earlier noticed that the effects
of his sleep deprivation occurred cyclically: many of the worst hallucinations
occurred in the early morning. This indicates the importance of circadian
rhythms, which make up the body's biological clock of rest and wakefulness.
Disruption of these rhythms takes time to get used to. When flying across
time zones, the body becomes unhappy and disorientated. Similarly, shift
workers experience a time-lag as they attempt to change their sleeping patterns
to adjust to different shifts. According to Simon Folkard, professor of
psychology at Swansea University, the body takes up to a week to adjust
even to the one-hour change in clocks at the start and end of British Summer
Time. The clocks go back on a Sunday morning and people find themselves
waking early until the following Thursday. Just one hour less sleep than
usual has a detrimental effect on productivity the next day. <BR>
<BR>
The body's circadian rhythms are affected by light and temperature. Bright
light is helpful in keeping people awake at night. According to a recent
article in <I>Sleep</I>, the industry's own magazine, shift-workers make
fewer mistakes and can be more productive in very well-lit environments.
Apparently, the darker the environment the more the brain secretes a hormone
called melatonin, which causes drowsiness. Melatonin capsules have become
the latest fashion in some circles, used by jetlagged travellers or shift
workers to help them sleep at convenient times. Caroline Evans of the British
Airline Pilots Association (Balpa) is dubious about melatonin, pointing
out that frequent travellers could end up in hooked on the drug: &quot;It
would pose difficulties for medical checks,&quot; she adds. Loughborough's
Horn adds that melatonin may interfere with the menstrual cycle and cautions
against its use for women of reproductive age. <BR>
<BR>
As far as the relief of jet lag is concerned, Folkard is unsympathetic.
&quot;Businessmen bring it upon themselves,&quot; he observes. &quot;They
should fly less frequently.&quot; He consents to offer a few more helpful
tips, however. Instead of watching films and eating throughout the flight,
passengers should adjust their watches to the new time zone as soon as they
board the plane and get used to sleeping at appropriate times. By doing
this, they shorten the period of disorientation on arrival. He adds that
alcohol should be avoided during flights, since it contributes to the body's
dehydration in the pressurised cabin. <BR>
<BR>
Pilots on some airlines are now permitted to take scheduled naps during
long-haul flights, although Balpa stresses that this is only appropriate
if at least two other crew members are awake to man the controls. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Pros and cons of naps </B><BR>
<BR>
The idea of power-napping has also caught on in business, as a brief afternoon
snooze can help to recharge the batteries. According to Folkard, however,
&quot;Naps can be disastrous&quot;. Particularly during the night, waking
up from a nap can take up to an hour, leaving you far more tired than you
were before. Folkard recommends that naps should be limited to 20 or so
minutes and says they are most beneficial in the early afternoon. Beyond
this, sleep becomes deeper and harder to recover from. <BR>
<BR>
Around eight hours after getting up, the body's circadian rhythms reach
a low point, Farney explains: &quot;There is a dip in alertness from about
two to four o'clock, as well as at night, when we want to sleep.&quot; So
the siesta, often thought to be merely an escape from the hottest part of
the afternoon, does have a biological base. The lull also reduces the body's
defences against alcohol, which is why a drink often seems more potent at
lunchtime. But Folkard plays down the significance of this lull: &quot;It's
only a problem if people are in a boring, monotonous situation - then they
may feel drowsy.&quot; He stresses that someone who is stimulated by his
or her work should not notice the afternoon lull. It is significant, however,
that the incidence of road accidents during this period is particularly
high, as bleary-eyed drivers lose concentration. <BR>
<BR>
The cost of sleepiness in both economic and human terms is huge. A recent
calculation by Damien Leger in the sleep unit at the Hotel Dieu hospital
in Paris concluded that 24,318 deaths in the US and nearly 2 million disabling
injuries were caused every year by sleep-related accidents and puts the
economic cost of them at $43.15 billion. Catastrophes such as Three Mile
Island, Chernobyl and the explosion of the space shuttle too have been traced
to mistakes made early in the morning by individuals at the end of long
shifts. So insomnia and other sleep disorders should not be dismissed lightly.
<BR>
<BR>
For those who have trouble sleeping, a number of factors may help. Insomniacs
should avoid exercise just before bed - a stretch in the afternoon is much
less disruptive to circadian rhythms. Also to be avoided are meals late
in the evening: a snack should not affect sleep, but large quantities of
food may do so. Some research has found that foods rich in carbohydrates
can help with sleep, though high-fat food hinders it. Adjusting the room
temperature can also help - a warmer environment is more conducive to sleep.
The ideal temperature is around 16-19&#154;C, or warmer for those who sleep
naked. Folkard points out that hospitals generally keep wards at a constant
temperature, which does not help patients trying to sleep. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Peace of mind is most important </B><BR>
<BR>
As far as noise is concerned, anyone can get used to falling asleep in a
regularly noisy environment but the quality often suffers, as it disrupts
the body's cycle of deep and lighter sleep. <BR>
<BR>
But to Horn all this is irrelevant. &quot;Forget all this mumbo-jumbo,&quot;
he counsels. &quot;The important thing is peace of mind.&quot; Horn suggests
insomniacs should do something distracting before bed: &quot;Feed the cat
or walk round the block&quot;. If after 10 minutes sleep fails to arrive,
leave the room and do something else to take your mind off things. He advises
that the bedroom should be a place of tranquillity, separate from daytime
activity. If possible, work in a different room, do not have a TV in the
bedroom and reserve it for sleep alone. <BR>
<BR>
Gradually, sleep is being recognised as a vital component of a healthy life.
In Britain a campaign has been launched with the message &quot;Sleepiness
can kill&quot;, in response to concerns about over-worked drivers falling
asleep at the wheel. In the US, a recent survey found that 31% of people
feel that sleeplessness has affected how they do their jobs. The survey
was carried out by the Better Sleep Council, an organisation funded by the
mattress industry which hopes to &quot;produce an environment conducive
to sleep&quot;. The survey also found that one in five people had called
in sick or been late for work because of poor sleep. But most employers
are still unsympathetic. Kiley comments: &quot;There is a low level of awareness
about sleep disorders in many segments of society.&quot; Chin Chu Morley
of the Council points out that it is more fashionable to brag &quot;I was
so busy, I only got three hours sleep&quot; than &quot;I slept soundly for
nine hours last night&quot;. <p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
