<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>
<H3>TIME OUT</H3> 

<H2>Holidays in hell </H2>
<H4>The thrill of political tourism puts pay to the idea that all modern
tourists are sun-soaked ignoramuses </H4>
<I>By Francis Harris </I><BR>
<BR>
Soon after the war began in Bosnia, a Japanese tour party landed at Belgrade
airport and was placed aboard a bus. The driver absentmindedly (and drunkenly)
drove off, paying little attention to the roads or his ultimate destination.
<BR>
<BR>
Some hours later the party was halted at a mountain roadblock. Armed men
approached the vehicle. Where did the driver think he was going, they asked?
&quot;Belgrade&quot;, the man said. Informed that he was about to enter
the besieged city of Sarajevo, then under artillery bombardment, the bus
reversed back up the road with a still-ignorant complement of tourists staring
uncomprehendingly out of the windows. <BR>
<BR>
The story, possibly apocryphal, is said to have caused hilarity in Sarajevo
at the time, not least among Sarajevans then under fire from Serbian positions
in the hills. The idea that something as alien as a busload of tourists
might have almost entered a city at war was absurd. <BR>
<BR>
Yet the political tourist is a distinct and rare species. At his most extreme
he is an irritation to professional observers, a source of suspicion for
the combatants and a menace to himself. Further from the frontline, the
intrepid lone traveller can also be regarded as a source of <BR>
fascination. Julian Borger of the British daily <I>The</I> <I>Guardian</I>
arrived in Dubrovnik last year in anticipation of a Croatian offensive to
drive the Serbs beyond artillery range of the beautiful old Venetian city.
Borger heard a rumour that the city still contained a foreign visitor. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Dubrovnik's tourist,&quot; he wrote, &quot;was proving so elusive
that sceptics were starting to question his existence. A lot of local people
claimed to have spotted him - at the hotel reception, at the travel agency,
in the old town's single functioning caf&eacute; - but on each occasion
he seemed to have vanished into the pale antique stone of the empty streets.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
When Borger finally tracked the solitary tourist down he discovered Matthias
Jung, a 32 year-old Hannover shopkeeper who had decided to see the Balkans
for himself. &quot;You read so much about ex-Yugoslavia, but somehow the
journalists - I don't want to be rude - never give the sense of what a place
is really like.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>Some people can't resist taking risks </B><BR>
<BR>
Peter Green, a <I>Newsweek</I> reporter with extensive experience in the
Balkans and central Europe, found others of a similar bent during the siege
of Sarajevo: &quot;There were tourists there during the war. Not that they
called themselves tourists. They didn't wear Reeboks or walk around with
guidebooks in their hands. They tended to be people who got journalistic
accreditation from dubious organisations like rock music magazines or politically
motivated aid groups from the lunatic extremes.&quot; A number were killed,
including two youngsters who ran over a road mine near Mostar in Bosnia.
&quot;Some people just can't resist going to a part of the world everyone's
talking about, whatever the risks.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Whatever questions might be asked about the sanity of these people, they
do give the lie to the idea that all modern tourists are sun-soaked ignoramuses.
For at the end of the 20th century it seems that the only widely available
experience of international travel offers transport in motorised metal boxes
and jet-propelled cigar tubes whooshing victims from one sanitised and banal
architecturally cloned destination to another. In this world, local colour
is limited to the noisy, the incomprehensible and the unthreatening. <BR>
<BR>
Reporters who arrived in Yugoslavia as war erupted in June 1991 remember
the fleeing western tourists whose main thoughts at the beginning of Europe's
nastiest conflict in 50 years were directed at those powers thoughtless
enough to have disturbed their long-planned break. Herr Jung in Dubrovnik
is the exception rather than the rule. <BR>
<BR>
Tourists who find themselves in tricky situations (<I>pace</I> Yugoslavia)
generally choose flight. Denied this option, they are forced to make the
most of it. During one of a series of coups in the Seychelles, with the
airport shut and hotel staff trapped at home by the fighting, western tourists
had to muck-in. An Englishman interviewed by the BBC said the various nationalities
had taken tasks according to inborn ability. The French occupied the kitchens,
the Swiss were running the switchboard and the Germans were in charge of
cleaning. What about the English, the interviewer asked? &quot;Oh we're
overseeing everyone else,&quot; the man said. <BR>
<BR>
The number of people seeking out conflict is limited and as a result, organised
tours for explicitly political holidays are rather uncommon. This is the
antithesis of mass market tourism. But it does exist: it always has. <BR>
<BR>
British schoolboys are taught that the first modern company to develop mass
tourism, Thomas Cook, enlivened early tours to post-siege Paris in 1871
by lighting fires amid the rubble and telling tourists that they were still
smouldering from the conflict. <BR>
<BR>
Thomas Cook's own <I>Excursionist and Tourist Advertiser</I> did not allude
to the fires but acknowledged that its tours to a war-torn city had provoked
complaints in the French National Assembly. A certain Count Joubert seemed
to have suggested Cook's tourists hoped to witness the misery and ruins
of Paris. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;It is most satisfactory to find such unfriendly sentiments indignantly
repudiated by M. Jules Favre,&quot; the <I>Advertiser</I> reported in July
1871. &quot;He pointedly told Count Joubert that no one had the right to
give that meaning to the visits of the English people, for those Excursionist
trains had been preceded by enormous trains of provisions for the revictualling
of Paris.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The paper then allowed itself a brief editorial: &quot;We grieve to think
that even men like Count Joubert should misunderstand the feelings which
sway so many of our Tourists. They visit Paris... to make themselves fully
acquainted with the true character and results of recent events. We firmly
believe that such visits are welcome to the Parisians and that they materially
assist the cause of international friendship and peace.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Revisiting this argument at the end of the 20th century is a curious experience.
Mass tourism is now often regarded as a cure-all, a fast-track path to development
for regions like the Middle East where the fruits of peace need to grow
fast. <BR>
<BR>
Israel and the territories it has occupied since the 1967 war have provided
one of the best areas for political tourism. Just before the <I>intifada</I>
began in the mid-80s, a firm called Diplomatic Services organised tours
to peer under the surface of everyday life, with an itinerary including
meetings with Arab politicians and journalists in Bethlehem, Jewish settlers
on the West Bank and security officials. Other trips included a view of
Jerusalem and its problems and a trip to the frontiers with Syria and Lebanon.
Of course the trips were rather one-sided, being run by an Israeli company.
<BR>
<BR>
South Africa too has spawned its fair share of political tours since the
introduction of multiracial rule. Alec Russell, a <I>Daily Telegraph</I>
reporter, joined a party of white foreigners heading for Soweto. &quot;No
one would admit to being worried... but as our minibus wound through downtown
Johannesburg, conversation grew stilted,&quot; he wrote. <BR>
<BR>
The travel firm, Jimmy's Face to Face Tours, takes parties around the township.
Although much time is spent on the bus, they are taken into a corrugated
iron drinking shack known by the Gaelic name <I>shebeen</I> and given Castle
lager. Most time in the field is spent in Soweto's wealthy areas, perhaps
because of an occasion when a bus was held up. That time, Russell told <I>World
Link</I>, the tourists only avoided robbery because the driver persuaded
the thief to leave without booty. The drive ends back at one of Johannesburg's
ritzier hotels as the tourists heave a sigh of relief. The tour is usually
judged a success. <BR>
<BR>
<B>No one admitted to being worried </B><BR>
<BR>
Bus tours through the battlefields of recent conflicts have also proved
popular in the northern hemisphere. Ulsterbus has used the ceasefire to
run regular tours past the unofficial war memorials and murals of Catholic
west Belfast and the Protestant east: the Bobby Sands mural and the loyalists
Freedom Corner are among the sights. <BR>
<BR>
A different type of visit is available in the towns of northern Pakistan
and the Russian Far East, where tourists can now spend time in the company
of the once-feared Red Army. According to a local English-language paper,
<I>The Vladivostock News</I>, soldiers offer tourists a range of weapon
practice at a price, including $60 to fire a rocket-propelled grenade, $18
for a clip of pistol ammunition and $1,440 for the joy of firing an anti-tank
missile. The trade is clearly lucrative for the troops, who reportedly gave
false names. <BR>
<BR>
Sadly, political tourism is likely to remain a minority pursuit. Life may
become ever more anodyne, but that seems merely to make most people more
cautious. Like the bus driver at Belgrade airport, most tourists are likely
to confront the world of bloody reality through accident rather than design.
<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
