<HEAD>
<TITLE>
EMWL: World Link Magazine:January/February 1996
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="7C1568" text="000000" link="7C1568">

<center>
<font size=3>
<table border=0>
<tr>
<td colspan=2 align=left>
<nobr>
<img width=199 height=44 name="top" border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../images/conban8.gif" alt="World Link Magazine"><a href="../../../../../index.html"><img width=141 height=45 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../../images/conban1.gif" alt="EMWL Home"></a>
</nobr>
<br>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<h2>
January/February 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 
<H3>BACKSEAT</H3>
<H4>Charles Darwent on why elephant 'planes, Bum crisps and Pschitt soda
don't have global appeal </H4>
Though it causes me a certain embarrassment to admit it, I have just spent
several minutes laughing helplessly at an empty packet of Spanish potato
crisps. It was not the emptiness of the packet that caused this mirth, nor
yet its Iberian origins. No, the object's amusement value lay in the brand
name emblazoned in large, yellow letters: the single, sonorous word, <I>&#161;Bum!</I>.
<BR>
<BR>
To non-Spanish speakers among you, &quot;bum&quot; is an onomatopoeia most
equivalent in force to the English word &quot;bang&quot;. The mystery of
why anybody should want to name a potato crisp Bang may be explained by
the circumstances under which the packet in question came to be transformed
into the desirable collectors' item it now is. <BR>
<BR>
By chance, the outgoing prime minister of Sweden chose to pass his holidays
this summer in the very same Spanish village to which Backseat's bronzed
stormtroopers had repaired. Whenever the unfortunate premier and his jittery
entourage attempted to stroll past the local bar in unconvincing incognito,
naughty Spanish youths inflated these crisp packets and burst them with
a report as of small arms fire. I do not know what &quot;bum&quot; means
in Swedish, but the effect on Ingvar Carlsson and his security men was clearly
distressing whatever it may be. <BR>
<BR>
It is presumably not the explosive quality of its packaging that has prevented
<I>&#161;Bum!</I> from taking the lucrative markets of the Anglophone world
by storm, however. Along with a Dutch coffee called &quot;Bonker&quot; and
a French soft drink with the memorable name of &quot;Pschitt&quot; - all
borne triumphantly home from foreign holidays past - the Spanish savoury
snack provides an object lesson in the corporate dangers of multilingualism.
When Our Lord punished the people of Babel for their unfortunate taste in
skyscraper-building, He would seem to have had His eye fixed most vengefully
not (as might have seemed logical) on the city's architects, but on its
marketing men. <BR>
<BR>
It is a curse from which even the greatest of their descendants are still
not immune. When, in the early '60s, the makers of a very famous British
motor car indeed chose to christen their latest marque the Silver Mist,
sales figures in Germany plummeted overnight to nil. Troubled executives
were at a loss to explain this unhappy phenomenon until a local agent gently
pointed out that <I>Mist</I> is the German word for dog ordure. Perhaps
understandably, well-heeled Berliners - already bewildered by having a visiting
American president tell them they should be proud to be doughnuts - found
the attractions of being chauffeured around in a vehicle apparently named
for an excretory function of the canine body all too easy to pass up. The
car's German name was swiftly - if expensively - changed. <BR>
<BR>
You might think that the world of automotive branding would have taken a
long, hard look at this baptismal <I>grand guignol</I> and mended its ways
accordingly. But no. Consider, if you will, the names chosen by Japanese
car manufacturers for their export products. <BR>
<BR>
It may be that the word &quot;Civic&quot;, say, suggests all sorts of desirable
qualities to the socially minded Tokyo motorist such as courtesy and immunity
from the fashionable road rage that seems to grip his Occidental brother.
When preceded by the word &quot;Honda&quot;, however, it hardly seems likely
to set the automotive pulses racing in quite the way that &quot;Testarossa&quot;
or &quot;Thunderbird&quot; might have done. &quot;Cherry&quot; (as in Nissan)
also appears a touch lacking in that hormonal belly-fire that allegedly
sells cars in the west, even if its suggestion of trembling blossom is intended
to call the haiku of Kobayashi Issa to the presumably more poetic mind of
the Japanese motorist. <BR>
<BR>
The only other possible explanation for the branding policy of Japan's car
manufacturers is that they sit around boardroom tables in Greater Okinawa
jabbing randomly at the pages of the Shorter Oxford English Dictionary with
a pin. If so, then we may in time presumably expect to see the Toyota Zeugma
and Datsun Nappy taking triumphantly to the road. <BR>
<BR>
Quite how this linguistic minefield is to be navigated is a matter for sober
thought. The admirably polyglot Emperor Charles V may have remarked that
he spoke Spanish to God, Italian to women, French to men and German to horses:
but what would he have spoken to his marketing department? <BR>
<BR>
The sad fact is that some languages are simply better for saying certain
things than are others: a truth whose eternal verity is borne out by the
unhappy attempts of the Acad&eacute;mie Fran&ccedil;aise to cleanse perfidious
anglicisms from everyday French. The jauntiness of English makes it good
at coming up with catchy names like &quot;jumbo jet&quot;. The Acad&eacute;mie's
alternative francophone offering - <I>l'avion &eacute;l&eacute;phantin </I>-
may have literality on its side but would you stand under one? <BR>
<BR>
There have, of course, been numerous attempts to reverse the one-nil score
at Babel by creating a universal language, most notably in the 120-year-old
form of Ludwik Zamenhof's Esperanto. That this renders the phrase &quot;I
love you&quot; as <I>mi amas vin</I> may go some way to explaining its abiding
lack of popularity with marketing departments, however. <BR>
<BR>
Understandably enough, therefore, new software programs that promise to
translate one's native tongue into nasty foreign languages at the press
of a button have recently been fallen upon by monoglot marketeers with brimming
tears of gratitude. <BR>
<BR>
They may be in for disappointment. A lexicographer friend tells me that
an Anglo-French example with which she was recently toying happily translated
Elizabeth I's &quot;the spirit is willing but the flesh is weak&quot; as
<I>l'alcool</I> <I>est sain mais la viande est faible</I>. When commanded
to retranslate this phrase back into English, the program scratched its
electromagnetic head for a minute and then smilingly proffered &quot;the
booze is serviceable but the meat is flavourless&quot;. What it might have
done to potato crisps does not bear musing over in the pages of a respectable
magazine. <p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
