<HEAD>
<TITLE>
EMWL: World Link Magazine: July/August 1996
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="7C1568" text="000000" link="7C1568">

<center>
<font size=3>
<table border=0>
<tr>
<td colspan=2 align=left>
<nobr>
<img width=199 height=44 name="top" border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../images/conban8.gif" alt="World Link Magazine"><a href="../../../../../index.html"><img width=141 height=45 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../../images/conban1.gif" alt="EMWL Home"></a>
</nobr>
<br>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<h2>
July/August 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra5.gif" alt="Cover Story">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 



<H3>WHO'S WHO IN EAST AND CENTRAL EUROPE </H3>
<H4>The revolutions in east and central Europe have cleared the way for a new
generation of business people. It is a community that ranges from high-&thorn;iers
too young to remember communism, grabbing their chance, to former Marxists
who have jettisoned their previous ideology in the race to make money and
in&thorn;uence people. Margie Lindsay and Craig Mellow have picked 58 leading
&THORN;gures in 13 countries across the region, a guide to those who have
reached the top and those who plan to join them there </H4>

<H3>ALBANIA </H3>
<H4>PRESIDENT </H4>

Sali Berisha <BR>
<BR>
Ordered to halt anti-communist demonstrations during December 1990, Berisha
joined the protesters and soon after co-founded the Democratic Party (DP)
Albania's first legal independent political entity since 1946. As DP leader
during nationwide general strikes that brought down the last communist government,
he led the party to victory in the March 1992 elections, when it took 63%
of the vote. But this year's poll came under a cloud, with accusations by
some foreign observers of massive ballot-rigging and intimidation by Berisha's
men. Having jailed both his predecessor as president and the head of the
main opposition Socialist Party, Berisha has come under international pressure
for his authoritarian style. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +355 42 823 13</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +355 42 337 61</I> <BR>

<H4>GOVERNOR OF THE CENTRAL BANK OF ALBANIA </H4>

Kristaq Luniku <BR>
<BR>
Luniku, who read economics and finance at Tirana University, took up the
post at the head of the central bank last year at the age of 34. Probably
the country's most able banking specialist since World War II, Luniku oversaw
the dismantling of the communist era's National Bank of Albania and the
subsequent creation of a central bank and three independent commercial banks.
Luniku has worked closely with the World Bank. He also heads the stock exchange.
<BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +355 42 328 14</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +355 42 225 89</I> <BR>

<H4>ECONOMIST </H4>

Gramoz Josef Pashko <BR>
<BR>
Pashko, a former deputy prime minister and Albania's leading economist,
is the eponymous son of one of Albania's most famous communist leaders.
He received a doctorate in economics at Tirana University where he later
lectured and became one of the most radical supporters of economic reform
under the last communist regime. A co-founder of the Democratic Party, he
was deputy prime minister and finance minister in the 1991 coalition. Re-elected
as a DP MP in March 1992, he later broke with Berisha and became a leader
of the Democratic Alliance party. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel/Fax +355 42 323 50</I> <BR>

<H4>MANAGING DIRECTOR OF ADA </H4>

Marsel Skendo <BR>
<BR>
Skendo was Albania's first millionaire businessman. He is managing director
of ADA, the Albanian-French holding company and airline operator, which
has a range of import-export activities. Skendo became one of the most celebrated
prisoners of the post-communist government after being held on remand for
most of 1994 on charges widely regarded as spurious before &THORN;nally
being cleared. Some suggest that his real offence was refusing to pay a
&quot;political levy&quot; to the ruling DP. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +355 42 332 14</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +355 42 230 27</I> <BR>

<H4>CHIEF EXECUTIVE OF THE ALBANIAN STOCK EXCHANGE </H4>

Albina Karamitro <BR>
<BR>
Karamitro is considered one of the country's brightest and most capable
financiers. Unfortunately, the exchange has no stocks to trade yet: just
government treasury bills and securities. Karamitro is one of the few women
in a position of power in post-communist Albania. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +355 42 329 45</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +355 42 225 89</I> 
<BR>
<H3>THE BALTIC STATES </H3>
<H4>PRESIDENT OF HANSABANK </H4>

Hannes Tamj&auml;rv <BR>
<BR>
Exploiting the liberalisation of the final years of the Soviet Union, Tamj&auml;rv
began a small furniture-making enterprise in Estonia. He moved on to create
Hansabank, which quickly became the country's biggest commercial bank. Although
small when compared with its western counterparts, Hansabank is one of the
most successful large companies in the Baltics with interests in the country's
second-biggest commercial bank and a number of other businesses. Tamj&auml;rv,
who holds right-wing political views, has a large influence on Estonia's
economy and economic policy through his ties with the Reform Party/Liberals,
sometimes dubbed the Hansabank Party. He is now expanding operations to
the other two Baltic countries. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +372 6 310 321</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +372 6 310 434</I> <BR>

<H4>DIRECTOR-GENERAL OF ACHEMA  JOINT-STOCK COMPANY </H4>

Bronislovas Lubys <BR>
<BR>
Lubys, 58, is one of Lithuania's wealthiest men with power to match in industry
and politics. His career began at the Azotas nitrogen fertiliser plant,
where he worked as a chief engineer and then director-general. When the
plant was privatised, reorganised and renamed Achema, Lubys also became
an owner. In 1992 he was appointed vice-premier and then prime minister.
As premier, Lubys secured changes in the privatisation law and preferential
rights for company employees to buy shares. After the first presidential
election, he returned to Achema. Now he defends business interests as the
president of the Industrialists' Confederation. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +370 19 56624</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +370 19 56911</I> <BR>

<H4>GOVERNOR OF THE BANK OF LITHUANIA </H4>

Reinoldijus Sarkinas <BR>
<BR>
Sarkinas, 50, was elected head of the Lithuanian central bank in February.
Before that he had served for two years as minister of finance, capping
a 16-year career in the ministry. In political circles Sarkinas has been
praised for his competence, reserved manner and independence. Considered
one of the country's best financial minds, he arrived at the central bank
just after the country's two major commercial banks had closed. Most of
the blame was attributed to Sarkinas's predecessor and the then Lithuanian
premier. But he has been attacked more than once, both for the banking crisis
and an &quot;anti-business&quot; taxation system. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +370 2 224008</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +370 2 628124 <BR>
</I>

<H4>MAYOR OF VENTSPILS </H4>

Aivars Lembergs <BR>
<BR>
Ventspils is Latvia's third-largest city and home to the largest cargo port
in the Baltics. Lembergs, who has been mayor since 1994, is also chairman
of the port board. Lembergs wants to attract local and foreign investment
to modernise the port, although he opposes foreign ownership of transit
enterprises. Instead, he wants to raise money by making the companies public.
Lembergs held a number of senior positions in the Ventspils administration
during the Soviet era and was a member of the Latvian parliament in 1990-1993.
<BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +371 362 2331</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +371 362 2929</I> <BR>

<H4>DIRECTOR-GENERAL OF THE PRIVATISATION AGENCY </H4>

Janis Naglis <BR>
<BR>
Two years ago Naglis became the first head of Latvia's privatisation agency
and gave it some momentum. He advocates granting privatisation rights by
putting firms out to tender. A graduate of the Riga Polytechnical Institute,
he is a member of the right-wing Latvia's Way party. He gets on well with
the prime minister and is a strong influence in the government. His foreign
languages are English and Russian. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +371 732 85 33</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +371 783 03 63</I> <BR>

<H4>DIRECTOR-GENERAL OF N-TERMINAAL </H4>

Endel Siff <BR>
<BR>
Dubbed an &quot;Oil king of Estonia&quot; and said be one of the richest
people in the country, Endel Siff runs the biggest private oil company in
the Baltics. His company, N-Terminaal, ships Russian oil through Estonia
to western ports. Siff is one of the three main shareholders of N-Terminaal,
which had a $35 million turnover last year. This performance earned Siff
almost $1 million in dividends. Educated as a mechanical engineer, he had
a quiet career during the Soviet era. In 1988 he joined the successful state-owned
trading company Estimpex, where he learned the international oil trade.
When Estonia regained its independence in 1991 he launched the firm, which
quickly and quietly became the biggest private oil company of Estonia. Siff
makes few appearances in public. His company's main interest seems to be
to achieve and maintain good Estonian-Russian relations, an elusive goal
since independence. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +372 6 503 500</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +372 6 503 501</I> <BR>

<H4>DIRECTOR OF THE LATVIAN SHIPPING COMPANY </H4>

Peteris Avotins <BR>
<BR>
Avotins graduated from the Kaliningrad-based Fish Production Institute in
Russia and gradually rose through the ranks of his profession. Since 1991,
he has run the state-owned Latvian Shipping Company (LSC), which is slated
for privatisation. With equity capital of about $500 million, LSC is reported
to be the company with the largest equity base in Latvia and it has wide
international links. Recently the firm ordered gas tankers worth hundreds
of millions of dollars from South Korea. Avotins has kept his job despite
changes of government. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel: +371 232 94 20</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax: +371 722 32 40</I> <BR>

<H4>PRESIDENT OF PAREX BANK </H4>

Valery Kargin <BR>
<BR>
A journalist by education, Kargin graduated from the Latvian State University
and during the Soviet times led a number of Komsomol (Young Communist) organisations
in Riga. With the advent of Mikhail Gorbachev's <I>perestroika</I> Kargin
founded a number of businesses, ranging from a tourist agency to a network
of currency exchange offices. The success of the latter laid the basis for
the creation of Parex bank in 1992. Parex gradually developed from a medium-sized
company to one of the two leading banks in Latvia, although it is still
small by western standards. Last year the bank had equity capital of about
$28 million, assets of $205 million and a profit of $14 million. It is strongly
geared towards the markets of the former Soviet Union, attracting money
from Russia as well as press allegations of money-laundering: the bank's
television advertisement in Russia featured a boy bringing his piggybank
to the counter with the slogan, &quot;We won't tell even your mother&quot;.
Kargin is deeply involved in Latvian politics and has provided financial
support to all the main political forces in the country, although he has
particularly strong ties with the governing Saimnieks party. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel: +371 701 02 11</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax: +371 701 04 00</I> 

<BR>
<H3>BULGARIA </H3>
<H4>FORMER PRIME MINISTER </H4>

Andrei Lukanov <BR>
<BR>
Andrei Lukanov entered the Bulgarian government in 1972 as deputy prime
minister. He was Bulgaria's first prime minister to take office after the
democratic changes in 1989 and gained international notoriety in 1990 by
declaring a debt repayment moratorium. In May last year, Lukanov left politics
for business. As a supervisory committee member of Top Energy Gas, a Bulgarian-Russian
joint venture, he aims to provide services for the transit of Russian gas
into western Europe through Bulgaria. Government approval for the venture
should be smoothed by the 58-year-old's political connections. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +35 92 8501 (ask for Socialist Party office)</I> <BR>

<H4>PRESIDENT OF MULTIGROUP </H4>

Ilia Pavlov <BR>
<BR>
Multigroup, run by this stocky, 36-year-old former wrestler, is one of the
richest companies in Bulgaria: it paid taxes of more than $5 million last
year. A graduate of the National Sports Academy, Pavlov is seen as an influential
but fearsome personality. In 1988, with the help of some military officials
and finance from Turkish businessmen, he established a business scrapping
Russian submarines in Malta. With the profits he formed Multigroup, a holding
company now comprised of more than 25 members, which trades in petroleum,
gas and metals and has the monopoly on gambling in Bulgaria, generating
a turnover of $1.5 billion last year. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +35 92 810 014</I> <BR>

<H4>PRESIDENT OF HARSEV &amp; CO, CONSULTANTS </H4>

Emil Harsev <BR>
<BR>
Harsev, 35, has devoted his life to business. Low-key but strong-minded,
at the age of 29 Harsev was named chief of the foreign exchange supervision
department at the Bulgarian National Bank, becoming the youngest-ever vice-governor.
After three years at the top, he began to criticise the bank and was effectively
booted out. After his dismissal, he formed a private consultancy company
specialising in auditing. His economic commentaries are broadcast weekly
on Bulgaria's most popular political and economic programme, Observer, which
helps to bolster his reputation as an imaginative thinker. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +35 92 805 003/313</I> <BR>

<H4>CHAIRMAN OF MOLLOV COMMERCIAL BANK </H4>

Valentin Mollov <BR>
<BR>
Mollov, a graduate of the Sofia Police Academy, is an affable and keen businessman.
In 1990 he founded the Union for Private Enterprises, the first organisation
committed to protecting small businesses. The union now has more than 1,000
members and Mollov represents company managers in labour-employee negotiations.
The most successful of his many ventures is Mollov Commercial Bank. He also
owns an investment and a real estate company, a spirit distillery and has
interests in the oil business. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +35 92 682 072</I> <BR>

<H4>BULGARIAN NATIONAL BANK GOVERNOR </H4>

Lubomir Filipov <BR>
<BR>
The tenacious 51-year-old mathematician was elected governor of the National
Bank in December after working there 20 years. Now charged with reforming
the crisis-stricken banking sector, Filipov demonstrated his political independence
by allowing the price of the Leva to fall to just above 100 to the dollar,
despite government efforts to shore up the currency. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +35 92 8551</I> <BR>

<H4>SEGA MAGAZINE EDITOR </H4>

Valery Naidenov <BR>
<BR>
As the son of two respected journalists, Naidenov's career choice was natural.
Now 48, he has been a correspondent in Moscow, a shareholder and partner
in the country's most profitable publishing company, 168 Hours, and editor-in-chief
of its newspaper <I>24 Hours</I>, Bulgaria's largest. Naidenov recently
left the company after he was forced to resign for failing to support the
Socialist Party candidate in local elections. Afterwards, he went to <I>Sega,
</I>Bulgaria's first respectable weekly economic and political news maga-
zine. He now plans to start a daily newspaper. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +35 92 981 2104</I> 

<BR>
<H3>CZECH REPUBLIC </H3>
<H4>CHAIRMAN OF SKODA </H4>

Lubomir Soudek <BR>
<BR>
Newspapers often call 52-year-old Soudek the saviour of Czech industry.
In 1992 this mercurial former Communist Party member presented a plan to
privatise and rescue Skoda, a large state-owned engineering company making
locomotives, machine tools and both conventional and nuclear power stations.
His private company Nero took a 20% stake in the enterprise. Under Soudek
the firm has returned to profitability and the company's reach now makes
Soudek probably the country's most influential industrialist. Fluent in
Russian, he is a workaholic, a teetotaller, rich (his stake in Skoda is
worth about $200 million) and controversial. In 1993 he tried to sell Skoda
nuclear technology to Iran, until western diplomatic pressure halted the
sale. A year later he was reported to be at it again, apparently trying
to export to Iran via Russia. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +42 19 722 3720</I> <BR>

<H4>FOUNDER AND PRESIDENT, HARVARD CAPITAL &amp; CONSULTING </H4>

Viktor Kozeny <BR>
<BR>
In 1991 Kozeny, then aged 27, left the US to return to his native Prague.
He set up Harvard Capital &amp; Consulting and within a year he claims to
have turned his $3,000 investment into $3 million. In 1992, he established
the Harvard group of investment funds. It attracted vouchers under the government's
privatisation scheme, which allowed Kozeny to acquire large stakes in 51
leading Czech and Slovak enterprises, including several big banks. At its
peak, Harvard managed about $1 billion of Czech and Slovak assets. A controversial
figure from the outset, the mystery that surrounds Kozeny deepened in 1993
when secret service agent Vaclav Wallis alleged he had paid him to supply
Harvard with classified commercial information. Kozeny went to the then
interior minister, Petr Cermak, claiming that Wallis was blackmailing him.
Wallis was given a 37-month prison sentence. After testifying at the trial,
Kozeny moved to the Bahamas. Wallis was later freed on appeal. Cermak, an
adviser to the Czech prime minister Vaclav Klaus, has since been hired by
Harvard. Meanwhile Harvard formed an alliance with Michael Dingman, a member
of the board of the Ford motor company and former president of Allied-Signal,
the US industrial conglomerate. Stratton Investments, Dingman's private
company, last year teamed up with Harvard and reportedly paid $250 million
for large, in many cases controlling, stakes in eight big Czech companies.
<BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +42 2 6106 1121</I> <BR>

<H4>CHAIRMAN AND CHIEF EXECUTIVE OF CHEMAPOL GROUP </H4>

Vaclav Junek <BR>
<BR>
Junek, 44, is smooth, urbane and fluent in both Russian and English. In
1975, in the hardline comunist days of &quot;normalisation&quot;, he became
a director of Chemapol, the Czech Republic's monopoly importer of Russian
oil and a holding company with large stakes in scores of chemical and pharmaceutical
firms. Since 1992, when voucher privatisation dismantled the country's chemical
and oil industry monopolies, Chemapol has aggressively sought to consolidate
these sectors and it has spent at least $250 million on acquisitions over
the past year. This year the company plans to sell more than $30 million
of stock via the London Stock Exchange. Junek came into the public eye two
years ago, when Chemapol bid unsuccessfully for a 49% stake in the Czech
Republic's two main oil refineries. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +42 2 6715 2115</I> <BR>

<H4>CHAIRMAN AND CHIEF EXECUTIVE OF PATRIA FINANCE </H4>

Zdenek Bakala <BR>
<BR>
Shortly after the revolution of 1989 Bakala, then 35, returned to Prague
from the US to help establish Credit Suisse First Boston's Prague office.
Frustrated by the corporate culture, he left the investment bank in December
1993, taking a handful of colleagues with him. In May 1994 he opened Patria,
the Czech Republic's first home-grown full-service investment banking company.
The company claims to have cornered 20% of trade on the Prague bourse and
is now a leading issuer and dealer of Czech corporate bonds. Patria's corporate
research is held in high regard and its macroeconomic research on the Czech
economy takes a piercing, often critical, look at the state's finances.
Bakala is also a board member of the Prague Stock Exchange. With his wife,
he part-owns several of Prague's swankier restaurants. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +42 2 2424 8770</I> 

<H3>HUNGARY </H3>
<H4>NATIONAL BANK PRESIDENT </H4>

Gyorgy Suranyi <BR>
<BR>
A respected figure in Hungary's business community, Suranyi is the head
of the National Bank, a position he previously held from 1990-91. A former
investment banker and close friend of Lajos Bokros (see separate entry),
Suranyi is seen as an economic reformer. The finance team of Bokros and
Suranyi quickly went from being golden boys to public enemy number one as
Hungarians started to feel the pinch of their spending cuts. Suranyi's reformist
views occasionally land him in hot water, as when he said: &quot;The historic
task of the Socialist government is to roll back the frontiers of the welfare
state.&quot; Suranyi remains wedded to these policies but now keeps his
views to himself. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +36 1 153 1444</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +36 1 112 6858</I> <BR>

<H4>HEAD OF MAGYAR HITEL BANK </H4>

Zsigmond Jarai <BR>
<BR>
Chairman and chief executive of Hungary's second largest commercial bank,
Jarai is a champion of reform and many expected him to succeed Lajos Bokros
when he resigned as finance minister. Open with journalists and well respected
by the world's banking community, Jarai would have been a popular appointment.
However, his apolitical stance appears to have cost him public office. When
he took the helm at Hitel Bank in March last year, his first move was to
trim the bank's inflated staff. Jarai is now turning around the bank's fortunes
by off-loading the non-performing areas and preparing for a sell-off. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +36 1 269 2122</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +36 1 269 2245</I> <BR>

<H4>CHAIRMAN, PHARMAVIT </H4>

Imre Somody <BR>
<BR>
Young, charming and rich, Somody, 37, is already a dollar millionaire and
head of his own company Pharmavit, based in eastern Hungary. His company
was the subject of the first take-over on the Budapest Stock Exchange, a
deal that netted $100 million from the buyers, US pharmaceutical giant Bristol,
Meyers Squib. Somody had held 21% of the shares. He is shrewd and aware
of the market. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +36 27 386 890</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +36 27 385 980</I> <BR>

<H4>FORMER FINANCE MINISTER </H4>

Lajos Bokros <BR>
<BR>
Probably the best-known figure in the country's financial community, Bokros
resigned as finance minister in March.<B> </B>With a background in investment
banking which included a spell in London, Bokros is revered by international
investors. He is a former head of Budapest Bank and a founder of the stock
exchange. He was the first finance minister to attack the social security
system and stimulate growth by raising import duties and devaluing the forint.
These austerity policies made him few friends among the electorate. Despite
his domestic unpopularity, Bokros tried to stay true to his policies. He
was not helped in this task by a severe lack of tact - journalists
described him as brusque and arrogant - and his refusal to explain
his actions to the public generated suspicion. Bokros is out of the limelight
but he is still considered influential. He will likely resurface, probably
in a western investment bank. <BR>

MANAGING DIRECTOR (HUNGARY) OF CREDITANSTALT </H4>

Andras Simor <BR>
<BR>
Bright and technically brilliant, Simor has carved himself an enviable reputation
in Hungary's financial sector for his key role in the major bank and utility
privatisations. Now in his late 30s, Simor is responsible for drawing many
large institutional investors to Hungary. Before he joined Austria's Creditanstalt,
the efficient, affable but cautious Simor was a rising star in the National
Bank. His reputation helps to engender a much-needed feeling of security,
calming potential investors' nerves in what is a fledgling and sometimes
hazardous market. Like Bokros and Jarai, Simor also advocates reducing the
government's intervention the economy. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +36 1 269 0711</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +36 1 269 0699</I>
<BR>
 
<H3>POLAND </H3>
<H4>WIFE OF POLISH PRESIDENT </H4>

Jolanta Kwasniewska <BR>
<BR>
Kwasniewska, 40, is making a new life for herself as the wife of Poland's
new president, Alexander Kwasniewski. Since leaving her successful real-estate
business after Kwasniewski's election last November, she has put her skills
as a lawyer to good use. The links she forged, working first for a small
foreign-owned company in the '80s and later in her own business, will continue
to provide the business community with a conduit to her husband. Kwasniewska
is building an image akin to that of the US president's wife Hillary Clinton,
although her power base is being built on the fledgling affluent middle
classes rather than the have-nots. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +48 22 694 6000 (President's palace)</I> <BR>
<H4>HEAD OF THE WARSAW STOCK EXCHANGE </H4>

Wieslaw Rozlucki <BR>
<BR>
It seems that Rozlucki had been preparing to lead the Warsaw Stock Exchange
his entire life. But it was only in 1990 that he realised that what had
been a hobby could become paid employment. As one of a small group of stock
exchange aficionados, he helped prepare the legislation and framework for
the bourse's creation in April 1991. Since then Rozlucki, who studied at
Warsaw's Central Planning School in the late '60s and earned a doctorate
in geography, has nurtured the market to its present state. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +48 22 628 3232</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +48 22 688 1754</I> <BR>
<H4>CHAIRMAN OF BANK HANDLOWY </H4>

Cezary Stypulkowski <BR>
<BR>
Before heading Poland's oldest bank the youthful Stypulkowski, 39, read
law at Warsaw University. In the '80s he joined the Polish government's
economic reform unit as a junior official. A spell at Columbia's business
school and then a stint at Citibank in New York introduced him to modern
banking techniques. Quietly spoken and with an easy smile, he instinctively
chooses a consensus approach in managing the bank's affairs and defending
its outside interests. His serious manner has won him the respect of his
peers as he works to rebuild Handlowy's pre-war position as a commercial
bank, at the same time taking it into the private sector. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +48 22 300 100</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +48 22 304 835</I> <BR>
<H4>DIRECTOR OF ELEKTRIM </H4>

Andrzej Skowronski <BR>
<BR>
Skowronski, one of Poland's best paid company directors, blazed a trail
when he led his company Elektrim onto the Warsaw Stock Exchange in 1991
- this at a time when the future of this specialist power and telecommunications
foreign trade organisation was uncertain. Skowronski was 40 when he was
appointed to lead the company in 1987 under the old regime. With his eagerness
and determination to succeed, he began to build an industrial conglomerate
around the old state core functions. Skowronski, who represented Elektrim
in Moscow in the '80s and holds a doctorate in economics, has taken the
company into new fields such as food processing, real estate and hotels
and most recently as part of PTK, a mobile telephone operating company.
Elektrim was the first local company to base its funding strategy on sales
and acquisitions on the Warsaw Stock Exchange. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +48 22 302 114</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +48 22 300 841</I> <BR>
<H4>HEAD OF BANK IG </H4>

Boguslaw Kott <BR>
<BR>
Kott, voted banker of the year by Poland's Banking Association, is seeking
to build the country's first private bank into a major local group able
to challenge foreign competitors. Kott, 50, took over a near-bankrupt operation
in Lodz and began a low-cost branch expansion programme. It became the first
bank to receive a Stock Exchange listing. Late last year Kott became the
strategic investor in Bank Gdanski, which is twice as large as Bank IG.
Like many of Poland's leading businessmen, he attended the foreign trade
faculty at Warsaw's Central Planning School and the finance ministry in
the '80s. Bank IG itself was conceived by a group of reforming government
officials. Originally financed with support from state-owned insurance companies
and the telephone operator, Bank IG sought to play down its nomenclature
links under successive Solidarity governments. However, Kott is well placed
to make the most of his old connections now that the former communists are
back at the helm. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +48 22 657 9000</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +48 22 267 180</I> 
<BR>

<H3>ROMANIA </H3>
<H4>PRESIDENT OF GENERAL CONSULTING &amp; PROCUREMENT (GC&amp;P) </H4>

George Constantin Paunescu <BR>
<BR>
Dubbed the Donald Trump of Bucharest, this sombre 58-year-old is possibly
the most powerful man in Romania and almost certainly the richest. He says
his experience abroad in the '70s and as an import-export director in the
Romanian ministry of finance helped him exploit the financial chaos that
followed the 1989 fall of communism. His company GC&amp;P, a holding operation
for countless business interests, recorded a turnover last year well in
excess of $1 billion, a figure that does not include &quot;indirect interests&quot;.
This year alone, he has paid $10 million outright for 31% of Romania's largest
private bank, bought aircraft worth $425 million from Canada and unveiled
plans to build eastern Europe's tallest building in the heart of Bucharest
at a cost of more than $100 million. Paunescu's acquisition last summer
of the Bucharest Intercontinental Hotel with a bid substantially lower than
rival group Marriott International is being investigated for possible fraud.
He is believed to have close links to Romania's ruling party, the Social
Democracy Party (PDSR). <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +40 1 312 3835</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +40 1 312 7557</I> <BR>
<H4>CONTENDER FOR MAYOR OF BUCHAREST </H4>

Ilie Nastase <BR>
<BR>
The world's top-ranked tennis player in 1973, this former scourge of the
establishment has just lost his campaign to become mayor of Bucharest. Although
hitched to the ruling Social Democracy Party (PDSR) Nastase, now 49, ran
on an anti-corruption ticket. He argued that his $20 million fortune made
him less likely to dip into the municipal coffers, thus the campaign nickname
of &quot;Honest Ilie&quot;. Criticised for spending most of his time outside
Romania, Nastase claimed that his 30 years in Paris and New York gave him
a firm grasp of western democracy, but his high-handed style left voters
unimpressed. All the same, many expect him to seek another political post
soon. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +40 1 633 5568</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +40 1 211 0838</I> <BR>
<H4>GOVERNOR, NATIONAL BANK OF ROMANIA </H4>

Mugur Isarescu <BR>
<BR>
Financial crises, corruption scandals, rampant inflation, exchange rate
fiascos and conflicting pressures from the government and the IMF have placed
the chief of the country's central bank in a difficult position. Well-groomed
and urbane, Isarescu is a sharp-minded career economist with a reputation
as a genuinely nice guy. His non-confrontational style, however, belies
a determination to get things done. Isarescu, who was lured back to Romania
in 1990 from a post as an economic adviser in Washington, would have no
trouble securing another job if the heat becomes unbearable. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +40 1 613 0410</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +40 1 312 0787</I> <BR>
<H4>LEADING BUSINESSMAN </H4>

Ion Tiriac <BR>
<BR>
Former tennis champion and one-time coach to Boris Becker, Tiriac has become
immensely successful as a businessman. As well as a 31% stake in his own
private bank, he has large shareholdings in private television station ProTV,
news agency Mediafax and an exclusive Mercedes car dealership, among other
interests. A former doubles partner to Ilie Nastase in the '70s, he established
one of the first private banks after the 1989 revolution, capitalising on
his public popularity by calling it the Ion Tiriac Bank. Admirers of the
good-looking 50-year-old - and there are quite a few - insist
that he has a genuine sense of altruism. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +40 1 613 4858</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +40 1 312 5878</I> 
<H3>RUSSIA </H3>
<H4>PRESIDENT OF UNEXIM BANK </H4>

Vladimir Potanin <BR>
<BR>
Although it opened only three years ago, the United Export-Import Bank (ONEKSIM
Bank in Russian) has become Russia's third biggest house. Potanin and his
team used the old system to reach the top: capital came from hard-currency
industrial exporters and the core of the management team from the defunct
Soviet Vneshekonombank. Potanin, who spent most of the '80s in the foreign
trade ministry, employed an aggressive style that quickly made the bank
into a powerhouse. UNEXIM Bank masterminded the &quot;loans-for-shares&quot;
scheme, under which the state dumped controlling packets of blue-chip enterprises
into the laps of Russian banks for nominal sums late last year. The scheme
was aborted under a cloud of scandal but UNEXIM kept hold of its prizes.
<BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +70 95 208 9008</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +70 95 975 2205</I> <BR>
<H4>CHAIRMAN OF BANK MENATEP </H4>

Mikhail Khodorkovsky <BR>
<BR>
Khodorkovsky was once a college Communist Youth League chairman, but he
joined the business opposition before it became fashionable He formed MENATEP
between 1987-88. As communist power collapsed, the bank pioneered one essential
business practice after another including public stock offerings, television
advertising and foreign exchange bureaux. The MENATEP image, which still
survives, was slick and mysterious. Khodorkovsky saw sooner than others
that &quot;We cannot make miracles without the state.&quot; MENATEP was
the first brat-pack bank to crack the lucrative circle of certified financial
intermediaries for government investment programmes. Khodorkovsky also got
on well with post-Soviet industry, particularly in energy. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +70 95 253 9003</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +70 95 923 5931</I> <BR>
<H4>PRESIDENT OF MOST-BANK </H4>

Vladimir Goussinsky <BR>
<BR>
Goussinsky's last job was as a theatrical director, something that may have
come to mind when his bank security team was raided by masked thugs who
later turned out to be Kremlin guards commanded by Boris Yeltsin's confidante
Alexander Korzhakov. Some people attributed the raid to a shadowy dispute
between the Kremlin and Moscow's Mayor Yuri Luzhkov, who is closely associated
with the bank. Goussinky's team is adept at playing the bond and currency
markets and issuing credit cards. However, most suspect that Luzhkov, who
once reportedly had most of the capital's revenues on deposit at Most-Bank,
is the real source of success. Goussinsky retreated to London after the
December 1994 attack and Luzhkov curbed his criticism of federal authorities.
Luzhkov is likely to progress further up the political ladder, while Goussinsky
has resurfaced as Russia's top press baron as a result of Most-Bank's media
holdings. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +70 95 203 2552</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +70 95 290 9184</I> <BR>
<H4>GENERAL DIRECTOR OF LUKOIL </H4>

Vagit Alekperov <BR>
<BR>
Kogalym, in the north-west Siberian oil country, is an unlikely site for
a major multinational corporation. However, after Alekperov arrived in 1983
as a brash administrative <I>wunderkind</I>, its production figures began
to rival those at the huge wells at Surgut and Nizhnyvartovsk. About six
years ago, Alekperov formed what was then &quot;Concern&quot; Lukoil. His
partner in the venture was another dynamic young director, Yuri Shafranik,
who two years later became Russia's energy minister. Lukoil's relations
with foreign partners are littered with recriminations and the occasional
lawsuit. The firm's efforts at muscling-in on international consortia in
Azerbaijan was ham-fisted. However, Alekperov is still well ahead of the
Siberian pack, even though he has yet to make Lukoil work any better. This
may explain the so-so performance of company securities. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +70 95 202 3713</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +70 95 203 8241</I> <BR>
<H4>GENERAL DIRECTOR OF NOVOSHIP </H4>

Leonid Loza <BR>
<BR>
From a motley collection of ageing vessels in the Black Sea port of Novorossysk,
Loza has quickly forged a world-class shipping line for oil and general
freight. In 1992, Loza hired Coopers &amp; Lybrand to do the books and he
sent his captains to study at British and American marine academies. Last
year Novoship became the first non resource-based Russian industrial company
to tap international financial markets in a big way, with an EBRD-backed
loan of $336 million to finance the purchase of 11 new supertankers. Novorossysk,
a third-string port in Soviet times, is the most logical outlet for oil
soon to come from the Caspian Sea fields of Azerbaijan and Kazakhstan. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +78 6134 628 00</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +78 6134 642 55</I> <BR>
<H4>PRESIDENT OF NIPEK </H4>

Kakha Bendukidze <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We had one guiding principal,&quot; says one of Kakha Bendukidze's
lieutenants, &quot;to buy as much as possible.&quot; While the big banks
scoffed at Russia's convoluted voucher auctions, this reclusive former microbiologist
leveraged a modest export-import based fortune into an industrial empire,
at least on paper. In 1994, Bendukidze caused a stir when he bought 22%
of the huge industrial firm Uralmash for $500,000. But his investments in
the western Siberian oil and gas belt may be more fruitful in the long run.
Pouncing on the voucher privatisation scheme, Bendukidze and insiders from
the Russian Oil Exchange bought into about 50 oil support organisations,
concentrating on the arctic gas-producing region. Like other Russian raiders,
NIPEK lacks resources to develop the properties it grabbed. However, when
multinational capital finally gets serious about Russia, it will surely
be more serious about western Siberia than it will be about anywhere else.
<BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +70 95 128 2904</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +70 95 913 9524</I> <BR>
<H4>GENERAL DIRECTOR OF VIDEO INTERNATIONAL </H4>

Dmitry Abroschenko <BR>
<BR>
After two years of running Russian operations for US advertising giant Young
&amp; Rubicam, Abroschenko, 31, thought he could do better on his own. Video
International, founded to sell time on Russian television, has become a
fully fledged ad agency whose creative work stands up to that of Madison
Avenue. It dominates the billings of big Russian advertisers such as Most-Bank
and Bank Imperial. It is also raking in business from the Russian ads of
multinational firms like Procter &amp; Gamble, Kodak and Sony. This year
Video International landed the biggest account of all, Boris Yeltsin's re-election
campaign. If the agency's &quot;I believe, I love, I hope&quot; slogan is
felt to have helped Yeltsin win, it could represent a quantum leap for Russia's
rising image-maker. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +70 95 232 3395</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +70 95 201 3160</I> <BR>
<H4>PRESIDENT OF IBS </H4>

Anatoly Karachinsky <BR>
<BR>
It was Karachinsky who helped provide the computer services for Russia's
growing financial services industry. Karachinsky learned his trade by computerising
railway timetables in the early '80s and he published a book about personal
computers in 1986, years before any existed in the Soviet Union. After forming
IBS in 1992, he promptly closed deals with Dell, Lotus, 3-Com and other
hardware and software stars. Thus armed, he set out to network the dynamic
young banks. Karachinsky's colleagues in the DATOR industry association
have named him the most influential figure in Russian high technology for
three years in a row. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +70 95 967 8080</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +70 95 967 8091</I> <BR>
<H4>GENERAL DIRECTOR OF CENTAUR </H4>

Alexander Podolsky <BR>
<BR>
The king of Russian consumer product distribution is an economist who started
his business career with a shopping trip to Germany in 1991. A year or two
later, Podolsky talked Mars Corporation into a distribution deal. The Centaur
Finance and Industrial Group was on its way. Centaur shoulders the burden
of Russian customs and shipping for multinational clients. It then sends
products to the vast interior from its 30 cash-and-carry warehouse stores
in Moscow. The firm itself does not brave Russia's bandit-infested highways,
contracting the work to others. &quot;If we did business only with people
we trust entirely, we would have one or two partners,&quot; Podolsky asserts.
&quot;But in fact we have 300 or 400.&quot; Podolsky thinks the most common
mistake of western companies in Russia is that they &quot;treat us like
some kind of colonial market. Firms pay their Russian manager $300 a month,
and then wonder why he steals from them.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +70 95 971 5563</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +70 95 971 5579</I> <BR>
<H4>CHAIRMAN OF THE BOARD OF PARTNERS, DELOITTE &amp; TOUCHE CIS </H4>

Kirill Ugolnikov <BR>
<BR>
Ugolnikov graduated from the elite Soviet economic institute on the eve
of <I>perestroika</I>. He completed a course at the Moscow Financial Academy
in 1983 and went straight to a plum post in the finance ministry's foreign
currency division. On a 1988 trip to monitor Soviet assets in Belgium, Ugolnikov
met some adventurous partners from the firm then called Touche-Ross. After
a two-year struggle, he talked his superiors into launching a joint venture
with them. The result was Inaudit, the first Soviet auditing firm, which
opened in 1990. Today Ugolnikov oversees more than 700 Deloitte &amp; Touche
employees throughout the Commonwealth of Independent States. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +70 95 956 5000</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +70 95 956 5001</I> <BR>
<H4>DIRECTOR OF THE PORT OF VOSTOCHNY </H4>

Gennady Zhebelev <BR>
<BR>
Russia's window on the east was in sorry shape before Zhebelev hatched the
idea of turning the seaside town of Nakhodka, just east of Vladivostok,
into a free economic zone. He attracted some serious investors including
America's Sea-Land Corp and P&amp;O Australia, to turn his backwater into
a contemporary container port fit to handle the growing trade with Japan
and Korea. More growth at Vostochny is hostage to events beyond Zhebelev's
control - the settling of Russia's dispute with Japan over the Kuril
Islands and the progress of mammoth oil projects near Sakhalin Island. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +7 42366 520 65</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +7 42366 436 93</I> <BR>
<H4>CHAIRMAN OF NORILSK NICKEL </H4>

Vsevolod Generalov <BR>
<BR>
The colossal mining centre at Norilsk presents one of the world's tougher
management challenges. Despite churning out 20% of global nickel production
and much else besides, Norilsk Nickel is floundering under the weight of
amateurish financial management and the cost of keeping a medium-sized city
running north of the Arctic Circle. When UNEXIM Bank acquired 51% last year,
management and workers were none-too-welcoming. Generalov was brought in
as a caretaker with unquestionably good credentials. After 16 years of dues-paying
at Kazakhstan's Ust-Kamenogorsk lead works he began to climb the administrative
ladder, alighting as deputy chairman of the powerful Russian State Metals
Committee. Yet Generalov has shown little sympathy for his fellow old boys,
quickly dispatching Norilsk Nickel's incumbent director in favour of an
UNEXIM Bank official. &quot;The company's basic problems are rooted in the
complete absence of an effective system of management,&quot; he declares.
In Russian apparatese, this is likely to translate as &quot;more heads will
roll&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +70 95 974 1765</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +70 95 755 6113</I> 
<H3>SLOVAKIA </H3>
<H4>GOVERNOR OF THE NATIONAL BANK OF SLOVAKIA </H4>
<BR>
Vladimir Masar <BR>
<BR>
Masar, 38, is one of the world's youngest central bank governors. After
a career that took him from the old Czechoslovak State Bank into private
banking and subsequently into government as Slovakia's state finance secretary,
Masar was appointed to his post in July 1993 by prime minister Vladimir
Meciar's Movement for a Democratic Slovakia. Masar has proved his independence
and professionalism by enforcing impressive monetary and fiscal discipline.
As Jaromir Cekota, Slovakia's resident representative of the EBRD once said,
Masar has overseen &quot;the most impressive fiscal turnaround anywhere
in eastern Europe&quot;. With his penchant for flashy attire, Masar has
a reputation as a bit of a ladies' man. His next challenge is to ensure
that Slovakia's banking system, laden with more than $3 billion of non-performing
loans, does not crack as the government tries to complete the privatisation
of the country's largest institutions. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +42 7 323 511</I> <BR>
<H4>CHAIRMAN OF DMD HOLDINGS </H4>

Julius Toth <BR>
<BR>
A former finance minister under prime minister Meciar, Toth is a force to
be reckoned with among Slovakia's economic and political elite. As a director
of VSZ steel works in Kosice, which earns 30% of Slovakia's export revenues,
he took part in the controversial 1994 management purchase of VSZ stock
just days before the collapse of Meciar's second coalition government. With
fellow directors he formed a private company, Manager, to buy a 9.53% stake
for only $10 million when the market value was a reported $50 million. This
purchase was financed partly by the Industrial Bank of Kosice, Slovakia's
fifth biggest bank, of which Toth is a board member. Toth declined a government
position when Meciar was re-elected in 1994, but he is still a member of
Meciar's ruling Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS) and he is said
to be a generous contributor to the party. In January Toth was appointed
head of DMD Holdings, a government-owned company that is charged with restructuring
Slovakia's arms industry. The company has taken a 34% stake in all Slovak
arms manufacturers. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +42 95 354 11</I> <BR>
<H4>MINISTER OF COMMUNICATIONS, TRANSPORT AND PUBLIC WORKS </H4>

Alexander Resez <BR>
<BR>
Resez, 48, is one of Slovakia's richest men. A member of Vladimir Meciar's
Movement for a Democratic Slovakia, Resez entered the government in the
autumn of 1994. His ministry is responsible for the country's infrastructure
and for civil engineering projects including the soon-to-be partially privatised
state telephone monopoly. As vice-president of VSZ, Resez was a founding
member of Manager (see Toth above). He also has an interest in metals import-export
company Ferrimex, which has a 15% stake in VSZ, and in Cassoviainvest, an
investment company that also holds 15% of VSZ. Through its VSZ interests,
which has stakes in scores of Slovak companies and in more than 40 Czech
enterprises, the Resez family has considerable industrial punch. Resez senior,
together with VSZ directors, last year reportedly acquired a 12% stake in
Harvard Capital &amp; Consulting (Slovakia). Resez is a football fan; he
is an owner of the Kosice football club and a part-owner of Sparta Praha.
<BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +42 7 674 67</I> 
<H3>SLOVENIA </H3>
<H4>GENERAL MANAGER OF GORENJE </H4>

Joze Stanic <BR>
<BR>
Stanic leads one of Slovenia's largest companies, Gorenje, a manufacturer
of white goods and domestic appliances. Before the break-up of former Yugoslavia
Gorenje was among the top manufacturing companies, but it was well-protected
from foreign competition. Stanic kept the company afloat despite difficulties
and then finally turned it into a prosperous organisation. He streamlined
operations, reduced production costs and made Gorenje competitive. Now Stanic
has his eyes set on the markets of Serbia and Montenegro. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +386 63 853 231</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +386 63 853 811</I> <BR>
<H4>HEAD OF MERCATOR </H4>

Kazimir Zive Pregl <BR>
<BR>
Pregl heads the Mercator trading company, one of the largest firms in Slovenia.
A youth leader while an economics student, Pregl later worked for the Slovenian
and federal governments and held important positions in the then-ruling
party. His last job before the former Yugoslavia disintegrated was as vice
prime minister in the federal government. Pregl left Belgrade for Ljubljana
in 1991, after the first armed clashes. Finding himself out of favour at
home, Pregl started a housing construction business. Shortly afterwards
he became president of Mercator. In widening its network of outlets, Pregl
led the company to a leading role in domestic wholesale and retail trade.
<BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +386 61 168 2282</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +386 61 168 6293</I>
<BR>
 
<H3>UKRAINE </H3>
<H4>DIRECTORS OF KIEV-ATLANTIC LTD </H4>

David and Tamara Sweere <BR>
<BR>
Little did Dave Sweere suspect, when he left his native Minnesota to attend
a seed conference in Ukraine in 1989, that this would be his first step
towards divinity. In certain Kiev circles these days he is known as the
&quot;agro-business demigod&quot;. Sweere met his second wife, Tamara, an
Academy of Agriculture translator, on the trip. Moving to Kiev he found
strong demand for his services, providing Ukraine's under-productive farms
with seeds, fertiliser and equipment as well as marketing their crop. He
has been through the nine circles of bureaucratic hell, however, trying
to build a $15 million state-of-the-art agro-processing centre in Myronivka,
a town south of Kiev. However, arm-twisting from both the EBRD and US agriculture
department, which are investors in the project, persuaded the local oligarchy
to reinstate the cancelled construction permits and the centre should be
completed this year. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +380 044 295 7275</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +380 044 294 9350</I> <BR>
<H4>PRESIDENT OF AGROINKOM </H4>

Nikolai Lobas <BR>
<BR>
Lobas bought the first consignment of John Deere combine harvesters to arrive
in independent Ukraine and has not looked back since. Nine of his customers,
all forward-looking collective farm managers, joined him as partners in
Agroinkom which soon had an impressive land holding of 20,000 hectares.
The firm is providing inputs or buying crops on 300,000 more hectares, or
1% of Ukraine's entire land mass. Lobas is not new to the soil. He spent
18 years in the economics department of the Ukrainian Institute of Land
Management before starting Agroinkom in 1991. Perennially short of capital,
he works through a web of barter agreements throughout the CIS, Europe and
north America. Lobas is diplomatic about his bruising encounters with local
vested interests. He has pursued a <I>nouveau riche</I> lifestyle, exemplified
by his $500,000 dacha on the banks of the River Dnipro. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +380 044 261 7319</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +380 044 266 0013</I> <BR>
<H4>GOVERNOR OF DONETSK OBLAST </H4>

Vladimir Scherban <BR>
<BR>
The most important figure in Ukrainian business is not a businessman at
all, but an extraordinary public official. Donetsk is supposed to be Ukraine's
bleeding sore, a concentration of outdated Soviet heavy industry piggy-backed
on exhausted 19th-century coal mines. Moreover, the province is Russian-speaking
and its miners the most politically organised of all CIS workers. Yet Scherban's
leadership has produced what World Bank representative Daniel Kauffman ecstatically
calls &quot;Donetsk, Inc&quot;, a heavy exporter of entrepreneurial zest
to the sleepy western Ukraine. In a land where most politicians are the
products of string-pulling and party ticket-punching, Scherban is conspicuously
self-made. He left school at 17 to work as a plumber, rising painstakingly
to become an enterprise manager in the food-processing industry and picking
up a higher education on the way. He has set loose a Jacobin tide against
his former colleagues, enforcing workers' usually ignored right to vote
their bosses out of office. Some 400 general directors have been sent packing
as a result. He also organised Ukraine's most aggressive small privatisation
programme. <BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +380 0622 933 571</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +380 0622 359 254</I> <BR>
<H4>PRESIDENT OF DICOM </H4>

Alexander Maksmudov <BR>
<BR>
The politicians in Kiev continue to dither over their commitment to privatisation,
but that does not bother Maksmudov. Armed with modest capital of $2.4 million,
this former computer science professor now has a controlling or strategic
stake in a dozen factories making everything from rope to macaroni. Dicom's
emphasis is on consumer and light industrial producers, whose productivity
it can, in theory, raise without heavy capital inputs. The firm's holdings
should expand as voucher privatisation kicks into high gear this winter.
<BR>
<BR>
<I>Tel +380 0622 953 604</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Fax +380 0622 972 026</I> <BR>
<BR>
<I>Additional reporting by: Aleksandar Lebl, Kevin Smith, Alex Standish,
Julius Strauss, Christopher Bobinski</I> <BR>
<BR>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

