<td valign=top align=left> 

<H3>THE TOP 100 COMPANIES IN CENTRAL AND EASTERN EUROPE </H3>
<H4>Jana Hamel on a survey that pinpoints the region's frontrunners<BR><BR>
In the move from centrally directed to market economies in central and eastern
Europe, the region's largest companies are playing a crucial role. Predictably
enough in a rebuilding market, where infrastructure or support industries
fuel the economy, these tend to be energy and utilities companies. The following
list of the region's top 100 companies, compiled by Deloitte &amp; Touche
Central Europe, attempts to provide an overview of the region's success
stories.</H4> <BR>

The search for foreign<B> </B>direct investors has been a driving force
in the reorganisation of companies and in more general legal and economic
change. Progress has generally been fastest in the more economically developed
&quot;Visegrad four&quot; countries and Slovenia. The exception is Slovakia,
where foreign investment has been somewhat discouraged by political turmoil,
leaving domestic investors as the backbone of the privatisation process.
<BR>
<BR>
As the region and its companies develop, the focus will shift from restructuring
companies to helping them compete in world markets. <BR>
<BR>
Among the Visegrad countries, manufacturing and heavy industry lead the
economies of the Czech Republic and Poland, supporting a large number of
utilities and other companies servicing the infrastructure. In Hungary,
one of the region's largest economies, banks form an important part of the
country's economy but fall outside the scope of the ranking. Oil and gas,
utilities and light industry also play key roles. Slovenia, ahead of the
rest in terms of investment, continues to be strong in pharmaceuticals and
light industry. <BR>
<BR>
In second-tier countries such as Romania and the former Yugoslavia, large
state-run companies are still dominant. The private sector has very little
depth. A few entries, mainly in the oil and gas sector, illustrate the varying
progress towards privatisation and investment in these countries. In Bulgaria,
currently going through some political upheaval, the imminent sale of state
enterprises should help in recovery. <BR>
<BR>
The Baltic states of Lithuania and Latvia are lagging behind, mainly because
of recent banking crises, and Estonia had little to contribute to this ranking.
This region is returning to its traditional emphasis on light industry,
trading and wood working after having Soviet-style industrialisation thrust
upon it. <BR>
<BR>
When reading the list of the region's top 100 companies, several constraints
should be kept in mind. First, the list is in &thorn;ux: the &THORN;scal
year is identical to the calendar year for all companies in central Europe
and data for 1995 is available only in very few cases. The most recent reliable
data for year-end 1994 was used as the standard to allow comparison. <BR>
<BR>
Another consideration is that many countries have a shadow economy made
up of small private companies with revenues not large enough to enter the
top 100 classi&THORN;cation but which make up a signi&THORN;cant portion
of GDP. <BR>
<BR>
Most importantly, it has been difficult to get accurate &THORN;nancial data
from former Communist bloc companies. Our information is limited to revenue
statements - translated into US dollars, based on a historic exchange
rate - as there is still no legal requirement to provide a cash-&thorn;ow
statement. But one also wants to ask about a company's gearing, number of
employees, level of accounts receivable compared with revenue, level of
minority interest and dependence on one customer or product. <BR>
<BR>
Reliable data is becoming easier to gather. Although it may not be possible
to answer all questions yet, in future rankings we will look at a company's
assets and pro&THORN;tability as well as revenues to give a better overall
picture. <BR>
<BR>
A further difficulty is in &THORN;nding a way to rate companies whose &THORN;gures
are gathered, calculated and evaluated differently. Indeed, the very need
for independent assessment of a company's &THORN;nancial condition in an
internationally acceptable form has fuelled the tremendous growth of the
Big Six audit &THORN;rms in the region. However, some of the assessments
referred to have been more limited statutory audits rather than those performed
to international standards, causing differences in the way the year-end
&THORN;gures are presented. <BR>
<BR>
For each company, an attempt was made to gain the most accurate and recent
revenue &THORN;gure, based on published information from the company. In
some cases, information came directly from the company via a questionnaire
or an existing list that was then veri&THORN;ed. In Bulgaria, for example,
&THORN;gures for company revenue are not included in the minimal amount
of information all companies are obliged to publish, so data must be obtained
from the government's department of statistics. <BR>
<BR>
The scarcity of information on Bulgarian enterprises re&thorn;ects the government's
lack of commitment to reform through privatisation. This seems to have caught
up with it suddenly in the form of a recent devaluation and economic crisis.
As the government tries to rid itself of some of its most expensive commitments,
the valuation of state companies and their assets will become a priority,
improving access to statistics as a by-product. <BR>
<BR>
Baltic companies have yet to be tracked by a reliable independent third
party, but newspapers and journals publish many unof&THORN;cial lists. In
Estonia, the country's lead in privatisation has created a demand for company
information while Latvia and Lithuania are committed to &THORN;nishing privatisation
by the end of 1997. <BR>
<BR>
In the Czech Republic, there are several rankings of the largest companies.
The &THORN;rst, the Resources 300, appeared in 1994 and was followed by
the Czech Top 100, compiled by ING Bank and published in the country's leading
economic newspaper. The database and publishing company ASPEKT Kilcullen
gathers data for its ranking via questionnaires and publishes the results
monthly. Our list is derived from the Czech Top 100 and ASPEKT Kilcullen.
<BR>
<BR>
In the Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia the initial data source was
a publication called <I>100+100 Most Successful Enterprises of the Republic
of Macedonia</I>, veri&THORN;ed through checks with the companies concerned.
State enterprises are still the largest by far in this country, which is
beginning to restructure and privatise. Its small privately owned companies
make an important contribution to the economy. <BR>
<BR>
The Polish list was based on the most used ranking, the <I>Gazeta Bankowa</I>
Top 500. Additional information was gathered by surveying companies directly.
That 500 such companies can be tracked indicates the depth of Poland's economy.
The country's political situation is less stable than that of its neighbour
to the south, but not enough to cause investors great concern. The sheer
size of Poland and its population make the country a more interesting and
difficult market. <BR>
<BR>
Romania's information was drawn from a government list issued in August
1995 that includes nearly 4,000 state companies slated for privatisation.
It excludes the <I>regies autonomes</I>, autonomously administered state-owned
companies not available for privatisation, such as the national railways
and telecommunications utilities for which no turnover or revenue &THORN;gures
are published. Typically, the largest private-sector creations reveal no
data, but they would not be large enough to make this list. <BR>
<BR>
The &THORN;gures for Slovakia are based on a list of companies from the
economic weekly <I>Trend</I> and were checked by a questionnaire to each
of the companies in question. The availability of mid-year 1995 &THORN;gures
allowed us to present the &quot;new&quot; top 10 list of Slovak companies.
<BR>
<BR>
Despite its small size, Slovenia does contribute companies to the list.
The initial data sources were published lists from MAG magazine and from
the <I>Economic Gazette</I>. Information was checked with the statistical
office and with companies themselves. The Economic Institute in Belgrade
was the source of the Yugoslav list. With the sanctions lifted less than
a year ago and privatisation still under discussion this list, although
accurate at present, is due to undergo some major changes. <BR>
<BR>
<I>The author is marketing manager of Deloitte &amp; Touche Centrale Europe.
This article was written with the help of all its regional offices. Special
thanks to Tina MacVeigh and Steven Fast for providing a future glimpse of
Slovakia (below).</I> <BR>
<BR>
