<td valign=top align=left> 
<H2>WHAT IS COMPETITION?  </H2>

<H4>Why do some nations fall behind while others charge ahead? The Global
Competitiveness Report sheds some light, writes Frederick Hu </H4>
Short of military conquest, economic growth is the only viable means for
a country to sustain increases in national wealth and living standards.
Yet throughout history, growth rates have varied widely. And this matters:
several percentage points of growth differentials, if persistent, make a
huge difference to the living standards and the balance of economic power
between nations. <BR>
<BR>
The Industrial Revolution and the subsequent rapid expansion in output made
Britain the world's greatest power for much of the 18th and 19th centuries.
Since the turn of the 20th century, the US has taken its place. But for
a millennium before the west's rise, China had the world's largest economy
and was the most technologically advanced nation. Economic stagnation and
a lack of technological progress in the late Ching dynasty allowed the country
to fall behind Europe, north America and, by the dawn of the 20th century,
Japan too. <BR>
<BR>
In the years just after World War II, the Soviet Union's industrial production
expanded rapidly under a centrally planned system, inspiring fear from advanced
western capitalist countries and admiration from newly independent but economically
less developed nations. In east Asia, economic prospects were bleak. Japan
was lamenting its defeat and destruction; Hong Kong was a poor island crowded
with refugees and slums; Korea was torn in a brutal civil war; Singapore
was a sleeping city with an uncertain future and Taiwan had an agricultural
economy under the threat of continuing civil war with the mainland. Only
the Philippines showed promise. <BR>
<BR>
Four decades later, Japan is a world leader in technology and has the second
largest economy. Hong Kong and Singapore are thriving &THORN;nancial and
trading service centres and South Korea and Taiwan are industrialised economies
with a strong manufacturing base. Rapid growth has lifted countries of the
region from extreme poverty to stunning prosperity within a generation.
Some east Asian nations' per capita income now matches or surpasses standards
in north America and Europe. <BR>
<BR>
East Asia's economic miracle sharply contrasts with what happened to Argentina,
a highly prosperous country between the world wars, the former Soviet Union
and the Philippines. Alternative economic systems, development strategies
and government policies have produced strikingly different outcomes. Some
nations fall behind, some catch up and some charge ahead. What word if not
competition describes this dynamic pattern in the world economy? There are
winners (fast- growing economies) and losers (slowly growing or stagnating
ones). In this sense nations compete, but not necessarily at each other's
expense. <BR>
<BR>
What does it take for a country to move ahead of others in economic growth?
The answer to this question, together with an analysis of how individual
nations are faring now, provides the impetus behind <I>The Global Competitiveness
Report 1996</I>. <BR>
<BR>
In the report, competitiveness is de&THORN;ned as a nation's capacity to
achieve economic growth. An economy is internationally competitive if it
performs strongly in three general areas: abundant productive inputs such
as capital, labour, infrastructure and technology; optimal economic policies
such as low taxes, little interference and free trade and sound market institutions
such as the rule of law and the protection of property rights. Some of the
report's important methodological advances are outlined by Jeffrey Sachs
(see page 8). <BR>
<BR>
<B>The main conclusions </B><BR>
<BR>
There are a number of basic conclusions that can be reached from this year's
rankings. As readers of newspaper headlines will have seen, the EU is slipping
behind many parts of the world in economic competitiveness. Prevailing social
welfare systems are proving to be too costly even for rich European countries
such as France, Germany and Sweden: the subject of a separate essay in the
competitiveness report<I>.</I> <BR>
<BR>
Five of the six most competitive nations are small, open economies with
relatively small governments and low tax rates: Singapore, Hong Kong, New
Zealand, Luxemburg and Switzerland. The US comes in fourth, well ahead of
the EU and Japan. Many reforming states, such as Russia, China, India and
Brazil, are still in a relatively early phase of achieving competitive policies
and institutions. They have come a long way from their recent past as closed
and state-led economies. But they have not yet created the conditions to
ensure sustained high rates of economic growth. <BR>
<BR>
Of course, poor countries such as China and India enjoy a growth dividend
as a result of their initial low levels of income, so they are expanding
rapidly despite enormous de&THORN;ciencies in economic institutions. Future
growth will require institutional reforms. <BR>
<BR>
This year's Competitiveness Index is shown in Table 1 (page 17). Singapore
tops the list, followed by Hong Kong and New Zealand. The US is fourth,
trailed by Luxemburg, Switzerland, Norway and Canada. The EU countries are
generally further down the list. Denmark is 11th, followed by the UK -
the country most at odds with overall EU policies - at 15th. <BR>
<BR>
This year, Japan is 13th and Germany 22nd. Chile is the top-ranked developing
country outside Asia. Many of the most talked-about reforming developing
economies - Brazil, the Czech Republic, India, Poland, Russia and South
Africa - remain far down the list. <BR>
<BR>
Some countries deserve particular comment. Singapore is the quintessential
entrep&ocirc;t economy: a centre of &THORN;nance and trade, a hub for the
regional activities of major multinationals and a manufacturer in its own
right. It ranks very high in every factor and tops the list, as be&THORN;ts
one of the world's fastest growing economies and a country that takes more
foreign direct investment as a percentage of gross domestic product than
any other. <BR>
<BR>
In third place is New Zealand, the new star. Its ranking is a tribute to
a decade of structural and policy reforms which include opening the economy,
cutting government spending, widespread privatisation and innovating in
many areas of governmental action from &THORN;scal policies to pensions
and central banking. New Zealand's reforms will be widely studied and emulated
in future years. <BR>
<BR>
The US is the most competitive of all the large economies with populations
of more than 10 million or so, but is fourth overall in the rankings. The
US falls below the front-runners because of its moderately high rates of
government spending and taxation, its relatively low rate of national saving
and the simmering frustrations with the justice system recorded by the Executive
Survey, a poll of business leaders that forms one of the report's competitiveness
criteria. It shows its greatest comparative strengths in infrastructure,
technology and management. <BR>
<BR>
Japan, recently widely admired as the most competitive nation, ranks 13th.
This is mainly because of its lack of openess to international trade and
&THORN;nance and its continuing &THORN;scal problems linked to the banking
crisis. Japan is recovering from its current recession but will not retake
the lead in global competitiveness without extensive economic liberalisation.
Despite slippage in some areas, Japan remains ranked highest overall for
technology. <BR>
<BR>
<B>An ill mood in Germany </B><BR>
<BR>
Germany, the economic powerhouse of the EU, can manage only 22nd place.
This is consistent with the ill mood in Germany, as social partners debate
the reduction of the welfare state. Germany, together with many of its partners
in the EU, ranks especially poorly in government and labour market &thorn;exibility
but does better in infrastructure and technology. <BR>
<BR>
Virtually all Latin American economies have made impressive progress on
opening to international trade, trimming the size of the state and allowing
markets to function. Nevertheless, the Competitiveness Index suggests that
only Chile has achieved a fairly high degree of international competitiveness.
Mexico, Argentina, Peru, Colombia, Venezuela and Brazil (in that order)
still lag far behind. <BR>
<BR>
The Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland have some way to go to achieve high
and sustainable growth. Although these economies have made startling progress
in creating democratic, capitalist economies and have resumed economic growth,
they still fall short in almost every factor of competitiveness. The countries
are notably weak in government, because government spending and taxation
remain very high as a percentage of GDP. They do poorly in areas such as
infrastructure, technology and management, the legacy of decades of forced
isolation from world markets. <BR>
<BR>
Russia is the least competitive of all the countries included in the report.
Neither the quantitative nor the survey data could relieve the general gloom.
Russia is still relatively isolated from world markets, taxation is high
and unstable and there is general disdain for the infrastructure, technology
and management. Only labour &thorn;exibility shows a mild, rather than strong,
negative. The country ranks last in its political and judicial institutions.
<BR>
<BR>
We want to emphasise that the rankings are only approximations. There are
signi&THORN;cant conceptual and empirical problems in squeezing a country's
growth-producing or growth-retarding attributes into a single quantitative
index. Even some of the data from 1994 and last year are out of date, especially
in the most rapidly reforming countries. This is an inevitable hazard of
cross-country comparisons. Nonetheless, the list tells an important story
and gives strong evidence about a country's relative capacity to achieve
future sustained economic growth. <BR>
<BR>
In addition to the main Competitiveness Index, we have introduced two supplementary
indicators of national competitiveness - the Growth Index and the Market
Growth Index. The Growth Index, generated from a regression model that relates
growth to the Competitiveness Index and initial income, aims to rank nations'
medium-term growth prospects. <BR>
<BR>
For a given level of competitiveness, it is reasonable to expect that poorer
countries will tend to grow faster than richer countries, partly because
poorer ones have the advantage of borrowing technology, ideas and capital
from the richer ones and partly because the market returns to new investment
(and therefore the saving and investment rates as well) tend to be higher
in the poorer countries. <BR>
<BR>
<B>New measurement for growth </B><BR>
<BR>
The Market Growth Index takes into account the size of the respective markets.
Measured in purchasing power parity dollars in 1994, the total GDP of the
49 countries was roughly $28 trillion. The GDP of the US was about $6.7
trillion, or 24% of the total. Singapore's GDP, by contrast, was $60 billion,
or 0.2% of the total. <BR>
<BR>
Even though Singapore is likely to grow more rapidly, the US will account
for a much larger share of future total world economic growth. The Market
Growth Index ranks a country's share of economic growth in the total world
growth. <BR>
<BR>
By introducing <I>The Global Competitiveness Report 1996</I>, we have a
better understanding of the complex issue of competitiveness and its relation
to growth. While the debate continues, the World Economic Forum will continue
to provide in-depth research and analysis in its future reports on global
competitiveness.* <BR>
<BR>
<I>Frederick Hu is head of the World Economic Forum's competitiveness research
team. This article is adapted from The Global Competitiveness Report 1996's
executive summary, co-written with Jeffrey Sachs, director of the Harvard
Institute for International Development. <BR>
<BR>
The Global Competitiveness Report 1996 is available from </I>World Link<I>
for $685, tel +44 171 779 8324, fax +44 171 779 8727.</I> <TABLE BORDER=1 CELLPADDING=1 CELLSPACING=1>
