<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra9.gif" alt="Feature">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 

<H2>HOME THOUGHTS FROM ABROAD </H2>

<H4>From Hong Kong, Chris Patten is leaping into the debate at the heart
of Europe, writes Francis Harris </H4>

There are politer ways to say it, but the truth is that the marriage between
Britain and the Hong Kong business community has everything to do with convenience
and little to do with love. To understand that you only have to meet Britain's
last mail-order-bride, Chris Patten: the Conservative Party politician chosen
as colonial governor to oversee reunification with China next year. <BR>
<BR>
The governor has been at the centre of a number of bitter rows with Beijing
and the Chinese-dominated business elite. On the day he spoke to <I>World
Link</I>, the Englishman was visibly preoccupied and exhausted by the most
recent public exchanges with business leaders over what he did or did not
say in an interview with <I>Newsweek</I> magazine. <BR>
<BR>
The atmosphere is souring as the months before the handover tick away. So
when Patten suggested to <I>Newsweek</I> that businessmen were ready to
support Beijing's plans to dump his democratic reforms only because they
had &quot;foreign passports in their back pockets&quot;, there was a storm.
As <I>The South China Morning Post</I> pointed out: &quot;The popular perception...
is that Mr Patten used the interview to accuse local entrepreneurs of betrayal.&quot;
Beijing has accused him of worse for his attempts to introduce limited democracy:
&quot;Criminal for 1,000 generations&quot; was one of the more polite brickbats.
<BR>
<BR>
Were Patten in the usual mould of colonial bosses - a career diplomat
or a minor politician - these disputes might already have tarred him
forever as the man who alienated China. But he is more substantial, both
intellectually and politically. The handover, due at midnight on June 30,
1997, will herald a new dawn for the colony. It will also mark a new beginning
for Patten, tipped by some on the Conservative left as a future party leader
and prime minister. <BR>
<BR>
Despite the sometimes fetid political atmosphere, Patten still seems willing
to tackle potentially controversial subjects. Sitting in the splendour of
the governor's mansion, he talks freely when asked about the Asian values
that regional leaders such as Lee Kuan Yew in Singapore suggest set the
continent apart from the west. Is their use of the term just a way of telling
the west to mind its own business? <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Yes it is. I think it is consistently used as a way of telling other
countries to get off Asian leaders' patches. It is a spurious argument.
How Confucian is it to focus discussion of one's success on GDP growth and
how Confucian is what happens in the explosive capitalist development in
parts of China? Confucius is sometimes used to justify almost anything.
I don't think Confucianism, which used to be used to explain low levels
of economic activity in Asia, is the reason for Asia's success.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>Free trade, not low pay </B><BR>
<BR>
That raises the overtly political question of what does lie behind Asia's
success, a tricky subject often raised by both the governor and Hong Kong
businessmen. Tricky also because Asian success is often cited by members
of Patten's party in Britain as an alternative to Europe's supposedly state
interventionist EU. So is Asian success, as is sometimes suggested, a victory
for low pay? <BR>
<BR>
&quot;In certain commercial and industrial sectors investment inevitably
chases low labour costs, although it is easy to over-emphasise the importance
of that in Europe and north America. The reasons for Asian economic success
lie elsewhere. The biggest single reason is the expansion of world trade
and access to the US.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Patten cites gloomy forecasts made about Asia in the '50s and '60s: &quot;What
they said about it was similar to what people have been saying about Africa
for the past 10 years. One reason for that is that they were expecting the
expansion of global markets to slow. [Yet] they were on the threshold of
a period in which trade increased threefold. The biggest argument for free
trade is what's happened in Asia. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;You can think of other policies [to explain Asia's success]. You can
point to sensible macroeconomic policies, you can point to stable political
structures in most of the countries, you can point to talent and entrepreneurial
flair. It seems to me just as it was in the Industrial Revolution.&quot;
Perhaps, then, thinking in the west is over-simplified? &quot;It is a debate
that tends to give people the opportunity to fit arguments to their prejudices.
On the whole, I have found that my experience here has [had the effect of]
dismantling many of my prejudices rather than reinvigorating them.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
In discussing Asia's success, the governor is positioning himself as a signi&THORN;cant
figure in the central economic and political discussion about the relative
merits of the Asian, European and north American experience. It is not without
risk: by the time the message has made the long haul back to the west, it
can arrive shorn of its subtleties and Patten has been derided for allegedly
proposing to foster Asian-style growth in Europe simply by cutting spending.
Government spending in the region, for example, is less than half that in
western Europe at about 20% of GDP. <BR>
<BR>
Asked about this, Patten is keen to offer a full explanation. &quot;Comparing
western and Asian spending can lead to crude over-simplifications. I tend
to discover that my caveats and conditional clauses are ignored and claims
that I would not dream of making are placed in my mouth because people assume
the point I am making is less sophisticated than the one I am trying to
argue. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The point is... that while I do not believe the proportion of GDP
taken by public spending or tax is the main feature or sole [condition]
for rapid economic growth, there is a relationship between those factors.
That is one of many lessons that can be taken from Asia's developed economies.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There is a subset of arguments: first that Asian politicians have
been much less ready than European and maybe north American [ones] to associate
the public good, which is often defined in terms of compassion, with public
spending. A related proposition is that an economy such as this one has
been much better at tapping private investment to achieve public good than
we have been, on the whole, in Europe. They are also more conscious of the
difference between capital and current spending than some European treasuries.&quot;
While in Europe, Patten says, public demand for services is in control of
public spending. <BR>
<BR>
This issue is moving to the heart of the debate about the economic destiny
of the EU. If, as is often suggested, the EU and to a lesser extent the
US cannot afford the rising burden of public expenditure, if the 15 member
states cannot make good the promises they made to their peoples by creating
welfare states after World War II, there will be some painful and widely
resented cuts. Few politicians are willing even to discuss the issue, let
alone suggest remedies. <BR>
<BR>
At first it seems Patten is going to steer clear of this minefield. &quot;I
am in a position that is politically precarious and that makes me intellectually
timid. If I start setting out an agenda for the public sector, I risk criticism
that I am becoming too political. So I have to err on the side of making
myself a target for all those who say 'He's doing the easy thing; stating
the objective but not how he would get there'.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
And then, perhaps typically, he leaps into the fray. He employs generalities,
but his targets are rather identi&THORN;able. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;However, let me offer three general propositions. First, when the
welfare state - and this is true of most of Europe - was introduced
or rather extended after the war, the assumption was that unless it was
available to the middle class as well as those who were less well-off, the
middle class would resent the tax burden required to pay for other people's
social provision. That has pushed us into a set of taxpayer-funded social
obligations that are far beyond what was ever intended and far beyond what
is desirable or in the long run affordable. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Addressing that is hard: dismantling middle-class benefits requires
courage. I reckon that is what politicians across Europe will find themselves
doing, and doubtless losing elections for doing, in the next period. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Second, I feel strongly that people need to be aware of the cost of
the social goods that they vote for and desire. The more cost can be linked
to the service provided the better. That is why in the UK I always favoured
a health tax, which was advocated by Leon Brittan [now an EU commissioner]
and others in the '80s. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Third, I feel that local taxation has some advantages over central
[taxation] in relating provision to cost. My fairly cheerless experience
of presiding over local government financing led me to the conclusion that
too much is paid for centrally, certainly in the UK, and that more should
be run locally.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
He pauses. Perhaps it his politician's sense that he may have said more
than he intended. He con&THORN;rms this, muttering that he has just gone
further than before in laying out his ideas. <BR>
<BR>
Such thoughts will not matter if Patten intends to retire after June 30,
1997. If, as many suspect, he intends to return to political life every
word could become ammunition for his enemies. The UK press has made much
of his likely return, with speculation recently fuelled by prime minister
John Major when he offered warm praise for Patten. But for the moment at
least, he is coy on the subject. Is it fair to suggest he is pitching for
a leading role in the Conservative Party after the next election? <BR>
<BR>
&quot;It is a fair assessment of what some people in the press say. It is
not a fair assessment of what I do or say or think. Do I spend every waking
moment thinking about what I'm going to do after June 30, 1997? No I don't.
If I do think about life after Hong Kong, I tend to think about it in terms
of sitting under a tree with a book and a glass of <I>vin blanc cassis</I>.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The only things I know for certain is that I'm going to take some
time off, that I want to write, that I would like in due course another
proper job and that, as you have observed, I still have an interest in political
issues. Although it sounds incredibly pompous to say so, I would like to
make a contribution to those debates. Not just a contribution as a rather
old-fashioned Tory, but a contribution as one who has spent five years after
a political career running one of the biggest cities in Asia and one of
the most important cities in the world.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
That sounds like a politician pitching for a future role in political life.
If Patten does have a political existence after Hong Kong, it will likely
involve him in what is probably the UK's most important political debate
since the beginning of this century: Europe. <BR>
<BR>
For that reason, his recent interviews and speeches will generate interest
in the chancelleries of Europe. Once regarded as a Europhile, it has been
said that the governor's Asian experience has made him more of a Eurosceptic,
someone more in tune with the right wing of his party at home. Patten acknowledges
some change but chooses his words carefully. &quot;I am not more sceptical
of the imperative of Britain's role in Europe. I am more sceptical of how
European commitment is defined. There is a political correctness about it
that I find rather unsatisfactory,&quot; he says. <BR>
<BR>
Does that mean that British political debate is too focused on the EU? &quot;I
think it is rather limited. I am much persuaded by the arguments of Timothy
Garton Ash [a writer and fellow at St Antony's College, Oxford] about the
real objective in Europe being enlargement and the salvation of democracy,
freedom and decency in central and eastern Europe, rather than some of the
present preoccupations. I don't take [that] to be an excuse for avoiding
the difficult arguments about sovereignty and the relationship between nation
states and Brussels. Those arguments apply whether [or not] you're talking
about enlargement.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Finally, Patten returns to the subject of Hong Kong, including the legacy
of the British and its last governor, Chris Patten. Outside, the trappings
of empire are intact: the beautiful governor's mansion on the island's Mid-Levels
is ringed by flowers and impeccably dressed colonial policemen: below, on
the harbour, there is a British forces headquarters and on the hills above,
the dishes of the GCHQ electronic eavesdropping stations. <BR>
<BR>
No one is sure what will become of them after next July (Hong Kong officials
joke that the governor's mansion will become a museum of British atrocities).
If Patten gives it any thought, there is little indication. He talks of
the future, comparing the colony to New York. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The most over-worked cliche about Hong Kong, which just happens to
be true, is that it stands a good chance of being the New York of Asia.
Everybody focuses on the political transition in Hong Kong. But there's
another shift as well: from being a rich city - improbably rich given
our circumstances, a spectacular refugee success story at the gateway to
China - to being one of the world's greatest business and financial
centres, perhaps the greatest. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;I believe Hong Kong is most likely to make that transition if it retains
its present decencies and freedoms - if it maintains the rule of law,
a clean and decent public administration... civil liberties and open, accountable
and steadily more democratic government - than if it does not. But
plenty of critics, some of them businessmen, do not agree with me. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;For me, there is a precise match between giving the people of Hong
Kong what they were promised in the Joint Declaration [between Britain and
China] and helping Hong Kong on the road to that transition. You only have
to read the international press to realise that some actions taken by China
and some things said by China's friends here recently have raised doubts
in some people's minds about our ability to make that transition. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;I think that is a pity and I hope it is not the end of the story.
No one can doubt the extraordinary economic momentum, which has almost doubled
our GDP since the Joint Declaration was signed and has increased it by a
quarter since I arrived [in 1992]. But for that momentum to go as far as
it can, the framework that has powered Hong Kong forward has to be retained.
That is what I see as being my main purpose here.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Patten will likely be disappointed in his hope of seeing that framwork left
untouched. But if China and his enemies in the business elite think they
have seen he last of him, they too are likely to be disappointed. Patten
may disappear from Hong Kong, but east Asia may well meet him again in another
guise, representing a country that is still the biggest European investor
in the region. 

</td>
</tr>
</table>

