<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra9.gif" alt="Feature">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 

<H2>A FRIEND OF THE FAMILY? </H2>

<H4>Some global &THORN;rms are doing much to help staff with children to
juggle their commitments. But many still resist change, Elisabeth Faure
shows in a poll </H4>
With more women workers struggling to balance commitments to work and family,
employers are under greater pressure than ever before to adopt &quot;family-friendly&quot;
policies to help staff balance those demands. <I>World Link </I>has surveyed
16 large US and European firms to discover their approach (see page 42).
The results suggest that provision has as much to do with national attitudes
and legislation as with individual company initiatives. <BR>
<BR>
Attitudes have some way to go. According to Susan Hay, the founder of the
&THORN;rst nursery in the City of London, a senior partner in a leading
law &THORN;rm once told her that not only did he regard her work as &quot;subversive&quot;,
he viewed the prospect of young children in his railway carriage as intolerable.
<BR>
<BR>
Those campaigning for change often hear this sort of response. Many &THORN;rms
are concerned only with what happens in the office. &quot;Outside&quot;
issues are seen as personal. But there is growing evidence that in some
sectors, often those in which women traditionally form a large part of the
workforce and especially among large corporations and multinationals, company
policy is changing. Some may have been won over by the expanding body of
research that shows that family-friendly &THORN;rms have reduced absenteeism,
cut staff turnover, increased productivity, attracted better recruits, improved
their image and lifted staff morale. <BR>
<BR>
Others may have been persuaded to change by the growing weight of demographic
factors that are radically changing the look of the workforce. Women will
make up 75% of Europe's new workers by the year 2000, according to &THORN;gures
from the EU. Employment among European women with children below the age
of 10 rose from 42% to 49% between 1985-90. In the UK, the government's
employment department says that the greatest increase in labour market participation
has been among women with children under &THORN;ve, up from 37% in 1984
to 52% last year. In the US, 60% of women with children under the age of
six now work outside the home. <BR>
<BR>
Whatever the reason, more companies now admit that employees' private lives
affect their work performance and recognise that schemes to improve the
quality of their lives can pay dividends. A 1990 survey by the US department
of labour showed that of 400 staff with children below the age of 12, childcare
problems were the most signi&THORN;cant predictors of absenteeism and inefficiency
at work. <BR>
<BR>
Among those companies that have enacted family-friendly policies, there
are wide variations in what they offer and to whom they offer it. Some indication
of this can be seen in the chart below. It examines a number of working
practices that are designed to help both women and men balance work and
family commitments, including nursery provision, job-shares and telephone
work and subsidised day-care. For many companies such policies are a sensitive
issue, which may help to explain why &THORN;rms such as Banque Paribas and
Arthur Andersen felt unable to respond to our survey. <BR>
<BR>
Liz Burgh is the director of Opportunity 2000, a British organisation campaigning
for family-friendly work practices. She reports that all of her members,
including the Rank Organisation leisure company and the high-street pharmacy
chain Boots, have changed course largely for economic reasons. Prominent
converts such as Lord Tugendhat, the chairman of Abbey National, refer to
corporate welfare as enlightened self-interest, she adds. <BR>
<BR>
The high cost of training is leading big &THORN;rms to try to staunch the
exodus of skilled working mothers. Britain's Midland Bank, for example,
has estimated that the cost of losing and replacing one experienced staff
member was equivalent to his or her total annual employment costs. On the
other hand, the cost of keeping a child in a nursery from six months to
school age is about &#163;10,000 ($15,000). <BR>
<BR>
Britain's official electronic listening post, the Government Communications
Headquarters (GCHQ), estimates that it costs &#163;93,000 to train one professional
while the UK's National Health Service spends &#163;250,000 to train a doctor.
Losing research and development staff can also cost companies lucrative
commercial opportunities if a person develops a new drug or product elsewhere.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Cheaper to keep her </B><BR>
<BR>
To prevent staff losses at Midland, where 63% of staff are women, the bank
set up 115 nurseries, with dramatic results: the proportion of women returning
to work after maternity leave rose from 30% in 1988 to 85% by the end of
1994. <BR>
<BR>
Rank Organisation introduced a scheme to let new mothers return to work
gradually. After &THORN;ve years, the company saved $1.5 million and its
retention rate for skilled women rose from 20% to 80%. A similar programme
has paid off for British Rail. In 1992, the company opened two nurseries
after it realised that only 20% of staff at London's Waterloo station returned
to work full-time after maternity leave. In their first year, British Rail
estimates, the nurseries generated a net return on investment of 20%. Opportunity
2000 says that Boots doubled the number of women returning from maternity
leave by offering &thorn;exible working hours. Rank Xerox estimates that
similar policies have saved it &#163;1 million in the past &THORN;ve years.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Although &thorn;exible working is often portrayed as a means for staff
to combine work and family responsibilities, &thorn;exibility is not only
employee-friendly but employer-friendly,&quot; says Diane Perrins, a lecturer
at the Gender Institute at the London School of Economics (LSE) who feels
that &thorn;exibility has become more &quot;employer-led&quot;. Alec Laken,
a manager at the engineering company Allied Signal, agrees: &quot;Employees
[working &thorn;exible hours] are happier, particularly in their relationships
with their managers.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Despite such arguments, most companies remain unswayed and little has changed
for most working women, to their strong regret. &quot;In Europe, 60% of
women who work full-time would prefer to work part-time, and 80%-90% of
women working part-time are happy working fewer hours,&quot; says Catherine
Hakim, author of the book <I>Female heterogeneity and the polarisation of
women's employment</I>. <BR>
<BR>
A recent article in <I>Business Week</I> suggests that even many well-educated,
professional women are unhappy with their conditions. The article traces
the careers of six women from the '80s to the present. In one typical example
Chantal Davies, a senior project &THORN;nance director at SG Warburg, found
that both her work and personal life suffered after her first child was
born. Chantal would kiss her son in the morning on her way to work and again
at 8pm on her return, when he was asleep. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Informal and unbinding </B><BR>
<BR>
While on maternity leave with her second child she decided to quit international
&THORN;nance, although she would have continued had her job been more &thorn;exible.
&quot;Unless you were prepared to make it your top priority, you were heading
for trouble,&quot; she says in the article. <BR>
<BR>
Where family-friendly policies do exist they are often informal, particularly
in the UK. It is common for each branch of a company to have a different
set of welfare policies and for employees to arrange their bene&THORN;ts
individually with line managers. Burgh of Opportunity 2000 recognises that
&quot;there is a resistance to formalising policies that are seen as binding&quot;.
<BR>
<BR>
This can hurt junior staff. A senior executive whose child attends the Broadgate
nursery in the City of London said to her employer: &quot;I have found the
childcare that I need - please pay&quot;. Her request was granted,
but that was probably a re&thorn;ection of her negotiating power. Perrins
of the LSE says that &quot;the discretionary nature of childcare is very
selective and enables companies to retain senior staff&quot;. Indeed, some
companies in the index, including American Express Europe and the Bank of
Ireland, make job-sharing available to directors but not to most junior
staff. <BR>
<BR>
Employers' resistance is partly understandable: workplace nurseries are
expensive to set up, for example. But there are cheaper options such as
&thorn;exitime, subsidising places in an independent nursery and offering
childcare information and referral services. <BR>
<BR>
The childcare consultant Hay would rarely advise firms to set up a nursery:
&quot;Only if a company were moving out of the capital would it be worthwhile.&quot;
Most of those firms in the index which provide childcare, including PepsiCo,
UBS, American Express Europe and the Bank of Ireland, subsidise places in
local nurseries. <BR>
<BR>
In resisting family-friendly policies, employers often argue that only a
few staff members would bene&THORN;t. Some employers also worry that male
staff will also demand the use of childcare services, thus adding costs
which should be carried by their wives' employers. However, research published
by <I>The Harvard Business Review</I> in 1990 shows that provision of childcare
boosts the morale of all company staff, regardless of sex. <BR>
<BR>
The chart opposite should be read with a number of provisos. The industry
in which a company operates, the type of workforce, existing work policies
and the level of community childcare services all have a bearing on what
any individual company may offer. <BR>
<BR>
A manufacturing company can hardly be criticised for not offering its employees
the option of teleworking - it is impossible to build a car from home.
On the other hand &thorn;exitime is particularly suited to manufacturing,
where shift work is common. At BMW's Regensburg production plant, for instance,
machines run on a six-day week cycle and employees work an average of four
days a week. <BR>
<BR>
Some companies, often in the &THORN;nancial sector, argue that they need
not be family-friendly because women tend to be under-represented in their
industry. At Merrill Lynch in London, for example, only 16% of front-office
staff are female. National legislation also plays a role. Where the government
is committed to family-friendly working conditions, as in Denmark, France
and Belgium, corporate welfare policies are correspondingly more generous.
In France, employers are required by law to contribute to &quot;family allowance
funds&quot; which are used to support local childcare services. Accessible,
high-quality state nursery education leaves companies free to focus on allowing
employees &thorn;exible work hours. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Economy blowing hot and cold </B><BR>
<BR>
The economic climate also plays a role. When Hay set up the &THORN;rst nursery
in the City of London in 1991, the recession was at its peak and many companies
felt obliged to withdraw their support. &quot;The recession separated the
employers who see childcare as a long-term commitment from the more aggressive
ones seeking short-term gain,&quot; she says. The Swiss bank UBS was hit
by the economic downturn, but did not abandon its childcare commitment.
<BR>
<BR>
Although corporate welfare provision as a whole is poor some companies stand
out, offering a number of imaginative models from which other &THORN;rms
can learn. One is the provision of childcare advice, an increasingly popular
option because it is cheap and universal. Ford provides an electronic bulletin
board through which working parents can obtain childcare information and
advice while UBS offers a toll-free telephone number for the same purpose.
At its headquarters, Allied Signal provides not only a nursery for 100 children
but also an emergency childcare service. If an employee whose child does
not attend the nursery has a problem, the nursery can provide cover at short
notice. <BR>
<BR>
PepsiCo has developed a scheme called &quot;compress work week&quot;. Each
week throughout the summer, employees are given half a day of holiday in
return for working longer hours the rest of week. The aim is to allow workers
and their families time to enjoy the summer weather. PepsiCo also provides
a dependant care reserve account so that staff can pay for such care on
a pre-tax basis. Patagonia, a US outdoor-wear manufacturer, has gone one
step further and allows administrative staff, including nursing mothers,
to keep children with them as they work. <BR>
<BR>
Many German corporations have developed comprehensive &thorn;exible working
schemes that are available to workers throughout the company. In its human
resources pamphlet, BMW promises that &quot;every request to work part-time
will be met&quot;. About 16,000 BMW employees can use &thorn;exitime and
more than 1,600 work part-time and the &THORN;rm has a network of child-minders.
About half of the workers at Siemens work &thorn;exible hours, and 80% of
all employees at Schering AG enjoy &thorn;exible working. <BR>
<BR>
Barclays Bank is noteworthy because it is one of the few British companies
to provide a complete range of bene&THORN;ts. These include career breaks
of up to two years, up to 12 weeks' unpaid paternity leave for fathers and
52 weeks' maternity leave for mothers. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Few women at the upper end of the corporate hierarchy in the UK have
children and even they don't often make it to the top,&quot; states Perrins
from the LSE. It is a situation that is likely to continue, in Britain and
many other countries around the world, unless employers accept the need
for reform.<BR>
<BR>
 </td>
</tr>
</table>

