<h2>
July/August 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>

<H2>FROM THE EDITOR </H2>

<H3>The state of competition </H3>

<H4>The debate about comparing national performance and growth continues
to stimulate useful questions </H4>


The idea of measuring national performance by ranking a country's competitiveness
and potential for growth has made headlines again. The renewed attention
is partly due to an outbreak of competition in the world of competitiveness:
the initial findings of a rival report were rushed out before the World
Economic Forum's long-established version was published in a substantially
revamped form in May. <BR>
<BR>
The main reason, however, remains vanity: countries care how they rate,
even as they deride the ranking exercise. The public, and experts, also
like to compare and contrast. They get another chance to do so in this issue
of <I>World Link, </I>with a ranking of the top 100 companies in central
and eastern Europe, a Who's Who guide to leading business figures in the
region and an assessment of &quot;family-friendly&quot; policies in the
world's top corporations. <BR>
<BR>
After new criteria used by the Forum in <I>The Global Competitiveness Report
1996 </I>put France somewhat lower on the index than previously, for example,
President Jacques Chirac could be heard denouncing &quot;Davosian&quot;
thinking on globalisation, in an apparent reference to the site of the Forum's
annual summit. On the other side of the coin, there was suspicion in London
among critics of the current Conservative government when it was noted that
Britain did slightly better than before: at a press conference one journalist
went so far as to wonder if Downing Street had lobbied for an improved result.
<BR>
<BR>
Some critics con&thorn;ate a global perspective with the politics of &quot;small
government&quot;, believing that the economic liberal is identical with
the political conservative. Such a con&thorn;ation is limited and wrong,
especially because the old right-left argument about small versus large
government has begun to shift. In his new column in this issue, Jeffrey
Sachs does argue that government interference can harm growth. But he also
puts the state &THORN;rmly in centre stage. If you look closely at the case
for why competitiveness matters, it is that good or bad policies make all
the difference to economic success, and policies are made by governments.
The state is crucial because it is able to influence outcomes. <BR>
<BR>
On this point at least Sachs is in agreement with the World Bank, whose
recently issued 1997 Development Report explores the role of the state.
Re&thorn;ecting a growing trend in political economy, it argues that &quot;the
state and market are institutionally intertwined&quot; and an &quot;activist
government&quot; can play a key catalytic role. The old debate, positing
a clear choice between the state and the market, &quot;now seems to be over&quot;,
with the limits of each revealed: the new aim is to make sure that one does
not dominate the other. There is no simple &quot;the market solves everything&quot;
argument. <BR>
<BR>
While politics are bound to flavour debates about competitiveness, there
is a more interesting impetus behind the revised competitiveness report:
to acknowledge some of the useful criticism it has received in the past
few years and to use the report's comparative model as the basis for yet
more questioning. Let the debates and dissent continue. <BR>
<BR>
This magazine often likes to take a contrarian approach to issues. The reason
is that the contrarian approach, at its most serious, is most likely to
tell you something you did not already know and need to know, before everyone
else tells you. Even at its most trivial, it leaves room for humour and
imagination. <BR>
<BR>
It was such an approach that alerted readers of our January/February issue
to the importance of General Alexander Lebed in Russian politics. At the
time, other commentators dismissed him as marginal but this June's presidential
elections made Lebed an indispensable ally to Boris Yeltsin and perhaps
poised for future power. We hope to offer yet more insights.<BR>
<BR>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

