<tr>
<td>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<h2>
July/August 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>

<H2>COMMENT</H2>
<H4>Developments in Asia show why we need to integrate economic and security
issues in any foreign analysis </H4>
<H3>The new policy mix </H3>
In the Cold War years, business leaders and policymakers in the major nations
grew accustomed to thinking of economics and security separately. Security
was a matter of force deployments and strategies for using them. Economics
was about managing stable growth. <BR>
<BR>
Although many analysts probably recognised political-economic linkages in
the abstract, they felt them unnecessary to explain real-world events. The
political parameters of the world economy, with two superpowers and international
institutions such as Gatt for trade and Bretton Woods for the monetary system,
were relatively stable. <BR>
<BR>
The world has changed shape, however, and this division is no longer tenable.
Policies made with only one perspective - either political or economic
- will leave policymakers &THORN;ghting with one hand tied behind their
backs. The likely evolution of global affairs over the coming decade will
force a much more sophisticated integration of the two, re&thorn;ecting
their growing interaction. It will also mandate the emergence of new institutions
to neutralise the dangerous side-effects of this interaction. <BR>
<BR>
A key factor in the evolution of global affairs is the decisive new impact
being made by East Asia, which threatens to overshadow that of the Middle
East and eastern Europe. After petro-power collapsed in the early '80s,
Japan was the only rising economic power with the potential to challenge
the equilibrium of international relations. However, the country's insularity,
reactive political processes and limited military capacity severely blunted
its geopolitical impact. <BR>
<BR>
Nevertheless, as east Asia's dynamism expands beyond Japan, Hong Kong and
South Korea towards the massive continent of Asia and the Indonesian archipelago,
the region's influence will expand. <BR>
<BR>
There are three main reasons for this. The &THORN;rst is that global capital
resources will be disproportionately concentrated in the region because
of its persistent international competitiveness and trade surpluses. Together,
Japan and Greater China (including Taiwan and Hong Kong) hold close to two-thirds
of the world's foreign exchange reserves. Asia's economy makes up a third
of the global market. It accounts for more than 41% of global bank reserves,
having risen from 17% in Such surpluses are likely to continue for years,
playing a central role in global finance. <BR>
<BR>
A second reason is that these expanding economies are consuming more energy.
The International Energy Agency predicts that demand in Asia will grow at
twice the rate of the rest of the world over the next two decades. China,
which was a net oil exporter until November 1993, will emerge as a key global
importer: its imports will approach three million barrels a day by 2010.
By 2003, Indonesia too will be a net importer. With Asian imports of Mideast
oil rising, eastward traffic of oil through the Straits of Malacca should
triple within 15 years to make up more than 15% of global consumption. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Do not take stability for granted </B><BR>
<BR>
A third reason is that, despite the patterns of the past two decades, future
stability in Asia cannot be taken for granted. The most severe tensions
are likely to arise in northeast Asia where both Korea and China are changing
in historic and potentially disruptive ways. The Korean peninsula is on
the brink of sudden developments in north-south relations, including the
possibility of sudden reunification through a collapse of North Korea. A
Greater China is emerging with Hong Kong's reversion to Beijing's control
only a year away, Macao's reversion scheduled for 1999 and Taiwan's ties
to the mainland deepening despite missile tests and volatile political rhetoric.
Such developments are putting pressure on Japan's traditionally low-profile
posture. <BR>
<BR>
Perhaps the most important lesson about integrating economic and security
policies is the need to recognise the destabilising political and social
consequences of rapid growth. It can lead to more spending on arms and a
tighter regional energy market: this has already happened in Asia since
the late '80s. <BR>
<BR>
As arms races become more affordable they can become more deadly, especially
given the region's rising level of missile technology. Regional energy shortages,
which are likely to be most pronounced in northeast Asian nations such as
Korea, could have security implications. One possible consequence is that
Asian nations could become more reliant on nuclear power, including plutonium-generating
reprocessing. Another is that they could develop closer political and economic
relations with the Middle East, including Iran and possibly Iraq. Shortages
could also make Asian offshore oil reserves more strategic along with east
Gulf sea lanes and the nations bordering them, such as India and Indonesia.
<BR>
<BR>
East Asia's experience suggests that decision-makers may need to broaden
traditional definitions of security and expand the range of policies that
can support security. Energy can be a legitimate, indeed a priority, issue
for security attention. Both conservation and resource development policies
can be used to respond to security challenges. <BR>
<BR>
The region's development also shows that economic and technological muscle
can have long-term strategic implications. Indeed, the inexorable rise of
economic prowess has shifted the balance of power on the Korean peninsula
and forced a once-strong North Korea virtually to its knees. <BR>
<BR>
The clearest example from east Asia is probably the US-Japan Security Treaty,
which provides invaluable political risk insurance for $200 billion in Japanese,
American and other foreign investment in Asia outside Japan. This amount
has more than doubled in the past decade. Yet as controversies over trade
and the US military base in Okinawa suggest, popular and business support
for the broader framework of US-Japan relations is fluid and not universally
accepted. <BR>
<BR>
The volatile interaction of growth, arms and energy points to the future
importance of clearly directed multilateral institutions to complement existing
US-Japan arrangements. An excellent prototype is the Korean Peninsula Energy
Development Organisation, which the US, Japan and South Korea set up in
late 1994 to provide nuclear energy and heavy oil to North Korea. <BR>
<BR>
Such bodies are needed urgently in northeast Asia because there is little
international organisation or transnational interdependence in the region.
Also useful would be broader Asian institutions to help reduce the negative
effects of regional growth. <BR>
<BR>
An example would be an Asia Atom, modelled on European precedent, to supervise
the region's nuclear development. The area could also benefit from frameworks
for offshore resource extraction and balanced force reductions, as tensions
on the Korean peninsula subside. <BR>
<BR>
Finally, there is a need for both public and private institutional mechanisms
that force decision-makers to consider the economic and security dimensions
simultaneously. In the US, a possible approach would be to give the national
security adviser a second deputy for economic affairs, who would force a
discussion of economic and security trade-offs at top levels of government.
Another would be to restructure the energy department to focus more on international
dimensions. Broader public-private dialogues on Asian political risk assessment
are also in order. <BR>
<BR>
East Asia's expansion is unlikely to falter for some time and its growth
will have some unsettling effects. However, these can be understood and
dealt with in an integrated analysis.* <BR>
<BR>
<I>Kent E Calder, on leave at CSIS from Princeton University, is the author
of Asia's Deadly Triangle (London: Nicholas Brealey Publishing, 1996) <BR>
<BR>
By Kent E Calder, Japan Chair, The Centre for Strategic and International
Studies <BR>
</I>
 <BR>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
