<td valign=top align=left>

<H2>SACHS ON COMPETITIVENESS</H2>

<H4>In his new regular column, the Harvard economist gives a shorthand guide
to a nation's growth prospects </H4>

<H3>Why good policy matters <BR>
</H3>
<I>By Jeffrey Sachs, director of the Harvard Institute for International
Development <BR>
</I><BR>
At least since Adam Smith's <I>The Wealth of Nations</I> was published in
1776, economists, politicians and business people have debated the sources
of national prosperity. What economic system is most likely to promote growth
in output and living standards: free trade and private ownership or protectionism
and state ownership? <BR>
<BR>
In recent years, that debate has taken place under the rubric of international
competitiveness. Protagonists in the modern-day debate ask which system
is most likely to promote international competitiveness. In this context,
competitiveness means the ability of a nation's economy to make rapid and
sustained gains in living standards. One important yardstick of success
is the performance of other economies, especially those at comparable levels
of economic development. <BR>
<BR>
<I>The Global Competitiveness Report 1996</I>, published in May by the World
Economic Forum with the participation of our institute (see page 14), uses
a measurement designed to help assess each country's prospects for economic
growth. Formally, the competitiveness index aims to gauge the ability of
a national economy to achieve sustained high rates of economic growth measured
by annual changes in GDP per person. It is an attempt to measure growth
potential on a horizon of five to 10 years, not next year. Thus there is
less concern with the vagaries of national business cycles than with the
underlying trend rate of growth of the national economy, after smoothing
over fluctuations around the trend. <BR>
<BR>
The theoretical framework is based on modern economic growth theory, as
propounded for example by Robert Barro and Xavier Sala-I-Martin in <I>Economic
Growth. </I>In that theory, a nation's growth prospects depend on two main
factors: its initial income level and its particular characteristics, including
government policies, geography, educational base and other factors. <BR>
<BR>
For two countries with similar structural characteristics, the economic
theory predicts that the poorer country will grow faster than the richer
one. In modern economic jargon, the poorer country tends to converge with
the richer country. <BR>
<BR>
Convergence is expected for several reasons. In general, poorer countries
lack the technology, management and capital stock per person found in richer
countries. The theory predicts that the poorer country will be able to catch
up in these areas faster than the richer one will be able to make new advances.
It does so through direct imitation of the rich, by promoting higher rates
of national saving and through inflows of technology and capital from abroad.
<BR>
<BR>
The index attempts to summarise the structural characteristics of an economy,
other than initial per capita income, that are likely to determine the economy's
prospects for medium-term economic growth. Once these are measured, the
country's income level must still be taken into account in order to rank
growth prospects. For example, Luxembourg and Singapore have similarly high
ratings. Nonetheless, since Singapore still lags behind Luxembourg in per
capita income, the expectation is that Singapore will grow more rapidly
than Luxembourg in the future. <BR>
<BR>
<B>What new research can offer </B><BR>
<BR>
The competitiveness index is based on key underlying structural characteristics
of the national economies and an extensive and rapidly expanding body of
academic research on national economic growth. This academic literature
identifies several factors as key contributors to economic growth. <BR>
<BR>
In the new competitiveness report, such factors are measured on a consistent
cross-country basis and the results then summarised. It is then demonstrated
that the index indeed helps to account for cross-country economic growth
in the recent past and therefore presumably in the near future as well.
<BR>
<BR>
One of the key assumptions of the new study is that certain kinds of structural
characteristics can be measured with standard published data, while others
are better measured by opinion surveys. For example, economic theory suggests
that high marginal tax rates tend to retard growth. Tax rates can be measured
directly with standard and readily available data, as in the new study.
<BR>
<BR>
On the other hand, the quality of the judicial system in protecting property
rights and settling commercial disputes is also a structural characteristic
likely to influence economic growth. Unfortunately, there is no item in
the national accounts of a country that measures the efficiency, honesty
and predictability of the judiciary. However, one can consult the opinions
of key participants in the economy. <BR>
<BR>
For this reason, the competitiveness index is built upon the two pillars
of quantitative and survey data. The latter comes from a unique survey carried
out by the World Economic Forum of more than 2,000 business executives in
the 49 countries considered in the report. <BR>
<BR>
In the end, eight clusters of structural characteristics are employed which
we call the eight factors of competitiveness: openness of the economy to
international trade and finance; the role of the government budget and regulation;
development of financial markets; quality of infrastructure; quality of
technology; quality of business management; labour market flexibility and
quality of judicial and political institutions. <BR>
<BR>
A weighted average of indices of each of these structural characteristics
is taken to construct the single competitiveness index. Greatest weight
is given to the four factors with the strongest proven academic record of
explaining cross-country differences in growth, namely openness, government
budget and regulation, financial markets and labour markets. These four
factors are given a weight of three, infrastructure and technology a weight
of two and management and civil institutions a weight of one. Note that,
in general, this weighting corresponds to the percentage of quantitative
data in each of the factors; those with more quantitative data relative
to survey data have higher weight. <BR>
<BR>
The decision to give more importance to openness, finance, government and
labour is influenced by two considerations. First, academic studies of the
determinants of cross-country growth have found strong evidence for the
kinds of variables included in these factors, with different samples of
countries and with different time periods. <BR>
<BR>
Second, we have conducted our own statistical analysis of growth during
the most recent period (1992-1995) and have found these four factors to
be most strongly related to recent growth. <BR>
<BR>
In this way, an overall competitiveness index is arrived at. But the proof
of the pudding is in the eating. Does the index help to explain cross-country
patterns of economic growth? <BR>
<BR>
The answer is a resounding yes: competitiveness does matter. A nation's
economic policies - in world trade, finance, labour markets, judicial
reform and related areas - can have major effects on economic growth
on a sustained basis. The difference of good and bad economic policies can
amount to several percentage points of economic growth per year. One table
produced for the new report summarises the story. A scatter plot shows each
country's competitiveness rating and its rate of per capita economic growth
during 1993-95, looking at the relationship between competitiveness and
growth after controlling for each country's income level. <BR>
<BR>
The relationship is unmistakably positive: higher competitiveness, as measured
by the index, is strongly associated with more rapid economic growth. Statistical
significance means that the positive relationship is most likely not a random
accident of the data, in which just by chance the relationship is found
to be positive. <BR>
<BR>
The economic significance is even more important. It means that the differences
in economic growth attributed to differences in competitiveness are sizeable:
the gap between the most and least competitive countries in the sample,
Singapore and Brazil, is about 8.1% per year. <BR>
<BR>
Of course, the competitiveness index does not fully explain the cross-country
differences: for example, the growth in Malaysia and Singapore is higher
than predicted while in Switzerland and Luxembourg it is lower. <BR>
<BR>
There are several reasons for these discrepancies. For one thing, the underlying
theory of growth is imperfect to say the least. A single index cannot capture
all of the complex factors that contribute to growth. The weighting of the
underlying factors may be incorrect, any of the variables used are necessarily
measured with error or at least do not capture exactly what is needed and,
crucially, economies are subject to short-run shock of all types including
fluctuations in the terms of trade, domestic financial market movements
that may contribute to business cycles and so forth. The index is not geared
to capture these short-run movements. <BR>
<BR>
Nonetheless, as a practical shorthand guide to business and government,
we think that the competitiveness index has considerable value, as long
as it is interpreted with such caveats in mind. <BR>
<BR>
Our biggest concern is with the weighting of the underlying variables. A
few key variables, such as the rates of taxation, government saving, relative
labour costs and openness to trade, may be relevant to long-term growth
but under-weighted compared with other variables of lesser signi&THORN;cance.
Future reports will address this problem. <BR>
<BR>
The bottom line on competitiveness is that national economic policies, an
effective judiciary, &thorn;exible labour markets and a stable political
system all make a profound difference to economic growth in the medium term.
<BR>
<BR>
Infrastructure, management and technology also contribute, though these
factors are much harder to measure and their effects much more elusive.
These basic facts are becoming increasingly appreciated: indeed, they are
helping to orient market reforms around the world, with greater or lesser
recognition in different places. <BR>
<BR>
Since good policies produce good outcomes and since countries surely compete
to obtain good outcomes, the quest for national competitiveness can be an
important stimulus for much- needed policy reforms in many economies around
the world. <BR>
<BR>
<I>This article was written with Andrew Warner of the HIID</I> <BR>
<BR>
 </td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
