<!--May 1996-->
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
EMWL: World Link Magazine: July/August 1996
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="7C1568" text="000000" link="7C1568">

<center>
<font size=3>
<table border=0>
<tr>
<td colspan=2 align=left>
<nobr>
<img width=199 height=44 name="top" border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../images/conban8.gif" alt="World Link Magazine"><a href="../../../../../index.html"><img width=141 height=45 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../../images/conban1.gif" alt="EMWL Home"></a>
</nobr>
<br>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<h2>
July/August 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>
<H2>WITH THE FORUM </H2>

CHICAGO: NOBEL LAUREATES 
<H2>The world is getting richer </H2>
The world's production is rising much faster than its population according
to Merton Miller, Professor Emeritus of Finance at the University of Chicago.
He was addressing the World Economic Forum's industry summit held in the
city, in a session called The Chicago Nobel Factory. <BR>
<BR>
Miller, himself a Nobel laureate, said that far from production outstripping
resources as many people worried, people were getting richer. His figures
show that before the 18th century both world population and production grew
at between 0% and +0.3%. During the 19th century production rose by 1% and
population by 0.5% <BR>
<BR>
In the first half of the 20th century, despite two world wars those rates
doubled to 2% for production and 1% for population. And from 1950-85, production
rose by 4.5% and population by 2%. <BR>
<BR>
Contributions from the other four Chicago University Nobel laureates present
included Robert Fogel's statement that a human being's upper age limit was
about 135 years and Ronald Coase's reminder to environmentalists that when
horses instead of cars filled London's streets, &quot;the number of flies
was quite extraordinary&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
Fogel sought to put the discussion about economic growth into perspective:
&quot;<I>Homo sapiens</I> is only about 150,000 years old; we have only
had growth for the past 300 years. From the point of view of the human race,
there should be surprise at how fast [development] has happened.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
CHICAGO: PENSION REFORM 
<H2>The pension puzzle </H2>
A single middle-income American male who retired in 1970 received $25,000
more in social security than he contributed. By 2020 a man in the same circumstances
will have paid $88,000 more than he receives from the state, said Martin
Eichenbaum, an economics professor at Northwestern University, speaking
at a session on social security reform. <BR>
<BR>
Put another way, the US has a problem of implicit debt: add up all current
and future social security payments and total commitment amounts to 2.8
times GDP. Thomas Sargent of the University of Chicago said that to change
the system, debt would have to paid off by those in work before a new system
could be constructed. <BR>
<BR>
That would add the equivalent of 2% on income tax for a generation, making
this working generation suffer but the next far better off. Not only would
it cease to pay the 2% extra income tax, it could also be relieved of current
12% welfare contributions. Instead, workers would pay into a privately managed
personal scheme. <BR>
<BR>
Robert Gordon, chairman of the Northwestern economics department, gave some
examples. Using the social security system, an investment of $1,000 returned
$1,900. Using equities, the same return could be achieved from an investment
of just $250. He estimated that the cumulative effect of this investment
gap amounted to 10% of GDP. <BR>
<BR>
Yet the gains of privatising the system assume that the stock market continues
to perform as well as in the past. He said: &quot;The current rate of return
is 2%, but it is risk-free.&quot; If there were a major and sustained fall
in the rate of return, large sections of the population could be impoverished.
<BR>
<BR>
The panel kept returning to the difficulties of the present set-up. &quot;We
have higher rates of tax than we need now, in part to build up funds in
anticipation of the retirement of the baby-boomer generation,&quot; Gordon
said. The problems of the US system paled in comparison to those of Europe
and Japan, where population growth and immigration are even lower, leaving
fewer taxpayers to support the growing community of old people. <BR>
<BR>
At least part of the problem was the increase in life expectancy. &quot;Life
expectancy has gone up dramatically since the system began, but there has
been no increase in the retirement age to match,&quot; Eichenbaum said.
<BR>
<BR>
CHICAGO: CANCER 
<H2>Bombers or magic bullets? </H2>
Progress in biological understanding has been as great as advances of the
Industrial Revolution and half of all cancers are now curable, leading Chicago
University oncologist Samuel Hellman told the industry summit session &quot;Is
Cancer Curable?&quot; <BR>
<BR>
But Steven Rosen, director of the Lurie cancer centre at Northwestern University,
said that his experiences made him less optimistic than 10 years before.
He said the term cancer covered more than 100 diseases and incidence was
rising in the US, along with an ageing population. There would be modest
improvements in prevention, but no magic bullet cure. <BR>
<BR>
A more optimistic Glenn Steele said that within five years there should
be more understanding of growth control. Ralph Weichselbaum pointed out
that the key to tackling cholera in 19th-century London had been the chance
discovery of a link with plumbing. &quot;We may have [curative] drugs now
without yet knowing how to use them. This fight needs the sort of commitment
we put into the military.&quot; He said the cost of a B-1 bomber equals
that of the US's annual cancer budget. <BR>
<BR>
Rosen said there might soon be a blood test for colon cancer, &quot;but
then the insurance companies are going to fight like hell not to insure
those people&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
Asked about the prospects for new approaches such as gene therapy, Steele
suggested that there had been &quot;a certain natural process of over-selling&quot;
by people looking for grant money to fund research. <BR>
<BR>
SOUTHERN AFRICA: PRIVATISATION 
<H2>Utilities begin at home </H2>
Delegates at the Southern Africa Economic Summit in Cape Town in May were
treated to a fiery attack on South African government policy by Sam Shilowa,
general secretary of the trade union congress Cosatu, in the plenary session
on privatisation. Plans to privatise the main utility companies have been
delayed, partly because of union opposition. <BR>
<BR>
Shilowa spoke strongly against the privatisation project, just as president
Nelson Mandela gave it his firm backing during a visit to Bonn. &quot;We
are told we have to privatise the utilities because there is not enough
capacity. But telecoms, transport, electricity are delivered to whites and...
now Transtel supplies Zaire. Why should my money pay for Zaire?&quot; he
said in an outburst. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;My mother has no electricity in her home: the government cannot give
it to her. She still carries bundles of wood on her head. I don't want some
theory, I want someone to explain.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Finance minister Trevor Manuel said he could not believe that Cosatu was
so emphatically opposed to privatisation under all circumstances and argued
that it did bring efficiency gains. <BR>
<BR>
SOUTH AFRICA: DE KLERK 
<H2>De Klerk on life in opposition </H2>
Frederik De Klerk, the former deputy president of South Africa who recently
took his National Party out of the coalition government, spoke to participants
of the Forum's summit for the first time as a member of the opposition.
<BR>
<BR>
Explaining the move, he said the new constitution had no provision for power-sharing,
making a government of national unity an anachronism. &quot;We must achieve
a healthy and dynamic multi-party system. Otherwise we could drift into
a one-party state,&quot; he said. &quot;We will be a vigorous but responsible
opposition, more effective by adopting a critical role than by operating
behind the scenes.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Questioned about union leader Sam Shilowa's opposition to privatisation,
De Klerk pressed home his party's case, arguing that there were internal
divisions in the ruling ANC alliance.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There are those such as Mandela who feel a sense of urgency, but others
are afraid to put their foot down,&quot; he said. &quot;If privatisation
could be done easily in any country, it is in South Africa. Two years ago
we were ready to move very fast. All state companies had... achieved a degree
of autonomy [and] were operating in the market as if private.&quot; Instead
of acting quickly, the government set up teams to analyse privatisation
candidates. &quot;The process was logical, but it took too long,&quot; he
said. <BR>
<BR>
De Klerk also criticised the government's handling of the rand crisis and
its labour policy, which treads softly on union sensibilities. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;There is a need for a social pact [to contain crime] and a need for
flexible labour,&quot; he said. &quot;The country's biggest problem is unemployment.
We cannot over-protect the employed at the cost of the unemployed.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
There were questions about how the National Party (NP), with its legacy
of apartheid rule, would overcome the ethnic divide in South African politics
and appeal more to other groups. De Klerk said that more than half of all
NP voters were non-white, mainly from the Coloured or Asian communities.
The party was also targeting black ANC supporters. &quot;We are looking
at five to six million black South Africans to change their allegiance.
A new institute for political leadership is looking for young talent [and]
we will have a well-balanced list of candidates, reflecting the make-up
of the whole nation,&quot; he said. <BR>
<BR>
SOUTHERN AFRICA: INDIAN OCEAN RIM 
<H2>A new region is born </H2>
Mauritius came into the limelight at Cape Town in a session on the Indian
Ocean Rim (IOR). The island took the initiative in helping to set up an
IOR regional grouping that would comprise 14 of the 30 countries bordering
the Indian Ocean. A draft charter was approved in May. The group will have
a secretariat and will operate by consensus. <BR>
<BR>
Mauritian foreign minister PR Berenger said that the IOR grouping was not
a utopia but a vast new market in the making. He said Mauritius believes
the initiative complements the Southern Africa Development Community. <BR>
<BR>
Berenger said that groups representing government, private companies and
universities have met to discuss trade, transport and technology since a
March 1995 intergovernmental meeting. It was decided to include only sovereign
states but some entities may be allowed observer status. <BR>
<BR>
Berenger said Mauritius was well placed to coordinate the initiative because
it had modern facilities and was a member of both the English-speaking Commonwealth
and Francophonie. But Ronnie Bethlehem, representing South Africa on the
trade committee of the Nedlac regional grouping, said the aim was &quot;regional
integration without domination&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
Gavin Maasdorp, director of the University of Natal's economic research
unit, echoed the potential benefits. &quot;With trade blocs, too many countries
join without doing the necessary homework on costs and benefits. This is
loose grouping like Asean when it started. Each country has some competitive
advantage that it can exploit.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
When asked if the focus of South African trade would shift from Europe to
Asia, Maasdorp said trade patterns would not change overnight. Despite the
development of a culture in South Africa more oriented to the Third World,
trade with Europe was sticking at 46% of the total. <BR>
<BR>
Trade with countries of the Indian Ocean Rim is rising from 2.8% 1990 to
8.8% in 1994, mostly with east Africa, but the increase may partly reflect
trade that used to be disguised under anti-apartheid sanctions, Maasdorp
said. <BR>
<BR>
Maasdorp argued that the 13 landlocked countries that depend on IOR ports
should join the grouping. Berenger felt this was unrealistic. &quot;Where
do we stop? We started with seven countries and moved up to 14. We decided
to stop there and show concrete results before becoming bigger.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
MERCOSUR ECONOMIC SUMMIT 
<H2>Presidents together again </H2>
Six presidents were the highlight of the World Economic Forum's second Mercosur
Economic Summit, held in Buenos Aires in June. At the end of the summit's
first full day, presidents Fernando Henrique Cardoso of Brazil, Carlos Sa&uacute;l
Menem of Argentina, Juan Carlos Wasmosy of Paraguay and Julio Mar&iacute;a
Sanguinetti of Uruguay together declared their faith in the benefits of
Mercosur, the trade grouping of the four nations. <BR>
<BR>
To close the summit, presidents Eduardo Frei of Chile and Gonzalo S&aacute;nchez
de Lozada of Bolivia, whose countries are joining Mercosur as associate
members, reaffirmed the region's dramatic changes: the Chile/Bolivia relationship
was once characterised by wars and sabre-rattling rather than smiles and
handshakes. <BR>
<BR>
Menem said Mercosur gives member nations the ability &quot;to do collectively
what we cannot do individually&quot;. Cardoso was more explicit: &quot;In
the next millennium we want to be actors. We want to be at the negotiating
tables. For this we have to be together.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The optimism and warmth between the presidents contrasted sharply with the
mood of the first Mercosur Economic Summit, held in June last year in S&atilde;o
Paulo. Then, Brazil and Argentina were rowing over auto production and exports.
Cardoso dismissed the affair: &quot;It was not a crisis. It was a little
problem that [Menem and I] solved over lunch at the summit.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
All of the presidents looked forward to building on Mercosur's achievements
in increasing intra-regional trade. They agreed that improved transport
infrastructure was a priority to realise the dream of linking Chile's access
to the Pacific, through Paraguay and Bolivia, to the Atlantic access of
Brazil, Uruguay and Argentina. <BR>
<BR>
Comparisons with Mercosur's major trade and investment partner, the EU,
were frequent. Leaders of the five-year old Mercosur emphasised that the
EU has had 40 years to reach its present level of integration. However,
all of the presidents were adamant that the Latin American regional grouping
would develop without the formation of an EU-like bureaucracy. <HR>
<H3>SOUNDBITES</H3>
&quot;I come from the University of Chicago. I'm not used to being called
a socialist.&quot; <BR>
<I>Professor Thomas Sargent during a discussion on reforming social security
</I><BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's the equivalent of trying to get to the moon by running and jumping.&quot;<BR>
<I>Professor Steven Rosen of Northwestern University on the use of alternative
medicine to cure cancer </I><BR>
<BR>
&quot;I like these sessions. They allow us to pool our ignorance.&quot;<BR>
<I>James McClung, vice-president, executive marketing, FMC Corp </I><BR>
<BR>
&quot;A number of senior executives at Mobil, including my boss, went out
and cleaned windows so they could talk to customers.&quot;<BR>
<I>Brian Baker, general manager of east and Gulf coast business, Mobil Oil
Corp </I><BR>
<BR>
&quot;I've allowed minister Stella Sigcau to overstep her time because it
is important for you to hear directly from her. Besides, she is my boss.&quot;<BR>
<I>Saki Macozoma, deputy managing director of Transnet, South Africa</I>
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We do discuss problems with the banking sector, but moral suasion
does not work very well when you have up to 50 banks competing with each
other.&quot;<BR>
<I>Christian Stals, governor of South Africa's reserve bank, on the recent
rand crisis</I> <BR>
<BR>
&quot;When we export raw materials to the developed world, we never have
any problems. When we export anything with added value, there are always
problems.&quot;<BR>
<I>Eduardo Frei, president of Chile</I> <BR>
<BR>
&quot;There will be problems. But if we didn't have problems, what would
we be doing as politicians?&quot; <I>Fernando Henrique Cardoso, president
of Brazil</I> <BR>
 </td>
</tr>
</table>

