<H2>REVIEW</H2>

<H3>Polemical theory </H3>
Pop Internationalism <BR>
<BR>
By Paul Krugman <BR>
MIT Press, &#163;14.95<B> </B>and $22.50 <BR>
<BR>
<I>Reviewed by Paul Hirst</I> <BR>
<BR>
Paul Krugman is a leading international trade theorist and an accomplished
polemicist. In this collection of essays he uses both these skills to tackle
some of his favourite <I>b&ecirc;tes noires</I> which are already familiar
to readers of this magazine, especially the idea of comparing national performance
in competitiveness rankings (see page 14 and <I>World Link</I>, September/October
1995). <BR>
<BR>
Krugman is determined to challenge the myth of trade as national competition
and he puts up a very good and useful fight. It is a shame, therefore, that
although each essay reads well on its own the collective impact is repetitive:
the book could have done with a good deal of editing. <BR>
<BR>
His main target is the prevalent idea that in a globalising economic system
modern industrial nations - like corporations - are engaged in
a competitive struggle for shares of world trade and winners can only succeed
at the expense of losers. The key aim of government policy, therefore, must
be to promote the country's &quot;competitiveness&quot;. Such rhetoric spans
the political spectrum: some, like Ross Perot, think foreign competition
destroys jobs and the only antidote is protectionist tariffs while others,
like Lester Thurow, propose active industrial policies. <BR>
<BR>
Krugman is opposed to both sides and hammers home the thesis that the enlargement
of markets through the reduction of trade barriers will promote growth and
overall prosperity. Along the way, his opponents are dismissed as either
economic illiterates or as people blinded by their beliefs. <BR>
<BR>
Unfortunately this means he can be excessively polemical and unfair, especially
when he poses as the poor sidelined economics professor who just happens
to be right. In fact his belief in gains from trade is mainstream and has
driven the two great recent moves toward trade liberalisation, the Single
Market of the EU and the successful conclusion of the Uruguay Round of GATT.
Someone must be listening. <BR>
<BR>
Lester Thurow in particular does not merit the ridicule he receives here.
Krugman is violently opposed to the US Democratic Party sympathisers who
advocate a strategic trade and industrial policy. In part the difference
stems from the degree of confidence in the free market. Thurow has long
argued that markets alone will not guarantee a productive economy and looked
for ways to reverse the very domestic processes of slow growth and investment
decline in the US that Krugman himself acknowledges as a problem. <BR>
<BR>
Krugman marshals a mass of empirical evidence to prove his argument about
free trade, making fools of its more naive opponents. Thus Nafta was supposed
to result in the loss of thousands of jobs to Mexico and threaten US wage
levels for unskilled work. However tariffs on manufactured goods were already
low (4%), which logically should have already led to the large-scale collapse
of American employment. The truth is that the Mexican minnow was never big
enough to alter US wage levels to any serious extent. <BR>
<BR>
His main point in these essays is that firms, not nations, are competitive.
A firm has to sell all its output, in other words to &quot;export&quot;.
Nations export only a fraction of their output and many goods and services
are not tradable on world markets. Nations have options that companies do
not. Countries can devalue and thus change the terms of trade and generally
have a comparative advantage in some sectors. <BR>
<BR>
In the main, Krugman says, jobs are not being lost in the advanced world
because of import penetration: the scale of losses is too big for that.
The cause is closer to home, from productivity gains and the increasing
relative importance of services. He also argues that Third World industrialisation
is not hurting First World prosperity. <BR>
<BR>
Exports of manufactured goods from newly industrialising countries still
represent a tiny fraction of the developed world's GDP, just 1.2% in 1990.
Wages in successful nations such as South Korea are rising rapidly and offer
the prospect of a win-win outcome in which newly affluent Asian consumers
create large markets for western goods and services. <BR>
<BR>
Krugman insists that advanced countries should neither fear a massive loss
of jobs and output to low-wage countries nor drive down wages to compete
with Third World workers, most of whose activities cannot be traded internationally.
Jakarta barbers cannot displace those in New Jersey. <BR>
<BR>
Whatever its limits in dealing with industrial and technology policy, Krugman's
analysis should help to dispel some western fears about international competition
and the threat of low-wage countries. But free trade is not a panacea: only
an elite of non-western countries are prospering and benefiting from foreign
investment. We need other policies to address the fact that the world remains
distressingly divided between rich and poor nations. 
<H2>Red revolution </H2>
Tell Newt To Shut Up <BR>
<BR>
By David Maraniss and Michael Weisskopf <BR>
Simon &amp; Schuster, $10 <BR>
<BR>
<I>Reviewed by Emily Spencer</I> <BR>
<BR>
At the beginning of his political career, Newt Gingrich was so desperate
to run the Republican Party's long-term planning department that he was
forever bombarding it with policy suggestions. The running joke was that
staff had a wall of filing cabinets full of Newt's Ideas and only a solitary
cabinet of Newt's Good Ideas. <BR>
<BR>
Whatever else might be said about the man who two years ago took control
of the US House of Representatives, his Contract with America, by which
Gingrich promised to change the relationship between rulers and ruled, was
a good idea. Even if it turns out to have been a disaster in the longer
term (polls suggest the Democrats will win the congressional vote in November)<B>,</B>
the contract was credited with returning the House to Republican control
for the first time in 40 years. <BR>
<BR>
Yet the supposed architect of this triumph is an ambiguous figure in the
minds of many Republicans. The title of this book is an echo of the message
sent to the House speaker by Republicans worried by his apparently endless
stream of public gaffes. <BR>
<BR>
This is Newt's story, but it is far more than that. It is also a book about
his allies, the congressmen imbued with a near-fanatical loathing for government
interference. It is a tale of Washington's inside-outsiders; the representatives
of a party long denied congressional power who plotted and planned and then
blew their big chance. <BR>
<BR>
But it is also a book in the best traditions of American journalism. The
project is a detailed, carefully researched, well-written and revealing
account of the new Republican Party's attempt at a constitutional revolution.
<I>Washington Post</I> reporters David Maraniss and Michael Weisskopf conducted
more than 300 interviews and drew on many other primary sources. Occasionally,
the large cast of characters is confusing for those whose knowledge of the
subject is less than encyclopaedic. <BR>
<BR>
The Republicans were fixated by the need to roll back government, but they
soon found themselves in deep water. Planning to slash the budgets of regulatory
bodies overseeing safety at work and the environment, they allowed business
lobbyists to hijack the legislative drafting process and in the process
forgot the little guy so central to their own rhetoric. As a result, at
least some of those little guys will be voting Democrat this autumn. <BR>
<BR>
Still more divisive were plans to reduce welfare programmes such as the
Medicare healthcare scheme for the elderly and the school lunch programme
that provides the only nutritious meal of the day for many children in the
southern US. <BR>
<BR>
This last issue was an unmitigated public relations disaster, according
to the authors. It was also the moment when the Republican revolution exposed
its flank to the Democrats. The incomers have suffered ever since from variations
on the Democrat theme that Gingrich and Co were taking food from needy children
to finance tax cuts for the rich. This was compounded by Gingrich's unerring
ability to seek out a political accident and fall victim to it. He claimed
that drug abuse was commonplace at the White House, insulted Hillary Clinton
and re&thorn;ected that orphanages might be expanded to slow America's social
disintegration. <BR>
<BR>
At the heart of it all was Newt, ruefully discovering that winning power
is one thing and keeping it another. He had to transform himself from a
firebrand who stoked up the Republican revolution to a sober political negotiator.
This was, and remains, a painful and incomplete metamorphosis. <BR>
<BR>
Although Gingrich was initially a dealmaker between his party's moderates
and right-wingers, he increasingly lost influence as disagreements with
the Clinton administration over the budget brought congress to a halt. <BR>
<BR>
At the start of last year commentators were speculating that Gingrich might
run for president. No longer. Yet the book still offers a valuable insight
into the Republican Party and its factions, whatever happens in November.
<H2>Asia's nanny state </H2>
The Missionary and the Libertine: Love and War in East and West <BR>
<BR>
By Ian Buruma<BR>
Faber and Faber, &#163;16.99 <BR>
<BR>
<I>Reviewed by Anthony Hyman</I> <BR>
<BR>
Singapore has just passed a law giving its aged citizens the right to financial
help from their offspring. It is another aspect of what author Ian Buruma
calls the Nanny State of Asia, whose peculiarities are sketched adeptly,
as is its long-time leader, Lee Kuan Yew. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Harry&quot; Lee actually used to describe himself as an Anglicised
Chinaman. Now, along with other authoritarian figures in the region, he
espouses Asian values, numbing the free expression of the otherwise fortunate
and prosperous citizens of the island state. <BR>
<BR>
Old clich&eacute;s about east and west have been dramatically reversed with
the rise of Asia's economic tigers. It is no longer the east that is usually
thought of as indolent and decadent compared with a disciplined and puritanical
west. Instead, western politicians loudly praise it for its superior discipline
and industriousness. Buruma argues that for many people in China, Japan,
Singapore, Malaysia and South Korea, &quot;Europe and the United States
are now models not of masculine vim but... of decadence, libertinism and
sloth&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
Cultural interaction has been going on for many generations. It was European
literature, after all, that liberated love for the Japanese, with romantic
love becoming for the first time a serious subject for writers. Yet the
sex, violence or cruelty so common in Japanese entertainment is, in some
cases, a sign of political desperation. The popular appetite for sexual
fantasy in Japanese literature is &quot;the institutionalised escape from
an oppressive society&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
Buruma, who lived and worked for a long time in Asia, surveys the scene
with a shrewd eye. Thus Tokyo comes to life as a city where the machine
age becomes somehow human. <BR>
<BR>
The sinister link between nation-building and sports is illuminated here.
South Korea craves recognition as a great nation, writes Buruma, and gold
medals at the Seoul Olympics and other sports events satisfy this yearning.
The pressure on Korean athletes is cruel but effective, as it was in communist
East Germany. The downside is that the nationalistic state media often fosters
xenophobia in its sports coverage, hampering any opening of Korean society.
<BR>
<BR>
On to the Philippines and Imelda Marcos, who felt very sincerely that the
US had betrayed the Marcos regime. South Asia is included too in portraits
of two Indian intellectuals, filmmaker Satyajit Ray and Nirad Chaudhuri,
and of Pakistan's Benazir Bhutto and her populist politics. <BR>
<BR>
The complex, often tortured relationship between east and west has a sensitive
interpreter in Buruma. His book shows clearly that myths are pervasive and
have a life of their own. A residue of western clich&eacute;s about the
inscrutable east dating from the age of imperialism still persist in popular
novels, even in more sophisticated thrillers such as the best-seller <I>Rising
Sun</I> by Michael Crichton. <BR>
<BR>
The historical burden also colours US-Japanese relations, still haunted
by the ghosts of Pearl Harbour and Hiroshima. In the US there are also the
professional Cassandras with their visions of doom. &quot;On the subject
of American decline, they tend to sound like French nationalists after losing
the war with Prussia in 1871. It is as though the virility of the nation
were at stake,&quot; Buruma writes. If Asian writers and publicists reciprocate
in kind with their own myths about the west, it is because we each seem
to need the alien other.<BR>
<BR>
<HR><BR>
<BR>
In 1985 Conrad Black, the Canadian businessman,  took over The Daily Telegraph
and became a British newspaper proprietor. Soon afterwards, as Richard Siklos
writes in &quot;Shades of Black, Conrad Black and the world's fastest growing
press empire&quot; (Heinemann, &#163;20), a letter from Black to The Spectator
went some way to revealing the views of the new man. Black's target was
the liberal journalist Christopher Hitchens, who had written a piece on
Ronald Reagan's state of health. Black declared that readers deserved &quot;better
than Hitchens's nasty, macabre, vulgar and insolent claptrap&quot;. He also
knocked the British press corps in Washington for its &quot;habitually snobbish&quot;
reports on the US. <BR>
<BR>
Black arrived in the UK unknown and with little more than three university
degrees, a string of small newspapers and a sharp tongue. (Black described
the author of an unkind review of his biography of former Quebec premier
Maurice Duplessis as having the &quot;professional ethics of a cockroach&quot;.)
<BR>
<BR>
Siklos kindly describes Black as &quot;hyperliterate&quot;, an indication
of the biographer's treatment of his subject. The book was written with
Black's cooperation and Siklos works for a newspaper part-owned by Black.
<BR>
<BR>
Black is a man both intimidating and serious, with a passion for military
history and Napoleon Bonaparte. He is depicted as dull at times, but consistent.
He has always railed against the left and successfully pursued wealth. During
the '60s, while others his age indulged in the liberal politics of the &thorn;ower
generation, Black spurned their paci&THORN;sm and clothing: he wore a three-piece,
pinstripe suit. <BR>
<BR>
Long before this, he had shown a cheerful disregard for what interested
other children. As a boy, Siklos relates, Black washed dollar bills in soap
and water and hung them to dry. Despite these anecdotes, the book lacks
colour: this is far from a searching insight into Black's character or his
motives. <BR>
<BR>
Siklos's excessively detailed description of Black's business activities
fails to compensate. He traces their development from early ventures in
Canada and his penetration of the US business community to the moment he
became a true press tycoon in 1985. <BR>
<BR>
The author's most lucid business account is of Black's acquisition of the
Telegraph papers from the Berry family in 1985-86, showing how unprepared
the old feudal set-up was to deal with such a determined predator. <BR>
<BR>
The book succeeds in portraying Black as a man of qualities. The author
points out that his subject knows more about 19th-century British politics
than Lady Thatcher. When Black told Thatcher that her reforms were more
important than the regicide of Charles I and the unceremonious disposal
of James II during the Glorious Revolution, the &thorn;attered prime minister
replied: &quot;That is very good, Mr Black. Do come back.&quot; 
<BR>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

