<H2>WORLD ECONOMIC FORUM, INSIGHTS </H2>
<IMG SRC="images/wl.96.04.12.gif" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="78"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The World Economic Forum is today the foremost international membership
organization integrating leaders from business, government and academia
into a partnership committed to improving the state of the world. Through
global, ef&THORN;cient, direct, personalized and highest-level interaction,
the World Economic Forum serves its members and constituents to de&THORN;ne
their agenda for action. The core community of the World Economic Forum
are the 1,000 foremost global companies. <BR>
<BR>
Incorporated since 1971 as a foundation, the World Economic Forum is independent,
impartial and not-for-pro&THORN;t, tied to no political, partisan or national interests.
It has consultative status with the United Nations. The motto of the World
Economic Forum is &quot;Entrepreneurship in the global public interest&quot;.

<H3>Membership News </H3>
Members of the World Economic Forum are not individuals but companies, which
are represented at the highest level of management. Each member should be
characterised by:<BR>
<UL>
  <LI>its global dimension or the strategy to grow in that direction 
  <LI>a top management that is forward-looking and of high reputation 
  <LI>a healthy organization - respected, growing and ethical. 
</UL>
<BR>
The World Economic Forum currently has two categories of membership: <BR>
<BR>
<B>Foundation Membership</B> <BR>
<BR>
In principle, Foundation membership is made up of the 1,000 foremost global
enterprises. In addition to the above general criteria, each is characterised
by the following speci&THORN;c attributes: 
<UL>
  <LI>a  signi&THORN;cant role in shaping the future of its industry and/or
region 
  <LI>the ability and willingness of its top management to contribute to
international cooperation and economic and social progress. 
</UL>
<BR>
<B>Global Growth Company Membership</B> <BR>
<BR>
Global Growth Companies are some of the world's fastest-growing business
groups. Each is characterised by the following speci&THORN;c attributes:
<BR>
<UL>
  <LI>a signi&THORN;cant role in shaping its industry as a niche producer,
a technological leader or an entrepreneurial innovator 
  <LI>the ability and willingness of its top management to network with
like-minded enterprises around the world. 
</UL>
<BR>
In order to integrate the advice of its members into the decision-making
process of the Foundation, the Council of the World Economic Forum has been
established. <BR>
<BR>
In 1996 the Council, presided by George Mallinckrodt, is composed of Rahul
Bajaj, Franco Bernab&eacute;, John H. Bryan, Hubert Burda, T. Neal Chapman,
Ronnie C. Chan, Bertrand Collomb, Oscar Fanjul, Hermann O. Franz, M. Sha&THORN;k
Gabr, Joseph T. Gorman, Cor A.J. Herkstroter, Jaakko V.A. Ihamuotila, E.
Neville Isdell, Donald R. Keough, Nemir A. Kirdar, Yoh Kurosawa, J. Martin
K. Laing, Gernot A. Langes-Swarovski, Kenneth L. Lay, Arne Martensson, Yuzaburo
Mogi, Minoru Murofushi, Masafumi Ohnishi, John B. Prescott, James J. Schiro,
Christopher A. Sinclair, Sarik Tara, Paulo D. Villares, John Zabriskie and
Lorenzo H. Zambrano. It re&thorn;ects an optimal sectoral and regional representation
of members. 
<H3>Industry Summit </H3>
Chicago, 12-15 May <BR>
<BR>
Globalization was again a theme on the working agenda of the World Economic
Forum's Regional Summits. At the Industry Summit in Chicago on 12-15 May,
500 global business leaders, experts and policymakers gathered to discuss
global business concerns ranging from the reform of the social security
system to management-related issues. <BR>
<BR>
Laura D'Andrea Tyson, National Economic Adviser to the President of the
United States, opened the meeting on 12 May at the University of Chicago
by saying that history has shown that when internationalism has prevailed
over protectionism and isolationism in US foreign economic policy, both
the US and international market have bene&THORN;ted. She said it was the
policy of the Clinton administration to compete and not retreat, and to
keep the &THORN;scal house in order while bringing down international barriers.
<BR>
<BR>
Asked by Klaus Schwab, President of the World Economic Forum, what issues
are the most crucial in the not-too-distant future, Tyson said that technology
and globalization have exacerbated differences in income and in opportunities
both between countries and between individuals within countries to such
an extent that the biggest challenge will be to empower those who feel threatened
by change. <BR>
<BR>
Set in Chicago, at the heart of the world's largest domestic market, the
three-day meeting brought together industry leaders from 40 countries to
contribute to sector-speci&THORN;c discussions in &THORN;nancial services,
energy, health and seven other industries. Participants also welcomed the
opportunity to present their views on the liberalization of the &THORN;nancial
services industries as being negotiated in the WTO at this point in time
during a seminar between leaders of EU and US &THORN;nancial services industries
and top of&THORN;cials of the EU Commission and US Treasury Department.
The meeting provided an opportunity to begin to identify practical ways
of collaboration between the US and European &THORN;nancial services sectors.
<BR>
<BR>
Held at the University of Chicago and Northwestern University, the meeting
proved that a real dynamic can take place between academia and business.
Some 40 CEOs and entrepreneurs from the Chicago Inc establishment participated
in the 70 working sessions and worked together as a host committee alongside
almost a hundred alumni to help put together the event. <BR>
<BR>
On the second day, &THORN;ve out of the last six Nobel Laureates in Economics,
who have all come from the University of Chicago's distinguished faculty,
formed a panel chaired by Hugo Sonnenschein, President of the University
of Chicago, to address issues in leadership, motivation and the questioning
of the status quo. They were Gary S. Becker, (1992 Laureate), Ronald H.
Coase (1991 Laureate), Robert W. Fogel (1993 Laureate), Robert E. Lucas
Jr (1995 Laureate) and Merton H. Miller (1990 Laureate). 
<H3>Turkey Meeting </H3>
Ankara <BR>
<BR>
18-19 April <BR>
<BR>
A few weeks earlier, the World Economic Forum held a timely meeting in Turkey
between 150 international and Turkish senior executives and key political
&THORN;gures of the new coalition government. <BR>
<BR>
After months of a political vacuum, Turkey's government was keen to discuss
its economic programme with the international business community and to
restore con&THORN;dence in the country's future economic potential, said
Frederic Sicre, Member of the Executive Board and Coordinator of the Turkey
Meeting. <BR>
<BR>
Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz opened the meeting in Ankara on 18 April speaking
on the future political, economic and social stability in Turkey. Several
ministers and leaders of the opposition including Necmettin Erbakan, Chairman
of the Welfare Party, also participated. Animated discussions punctuated
the two-day meeting between government and business leaders. Following are
excerpts from the concrete recommendations put together by the participants
for the Turkish government to help it determine an action plan for Turkey's
future economic priorities: <BR>
<DL>
  <DD>In the preparation for Customs Union: 
</DL>
<UL>
  <LI>Customs Union negotiations have reached a delicate stage. Short- and
medium-term goals need to be reviewed and prioritized so as to be more proactive.
  <LI>Rules and regulations on trade need to be synchronized with EU directives
as much as possible. 
  <LI>Imports into Turkey are slowed by the mandatory inspection by the
Ministry of Health. Turkish customs of&THORN;cer need to be better trained
as to developments in EU-Turkey trade. 
</UL>
<DL>
  <DD>In privatization: 
</DL>
<UL>
  <LI>need to clearly de&THORN;ne and communicate Government objectives
  <LI>empower the Privatization Administration to carry out the privatization
programme effectively and ef&THORN;ciently over the next three to four years.
Assign one strong privatization leader. 
  <LI>Build trust with national and international investors through transparent
decision processes and decision criteria and address unavoidable social
aspects 
  <LI>Prioritize all companies in the privatization portfolio according
to government priorities and market interest. 
</UL>
<DL>
  <DD>In &THORN;nancial services: 
</DL>
<UL>
  <LI>Harmonization of taxation on &THORN;nancial instruments and reduction
of the costs associated with &THORN;nancial transactions on foreign exchange,
money and capital markets; lowering of stamp duties; and lowering of reserve
requirements 
  <LI>The establishment of specialized courts to deal with &THORN;nancial
cases. Set up a regulatory framework for factoring 
  <LI>Limiting the unfair competition provided by state-owned banks 
</UL>
<DL>
  <DD>In manufacturing: 
</DL>
<UL>
  <LI>Implementation of an in&thorn;ation accounting system 
  <LI>Lowering high real interest rates to help capital investment. 
</UL>
<BR>
Although foreign and Turkish participants showed concern with the present
political situation, they seemed con&THORN;dent that in the medium- to long-term
Turkey's key advantages in terms of its sheer size and quality of its workforce
will allow it to become an important bridge between Asia and Europe. Already,
strong links have developed between Turkey and Russia, said one of Turkey's
leading businessman Rahmi Koc. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="insights/Logo%20WEF%20Syntax%20ill.3.GIF" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="78"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
<BR>
<H3>Future Meetings</H3>
<H3>Central and East European Economic Summit </H3>
Salzburg 7-9 July <BR>
<BR>
For years, the World Economic Forum has pioneered the opening of the countries
of this area and their integration into the global economy. Now, the World
Economic Forum welcomes the international business community to the &THORN;rst
Central and East European Economic Summit under the patronage of President
Thomas Klestil of Austria. <BR>
<BR>
The focus of the Summit is on the countries of the region and their neighbours
- Austria, Germany and Russia - and will stress the importance
of the region as a whole in the wider European context. It will point to
the need to develop both the infrastructure and the business links capable
of raising local capital, attracting foreign investment and promoting trade
and industry. We also will look closely at the thrust towards European integration
and the search for collective security arrangements. 
<H3>1996 Asia Summits </H3>
<B>Three exceptional Summits this autumn will bring businessmen up to date
on the latest economic, &THORN;nancial and business developments taking
place in the most dynamic part of the world.</B> <BR>
<BR>
<B>China Business Summit</B> <BR>
<BR>
Beijing <BR>
<BR>
16-18 September <BR>
<BR>
Bolstered by a sustained period of growth, China must now contain in&thorn;ationary
pressures and rein in the development of some of its most successful provinces.
Our Summit will address the most salient questions related to this new phase
of economic maturity and help foreign investors position themselves in the
newly reshaped environment. As the handover of Hong Kong approaches, participants
may also be able to assess China's new role on the world's economic scene
and its position among other markets in the Asia-Paci&THORN;c region. <BR>
<BR>
Senior government of&THORN;cials, top Chinese and foreign experts, Chinese
business leaders, as well as senior executives from companies involved in
China will be the key discussion partners during the Summit, held in partnership
with the China Enterprise Management Association (CEMA) under the patronage
of the State Economic and Trade Commission. <BR>
<BR>
<B>India Economic Summit</B> <BR>
<BR>
New Delhi <BR>
<BR>
27-29 October <BR>
<BR>
Following India's June elections our Summit will be a unique opportunity
to meet with key members of the new cabinet and thus help to relieve foreign
investors' uncertainties concerning the future course of liberalization.
<BR>
<BR>
Two key issues to be addressed at the Summit (held in partnership with the
Confederation of Indian Industry, CII) will be identifying new opportunities
for partnerships and cooperation and improving the environment for domestic
and foreign companies as the Indian economy builds on current strong results,
especially in the industrial sector. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Europe/East Asia Economic Summit</B> <BR>
<BR>
Hong Kong <BR>
<BR>
18-20 November <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Partnership in Growth&quot;: the &THORN;fth Europe/East Asia Economic
Summit (held in partnership with the Hong Kong Trade Development Council)
will re&thorn;ect the enhanced business, trade, &THORN;nancial and technological
ties between these two industrialized poles and will thus constitute a business
complement to this year's government summit. Given the backing of EU governments,
European enterprises are now gearing up for overseas expansion in an effort
to boost their competitiveness in Asia. The Summit programme will draw attention
to some new trends in Asian investment in Europe. As the Summit will be
the last opportunity for high-level discussions before the WTO ministerial
meeting in Singapore, trade issues will feature prominently on the agenda.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Autumn 1996</B> <BR>
<BR>
China Business Summit, Beijing <BR>
16-18 September <BR>
<BR>
India Economic Summit, New Delhi <BR>
27-29 October <BR>
<BR>
Middle East/North Africa Economic Summit, <BR>
Cairo 12-14 November <BR>
<BR>
Europe/East Asia Economic Summit, <BR>
Hong Kong 18-20 November <BR>
<BR>
For further information on membership of the World Economic Forum and on
its meetings, please contact Claude Smadja, Managing Director, World Economic
Forum, 53 chemin des Hauts-Cr&ecirc;ts, 1223 Cologny Geneva Switzerland
<BR>
<BR>
Telephone: <BR>
+41 22 736 0243 <BR>
<BR>
Telefax: <BR>
+41 22 786 2744 
