<td valign=top>
<h2>
July/August 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>

<H2>TECHNOLOGY</H2>

<H4>Competition is growing in the world of industrial espionage as official
spooks get into an old business </H4>
<H3>Spies like U.S. </H3>
An American businessman went to France a few years ago for negotiations
with a leading company. At a meeting with his French opposite numbers, the
man was appalled to see that they had a copy of his papers, complete with
the notes he had made in his hotel room the night before. In the ensuing
confrontation, the French admitted they had been given the document by government
agents<B>.</B> <BR>
<BR>
This widely reported story may seem apocryphal but it illustrates the ease
with which competitors can obtain con&THORN;dential information. Of course,
industrial espionage is as old as the hills. But according to some experts
the problem is growing. <BR>
<BR>
A new<B> </B>study by the American Society for Industrial Security suggests
that US companies lose $2 billion a month as a result of espionage, often
by foreign governments. In the colourful words of US Senator Arlen Specter,
chairman of the senate intelligence committee: &quot;We are being skinned
alive by foreigners who use cut- throat practices to steal our secrets.
That's taking away a lot of American jobs.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
There are three reasons for this possible growth in spying. Firstly, with
the fall of the Iron Curtain intelligence agencies have been forced to reinvent
themselves and commercial espionage is an obvious route. This is confirmed
by Wayne Madson, a computer security specialist based in North Virginia,
who has worked for US security organisations. &quot;The huge intelligence
community now has to justify its existence. Its large in-built infrastructure
needs to find something to do,&quot; he says. <BR>
<BR>
A second and related point is that any growth in industrial espionage will
be matched by an equal or greater growth in industrial counter-espionage.
Growth in the spy world fuels itself and gives spies a reason to exaggerate
the extent of the problem. In the US, estimates of the cost to business
vary from $24 billion up to $100 billion a year. But it probably makes sense
to view such estimates with a degree of scepticism. In the US, they have
just helped prise a cool $30 billion from congress this year, a surprisingly
high &THORN;gure considering the end of the Cold War and intense pressure
for budget cuts. <BR>
<BR>
Part of the money has gone towards bee&THORN;ng up counter-espionage departments:
the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI), for example, set up an Economic
Counterintelligence programme in 1994. However there is an ongoing debate
among intelligence circles over whether the state should &THORN;nance spying
on foreign firms to get information for US business. On one hand, it is
argued that this will help the US economy to remain competitive and anyway,
other countries do it. But someone has to define which firms are domestic
or foreign, an increasingly dif&THORN;cult thing to do in a globalised economy,
and then discriminate by deciding which US company deserves to get this
information. For France and other countries with a large state-owned sector
the dilemma is less acute. <BR>
<BR>
The former director of French intelligence, Pierre Marion, was quoted as
telling an American audience: &quot;In economics, we are competitors not
allies. America has the most technical information... it is easily accessible.
So naturally your country will receive most [attention] from intelligence
services.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
There have been several disputes between the US and Paris. The French secret
service allegedly bugged the conversations of US businessmen on airline
flights. Last year, France responded with accusations that US agents tried
to recruit French corporate and government officials. Some press reports
suggested they were after sophisticated France Telecom technology for use
on the Internet. <BR>
<BR>
The third reason for the growth in industrial espionage is the advance of
technology, making equipment cheaper and easier to use. There is now an
entire industry supplying the needs of would-be executive spies and high
street shops offer many of the tools of the trade. According to the <I>Washington
Post</I>, this gadget industry is worth $100 million a year. While it is
illegal to sell bugging equipment to the public in the US, recent police
raids on spy shops have resulted in a haul of more than 4,000 devices. Much
like the pornography industry of old, more seems to be available under the
counter than over it. <BR>
<BR>
In the UK, the sometimes arcane legal system allows a shop to sell a bugging
device but it is illegal to use it to spy on people. The Spy Shop in London's
Bayswater, for example, sells pinhole cameras hidden in watches, binoculars,
cigarette packets and clocks, presumably for export. Students at Edinburgh
University have developed a television camera built into sunglasses. The
New York-based company CCS even sells a surveillance submarine. Bugs are
sold in products ranging from wall plugs to calculators to buttons and umbrellas.
<BR>
<BR>
Most can only transmit up to 250 metres but a bug attached to a telephone
line can transmit around the world. Fax interceptors which can reproduce
perfect copies of faxes sent or received on a chosen machine cost about
&#163;20,000 ($30,000). Scanners which can listen in to telephone conversations
on analogue (as opposed to digital) mobile phones are only about &#163;300.
It was a device of this sort which was used to record the Princess Diana's
infamous 'Squidgy' conversations with a male friend. It was overheard by
a private individual who listened to mobile telephone conversations as a
hobby. <BR>
<BR>
If worried, a company or individual may consider employing a counter-surveillance
consultant who can &quot;sweep&quot; buildings for bugs and produce a detailed
report listing all possible security risks. A typical sweep of up to 10
executive offices with telephones and fax machines costs roughly $5,000.
Devices have even been found in the foundations of a building but Kevin
Murray, director of counter-surveillance consultancy Murray Associates in
New Jersey, says that only 5% of sweeps detect bugs. Murray uses equipment
worth approximately $80,000 but a basic bug detection device can cost as
little as $450, a &THORN;gure which pales in comparison to the potential
cost of industrial espionage. Consultants can also train a company's staff
to conduct their own sweeps. <BR>
<BR>
All companies are potentially at risk, but certain industries are in greater
danger. This includes those in high technology or undertaking costly research,
covering businesses as diverse as vehicle manufacture, electronics, pharmaceuticals
and computing. Companies competing directly with a foreign firm are also
at greater risk. <BR>
<BR>
Recent cases highlight the problem. The Norweigan engineering group Kvaerner,
for example, launched a massive damages case against the Austrian firm VAI
Industries over the alleged theft of information from a UK subsidiary. According
to Kvaerner, a court-sanctioned raid by its officials uncovered more than
2,000 documents and computer discs belonging to subsidiary Davy International.
Among the VAI staff served with a writ was Roy Tazzyman, Davy International's
former chief executive. Both VAI AND Tazzyman deny any wrongdoing and by
late June, VAI was reported to be considering a counter-claim over the of&THORN;ce
raid. <BR>
<BR>
Authorisation of the raid was based on detective work by a commercial security
consultant, which had trawled through Tazzyman's dustbins. <BR>
<BR>
In an older but high-pro&THORN;le case, car-makers General Motors and Volkswagen
swopped suits over the alleged theft of company secrets. <BR>
<BR>
Events like these are a matter of the utmost seriousness for large firms.
For smaller companies they can prove fatal. Earlier this year employees
of Semiconductor Spares of Belmont, California were charged with industrial
espionage. After an anonymous tip-off, an FBI raid of their offices found
500 designs believed to have been stolen from Allied Materials. According
to the FBI, it also uncovered $200,000 in payments to an Allied Materials
employee. <BR>
<BR>
There are a number of signs to look out for. These include losing contracts
to competitors who give very similar but cheaper quotes, information leaks,
and break-ins where nothing appears to have been taken. Firms might also
ask questions when a competitor is able to match a new product suspiciously
fast. <BR>
<BR>
Spies have glamourous James Bond images, but the reality is that 007's industrial
counterpart is more likely to be found rifling through a competitor's rubbish
bins. This is legal in most countries, so it is wise to shred all confidential
material. <BR>
<BR>
Yet the most popular technique is still hiring someone from the opposition
team. &quot;People are the worst: they are not protective of their company's
information,&quot; comments Murray. Madson agrees: &quot;The threat is largely
internal.&quot; This risk increases if a company has a high staff turnover
as ex-employees usually go to work for a direct competitor. It is important
to check job applications carefully and use outside consultants sparingly.
However, leaks are often the result of disaffection, na&iuml;vet&eacute;
or carelessness. <BR>
<BR>
What staff members tap into their computers must also be safeguarded. Information
can be obtained by stealing a computer or copying onto discs. Access through
email and Internet servers is relatively easy for an experienced hacker
and there have been over one million reported security breaches on the Net
in the last four years. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Paranoia can be bad for business </B><BR>
<BR>
One suggestion for beating online theft is to include numbers in passwords
and use encryption devices. Users can also deploy a so-called firewall,
which places a barrier between a computer system and the outside world and
denies unauthorised access: Trusted Information Systems has put a free &THORN;rewall
kit onto the Internet. To limit further any risk, it is advisable to put
sensitive information onto discs which can be carried around at all times.
<BR>
<BR>
Information is becoming more accessible and its value is increasing. But
it is important to remember that over 90% of the most useful company information
is available legally. Too much paranoia and security can slow down efficiency
and create a sti&thorn;ing and counterproductive working atmosphere. <BR>
<BR>
Madson says it can be wise &quot;not to go high tech, but low tech&quot;
by putting confidential information on paper and limiting its circulation.
Perhaps a lesson can be learned from the tactics of US President Reagan's
team when he first met Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev in Geneva. The
team was so worried about bugs that it communicated with children's magic
slates, which erase writing without a trace. So much for James Bond.<BR>
<BR>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

