<td valign=top>
<h2>
July/August 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>
<H2>TIME OUT</H2>

<H4>Characters in Hollywood films are expected to earn their cash. Except
for women, who may marry for money </H4>
<H3>The reel way to riches <BR>
</H3>
<I>By Mark Tran </I>
<H3></H3>
&quot;You make as much money as you can. Whoever has the most when he dies
wins. It's the American way,&quot; says Danny De Vito in <I>Other People's
Money</I>, the 1991 film directed by Norman Jewison. De Vito plays Larry
the Liquidator, a corporate raider who takes over companies and breaks them
up for a quick buck. Modelled on '80s predators such as Carl Icahn and T
Boone Pickens, De Vito represents the profit motive in its unadulterated
form. He is more likeable than Michael Douglas's Gordon Gekko in <I>Wall
Street</I> but the two want the same thing. <BR>
<BR>
Getting rich is a bedrock of the American dream. Thousands of illegal immigrants
pour into the us in the quest for the good life, and Americans love rags-to-riches
stories. Hollywood also likes get-rich stories, the more sentimental the
better. What it does not like are rapacious capitalists. <BR>
<BR>
Although notorious for its own excesses - bloated salaries, ignored
budget and prima-donna behaviour - Hollywood likes to preach restraint
to others through its films. The other perennial Hollywood motif is that
money cannot buy love - unless you are Richard Gere in <I>Pretty Woman</I>.
<BR>
<BR>
In the recent political condemnation of Hollywood as a purveyor of sex and
violence to the masses, Republican presidential hopeful Robert Dole overlooked
one thing. When it comes to making money Hollywood takes an old-fashioned
attitude in its movies, which preach the same values of hard work and long-term
commitment that Dole prized when growing up in Russell, Kansas. Ironically,
that message seems quaint and even discordant given the dominant get-rich-quick
mentality. <BR>
<BR>
Although the casinos of Donald Trump and Native American tribes compete
for customers, us films take a dim view of gambling one's way to prosperity,
with Las Vegas typically treated as a place of broken dreams. In Albert
Brooks's 1985 comedy, <I>Lost in America</I>, Brooks and Julie Hagerty decide
to drop out. Unfortunately, they stop in Vegas for a last taste of luxury.
Hagerty proceeds to lose their entire nest-egg at the roulette table while
Brooks sleeps upstairs. In <I>Indecent Proposal</I>, an examination of the
power of money, the downward spiral for the main characters begins there.
And in <I>Leaving Las Vegas</I>, Nicolas Cage chooses this location to drink
himself to death. <BR>
<BR>
If anyone epitomises Hollywood's cinematic attitude towards money in the
real world it is Warren Buffett, the archetypal long-term investor who has
amassed one of the great fortunes of the 20th century. Buffett, who is now
the subject of several glowing biographies, carries plenty of material for
a biopic. A man from the Midwest grows fabulously rich through long-term
investments, not from busting up companies, and through it all, he retains
a James Stewart-like, everyman quality. The problem is that Buffett is dull
compared with a snake such as <I>Wall Street</I>'s Gordon Gekko. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The takeover as social murder </B><BR>
<BR>
In the mildly comic <I>Other People's Money</I> De Vito targets for takeover
New England Wire &amp; Cable, a struggling company owned by the worker-friendly
Gregory Peck. The shareholder meeting held to decide on the bid, the big
set-piece of the movie, presents two different views of capitalism which
mirror the real-life debate on a shareholder versus a stakeholding society.
<BR>
<BR>
In a crowded hall, Peck condemns De Vito for playing God with other people's
lives and compares him unfavourably with the notorious robber barons. &quot;The
robber barons of old,&quot; Peck thunders, &quot;at least left something
tangible in their wake - a coal mine, railroads, banks. He [De Vito]
creates nothing, he builds nothing, he runs nothing. In his wake lies nothing
but a blizzard of paper to cover the pain.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Peck goes on to condemn De Vito's takeover bid as &quot;murder on a mass
scale&quot;. He then tugs the heartstrings by describing a business as &quot;something
more the price of its shares, but as a place where people earn a living,
dream their dreams and the fabric that binds society together&quot;. <BR>
<BR>
Recently, Labour Secretary Robert Reich made a remarkably similar declaration
in <I>Harper's </I>magazine. The corporation's ultimate goal was not pro&THORN;ts,
Reich said: &quot;The end is several other things... We want to have a society
in which most people have a chance at a high standard of living. We want
a society that has a moral character, in which there is a degree of trust
among people and a deepening sense of what it means to be a human being.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
De Vito has no time for such noble sentiments. He reminds shareholders that
they bought shares to make money. He argues that New England Wire &amp;
Cable is a dead company and urges the shareholders to take their money and
invest it elsewhere. &quot;Let's have the... decency to sign the death certificate,
collect the insurance and invest in something with a future,&quot; De Vito
tells the shareholders. &quot;Maybe you'll get lucky and it'll be used productivel,
and if it is, you'll create new jobs and provide a service to the economy
and even make a few bucks for yourselves.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
De Vito wins the proxy battle and the factory is closed. But Hollywood cannot
allow economic logic to prevail over a happy ending. A Japanese company
buys De Vito's stake and modernises the factory to make airbags. De Vito
makes a profit and the workers get their jobs back. <BR>
<BR>
There is no mixed message in Stone's 1987 film <I>Wall Street</I>, but then
Stone is an ideologue. Michael Douglas in the Gekko role is not merely rapacious
but a crook, using inside information to dismantle companies because it
makes him a player. Apart from his &quot;greed is good speech&quot;, Douglas
sneers at hard work. His philosophy is summed up in one line: &quot;It's
all about bucks, the rest is conversation.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Charlie Sheen, a small-time broker, ingratiates himself with Douglas by
providing inside information. Sheen persuades Douglas to buy Blue Star,
a struggling airline company where his father works. But the latter immediately
realises that his son is being used as a Trojan horse to break up the company.
Charlie Sheen saves the day by persuading a raider-turned-stakeholder to
buy Blue Star, causing Douglas to lose a pile of money in the process. Sheen
goes to prison for insider dealing but takes Douglas down with him. <BR>
<BR>
Adrian Lyne's 1993 film, <I>Indecent Proposal</I>, tackles head-on the question
of whether money can buy anything. Down on their luck, the loving couple
played by Harrelson and Moore take off for Vegas in the hope of a big score.
They lose but Robert Redford steps in, offering $1 million to sleep with
Moore. Redford wants to test the clich&eacute; that money can't buy love
by offering a lifetime of security for one night. <BR>
<BR>
The couple agrees to the Faustian pact but the relationship subsequently
crumbles. The film takes a neat twist when Redford falls in love with Moore,
before she ends up going back to her &THORN;rst love. For a moment, the
film tantalises us with the unromantic notion that money can indeed buy
anything, but the film soon reverts to sentimentality. <BR>
<BR>
While it clucks its tongue at get-rich-quick merchants, Hollywood takes
a different tack with women: it is ok for them to find wealth not through
sweat and toil but marriage. It is a persistent theme of Hollywood movies
stretching back to at least the '50s in films such as Billy Wilder's <I>Some
Like it Hot</I>, where Marilyn Monroe's goal is to marry a millionaire.
The motif crops up again in Howard Hawks's <I>Gentlemen Prefer Blondes</I>
and Jean Negulesco's <I>How to Marry a Millionaire</I>. <BR>
<BR>
Despite the feminist movement and films such as Ridley Scott's <I>Thelma
and Louise</I>, the theme of poor girl who makes good by meeting rich boy
still has plenty of mileage. One example is <I>Arthur</I>, in which the
coarse Liza Minnelli marries the rich, loveable but dissolute Dudley Moore.
<I>Pretty Woman</I>, directed by Gary Marshall, is the most successful film
of that kind in recent years, proof that Hollywood believes in traditional
values when it comes to women as well as money. <BR>
<BR>
In <I>Pretty Woman</I>, Roberts plays an improbably beautiful and kind-hearted
hooker whom Richard Gere picks up while lost in Los Angeles. Gere plays
a corporate raider stalking a struggling shipping company so he can break
it up. In falling in love with Roberts, Gere becomes humanised and changes
his predatory spots and decides to invest in the company: it is as if De
Vito has metamorphosed into Peck. &quot;I no longer want to take over your
company and take it apart,&quot; says Gere to Ralph Bellamy, who plays his
erstwhile prey. &quot;I want to help you.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
It could be said that Gere does manage to buy happiness after paying Roberts
$3,000 to spend the week with him, but the focus of <I>Pretty Woman</I>
is more on Roberts. Her dream of finding her knight on a white horse -
or in this case in a white stretch-limousine - comes true. <BR>
<BR>
Hollywood's penchant for women who find happiness and wealth through men
also comes across clearly in <I>Working Girl</I>. In Mike Nichols's film,
Sigourney Weaver plays the corporate bitch from hell. She is a deal-maker
at a brokerage firm who employs an industrious secretary played by Melanie
Griffith. With her ridiculously big hair Griffith is definitely from the
wrong side of the tracks, but she wants to improve her lot in life. When
she comes up with an idea for a deal with an outside client, Weaver filches
the idea. But Griffith triumphs with the help of Harrison Ford, an outside
deal-maker who also happens to be Weaver's lover. She gets the deal and
the man: Weaver gets to look ridiculous. <BR>
<BR>
Through its films, Hollywood perpetuates the American dream of finding wealth,
success and happiness but prescribes a right way and wrong way of making
money. It should be earned the old-fashioned way, through honest toil or
patient investing. Trying to make a quick buck, as in robbing banks, is
not usually a good idea although some film crooks, as in the Thomas Crown
Affair, get away with it. But the Hollywood industry exempts women from
hard work. They can find the dream if they find the right man: preferably
one with money, lots of it.<BR>
<BR>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

