<tr>
<td>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<h2>
July/August 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra18.gif" alt="Department">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left>

<H2>BACKSEAT</H2>

<H4>Charles Darwent finds that the world can take offence at the drop of
a hat and offers a guide to survival for the unwary </H4>
Visitors to the Gulf emirate of Qatar may be suprised by one of the knick-knacks
that now habitually lie in wait for business travellers in their hotel bedrooms.
Skulking among the more usual undesirables to be found in quality hotels
- midget shoe buffers, anhydrous shower caps, unopenable sachets of
something called 'body shampoo' - will be a card with a puzzling message.
&quot;Remember!&quot; it says in accents of dread: &quot;Do not cross your
legs while in Qatar.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Weary after a transcontinental flight, the traveller may find himself sitting
up sharply on the end of his bed, musing over the message of the card and
why it should be so. A little known Koranic edict on deportment? The existence
of a species of Qatari predator which interprets the crossing of legs as
a sign of vulnerability? <BR>
<BR>
Well, no. The truth is that you must not cross your legs in Qatar because
in doing so you may risk showing someone the soles of your shoes. To do
so is to suggest that you consider him to be of a kind with that substance
in which you may inadvertently step should you cross a camel paddock without
paying sufficient attention to where you are going. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Crossed communication lines </B><BR>
<BR>
In Qatar it is, quite simply, the deadliest insult the emirate has to offer.
Cross your legs in neighbouring Bahrain with impunity. Fling them about
as you will in Dubai and no harm will befall you. Cross your legs in Qatar
and you may find yourself under threat of having them removed, not necessarily
with the aid of anaesthetic. <BR>
<BR>
Now this is the kind of thing to give the modern business traveller pause.
Picture the scene. There you are one minute, about to clinch that multibillion
dollar liquified petroleum gas deal. The next, white-robed arms are flailing
angrily, swords are glinting in the Arabian sun. Not only is the deal off,
but so may be various of the more favoured bits of your anatomy. <BR>
<BR>
It is one of the undeniably more inconvenient inconveniences of the jet
age. The fact that you board your 747 in a country where the natives speak
English and suffer from nasty colds and are decanted in one where they speak
Swahili and have occasional epidemiological tussles with paratyphoid need
not detain you unduly. A phrase book and a jab or two will see you through
most crises. <BR>
<BR>
But how is one to deal with finding oneself whisked, willy-nilly, from a
country where the crossing of the legs denotes nothing more venal than a
passing discomfort of the posterior to one where the same motion suggests
comparison with the end product of a camel's alimentary canal? <BR>
<BR>
And so - in the spirit of world harmony and international brotherhood
- we would like to offer readers a glimpse into the invaluable new
<I>Backseat Guide to World Body Language </I>(soon to be serialised in an
all-star video, <I>Mensch Without Tears</I>). Cheques for the complete <I>oeuvre
</I>should be forwarded in Swiss francs to the usual address. <BR>
<BR>
*Leg-crossing. This is an unexpected minefield. Quite apart from the example
quoted above, the etiquette of the lower anatomy marks one of the most divisive
of the innumerable transatlantic divides. All Europeans, of all sexes, cross
their legs in the same way, ie., with one knee tucked behind the other.
In America, only women cross their legs like this: American men rest their
ankles on top of their knees. <BR>
<BR>
Mr Tom Wolfe has suggested that this is intended to convey the impression
that the virile nature of the US male is such as to make knee-crossing impossible.
Whether or not this is so, Frenchmen or Hollanders who cross their legs
<I>&agrave; la mode europ&eacute;enne</I> in American business meetings
may find their commercial fortunes taking either an un- expected dip or
an inexplicable upturn, depending on the company they keep. <BR>
<BR>
*Pulling down the lower eyelid. In the Anglophone world, this gesture generally
indicates nothing more sinister than that the user is having problems with
his or her contact lenses. In Latin countries, by way of contrast, it implies
that the gesturer - and, indeed, many members of the gesturer's closer
male acquaintance - have been on intimate terms with the gesturee's
wife/sister/ grandmother/all three of the above. If this might be thought
to convey a cosy sense of familiarity, the implied message is actually rather
less well-intended. Anglo Saxon myopes doing business in Naples or Rio may
prefer to bring along a pair of spectacles for the occasion, just in case.
<BR>
<BR>
*Finger V-signs. Among the more perilous of the gestural <I>faux amies</I>.
In the English-speaking world, the forward-facing version of this gesture
is used to convey either (a) a sense of victory or (b) the fact that the
user would like two more large gins and tonics from behind the bar, please,
and light on the tonic. The backward-facing V-sign, contrariwise, suggests
something altogether less polite to do with the act of procreation. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Which way around? </B><BR>
<BR>
In most of the rest of the world, V-sign etiquette is (as might be expected)
precisely the reverse. Rounds of drinks are ordered <I>volte-face. </I><BR>
<BR>
The forward two-fingers, contrariwise, is intended to suggest that the wife
of the person at whom it is aimed is accustomed to entertain other male
friends while he is away. <BR>
<BR>
Thus when a battered Mrs Thatcher appeared on the steps of the British embassy
in Paris flashing forward Vs at waiting French journalists, she meant the
gesture to convey her determination to fight and win the leadership contest
that had been sneakily called back in London in her absence. <BR>
<BR>
In fact, the Iron Lady appeared to be telling the world that she considered
her opponents to be a fraternity of cuckolds: a frankness that won her astonished
admiration in certain factions of the French press, even if the muffled
cries of &quot;zut&quot; were actually misplaced.<BR>
<BR>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

