<td valign=top align=left> 

<H3> THE INSIDER'S GUIDE TO MANAGEMENT CONSULTANTS </H3> 
<H4> Distinguish yourself or die: Adrian Murdoch advises the advisers in an update of our regular
survey </H4> <P>

 Sitting at your executive desk, you look at the pile of invoices
awaiting approval. One stands out, the six-figure bill from a consultancy firm.
Its work resulted in a report which, by giving the stamp of outside authority,
helped get an unpopular pet project through the company board. But as you look at
the cost you cannot help asking: was it worth it?

<P> Sceptics of consultancy and its uses have become more vocal in recent years.
The view of Scott Adams, creator of the US business cartoon strip Dilbert,
typifies the worst type of fashionable opinion: "A consultant is a person who
takes your money and annoys your employees while tirelessly searching for the
best way to extend the contract."

<P> Yet at the same time, the management consulting industry is one of the
world's most envied of sectors. The global market for its services grew 18% last
year to around $40 billion and worldwide fee income from consultancy is expected
to hit around $21 billion by 1999, a compound growth rate of 13%.

<P> The demand is obvious and consultants are clearly offering some tangible
benefit. At the very least, they can bring cross-industry expertise to bear and
offer a fresh view for executives too close to the coalface. The analogy with
family therapy is useful, as much of a consultant's work involves talking to
people about problems. Poor communication is at the root of many organisational
problems: a failure to connect those on the shop floor with greater knowledge
about a particular issue with decision-makers on the board, for example.
Consultants can help bridge the gaps and identify problems.

<P> There are some <I>sotto voce</I> mutterings, however, which warn the industry
to beware hubris. Fees have only been growing, critics say, because of expansion
into underdeveloped markets such as east-central Europe and China. In these
markets, they add, such firms are getting money for old rope.

<P> Consultants have traditionally fitted into three broad groups: old-style
strategy firms like Booz Allen &amp; Hamilton or the Boston Consulting Group,
information technology specialists such as AT Kearney and Andersen Consulting and
multinationals like the so-called Big Six, which offer a wide range of services.
These distinctions are breaking down, however, with everyone now apparently
offering "change" as the philosopher's stone that will restore profits and
increase market share.

<P> There are three key areas that management consultants must address. Firstly,
there is an increasing perception that the sector bends too much with the wind
and cashes in on management fads. Even though business cycles are becoming
shorter, companies are starting to rail against firms that encouraged beleaguered
chief executives five or six years ago to downsize and are now arguing that they
should upsize.

<P> The other area for concern is that consultants have been slow to develop new
techniques and ideas. The Boston Consulting Group leaped ahead in the '70s with
exciting analytical tools, but in the '90s the industry has produced few new
thinkers. After all, a key selling point has been a supply of bright,
multi-talented individuals with a unique insight into industry. But in this
field, consultants appear to have stepped aside in favour of business school
professors. Where are the Moss Kanters, the Hamils and Prahalads of the
consulting world? Even CSC Index's James Champy plays second fiddle to former MIT
professor Michael Hammer as the advocate of reengineering.

<P> Third is the use of the Internet. Many consultants such as Andersen
Consulting, Coopers &amp; Lybrand and Price Waterhouse pride themselves on IT
innovation and have developed successful and complex closed computer systems,
known as Intranets. They have been rather unsophisticated in their use of the new
medium, however, and the Boston Consulting Group does not even have a web site.
McKinsey stands out with a site both informative and clever.

<P> The lessons to be learned are threefold. First, clients' needs are becoming
ever more complex and the biggest demand is for consultants who can work across
borders. This is addressed by companies such as Price Waterhouse which have
developed an integrated global practice. Second, although the death of
traditional strategy firms is massively overstated, companies like Bain cannot
afford to ignore the implementation route if they wish to maintain growth. Third,
with fee income from traditional services such as audit on the decline,
accountancy firms are moving heavily into the consultancy market. Firms have to
differentiate themselves in an increasingly overcrowded market.

<P><I> <I>Additional research by Emily Spencer</I> </I> 

<H3> ANDERSEN CONSULTING
</H3> <P> Founded: 1989

<P> Number of consultants: 40,000, up from 32,711 in 1994

<P> Revenues: $4.2 billion in 1995, up 22% over previous year

<P> Of&THORN;ces: North America 63, Europe 47, Africa and Middle East 8, Asia
Paci&THORN;c 21, Latin America 10

<P> Head of&THORN;ce: Chicago, IL, US

<P> Web site: http://www.ac.com/

<P> Clients: Paci&THORN;c Bell, Deutsche Telekom, Samsung, AT&amp;T, Volkswagen,
Pirelli

<P> This management consultant heavyweight has been one of the success stories of
the '90s. Although not as glamorous as McKinsey or as friendly as Gemini,
Andersen is by far the biggest and most profitable consultancy and helps set the
standard for the industry. Wags refer to it as the McDonald's of the consulting
world because of the high number of projects it completes.

<P> The accounting practice Arthur Andersen was founded just before World War I.
By the '70s it had built up a huge systems consultancy and by the end of the '80s
its profitable consulting arm had split off.

<P> Between 1990 and last year, global fee income for Andersen Worldwide more
than doubled from $3.4 billion to $8.1 billion. Much of the expansion is down to
Andersen Consulting, which in 1995 grew 22% over the previous year. European
revenues increased 20% from $1.1 billion to $1.4 billion but growth has been
fastest in Asia Pacific, where revenues climbed 27%.

<P> The chairman of Andersen Worldwide, Larry Weinbach, has predicted revenues of
$9.3 billion this year and $16 billion by the end of the century.

<P> These demanding targets are feasible given the company's "value-based
arrangements" that link fees to profits or savings made by clients.

<P> Andersen has changed gradually from being a computer systems integrator to an
IT and management consultancy with an expanding outsourcing business.

<P> High-growth areas are the telecoms sector (57%) and industrial products
(53%). In the client/server sector, the company leads the market with a 9% share,
just ahead of IBM with 8%.

<P> Andersen's media profile has grown alongside its profits. A worldwide
television advertising campaign (the most recent shows a shoal of fish morphing
into one larger, more predatory fish) and sponsorship of the Williams-Renault
Formula One team have raised the company profile.

<P> The firm is famous for throwing the rank and file at problems (the typical
ratio is up to 16 juniors per partner). It does have an up-or-out culture but it
is not as strong as that found at McKinsey.

<P> Training is more crucial to Andersen's culture, with the company spending an
annual 5.5% of revenue and 6 million hours on the process. Recruits are sent to
boot camp at Andersen's 150-acre university, The Andersen Consulting Centre for
Professional Education in St Charles, Illinois, but even partners come back for
refresher courses. This fosters a particularly strong company culture and
consultants run the risk of being dubbed "androids" because their speech is often
littered with in-house jargon.

<P> Increasingly Andersen Consulting competes with Arthur Andersen's own
consultancy arm, and each year it transfers an uncomfirmed amount (estimated to
be $200 million) of its profits to Arthur Andersen partners under a 
profit-sharing deal.

<P> This situation has fuelled rumours that Andersen Consulting will split off
through a stock buy-back or a flotation towards the end of the year. Last year a
project team, Andersen 21, was set up to see how to take the company forward. Its
findings will be presented in the autumn.

<P> There are some cracks in Andersen's otherwise faultless fa&ccedil;ade. In
Britain the company had to pay an $18 million penalty fee for not delivering the
government's new National Insurance system in time and it has failed to win a
$1.5 billion, eight-year computerisation contract with the Post Office.

<H3>

</H3> <H3> ARTHUR D LITTLE </H3> <P> Founded: 1886

<P> Number of consultants: 3,000 plus

<P> Revenues: $514 million for 1995, up 20%

<P> Of&THORN;ces: North America 14, Europe 21, Asia Paci&THORN;c 8, Latin America
6, Middle East 3

<P> Head of&THORN;ce: Cambridge, MA, US

<P> Web site: http://www.adlittle.com/

<P> Clients: Nasa, Volvo, Ford, Mobil, Shell, Thomas Cook, Philips

<P> The leader in technology consultancy grew out of a research laboratory that
Arthur Dehon Little founded in the late 19th century. By the '50s the firm had
expanded into broad management consultancy. Its infamous advice that IBM should
not buy the Xerox patents is one of the company's few major errors of judgement.
It endured a period of confusion in the '80s when it over-diversified into
non-core areas. This culminated in 1988 in a threatened takeover by New
York-based Plenum Publishing. After that, US business was restructured and has
since proven successful.

<P> In the '90s the firm has been back on track, preaching a management
philosophy of incremental and modest innovation rather than radical concepts or
designs. Last year was ADL's fifth consecutive year of growth and chairman
Michael Younger is aiming for a 15% rise in revenue this year. The target is
feasible given that overseas revenue now represents 60% of the total and is
growing. The firm opened 12 new offices last year, 10 of them outside the US.
Already this year it has opened offices in Bombay and Seoul.

<P> Arthur D Little recently restructured its North American operation to align
with Europe and to focus on areas where it is pre-eminent. Restructuring was not
without pain as it had to lose 49 people (including 29 consultants) from its
financial and transport divisions.

<P> Now, operations are divided into functional practices focusing on strategy
and six industry sectors: automotive, chemical, health, metals, utilities and
information. The last covers media, electronics and telecoms because, the company
says, those industries were already converging. This strengthens the firm's
reputation as industry insider (consultants are more likely to be industry
experts than business-school graduates) and reinforces the internal help ethic
for which it is famous.

<P> The company is trying to gain a foothold in other areas. Last summer it moved
into organisational learning by acquiring the leading training consultancy
Innovation Associates &#173; a firm founded by Peter Senge, author of <I>The
Fifth Discipline</I> and director of organisational learning at MIT. This new
emphasis should help consultants better explain the roots of problems.

<P>


<H3> AT KEARNEY </H3> <P> Founded: 1926

<P> Number of consultants: 2,700

<P> Revenues: $650 million in 1995, up 19%

<P> Of&THORN;ces: North America 29, Europe 20, Asia Paci&THORN;c 11, Latin
America 3

<P> Head of&THORN;ce: Chicago, IL, US

<P> Web site: http://www.atkearney.com/

<P> Clients: Rolls-Royce, General Motors, former Treuhandanstalt

<P> McKinsey might call itself the Rolls-Royce of consultants, but Kearney has
the British auto-maker's account: a 10-year, $900 million joint contract to
outsource technology.

<P> AT Kearney has its roots in the company James McKinsey (see page 23) founded
in 1926. Andrew Thomas Kearney was McKinsey's first marketing partner but he left
in 1937 after McKinsey's death and a disagreement with Marvin Bower and set up
under his own name just after World War II.

<P> Last September, after a two-year courtship, EDS acquired Kearney for $600
million in cash and stock. Kearney needed the capital and IT capabilities and EDS
needed the expertise and the brand. The company became a wholly owned subsidiary
of EDS, but it retained the AT Kearney name and kept its board of directors,
management and Chicago headquarters.

<P> The buyer EDS was happy with the arrangement as Kearney has experienced
double-digit growth over the past 12 years. Under the leadership of long-time
chief executive and chairman Fred Steingraber it has been attracting bigger and
better clients in the US and, significantly, in Europe.

<P> On the surface the merger seems a marriage made in heaven. EDS's consulting
unit has doubled revenues and the number of consultants. It has given AT Kearney
an especially strong IT position to add to its traditional leading roles in
engineering and finance. The merger also helped expand the firm's reach into new
markets such as Argentina, Venezuela, New Zealand and the Philippines.

<P> The danger of the merger is that EDS's more strong-arm and bureaucratic
approach might stifle AT Kearney's popular common-touch consulting style. There
are also fears that EDS will use Kearney as a stalking horse to push its computer
services.

<P> Until now, AT Kearney's style has been very strong on client feedback and its
consultants have had no qualms about rolling up their sleeves and helping clients
implement changes. It is a successful technique: it is claimed that more than 80%
of the firm's jobs have positive results.

<H3>

</H3> <H3> BAIN &amp; COMPANY </H3> <P> Founded: 1973

<P> Number of consultants: 1,200

<P> Revenues: $350 million-$375 million in 1995, up 25%

<P> Of&THORN;ces: North America 7, Europe 12, Asia Paci&THORN;c 7, Latin America
1, southern Africa 1

<P> Head of&THORN;ce: Boston, MA, US

<P> Web site: http://www.rec.bain.com/

<P> Clients: Guinness, Dun &amp; Bradstreet

<P> The most entrepreneurially minded of consultancies, Bain was formed in 1973
by former Boston Consulting Group vice-president William Bain and seven
former colleagues. By the mid-80s revenues had risen to more than $100 million.
With a list of blue-chip clients, the company charged astronomical fees. Dun
&amp; Bradstreet, for example, paid an estimated $35 million for a year's work.

<P> An ill-judged 30% stock buyback at the end of the '80s almost wiped out the
company and staff shrank from 1,300 to 1,000. Fighting between the old guard and
young Turks was vicious and after an unsuccessful attempt to sell the firm and
200 more job losses, Bain himself stepped down. He was replaced by the much
younger W Mitt Romney, head of Bain Capital.

<P> The company was rapidly restructured and since then has tried to project a
youthful image. The voice of the firm is Orit Gadiesh, the chairman of the board
noted for striking purple hair and a sharp intellect: she came top of her year at
Harvard Business School while finishing a psychology doctorate and learning
English (she is Israeli by birth). Gadiesh has done much to attract younger MBAs
and is popular because she leads by example: unlike many senior consultants, she
still spends most of her time with clients.

<P> Bain &amp; Co plays its cards very close to its chest: it refused to
cooperate with this report, for example. The company has developed ways of
keeping employees and achieving what it terms zero customer defections. One of
its strengths is in advising on acquisitions and divestitures. The company has
recently advocated the caring corporation: it has even trademarked the term
"loyalty-based management". This is quite a U-turn: Bain was one of the firms
most closely linked with the cold-hearted cost-cutting culture of corporate
America in the early '90s.

<P>


<H3> BOOZ ALLEN &amp; HAMILTON </H3>


<P> Founded: 1914

<P> Number of consultants: 5,200

<P> Revenues: $785 million in 1995, up 30%

<P> Of&THORN;ces: North America 42, Asia Paci&THORN;c 9, Europe 9, Middle East 1,
Latin America 6

<P> Head of&THORN;ce: McLean, VA, US

<P> Web site: http://www.bah.com/

<P> Clients: US government, Federal Bureau of Investigation, Nasa Space Station,
Procter &amp; Gamble, Boeing, L'Or&eacute;al

<P> Founded in 1914, Booz Allen &amp; Hamilton (BAH) has long had a reputation as
the one-stop management consultancy because it offered both IT and strategy
expertise. Like ADL it expanded too rapidly in the '80s, a time when it also
suffered from damaging infighting and internal bureaucracy. The '90s have been
much happier. The firm has reorganised along industry rather than regional lines,
primarily in two divisions: the worldwide commercial and worldwide technology
business units.

<P> The firm has a strong relationship with the US government going back more
than 50 years. Its work in the defence and intelligence sector has enabled it to
offer unique tools and it has adapted a computer war-simulation program for the
commercial world. Revenues from IT have doubled over two years and the company
hopes to maintain growth for at least three more.

<P> Booz Allen &amp; Hamilton has started to establish a presence outside the US
and has opened offices in a number of locations. Its current emphasis is on new
markets in the Asia Pacific region. It has been pushing heavily into Australia
where it won contracts with mining group BHP, National Australia Bank and others.
The firm has just opened its first office in India and plans up to four more
there in the near future. The firm will also attack new markets in China and
Korea.

<P> The company is popular because it spends a great deal of time working out
what has to be done and implements changes carefully. Clients like the fact that
it tries to offer a small-firm feel with large-firm capabilities. Critics say it
is too prescriptive, but it is moving away from that. However its presence in
Europe remains rather low key.

<H3>

</H3> <H3> BOSTON CONSULTING GROUP </H3>


<P> Founded: 1963

<P> Number of consultants: 1,320

<P> Revenues: $550 million in 1995, up 28%

<P> Of&THORN;ces: North America 9, Europe 16, Asia Paci&THORN;c 12, Latin America
2

<P> Head of&THORN;ce: Boston, MA, US

<P> Web site: n/a

<P> Clients: Russian government, Harvard Business School

<P> Set up by former ADL consultant Bruce Henderson, Boston Consulting Group
(BCG) was the first to specialise purely in strategy, a subject which began to
emerge as a discipline in its own right in the mid-60s.

<P> The company owed its initial success to innovative methods of analysis that
have since become business standards, identifying cash cows, experience curves
and portfolio management (aka the Boston Box). These were so successful that the
firm briefly stole the lead from McKinsey as the number one consultancy in the
'70s.

<P> The structure of BCG is based on 10 worldwide practice areas with specific
industry or functional expertise. Among the strategic issues these groups cover
are consumer goods and retailing, corporate development, energy and utilities,
financial services, healthcare, high-tech, industrial goods, IT and organisation
and operational management.

<P> The firm has a very clean-sheet approach to consulting: clients buy original
solutions. One downside, however, is that those solutions can be very
textbookish. Another is that the firm's stance against hierarchies can make
cross-border work unwieldy and difficult. Nevertheless the company does well in
keeping its customers: four-fifths of the 50 largest clients that engaged BCG's
services five years ago still retain them.

<P> Hiring procedures at BCG are rather MBA-oriented. The firm prides itself on a
rigorous selection procedure and exceptional compensation levels. BCG, which is
still privately owned, regards its consultants as top officer material while
rival consultants potter around in the engine room. In turn the company expects a
rapid career progression &#173; to senior partner in six to eight years rather
than 12 at, say, McKinsey. Consultants at BCG have such a high standing as
theoreticians that the firm has a revolving-door relationship with academia. It
hires business-school professors as consultants and sometimes loses consultants
to the same business schools.

<P> The &THORN;rm does not yet have the same ties with the brave new world of
computer technology, however: BCG is the only consultancy profiled here which
does not have a Net site.

<P>


<H3> COOPERS &amp; LYBRAND </H3> <P> Founded: 1898

<P> Number of consultants: 9,000

<P> Revenues: $6.2 billion in 1995, up 12.7% Consulting, $1.2 billion, up 34%

<P> Of&THORN;ces: More than 730 of&THORN;ces and member &THORN;rms in 126
countries

<P> Head of&THORN;ce: New York, NY, US

<P> Web site: http://www.colybrand.com/

<P> Clients: Levi Strauss, Digital

<P> One of the Big Six accountancy firms, Coopers &amp; Lybrand (C&amp;L) has a
long history in audit. Recently, it has become a quite a force in human resource
consulting and has achieved the largest growth of the consultants discussed here.

<P> The growth is a result of urgent fixes the company had to undertake. Until
1991, C&amp;L did not have a technology chief and it was lagging at the rear of
the Big Six in terms of fees. To address that, former chairman Eugene Freedman
replaced a third of the consulting staff, reduced 130 profit centres to 30 and
cut operating costs by almost a third in the US alone. These measures, along with
the introduction of a performance-related system, seem to have worked. The
consulting arm, which became a stand-alone operation early this decade, turned
its first profit in 1993.

<P> Technological innovations have also helped the company find its feet. Until
the beginning of the '90s, C&amp;L had no company-wide computer system: each
practice had <I>carte blanche</I> to buy what it wanted. The answer was the
Knowledge Network (similar to Andersen's Knowledge Xchange and Price Waterhouse's
KnowledgeView), an in-house information system that consultants can tap into from
anywhere in the world. Having tackled the problem itself, C&amp;L preaches that
IT should be a function rather than a prime resource within a firm.

<P> As has become the industry norm, C&amp;L links all fees to cost reductions
and about a quarter of its consultants have MBAs. One of the few criticisms of
the firm is that it is structured too regionally.

<P> Of special note is the company's work in east and central Europe. For the
sixth year in a row, the company has topped <I>Privatisation International</I>
magazine's league table of global privatisation advisers with 397 assignments
that have a disposal value of $21.5 billion. In Hungary, C&amp;L's turnover grew
20% last year as a result of its work in the energy sector. The firm is also
booming in the Asia Pacific region. Last year, fees in China grew by 300%.

<P> The firm is embroiled in a legal wrangle with Ernst &amp; Young (see page 20)
in Spain. Coopers &amp; Lybrand claims that E&amp;Y poached 90 of its consulting
staff in a four-day period, causing it to lose a major client, the Spanish
Airport Authority, as a result. The dispute has yet to be be resolved.

<P>


<H3> CSC INDEX </H3> <P> Founded: 1969

<P> Number of consultants: 450

<P> Revenues: $200 million in 1995, up 14%

<P> Of&THORN;ces: North America 6, Europe 4

<P> Head of&THORN;ce: Cambridge, MA, US

<P> Web site: http://www.csc.com/

<P> Clients: Hallmark Cards, Liberty Mutual, Lloyds Bank

<P> A leader in the change management field, CSC Index is the developer of
reengineering, the management buzzword that has done for the '90s what strategy
did for the '70s and quality for the '80s. The company is small but its work
carries considerable weight in the industry.

<P> In 1993, chairman and chief executive James Champy led the way with the
bestseller <I>Reengineering The Corporation</I>, which he wrote with former MIT
professor Michael Hammer. Last year he followed that with <I>Reengineering
Management</I>.

<P> The company was founded as a strategy specialist at the end of the '60s by
Tom Gerrity, who is now dean at Wharton Business School. The firm was bought by
IT experts Computer Sciences Corporation in 1988 and now acts as its strategy
management consultancy, working closely with its parent and systems integration
sister, CSC Consulting, to implement new processes. Its work in this &THORN;eld
for US bank Wells Fargo has been particularly noted. The company's position was
boosted in 1991 with the acquisition of London-based consultancy Butler Cox.

<P> The corporate backlash against reengineering has hit CSC's profits and it has
been looking at other potential growth areas. So far, the signs are that the
search will be successful. In May it signed an outsourcing deal with global
banking firm JP Morgan that was the most sophisticated and largest ever, worth
more than $2 billion.

<P> As a further protection against declining reengineering fees, CSC recently
merged with the Texas-based consulting and computer services firm Continuum to
boost its presence in the banking and insurance sectors. The company will now be
better placed to compete for outsourcing contracts and provide data management to
those sectors.

<P> The firm has also pioneered the inelegantly titled skill of
cyberpsychographics for companies that wish to market on the Internet.

<P>


<H3> DELOITTE &amp; TOUCHE </H3> <H3> CONSULTING GROUP </H3>


<P> Founded: 1845

<P> Number of consultants: more than 6,000

<P> Revenues: $2.6 billion in 1995, up 15.2%. Management consultancy revenue was
$1.4 billion, up 20%

<P> Of&THORN;ces: 124 consulting of&THORN;ces

<P> Head of&THORN;ce: Wilton, CT, US

<P> Web site: http://www.dttus.com/dtti/home.htm

<P> Clients: Microsoft, Chrysler, Daimler, Nike, Boeing, UK government

<P> The firm began in the 19th century when William Welch Deloitte opened an
accounting office in London. Early this year, its global consultancy practice was
renamed and reengineered to much short-term confusion.

<P> The UK consulting arm, then called Touche Ross Management Consultants, was
operationally linked with &#173; and took the name of &#173; the Deloitte &amp;
Touche Consulting Group in the US and Canada.

<P> Other consultancy arms throughout the world will follow within two years. The
new company will owe its partners' incomes and profits to a global rather than a
national company. The firm is adamant that unlike Andersen Consulting, it will
not seek to hive itself off from the rest of the accountancy practice.

<P> The change, a response to clients' requests for consultancy across borders,
will provide a single global identity and help the firm service large
multinationals and public-sector organisations. On a practical level, consultants
are grouped into multinational and multi-disciplinary teams. However the
management and control of projects will still be run on a regional basis.

<P> The firm believes that it gains a competitive advantage from the synergy
between consultancy and accounting, and is adamant that the former will not seek
to split itself from the latter. Its strengths are process reengineering, change
management and IT.

<P> This is because Deloitte &amp; Touche is the world's largest implementor of
integrated software systems via its wholly owned subsidiary International
Consulting Solutions.

<P> Russia has provided much recent growth. The consultancy opened an office in
Moscow with 10 employees in 1990: the firm now has six offices and 700 staff.

<P>


<H3> ERNST &amp; YOUNG </H3> <P> Founded: 1845

<P> Number of consultants: 9,419

<P> Revenues: $6.9 billion for 1995, up 14%. Consultancy arm $1.5 billion, up 9%

<P> Of&THORN;ces: 670 in 125 countries throughout the world

<P> Head of&THORN;ce: New York, NY, US

<P> Web site: http://www.eyi.com/

<P> Clients: British Aerospace, <BR> Coca-Cola, Reebok

<P> The audit king has been making great noises in the consulting market and is
one of the world's fastest growing professional services firms. Along with KPMG,
it is now rated number three in terms of global consultancy fees, snapping at the
heels of Andersen and McKinsey.

<P> Almost every aspect of E&amp;Y's consulting practice has been expanding.
Revenue in the US grew almost 50% and healthcare consulting alone grew 42.2%. It
has also been targeting the emerging markets with more offices in the Middle East
that any other professional services firm, four in China and plans to open seven
others there soon. To help expand into south-east Asia it formed an alliance with
Tata Consultancy Systems, India's largest systems development and IT company.

<P> To allow collaboration across geographical and organisational borders E&amp;Y
has been trying to create a virtual organisation via video-conferencing and
computer networks. The consultancy practice is split into two divisions:
Information Technology and Performance Improvement.

<P> Its corporate culture is fast and furious. Those who join from the outside
relish its integrated teamwork approach, in which consultants are attached to
individual practices. To encourage fieldwork E&amp;Y has taken on the idea of
hotelling, whereby consultants have no fixed offices and book space at a location
only when they need it.

<P> It seems that E&amp;Y can do almost nothing wrong. It is sometimes seen to be
lacking a distinct image but this has not affected the bottom line.

<P> The only error it seems to have made lately was both understandable and
human: in the US the management consulting division and the chairman's office
reported different revenue figures, which generated mentions in the international
diary columns.

<P>


<H3> GEMINI CONSULTING </H3> <P> Founded: 1991

<P> Number of consultants: 1,400

<P> Revenues: $548 million in 1995, down 1%

<P> Of&THORN;ces: North America 5, Europe 11, Asia Paci&THORN;c 1, Latin America
1, Africa 1

<P> Head of&THORN;ce: Morristown, NJ, US

<P> Web site: http://www.gemcon.com

<P> Clients: Union Carbide, Du Pont, Merrill Lynch, Glaxo, British Telecom

<P> The rising star of consultancy has waned somewhat recently. In the early '90s
it was spoken of in the same breath as McKinsey and Boston Consulting Group. The
reason for such fast initial growth was its range of expertise, the result of a
merger between the MAC Group (strategy experts), United Research (organisational
change experts) and Gamma International (leaders in information change).

<P> However, Gemini has shown little growth in the past two years: it has slipped
from the world's fifth largest consulting group to 15th position. Concerns over
revenues led Standard &amp; Poor's to downgrade the rating of Gemini's parent,
the Paris-based Cap Gemini Sogeti (CGS) group, from BBB to BBB minus.

<P> Last year Gemini downsized by firing one in 12 of its consulting staff and
carrying out a cull at the top when tensions between Gemini and CGS resulted in
the ignominious expulsion of the consultancy's founding chairman, David Teigler.
Chief executive Daniel Valentino followed him out the door a few months later
after disappointing results in North America.

<P> With morale at an all-time low, the company had difficulty attracting new
clients and industry watchers say that it has done little to differentiate itself
from competitors.

<P> Gemini's work style is based around the Four Rs, set out in <I>Transforming
the Organisation</I>, published last year by company co-chairman James Kelly and
senior vice-president Francis Gouillart.

<P> The Rs refer to reframing, or opening the corporate mind to new visions;
restructuring, a way of getting the company to perform competitively;
revitalisation, which aims at fostering growth; and renewal, the goal of
investing individuals with new skills. Because of the difficulties that Gemini
has been having recently, some people have asked whether the company should
perhaps listen to its own advice.

<P> To try to stop the rot, Gemini has focused on retaining good people. Instead
of "up or out", its stated philosophy is "grow or go". It is the first
consultancy to institute sabbatical programmes of up to three months to reward
high performers, attract top recruits and reduce burnout.

<P>


<H3> KPMG </H3> <P> Founded: 1867

<P> Number of consultants: 8,915

<P> Revenues: $7.5 billion in 1995, up 13%. $1.5 billion for consulting, up 28%

<P> Of&THORN;ces: About 95 specialist management consultancy of&THORN;ces
worldwide

<P> Head of&THORN;ce: New York, NY, US

<P> Web site: http://www.kpmg.com/

<P> Clients: European Commission, Lebanese government, British government, Hong
Kong government, Visa International

<P> Of the the Big Six firms involved in consultancy, KPMG is the most open and
international. It was the first to publish revenues, of which two-thirds now come
from outside the US.

<P> Founded in 1867 by Robert Fletcher in London, the firm has been involved in
management consultancy since 1955. In the past year, KPMG has identified six
business issues that it feels companies must address: post-merger acquisition
integration; globalisation and Europeanisation; financial turnaround; cost
reduction; business creation and privatisation.

<P> One of KPMG's strengths is IT. The firm has a strategic alliance with German
software company SAP, which provides fully integrated software, and is expanding
its capacity in that sector: it aims to employ 3,000 SAP consultants within the
next four years. This is a far cry from the bloodletting of 1990, when the firm
fired 300 partners.

<P> In the past 12 months, KPMG has developed two new schemes. It announced the
formation of a Global Year 2000 software conversion practice earlier in the year
to help corporations deal with the threat to their information systems from
computer date-change problems. And to reinforce the strong ethical culture for
which it is known, KPMG offered a free consultancy to any US organisation that
wants to diversify its workforce. It has established a Business Ethics Unit in
Montville, NJ, to change unethical behaviour in firms and measure ethical
practices in companies.

<P> The firm tries to recruit from different backgrounds: it is not uncommon to
&THORN;nd former doctors and biochemists rather than accountants and MBAs. It
eschews the up-or-out policy, recruiting carefully and working in a strong
appraisal culture. As a result, the attrition rate is in single figures.
Consultants are popular with clients for their unprescriptive style and their
emphasis on skills transfer. The firm's goal is for clients to understand the new
processes so well at the end of a project that they do not notice when the
consultants leave.

<P> There was substantial growth in India last year, the result of large projects
for the Central Bank of India and the Industrial Development Bank. The company
also worked with the British government in its electricity sector privatisation.

<P>


<H3> MCKINSEY &amp; COMPANY </H3> <P> Founded: 1926

<P> Number of consultants: 3,650

<P> Revenues: Estimated at $1.8 billion in 1995, up 20%

<P> Of&THORN;ces: North America 21, Europe 29, Asia Paci&THORN;c 12, Latin
America 4

<P> Head of&THORN;ce: New York, NY, US

<P> Web site: http://www.mckinsey.com/

<P> Clients: the Vatican, PepsiCo, IBM, Nissan, Johnson &amp; Johnson, Mexican
government

<P> McKinsey's consultants have been described as secular Jesuits. They are
gifted, arrogant, single-minded intellectuals who never doubt their credo. In the
profession, the firm's consultants are the knowledge merchants <I>non pareil</I>
and they relish being revered and feared. The news earlier in the year that the
Vatican has asked McKinsey for advice prompted many wry smiles. Results of a
worldwide survey by Swedish researchers Universum earlier this year showed that
McKinsey, dubbed "The Firm", was the employer of choice for graduates. But
however highly the company is rated by graduates, it is not nearly as high as the
firm rates itself.

<P> Founded by Chicago accounting professor James McKinsey in 1926, the firm
&#173; still run as if it were a partnership &#173; expanded rapidly under Marvin
Bower, who from 1939 controlled the company for almost 30 years. By 1950,
revenues had hit the $2 million mark. It soon became known as the first
consulting firm to hire directly from business schools.

<P> At about $1 million a report, McKinsey's advice does not come cheap. But
spurning the common practice of basing fees on results has not affected
McKinsey's bottom line. Its consultants are among the most profitable in the
business, bringing in an estimated annual revenue of $475,000. They also work
some of the most gruelling hours in what is a traditionally demanding business.

<P> For its mostly white, male employees, the company is fiercely competitive.
Each year, about 50,000 people apply for only 550 places. Inside, the company has
a rigid up-or-out policy that gets rid of about 17% of consultants a year. If you
don't make partner in five years you are asked to move on. Expressions of
personality are discouraged and there is a IBM-style dress code. All consultants
must wear long socks because Bower deemed it unseemly to show flesh in a business
meeting.

<P> Right up to the mid-60s all consultants, bar those in the San Francisco
office, had to wear hats. "The squeaky wheel at McKinsey usually gets discarded
not oiled," Tom Peters wrote rather bitterly of his experience with the company
after a fairly public spat.

<P> There is little scope for hand-holding after you call in the firm's
consultants. McKinsey's style is famously cerebral and hypothesis-driven. "So
what?" is the question teams ask as they discuss issues with a client.
Consultants do not work "for" clients, they work "with" them: they do not go out
on a "job", they have an "engagement".

<P> A recent growth area has been Asia: the firm opened a practice in Beijing
this year, only its second in China. The banking sector has also been expanding.
Since the '80s McKinsey has made a speciality of advising investment banks in the
wake of mergers.

<P> The company takes institutional knowledge development very seriously. It runs
a Rapid Response Network (RRN) with 70 volunteer consultant specialists that
promises a quick response to internal consultant and customer queries. Each
member of the RRN agrees to be on call for a couple of weeks a year (on top of
normal work) and guarantees that every question will be answered within 24 hours.

<P> This is not to say that the company never makes mistakes. It sat back for a
while and watched Boston Consulting Group clean up in the '70s before coming back
and its disastrous restructuring of General Motors in the '80s still haunts
partners.

<P> The list of McKinsey men in positions of power is long and the company
nurtures its alumni constantly and expertly. They range from the last three
director generals of the Confederation of British Industry; Lou Gerstner, the
chief executive of IBM; Michael Jordan, chief executive of Westinghouse; Kenichi
Ohmae and Tom Peters, management "gurus" <I>par excellence</I>.

<P>


<H3> MERCER MANAGEMENT </H3> <H3> CONSULTANCY GROUP </H3>


<P> Founded: 1992

<P> Number of consultants: 1,100 staff

<P> Revenues: $1 billion in 1995 up 13%

<P> Of&THORN;ces: North America 7, Europe 5, Asia Paci&THORN;c 1

<P> Home of&THORN;ce: Boston, MA, US

<P> Web site: http://www.mercermc.com

<P> Clients: South African railways

<P> Mercer Management Consulting is one of the main strategy consultants and one
of the first consultancies to rail against corporate anorexia. It is certainly
anything but thin. Two of its consultants, Dwight Gertz and Joao Baptista,
trumpeted that very theme in a recent book, <I>Grow to be Great</I>. The firm has
expanded rapidly, doubling in size on three occasions since it was founded, and
last year it became the eighth highest revenue earner. The smart money expects it
to double again in three years.

<P> Founded as a result of a merger between Strategic Planning Associates and
Temple, Barker &amp; Sloane in 1992, Mercer is part of the Marsh &amp; McLennan
Group. At the moment, the focus is on Europe. In 1993 it acquired UBM, a German
consulting group. Two years later Mercer bought MID, the French strategy
consultancy that was merged into Mercer's Paris office. This year it opened its
first office in Hong Kong.

<P> Mercer believes that for a company to grow, it must have in place three
precepts: the value proposition, or making sure that customers judge the
company's product to be consistently better than that of competitors; economics
across the value chain, ensuring that product can be supplied at a low enough
cost to ensure profitability; and execution, or effectively delivering low-cost
products to the customer. The firm has been particularly successful in
telecommunications and post-merger company integrations.

<P> Mercer has a reputation for valuing its workers. It attracts people who care
about their colleagues and the value of a friendly office atmosphere, and it bids
strongly in the recruitment stakes.

<P>


<H3> PRICE WATERHOUSE </H3> <H3> MANAGEMENT CONSULTANCY </H3>


<P> Founded: 1849

<P> Number of consultants: 5,201

<P> Revenues: $4.5 billion in 1995, up 12%. Management consultancy income $1
billion, up 26%

<P> Of&THORN;ces: US, 100, 36 Europe. Altogether 434 of&THORN;ces in 119
countries.

<P> Head of&THORN;ce: New York, NY, US

<P> Web site: http://www.pw.com/

<P> Clients: Disney, Renault, Carlsberg, Croatian government

<P> Unlike its Big Six colleagues in this survey, Price Waterhouse (PW) is a
fully integrated global consulting organisation: partners share profit
internationally rather than regionally.

<P> Samuel Lowell Price founded the company in London in 1849. In 1865, William
Holyland and Edwin Waterhouse joined. Holyland retired six years later and the
firm became Price Waterhouse in November 1874. The company grew rapidly, and it
opened a New York office in 1890. Management consultancy services were formally
offered after 1963, but the company had been moving in that direction since the
mid-50s. By the '70s it had become one of the most profitable firms.

<P> At the beginning of this year the consultancy practice was restructured to
get rid of internal barriers and better serve multinationals. By combining the
US, Japanese and European services, the company can ensure the speedy delivery of
cross-border expertise. Scott Hartz was named managing partner in charge of
consulting services worldwide.

<P> Although Andersen hived off its consulting practice from accountacy six years
ago and Deloitte &amp; Touche did the same at the end of last year, PW is quick
to emphasise that it will not follow this trend.

<P> Price Waterhouse is particularly strong in the media sector &#173; it advises
Disney and film magnate Steven Spielberg &#173; and in east and central Europe.
The firm is number two in <I>Privatisation International</I> magazine's league
table of global privatisation advisers with 344 assignments that have a disposal
value of $11.62 billion. One particularly large assignment is Croatia's voucher
privatisation, worth $3.5 billion.

<P> Like many other firms, PW is showing particular growth in Asia (45%) but is
also targeting South America for expansion in outsourcing activities.

<P> One of the firm's core competences is in IT and about half of all new
recruits have IT backgrounds. The rest have line management experience in other
business disciplines from finance to human resources. Price Waterhouse was one of
the first consultancies to start using Lotus Notes, a software system that helps
share knowledge within a company, via an in-house, globally shared database
called KnowledgeView.

<P> In 1989, it became the first consultancy to sign an agreement with German
integrated software company SAP. At the end of last year PW formed an alliance
with Minneapolis-based Information Advantage, which will help speed the delivery
of IT solutions.

<P> Multi-disciplinary staff work in teams with management of blue-chip
companies. The company dislikes hierarchies: everyone in a team is considered an
expert and debate encouraged.

<P> The company's up-or-out policy &#173; in PW-speak ETL or "encouraged to
leave" &#173; has been relaxed recently. Increasingly, the company is creating
niches for people who do not want to move up to partnership level.

