<H3> 2000 REASONS TO PANIC </H3> 

<H4> Computer systems
worldwide are heading for a crash in the year 2000 because of a digit crisis. But
the gulf between chief executives and their IT staff means that businesses still
have a huge task to prevent the biggest New Year hangover of them all, warns
Emily Spencer </H4> <P> 

It is January 1, 2000 and something has gone badly wrong.
Awakening with a hangover, you go to the bank where a queue of people is buzzing,
thwarted by cash machines that do not work: the bank's safe will not open because
its time code has gone haywire. Back at home, news &thorn;ashes interrupt the
usual upbeat New Year programmes with tales about the breakdown of a nuclear
power station and a series of aeroplane crashes.

<P> One of the &THORN;rst letters of the new century to arrive on your doormat is
a bill that adds 100 years' interest to your credit-card charges. Back at work a
few days later, colleagues cry as computers crash and &THORN;les disappear.
Clients steam with rage when they receive grossly in&thorn;ated invoices. To top
the mood of crisis, Washington announces on the evening news that its weapons
systems have failed.

<P> This is an alarmist picture of what may happen at the turn of the century,
but the dangers are serious enough. A pervasive programming fault in the way
computers keep track of the years could cause millions of computers worldwide to
fail, affecting everything from air-traffic control to major business
transactions. The scale and cost of the problem is huge and rising every month.
Companies must act now as time is running out.

<P> The problem arises because most commercial application programs more than a
few years old use just two digits, not four, to calculate the year: for example,
they record 1996 as 96. When 2000 arrives the computer will "read" 00 as 1900.
Computers will calculate that the age of someone born in 1958 is "minus 58 years"
and pensioners could appear on waiting lists for primary school.

<P> Computer consultant and Year 2000 expert Peter de Jager, from Brampton in
Ontario, told a conference of UK civil servants this year: "If architects built
buildings the way programmers designed systems the &THORN;rst woodpecker would
destroy western civilisation. Our woodpecker has arrived in the form of 00, the
Year 2000."

<P> Experts say large companies will need three to four years to tackle this
millennium time bomb. Changing codes and programs is only half of the battle:
companies need an additional year to test and debug them. As companies use their
computers all week long, much of the work will have to be done on weekends, which
makes prompt action all the more essential. There are only about 500 working days
and 120 weekends left until the end of 1998.

<P> The root of the problem is historical. Many computer programs were &THORN;rst
written in the '60s and '70s at a time when computer storage space was scarce and
very costly. Programmers thought that application programs would be replaced
before the millennium. Instead, they were modi&THORN;ed over the years.

<P> Jim Inglis, a computer scientist at Birkbeck College who sat on an
international committee standardising computer codes, says that at the time no
one would use more storage than absolutely necessary because of the cost: "This
continued through sheer convention when there was no more need to save space."

<P> Now organisations around the world are reaping the chaos of delayed reform.
Even worse than a crash is the prospect of different systems making simple
miscalculations, causing problems that take weeks or months to discover. This
includes aircraft computers shutting down because they calculate they have not
had any maintenance for 99 years. Nuclear power stations could suffer the same
fate and the Pentagon has warned that the US might not be able to protect itself
if this happens to its nuclear weapons systems.

<P> The problem is compounded by the fact that even a cleaned-up IT system could
be corrupted again if it shares or receives information from an infected external
computer. Furthermore, it is not just IT systems that are affected. Every device
that uses a software timer could be at risk, including a bank safe. Jacky
Olivier, director of the Year 2000 project for Hoskyns, says that many devices
containing computer chips, such as faxes, could be affected.

<P> Although the Year 2000 issue has been widely publicised, many companies are
either unaware of the scale of the problem or are ignoring it. De Jager told the
US House of Representatives Science Committee this year that less than a third of
US companies has started to change its programs. Hoskyns, the UK division of Cap
Gemini Sogeti, surveyed 121 British &THORN;nancial institutions and found that
40% are still in the process of "assessing the scale of the problem" and only 4%
had started to change their applications.

<P> A number of bodies, including the UK government's Central Communications and
Telecommunications Agency (CCTA), produced a report showing that only 8% of
British companies across all sectors had conducted a full audit of the problem
and only 15% of senior managers knew of its existence. Their conclusion: "Unless
speci&THORN;c action is taken immediately, what is currently a manageable problem
will become a crisis in 1997 and 1998."

<P> According to Robin Guenier, a former chief executive of the CCTA who is
organising a Year 2000 conference for chief executives, "Those who say it is not
a problem have often not started to tackle the issue whereas those who have are
much more worried".

<P> Already, companies are experiencing difficulties. Marks &amp; Spencer, the
British food and clothing retailer, became aware of the problem last year when
its computers rejected tins of corned beef that had use-by dates beyond 2000,
calculating that they must be almost 100 years old. British driving licences have
been refused by some US car-hire computers because they run out in the next
century.

<P> Credit cards cannot be issued with expiry dates after 1999 because machines
will calculate that they are long out of date. And any program that uses two-date
digits to calculate sums needs to be &THORN;xed, including accounting
applications and programs involving &THORN;nancial transactions. The Gartner
Group, an IT research organisation, estimates that 90% of such programs will be
affected in 1999.

<P> Technically, the problem must be addressed from three angles. A computer
system generally has three layers: its hardware, an operating system offered by
vendors such as IBM and application programs that large companies usually develop
themselves. Companies with IBM-compatible operating systems can buy a program to
update them for the Year 2000 and other vendors should release similar products.
But companies that have bought operating systems from vendors that have since
gone bust may &THORN;nd their systems extremely difficult to &THORN;x, and it is
almost impossible to salvage corrupted hardware. Philip Oliver, IBM's European
Year 2000 executive, says that companies with this problem may have to buy new
PCs.

<P> Large companies may have up to 30,000 application programs with thousands of
lines that need to be checked: some businesses have more than 10 million lines of
code. These companies will almost certainly need outside consultants,
particularly if they have cut staff in internal IT departments.

<P> The re-programming task is not complicated but is likely to take a long time.
Using the manual approach, each program will take about three days to change. To
&THORN;x 20,000 programs will take 60,000 days or more than 300 man years.
Hoskyns' Olivier says this is a very repetitive and labour-intensive task. Inglis
concurs: "It is not an intellectually demanding job. It is very, very tedious.
Programmers are going to miss things." For this reason, the equally
time-consuming job of testing is vital.

<P> There are expensive tools coming onto the market that will cut the time
needed for this process in half, according to consultants, but they warn that
companies waiting for a "magic bullet" tool that can identify the wrong date and
change programs by itself are misguided. "Anyone who is waiting for that is
kidding himself," says Hoskyns' Olivier.

<P> Jerry Smith, chief technical officer for the Massachusetts-based computer
consultancy &THORN;rm Semaphore, insists that none of his clients has a digit
problem because the company uses object-oriented programming. This allows
programmers to identify and change separate "objects" such as time more quickly.

<P> Time is not the only problem: companies will also have to pay out more money
the longer they wait to act. The Gartner Group estimates that fees have increased
from 30 cents a line of computer code three years ago to more than $1 per line
today and large companies can expect to pay from $50 million to $100 million.
Even small and medium-sized companies will be hit hard, because they will have to
increase spending drastically within a short time period without raising
pro&THORN;ts.

<P> Costs will rise every few months because of the scarcity of programmers who
know Cobol, the most common old-fashioned computer language. Many of the original
programmers are long-retired and companies are already poaching staff from each
other to get the best workers. In one example quoted by De Jager, a large US
insurance company was on the way to solving its digit problem when three of its
top people moved to another company. The estimated cost of starting again from
scratch was $13 million. "Every company in every country faces the same
deadline," says Olivier. "There won't be enough programmers available."

<P> Governments will &THORN;nd it particularly hard to keep their IT staff as
large companies tempt them with huge rises. There is a similar anecdote about an
IT expert working for the US government who was offered $1 million to work for a
consultancy. He refused, reportedly because he thinks he can hold out for more.

<P> Estimates of what it will cost businesses worldwide to &THORN;x the Year 2000
bug range from $400 billion (IBM) to $600 billion (the Gartner Group). The big US
computing services company EDS estimates the cost of solving the problem in
Europe alone at $600 billion. It has been suggested that it may cost the US
government $25 billion and the British government &#163;5 billion ($7.5 billion)
to &THORN;x their systems.

<P> Consultants say that one reason why the Year 2000 problem persists is that IT
managers take a short-term view, because they change jobs frequently. Others are
ashamed to tell the boss because of the large cost involved or because they wrote
the programs themselves. "A lot of people are saying 'I will have retired by
then' or are putting their heads in the sand," explains Hoskyns' Olivier.

<P> Those who work in IT are also renowned for failing to meet deadlines:
Microsoft's on-line magazine is named <I>Slate</I>, apparently, because when
programmers ask each other how a new project is going, the usual reply is,
"S'late". But this is one deadline that cannot be put off.

<P> Managers have tended to leave IT alone and focus on higher level strategy.
With computers now essential to modern business, however, this attitude is no
longer tenable. Oliver of IBM says: "The Year 2000 issue is not just about
technology. It is at the heart of the competitiveness issue." The answer,
according to Guenier, is to see the issue as a management rather than technical
one: "Those with senior positions in IT are not there because they are good
managers but because they are good at IT."

<P> Even when CEOs are aware of the problem, they can be reluctant to tackle it
because of the huge expense involved. "There is a lack of board-level commitment
but because of the price tag, a project like this needs heavyweight people behind
it," says Hoskyns' Olivier. "The business bene&THORN;t is simply to stay in
business, which is a very bitter pill to swallow."

<P> The US is way ahead of most countries in &THORN;ghting the Year 2000 bug. A
recent EDS survey of 352 European companies revealed that only 45% have made
plans to defuse the date time bomb. German companies have made the most progress,
Italians have made the least. Some governments are acting to ensure that their
companies prepare for the millennium. Singapore has passed laws obliging
companies to change their programs and the US government is considering making
inaction illegal.

<P> If a company has not tackled the problem, it should &THORN;rst identify which
programs and code lines are affected. Oliver says IBM started to look at the
issue in the late '80s. "We thought we would replace systems faster than we have,
which is a common problem for companies." With its expertise, IBM is in a much
better position than most companies and expects to be ready by the end of 1997.

<P> Core systems should be a priority. Chris Town, in charge of the Year 2000
issue at Barclays Bank, says: "We are focusing &THORN;rst on the
business-critical systems important to us and our customers. These should be
ready by 1998."

<P> Consultants and software developers suggest that companies use the whole
problem as an opportunity to clean their systems thoroughly. According to Tani
Haqui, chief executive of Virginia-based software company SQL, the Year 2000 is
"the tip of the iceberg in terms of software problems". Haqui's company has come
up with a program to help managers and programmers track the steps a new program
goes through in its development stage. This makes it easy to go back and
&THORN;nd mistakes, reducing the risk of bugs.

<P> If after all this you are still sceptical or believe that the Year 2000 is an
issue dreamed up by consultants and programmers to allow them to dig deep into
your pockets, you might be tempted to test it out on your computer. You would do
better to resist. One businessman changed the date on his computer, setting it to
just before midnight on December 31 1999. Unfortunately, he had a program that
time-stamped data and deleted any &THORN;les more than &THORN;ve years old. The
next thing he knew, most of his &THORN;les were gone.

<H3> HOW TO AVOID THE CRASH: 8 TIPS FOR 2000 </H3> <TABLE BORDER=1 CELLPADDING=1
CELLSPACING=1> <TR><TD><B>Treat the problem as a management issue, not just an IT
problem. Techies are renowned for missing deadlines but this one is immovable.
Make sure all staff are aware of the implications</B></TD> </TR><P>
<TR><TD><B>Start now: it will take time to identify correctly which application
programs are affected. Once you do, miles of code need to be changed in
painstaking work </B></TD> </TR><P> <TR><TD><B>Test your system: do it on replica
hardware and software and allow a year for the job. Remember: there are only 500
working days until the end of 1998 </B></TD> </TR><P> <TR><TD><B>Line up extra
help now: few companies will be able to cope without it but programmers are
scarce and their fees will shoot up as the millennium edges closer. Every
organisation in the world has the same deadline</B></TD> </TR><P> <TR><TD><B>Tool
up: &THORN;nd out more about more automated checking programs that should speed
up the process. But remember that they are not a magic wand: they come at a price
and still take time</B></TD> </TR><P> <TR><TD><B>Ask your regular business
partners what they are doing about the problem. External computers that share
information, if left uncorrected, can corrupt your own system </B></TD> </TR><P>
<TR><TD><B>Look at all your equipment: it is not just IT systems that are
affected but many devices containing silicon chips with time-coded information
</B></TD> </TR><P> <TR><TD><B>Make sure your programs know that 2000 is a leap
year: many do not, with damaging consequences</B></TD> </TR><P> </TABLE> 

<BR>
<BR>
</CENTER>

</TD> </TR> </TABLE> 
