<td valign=top align=left> 

<H3> THE MYTH OF PARTITION </H3>

<H4> As ethnic rivalries multiply, outsiders
often see partition as an easy way to limit their involvement and end the
bloodshed. But history shows that it can often makes things worse. Lessons from
the Cold War and Britain's divide-and-quit past suggest the need for new
solutions, writes Radha Kumar </H4> 

<P> There is a law of partition that runs
something like this: when countries face ethnic division, the warring parties
reach for a copy of the Swiss constitution. This seems to make sense: after all,
the cantonal system has given a multinational state with few natural resources
several centuries of peace and prosperity.

<P> The above law has operated on a number of occasions. During desperate
last-minute negotiations to stave off war in Bosnia-Hercegovina in 1992, it is
said that the Serb, Croat and Muslim delegations all arrived in Lisbon bearing
copies of the Swiss text. Warring parties in Cyprus, Sri Lanka and Kashmir have
also used the document as a common point of reference.

<P> But what works for the Swiss is likely to be of little use in other contexts.
It was an independent candidate from a Tamil-dominated region in Sri Lanka who
pointed out the absurdity of a 1956 proposal to apply the Swiss model: "Let the
[Tamil] federals produce a map of Switzerland. Does it make as ridiculous a map
as the one of Ceylon produced by them? Does not even common sense suggest to them
that there should be geographical continuity among the cantons of the various
states?"

<P> Despite the unhappy experience of modern partitions, there is a deep-seated
belief among many governing elites that the process of slicing countries into
pieces provides a short-cut to ethnic or religious peace. If people cannot live
together, they should live apart.

<P> Last year's Dayton agreement on Bosnia reignited an old debate on partition
as a solution to ethno-nationalist con&thorn;ict in the post-Cold War era.
Although the policy has recurred as an administrative means of resolving
political con&thorn;ict since the third century, when Diocletian divided the
Roman empire along an east-west axis, it began to acquire its capital P only from
the turn of the 17th century and matured only in the 20th.

<P> Since then it has been deployed in two contexts: as a part of the British
divide-and-quit policy in Ireland, India, Palestine and Cyprus, and as part of a
Cold War policy of ideological divide and rule, as seen in Germany, China, Korea
and Vietnam. Now that the Cold War has ended, con&thorn;icts seen as ethnic have
taken centre-stage in contemporary security concerns. These are categorised as
prolonged low-level con&thorn;icts over statehood between groups that de&THORN;ne
ethnicity according to language, culture, race or religion.

<P> Attention has turned to partition as a means of resolving or containing such
wars, following the division of Ireland, India, Palestine and Cyprus which were
said to be based on irreconcilable ethnic differences. The argument goes that
partition is probably the most humane form of intervention in an ethnic
con&thorn;ict because it attempts through negotiation what would otherwise be
achieved through war: it telescopes the con&thorn;ict and saves lives.

<P> Yet the success of divide-and-quit depends on who is getting (or staying) out
and where the partition is. The quitting impulse goes some way to explaining
British support for partition in Ireland and India. From the sequence of events
in Bosnia, it seems clear that Europe and the international community were
prepared to accept partition if this would curtail outside intervention in the
con&thorn;ict and limit the length of western involvement.

<P> But does it work? Proximity has made it very difficult for the British to
disengage from Ireland; if anything, partition has involved it more closely in
the six counties of the north. Bosnia's Europeanness creates a similar difficulty
for both Europe and the US. It is already clear that international troops will
have to remain longer than Washington planned. The international civilian
presence has multiplied severalfold since the Dayton peace accord and its tenure
is likely to extend beyond the &THORN;ve years originally envisaged.

<P> For the inhabitants of a partitioned country, the policy means misery. They
pay an incalculable price through continuing loss of life, a consequent drain on
resources, the barriers imposed on economic development by con&thorn;ict and the
psychologically debilitating sense of victimisation.

<P> Partition is sold as a means of ending con&thorn;ict. It can, however, be
argued that the reverse is true: that far from curtailing war, partition is an
essential element in it (see below, pages 28-33).

<P> It is often argued that partition can be achieved through a peaceful rather
than a bloody population transfer, especially where it is agreed in advance.
India is seen as a prime example in this context, because the Congress Party and
Muslim League had agreed to partition before civil war broke out. But it is
difficult to imagine millions of people agreeing to give up their homes without a
protest.

<P> The Greek-Turkish population exchange, agreed as part of a settlement
following World War I, is frequently cited as a peaceful transfer because it did
not take place in conditions of war, but it nevertheless comprised the forcible
movement of populations. The British examined population transfers in
considerable detail during early discussions of the partition of Palestine in
1936-7. The recognition that these would have to be achieved by force was one
argument for jettisoning partition plans.

<P> In Bosnia, as in India and Palestine, populations were transferred by force
rather than agreement. This process began in the spring of 1992, when Serb
paramilitaries and the Yugoslav National Army (JNA) began to create the eastern
crescent and western bloc of the ethno-territory later named Republica Srpska. At
the same time Serb forces began shelling Bosnia's capital city, Sarajevo. By the
summer, a three-way partition of Bosnia had been &thorn;eshed out by Serbs and
Croats and detailed maps of Republika Srpska and the Croatian entity Herceg-Bosna
were agreed, including the partition of Mostar. Until this point Croats and
Muslims had shared the brunt of Serb attack, but now the Croatian paramilitary
HVO turned on the Muslims in the east of Mostar.

<P> The HVO began to consolidate its hold on territory with cash and materiel
support from its backers in Croatia, including President Franjo Tudjman's
government. In October con&thorn;ict began between the Croats and the Bosnian
army. Within the &THORN;rst six months of the war the thrust towards partition
was unmistakable: borders had been agreed by the main contenders and various
armies had launched offensives to impose them on the ground. European leaders
appeared to anticipate this development. At the European Community-sponsored
peace conference in September 1991 the chairman, former British Foreign Secretary
Lord Carrington, sought to avert a war of partition by proposing power-sharing
arrangements that were both decentralised and ethno-political.

<P> This was an approach last adopted by the British in India in the years before
partition. It had failed partly because it was grounded on ethno-nationalism,
elements of which had informed British colonial policy for many years. In a
policy commonly referred to as divide-and-rule, the British initially granted the
right to hold local elections in tandem with the creation of separate Muslim and
Hindu electorates. Instead of encouraging power-sharing, the policy stimulated
con&thorn;ict between the minority Muslim League and the majority Congress Party,
encouraging ethno-political mobilisation in both communities.

<P> Its effects were bitterly felt between 1945-7, when the British attempted to
negotiate an agreement on power-sharing between Congress and the League that
would allow a British withdrawal from India and avert a war of partition.
Negotiations broke down time and time again over two related issues: Congress's
refusal to concede the League's claim to be sole spokesman for Indian Muslims
&#173; which would by implication give Congress a clearly Hindu label &#173; and
the League's defensive refusal to enter any power-sharing relationship that would
question its right to rule in Muslim-majority areas.

<P> By breaking down trust, ethno-politics militates against power-sharing.
Congress and the League came to the verge of agreement on a decentralised
federation of Muslim and Hindu-majority provinces in 1946, but the agreement
broke down when the League refused to allow the Congress to nominate a Muslim to
the transitional government.

<P> More strikingly, the British-brokered 1960 constitution that made Cyprus
independent was an attempt to avert the partition the British had themselves
threatened in 1956. It was based on a minimum compromise that employed the
principle of ethnic representation at every level. This created separate
municipalities and provided for ethnic quotas in the civil service, the police
and the army.

<P> Though Turks comprised some 18% of the population, they were allocated 30% of
the jobs. They were also given a right of veto in legislative decisions on the
electoral system and taxation. Because the constitution was achieved by engaging
moderates on either side while conciliating ethno-nationalists, it stimulated
protracted con&thorn;ict that eventually resulted in the Turkish invasion and
partition.

<P> As the case of Palestine shows, ethno-political negotiation generally leads
to ethno-territorial consolidation: the more demographically mixed the regions
the more violent the process. In Bosnia, once it was clear that the international
community would mediate on an ethno-political principle, the logical move was for
the warring parties to consolidate territories.

<P> Thus, in 1993, when UN mediator Cyrus Vance and his EU colleague David Owen
proposed 10 ethnically based cantons under a weak federal government, it helped
escalate the Croatian-Muslim con&thorn;ict to all-out war. According to Owen, the
cantonal borders had been arranged so that no single ethnic group would have
contiguous territories, thus preserving the unity of Bosnia. But the Croatians,
who stood to gain larger territories under the plan than they either controlled
or could claim on the basis of ethnic proportionality, hastened to expel Bosnian
Muslims from these areas. The Serbs, who stood to lose territory, at &THORN;rst
attempted to establish contiguous territories and then rejected the plan.

<P> By 1993 Washington had moved closer to support for the ethnic partition of
Bosnia. In May the US, Russia, Britain, France and Spain put forward a Joint
Action Plan for a union of three republics, the sealing-off of Bosnian borders
and the establishment of six safe areas. The plan was widely seen as a harbinger
of the next stage of talks towards a three-way partition. Hard bargaining began
over territorial boundaries which continued well into the autumn, accompanied by
&THORN;erce &THORN;ghting. The US, however, was pursuing a two-track policy:
while officially supporting the Joint Action Plan, it made behind-the-scenes
attempts to limit partition by brokering a Muslim-Croat federation. Initially
these attempts were met by intensi&THORN;cation of the Croat-Muslim war but US
pressure eventually persuaded Tudjman to sign a federal agreement with the
Muslims in March 1994. Viewed as a tacit acceptance of the two-way partition of
Bosnia, it was immediately followed by a Serb demand for recognition of Republika
Srpska and renewed attacks on Muslim eastern enclaves.

<P> The Washington agreement, a version of the Swiss cantonisation model, in fact
brought partition to a more intimate stage. Like the 1960 Cyprus constitution, it
mandated ethnic representation at local as well as national levels and extended
it to the civil services, entrenched partition from the bottom up.

<P> Under the Washington agreement, Mostar was intended to embody precisely the
opposite process: the city was placed under international administration so as to
dissolve partition at the local level. But because the agreement on Mostar made
all decisions dependent on a council composed equally of Croats and Muslims, each
represented by their own mayors, the EU administration found itself a frequent
and rather expensive bystander as the ethnic nationalists who partitioned the
city consolidated power through the agreement's provisions. The struggle still
continues despite recent city elections.

<P> Not that Richard Holbrooke, then US assistant secretary of state and the
architect of the Dayton agreement, would admit that partition was on the agenda.
Refusing to use the label, he told a US news programme that the voluntary
dissolution of Czechoslovakia &#173; the bloodless "velvet divorce" of 1992
&#173; was a better comparison. The disingenuity of this comment was striking,
given that the Dayton agreement was prefaced by another Serb onslaught on the
eastern enclaves of Bosnia that resulted in the fall of Srebrenica and the worst
genocide of an already atrocious war, while the international community stood by.
The west continued to dither while the Serbs moved on to Zepa and only threatened
air strikes when Gorazde, the largest enclave, was imperilled.

<P> Meanwhile, Croatia conquered the Serbian-held Krajina, resulting in a mass
exodus of indigenous Serbs to Bosnia. President Clinton responded by saying this
meant a solution for Bosnia might be in sight. At the same time, Serb forces
mopped up in the Muslim eastern enclaves. It was now possible to see a viable
partition on the ground.

<P> This suspicion grew as Croatian and Bosnian forces jointly attacked
Serbian-held areas, which fell with the same ease as the Krajina. Only when the
Croatian-Bosnian forces controlled the 51% share of Bosnian territory that was
allotted them in 1993 by the international community did international pressure
to halt the war become overwhelming.

<P> In other words, the Bosnian war only underlines the point made by the
partitions of Ireland, India, Palestine and Cyprus: in demographically dispersed
countries partition is only achieved through the violent creation of ethnically
homogenous territories on the ground. Indeed, partition negotiations can occur
either as the culmination of war, or as its cause.

<P> It is now being argued, in the context of the Dayton Accord, that to agree
partition after homogenous territories have already been established is
substantively different from consenting before their creation on the ground.
Quite apart from the peculiar formalism of an argument that ignores the process
of tacit and not-so-tacit recognition of partition, it is usually fallacious to
argue that ethnically homogenous territories have already been created. Close to
half the population of Bosnia remain refugees outside Bosnia: ethnically
homogenous territories can only be created if they are refused repatriation to
the towns and villages from which they were driven. In this sense "peaceful
partition" is a grotesque misnomer for a process that can entail genocide.

<P> Signi&THORN;cantly, partition is often seen as a temporary solution to a
crisis, which can be reversed later. Experience shows, however, that
ethno-nationalist partitions have never been reversed: instead, the process has
inexorably driven communities further apart. Sinn Fein's acquiescence to the
partition of Ireland, for example, was conditional on a later referendum on
uni&THORN;cation. The referendum never took place and now, when there are renewed
negotiations on the status of Northern Ireland, Sinn Fein has to face the ironic
possibility that Ireland may no longer wish for uni&THORN;cation.

<P> India similarly hoped that a subsequent vote would reverse the partition.
Again, no vote took place. Instead, Pakistan was further divided when Bangladesh
split off in an even uglier war than that sparked by India's division. As most
Bosnia-watchers would agree, yet another partition lurks within the Dayton
Accord: the disintegration of the Muslim-Croatian Federation.

<P> Nor does partition ensure a post-war peace. Far from solving the Irish
con&thorn;ict, partition merely helped to entrench guerrilla con&thorn;ict in
Ulster: India and Pakistan have twice gone to war and continue to battle over
Kashmir. The Middle East has suffered from conflict since the partition of
Palestine and recent moves towards peace resulted in the assassination of Israeli
prime minister Rabin.

<P> Indeed, partition can often hamper the development of post-war peace.
Attempts to build economic cooperation and encourage cross-cultural exchanges in
south Asia have been successively impeded by the Indian-Pakistani dispute over
the status of Kashmir.

<P> Irish nationalists and UN mediators in Palestine both hoped that moves
towards economic union would gradually dissipate the horrible aftermath of
partition. Instead, partition's legacy was to thwart economic union and keep both
regions in poverty. The lessons of these examples for Bosnia are noteworthy. The
Dayton Accord provided for economic union in the hope that market forces would
bring the Serb entity and the Muslim-Croat Federation closer together. Experience
elsewhere implies this hope is unfounded.

<P> <I>The author is a SSRC-MacArthur fellow at the Institute of War and Peace
Studies, Columbia University. This article is taken from a forthcoming book on
partition in India and Bosnia</I>

<H3>Ireland 1921  </H3>  

<P> Although
the British idea to divide Ireland cropped up late in the midst of talks on home
rule during the 1919-21 Irish war for independence, partition had been suggested
years before, when Irish Protestants threatened to secede if Catholic Ireland won
home rule. In&thorn;uential support for this position on the British mainland led
London to explore means of excluding Ulster from Irish home rule, including a
temporary <BR> six-year partition. By 1914 Irish Nationalists and Ulster
Unionists had agreed on the principle, but were deadlocked on the division of
territory. But the willingness of moderate nationalists to consider partition
divided and splintered the movement through the creation of the radical
nationalist Sinn Fein.

<P> Although home rule was suspended during World War I, negotiations continued
and gained new impetus from the Easter 1916 nationalist uprising. The execution
of the rebellion's leaders by the British infused Irish nationalism and in 1918
Sinn Fein swept the polls, declared independence and formed an Irish Assembly.
Partly under the pressure of these events, Britain tabled the Government of
Ireland Bill in 1919 giving Ireland two parliaments, one for the south and
another for the north.

<P> The original proposal was aimed at averting partition along religious lines
by including all nine of the Ulster counties in the northern parliament. This
would have ensured roughly equal proportions of Protestants and Catholics.
However the Unionists' desire to have <BR> a separate parliament and their fear
of living with too large a Catholic population moved talks towards a six-county
limit.

<P> Sinn Fein, arguing that the bill was tantamount to a double partition of
Ireland and Ulster based on religion, rejected it and con&thorn;ict spread across
the country, escalating to guerrilla war with the formation of the Irish
Republican Army in 1920. Nor did the war end in 1921, when Britain negotiated a
treaty with Sinn Fein offering South Ireland dominion status on condition that it
<BR> accept the creation of a separate Ulster that would remain within the United
Kingdom.

<P> By this time, Sinn Fein preferred that Ulster remain under British rule
rather than have its own parliament because this would keep open the possibility
of uni&THORN;cation. The treaty provided for a temporary partition <BR> of
Ireland on condition that a referendum on reuni&THORN;cation be held within two
years. The decision to accept partition split Sinn Fein, adding two years of
internecine con&thorn;ict to communal con&thorn;ict. The British later reneged on
the promised referendum.


<H3>India 1947</H3>

<P> Like Ireland, the religious partition of north-western and eastern India that
created two independent states, India and Pakistan, emerged from a
now-you-see-it-now-you-don't process of devolution from London's imperial
control.

<P> In 1917 British Foreign Secretary Arthur Balfour of Palestine fame promised a
"gradual" move towards self-government in India but over the next 20 years it was
introduced at local levels only.

<P> As in Ireland, war hastened partition and independence. Following World War
II the radical new Labour government had no desire to pit an emaciated Britain
<BR> against powerful Indian independence movements and it agreed to the speedy
transfer of power.

<P> Although partition was decided only in 1947, the idea had been proposed
intermittently from the early years of the century.

<P> By the '40s British officials, especially those in north-western India, were
referring openly to an entity called Pakistan. The decision to divide India was
taken in 1946 after the breakdown of negotiations on a decentralised
federation.

<P> Agreement was &THORN;nally given to the ethno-nationalist logic of the
"two-nation theory", that separate nations deserved separate territories. This
entailed the division of Punjab and Bengal and meant not only a much smaller
Pakistan than that envisaged by its advocate, the Muslim League, but also a
Pakistan divided into east and west, and separated by India.

<P> The partition of India was announced quickly after the agreement was
&THORN;nalised, before borders had been decided and without any consideration of
the people involved.

<P> In the six months following the decision to establish the partition, close to
4 million people died and 20 million were displaced as a partition planned on
paper was then bloodily created on the ground.

 <H3>Palestine 1948 </H3> 

<P> Detailed proposals for the partition of Palestine had been made by the
British in 1937-8, spurred by Hitler's persecution of the Jews. However the
eastward spread of World War II and the Axis threat to British positions in the
Middle East led to a rapid reversal of support for a Jewish state.

<P> After the war London proposed a &THORN;ve-year trusteeship that would include
a large amount of <BR> self-government for Arab and Jewish areas. The proposal
was rejected by Arabs on the grounds that this would entrench partition and by
Zionists on the grounds that it would create a single state with an Arab
majority.

<P> In 1947 the British referred the dispute to the UN. This produced a minority
proposal for a binational federal state and a majority proposal for partition.

<P> The Security Council opted for partition, with a special UN regime for
Jerusalem and a continuing economic union for Palestine.

<P> Britain then washed its hands and announced that it would withdraw in May
1948. Con&thorn;ict broke out in Palestine and rapidly escalated into war between
Israel and a clutch of Arab states, resulting in the displacement of some 750,000
Palestinian Arabs, whom Israel refused to repatriate once the war had ended.

<H3> &#009;Czechoslovakia 1993 </H3> <P> Czechoslovakia is often cited by
supporters of partition. The country divided in peace on January 1, 1993, just
four years after the anti-communist revolution. The result, separate Slovak and
Czech Republics, re&thorn;ected their different histories and political cultures.

<P> The creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918 out of the former Austro-Hungarian
empire was the result of horse-trading between the &THORN;rst President TG
Masaryk and various Czech and Slovak emigrant groups in the US. A referendum on
union with the Czechs was promised to the Slovaks but was never made good. So
from the outset, there was the bitterness of a broken promise at the heart of the
marriage between the two Slav peoples. That may have been partly responsible for
the strong showing of anti-Czechoslovak parties in Slovakia before World War II
and the subsequent creation of a Nazi puppet state run by clerico-fascist Slovak
collaborators.

<P> The installation of a communist regime from 1948-89 froze the <I>status quo
ante</I> but within a year of the restitution of democracy, strains developed
between the liberal ex-dissidents around Federal President Vaclav Havel in the
Czech capital Prague and the regional government in Bratislava, which was keen to
articulate a Slovak identity and move more slowly on economic transformation.

<P> Unable to agree a workable plan for devolution, the two sides were caught in
years of increasingly frustrating negotiations up to the 1992 federal elections.
These returned the nationalist Vladimir Meciar to power in Slovakia and the
impatient economic reformer Vaclav Klaus in the Czech Republic.

<P> With Havel's liberal dissidents gone, the Czechs resumed negotiations in a
brisk <BR> no-nonsense atmosphere and called Meciar's bluff. Havel's long-stated
demand for a referendum was brushed aside by the regional Czech and Slovak
governments which quickly agreed on separation. Since then relations have
remained civilised and indeed there was never any suggestion that the division
would be marred by violence: for one thing, Havel made it clear he would never
use force in Slovakia.

<P> Although it is tempting to point to such a happy experience as a model, there
are several reasons why this is inappropriate. The main one is that it is largely
unrepeatable. Czechoslovakia was always likely to be an easy divorce: there was
very little ethnic mixing and no tradition of inter-communal violence. At worst
there is irritation rather than hatred between the two peoples.

<P> It is also too early to tell whether partition is bene&THORN;cial. Although
the Czech and Slovak economies have prospered since the split, the federation
would almost certainly have achieved a similar performance. And from a
geopolitical point of view the division has left Slovakia somewhat adrift, more
prone to look east than west for neighbourly support. The unrivalled control of
the populist and illiberal Meciar has arguably ensured his country's exclusion
from Nato and the EU.

<P> The divorce also left the Czechs alone with themselves, an even smaller
country in a region full of small countries, leaving a grain of self-doubt.

<P> The evening the split was agreed, one Czech negotiator wondered aloud about
the decision: "Before tonight I hadn't really thought about the implications, we
just got on with the talks. Now I ask myself, just what have we done?"

<H3> Bosnia 1991 to present </H3> 
<P> The case of Bosnia shows that
partition provides no answer to ethno-nationalist con&thorn;icts.  In March
1991, Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic met Croatian President Franjo Tudjman
to discuss a partition of Bosnia. The Croatians wanted a division into ethnic
cantons or restructured as a union of three constituent nations but Bosnian
President Alija Izetbegovic rejected the proposal.

<P> By autumn 1991 the &THORN;rst outlines of partition began to be sketched. In
September Bosnian Serbs started declaring so-called Serb autonomous regions and
in November the Croats followed suit, declaring a "Croatian Community of
Herceg-Bosna" in the 38 mainly Croat communes. Later that year Serbs and Croats
agreed on borders. In February 1992, a week before the referendum on independence
for Bosnia-Hercegovina set by the European Community as a condition of
recognition, the Community sponsored talks in Lisbon that focused on the
possibility of cantonisation.

<P> Few believed that it would take more than three years of bitter war,
prolonged international mediation and an intervention force of 60,000 heavily
armed troops to make partition acceptable. Few realised that the subsequent peace
settlement would largely formalise what war had already achieved.

<P> Yet this, it seems, is what will happen. Formally, the Dayton peace agreement
of last November is intended to institute a prolonged cease&THORN;re that will
result  in a peace based either on partition or reintegration. Most
Bosnia-watchers agree, however, that the chances of reintegration are slim since
it depends on the erasure of internal borders, the reinforcement of external
borders, the prosecution of war criminals, the return of refugees and a speedy
injection of massive &THORN;nancial aid.

<P> Instead, with a little help from Nato, the zone of separation is turning into
a <I>de facto</I> partition line that might soon constitute the real border
between Serbia and Bosnia. The border between Croatia and Bosnia continues to lie
deep inside western Bosnia, while refugees are caught in a game of population
transfer: as late as March, Serbs were resettling Brcko, an area under
international arbitration. Even the promised aid, which at $1.5 billion fell far
short of the $5 billion estimate for basic reconstruction, has not arrived.

<P> The two main &THORN;gures indicted for war crimes, Radovan Karadzic and Ratko
Mladic, continue to wield considerable in&thorn;uence in Serb-controlled
territories. Elections planned for September are not expected to be free and fair
and will probably constitute another stage of the partition process. Their virtue
will be to demonstrate that "the people" want ethnic states, precisely why the
Serbs fought in the &THORN;rst place.

<BR>
