<H3> NASTY OR NICE? </H3> 

<H4> The intellectual tide
is now beginning to turn against downsizing. The focus has shifted from the
benefits of mass redundancy to the impact on social peace and business
ef&THORN;ciency it seems to entail. But the nicer alternatives, if they are to
succeed, call for that elusive quality of management originality. Francis Harris
reports from the shop&thorn;oor </H4> <P> Downsizing is not just a dirty word at
the Lincoln Electric Corporation plant in Cleveland, Ohio. It is redundant. The
idea was given its marching orders in 1948 and it has not been heard of since in
the cavernous factory halls of the welding equipment manufacturer.

<P> The people at Lincoln are not exactly smug about this feat. Every business,
however successful, ought to know that resting on your laurels is a sure way of
provoking disaster. But there is some incomprehension about what has happened in
the rest of the US, where many companies have improved the bottom line by sacking
staff.

<P> There are now some indications that the intellectual tide has turned against
downsizing as the cure-all for corporate ailments. Of course, firms have always
laid off staff and they always will: once again this summer, there has been a
grim roll-call of casualties from America's corporate frontline as Nabisco,
Digital and other giants laid off staff.

<P> But there has been a backlash. In the '90s, senior managers are described by
the media in terms close to those used for the generals of World War I, men
lambasted for lack of imagination and over-reliance on a single strategy. In both
the US and Britain, the two countries where the blood-letting has been most
severe, there is now widespread political and public hostility to downsizing and
its practitioners.

<P> There is also a gathering alliance of economists, management theorists and
consultants who question whether the cure is more damaging than the illness and
who stress the need for growth in revenue. In this atmosphere, companies like
Lincoln that have bucked the trend are being put under the microscope to see what
lessons, if any, can be learned by other firms.

<P> Richard Sabo has some claim to personifying the spirit of the firm. A 30-year
veteran, he held a number of positions including some on the shopfloor before
becoming assistant to the chief executive. Asked about downsizing, he is careful
never to say never: "I'm sure that it is inevitable in some circumstances, but we
like to think that we would try everything else first."

<P> In the recessions of the '80s and '90s that commitment was put to the test at
the firm, which has a US payroll of 3,500. On both occasions Lincoln held the
line through its use of flexible employment practices. Factory workers turned
salesmen and were sent out into the country to boost revenues, while other
workers were re-employed on maintenance work.

<P> The firm argues that this sort of scheme proves its value when there is an
upturn in the wider economy. While rivals have to rehire and retrain, Lincoln can
rapidly put staff back into productive work. While the firm lost money in 1992
and 1993, last year it posted record profits of $61 million on sales of $1.03
billion. In the first quarter of this year, net sales were up nearly 6% to $278
million.

<P> This story might have been different if Lincoln relied on Wall Street, but
the firm's shareholders are descendants of the founder or former employees. Thus
when Lincoln's management wanted to pay staff bonuses in the loss-making year of
1992-3, it went and borrowed the cash. "The shareholders were very
understanding," Sabo says.

<P> The firm has an unusual pay and benefit system. After three years staff are
guaranteed at least 30 hours' work a week but pay is calculated according to
performance, as are holiday entitlements. They are also expected to put defective
products right in their own time, so there is a considerable incentive to produce
the best product as quickly as possible. According to Sabo, Lincoln's US
pieceworkers make $62,000 a year compared to the national average of $55,000: the
best make up to $130,000.

<P> The incentives mask a tough attitude. Management trusts staff and expects
hard work in return. There are no unions: Sabo says the employees have no desire
for one. Overtime is non-negotiable, so that at busy times staff can work up to
70 hours a week. "We are pretty tough," Sabo says. "We expect people to be
dedicated and accept overtime. Anything less would be a disservice to everyone."

<P> Not everyone likes this and the firm is coy about the number of employees who
leave before the three-year watershed. "We find many people looking for a job,
but not so many who want to succeed," Sabo says. Even so, the company rarely
needs to be heavy-handed: "Our employees are committed to a job. They never cease
to amaze me. Even if they are not asked, they come back [late] at night to check
on a job. It's a culture that we expect people to pass from one generation to the
next."

<P> Such a comment probably summarises the Lincoln attitude, with its stress on
continuity. While management elsewhere is often accused of slavishly pursuing the
latest management craze, its system has developed from the ideas of founder James
Lincoln who established the firm 101 years ago. An advisory board established in
1914 gives workers the chance to discuss issues with the chief executive or
chairman and there are regular meetings in the canteen which draw up to 400
staff.

<P> Despite the evident commitment to consultation, there are worries among the
staff. Recent years have seen a growing number of outsiders brought into the
company and some question whether new board members and finance staff have the
same commitment to the Lincoln way as those raised within the company. One worker
said he had heard an accountant muttering that the firm had mortgaged its future
by paying out such high bonuses.

<P> Even so, it seems unlikely to abandon its independent course. Chief executive
Donald Hastings parades his company's example, telling one recent business
meeting: "We need to find creative solutions to replace the notion that lay-offs
are a cure-all for a company's problems. It is management's responsibility to
find solutions, to plan ahead for down times, to be flexible enough to respond to
any new situation. That's what management is all about."

<P> For many industrial workers who have been downsized out of a job, and for
politicians seeking an alternative model, Lincoln Electric might sound close to
paradise. Indeed, many other companies have sent teams to examine the Lincoln way
and it was represented on President Bill Clinton's corporate citizenship panel
that sought "good corporate citizens" to hold up as examples. But like so many
firms with alternative strategies, it is a success in its own terms: the fact
that many workers leave in less than three years raises doubts about how it might
work if applied more widely. The truth seems to be that Lincoln has blazed its
own trail and it would be hard for others to follow.

<P> It is a point made by downsizing debunkers like Jeffrey Pfeffer, professor of
organisational behaviour at Stanford Business School. "This is an issue of
mind-set: there is no magic bullet. The very fact that most managers cannot do it
means that those who are able to do it can achieve enormous returns. How can you
get above-average returns if you do what everyone else does? The only way to
achieve that goal is to do something different."

<P> This holds true for other successful US rogue corporations cited by Pfeffer
such as Southwest Airlines, Wal-Mart, Tyson Foods, Circuit City and Plenum
Publishing, which rank as the top five performing firms in the country from
1972-92 in terms of returns to shareholders. He identifies the defining element
in their success as an imaginative approach to managing the workforce, but doubts
that this can be applied in some mechanistic fashion by competitors. And of
course, even if they could, a law of diminishing returns would come into play.
"If everyone looked like Demi Moore, she would not be worth the same amount of
money and it is the same with companies. If every company could grow quickly, it
would be valued less," Pfeffer says.

<P> Although he argues that downsizing is a failure, like most of the debunkers
Pfeffer does not rule it out: "The simple lesson is to understand where your
value is coming from. If [downsizing] actually creates value, then perhaps it's
the wise thing to do. But I think the evidence is fairly clear that the only
thing guaranteed by downsizing is that you get smaller."

<P> A number of US firms have been given favourable press. Johnson &amp;
Johnson's ethical approach and its patience with non-performing subsidiaries and
managers is wholly at odds with current Wall Street thinking, yet it produced a
17% return to investors from 1989-94.

<P> Hewlett-Packard has won plaudits for showing a sense of corporate
responsibility and for helping redundant workers find new jobs, while smaller
firms such as vehicle parts maker Fel-Pro of Illinois has been feted by the White
House for its distribution of generous employee benefits. The privately owned
jeans maker Levi Strauss received considerable publicity when it promised
employees a year's extra pay if cashflow targets are reached in 2002. In the UK,
considerate employers such as the giant Cadbury-Schweppes and the smaller
domestic heating group Baxi Partnership have attracted positive comment.

<P> The search for alternatives is the result of an implicit alliance between
management theorists, economists, business figures and politicians that has
reached critical mass over the past year. But this shift has failed to produce a
coherent theory with the same appeal as downsizing. Firms that cut staff can
expect the markets in New York and London to reward them with a rapid improvement
in share price, although many observers question whether the reward is lasting.
The problem is that while "nice" behaviour can pay dividends, it is a far tougher
course and requires greater imagination than being "nasty".

<P> Two years ago Gary Hamel and CK Prahalad wrote <I>Competing for the
Future</I>, in which they described alternative strategies for productivity
improvements and growth. The authors argued that the starting point was an
independent point of view about future opportunities. Firms seeking an improved
return on investment could follow two paths. Either they could increase net
income (the numerator) or cut assets and payrolls (the denominator). Faced with
the need to make quick returns, many managers took the easy path and cut staff.

<P> "The United States and Britain have produced an entire generation of
denominator managers. They can downsize, declutter, delayer and divest better
than any managers in the world. Even before the current wave of downsizing US and
British companies had, on average, the highest asset productivity ratios of any
companies in the world," they wrote.

<P> But without growth, reducing staff or assets is simply a means of selling
market share at a profit. Taking the example of Britain during the Thatcher years
of the '80s, Hamel and Prahalad point out that from 1969-91 manufacturing output
rose by just 10%. Encouraged by a welter of deregulation and anti-union
legislation, manufacturing employment fell by 37% while British ministers
trumpeted the resulting surge in manufacturing productivity. "In fact," the
authors note, "with scarcely any net gain in real manufacturing output over the
period, British companies were in effect surrendering global market share."

<P> Two events this year have propelled a shift in the debate. The first was the
noisy presidential election bid by right-winger Pat Buchanan, who campaigned on
an uncompromising ticket expressing middle-class fears about job insecurity .
This swelled an already considerable volume of journalism on the subject. Mused
<I>The Washington Monthly:</I> "What do we do if there is not enough...
decent-paying work to go around in a democracy built on the work ethic? Would the
democracy survive if there were millions and millions of unemployed or
under-employed men and women pushed out of... white-collar and skilled
blue-collar work?"

<P> The US daily <I>The New York Times </I>&#173; one of those rare institutions
taken almost as seriously as it takes itself &#173; decided the issue was so
important that it merited the longest piece of reportage the paper had produced
since the Pentagon Papers. The resulting book, <I>The Downsizing of America,</I>
made the startling claim that 43 million US jobs had been lost since 1979.

<P> "Workers have always lost jobs in America to the churning cycles of the
economy and [usually] more jobs were being created than eliminated, but never
before had lay-offs persisted with such tenacity and in such magnitude in an
expanding economy," it wrote.

<P> To the defenders of downsizing who suggested the economy was doing well, the
paper responded: "Almost 200 years ago, the same argument might have been made
when the peasants of England were shunted off the land and left to toil in misery
in the slums. It was good for the economy, maybe, but it also precipitated the
wrenching social ills that fill the sorrowful pages of Charles Dickens."

<P> The second factor to change the debate was the conversion of one of the high
priests of downsizing. The public recantation by Morgan Stanley chief economist
Stephen Roach clearly surprised a lot of people. In a report earlier this year,
Roach mused: "In the face of intense competition, managers may simply have pared
the largest [cost], worker compensation, which represents 70% of corporate
production expenses. If that is so, the so-called productivity resurgence has
been built on slash-and-burn restructuring strategies that have put extraordinary
pressures on the workforce. This approach is not a permanent solution. Tactics of
open-ended downsizing and real wage compression are ultimately recipes for
industrial extinction."

<P> Every action produces a reaction and the defenders of corporate change have
been quick to respond. For every American Management Association survey showing
that downsizing is bad for business, there is a response from financial
institutions showing that corporate profits have merely returned to '60s peaks.

<P> According to a research paper by Joshua Feinman and John Williams of Bankers
Trust, the share of US national income taken by employees has remained at about
72% since the '70s. Since 1959, the share taken as corporate profits has
fluctuated around 10%. The common belief that workers have lost out to
shareholders is bogus, they argue: once rises in non-wage compensation like
bonuses and retirement benefits are included, workers are being rewarded for
higher output.

<P> While they accept that living standards have fallen for many Americans they
say: "The average worker is not being cheated by unscrupulous corporations or
cheap Third World labour. Workers as a group are getting their just rewards. And
these rewards have continued to grow, albeit at a pretty sluggish pace in the
past generation."

<P> Jill Jacobs of Goldman Sachs makes a similar argument in a research paper
produced in June, where she says that the rise in profit margins merely reflects
a return to the "normal" profit levels of the '60s. But now that profits have
returned to these levels, they are likely to stabilise as a share of GDP.

<P> Nonetheless, Jacobs accepts that this "return to normal" has been achieved at
a price: "White-collar workers saw their displacement rate &#173; the rate of job
loss for workers tenured three years or more &#173; rise from 2.6% in the early
'80s to 3.6% a decade later. Although white-collar workers have a high
re-employment rate, the churn in jobs is important because it creates uncertainty
by indicating that even managerial, executive and administrative jobs are not
immune from downsizing pressures... displaced workers typically rejoined the
labour force with lower earnings &#173; a 7.7% average decline for white-collar
workers and a 10.9% average drop for manufacturing workers."

<P> Among those entering the fray is Paul Krugman, the Stanford economics
professor. In an article in <I>Slate</I>, Microsoft's online magazine, Krugman
takes issue with those debunkers in the US administration led by labour secretary
Robert Reich, whose arguments are described as "clear, compelling, brilliantly
packaged and mostly wrong".

<P> Krugman cites a report by the White House's own council of economic advisers
to counter the argument that downsizing is cutting through the sinews of the
American middle class. "The big picture looks like this," Krugman says. "Both the
number of 'good jobs' and the pay that goes with [them] are steadily rising...
Only a relative handful of good job holders (which is to say only a few hundred
thousand a year) experience serious reverses. America's middle class may be
anxious, but objectively it is doing fine." The real losers are those on the
bottom, "who do not have good jobs and never did. Those with lousy jobs have seen
their already low wages sink."

<P> The council's report found the US economy to be in good health. From 1993-6,
8.5 million new jobs were created and two-thirds of these paid above-average
wages. Most of these jobs were full-time. Nonetheless, the author Joseph Stiglitz
said that real wages had stagnated and income inequality widened: "Data from
1981-93 indicate that job-losers were more likely to be permanently dismissed
(rather than temporarily laid off), that older workers were subject to a greater
risk of job displacement and that the average real wage loss due to displacement
was significant and persistent."

<P> In an apparent reference to Reich's concerns, Stiglitz acknowledged the
"considerable evidence" that Americans are anxious about job loss, but like
Krugman appealed for an objective examination of the evidence.

<P> This reaches to the heart of the debate. While an examination of cold
statistics may be grist to the optimists' mill, that message is simply not
getting through to the population at large. It is tempting to attack the
messenger. Thus Krugman refers to downsizing as a "camera-ready tragedy, perfect
for media exploitation" and John Cassidy in <I>The New Yorker </I>talks of a
journalistic growth industry. In other words, the population is being misled by
journalists who cannot see the woods of economic success for the trees of
individual suffering.

<P> But the problem is the message, not the messenger. For all the weaknesses of
<I>The New York Times</I> articles, so clinically exposed by Cassidy (the
estimate of 43 million lost jobs is suspect and ignores massive US success in the
creation of jobs), there is an underlying core of truth to what journalists are
reporting. The "good news" heralded by cold statistics are unlikely to achieve
much resonance with the middle-class man made fearful as friends lose jobs and
angry at ever-longer hours of work.

<P> This may be attributable to the first real experience of economic insecurity
among the middle classes since the Great Depression, but it clearly exists.
<I>The New York Times</I> reproduced a survey of graduates from Bucknell
University's class of 1970. Some of the findings among graduates are startling:
72% feel it is unlikely that young people will have a better life than their
parents; 54% are working longer hours; 74% worry that their savings will prove
inadequate for retirement; 91% feel firms have become less loyal to employees;
60% believe that the working atmosphere has become angrier and more than
three-quarters of the respondents had either been laid off or knew of a relative
or friend who had been so.

<P> The survey was not universally bleak. More than four out of five Bucknell
graduates felt economically secure and a similar number felt they were becoming
better off or staying the same. But for people at the top of the tree in what is
generally thought to be an optimistic country, their view of the future was often
negative. The graduates split 39%-39% on whether America's best years have
already gone and nearly three-quarters believe young people with a similar
educational background will find working life tougher.

<P> A poll by <I>The Observer</I> among British voters in May found a strikingly
similar picture. Nearly half those in the survey had lost a job, were working
longer hours, had taken a new job at lower pay or were on short-term contracts.
Only a third believed that finding a new job at the same salary would be easy.
Just one in six found it easier to plan their financial future.

<P> "The main lesson," according to the paper, "is that a huge gulf persists
between the economic state of the nation, as measured by the (mainly cheerful)
data from the government, and the economic mood of the people... This nervousness
affects all ages, regions and social classes. Past recessions have tended to have
a muted impact on the middle-class Tory heartlands of southern England... Today
[it] is a nationwide experience."

<P> Unsurprisingly, the debate has had little impact on the global march of
downsizers. The first country to mimic US trends was the UK, where American
management theories are never more than a jet ride away. It is now spreading to
continental Europe, long resistant to the Anglo-Saxon approach. When the French
household appliances group Moulinex recently announced it was laying off 20% of
its staff and suggested that products aimed at developing markets might be
produced overseas, a protest march in Mamers was led by a nine-year-old with a
banner reading, "My mum and dad don't have a factory any more".

<P> Faced with a choice between a child's <I>cri de coeur</I> and the baffling
phraseology of management-speak, the downsizers are likely to lose the wider
public debate. This is not helped by the related issue of perceived corporate
greed. In the public eye, top managers reward their own efforts with ever-larger
salaries.

<P> Figures vary, but one set of US statistics show the ratio between a chief
executive's pay and an average worker's has moved from 41-1 in the '70s to 187-1
last year. So powerful was the British campaign against the privatised gas
utility that the name of chief executive Cedric Brown became a by-word for
excess.

<P> The danger is that the public in democratic states is becoming ever more
cynical about business and the people who run it. The downsizing debate may have
been overdone, but the impression of mass lay-offs for the working population
combined with pay rises for a superclass at the top threatens to create a witch's
brew of popular bitterness.

<P> Such feelings may be a passing phenomenon. If Jacobs at Goldman Sachs is
right, profits in the US might level off close to their current share of national
income, downsizing abate and a growth of high-quality jobs remove the fear from
middle-class life. Whether the same will be true in the UK and the rest of Europe
is another matter: the EU's failure to create new jobs is well-documented. That
could leave politicians there under pressure to act, prompting a possible bout of
business regulation and even protection to ameliorate the effects of the market.

<P> It is only a matter of time before the world's successful businesses are
asked the question posed by John Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO, America's
biggest trades union movement: "Does a rising tide now sink all ships, except for
the luxury yachts?"

<BR>
<BR>
</CENTER>

