<td valign=top>
<h2>
September/October 1996
</h2>
</td>
</tr> 

<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra9.gif" alt="Feature">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 


<H3> TRADING WITH THE ENEMY </H3> 

<H4> Europe is angry at new US rules that
attempt to enforce third-party trade sanctions on pariah states and threatens to
hit back. The lesson is that morality in global business should be used
sparingly, consistently and consensually. Charles Darwent on the story so far
</H4>

<P> For several months, everyone has watched with a growing sense of
disbelief as the world's two biggest trading blocs &#173; the US and the EU,
devout free-traders both &#173; squared up to each other for what could be a
bloody con&thorn;ict.

<P> In a US election year made even more panicky by the bomb at the Atlanta
Olympic games and crash of a jumbo jet near New York, Washington has reached for
the familiar weapon of the trade boycott to hit its favourite pariah states,
Cuba, Libya and Iran.

<P> But this time it is going much further, imposing its own sanctions policies
on other countries and conjuring up the unlikely vision of respectable business
executives from friendly states being banned from entering the US under the
banner of "trafficking" in stolen goods.

<P> This has prompted accusations of extraterritoriality, counter-measures and
the threat of a full-blown trade war that could entangle European and US
companies around the world. Critics also doubt if the measures will even succeed
in their stated aim of ending Middle East terrorism and Cuba's single-party rule.

<P> The details of both cases were in &thorn;ux at the time of writing, but they
raise questions of lasting importance. Could such laws set a precedent for future
sanctions legislation? Is there, as Brussels fears, an ulterior aim of curbing EU
trade? Do trade sanctions work? Should morality enter trade, and in what
circumstances?

<P> The main lesson from such an exercise is that while one should not rule out
the moral dimension from business and trade practice, it should be used sparingly
and consistently and should involve the consent of allies.

<P> The Cuban case, while hitting a smaller group of business interests, is the
most high-pro&THORN;le. This is partly because Cuba is still run on socialist
lines by that old anti-gringo Fidel Castro, who has made a career of defying
Uncle Sam and his embargoes.

<P> Although it no longer poses any real security threat, and human rights
violations there pale compared with other, bigger &THORN;sh, Cuba bothers US
politicians no end. Some are looking for a familiar enemy after the Soviet
Union's fall; others are courting the votes of Cuban exiles.

<P> When the proposed measures of the Helms-Burton Act were outlined in <I>World
Link</I> a year ago, most world trade experts and Cuban investors thought they
would not pass in their original, extreme form. They got a nasty shock when it
became law this May.

<P> Citing "continuing violations of fundamental human rights" by the Castro
government, the Cuban Liberty and Democratic Solidarity (Libertad) Act promoted
by Republican Senator Jesse Helms purports to "assist [the Cuban people] in a
decisive manner to end the tyranny that has oppressed them for 36 years". Since
it judges the international community to have shown "ethically improper conduct"
by continuing to do business with Castro, the new law aims to give the world a
quick lesson in ethics.

<P> The &THORN;rst lesson, Title III, allows foreign companies that are
"trafficking in" or otherwise bene&THORN;ting from the use of con&THORN;scated
properties in Cuba to be sued for restitution in US courts by their
pre-revolutionary owners. The second, Title IV, allows the executives of
companies doing business in Cuba to be denied US visas, a ban that has also been
extended to include their families.

<P> Among those already hit by this provision is Rupert Pennant-Rea, ex-editor of
<I>The Economist</I>, ex-deputy governor of the Bank of England and &#173; alas
for any US holiday plans the Pennant-Rea family might have had &#173; a director
of Sherritt International, a Canadian mining company with interests in Cuban
nickel.

<P> The D'Amato law aims to deter foreign investment in Iran and Libya, this time
in the name of &THORN;ghting international terrorism. Both countries have been
accused of sponsoring terror groups and Washington still says Libya bombed a US
aeroplane over Lockerbie, Scotland in December 1988. According to the law, any
foreign company investing more than $40 million in the energy sectors of either
Libya or Iran will &THORN;nd itself facing a range of sanctions aimed at hitting
its US business. Companies could also face the denial of US import licences, as
well as an embargo on loans from US banks.

<P> President Bill Clinton, told of European threats to retaliate against such
measures, made a comment that characterises Washington's logic when it has
decided to take the moral high ground: "Every advanced country is going to have
to make up its mind whether it can do business by day with people who fuel
attacks on innocent children by night."

<P> Such thinking, and the new law it has fostered, has caused outrage in Europe.
In part it is venal: the sanctions are tougher and the investment sums involved
are potentially much larger than those in Cuba's case. In part it is injured
<I>amour propre</I>. But it is also a principled objection to US policy.

<P> "Let it not be forgotten that Europe has been the hardest hit by terrorist
actions allegedly carried out with the support of these two countries," says
Peter Guilford, spokesman for EU trade minister Sir Leon Brittan. "The EU is
highly sensitive to the threat of terrorism and will not shirk its
responsibilities in &THORN;ghting it. We happen nonetheless to believe that
passing extraterritorial laws that strike America's friends is by no means the
best way of achieving such an objective."

<P> Europe has much to lose. Each year, for example, Italy imports more than 44%
of its oil from Libya and Iran, and the Italian energy company Agip has
signi&THORN;cant new natural gas investment planned in Libya. Britain, France,
Spain and Germany also have commercial interests in one or the other country.

<P> The main complaint against both laws is over extraterritoriality, which
arises whenever a country unilaterally tries to impose its legal will on the
institutions of another. It has been regarded as unacceptable since the Arab
boycott of foreign &THORN;rms doing business with Israel in the '50s, when the US
vehemently denied the moral propriety of such strong-arm tactics.

<P> Another issue, arising in Cuba, is over expropriations. Even in Iran
compensation for seized American property was agreed between the two governments,
as customary in international law, without involving private business. The Castro
government has signalled that it will discuss the issue even if it cannot repay
the estimated $6 billion involved. It is Washington that refuses to talk. Time is
another factor: when do you draw the line under the past? To make this point, two
Canadian opposition parliamentarians have proposed a tongue-in-cheek bill seeking
compensation from Washington for Canadian land lost to the US as a result of the
1775 War of Independence.

<P> "The real trouble here is that there is nothing actually illegal in what the
Americans are doing," says Jagdish Bhagwati, Indian-born professor of economics
at New York's Columbia University and long-time scourge of American trade policy.
"If they want to be bitchy, no one can stop them. So what if America decides to
deny visas to some European executives? The World Trade Organisation (WTO) can
scream its head off if it likes, but there is nothing it can really do about it."

<P><B> Exemptions to free-trade rules </B> <P> In any case, the WTO's free-trade
rules make a speci&THORN;c exception for cases where their imposition might
constitute a threat to national security. It is a waiver likely to be claimed
under the D'Amato law against Libya and Iran. The Helms-Burton Act contends that
the Cuban government poses a national security threat, although the WTO might
question this when Cuba's MiGs only have enough fuel to get airborne on special
occasions.

<P> Even if America's new extraterritorial legislation is not illegal, experts
are still troubled by its apparent &thorn;outing of the norms of international
law. Ruth Wedgwood, Yale professor of law and senior fellow at the US Council on
Foreign Relations, pointed out in a recent letter to <I>The Financial Times</I>
that the Helms-Burton Act's improbably broad de&THORN;nition of the word
"trafficking" means that the foreign businessman who haplessly buys a tonne of
sugar from an expropriated Cuban sugar re&THORN;nery may &THORN;nd himself being
sued in an American court not simply for the cost of the sugar in question but
for the entire value of the re&THORN;nery that made it.

<P> "One of the standards set up by the American Law Institute is that
jurisdiction to prescribe should depend on reasonableness," Wedgwood tells
<I>World Link</I>. "Can any law that allows for compensation so out of proportion
to commercial activity really be held to be reasonable?" Whether or not it can,
US courts are unlikely to be swayed by any appeal to extraterritorial
reasonableness. "Their answer would be 'Sorry &#173; that's not our business',"
Wedgwood says. "A court might chide a piece of legislation gently for breaking
international law, but that is about as far as it would go."

<P> Even so, the new rule may not be unassailable. "Generally, US courts are
loath to cast their nets abroad because of the right for due process under the
Sixth Amendment," Wedgwood says. "We're talking about foreign property that is
being penalised here, in the US. If I were the lawyer for a foreign company, I
would certainly argue that was unconstitutional."

<P> European indignation is freshly exercised, but Bhagwati has seen all this
before. "The idea that it has virtue on its side has always been basic to the US
approach to trade, and Americans have never hesitated to enforce what they see as
obligations by the use of threat," he says. "Look at the Japanese luxury-car
dispute, where [Washington] threatened a 100% penal tax to get Japan to
capitulate. Just imagine what would have happened on Capitol Hill if France's
computer industry had persuaded the French government to zero in on IBM in the
same way."

<P> His advice to those who stand to be hit hardest by the latest punitive
measures is the same as the advice he gave to the Japanese government. "I would
like to see the EU rap the US over the knuckles really hard on this one &#173;
refuse visas to brothers, sisters, grandparents, everyone. Nafta isn't going to
do it: Mexico's just had to &THORN;nd $7 billion to help Clinton out, and Canada
is no longer the Canada of [the assertive former prime minister] Pierre Trudeau,
unfortunately. So someone else will have to stand up to them, and it's got to be
the EU."

<P> At the time of writing, there is every indication that Bhagwati will get his
wish. An unexpectedly belligerent Brussels was planning to have a retaliatory law
on its books by October, when foreign ministers hold their next meeting. European
Union trade minister Sir Leon Brittan has already stated that this blocking
statute &#173; originally aimed just at the Helms-Burton Act &#173; will be
extended to include the anti-Libya legislation as well.

<P> Sir Leon also speaks of giving his American trade counterparts "a rap on the
knuckles". This action could include provisions prohibiting European companies
from complying with US extraterritorial legislation and entitling them to
counter-sue in European courts for damages awarded against them in the US.

<P> A tit-for-tat refusal of visas for US executives wishing to visit Europe
seems likely. The EU's executive Commission has already agreed to call on
European companies to compile a "watch list" of US companies or individuals that
&THORN;le lawsuits against them. The end result is that companies based in the US
that observe the new sanctions, caught between Scylla and Charybdis, could
&THORN;nd it difficult to conduct business almost anywhere else in the world.

<P> A compromise is still possible, given Clinton's well-known penchant for
changing his mind. After the unexpected volume of sabre-rattling emanating from
Brussels this summer, the president executed what <I>The Economist</I> tartly
dubbed "the most slippery Clinton wriggle for a while": signing the Helms Bill
into law to placate Cuban-American voters on the one hand, he simultaneously
waived its punitive Title III provisions for six months in order to lower
temperatures in Brussels on the other.

<P> If, as seems probable, Clinton is re-elected in November there may be less
pressure on him to appear gung-ho on foreign-policy issues. Congress is unlikely
to repeal the two new laws, however the president could avoid their most
troublesome provisions by waiving them inde&THORN;nitely. After all, Wedgwood
recalls, "The Trading with the Enemy Act that forbade US trade with North Korea
was actually extended at six-month intervals for 40 long years."

<P> Even if this expedient cools tempers in the short term, broader issues of US
extraterritorial legislation will remain. The current six-month suspension, for
example, applies only to the right to sue and not to the provision barring
executives from the US. In any case, punitive measures still act as a deterrent
to potential investors as they can be reinstated at any time.

<P><B> Work for the lawyers </B> <P> In the meantime companies are expected to
&THORN;nd ways around the rules, providing more proof for those who argue that
extraterritorial law-making does not work. Wedgwood suggests, for example, that
foreign companies with interests in Libya and Iran will be able to get around the
D'Amato law's $40 million cap simply by staggering their investments.

<P> And although the Helms-Burton Act has registered the odd triumph, its
principal effect has been to force companies to dodge its provisions by
restructuring themselves out of the US market. The principal bene&THORN;ciaries
have not been the Cuban people but corporate lawyers.

<P> A de&THORN;ant Cuba enjoys pointing out the loopholes. In an interview with
<I>The Financial Times</I> recently, vice president Carlos Lage admitted that the
new penalties added to potential investor risk and created a &THORN;nancing
squeeze for Havana but insisted that companies were &THORN;nding ways around the
problem.

<P> Parrying questions about the reported pull-out of the Mexican giant Cemex,
for example, he said the real business partner was another institution and "the
joint company is continuing to operate". Equally, although the Dutch-based
investment giant ING has said it would discontinue a &THORN;nancing contract for
two sugar-growing provinces in Cuba, Lage said that the bank is still maintaining
its operations.

<P> Nor is the potential ineffectiveness of the punitive measures merely
practical: there is the psychological factor. In short, attempting to enforce
agreement at the point of an economic gun has a marked tendency to make
governments do precisely the opposite of what they are told. With the popularity
of the boycott tactic still alive and perhaps growing, it is a lesson likely to
need repeating.

<BR>
<BR>
</CENTER>

</TD> </TR> </TABLE> 
