<td valign=top align=left> 

<H3> Hong Kong </H3> 

<H4> The impending transfer of sovereignty in the territory from Britain to China
will provide stern challenges to Asia's leading entrep&ocirc;t city. But Hong
Kong has faced a series of tough choices in recent years and has invariably
exceeded expectations. From vast infrastructure programmes like the new airport
to the export of investment and know-how, it is gearing up for change  </H4>
<BR>

<A HREF="#bulls"> Bulls and bears </A> <BR>

<A HREF="#asia"> Asia's money machine </A> <BR>

<A HREF="#future"> Future foundations </A> <BR>

<A HREF="#china"> China calling </A> <BR>


<A NAME="bulls"></A><H3> Bulls and bears </H3> 

<H4> Changes affecting business around the world mean more to Hong Kong's future than the transfer of sovereignty </H4> 

<I> By Gareth Hewett </I>

<P> The pessimistic view about Hong Kong's future was best
summed-up in the cover article of the US financial magazine <I>Fortune</I> last
summer. The author of "The Death of Hong Kong" said the territory was was due to
be relegated to the status of global backwater after the handover to China next
June.

<P> "The naked truth about Hong Kong's future can be summed up in two words: it's
over," he wrote. "Troops of the People's Liberation Army, which has already
formed links with powerful local criminal gangs known as 'triads', will stroll
the streets," after the British withdrawal, he added.

<P> Most people would probably accept there is a lot of uncertainty in Hong Kong,
especially in the political arena. But this should be seen in a regional context.
Since 1984, the date of the Sino-British treaty agreeing the transfer to Chinese
rule, there has been a revolution in the Philippines (1986), a massacre in
Beijing (1989), the threat of war between North and South Korea and between China
and Taiwan.

<P> There were riots in Bangkok (in 1992) and in Jakarta this August. If
political uncertainty is what you want, the Asia-Pacific region has a lot on
offer. But of course Hong Kong has a political sell-by date and that opens up
vast new areas for speculation.

<P><B> Reasons to be wary </B> <P> The debate has divided people into two camps,
best described as the optimist bulls and the pessimist bears. The bears all make
a number of similar points, according to Morgan Stanley Asia's managing director
of research, Peter Churchouse. They believe that the dollar peg will break,
inflation is wiping out the territory's international competitiveness, trading
performance is on the slide and the current uncertainty will only worsen as the
handover looms. Finally, they say, doubts linger about China's commitment to the
rule of law. Mixed with corruption and heavy-handed economic intervention, this
could create a cocktail of disaster. The bears have representatives not only
among the foreign community and opinion-formers outside the territory, but also
among those Hong Kong Chinese who have already left the territory. This is the
strain which most influences portrayals of the colony's post-1997 prospects in
the international media.

<P> Churchouse sides with the bulls, arguing that the pessimists have failed to
comprehend fully both China's crucial role in Hong Kong's development and its
reliance on China in the future. The days when Hong Kong could be viewed as a
foreign enclave pinned onto a hostile mainland are long gone, he argues: "Instead
we believe Hong Kong should be considered as the capital city of a sub-region of
perhaps 100 million people, a region that has been growing at [more than] 10% a
year for a decade."

<P> Proponents of the bull scenario focus on the economic story. They tend to be
people in the Hong Kong Chinese business community who either have big
investments in Hong Kong or China, or are members of the expatriate community
planning to live in the territory after the handover.

<P> They have a strong case in arguing that Hong Kong's future can be divined
from its past. The territory has been voted the world's freest economy and has
one of the highest GDP per capita on a purchasing power parity basis. Real
economic growth has been strong for decades and unemployment is historically low.
According to surveys it is the fourth leading financial centre in the world, the
eighth leading trading economy, the 11th largest exporter of commercial services
and it has the third largest positive trade balance. In 1994 it was the largest
inward recipient of foreign direct investment flows, as measured as a percentage
of GDP, and the largest exporter of FDI.

<P> This progress is all the more startling given Hong Kong's origins.
Historically, it has served as a trading entrep&ocirc;t from the time of the
earliest formal British settlement in 1841. Modern Hong Kong really began to take
shape when it became a sanctuary for successive waves of mainland emigrants and
refugees following the communist revolution in 1949.

<P> Hang Seng Bank chairman Sir Quo Wei Lee argues, "Between 1949 and the late
'50s, there was a continuous influx of capital, technology and talent from the
mainland which led to our industrial development. The environment was favourable:
rising incomes, low tax and a stable convertible currency."

<P> At first Hong Kong made its name in manufacturing cheap goods and textiles
became a key industry. From the mid-70s its development has been characterised by
the need to adapt to globalising markets and the erosion of its enclave status as
China began to open up to the outside world. This allowed Hong Kong's
manufacturing sector to relocate to mainland China, the main economic
transformation in the last decade. Since then, Hong Kong has laid a boxful of
golden eggs.

<P> Anything which threatens this is obviously a matter of concern to the
business community. Of greater concern, however, are a whole series of issues
unrelated to the swapping of flags in 1997. This view is best expressed in the
Political &amp; Economic Risk Consultancy bi-monthly journal recently: "There is
so much speculation about how Hong Kong will be changed by the 1997 transition
that too little attention is being given to the factors that could also have a
profound impact on the business environment in the longer term. If you want to
have an idea of what Hong Kong will look like a decade from now, it is probably
wise to think about the global forces shaping major industries and how these
forces could change the situation in Hong Kong." Among such key trends are the
further opening up of China's economy and the development of a competitive
services sector, as trade barriers are rolled back.

<P> To illustrate the issues, take a look at the banking sector. Paul Proudfoot
of the risk consultancy says: "The change to Chinese sovereignty is interesting,
but few bankers are [as worried] about this as they are about how technological
change promises to remake the entire global banking industry."

<P> Hong Kong is developing as a key hub for a whole range of products and
services. The UN annual investment report singles it out as the biggest Asian
player in FDI. The average outflow of foreign direct investment between 1983 and
1988 was $1.45 billion. This more than doubled<B> </B>to $2.3 billion in 1990,
hit $3 billion in 1991 and reached $7.3 billion in 1992. In 1993, the figure
soared to $17.45 billion in 1993 and $20.95 billion in 1994, the fifth highest
figure in the world. Singapore, by contrast, managed only $650 million in 1994.
Outward investment stock in Hong Kong rose to $60 billion in 1994 from just $2.34
billion in 1985.

<P> At the same time inward investment stock, representing the accumulated value
of the inward investment flow, reached $19.6 billion compared to $3.5 billion in
1985. The investment flow out of the territory incorporates net outward
investment by Hong Kong companies along with outward investment by foreign
companies using Hong Kong as a platform. Much of the money headed for China. In
1994, Hong Kong was the biggest investor in China.

<P> But the colony is more than an investment centre. It is also a trading hub. A
report by Kurt Salmon Associates commissioned by the territory's government
pinpointed soft goods, saying it supplied $50 billion or 10% of all textiles,
clothing and footwear to the world's major markets. Hong Kong soft goods
companies have the firepower to finance large-scale manufacturing activities for
customers in North America and Europe. "Thus Hong Kong companies have been able
to offer their western customers a reliable means to transact business that
provides access to the attractive low cost and large capacity of the Chinese
soft-goods manufacturing sector," the report says.

<P> The territory has developed a strategic core competence in the global
international trade value chain. This has enabled the territory to handle a level
of business far beyond its domestic capacity or geographical borders.

<P> A survey by the Hong Kong Trade Development Council of 2,510 companies found
that 39% exported goods produced in Hong Kong and 81% exported goods produced in
China. More importantly over a third exported goods produced in third countries.
According to the survey, the estimated total value of unrecorded offshore export
business by Hong Kong companies was HK$655 billion ($84 billion) in 1994,
equivalent to 70% of the territory's re-exports that year.

<P><B> Reasons to be cheerful </B> <P> What the report shows is that Hong Kong
companies are becoming more efficient through a combination of investment
overseas, cost-cutting and by using Hong Kong as an efficient central processing
hub. There are 1,850 multinationals with offices in the territory. Of this, 700
are regional headquarters. More than 92% of companies surveyed in trade and
manufacturing said they would keep their headquarters in the territory.

<P> The Trade Development Council emphasises that as a global middleman, Hong
Kong's role is not in danger of diminishing because its transnational
corporations have built up expertise in their sector. For a customer they will
handle financing, insurance and freight and will even act as principal through
the acquisition of goods, from the manufacturer to the final end-user.

<P> What all this wealth of survey data indicates is that, while there is a
tremendous amount of uncertainty about Hong Kong's prospects post-1997, there are
also good reasons for optimism. Despite the rising costs of doing business, the
territory continues its evolution into a global Mr Fixit in international trade.
<P>

<A NAME="asia"></A><H3> Asia's money machine </H3>

<H4> Britain is leaving $47 billion in the kitty and future growth from two-way
investment looks quite likely </H4>  

<I> By Keith Wallis </I>

<P> Some ofAsia's tallest skyscrapers now stand like giants in Hong Kong, a far cry from the
"barren rock with hardly a house upon it" that British foreign secretary Lord
Palmerston described 150 years ago at the start of British rule.

<P> This is now a territory sweating money from every pore. With all land owned
by the government, each time a site is auctioned, a portion of the sum paid by
developers goes into the official land fund. The barren rock has become a rich
piece of real estate earning the Hong Kong authorities $26 billion in land
premiums.

<P> Combined with other fiscal reserves, China's new "special autonomous region
government" will inherit more than $47 billion from the old colonial
administration on July 1, 1997. This is almost 15 times the $3.3 billion Britain
had promised to leave in the kitty.

<P> There are losers. Despite a public housing programme which produces about
40,000 new homes a year, some 3,000 old men and women still live in tiny wire
cages. Such conditions have been condemned by the UN Human Rights Commission, but
the government says it has no resources to help. More than half of all public
housing is being sold to broaden private ownership, even though buildings erected
before 1970 were poorly constructed and poorly maintained.

<P> In fairness, many of the territory's problems stem from its success. In the
'60s it was a quiet backwater known for cheap toys, a corrupt police force and
girly bars. Before 1972, when the first cross-harbour road tunnel was completed,
vehicles had to use ferries across Victoria Harbour, the 1,600m-wide natural port
that separates the main urban areas on Hong Kong Island and Kowloon. And until
the metro system opened in the early '80s the only way to go from one end of the
island to the other was by bus or antiquated tram, a journey which took several
hours.

<P> Deng Xiaoping's "open door" policy in the '80s spurred development of the
territory's huge container port complex at Kwai Chung, now approaching full
capacity. Last year Hong Kong was the world's busiest container port. Some 80% of
all traffic came from China, the result of burgeoning industrial expansion in
Guangdong and other southern Chinese provinces.

<P><B> Expanding circles of growth </B> <P> Tony Clark, a senior official with
Hong Kong's Port Development Board, expects container volumes to grow by 250% in
the next 10 years. "Handling that demand will mean building a new four-berth
container terminal every two years for the next 20 years," he says.

<P> Two years ago the neighbouring Guangdong economy was growing by 25% a year
and although the annual rise has cooled to about 10%, experts believe this level
of growth will be sustained for at least the next 20 years. Indeed the booming
economy of southern China is spurring development further north as companies
search for cheaper sites in Hunan, Fujian and Hubei provinces.

<P> "The early pioneers who moved across the border from Hong Kong 15-20 years
ago are now finding its too expensive in Guangdong. They are moving further north
where land and labour is cheaper," says one expert.

<P> Rapid development in southern China has fuelled investment in both
directions. The most recent flagship deal was reached in June when the China
National Aviation Corporation took a controlling 35.85% stake in Hong Kong Dragon
Airlines (Dragonair), one of Hong Kong's three air carriers. The CNAC paid nearly
$255 million to Dragonair's major stakeholders: Swire, Cathay Pacific Airways and
CITIC Pacific, the Chinese government's main overseas investment vehicle. Wang
Guixiang, the head of CNAC, became Dragonair chairman and CITIC spent almost $816
million increasing its stake in Cathay Pacific from 10% to 25%.

<P> The ramifications were far wider than in normal share deals. It signalled a
shift of changing economic fortunes every bit as significant as next year's
political handover. The deal ended a 50-year dominance in the airline industry by
Swire, the British <I>hong</I> (trading company) which founded Cathay and
Dragonair. It also showed that mainland companies are now the young turks, keen
to claim their inheritance.

<P> The future of both air carriers had been under a cloud for more than a year
since it became clear CNAC was planning to start its own Hong Kong-based airline.
Swire did not want a repeat of the situation faced by another British
<I>hong</I>, Jardine Matheson, which has been virtually blackballed by China
since it moved to the Caribbean in 1984 amid post-handover fears.

<P> Other companies without the same ties of British blood and history, like the
electricity generator China Light &amp; Power, have had considerable success on
the mainland. It has invested heavily in power stations across the border, partly
as an investment and partly to guarantee power supplies to the territory. The
latest deal is a $2.3 billion agreement to build China's largest coal-fired power
station complex using foreign partners. Plant will be built in three different
cities by the Shandong China Light Power Electricity Company, 29% owned by
CL&amp;P. The firm is also competing for the $600 million Laibin B power station
in Guangzi Zhuang autonomous region, in south-west China. The CL&amp;P is jointly
operating the Daya Bay nuclear station east of Hong Kong and a pumped-storage
hydro-electric station at Changshu.

<P> Hutchison Whampoa has recently increased its stake in China Strategic
Holdings, which co-ordinates investment on the mainland. Hutchinson, one of Hong
Kong's largest conglomerates, has extensive interests in China including
container terminals, infrastructure and retail outlets.

<P> Hopewell Holdings, created in 1972 by civil engineer Gordon Wu Ying-sheung,
was one of the first investors, building the Shajiao B coal-fired power station
as one of the first privatised build-own-operate projects in China. Once a
darling of the Chinese government, Wu's star has waned as a result of massive
cost overruns and delays on his 123km superhighway between Hong Kong and
Guangzhou. Problems have also dogged his Shajiao C power plant near Guangzhou.

<P> A recent research report by Credit Lyonnaise shows Hong Kong companies are
set to invest more than $18 billion in the next three to four years. Analysts see
this continuing at least into the early part of the century, although Credit
Lyonnaise says companies tend to reduce their exposure by keeping a low asset
value. "The ability to cooperate and coordinate with Chinese authorities to
expedite project approvals is hugely valuable" says Credit Lyonnaise analyst
Randall Gilbert.

<P> But despite the public optimism shown by many local firms, there are still
doubts. Last October Li Ka-shing and a group of entrepreneurs launched the Better
Hong Kong Foundation to "express and encourage confidence in Hong Kong" in the
years beyond the coming handover. It was later revealed that Li had moved his
personal stake in Cheung Kong (Holdings), worth more than $360 million, to the
Cayman Islands "for personal reasons". Tsang Hin-chi, head of Goldlion, has his
personal shareholdings registered in Nauru, a tiny Pacific island.

<P><B> Hope for best, prepare for worst </B> <P> For ordinary people, next year's
union of capitalism and communism is extremely worrying. There was a time at the
height of the pro-democracy movement in the late '80s when business leaders said
Hong Kong people were too busy making money to be interested in democracy.

<P> That changed almost overnight with the Tiananmen Square massacre when Chinese
troops killed and injured hundreds of protesters in Beijing on June 4, 1989.
Thousands of people have marked the occasion every year with a candle-lit vigil
in the colony: further protests are under threat come the transition.

<P> Thousands of fearful Hong Kongers have travelled to Canada, Australia and the
US to work for two years until they are eligible for a second passport. With this
safety net in place they have returned, rejoining friends and family to continue
their lives.

<P> Carl Chu Ka-shing is typical of the many small businessman who hope for the
best but also fears the worst. Educated at London's Imperial College, he is the
managing director of a building firm turning over about $5 million a year. He has
modest investments on the mainland, as he says, "to put something back into the
motherland". He also has a full British passport which he says he will only use
in an emergency. "Where will I go? Hong Kong is my home. If I go to England what
will I do? If I try to set up a building company I face opposition for being
Chinese," he says.

<P> Many people like Chu are extremely concerned for the future, not because they
fear a catastrophic overnight collapse, but because they worry about a more
insidious breakdown in social order. People compare Hong Kong with Shenzhen
immediately across the border where they see a town with rampant crime, pollution
and mounting inflation. These concerns are compounded by reports of the 10,000
People's Liberation Army soldiers due to be stationed in the territory. Locals
fear that the low-paid soldiers may be corrupted by the bright lights and vast
wealth that exists in the territory.

<P> The outgoing establishment seems optimistic, however. "The foundation stone
of the present bullish forecasts is the view that the new sovereign will want to
ensure the territory performs well beyond July 1," says Ian Perkin assistant
director of the Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce. "It is difficult to argue
with this view."


<P> 

 <A NAME="future"></A><H3> Future foundations </H3>
 
<H4> The city is awash with ambitious
infrastructure plans, however only a few of them have China's crucial blessing
</H4> 

<I>By Keith Wallis </I> 

<P> Next year promises to be more than a
political watershed for Hong Kong when it reverts to Chinese control after more
than 150 years of British colonial rule. Contractors, including many foreign
companies, are predicting an uncertain future once the territory's $20 billion
Chek Lap Kok airport and related reclamation, road and rail projects are
completed."It's worrying. The Hong Kong government has put on an optimistic face,
talking everything up, but the reality is that nobody knows what's going to
happen," comments one construction boss.

<P> The Hong Kong Construction Association (HKCA), which represents about 350
local and international contractors in the territory, agrees. It says that
although several mega-projects are on the drawing board there is no certainty
they will go ahead.

<P> "The government has big plans in hand including the Western Corridor Railway,
ports, sewage improvements and housing," says Patrick Chan Wing-tung, secretary
general of the HKCA. "Putting political issues aside, there should not be a
sudden stop. But it's difficult to say what will happen."

<P><B> Opposition from China, environmentalists </B> <P> Follow-on projects,
including the $10 billion Western Corridor Railway and the $5 billion north
Lantau port development, are under a cloud following opposition from local
environmentalists and from China. Engineering and architectural consultants are
unlikely to be as badly hit as contractors, because most have already been paid.
Many of the locally based firms are the subsidiaries of British and foreign
consultants with extensive overseas interests.

<P> Cracks began to appear in the grand infrastructure plan last year when
Winston Chu Ka-sun, a prominent solicitor, enlisted the help of independent
legislator Christine Loh Kung-wai to curb the authorities' massive reclamation
plans. Chu, with popular support, helped Loh introduce a harbour protection bill
into the local parliament or Legislative Council. If approved it will severely
curtail government plans to reclaim more than 630 hectares of waterfront on Hong
Kong Island and Kowloon to provide land for future developments, including two
container terminals at north Lantau. Public anger has already been stirred up
after the filling-in of more than 600 hectares of the territory's picturesque
harbour needed for the airport-related projects.

<P> Chu argues that the opposition coming from Beijing is not mere posturing
against the colonial regime and support for infrastructure projects could
evaporate once the new administration is installed next July.

<P> The current government has already been forced to postpone the initial
segment, the 190-hectare Green Island reclamation, pending further studies.
Beijing says Hong Kong's secretary for planning, environment and lands, Bowen
Leung Poving, broke his pledge that there would be no new reclamation before the
handover. There also seems to be some scepticism about the colonial government's
argument that the Green Island scheme was for a public dump, not reclamation.
"This [postponement] is a completely reasonable request and is good for the
preservation of Hong Kong's natural resources and long-term interests," says a
senior official at China's Hong Kong and Macau Affairs Office.

<P> The Green Island scheme is not an isolated project: it seen as a key element
in the high-profile plan to build a road from the western end of Hong Kong Island
to the north Lantau port. Board secretary Tony Clark insists that the territory
will lose $10 billion between 1997 and 2011 if the first two port areas,
container terminals 10 and 11, are not constructed on schedule.

<P><B> Crying wolf for growth </B> <P> All the same, critics believe the board
has cried wolf once too often and has over-estimated the need for additional
berths. Jeremy Marriott, the managing director of ferry company HKR
International, says officials several years ago predicted the collapse of the
territory's trading status if terminals 10 and 11 did not start this year. "This
simply hasn't happened. Operators have become more efficient and ports have
developed along the coast of southern China," he says. Instead, as Clark admits,
productivity at the Kwai Chung container port complex has soared 30% in the past
18 months following the introduction of new equipment and working practices.

<P> China, upset at a lack of consultation, has also voiced its opposition to the
Western Corridor Railway, a 53km heavy rail link from Hong Kong's current main
port area at Kwai Chung to the border. The scheme is being promoted by the
Kowloon-Canton Railway Corporation, the territory's only heavy rail operator.

<P> It has not yet received the full development go-ahead but it has planned 20
technical studies covering route alignment, environmental impact and other
matters. Chinese officials, fearing a <I>fait accompli</I> similar to the airport
debacle, made it clear that any engineering contracts would be cancelled after
the handover if there is no consultation.

<P> The political crisis was only diffused when Governor Chris Patten stepped in,
telling KCRC that the nine most critical studies could go ahead but the remainder
would have to wait. Despite Patten's intervention there has still been widespread
opposition, amid concerns about the project's huge cost and scale.

<P> Estimates of the cost of construction and finance have risen from $10 billion
to nearly $13 billion, which would make it Hong Kong's most expensive railway
ever. Land purchase alone will take five years to complete which the government
admits would delay the scheme beyond the anticipated 2001 completion date. Even
engineers, who have most to gain from the studies, have proposed three cheaper
alternatives which they say would better link Hong Kong's port with China's main
Pearl River harbour at Shekou.

<P> Wang Liang Huew, chairman of the China-backed Hong Kong Institute for
Infrastructure Development, says there have been no talks on the issue with the
neighbouring Shenzhen government. "According to the KCRC plans, the railway goes
through the middle of Shenzhen. But KCRC has not yet discussed its proposals with
the Shenzhen authorities. It is ludicrous," he says.

<P> In an effort to deflect criticism HSBC Investment Bank Asia, the
corporation's financial advisers, say the government will reap about $130 billion
in land revenue and dividends from rail revenue by 2034. Passenger traffic is
expected to reach 260,000 a day by 2011.

<P><B> Re-run of the airport saga </B> <P> The wrangle threatens to become a
re-run of the Chek Lap Kok airport saga. Britain and China fought for more than
five years before they could reach an agreement after the then governor, Sir
David Wilson, announced the massive scheme with much fanfare in 1989.

<P> Britain saw the airport and nine related projects as the key to Hong Kong's
continued economic survival. It had become clear that the existing Kai Tak
airport had reached its saturation level of 30 million passengers. Revised
traffic forecasts recently published by the airport authority show that 35
million passengers are expected<B> </B>to use Chek Lap Kok when it opens in April
1998. The Authority says this will grow to 56 million passengers by 2010.

<P> Whatever the economic reasoning, China remains suspicious and angry at the
lack of advance warning. Beijing counters that the infrastructure plans are a
massive drain on the financial reserves of the future special autonomous regional
government. It also accuses Britain of rewarding its own construction and
manufacturing companies.

<P> In fact Japanese industry has benefited most from the airport core programme.
With all the large bridge, road and rail contracts awarded, Japanese contractors
have scooped 27% of the $12 billion worth of orders let so far.

<P> Hong Kong companies come second with 23% of the work. By comparison British
outfits come third with<B> </B>16%. But even this figure could be an
over-estimate because several UK contractors have withdrawn from their contracts.
For example, Alfred McAlpine International won a $336 million contract in the
middle of last year to build the airport's runway and taxiways in a joint venture
with a local firm, but pulled out six months later because of a corporate
decision to end work abroad.

<P> The lack<B> </B>of effective consultation between the Hong Kong and Chinese
administrations is creating an air of uncertainty. Hong Kong officials are
merrily proposing projects without the slightest idea whether they will continue
come July next year. A cross-border infrastructure committee set up by both sides
appears to be a talking shop and seems to lack the ability to coordinate
development.

<P> But that has done little to stop some highly ambitious private plans for the
post-colonial era. One was unveiled recently by David Li Kwok-po, chief executive
of the Bank of East Asia and a member of the preparatory committee, China's
shadow government in Hong Kong. This was Pearl City, a megacity which would
connect the 24,000 sq km and 40 million people of Hong Kong, Macau and several
Chinese cities including Guangzhou (Canton) and Shenzhen. "It is one of the
largest, richest urban areas of the world... (with a) gross domestic product of
$800 billion a year. Pearl City's infrastructure is the envy of the world," he
says.

<P><B> Effects of uncertainty </B> <P> But before the concept can become a
reality it will need an unprecedented level of coordination and joint planning
among central, provincial and local governments. "Think about the current
administration structures for the [Pearl] Delta region," he says. "They do little
to promote coordination. These communities are so near and yet so far apart".

<P> Uncertainty is having other effects. Chan, secretary general of the
Construction Association, says that it is causing larger contractors to look
further afield, regionalising their businesses as a bulwark against any local
downturn. Large firms which have invested heavily in China, including Hopewell
Holdings and Cheung Kong, owned by billionaire Li Ka-shing, are also looking for
work elsewhere.

<P> Representatives from a number of top firms recently accompanied Hong Kong's
financial secretary Donald Tsang Yam-kuen on a tour of several member-countries
of the Association of South-East Asian Nations (Asean) to promote their expertise
in the region.

<P> One construction boss has even gone so far as to demand official government
help to win business. Chan Ka-kui, the managing director of Hsin Chong
Construction, would like the government to pay for trade missions and market
research: "Quite a few contractors &#173; such as Hsin Chong, Shui On, Gammon and
Hip Hing &#173; have reached a size where they are capable of competing
internationally."

<P> Hong Kong's rapid development, especially the experience gained on
airport-related construction, gives local firms a competitive edge in the region,
he adds. "Being a contractor anywhere is tough, but I do feel that if the
construction industry gets together &#173; developers, professionals and
contractors &#173; we do have a lot to sell," he says. "Our experience of
mega-projects shows we can deliver projects on time and within budgets, which is
something we can capitalise on."

<P><B> Cooperate and survive </B> <P> Taking this view into account, the
territory's largest contractor Gammon Construction has embarked on a long-term
programme to create the region's biggest building group. "We've been
regionalising the business because we were banging our head on the ceiling in
Hong Kong," said Martin Hadaway, Gammon's group chief executive.

<P> The firm recently picked up a $202 million contract to build Singapore's
first automated light rail system in a joint venture with the German engineering
group AdTranz and the island-state's Keppel Integrated Engineering. Hadaway said
the partnership will be maintained for similar rail projects in the region.
Gammon, which had a turnover of $850 million last year, has linked up with blue
chip clients in selected Asian countries. The most recent tie-up was with a
Filipino company, Ayala Land based in Manila.

<P> Hsin Chong's Chan also stresses Hong Kong contractors' natural language
advantage against overseas competitors trying to win work in Asia. "We have the
language skills so we can communicate with clients who initiate projects," he
says: only Japanese firms, with an enormous foreign workload, can rival Hong Kong
companies.

<A NAME="china"></A><H3>China calling </H3>

<P> <H4> The telecom monopoly faces greater
competition and ownership dilution, but China offers a tempting market </H4>  

<I>By Keith Wallis </I>

<P> If the speculation is right Hongkong Telecom (HKT), one
of the territory's biggest monopolies, will become the next blue-chip company to
fall victim to raids by mainland Chinese shareholders anxious to increase their
holding before the handover of power.

<P> After the recent upheaval at Hong Kong Dragon Airlines (Dragonair) that saw
Chinese companies take a controlling stake, HKT has been identified as the next
likely target. This gained extra credence just as ink was being put to the
Dragonair agreements in June when CITIC Pacific, China's overseas investment arm,
sold Telecom shares worth $388 million to a mystery buyer. Rumours intensified
when CITIC refused to allow HKT to reveal the identity of the buyer.

<P> The sell-off comes at a particularly uncertain time for HKT, just a month
before merger talks collapsed between Cable &amp; Wireless &#173; which owns a
controlling 58% stake in the company &#173; and British Telecom. The $50 billion
"deal of the decade" apparently fell apart because the two sides could not agree
a price. But British Telecom was also wary of what would happen to HKT after next
year's handover.

<P> Deregulation of the telecommunications market in Hong Kong is already putting
pressure on Hongkong Telecom's traditional monopoly. The firm is facing tough
competition from a new generation of local operators and it has been forced to
enter a price war on international telephone call charges to maintain market
share.

<P> Recently Telecom posted a 14.4% increase in pre-tax profits for 1995-96 to
$1.48 billion, but chief executive Linus Cheung Wing-lam admits it has been a
year of change and pressure. The firm's international call revenue growth was 70%
lower than the figure for 1994-95.

<P> A greater threat looms. In 2006, HKT will be forced to surrender its monopoly
on international telephone lines and the company is negotiating a compensation
package with the government for the expected loss of business. Experts estimate
HKT is seeking anything from $260 million to $650 million. Part of that could be
paid in kind, as concessions to redevelop buildings and liberalise prices. The
company has already warned customers that they will be charged for currently free
local calls.

<P> The firm was dealt a further blow at the end of July when it failed to win
tenders for any of six new mobile telephone network licences. The company offered
a rate of about 26 cents a minute. The government's regulatory agency, the Office
of the Telecommunications Authority, was unimpressed, since other bidders
suggested tariffs of 10-13 cents a minute.

<P> The increasingly difficult domestic market has encouraged the company to
examine prospects elsewhere and it is set to pounce as telecom deregulation rolls
across Asia. The firm's mobile telephone company, HKTCSL, has already begun to
offer some services in China. In July HKT became the first foreign company with a
mainland shareholder to invest in Taiwan when it took a 26% stake in Taiwan
Telecommunications Network Services. This investment followed similar
acquisitions in Singapore, South Korea and Japan.

<P> This shift may also run into political trouble. While financiers feel the
company has the muscle for further significant investments, it seems certain this
would require the support of mainland partners given next year's handover.

<P> China has yet to say how it will react to British firms continuing to own key
companies after the change of sovereignty, but there is a general sense that some
dilution will be necessary. International brokerage firm Merrill Lynch recently
said HKT would greatly benefit from the introduction of another mainland partner.
HKT is making positive noises, but says no formal approaches had been made. "It's
up to the Chinese government if one of its agencies wants to take a stake in our
company," says HKT chairman Brian Smith.

<P> Of course a mainland tie-up could also open the way for lucrative work there.
Andersen Consulting managing partner Larry Levitan says that the standard of
services in China is so low that phenomenal growth is inevitable: there could be
more telephone lines in Asia by the turn of the century than in the US. For HKT
the question is twofold: will the firm get a share of the vast neighbouring
market and, if it does, who will take the profits?

<p>

</td>
</tr>
</table>

